<SLUG> BC-MILLBABY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK TICKING FOR CONCEIVING MILLENNIUM BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA HELSER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Tonight's the night.
</P>
<P>
   Snooze and you'll lose the optimum date for conceiving what
might _ in nine months _ become the first baby born in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Sawing logs instead of making hay today could defeat Renee and
Walter Harris of Phoenix, declared Y2K Kid contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife works days and I work nights,'' said Walter, a
fast-food restaurant manager, ``so our biggest trick is to have
both of us awake at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Harrises and other couples around the world, who want to
make history as well as a baby, the promise of prizes, gifts and a
lifetime of fame and press clippings is heady stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Unconfirmed rumors promise treasures for the First Family of the
Millennium, including a year's supply of diapers, a college
education and diamond rings.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Canadian businessman who's trying to round up
$2 million in goods and has obtained a U.S. trademark for the term
``Official Millennium Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   China has been beset with rumors of what the first babe might
receive, so much so that the ``Beijing Youth Daily'' reported on
one woman who aborted her fetus so that she could time her
pregnancy closer to the target date.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Valley, others just want to offer support for the
conjugal cause.
</P>
<P>
   KZON radio in Phoenix is providing a conceptual cubicle for
competing couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the millennium baby conceived on ZON property and
during the morning show,'' said the show's producer, Kevin Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix radio station Power 92 offered free Millennium
Conception Kits valued at $49.99 to any couple entering the
reproduction race.
</P>
<P>
   Three accepted, including the Harrises.
</P>
<P>
   All vow to make good use of the kit's contents, including a
how-to volume titled ``Taking Charge of Your Fertility,'' an
ovulation calculator and pregnancy test kit, along with such mood
enhancers as massage oil and red tapers.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site _  &UR; www.having-a-baby.com/millenium.htm _ (that's
their spelling of millennium) is posting daily preconception tips
that include sound suggestions, such as that women should start
taking folic acid supplements before they become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Another site _ babycenter.com _ designed for new and expectant
parents, is offering the conception kits for sale and free advice
on everything from picking a baby's name to calculating how long it
might take to become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Even theologians appear supportive of parents who hope to create
a new life early in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all for procreation,'' said the Rev. Mark Hebert,
associate pastor at St. Thomas the Apostle Catholic Church in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But there are some conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child has to be wanted for its own sake and not just for
the big prizes,'' he said. ``And the child's safety has to come
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Father Hebert would be appalled if any doctor performed an
elective Cesarean-section or induced labor just to increase the
odds of a timely delivery.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to timing, competing couples might want to consult
Sharon Murri of Paradise Valley, who produced Arizona's first baby
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``She arrived at 12:01 a.m. on January 1,'' Murri said, ``and my
labor nurse was pretty excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Murri, however, wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted the tax deduction and we just missed it by
seconds,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But just to show how unpredictable Mother Nature and babies can
be, Murri remembers that Cassidy Joy arrived eight days after
Murri's Dec. 24 due date. That confirms what reproduction experts
have always known _ only 5 percent of mothers give birth on their
due dates.
</P>
<P>
   And although April 9 is the prime conception date for a Jan. 1
delivery, the window of opportunity is March 26 to April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Or thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-eight to 42 weeks is considered full-term, so you
really have a month there to play with,'' said Dr. Ole George
Torjusen, a Valley obstetrician/gynecologist.
</P>
<P>
   Even the duration of labor could throw off a well-timed due
date, Torjusen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For first-time mothers, labor could last 12 to 18 hours,'' he
said. ``A second labor usually lasts 12 hours or less.''
</P>
<P>
   But just getting pregnant could be the biggest feat of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of hurdles,'' said Barbara Faber, a
reproductive endocrinologist and infertility expert at Samaritan
Institute of Reproductive Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Her best advice to couples wanting the first baby of the
millennium is to be healthy, eat well, exercise, get plenty of
sleep, keep caffeine at a minimum, avoid alcohol and don't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I tell people to use an ovulation prediction kit that you
can buy at the grocery store for $15,'' she said. ``In advance, it
will predict when the egg will be released.''
</P>
<P>
   With that type of insider information and adequate contact,
something Faber recommends should occur every other day around the
time of ovulation, couples stand a 90 percent chance of conceiving
within one year.
</P>
<P>
   If, she adds, there are no infertility problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five percent of the time, it's the male's fault for not
conceiving,'' Faber said. ``And the rest of the time, it's the
female's.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly if the woman is older than 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then their chances of getting pregnant each month go down,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if conception does occur, 15 percent of all pregnancies end
in spontaneous miscarriages in the first trimester.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who do manage the miracle of conception, what are
their chances of having a safe delivery in a millennium that
threatens to dawn with computer breakdowns and electrical
malfunctions?
</P>
<P>
   Two of the state's largest hospitals say they are braced for the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have emergency generators that can run indefinitely, and
we've had a committee working on Y2K problems so that we'll be
prepared,'' said Jennifer Pool, spokeswoman for Good Samaritan
Regional Medical Center in Phoenix, the state's most prolific
birthing site, with a record 7,732 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we've been preparing for that for a couple of years,''
echoed Laurie Munn of St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center in
Phoenix, adding her facility will be Y2K compliant by July.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's the most troubling niggle of all. Just who's
declaring the winner and according to which time zone?
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, labor room nurses keep in touch on New Year's Eve,
determining the number of laboring moms in the running. There's a
recheck after midnight, when times are compared and a winner named.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they always cheat,'' Torjusen said. ``We all do.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a consolation prize for parents whose babies
just can't wait for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Figure on about $1,350 in tax deductions. &QL; 
Linda Helser can be reached at (602) 444-8243 or at
linda.helser(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
