<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN HEADED FOR DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Barring a miraculous recovery from Thursday night to
today, first baseman Mo Vaughn is headed for the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who suffered a bone bruise and sprained ligaments in his
left ankle while falling into the Indians dugout on Tuesday's
opening night, won't try to talk the Angels medical staff out of
it. In fact, it's Vaughn's idea as much as anybody's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to argue,'' Vaughn said. ``I've stated my
point. It's already been 48 hours and it's not feeling that good.
I'll let 'em know by (today).
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, we're playing with 24 guys, so that limits
the club. I don't think I'll be feeling that good (today). It's
been three days now. The DL is 12 more. If I'm not ready in 12
days, I'll cut the whole damn foot off. It'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is confident he'll be back when he'd be eligible to
return from the DL, which would be April 22 in Toronto. But the
medical staff has indicated an injury the nature of Vaughn's could
put someone out anywhere from two to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, however, has a history of healing quickly. He has been
on the disabled list only one time in his career _ he had torn
cartilage in his left knee in 1997 but missed only three weeks.
Vaughn also seems to know his body well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tried to play in a couple days, I'd be in worse shape in
a couple weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins said the decision of what to do with
Vaughn is strictly out of his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the medical staff, Mo and (general manager) Billy
(Bavasi), he said. ``However they feel. If he thinks it's going to
be that long....''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will likely call up first baseman Chris Pritchett
from Triple-A to replace Vaughn on the roster. Pritchett was the
final cut from the roster after a solid spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen overworked: Tim Belcher and Ken Hill each lasted only
41/3 innings in the Angels' first two games, putting an unwanted
burden on the bullpen at such an early point of the season. But
that is exactly why Collins and his coaching staff decided to begin
the season with 12 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here wondering if we've got enough even now,''
Collins said. ``We're going to be as cautious as we can early in
the year. Twelve pitchers gives us the opportunity to be
cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington: The Angels begin a four-game series in Texas
tonight against the Rangers. Pitching matchups for the series:
Tonight (5:35) _ Chuck Finley vs. John Burkett; Saturday (5:35) _
Omar Olivares vs. Rick Helling; Sunday (5:05) _ Tim Belcher vs.
Aaron Sele; Monday (11:35) _ Ken Hill vs. Mark Clark. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
