<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ZHU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERY CHARMING GUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China's prime minister, Zhu Rongji, charmed his
dinner audience on Thursday night with his knowledge of American
history and his candor, drawing applause when he recited part of
the Gettysburg Address and smiles at his honesty in complaining
that his legs fell asleep as he stood in the lengthy receiving
line.
</P>
<P>
   After their daylong official visit together, he and President
Clinton toasted each other at a black-tie event at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In his own toast, the president noted that Zhu had said that
only good friends tell each other what they really think. ``If
you're right about that, you have turned out to be quite a good
friend indeed,'' Clinton said, taking note of Zhu's renowned
outspokenness.
</P>
<P>
   In a chatty way, Zhu spoke not only of the nations'
disagreements but also of the moments during the day when he toured
parts of the White House and saw the original copy of the
Gettysburg Address. He told the audience he had once been able to
recite all of it in English, having learned it in school. And he
switched to English to say, ``of the people, by the people and for
the people,'' drawing applause.
</P>
<P>
   But he also might have caused a tiny bit of consternation as he
set the scene for his recitation of Abraham Lincoln's words. He
mentioned that he had toured the Lincoln bedroom. In the last few
years, it has become a symbol of the Clintons' eager wooing of
influential political donors; many spent the night there.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that Zhu was aware of the room's recent
political history. Just earlier on Thursday, Zhu spent time
dismissing media questions about allegations that China had tried
to influence the 1996 presidential election here.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's dinner drew members of Congress, the elite of
the business world and Clinton's national security team, which took
a break from the war in Kosovo to try to repair a relationship
badly strained by allegations of China's theft of American military
secrets and illegal campaign contributions to Clinton, and by the
country's human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   It came in the middle of Zhu's three-day visit to Washington,
the first by a Chinese prime minister in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu received the 19-gun salute befitting an official visit,
rather than the 21-gun salute reserved for heads of state. But like
heads of state, Zhu and his wife, Lao An, stayed in Blair House,
the president's guest house, and received protection from the
Secret Service (although they brought their own too). The red
Chinese flag with its yellow stars fluttered next to the Stars and
Stripes on lampposts around the White House.
</P>
<P>
   And their dinner _ of grilled chicken and roasted salmon, served
on Reagan china with Kennedy crystal and vermeil flatware, set on
rose damask tablecloths _ was every bit as formal. The bamboo
centerpieces contained flaming yellow tulips with red stripes,
orchids and poppies. Afterwards, the Clintons and their guests
adjourned to the East Room to hear Yo-Yo Ma, one of the world's
premier cellists, pianist Sara Wolfensohn and pipa soloist Wu Man.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list of more than 220 people was stocked with business
executives who have been anxious for more access to what is
potentially the world's largest market. Some were disappointed with
Thursday's news that negotiations failed to nail down a deal that
would allow China to enter the World Trade Organization, but many
were pleased that China had made certain concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending were Chris Galvin, chief executive officer
of Motorola Inc., which wants to build a cell-phone network across
China. China has agreed to allow American firms to invest up to 51
percent in cellular telephone and paging systems and will allow
them to operate throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been under fierce attack from Congress for openly
welcoming China at a time when relations between the two countries
border on the hostile. Key members of Congress have said that
because of major disputes between the two countries they were
alarmed at what they saw as Clinton's goal of rewarding China by
trying to bring it into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu had come seeking entry into the trade organization. After it
was clear on Thursday that this would not happen, at least now, Zhu
told reporters he had almost canceled his trip here because he was
afraid that anti-Chinese sentiment was so strong, he ``didn't have
the guts'' to show up.
</P>
<P>
   But he seemed quite relaxed at the White House on Thursday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
