<SLUG> BC-CADILLAC-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CADILLAC SIGNS LONG-TERM DEAL FOR SIGNS IN TIMES
SQUARE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The automotive brand promoted as the standard of the
world is taking a long-term parking space in the neighborhood
promoted as the crossroads of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac, the luxury division of the General Motors Corp., has
signed its first extended lease for advertising signs in the
cacophonous canyons of Times Square. For the next three years,
Cadillac ads will be visible on 2 Times Square, the northern anchor
of the district at the corners of 47th Street, Broadway and Seventh
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Cadillac nor Sherwood Outdoor in New York,
which oversees ad sales for 2 Times Square, would discuss the
terms, it is estimated that Cadillac is paying $1 million to $1.5
million annually to lease the space. Cadillac has an option to
renew the lease in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   There are six signs for Cadillac at the site, now pitching the
Evoq roadster concept car and the brand's World Wide Web site
(www.cadillac.com). The so-called flex-face panels of vinyl and
fiberglass are wrapped around the cube-like structure directly
under the familiar neon sign for Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The site, which houses the Olive Garden restaurant and the
Foley's restaurant of the Renaissance Hotel, previously carried ads
for Broadway shows, Apple Computer and Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   The Cadillac display may be supplemented at some point with a
metal version of the brand's crest, car headlights that would
illuminate and even actual vehicles, mounted on a concrete platform
on the roof of the structure.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's arrival in what could be called the Cadillac of
outdoor advertising venues is indicative of the boom that has
brought many classic brands back to Times Square. Decades of decay
had led blue-chip marketers to avoid the area until recently.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which used to advertise Chevrolet above the site
where Cadillac is now perched, joins Coca-Cola and other household
names like Budweiser and Planters in returning to Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment is a better place to be for marketers now,''
said Kim Kosak, director for advertising and sales promotion at
Cadillac in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be more of a global player in the marketplace,
and this is a great opportunity to reach a large global audience,''
she added. ``With 1.5 million eyeballs a day passing by, global
eyeballs, it's perfect for us.''
</P>
<P>
   A top executive at the longtime Cadillac agency echoed his
client.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real statement being in Times Square, and we're
delighted about it,'' said John Farrell, president for the North
American operations of D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles
Communications, a unit of MacManus Group in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Times Square ``is very appropriate for Cadillac and where
Cadillac is going to go,'' he added, referring to ambitious plans
to revitalize the brand. These include campaigns asserting that
Cadillac vehicles offer a blend of ``art and science'' with
``world-class technology'' and ``new design and styling.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if a decade ago the Times Square advertising business
needed Cadillac more than Cadillac needed Times Square, perhaps
today the reverse is true. Then, because of perceptions that Times
Square was a seedy, perilous place, there was a buyer's market for
signs. And Cadillac was the leader in American luxury-car sales, a
status the brand enjoyed for nearly six decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the sign business is flourishing in a prospering Times
Square, and demand for Cadillacs has tapered off. In 1998, Cadillac
held onto its No. 1 ranking in the competitive luxury-car market
only by staging an expensive, last-minute sales blitz.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Cadillac has fallen behind rivals like Lexus,
Mercedes-Benz and Lincoln; sales through March 31 declined 15.9
percent from the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Evoq is the first visual embodiment of what the new
direction of Cadillac is from a product standpoint,'' Ms. Kosak
said. ``And our communications are being designed to better
represent this new direction.''
</P>
<P>
   After Evoq, the signs will advertise the redesigned Cadillac
DeVille to be introduced for the 2000 model year. The celebration
of New Year's Eve in Times Square for the year 2000 ``will be
important for the DeVille launch,'' Ms. Kosak said.
</P>
<P>
   That embodies the potential benefits of advertising in Times
Square that extend beyond posting the signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promotional and event-marketing opportunities that Times
Square can offer advertisers can really help get an edge up on
their competition,'' said Brian Turner, president at Sherwood
Outdoor. Those can be multiplied by the free publicity the signs
draw through appearances in movies and television programs as well
as in photographs in magazines and newspapers and even on
postcards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enormous residual value there,'' said Jeffrey Katz,
chairman of real estate company Sherwood Equities, who formed
Sherwood Outdoor last year to market signs on three buildings he
owns and manages: 2 Times Square, 1 Times Square and 1600 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of sounding like a real estate guy in the
advertising world, it's location, location, location,'' Katz said,
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Square signs are emblematic of steps Cadillac is
taking to rejuvenate its brand identity, particularly among younger
drivers. The division also ran a commercial during Super Bowl
XXXIII for Escalade, the new Cadillac sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The spot, created by Berlin Cameron &AMP; Partners in New York, used
the George Thorogood rock tune ``Bad to the Bone'' and an assertive
slogan, ``It's good to be the Cadillac.''
</P>
<P>
   More surprises may be on the way from Cadillac. As they say in
the outdoor advertising business, watch this space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
