<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG IMPRESSES JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi had three homers and eight RBI through the first
three games for the Dodgers. The bullpen went nearly 10 innings
without allowing a hit. Yet, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said
it's second baseman Eric Young he's most pleased about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been my MVP,'' Johnson said. ``He's had nothing but great
at-bats, stealing a base when you need it, exciting to watch, has a
great stroke, knows how to work a pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mouthful, but Young's been all that.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Thursday's game with the Colorado Rockies, Young
was hitting .455. Equally important, Young had a firm grasp on the
strike zone and was getting deep into counts.
</P>
<P>
   In the three games, Young drew three walks and was hit by a
pitch. That was one of the things he needed to improve upon as a
leadoff hitter. In 117 games last season, he walked 45 times. His
career high for walks in a season is 63, which he accomplished in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's all about, making the pitchers work,'' Young
said. ``Don't give away any at-bats. Make it a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opener, Young reached base in his first four plate
appearances. He reached twice in Tuesday's 3-2 win and went 3 for 4
in Wednesday's series finale. And once on base, Young is causing
trouble. His four stolen bases were more than any other team in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven or 12 in pen: The Dodgers' bullpen was outstanding
against the Diamondbacks, allowing three runs in 102/3 innings.
There was a stretch in which the bullpen didn't allow a hit in 92/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he wouldn't rule out using 12 pitchers once
right-hander Antonio Osuna (elbow soreness) comes off the disabled
list. Johnson said that decision remains a week to 10 days ahead.
Currently, the Dodgers have 11 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the American League (with Baltimore), sometimes
I wished I had 13,'' Johnson said. ``(Osuna) needs to pitch, just
to be safe, maybe two or three times. It's not like we're in a
panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports were good after Osuna threw a simulated game Thursday.
He is set to begin a rehab stint with Single-A San Bernardino on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go slow so we don't have any setbacks,'' Johnson
said. ``I'd like to see where he can throw three innings down
there. He needs to build (up to) that.''
</P>
<P>
   Walks, balks and chalks: Injured outfielder Todd Hollandsworth
(pulled hamstring) began throwing and jogging and said,
unquestionably, he'd be ready when he's eligible to come off the
disabled list April 18. Hollandsworth said he wants to begin a
rehab assignment late next week so he can get his timing back...
With Paul Lo Duca scheduled to make the start against the Rockies,
it left utility infielder Tripp Cromer and long reliever Dave
Mlicki as the only two Dodgers yet to appear in a game... Johnson
came up with a humorous take on Mel Rojas' outing Wednesday in
which both Arizona hitters he faced homered. ``That wasn't what I
expected, but he did throw strikes,'' Johnson said.... Offensively,
the Dodgers want to improve on last year's lack of production from
their six through eight hitters. In the three-game series with
Arizona, the home team's six through eight hitters were 9 for 36
(.250) with two runs scored and two RBI. Last season the six
through eight batters hit .228.
</P>
</TEXT>
