<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-100DAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR PROCLAIMS FIRST 100 DAYS A SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- Gov. Gray Davis said Thursday he believes
his first 100 days in office have been more productive than any
other administration in four decades, launching reform and higher
expectations in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Republican Assemblyman Tom McClintock, and the Granada
Hills lawmaker laments Davis' term so far as ``100 days of lost
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in between is Diana Dixon-Davis, an education activist
from Chatsworth and a mother of three. Dixon-Davis said the
education reforms that were the focus of the governor's first days
in office have not been ``earthshaking,'' but she's still happy for
any progress at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a sense of relief -- my God, someone up there finally
recognizes we have a problem in our schools,'' Dixon-Davis said.
``I feel like we are getting back to thinking about standards,
accountability and putting money in schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first week of office, during his State of the State
speech, Davis promised to make education his first, second and
third priority, and he didn't disappoint. Davis pushed through his
four education bills at breakneck speed, and Democrats solidly
backed him, allowing for little debate or Republican input along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say, without any false modesty, that my
administration has produced more substantive achievements than any
administration in the last 40 years,'' Davis told reporters
Thursday at a news conference. ``I have established a moderate
course, and we have moved mountains that people thought couldn't be
moved on our most challenging issue: public education.''
</P>
<P>
   All now signed into law, the reforms will implement a peer
review system for teachers, set up a reward and sanction system for
poorly performing campuses, require seniors to pass an exit exam
before graduation and implement intensive reading academies. And,
he successfully pushed for the University of California to approve
a plan that would admit the top 4 percent of the graduating class
of any high school into their campuses, a plan seeking to boost
minority enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   But McClintock's contention is that because of Davis' renowned
caution, the governor's bills became watered down and failed to
seek far-reaching educational reform -- including provisions that
would hold teachers accountable. This, despite Davis being the
first governor in 16 years with a Legislature dominated by his own
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis' great failing is that he is adverse to anything
controversial -- and real change is controversial,'' McClintock
said. ``I believe that because the governor did little to change
the status quo in our schools, in the next four years we are going
to see campuses with more bureaucracy and lower test scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis sees his deliberate method of approaching education reform
as crucial to its passage. But he admitted it wasn't easy. In fact,
he said he grew very depressed at the constant demand by a host of
constituencies for him to ``deal with their problems now.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis believes ``16 years of pent-up demand'' created the lack
of patience.
</P>
<P>
   A slow appointment process in some instances left commissions
unable to operate because they lack the necessary appointees.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he has made strides in other areas besides education.
The governor said he is proud that he has strengthened ties with
Mexico, brought economic relief to farmers hit by this winter's
citrus freeze and negotiated environmental protections for the
old-growth redwoods in the North Coast's Headwaters Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Davis agreed to a temporary salary hike for state workers and
has supported the return to the eight-hour workday, a move critics
say is a political payback to labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Davis vowed Thursday that education issues would continue to
dominate his agenda. He said he would push for all college students
to perform community service before they graduate. And he wants to
increase the involvement of business in education, particularly
looking at corporations to fund textbooks and computer wiring to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Any budget surplus, he said, would likely go to the schools.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
