<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-1ST-ROUND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S WORTH THE WAIT  
 CHAMBLEE'S 3-UNDER 69 GOOD FOR 1ST-ROUND TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ After 12 long years of watching his peers get
eaten up at The Masters, Brandel Chamblee finally was invited to
play at the Godzilla of golf courses known as Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   But in his haste to make his way down Magnolia Lane, the
tree-shrouded driveway that leads to the front door of the club, a
funny thing happened to the pro from Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee, who arrived last Saturday, almost missed the
unpretentious, white-and-green sign that reads: ``Augusta National
_ Members Only.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It snuck up on me,'' he said. ``I came down Washington (Road)
and almost went right past it _ that little, small entrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing Chamblee made a sharp right. Otherwise he wouldn't
have gotten the jump on the competition by getting in a ``few extra
practice rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chamblee was guarded when he arrived Thursday morning for
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard all of the horror stories, about how much the
course changed from practice rounds to tournament rounds,'' noted
Chamblee, who earned his way onto these hallowed but humbling
grounds by winning last year's Greater Vancouver Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much everybody I talked with this week said, `Don't get
used to this,' when you hit a shot and it stopped on the green. So
I didn't know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   How about a tie for the lead with Davis Love III and Scott
McCarron after an opening 3-under 69?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the course played pretty much how I expected it to
play,'' a beaming Chamblee said. ``Television doesn't do it
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many neophytes get their way with ``the National,'' as the
green-jacketed members refer to their course. But Chamblee had his
day, the highlight being a 4-foot eagle at the 13th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit my drive right where I aimed, and that left me 216 yards
from the hole,'' Chamblee reported. ``Then I hit my Zoom by PRGR.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoom?
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like either an iron or a wood. It's ugly the
first time you see it, but when you hit it, it gets much
prettier.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the Zoom is a driving iron and looks like a thick
1-iron. Many pros are picking up the club because it hits the ball
long and straight, perfect for this layout.
</P>
<P>
   Love and McCarron also did a lot of that, each making four
birdies against a lone bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tough out there, and the course played pretty
difficult, too,'' said Love, whose game seems ready to win the
tournament he seeks most. ``The greens, I was surprised how firm
and fast they were. It wasn't the most consistent I've seen them,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, a thunderstorm interrupted play for 95
minutes. When it resumed, the tournament favorite, David Duval,
made his third straight bogey at the 14th hole.
</P>
<P>
   Duval was one of 12 players who failed to complete their rounds
in the light of day. He is 1 under through 17 holes thanks to a
late birdie and will complete his round today. Also with one hole
to play was Zimbabwe's Nick Price, who was 3-under.
</P>
<P>
   The rain was no great surprise. High humidity and temperatures
in the upper 80s had hung around all day. Most players' shirts were
drenched before they reached the first tee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, the defending champ, opened his title defense with
a splendid 70.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there were the usual disasters. Duval got wet at the
13th for one of his bogeys, and Phil Mickelson took a plunge at the
15th, leading to a round of 74.
</P>
<P>
   There also was superior shot-making. Lee Janzen holed out from
the fairway for an eagle 3 at No. 2 en route to a 70. Japan's Jumbo
Ozaki made a rare 2 at the 10th, again with a wedge from the short
stuff, finishing at 71.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a good rally, it was the one strung together by
Tiger Woods, who got sandwiched between two pine cones after he
pulled his drive into the tall Georgia pines on the eighth hole.
That led to a slashing shot across the fairway into an azalea bush,
where he took a penalty drop. He finished with a triple-bogey 8 on
his card.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Woods was 2 over. No problem. Three straight
birdies, beginning at No. 12, the famed middle hole of Amen Corner,
and he was in the red. A bogey at the 17th left him at 72.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blunder was the tee shot,'' Woods explained. ``In the
past, when I'm 2 over I would try to be aggressive. Now I say to
myself, `Be patient.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There is no other way to approach this monster. The weather is
not cooperating, the trees are as terrifying as always, and the
greens appear to be even scarier than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this must be The Masters. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
