<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS OF NELSON SHINES AT AUGUSTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ One hand gripping a wooden cane, the other
clutching his wife's arm, the greatest iron player in golf history
steadied himself and began the slow loving walk he makes here every
spring.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't yet 8 a.m. Augusta National was yawning, stretching,
the grass damp with dew.
</P>
<P>
   An early riser, Byron Nelson had arrived at the course to music
of songbirds and the whispery sounds of employees with brooms
sweeping purple wisteria blooms from the porch of the
plantation-style clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   He first played here in 19-and-35. He won The Masters in 1937,
and again in '42.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who, three years later did something no golfer will do
again, returns every year. He hopes to keep coming back, God
willing, until he dies.
</P>
<P>
   But as for teeing up a ball. In front of cameras and all those
people. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Going down there is hard for me,'' Nelson said, his pale blue
eyes gazing toward the first tee. ``Hitting a ball is harder than
any championship I won. It's the hardest thing I've ever had to do
in golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Nelson, 87, weighed his obligation to tradition against
his pride.
</P>
<P>
   Nodding thanks to well-wishers, the old man in the white straw
hat steeled himself and shuffled on, his hip aching, Peggy at his
side.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys seeing Gene and Sam again. The annual reunion is a
celebration. Their smiles and winks and handshakes say ``Well, we
made it another year.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the first round of The Masters the three honorary
starters are introduced, like members of royalty, even though
introductions are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Those who follow golf and cherish the game's history, know who
they are, and were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now on the tee. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sarazen always has the honors. ``The Squire'' is the
oldest.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson hits next. Born in 1912, ``Lord Byron'' is three months
older than Sam Snead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gene was 90,'' Byron said, smiling at the memory, ``he
told me `I'm ``never'' going to do this again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Sarazen keeps coming back, too. He is 97.
</P>
<P>
   They return to Augusta as if answering some beckoning call. They
make the pilgrimage because winning The Masters was a milestone in
their lives. Because they have a standing invitation to attend the
champions dinner and play here forever if they wish. Their memories
are here. They feel welcome.
</P>
<P>
   This year Nelson feels like a special honoree. A bronze statue
in his likeness was unveiled this week in downtown Augusta. Asked
if he ever dreamed of such an honor, the gentlemanly Texan blinked
from behind his bifocals and said, well, no, of course not.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be awful egotistical,'' he said. ``When you're
playing you never think of that.''
</P>
<P>
   All Nelson thought about during his prime was winning and
winning is what he did. He won 52 professional tournaments. The
golf world buzzes about David Duval being on a roll. In 1945 Nelson
won the Phoenix Open and then claimed 18 more tournament titles,
including a record 11 in a row. The Tour's leading money winner
that year collected $63,336 in War Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   While the years haven't diminished Nelson's memory _ he can tick
off details of rounds he played 60 years ago _ he can't play golf
anymore. Nelson underwent hip replacement surgery in 1990. Another
operation came the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't shift,'' he said, frustration in his voice. He
demonstrated his lack of mobility. ``I can't ``pivot''. . .''
Nelson sounded like a golf instructor giving a lesson to himself.
``I tend to come up.'' Then he voiced his fear of public
embarrassment. ``I top a lot of balls.''
</P>
<P>
   But he performed his obligation Thursday. Trading his cane for a
golf club, Byron Nelson swung as best he could. As he silently
lamented the result, the gallery applauded loud and long for the
man who smiled and took his wife's arm and hobbled back toward the
clubhouse and said, ``Peggy, let's have breakfast.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
