<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-90-BEST/WOR     04-09 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-90-BEST/WORST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCK IS OFTEN KEY INGREDIENT TO DRAFT SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Ortmayer made up his mind the day he watched Nebraska
running back Lawrence Phillips run for 165 yards and two touchdowns
in the 1996 Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Ortmayer, then vice president of the St. Louis Rams, returned to
his office the next day and told team officials he knew the
identity of their No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Phillips, chosen sixth overall in '96, is out
of the NFL and the Rams are saddled with making one of the worst
picks of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the fortunes of the NFL drafts in the 1990s. A lot of
time has been spent on evaluating talent. But some of the best
selections are more luck than skill.
</P>
<P>
   Denver, which has won back-to-back Super Bowls, made one of the
decade's best picks when it took Georgia running back Terrell Davis
in the sixth round in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get all the credit, but if we had known he was that good,
we would have taken him higher,'' said former Broncos scout Jeff
Smith, who first saw Davis in a game against Clemson during Davis'
senior season.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos aren't the only team to have great success in later
rounds of the '90s drafts.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay got quarterback Mark Brunell, now of Jacksonville, in
the fifth round and tight end Mark Chmura in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh took starting strong safety Lethon Flowers in the
fifth round and starting linebacker Carlos Emmons in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Bengals, meanwhile, have the AFC's worst record
this decade, and their blown first-round picks of quarterback David
Klingler (1992), Dan Wilkinson ('94) and Ki-Jana Carter ('95) are a
big reason why.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Washington Redskins' draft record this decade and
you can see one reason why they haven't made the playoffs since
1992.
</P>
<P>
   They used the fourth pick in '92 on Michigan wide receiver
Desmond Howard, who was a bust other than as a return specialist.
Desperate for a quarterback, they took Heath Shuler of Tennessee
third overall in '94, and after being released by New Orleans, he's
out of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people tend to do is overrate players who come from
strong (college) programs, when their supporting cast makes them
better than they are,'' said Gary Horton, editor of the ``War
Room'' draft publication and a former scout for Cleveland and Tampa
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shuler's a guy who didn't have a great feel for running an
offense. He was part of a very successful system (at Tennessee)
that hid his weaknesses. He never had to win games by himself, and
it showed when he got into the pros.'' &QL; 
Good or lucky? &QL; 
Joel Buchsbaum, ``Pro Football Weekly's'' draft expert, doesn't
think the Broncos pick of Davis was as good as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you let a guy hang on the board as long as they did, you
don't think he's a great player,'' Buchsbaum said. ``You
misevaluated him. Everyone misevaluated him. You just misevaluated
him less.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he never thought Davis had potential to be a
2,000-yard rusher when he scouted him. ``He caught a swing pass
(against Clemson) and turned it into a nice play,'' Smith said,
adding that Davis was a ``tweener'' in terms of size and speed who
``flashed some good things.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the second day of the '95 draft came around, the
Broncos still were in need of a running back and had Davis
available on their draft board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike (Broncos Coach Mike Shanahan) decided he wanted another
back for (training) camp,'' said Smith, now a scout for the Miami
Dolphins. ``Fergy and Mike talked it over. Mike pulled the
trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Fergy is Bob Ferguson, vice president-player personnel of the
Cardinals, who was the Broncos' personnel boss at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to Mike's credit and (offensive coordinator) Gary
Kubiak's credit that when they saw Terrell's stuff early in his
first camp, they did the things to take advantage of his skills,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Last season's Super Bowl XXXIII was billed as battle of running
backs: Davis vs. Atlanta's Jamal Anderson, a seventh-round pick in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson still was available in the seventh round because he was
slowed by an ankle injury much of his senior year at Utah and was
used some as a fullback by the Utes even though he wasn't a great
blocker.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons had him rated the third-best back in the draft
behind Marshall Faulk and William Floyd and considered drafting him
as early as the third round.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons shouldn't be considered drafting geniuses for the
Anderson selection. In 1991, they took Nebraska cornerback Bruce
Pickens third overall. He didn't sign until early October,
collapsed at his first practice and remained with the team only one
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just a bad pick,'' Buchsbaum said. ``A lot of people
had him in the second round.'' &QL; 
All downhill &QL; 
The worst pick of the '90s has to be the New York Jets taking Penn
State running back Blair Thomas second overall.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas never recovered from a lengthy holdout as a rookie. In
1992, he had no touchdowns. The next year, he lost his starting job
to former Cardinals running back Johnny Johnson, and, by 1994, he
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone agreed on Blair Thomas that he should have been
picked second (overall),'' Buchsbaum said. ``I asked Jimmy Johnson
(then coach of Dallas) after the draft how he had the backs rated.
He gets a lot of credit for getting Emmitt Smith in that draft, but
they had Blair ahead of Emmitt. The Jets just got stuck with a
lemon.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is a different story. The Rams took him in the first
round even though five teams ahead of them passed because of his
considerable baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-field problems were the reason quarterback Todd
Marinovich (Los Angeles Raiders in 1991) and offensive tackle
Bernard Williams (Philadelphia Eagles in 1994) were busts.
</P>
<P>
   Buchsbaum said those players could easily have been the success
stories Marshall wide receiver Randy Moss was as a rookie with the
Minnesota Vikings last season. Moss lasted until the 21st pick
after getting into trouble at Florida State and Notre Dame. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
