<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1567 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBH-PAYSON-WALDEN-AZR     04-09 1506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBH-PAYSON-WALDEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CAN WE HELP? 
 COMMUNITY RALLIES AROUND PAYSON YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PAYSON, Ariz. - Hunter Walden's duffel bag is filled with thank-you
notes. Between classes at Payson High, before physical therapy,
after baseball practice, late at night, he expresses his gratitude
on blank cards.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has so many to acknowledge in this town of about 13,000.
Construction companies, police officers, doctors, businesses,
teachers, tribal leaders, classmates, coaches.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't stop. Love and support keep pouring in for the town
superstar, who, a little more than two months ago, wondered where
he would find the money to pay for his knee surgery. Five dollars
here. A hundred bucks there. A thousand. Many from unknown sources.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, in four days, the $10,000 needed was raised.
</P>
<P>
   At a $5-a-plate spaghetti dinner organized this week by the high
school to help pay back those who loaned money, about 500 people
showed up at Payson Elementary School. One person handed Pam
Walden, Hunter's mother, a $300 check. She cried.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter never expected this.
</P>
<P>
   He is the senior class president, the three-sport star, the guy
who quarterbacked Payson to the Class 3A football title that ended
Lakeside Blue Ridge's state-record 64-game winning streak, the kid
who set a season state home run record as a junior with 17, and the
person younger boys in Payson grow up trying to emulate. And he is
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People I didn't even know were sending me stuff,'' he said.
``They'd say, `Hey, here's some money. Get better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize the impact I had. I'd be walking down the
street, and a little kid I didn't know would yell, `Hey, how's your
knee?' '' &QL; 
Speedy recovery &QL; 
It's much better, thank you, following surgery to clean out loose
cartilage and hours and hours of therapy for an anterior cruciate
ligament that was 50 percent torn in a Jan. 23 basketball game at
Payson's domed gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   His doctor told him that it would take six to eight weeks before
he could join his baseball teammates. He was back 27 days after the
surgery. The day he was released, while waiting for delivery of a
brace that had been ordered, Walden grabbed his mother's knee brace
and played in a spring tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   He started as the designated hitter but is now back at first
base, hitting .500 with two home runs. At times, he is impatient at
the plate, going after pitches out of the strike zone, still
searching for the stroke that led to 13 home runs in his last 15
games a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past few months, Walden has realized he has so much
more to value than home runs and touchdowns and three-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learned from this the most is that everything can be
taken away in a second,'' Pam Walden said. ``Have other avenues in
case something happens.'' &QL; 
Sense of humor intact &QL; 
Walden now can joke with the maintenance man in Payson's gym about
that fateful game against Cave Creek Cactus Shadows. ``You missed a
spot'' on the floor, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was no wet spot. There was nobody around Walden,
who was on a breakaway layup when he planted his left leg. The
6-foot-1 guard, who was averaging 22 points, heard a pop. And a
crack.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, faced with surgery in order to salvage Walden's
senior season in baseball, the family didn't have the money or
health insurance to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, who owns a dance studio, didn't have Hunter covered
under school insurance. For the football season alone, it was $130.
For a single mother with five children at home, that's a lot of
money. Pam says she regrets her decision. She now has the
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The problem arose when her ex-husband, who had the children
covered under his insurance, switched employers before Hunter's
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Walden, a former Arizona State linebacker who operates
heavy machinery, moved to Phoenix for a higher-paying job to help
support his children, who range in age from 4 to 17 (Hunter is the
oldest).
</P>
<P>
   His new insurance didn't take effect until February. It was too
late to cover Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the times the window to hit right here,'' Pam Walden
said. ``The odds of that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It was a window of misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   Payson Principal Phillip Gille and school counselor Dean
Pederson spearheaded a drive to help the Waldens.
</P>
<P>
   Various school clubs and athletic programs pitched in.
Carwashes. Bake sales. Fund-raisers. A construction company donated
more than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just brought people together that would want to know,''
Gille said. ``They, in all different ways, jumped on the
bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   The student council wrestled with the idea of helping only
Walden, the favored star athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want it to be just because he's an athlete,'' said
Anna Van Zile, student council adviser. ``He really was the guy who
helped bring Payson the state football championship. Even though
he's the president of the student government, we represent the
entire student body and it would look, I think, poorly on us.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting for hours on the matter, the student council
created a hardship fund and donated $1,500 to the Walden family.
</P>
<P>
   As the Waldens repay the donation, the money goes into the
hardship fund. Van Zile said it will be used for others in need.
Two Payson students lost both of their parents this school year.
</P>
<P>
   Pam doesn't want the support to end with her son. With help from
the Tonto Apache Tribe, money was raised by selling Indian fry
bread to help pay off loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that we need to continue,'' Pam said. ``If
there is ever another mother in a situation I'm in, I hope someone
is there to help her.''
</P>
<P>
   But Van Zile sees a potential bee's nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about pushing this into a community type of thing,''
Van Zile said. ``But one of the nice things is working within the
school, we've got these guidelines to go by. So anything that has
to do with substance abuse, `Sorry, you no longer qualify.' We're
trying to be really careful. After talking to some elementary
school teachers, there's a need in this community.'' &QL; 
People pull together &QL; 
Only in a small town can this happen, Donnie Walden tells himself
as he sits in Tolleson, part of an ever-growing metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   The family, which recently paid off the final medical bills,
feels awkward to have taken so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's right when there are so many others worse
off,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was taught the value of giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd always pick a family at Christmas to buy for,'' said
Donnie Walden, who was divorced three years ago but maintains an
amicable relationship with his ex-wife and takes an active role in
his children's lives. ``We didn't know who we'd pick. We'd leave
the gifts on the doorstep and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're giving something hoping to receive something, that's
not what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam said: ``I guess we put our time in to help others. What goes
around, comes around. But, boy, this has really come around big.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waldens settled in Payson when Hunter was 6. He played all
the sports: football, basketball, soccer, baseball. He excelled in
everything, especially football, playing quarterback on Pop Warner
teams since he was in the fourth grade.
</P>
<P>
   He thought about ending his high school career in the Valley at
St. Mary's, where he could get noticed, prove himself against the
best competition and maybe earn a scholarship to ASU like his dad,
who played for Frank Kush in his last year (1979).
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I've played with these guys since preschool. We've
been together since the eighth grade. If I leave, not only do I let
them down, but myself down. If I leave for a bigger school, that's
not the example I want to set,' '' Donnie Walden said.
</P>
<P>
   Last football season, Hunter ran for more than 1,000 yards and
passed for 1,000, leading the Longhorns to a 13-0 record. He capped
the year with a three-touchdown performance in the 3A title game
against Blue Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a hero in Payson,'' Donnie said. ``He's done things
nobody's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie realized how popular his son was last winter when he and
his 14-year-old son, Taylor, took a stroll through a Payson park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids were throwing the football, little kids, getting ready to
play a game,'' Donnie said. ``One kid said, `I'm Jamir Miller.' He
was on defense. Another kid who was the quarterback said, `I'm
Hunter Walden.' There's a big difference there, but that's the way
these kids look at that. Taylor said he was going to go tell
Hunter. I told him not to. He said, `Why, dad? You think his head
will get so big, you'll have to tie him to the ground?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But it makes me feel good as a father that people look up to
him and he's been an example to these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hunter scribbles onto cards, trying to put into words the
debt he believes he owes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the hardest part,'' he said. ``Finding the right words
to thank everybody.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
