<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SCRIMMAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDMOND, HEAP PACE SCRIMMAGE  
 KEALY ACCURATE BUT ISN'T SATISFIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - It was less a scrimmage than a sneak preview of
the 1999 season.  &UR; J.R. Redmond and &UR; Todd Heap made it clear Thursday
that they will be carrying the offensive load for Arizona State in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Redmond rushed for 92 yards and tight end Heap caught
two passes for 23 yards in the Maroon and Gold scrimmage at Sun
Devil Stadium. Both scored touchdowns, with Redmond shedding
several tacklers and running 78 yards for his.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this season that J.R. has got to have the ball a
lot,'' ASU Coach &UR; 
 &UR; Bruce Snyder said, ``particularly because we're so young at wide
receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond also showed that he can play wideout.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback &UR; Ryan Kealy, who has been limited recently because of
knee tenderness, was sharp, completing 6 of 8 passes for 70 yards.
The junior is rarely satisfied with his performance, and Thursday
was no different.``''
</P>
<P>
   `` '' ``I don't think you can ever be happy,'' he said. ``I, we,
still have a lot of work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I can see about this team is there's definitely a
different attitude. We're not setting limits on each other this
year. That's the big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Snyder's concerns during spring ball were evident in the
scrimmage. The team had to go through 70 plays with only seven
healthy offensive linemen. Injuries have contributed to a depth
problem that should improve when the remainder of the recruiting
class reports in August.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of linebackers, too, has set the Sun Devils back this
spring. Thursday, they had five players working three spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain plays we haven't called because there hasn't
been enough linebackers,'' Snyder said. &QL; 
The gift of Flowers &QL; 
No one made more of an impression Thursday than defensive end  &UR; Erik
Flowers, who posted four sacks and was close several other times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great football player,'' Snyder said. ``He's been
possessed playing his position. He's playing as well as J.R. is
playing his spot and Ryan is playing his.`
</P>
<P>
   The defense had a tendency last season to perform well for
several plays and then give up a big one. Although Flowers said he
is grateful that he has been anointed the leader of the unit by
several coaches, he expects leadership behavior from from his
teammates as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense did horrible last year,'' he said. ``We have
something to prove. We have to show people we're a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't call it my defense. If you step on a field, you
should have pride and not want the offense to score. I look at all
of us as leaders. Maybe we shouldn't haven't been rated as high as
we were last year, but there's no excuse for playing the way we
did.'' &QL; 
Trophy talk &QL; 
With Redmond expected to carry much of the offensive load in '99,
the Heisman campaign should kick in gear again. A season-opening
meeting with another Heisman hopeful, &UR; Ricky Williams of Texas Tech,
will only draw attention to the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, who has stressed a team philosophy all off-season, said
he's not worried that a lot of attention will fall on Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a solid person,'' he said. ``And as I told our team,
`Let's go and get him the award.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
