<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-JAZZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULE DOES SUNS NO FAVORS IN PLAYOFF BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Last week, when the Suns were in the midst of
losing five of six games, Suns Coach Danny Ainge looked over the
NBA standings and said not much had changed for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still one of five teams fighting for the last couple of
playoff spots in the West,'' Ainge noted.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Suns are tonight as they begin the 15-game
stretch run against the Utah Jazz at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   But all things are not equal.
</P>
<P>
   If the Suns are going to extend their streak of playoff
appearances to 11 years, they're going to have to do it against
arguably the most difficult schedule of the teams fighting for the
last three of eight Western Conference playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   And that's only if some of the other contenders stumble against
some bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Suns are headed to the draft with two lottery
picks in a draft that's considered mediocre by many analysts _
depending on which underclassmen declare themselves eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no time to be tired,'' guard Jason Kidd said after the
Suns beat Minnesota _ one of those five teams Ainge spoke about _
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only got 15 games left. The most important thing is for
us to make sure we're healthy and make sure we get into the
playoffs, and then we all start over again.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no easy task. Here's how it breaks down for the Suns:
</P>
<P>
   The Suns (17-18) play only seven of their final 15 games against
teams that had sub-.500 records through Wednesday night's games.
They get Dallas twice, Seattle twice, Vancouver once, Denver once
and Sacramento, which is on their heels, once.
</P>
<P>
   The other eight games include three against the defending
Western Conference champion Jazz, two against San Antonio and
Minnesota and one against Houston. They play seven of the 15 at
home, where they have struggled.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (15-20) appear to have the easiest path. First,
they've clinched a tiebreaker with Phoenix should the two end up
tied.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings play 12 of their final 15 against sub-.500 clubs,
including three against the Nuggets, two against Vancouver and two
against the Clippers. They get 11 of 15 games at home, where they
are 7-7. However, they also are two games behind the Suns and three
behind Seattle in the loss column.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (17-17), which moved a half-game ahead of the Suns for
the No. 7 spot by beating Portland, 87-86, on Thursday night, has a
schedule that's comparable to the Suns' in difficulty. The
SuperSonics have 16 remaining, with nine against sub-.500 teams.
Seven are at home, and they get the Clippers, Denver and Dallas
only once each, and Vancouver twice.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State (14-21) has a mixed bag. The Warriors will play 11
of 15 against sub.-500 teams, but they get only six of the 16 on
their home court, where they are 10-9. The Suns have the tiebreaker
on the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (20-14), which played the Clippers in Los Angeles on
Thursday night, appears to be in the best shape to clinch. The
Timberwolves had a 2{-game lead on the Suns before Thursday's game.
Their final 15 games include eight against sub-.500 teams and seven
games at home. The schedule includes one game each against the
Clippers, Dallas and Vancouver, and two against the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are other ways to look at what the Suns face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play our best against the better teams, so maybe it will
work out better for us,'' guard Rex Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns also are the only team among the five with a winning
record on the road. They have beaten Seattle, San Antonio and the
Los Angeles Lakers on the road this season, and they've come close
twice in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   With some luck, the Suns are capable of finishing the season
with a .500 record and extending the playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the part of the year when we need to step up our game
to make that push for a playoff spot, whether it's the eighth spot
or what,'' forward Clifford Robinson said. ``The important thing
now is for us to string some wins together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
