<HEADLINE>
LUMME THRILLED TO RETURN  
 SHOULD HELP ON POWER PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes look at tonight's match-up with Nashville
at America West Arena as a good chance to open space between
themselves and Anaheim and St. Louis in the race for the No. 4 seed
and home ice advantage in the first round of the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It represents much more to defenseman Jyrki Lumme.
</P>
<P>
   It is a release from prison, a situation he equates to being
sidelined because of a shoulder injury that has caused him to miss
the past 16 games and has thwarted him for 30 to 40 other games, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a return, he said, to a lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to tonight,'' said Lumme, who with
seven goals and 20 assists ranks eighth on the team in scoring with
27 points. ``I can't wait to get out there again and feel like I
belong again. It's long days when you're injured and not playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating, especially at his time of year, although
there is never a good time. There's not much you can do about it.
I've never been out this long, at least consecutively, before.''
</P>
<P>
   Lumme, who was signed as a free agent in July to bolster the
defense and power play, said he bided time during rehabilitation by
playing more with his infant daughter, Beanoora, and trying to
maintain his cardiovascular conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting my timing and hockey conditioning back are probably
the two biggest challenges I'll have,'' Lumme said. ``Being in
hockey condition is so different. You can do the (exercise) bike,
you can have hard practices, but once you're out there in a game,
it's so different. It will take a couple of games for me to get my
wind back.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld doesn't plan to nurse Lumme's
return, saying he will step right in on the No. 1 power play unit.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, the power play was showing signs of life
under Lumme's direction. Then the lingering shoulder injury finally
took away his shot after playing hurt for what he said was ``30 to
40 games.'' A decision was made to rest him and get him ready for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the shoulder healthy?'' he said. ``We'll see when I get out
there. Is my shot back? We'll see when I get out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the power play has slumped to the league's
second-worst and is operating at a miserable 11.8 percent and went
0 for 6 in a 1-0 loss to San Jose on Tuesday night. But Lumme's
return and the acquisition of center Robert Reichel from the New
York Islanders figure to add punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to get out there as much as I can,'' Lumme said when
told of Schoenfeld's statement. ``Let's just see how it goes right
now. At least we're in a position where we can kind of experiment
with some stuff. It's not like we're fighting to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean we still want to win, but we can try different things
and get some chemistry back. The power play is usually for whoever
is going best. Sometimes it doesn't make sense to name a No. 1 and
a No. 2 power play unit. We now have two pretty good groups
together. We just need some chemistry and to keep the puck moving
to get chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick said Lumme's return will provide a
necessary spark to a power play that he says is in ``sheer panic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be a big lift,'' Roenick said. ``Anything we can get is
huge to us. Jyrki is a good puck handler. He just has to make sure
he doesn't handle it too much, that's all. He provides those flip
shots, which are sometimes more dangerous than the big slap shot
from the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got hurt, it took away a lot of creativity and our
defensive offense. We have a lot of guys capable of doing the job,
but when he has been healthy, he has been a horse for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lumme said nothing is wrong with the power play that can't be
fixed. He called Tuesday's non-production a classic example of the
team's lingering power outage.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, the guys are getting frustrated,'' he
said. ``When you're on the ice and nothing happens and fans start
booing, you start pressing and try to create something out of
nothing. You don't take your time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against San Jose we had two, actually three, breakaways from
point-blank range. When those chances didn't go, you think, `Holy
smokes,' then really start pressing. You try to get something
quick, instead creating the chances like you had been doing.'' &QL;
</P>
