<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SIGN MEMBER OF NCAA CHAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - David Cullen, a senior defenseman on Maine's NCAA
championship team, has been signed to a multi-year, free-agent
contract by the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen, 22, was Maine's No. 3 scorer this season with 11 goals
and 33 assists for 44 points. He was also third on the team in
power-play goals with seven, and his assist total was second only
to Steve Kariya, younger brother of Anaheim's Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen, 6-foot-2, 209 pounds, was scouted by Coyotes General
Manager Bobby Smith at the NCAA Frozen Four in Anaheim last
weekend, where Cullen notched an assist in the Black Bears' 3-2
overtime win over New Hampshire in the final game. A first-team
All-American, Cullen had 28 goals and 89 assists for 117 points in
four seasons at Maine. He finished two goals short of Maine's
single-season record for defensemen this year, and four short for
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen will report to training camp next season for assignment
in the Coyotes' system. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
