<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-BRAVES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS STRIVE TO BECOME AS GOOD AS BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Diamondbacks close their eyes and wish long
enough, maybe someday they can become like the Atlanta Braves, one
of baseball's dominant clubs of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be shortly after the new millennium begins, or will it
take longer for Arizona to become a playoff-caliber team?
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading the pitching staff over the winter was a start, but a
shaky bullpen must be addressed. The club has tripped over its bats
coming out of the gate after averaging seven runs during the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   After the Diamondbacks were swept by the Los Angeles Dodgers in
their three-game season-opening series, they hope they can emulate
the Braves tonight, Saturday night and Sunday at Turner Field
without becoming the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're consistent,'' said third baseman Matt Williams, who
had two home runs in the LA series, the first of which was the
300th of his career. ``Their pitching, of course, has been good.
They just do everything right. They catch the ball well, they hit
it, they're a well-rounded team. That's the type of team you want
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not there yet, but we're getting closer, even though we
lost that series. We played them tough for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Omar Daal will be making his first start of the
season after finishing fifth in the National League in ERA in 1998
at 2.88.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of good hitters,'' Daal said. ``If you miss
a pitch, you're going to be in trouble. Hopefully, I can keep the
game close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves lost first baseman Andres Galarraga for the season as
he battles cancer, but they still have plenty of firepower with
third baseman Chipper Jones, outfielder Brian Jordan, catcher Javy
Lopez and Ryan Klesko, who has moved from the outfield to fill in
for Galarraga at first.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the pitching. Left-hander Odalis Perez pitches
against Daal tonight, with left-hander Tom Glavine, the 1998 Cy
Young Award winner, waiting to pitch Saturday and right-hander Greg
Maddux on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their starting pitching is what makes them successful, without
question,'' second baseman Jay Bell said. ``It's tough to score
runs on them. You have to have your total concentration in every
at-bat. Our starters are capable of being like that. The key is
jumping on those guys early. If you do that, you've got a chance.
They seem to get better as the game goes along.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks hit eight home runs against the Dodgers but did
little else. They'll need to raise their .214 average to have a
chance. The bottom part of the order needs to pick up the pace.
Shortstop Tony Batista is hitless in 12 trips, and catcher Kelly
Stinnett is just 1 for 9.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter said the Braves' staff ``makes you earn
everything you get. They don't walk many, and it's tough to string
three or four hits together against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The most underpublicized part of Atlanta's game is its defense,
according to Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best in baseball, if not the best,'' he said.
``(Walt) Weiss at shortstop and (Bret) Boone at second _ you're not
going to find many better there. And (Otis) Nixon, (Andruw) Jones
and Jordan in the outfield _ they can really run it down. They
don't really have any weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter hopes people say that about the Diamondbacks one day.
He also hopes he'll still be the manager when they say it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
