<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS DEFEAT METS, 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The New York Mets are now 0 for 2 in other teams'
home openers. And Orel Hershiser is 0-1 as a member of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   In his first regular-season start since signing with the Mets
during spring training, Hershiser lasted only four innings in a 5-1
loss to the young Montreal Expos. It was hard to tell what cost the
Mets more: Hershiser's inconsistency on the mound, or the Mets'
uncharacteristic poor defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he pitched as well as he can,'' Manager Bobby
Valentine said of Hershiser, the Mets' fourth starter. ``And I know
we didn't play behind him as well as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser's inauspicious four-inning debut as a Met came against
a festive, if concerned, backdrop. Thursday night was the Expos'
31st home opener. And there are chances that it could be their last
here before the franchise moves to either northern Virginia or
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But if Major League baseball was looking for signs that Montreal
wants to keep the team, there were plenty to go around at Olympic
Stadium, which was nearly full. A cluster of fans carried around a
five-placard message reading ``Hey, Bud, Read Our Lips: Claude Must
Go!'' a plea to baseball commissioner Bud Selig that was referring
to Claude Brochu, the unpopular team president and general partner
of the Expos and the person cited by many as trying to run the team
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the signs here, it brought the biggest cheers. And the
near-capacity crowd of 43,918 _ the team's biggest in nearly three
years _ cheered loud and often, especially once the game began
because Hershiser started shakily and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old right-hander had not allowed a run in seven
official spring innings with the Mets and five more in a minor
league spring game. But Vladimir Guerrero singled home Orlando
Cabrera from second with two out in the first inning for the game's
first run.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fullmer followed Guerrero's single with a liner to right
that went for a triple after it skipped past Bobby Bonilla.
Guerrero scored.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser did not help matters much with his base running. After
the Montreal right-hander Miguel Batista walked both Hershiser and
Rickey Henderson to open the third, he nearly picked Hershiser off.
And after Edgardo Alfonzo squared to bunt on Batista's next pitch,
catcher Chris Widger picked Hershiser off.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Widger fired a perfect strike to nail
Henderson as he attempted to steal.
</P>
<P>
   But Batista allowed a solo homer to Alfonzo two pitches later,
and the Mets had sliced the deficit in half to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the third, Hershiser's defense failed him
again. This time, it was the Mets' two-time Gold Glove winner,
shortstop Rey Ordonez, who threw away a Rondell White grounder for
a two-base error. Guerrero followed by looping a soft liner over
Alfonzo at second for his second run-scoring single of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And then Fullmer launched a ball to deep center. After a long
run, Brian McRae caught up with the ball and leaped for it before
the wall. But the ball glanced off McRae's glove for a double, as
Guerrero advanced to third. Two pitches later, Shane Andrews rifled
a two-run single up the middle. And it was 5-1 Montreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
