<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-REVISED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD ACCEPTS WHAT FATE DEALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mo Vaughn's trip to the disabled list gives the Angels
nine who are out with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the healthy Angels? While some admit that they
can't forget who's not on the field, others _ like Darin Erstad _
refuse to worry about what's out of their control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer, and my dad always pounded this into my
head, that things happen for a reason one way or another,'' Erstad
said. ``With that approach, you don't have to worry about anything
else other than what you do once you step on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Injuries happen, and with our team they happen a lot. But one
of these years we're going to get rewarded for our hard work. It
will pay off for us some time. I believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Angels on the DL are pitchers Jason Dickson, Pep
Harris, Mike James and Jack McDowell, infielders Justin Baughman
and Gary DiSarcina and outfielders Jim Edmonds and Reggie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad has been on the DL as well in his career, but it has
happened near the end of the season when it seemed his body wore
down. He went into spring training this year with a slightly
different approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it easy the first couple of weeks of spring training,''
he said. ``Just got my feet under me a little bit. I'm eager for
the challenge of a full season. There's something to be said for
playing a full season. You can walk away saying you gave it your
all, and accept the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will call up first baseman Chris Pritchett from
Triple-A to replace Vaughn on the roster. Pritchett was the final
cut from the roster after a solid spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers need relief: Tim Belcher and Ken Hill each lasted only
41/3 innings in the Angels' first two games, putting an unwanted
burden on the bullpen at such an early point in the season. But
that's exactly why Collins and his coaching staff decided to begin
the season with 12 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here wondering if we've got enough even now,''
Collins said. ``We're going to be as cautious as we can early in
the year. Twelve pitchers gives us the opportunity to be
cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming: The Angels begin a four-game series in Texas tonight
against the Texas Rangers. Pitching matchups for the series:
Tonight (5:35 p.m.), Chuck Finley vs. John Burkett; Saturday (5:35
p.m.), Omar Olivares vs. Rick Helling; Sunday (5:05 p.m.), Tim
Belcher vs. Aaron Sele; Monday (11:35 a.m.), Ken Hill vs. Mark
Clark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
