<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALM DOWN, D-BACKS ARE OK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The hottest topic in the Valley these days centers
around the Diamondbacks and their failures while starting the
season 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable considering where the Diamondbacks are
coming from, which is basically the trash heap when you remember
their only season resulted in 97 losses.
</P>
<P>
   But these are not the Brent Brede and Efrain Valdez
Diamondbacks. They're not even remotely close to resembling last
year's expansion group.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last season, this is not a bottom-feeding club. The
skeptics, however, are out en masse, ready to stick a dagger
through the Diamondbacks and pronounce them worse than last year's
club after just one series.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, folks. Lighten up. The 1999 Arizona Diamondbacks will be
fine soon enough. Within weeks, those same doubters won't be
rushing to jump back on the bandwagon. They'll be driving it,
telling everyone how they never wavered.
</P>
<P>
   They're probably the same people who routinely crucified the
Cardinals only to turn into the biggest Cardinal honks in the
Valley during the playoff run last season.
</P>
<P>
   It's unquestioned that the 1999 Diamondbacks have holes that
cannot be hidden. Shortstop Tony Batista has not looked good at the
plate and his range in the field is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has been shaky and the duo behind the plate of Kelly
Stinnett and Damian Miller has not done much to stand out, either
at the plate or with their calling of games. Stinnett has
particularly struggled, catching for 15 of the 17 runs Arizona has
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   There are definite flaws. However, they are nowhere near the
defects the inaugural version had on its roster. This is a club,
like so many other good ones in the National League, with
weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look around the NL and Mordecai ``Three Fingers'' Brown
would have trouble coming up with his own handful of sound clubs.
The Atlanta Braves jump to mind, as do the Houston Astros and Los
Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But each of those clubs is applying a Band-Aid or two to its
roster. The days of the rock-solid ballclub with no glaring
weaknesses are long gone everywhere outside the south Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians, generally considered the second-best club
in all of baseball, has a pitching staff that has a huge question
mark looming over it. It's the single-biggest reason Indians
General Manager John Hart calls Philadelphia GM Ed Wade several
times a week, wanting to know if Curt Schilling has become
available.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are missing Moises Alou, out for the season, have
health concerns with third baseman Ken Caminiti and are still
searching for a dependable everyday shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were dealt a big blow when first baseman Andres
Galarraga was diagnosed with cancer during spring training. But
even before then, the Braves had worries with their relievers, a
source of anxiety for years.
</P>
<P>
   All around, the very best clubs in the league have obvious
issues to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Recall last season's three NL division champions _ San Diego,
Houston and Atlanta. What was the common denominator they all
shared and everyone else envied? Solid and dependable starting
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the Braves' and their star-studded rotation,
Houston's acquisition of Randy Johnson to go along with Shane
Reynolds and Mike Hampton or San Diego's big two of Kevin Brown and
Andy Ashby, the foundation for winning was based around the same
principle, starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   It's why the New York Yankees rumbled through the season and the
playoffs virtually untouched. It was the reason Boston, with
comeback seasons from Bret Saberhagen and Tim Wakefield to
compliment All-Star Pedro Martinez, made a surprising return to the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, it always comes down to pitching in the major
leagues. It's why Brown and Johnson were ``the'' most sought-after
free agents on the market last winter.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' long-term plans are definitely open for
criticism, but loading up on starting pitching will pay its
dividends this season.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the baseball season is still a 162-game marathon, not
a one-week sprint. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
