<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NASTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGH BUT NOT ALL TOUGH: NEW AUGUSTA FAILS TO MASTER FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ An off-season facelift at Augusta National Golf
Club produced a fresh collection of front-runners in Thursday's
opening round of the Masters Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But it failed to produce the rash of higher scores that course
officials envisioned when they significantly redesigned four holes
after the 1998 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when play was suspended because of darkness with 12
golfers remaining on the course, the average score of first-round
competitors in this year's tournament was almost a stroke better,
at 74.5, than first-round scores in 1998 (75.4).
</P>
<P>
   Just don't count on that becoming a weeklong trend, said Davis
Love III, one of three players to finish at 3-under-par 69 and take
a share of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes, they look very good, and I think they make the
course play a little harder. We'll probably see that borne out over
time,'' said Love, who joins Scott McCarron and Brandel Chamblee
atop the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, who must return at 8 a.m. Friday to play the final
hole of his opening round, also is at 3-under. That means none of
the top four players on the leader board has ever wrapped himself
in a Masters green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Two have come close: Love, a runner-up in 1995, and Price, who
set the Augusta course record with a 63 in the 1986 tournament.
Chamblee and McCarron, on the other hand, sit atop an Augusta
leader board for the first time in their PGA Tour careers.
</P>
<P>
   For Chamblee, a Masters rookie who played college golf at the
University of Texas, this qualifies as an unexpected pleasure. A
former cutting horse competitor, Chamblee compared the excitement
of being in the hunt at the Masters to the rush that comes from
getting a foot caught in the saddle while falling off a horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same sort of feeling,'' said Chamblee, 36, who calmed
his racing adrenaline with three birdies and an eagle, offset by
two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Price, who missed a chance to take the lead by misfiring on a
10-foot birdie putt at No. 17 in the dwindling twilight, could go
into the record books as the solo first-round leader if he birdies
No. 18 before starting Friday's second round. Other players under
par during partial rounds halted Thursday included David Duval
(1-under, 17 holes) and Stewart Cink (1-under, 15 holes).
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks was at 2-over through 14 holes
when play was suspended after a 90-minute weather delay. Hank
Kuehne, the U.S. Amateur champion from SMU, shot 2-over and played
in the final group to complete its opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne suggested Masters officials may have added an
unadvertised twist in their attempt to make the course play more
difficult: wet landing areas for longer hitters. Kuehne, who
averaged 292 yards per drive, said he kept finding ``a lot of mud''
on his ball after splitting a fairway before the afternoon rain
delay, while playing partner Mark O'Meara (264-yard average) did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Kuehne's theory may be found in the fact that Tiger
Woods, who averaged more than 322 yards per pop while winning the
1997 Masters, averaged 296 yards off the tee Thursday yet still led
the field in driving distance.
</P>
<P>
   Among Augusta's more tangible changes, which included major
revisions at Nos. 2, 11, 15 and 17, all four holes had a higher
difficulty rating Thursday than during the 1998 tournament. Yet the
course, overall, played easier than during the opening round a year
ago despite several well-tucked pin placements.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron, like Love, attributed that to benign winds and said
scores likely will rise as the week progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you're in the rough, it's a guessing game,''
McCarron said. ``That's only going to get worse as the greens get
tougher and the fairways get faster and firmer.''
</P>
<P>
   For a day, at least, the touring pros made Augusta's off-season
course changes seem minimal rather than revolutionary. Whether that
continues until Sunday remains to be seen. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
