<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-WNBA-LAWYER-AZR &LR;      04-09 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-LAWYER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY LAWYER TAKES UP WNBA LABOR FIGHT  
 EX-CBA ADMINISTRATOR EAGER TO START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As Pamela Wheeler sat in her 14th-floor downtown
Phoenix office last fall reading in the ``Sports Business Journal''
about WNBA player ratification of its union, her phone began to
ring. And ring. And ring.
</P>
<P>
   The callers all asked the same question: Did you see that story?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reading the article,'' Wheeler said. ``I think it's
something for me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Something perfect for a woman who at age 6, according to her
father, announced that she was going to be a sports attorney. After
growing to only 5 feet 4, impeding a basketball career, she
followed through on her childhood plan by earning degrees from
Dartmouth and Boston University Law School while interning in the
legal departments of the San Francisco Giants and Oakland
Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after an 18-month stint with the Continental Basketball
Association headquartered in the Valley and a weekend appearance as
a bridesmaid in her sister's wedding, Wheeler begins work Monday in
her native New York as operations director of the Women's National
Basketball Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Although Billy Hunter, as NBPA executive director, is the chief
executive of the collective bargaining agency for NBA and WNBA
players, the 32-year-old Wheeler takes the point for the women at a
critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   If an agreement between the union and league is not reached by
Saturday, WNBA President Val Ackerman said, the June 10 start of
the season could be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long ago when we started the bargaining, we made it clear to
the players we didn't have a lot of time,'' Ackerman said. ``We
have a lot of activities in April that are important to the
operation of the league, and we needed to do it in a certain way
with some lead time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all still true. Time is getting short. My hope is
people understand the urgency attached to making a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wheeler, hired March 30 and on the fast track getting up to
speed on negotiations, the urgency is not Saturday's deadline,
which primarily puts only next week's pre-draft camp in jeopardy.
Her priority is to get the league to budge off its $20,000 minimum
salary offer for a four-month season.
</P>
<P>
   The players, who except for a few with personal services
contracts earned $15,000 to $62,500 last year, twice have lowered
their minimum salary demand to $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler understands money.
</P>
<P>
   She shouts the word instead of ``cheese'' to bring a smile to
her face while being photographed. Like the players who opted for
the WNBA instead of the better-paying but now-defunct American
Basketball League, she gave up money by not taking the corporate
path of her law school classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have already been too many comparisons to the (NBA) men
that are just unwarranted,'' Wheeler said. ``The issues are just
diametrically apart, they're not even in the same ballpark. Because
of that, I don't think we're in a situation where we even want to
consider not starting the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women made a number of sacrifices initially, which is
proof they're willing to work with the league. They're not
interested in bankrupting the league. I use the example of
Microsoft. A number of people took jobs in Microsoft and they
didn't get outright salaries, they got stock options and they made
sacrifices to help build that company. Once that company became an
empire, they were greatly rewarded. Now the women just want an
opportunity to be modestly rewarded for their efforts in helping to
build women's basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   No one pretends the 12-team WNBA, with a per-game average
attendance of 10,869 last season, is an empire or even that pro
women's basketball in the United States is a lock with all players
in one league.
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Levy, the agent for more than 30 WNBA players,
estimates the league made about $25 million more than projected for
the first two years because of success stories such as the Mercury.
Including playoff games, Phoenix has drawn more than 440,000
spectators (13,760 average) for 32 dates at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Because of being located in the Valley with the CBA, first as
assistant to former Commissioner Steve Patterson and for the past
year as director of business development, Wheeler has seen the
Mercury phenomenon up close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my (CBA) responsibility was sponsorship and how do you
get people in arenas,'' she said. ``When I went to the Mercury
game, I thought, `Is this not a great marketing opportunity? How do
you get fans so involved?' It's almost like WWF. That was the part
that amazed me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of expecting not to see men there. But I saw a lot
of men with what I assumed to be their daughters, which I thought
was really interesting, too. I was like, `Wow, we're on to
something here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   CBA Commissioner Gary Hunter said the women's union hired
someone special in Wheeler, whose restaurateur father, Bobby,
taught her a jump shot in junior high and joined with her mother,
Virginia, a sergeant first class in the Army, in stressing
education and independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is mature beyond her age,'' Hunter said. ``She's a
strategic thinker and extremely personable. Those qualities are
going to carry her far. I'm very disappointed we're going to lose
her after only 18 months, but that's part of what we do, develop
new talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say she is the Billy Hunter of the WNBA. I say no,
Billy Hunter is the Pam Wheeler of the NBA.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
