<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ASU-TRANSFERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFERS INTERESTED IN ASU  
 COLORADO PLAYERS LIKE TURNER THORNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Two of the four sophomore women's basketball
players transferring from the University of Colorado have Arizona
State at the top of their wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki Swagger, a 6-foot-3 forward, has virtually committed to
ASU, saying Thursday she is looking nowhere else. Melody Johnson, a
6-2 center, plans to visit ASU in two weeks and expects to make a
decision after that trip.
</P>
<P>
   Both must sit out a season, then will have two years of
eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The other Colorado transfers are Nikki Weddle, whose interest in
ASU probably will not be reciprocated because point guard is not a
need position, and forward Chaquita Dilworth, who is returning to
her native Texas to play for Stephen F. Austin, which this week
signed guard Rhonda Rajsich of Phoenix College.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players have left Colorado in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Charli Turner Thorne cannot comment on the potential
transfers until paperwork certifying their scholarship release is
received.
</P>
<P>
   Both Swagger and Johnson were recruited out of Colorado Springs
high schools by Turner Thorne in her first season at ASU. They were
prep rivals: as juniors Johnson's Palmer High team upset Swagger's
undefeated, defending state champion Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   If ASU lands both posts, they will replace 6-4 Rachel Holt and
6-foot Kristine Sand, who have one year of eligiblity left, and
team with 6-3 Theresa Jantzen and 6-2 Leah Combs for their final
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my experience, she (Turner Thorne) is a very honest, good
person,'' Johnson said. ``That's very important to me. I'm looking
more for a coach than a program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember her and what she is about. I see a connection with
her, and I think we'd have a good player-coach relationship. ASU is
my first choice. They say the grass is not always greener, but I'm
willing to give it a try.''
</P>
<P>
   Already with 46 career blocks, Johnson averaged 12.8 points and
4.4 rebounds off the bench in the Buffs' final eight games,
including 14 points in 14 minutes in a WNIT loss to Drake. She has
career averages of 7.9 points and 3.5 rebounds and 22 career
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very comfortable in the low post,'' Johnson said.
``I'm not the tallest center, but I play bigger than I am, and I'm
deceivingly quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson played on a BCI summer team with ASU sophomore forward
Kellie McDanal of Conifer, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ASU, Texas A&AMP;M and Colorado were finalists out of high school
for Swagger, who also visited Kansas State and Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was thinking of a place to go, I thought back about my
initial picks and about my trip to Arizona and Coach Turner,''
Swagger said. ``I knew I liked it when I went there, that the
players were like a team. When I spoke with her (Wednesday), I got
the same feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Swagger played a small role with the 15-14 Buffs, averaging 5.7
minutes, 1.4 points and 2.1 rebounds in 21 games. As a freshman on
a 12-16 team, she averaged 5.0 points and 4.6 rebounds and made
nine starts.
</P>
<P>
   Transferring is ``a choice I made based on my happiness here,''
Swagger said. ``It was time to go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU is coming off a 12-15 season, its most wins in six years,
and tied for sixth in the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   The team returns four starters, including Jantzen who made the
Pac-10 All-Freshman team. But it loses starting small forward Leaf
Newman, a sophomore who is transferring. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
