<HEADER>
A1623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-CAPITALS-N     04-09 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SHUT OUT CAPITALS, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils clinched their
third straight Atlantic Division title on Thursday night with a 1-0
victory over the Washington Capitals, becoming the first team to
take a third straight crown since the Philadelphia Flyers 12 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little celebrating in the Devils' dressing room
because they played far below the standard of an elite team for the
second game in a row. Although this was a victory, the Devils'
performance was poorer than in Tuesday's loss at Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek and several players said that clinching the
division title and having a chance to finish first in the Eastern
Conference was of less significance than performing well going into
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the scheme of things, when you take care of the little
things the big things take care of themselves,'' Ftorek said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rolston, who scored the game's only goal, said, ``It's
fine and good if you win the division and the conference, but the
Stanley Cup is the most important thing you want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils failed to gain any ground in the Eastern Conference
as the Ottawa Senators defeated the Toronto Maple Leafs, 3-1,
tonight to maintain a 3-point lead as the top team. But the Devils
(43-23-11) have a game in hand on the Senators (44-22-12).
</P>
<P>
   For the Devils to have a chance to overtake the Senators for the
conference title, they will need the services of the injured Jason
Arnott, the center for Patrik Elias and Petr Sykora. They have been
the team's most productive line, especially in the last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott missed his second game in a row on Thursday night because
of a bruised right hip. His place in the loss to Carolina was taken
by Brendan Morrison, but on Thursday night Ftorek decided to put
Sykora at center and use Vadim Sharifijanov in Sykora's place at
right wing.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals, who were swept by Detroit in last season's Stanley
Cup finals, were eliminated from the playoffs a day earlier. They
played on Thursday night without eight regulars, most of them out
with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Capitals were short-handed, Rolston's goal was
all the Devils could accomplish offensively. The defense was much
better, however, limiting the Capitals to 15 shots against Martin
Brodeur, who earned his fourth shutout of the season and 36th of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was great,'' said Brodeur, whose record is
36-10-10. ``It's good to see that the one goal held up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston's goal was the 20th of the season and marked the first
time that the 26-year-old wing has reached that plateau. But the
goal was also his first in 16 games. It came from close range on
the left after he collected a rebound from a shot by Sheldon Souray
and had plenty of time to beat Olaf Kolzic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't scored in a few games,'' Rolston said. ``That's why
this was a big one tonight. Winning the division is great, but we
want to play our best in the five games we have left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
