 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; SERB COUGHS UP THE TRUTH: `MILOSEVIC CAN'T LOSE' &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;   &UR; (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ If you want to talk to the free press in Belgrade,
hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette smoke in Radomir Diklic's cluttered Beta news
agency office is as thick as fog, great swirling blue wreaths of it
that have the ladies banging open the windows for air above Srpskih
Vladara street.
</P>
<P>
   Diklic smokes himself, of course, a small agitated man with a
potbelly and uncombed hair who breathes through his cigarette until
I am coughing over my notes. But there is a lot to cough about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our friends from the Western embassies here,'' he says.
``We had a lot of contacts and we warned them that the day the
first bomb drops, they could count on the fact that everyone will
be for the defense of their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you people _ NATO _ did a good job for Slobodan Milosevic.
It was the best present he could be given. For ordinary people,
Milosevic is now a god; when you bombed, he became a symbol of our
country _ which is awful.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Note TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, totaling 200 words; uncut
1,025) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-MILOSEVIC-CAN'T-LOSE-600&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATO'S `CLOBBA SLOBBA' NONSENSE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Provocative Commentary) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Instead of admitting the truth about the current
Kosovo conflict, our leaders have consistently lied to us. It has
all gone horribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the initial objectives are recalled, then we have
already lost this war. And it is not only the tragedy of Biblical
proportions on the Balkan mountainsides that proves the futility of
what we have done.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two weeks ago, we thought we had gone to war to save the
Kosovo Albanians. Now it turns out that we are at war to save NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The 12,000 soldiers who were meant to look after the Kosovo
Albanians are now doing just that _ but in the wrong country,
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb civilians of Kosovo, whom they were also meant to
protect, are now being bombed by us. The destabilization of the
southern Balkans, which we went to war to prevent, is now well
underway... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Note 300-word OPTIONAL TRIM at 875. Total uncut is
1,450) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-WE'VE-LOST-FOOLISH-WAR-875&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOMBS AND BOMBAST: WAKE UP, 1999 NEVILLE CHAMBERLAINS! &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Pithy Commentary) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID AARONOVITCH, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ We pampered Westerners are all very martial as long as
we are only dropping ordnance from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The air is now thick with the stink of attitudinizing. Every
columnist, reporter, letter-writer, pub bore and backbencher knows
what should have been done, and what ought to be done now.
</P>
<P>
   What I believe about Kosovo _ that we had little alternative but
to intervene, and that we should now begin to deploy an army
charged with winning it back for its dispossessed people _ is not
the consequence of deep strategic and military insight. It is,
rather, a product of conscience allied to a deep worry about what
would happen elsewhere were we to fail this test... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Note 325-word OPTIONAL TRIM at 600. Total uncut is
1,175) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS
BC-ARMCHAIR-WARMONGERS-OPED-600&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YK2 BABIES: WHAT WILL THEIR FUTURE BE? &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: Friday, April 9, a Millennium baby will be conceived) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By GEOFFREY LEAN, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This Friday, somewhere in the world, a historic baby will start
its journey into life. For then _ the 266 days of an average
pregnancy away from the turn of the year _ the first child of the
new millennium will be conceived.
</P>
<P>
   No one will know who or where it is, as it grows towards its
date with destiny spinning gently in its mother's womb. It may be
born rich or poor, male or female, black, brown, yellow or white _
in circumstances as diverse as the wide world itself.
</P>
<P>
   The real millennium baby is most likely to be born with no clock
in sight, with no record of its time of birth. It may not even live
long enough to be given a name. For there are nine chances in 10
that it will arrive in the Third World, rather than in the West _
and four in 10 that it will be born into extreme poverty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: This story stands in 475 words. Total uncut is
1,250.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-WOE-BABIES-MILLENNIUM-475&AMP;add-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BODY AND SOUL: A DAY OF RECKONING WITH GOD'S MUSCLE MEN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANN TRENEMAN, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Henderson is the largest man I have ever met. He is 6-ft.,
5-in. and weighs 390 lbs., but those statistics cannot do justice
to his extreme gigantism. He is a fridge-freezer with skin.
</P>
<P>
   He has come to east London from Texas to tell me what it is like
to be a Muscle Man for God.
</P>
<P>
   James, plus some 25 others, are members of the ``Power Team.''
In between breaking walls of concrete, bending steel bars, snapping
baseball bats and ripping up phone books, they talk about the Lord.
The whole thing is a bit like evangelical wrestling... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (950 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-BICEPS-FOR-JESUS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `STAR WARS' PHENOMENON: THE FORCE TO BE RECKONED WITH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (NOTE: MAY 29 U.S. opening of `Star Wars' mega-movie) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ANDREW GUMBEL, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Force is about to be with us once more, this
time in the form of a brand new ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' opens in the
United States on May 19, but already it feels as though it has been
with us for months. Hollywood loves a sure winner, and winners
don't come much surer than this one.
</P>
<P>
   The only real questions are whether the film will manage to earn
$100 million on its opening weekend, a feat never before achieved,
and whether its total gross receipts will hit the near-mythical
target of one billion _ that's right, folks, billion _ dollars.
</P>
<P>
   What is about the ``Star Wars'' phenomenon, anyway? Why do
people, especially young people, find the films so
irresistible?... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,050 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVED AS BC-WHY-`STAR-WARS'-OBSESSION?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
