<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1649 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     04-09 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS BEAT MINNESOTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers, who've stockpiled enough grief to
freeze a batch for later, began Thursday's work shift at the Sports
Arena by discovering a new predicament:
</P>
<P>
   An opponent scorned.
</P>
<P>
   Going in with a 3-30 record, they had yet to face down the
bitter feelings of revenge carried by a team they had beaten in
their last encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Going against them were the playoff-bound Minnesota
Timberwolves, who were beaten by the Clippers 18 days ago in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers suggested the previous result was no fluke by
beating the Timberwolves 99-91 in front of 7,205, ending their
losing streak at six.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves (20-15), who were clobbered Wednesday by the
Phoenix Suns, had a dandy alibi _ point guard Terrell Brandon was
home with a bruised thigh. But if they had lost, the Clippers had a
better alibi _ the co-stars in those 30 defeats were all here.
</P>
<P>
   One crucial appearance was made by power forward Maurice Taylor,
who missed the two previous beatings thanks to bilateral Achilles
tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor scored 20 points and had eight rebounds (a personal
revelation) in a command performance against Minnesota's big and
jumpy front line.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the Clippers' bonanza was the cold marksmanship
of Kevin Garnett. The 7-foot Garnett, a four-year pro whose high
school-to-NBA learning curve was taken on two wheels, missed 16 of
21 field-goal attempts through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Two Eric Piatkowski free throws gave the Clippers a 68-56 lead
going into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When the Clippers reach that fork in the road to victory, they
usually pick it up and take turns stabbing it in their eyes. But
when Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders deployed the obligatory
trapping defense _ the same monster Phoenix used in rallying to
beat the Clippers on Tuesday _ the home team refused to yield.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, as prescribed by coach Chris Ford, was attacking the
defense rather than rolling over. Putting the bite in the Clippers
offense was forward Lamond Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Murray scored nine points in the final quarter, and veteran
playmaker Sherman Douglas _ who finished with a season-high 16
points _ was key against Minnesota's defensive pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first return to the Sports Arena since the Clippers
waived him last month was James ``Hollywood'' Robinson, who just
signed his second 10-day contract with Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanna know,'' Robinson said before tipoff, ``was how I
can't get any minutes on a losing team, then go to a playoff team
and be in the rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight minutes later, Robinson and his new cronies, must
have been at a loss to explain it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
