<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES CAMPAIGN TO START TV ASSAULT THIS MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another sign of what is becoming a prematurely overheated
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination, publishing
magnate Steve Forbes will launch his first nationwide ad campaign
later this month, a full nine months before the first primary
election.
</P>
<P>
   The media blitz will air most heavily in Arizona, New Hampshire
and Iowa, states with key early contests, according to a Forbes
campaign official.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes used television to stunning effect in 1996, running ads
that ultimately won him victories in two presidential primaries,
Arizona and Delaware, even though he had never run for elective
office. The self-financed Forbes campaign spent $4 million in
Arizona and $37 million nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we're going to be bombarded with ads from now
through November (2000),'' said Larry Makinson, director of the
Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington, D.C.-based
organization that tracks campaign finance issues, when he learned
of the campaign. ``I'm beginning to feel what they are feeling in
Belgrade right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to former Vice President Dan Quayle downplayed Forbes'
ability to dump huge sums of his own money on an ad campaign,
saying Forbes is doing what everyone expected him to do: spend his
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will make one bit of difference,'' said Fred
Davis, Quayle's media advisor. ``When your greatest strength is
your deep pockets, you play to your greatest strength, and that's
the only one he has.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of ads paid for by a presidential campaign before
the end of April surprises even longtime campaign observers.
</P>
<P>
   The quick start will put increasing pressure on other candidates
to come out with their own ads, according to Makinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the kid in the class that wrecked the curve for
everyone else,'' he said. ``If one candidate is on the air, it's
going to be more and more difficult for other candidates to stay
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Makinson argued that a sustained television presence so early in
the campaign could shell-shock candidates like Quayle, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former Family Research Council
President Gary Bauer, all of whom are ``out there making their
pitches as to why they are credible when someone else is already on
TV in May.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It undercuts their argument that they've got a chance,''
Makinson said. ``There are a lot of reasons that people give to
campaigns, but pragmatism is one of them. This year more than any
other, donors are going to separate the candidates with potential
from the lost causes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Quayle campaign's Davis predicted the Forbes ads will be the
only ones that viewers see for a while, not because other
candidates aren't interested in making their own, but because they
can't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you look at the fund-raising reports?`` Davis asked,
referring to the first round of financial reports filed by
candidates with the Federal Election Commission on March 31. ``We
were the second-highest, and we were a third of (Texas Gov. George
W.) Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``There's no one right now who can step up to the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Makinson said the greatest impact of a Forbes media blitz could
fall on Bush, who reportedly is considering whether to opt out of
the federal campaign finance system entirely in order to be able to
match Forbes dollar for dollar in the primary. Candidates who
accept federal matching funds must abide by severe contribution
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Steve Forbes stands much chance of winning the
presidency,'' Makinson said, ``but it does give George W. Bush a
rationale for opting out, and I think it's something his staff
wants to do.``
</P>
<P>
   All candidates should think twice about filling the airwaves
with ads so soon, according to Makinson, noting they risk
alienating an already wary public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a guaranteed good reception or bad
reception,`` he said. ``If these ads aren't good, they could
backfire. People just don't want to be reminded this soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes national co-chairwoman Dodie Londen said she was aware
that the candidate might launch the ad campaign, but she had no
details. Londen, a former chairwoman of the Arizona Republican
Party, defended the decision, saying Forbes must worry about
raising his name identification in states like Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes may also have cause for concern in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he won the state's GOP primary in 1996, the
candidate showed poorly in a recent Arizona Chamber of Commerce
poll, placing fifth, with 7 percent of the vote. He was outpolled
by Quayle, Arizona Sen. John McCain, Bush and former Red Cross
President Elizabeth Dole. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
