<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANTAGE, AUGUSTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ They were bunched like raindrops, and soon many
of the leaders will be falling too. Thursday at The Masters, nobody
raced in front, Augusta National asserting itself more than anyone
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   After a mostly searing afternoon followed by a thunderstorm that
stopped play for 90 minutes, four players emerged as the
first-round leaders at 3-under-par 69. Two you have heard of, Nick
Price and Davis Love III. The others are Scott McCarron and Brandel
Chamblee, one-time winners on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   There is a group of seven at 2-under, featuring defending
Masters champion Mark O'Meara, former Masters champion Jose Maria
Olazabal and former major tournament champions Jeff Sluman, Lee
Janzen and Justin Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Nine more players are in red numbers at 1-under, led by Masters
favorite David Duval and sentimental favorite Greg Norman. Thirteen
more _ among them Tiger Woods _ are at even par.
</P>
<P>
   Darkness prevented 12 players from finishing, including Price,
who was stranded on the 18th tee.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta presented a rough challenge. The second cut was
everywhere. It was short in comparison to U.S. Open rough, but just
tricky enough to cause hesitation in club selection and swing
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Additional trees and yardage resulted in additional problems for
golfers who otherwise would have handled Thursday's mostly benign
conditions until the storm rolled in.
</P>
<P>
   Pin placements on the already undulating greens created a game
of miniature golf. After taking three strokes on several greens,
Fred Couples finished with a 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pins were all on nobs and crows and front edges,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   What is supposed to be a tournament resembles a scrum thus far.
The battle resumes Friday with big names and no names taking
another shot, hoping to thread the pine needles and find an opening
in Augusta's defense.
</P>
<P>
   No one found much daylight, particularly those in the final four
groups and Tiger Woods, a camouflaged star but lurking nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded one of golf's most dreaded scores, a snowman,
triple-bogey 8 at the eighth hole when he mingled too closely with
nature. After pulling his drive to the left, Woods attempted to hit
a recovery shot but caught a branch, his ball ending up in an
azalea bush.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was forced to take an unplayable lie. His next shot soared
over the green and Woods failed to get up and down in more ways
than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past when I'm 2-over, I would try and be aggressive
right away,'' Woods said. ``Now I say to myself to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid off, as Woods reeled off three birdies in a row at 12,
13 and 14 to work his way back into contention.
</P>
<P>
   After getting to 3-under, Duval dropped back after bogeying 12,
13 and 14. The world's top-ranked player tried cutting the dogleg
at the par-5 13th and hit a branch, his ball bounding into Rae's
Creek, lowlighting his stretch of atypical golf.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders hung in there, avoiding casualties, using
persistence and steady play. Accomplished professionals who have
won other major championships and 29 tournaments between them, Love
and Price do not own a green jacket. They were both at 1-over at
one point but turned solid on the back side, neither recording a
bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Love nearly won The Masters in '95, shooting 13-under but losing
to Ben Crenshaw by one shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a good score, a very good score,'' Love said. ``I
called Ben. I told him how happy I was for him...I'd like to just
shoot that score a couple more times.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the ricochets that derailed Woods and Duval, Love got a
break at the fourth when his approach hit someone in the gallery
and bounced within 5 feet of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee is in an unusual position _ just being here. The
36-year-old from Phoenix earned a spot in the tournament by winning
the Greater Vancouver Open last year.
</P>
<P>
   An eagle-3 at the 13th highlighted his round. It came
unconventionally, Chamblee hitting a ``Zoom'' club from 216 yards
within four feet of the hole. The ``Zoom'' is a cross between a
wood and an iron, playing like a 4- or 5-wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ugly the first time you see it, but when you hit it, it
gets much prettier,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to Augusta, Chamblee used to watch The Masters at
home. He learned about Augusta's nuances from his TV set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everybody else, I do my taxes and have a Masters party
and invite everybody over to watch it on Sunday,'' said Chamblee,
who as a kid taught himself the golf swing by mimicking the ones he
saw on TV.
</P>
<P>
   If he is not the featured performer on the big screen this
weekend, Chamblee won't care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I've played poorly, I've enjoyed it,'' he said.
``It's like that bumper sticker _ a bad day of golf is better than
a good day at work.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron is another likeable fellow. He is best known for the
rockets that are launched from his driver, and the long-shafted
putter he uses on the greens.
</P>
<P>
   For four years after graduating from UCLA, McCarron gave up golf
and worked with his father in the family clothing business. Now he
hopes to add a green jacket to his wardrobe on a course that is
tailor-made for him. Before the tournament began, Couples predicted
that McCarron would do well at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that because I took money from him (Wednesday),''
McCarron said. `But, yeah, the course does set up real well for me.
For some reason, I get here and start relaxing and feel
comfortable. I drive the ball farther and feel more powerful. It's
kind of a mystical place for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Augusta National was more like a mystery to everyone
else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
