<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1686 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     04-09 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY LOSES IN SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Talk about your miserable nights. Everything seemed
lousy Thursday -- the fans, weather and the soccer. And of course,
another dreaded shootout didn't help any.
</P>
<P>
   After winning its first two shootouts to start the season, 2-0,
the Galaxy saw its record drop to 2-2 after defender Greg Vanney's
final shootout attempt hit the near post, allowing Columbus to
escape with a 2-1 victory (3-2 in the shootout) in front of a
franchise low 4,825 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news, bad news story of the Galaxy's 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   Good news first: The Galaxy hasn't lost a game in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: The Galaxy hasn't won a game in regulation,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Other than Cobi Jones' one-touch finisher in the 55th minute or
Stern John's equalizer for Columbus in the 65th minute, the worst
part of Thursday's match came in the 90th minute when referee Alex
Prus put a stop to this thing to send the Galaxy to its fourth
consecutive shootout in as many games.
</P>
<P>
   Stern John, Brian McBride and Robert Warzycha notched shootout
goals for the Crew (2-1). After Welton and Jones missed their first
two attempts, Clint Mathis and Mauricio Cienfuegos pulled the
Galaxy to within a goal, but Vanney was unable to force an extra
round.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano continued to preach patience after
the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced this team will show what it is capable of
doing, Zambrano said. ``By the time we reach the middle of the
season we will be where we want to be. Right now this is a young
team that is still finding its way. It's just a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Jones, are growing impatient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start winning games in order to keep ourselves in
the hunt and play to the level our fans expect us to play, said
Jones. ``I know we're a young team but this team expects better
resutlts -- I expect better results. There's no serect, we need to
start playing 90 minutes of intense soccer the way we know how to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy enjoyed a 1-0 second half lead thanks to Jones, but
certainly Cienfuegos and Ezra Hendrickson, who made his first start
since injuring his groin a day before the season started, deserved
some credit.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson, arguably the best attacking defender in the league,
received a pass from Cienfuegos behind Columbus' defense down the
right side. Hendrickson dribbled a couple of steps toward the goal,
then slid a pass in front of a rushing Jones who was able to
one-touch his shot past Crew goalkeeper Mark Dougherty from a few
yards out.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman made his best save
of the season, he let a John shot slip through his hands to the
near post.
</P>
<P>
   John appeared as though he would get the equalizer in the 64th
minute, but Hartman made a spectacular flick save with his right
hand following a header from John five-yards in front of the Galaxy
net.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, John found himself open again from 20-yards
out. He tried to sneak a quick shot to the near post past Hartman.
The Galaxy keeper appeared to be in position, but the ball slipped
pass his right arm and trickled into the net to tie the game, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, maybe it had something to do with the rainy
conditions, but the same problems the Galaxy has encountered its
first three games appeared to surface again.
</P>
<P>
   -- Midfield newcomer Daniel Hernandez continued to struggle in
place of Guatemalan Martin Machon, who was sold in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cienfuegos wandered about most of the time, showing a look of
frustration as his teammates spread the ball everywhere except in
his direction.
</P>
<P>
   -- And Welton, last year's scoring surprise -- has been useless.
</P>
<P>
   No one said this would be the new and improved Galaxy after last
year's record breaking regular season -- but no one expected the
team to look this unorganized either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not clicking all the way yet, said Jones. ``Sometimes we
play 90 percent and other times we play at 80 percent. We're not
yet at the level we should be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
