<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1687 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-09 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S AND SONICS FANS STRIVE TO SURVIVE SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The inevitable cyclical nature of sports presents us
with a harsh reality: What goes up, must come down.
</P>
<P>
   And boy are we mostly down around here.
</P>
<P>
   Lower than low tide at Myrtle Edwards. Lower than the Space
Needle elevator stuck on ground level.
</P>
<P>
   At water coolers and lunch counters across Seattle, sports fans
are shivering through a very chilling spring. Where's the Sonics'
bounce? Where's the Mariners' pop? Why does mediocrity reign?
</P>
<P>
   The questions, the collective agony and growing anger over the
demise of the Sonics and Mariners has just about reached full metal
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   That is why people are still talking about what a yawner the
Mariners opener was on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Sonics, fans are finally realizing they are not the
SuperSonics of the past six winning seasons. Beating the Trail
Blazers 87-86 at KeyArena Thursday night was a morale booster, but
this is not a Sonics team that has sustained any energy or momentum
this season.
</P>
<P>
   What gives? What did we do to deserve this?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't KeyArena get a massive overhaul in 1994-95, making it one
of the hottest buildings for home-court advantage?
</P>
<P>
   Don't the Mariners have that new and now world's most expensive
baseball stadium looming on the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   Don't we have Ken Griffey Jr. taking over games at the Kingdome
with his uncanny knack for belting homers and going 4-for-4 just
when the moment calls for it?
</P>
<P>
   Don't we have Gary Payton taking over games at KeyArena with his
complete unwillingness to conceed defeat?
</P>
<P>
   These are not the issues, however. It is a mistake to think the
monstrous amounts of cash it has taken to spruce up and build new
sports palaces guarantee high times and giddy playoff runs.
</P>
<P>
   And even the brightest stars can't make up for the glaring
mistakes of a franchise that has failed to promote an aggressive
plan of attack for keeping the Mariners competitive, even in
horrific market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone say, ``No. 1 starter?''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, expectations for success are unrealistic in
today's world of professional sports. Money has thrown the entire
equation for enjoyment and satisfaction out of whack.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to offer up a survival guide for followers of
.500 teams, but there are things Mariner and Sonic fans must keep
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   For Sonic fans, the only hope is that team president Wally
Walker did not like the boos he heard during the retirement of Nate
McMillan's number two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassment is a terrific motivator, although it is unclear
whether Walker and his hand-picked successor to George Karl, Paul
Westphal, have a clear vision of where they want the Sonics to go,
this season or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Fault Karl's trapping, helter-skelter system all you want. It
still got the Sonics to Game 6 of the NBA Finals in '96. Now the
trick is for the Sonics to carve out a new identity _ something a
little more difficult in this expansion-diluted, Post-Jordan NBA.
</P>
<P>
   It is still hard to imagine how a team with Payton and Shawn
Kemp at its core was not an automatic contender, but we all know
how Walker's rush to sign Jim McIlvaine and the inability to
appease Kemp busted apart the Sonics, who could have had a
Jazz-like reign.
</P>
<P>
   Now the burden is on Walker stop the slide this summer during
free-agency. And with Vin Baker demonstrating less than All-Star
qualities, Walker's job of surrounding Payton has become that much
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mariners, returning to contender status could take a
long time, or it might never happen _ unless a billionaire buys the
team.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the Seahawks are not in this category of ``Local
Teams Who Severly Disappoint Us'' is because Paul Allen has the
money to do whatever the NFL will allow him to do. Money is no
object. Winning is.
</P>
<P>
   Since baseball can't get itself a system to control owners'
spending, the Mariners, with a $49 million payroll, have no chance
of being like the Yankees ($84 million) without the help of a sugar
daddy owner.
</P>
<P>
   That is why it is not unreasonable for Mariner fans to pray that
after the new ballpark opens, Mariner owners move to restructure
themselves. In fact, it might be wise to pray that a single owner
emerges from this band of red-ink fearing Nintendo and Microsoft
folks.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance for unbridled spending is if the M's are in the
hands of a solo owner, say like Microsoftie and Mariner part-owner
Chris Larsen. He is the kind of baseball junkie who may want a team
to call his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, try and enjoy Carlos Guillen and Freddy Garcia
and Griffey, who is still here. Try to hang tough with Payton and
Baker, who are as frustrated as you are. Their nasty spat in
practice proves their nerves are worn, too.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere under all this rancor, all this baggage of megabucks
and expectations, it is good to remember these guys are human and
these are only games and this is supposed to be fun.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
