<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Clippers send a message, they usually
forget to use a stamp.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's missive was delivered in person to the Minnesota
Timberwolves with 7,205 Sports Arena witnesses. And the message was
this:
</P>
<P>
   Nah-nah, nah-nah-nah. Us 99, you 91.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are an NBA team,'' T'wolves star Kevin Garnett said of
the Clippers, in case anyone needed clarification, ``and they have
talent just like we do. They are a hell of a team.''
</P>
<P>
   This translation of hell would be 4 victories in 34 games. But
in game 34, the Clippers were finally facing down the bitter
feelings of revenge carried by a team they had beaten in their last
encounter. The playoff-bound Timberwolves were conquered by the
Clips 18 days ago in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers, the best (and only) 4-30 team in the NBA,
suggested the previous result was no fluke by smiting the T'wolves.
This ended the Clippers' chump-change losing streak at six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good win,'' said Clipper coach Chris Ford, whose
flair for understatement is defined by still needing one more
victory to make a fist.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call of Clipper heroes should begin with crusty point
guard Sherman Douglas, whose sage shenanigans prevented another
fourth-quarter free fall. Under siege by the Minnesota defense,
Douglas' ballhandling kept his team out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I done seen everything,'' Douglas (16 points, four assists)
said of his ability to deal with Minnesota's pressure defense. ``I
was just hoping this wasn't going to be the Phoenix game all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   So let's rewind to Tuesday's date with the Suns, when a
half-court trap left the Clippers puckered up on the doorstep of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves (20-15), who were clobbered Wednesday by the
Phoenix Suns, had a dandy alibi for losing to the Clippers - point
guard Terrell Brandon and his bruised thigh were under therapy in
Minnesota. But if they had lost, the Clippers had a better alibi -
the co-stars in those 30 defeats were all here.
</P>
<P>
   One crucial appearance was made by Clipper power forward Maurice
Taylor, who missed the two previous beatings thanks to bilateral
Achilles tendinitis.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor scored 20 points and located 8 rebounds (a personal
revelation) in a command performance against Minnesota's big and
jumpy frontline.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all?'' Taylor said upon hearing the news of his
rebounding exploits. ``I thought it was more than that. Well, he
(Ford) has to take what the hell he can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he will.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to Ford's bonanza was the unreasonably cold
marksmanship of Garnett, the lone T'wolf in the franchise fold
following highly scrutinized defections by Stephon Marbury and Tom
Gugliotta. The 7-foot Garnett, a four-year pro whose high
school-to-NBA learning curve was taken on two wheels, missed 18 of
25 field-goal attempts through three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have pride and they mess up other teams' records and
season,'' said Garnett, who did some of that himself. ``I don't
think they're gonna lay down to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Kevin got the message.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
