<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1695 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-BLAZERS-SP     04-09 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-BLAZERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GET BAKER BACK, BEAT BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Sonics continue to resemble the stock market _ up
one day, crashing the next.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, after their 87-86 victory against the Portland Trail
Blazers Thursday night, the Sonics are hoping for at least two
constants during the final 16 games of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing they are in a fight to make the playoffs, the Sonics
are counting on solid play from Vin Baker as well a renewed
defensive stance.
</P>
<P>
   Baker played for the first time since he went on the injured
list March 23 with a partially torn ligament in his right thumb.
For the second time in three games, the Sonics (17-17) reverted to
the ball-hawking defensive style that had been synonymous with
their past dominance.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics held the Trail Blazers (27-7) to four field goals in
a decisive third quarter. A 30-13 run by the Sonics in that period
erased a 12-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our team is out there, we can beat anybody,'' Sonics
coach Paul Westphal said. ``(Portland) has the best record in the
league so this win does a lot for our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's presence did wonders, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics needed an emotional lift after Tuesday's overtime
loss at home to the Sacramento Kings. More importantly, the Sonics
needed Baker's inside presence to draw double teams and create open
outside shots.
</P>
<P>
   Baker came off the bench with 9:51 left in the first quarter
after rookie Vladimir Stepania picked up two quick fouls. He scored
on his first touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was pumped up for this game,'' said Baker, who wore
a protective brace and did not appear bothered by the thumb. ``I've
been playing pretty well in practice, better than I thought I've
played in a long time. So I wanted to come out and take my time. I
was going to come out aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. Baker finished with 15 points and seven rebounds in 38
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played extremely well,'' Hersey Hawkins said of Baker. ``He
was a lot quicker and more aggressive. With him drawing double
teams, it opens up the perimeter for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had plenty of motivation for this game.
</P>
<P>
   They lost to Portland April 2 after committing 11 fourth-quarter
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Sonics led 87-83 with 50 seconds left when Greg
Anthony hit a 3-pointer 36.4 ticks remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster nearly struck when the Sonics, who had 10 turnovers in
the game, committed a costly miscue with 16.1 seconds to play.
Rasheed Wallace slapped the ball away from Detlef Schrempf and Jim
Jackson gathered the steal. The Sonics, though, forced Portland to
turn the ball over with 1.5 seconds left and preserved the win.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics played with fire defensively the entire second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to pick up full court and gamble. They beat us a
few times. But at least the energy was up,'' Westphal said. ``It's
just a good precedence to set _ that we're going to outwork the
other team. It's something I think will help us play 48 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers, who had won 10 of their last 11 games, flew
around the glass like kids going after cotton candy in the first
half. They outrebounded the Sonics 25-12 in the first half,
outscored the Sonics 10-3 for second-chance points and led by as
many as 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two rebounds,'' center Olden Polynice said. ``I just
thought, `Hey, I can get two rebounds in my sleep.' We all took it
upon ourselves to be more aggressive. So we turned it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton, who led the team with 20 points, ignited the team's
biggest run after Portland dominated the first half. He opened the
third with a 3-pointer and the Sonics used an 18-4 run to go ahead
59-57.
</P>
<P>
   Portland also went cold after shooting 52.5 percent in the first
half. The Trail Blazers missed 20 of their 24 shot attempts in the
third. The Sonics limited the Trail Blazers to one shot in the
third quarter and most of them came from the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were accustomed to playing that style for so long,''
Schrempf said. ``We got away from that and we were being passive.
We were always the aggressor. I like it when we're the aggressor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
