<HEADER>
A1696 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-UNSER-LBPT     04-09 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-UNSER-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSER HAS BROKEN ANKLE, ACHING HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smacking a wall while traveling 200 miles per hour or at least
the danger of that happening is part of Al Unser Jr.'s chosen
profession.
</P>
<P>
   And like any other race car driver, Unser knows and accepts
that. But, there is no collision in the world not even one at 200
miles per hour that could prepare Unser for the pain of watching
one of his children suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Unser was at work testing his CART FedEx Championship Marlboro
Team Penske entry at the Miami-Dade Homestead Motorsports Complex
when he received word that his 12-year-old daughter, Cody, was
stricken with tranverse myletis, an inflammation of the spinal cord
caused by an attack of the body's immune system. Cody, a
sixth-grader and an accomplished athlete, was playing basketball in
the Unser's hometown of Albuquerque on Feb.5 when she complained of
pain and numbness in her legs. As her condition worsened, she
became paralyzed from the chest down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me right in the gut,'' said Unser, a six-time Toyota
Grand Prix of Long Beach champion, who has become known as the King
of Long Beach for his success here. ``Not having control over what
was happening to my little girl is very frustrating. I was looking
at the doctors (and) at first they were scratching their heads
saying `We don't know.' That's really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Cody's progress toward recovery has been slow, and it will
continue to be. She spent three weeks at the Barrow Neurological
Institute in Phoenix before returning home and is now undergoing
rehabilitation at Albuquerque's Carrie Tingley Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cody is doing great,'' Unser said on Wednesday after attending
a weekly meeting that includes Cody's doctors, therapists and
school teacher. ``Everybody (in the meeting) gave her straight A's.
She is still paralyzed from the chest down, but she is getting
better. The process is pretty slow.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser returned to Homestead on March 21 for the CART FedEx
Championship opening race the Marlboro Grand Prix of Miami. It was,
he hoped, the first step toward Marlboro Team Penske's climb back
to the Champ car pinnacle. However, literally seconds into the
opener, a frustrated Unser was slinging the steering wheel out of
the car after being run into the wall by rookie Naoki Hattori.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I was in the wrong place at the wrong time,'' said
Unser, who will turn 37 on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   What resulted was a right ankle broken in two places and a
sprained knee for Unser and a broken leg for Hattori. The reaction
by the other CART competitors showed the kind of respect the classy
Little Al has earned in his 18 years in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see someone like Al get hurt like that is tough for
everyone,'' said fellow driver Christian Fittipaldi. ``He's a guy
that all of the drivers respect and look up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Andretti, who came into the series a year after Little
Al, also expressed sympathy for his long-time friend and rival
after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it rains, it pours,'' said Andretti after finishing
second in Miami. ``I feel bad about Cody, and now this happens.
It's been a tough winter for him. But they're tough people. They'll
get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser, who had surgery two days after the incident, has seen
pretty much everything the series has to offer since joining the
circuit. He's been injured while racing, including suffering a
broken ankle in 1985. But he had never missed a race because of an
injury. In fact, after the first broken ankle, he was back in the
car in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being in Japan for the Firestone Firehawk 500, which
begins today at 9 p.m. PST, Unser was at home. And, although he'll
be in Long Beach on April 16-18 for the 25th running of the Toyota
Grand Prix of Long Beach, Unser won't be where he wants to be on
the track.
</P>
<P>
   Unser and wife, Shelly, are the parents of Cody, Alfred Richard,
16, Shannon Lee, 11, and and Joseph Scott, 2. Which brings us to
the bright side of his time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting to spend time with my family,'' said Unser. ``If
there's anything good coming from this, it's the fact I get to
spend time with all four of my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Al and Cody have attended rehab sessions together. Al's
rehab consists of range of motion exercises and plenty of ice for
the ankle. Cody's work includes building her upper body and keeping
her legs stretched. She's also learning how to operate a wheel
chair and things we take for granted such as putting on her shoes.
Little Al alternates between using a wheelchair and crutches, and
Cody is in a wheelchair full-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's teaching me wheelies,'' Cody told the Associated Press.
``I'm teaching him how to get around the house better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Little Al will be a few weeks away from walking, he
plans on being back in the car by the end of April and racing in
the Bosch Spark Plug Grand Prix in Nazareth, Pa., on May 2. He said
he literally may have to be carried to and from his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have the same goal,'' said Unser, `` which is to put
the No. 1 (signifying the series champion) on the Marlboro car.''
</P>
<P>
   It was with that theme that Unser and Team Penske attacked
off-season testing. The team is in its 30th season overall and 21st
in CART. It has compiled 86 Champ car victories, 10 Indy 500 wins,
118 pole positions and seven Champ car titles. But the last victory
was by Paul Tracy at Gateway in 1997. Little Al hasn't won since
taking the checkered flag at Vancouver in 1995 and the team's last
championship was Unser's title in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's gotten very frustrating,'' Unser said of the 54-race
winless streak. ``But my dad said a long time ago, `If it was easy,
everybody would be doing it'.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Unser had podium finishes of second at Japan and
third at Michigan, but only delivered five other top 10 finishes
and his 11th-place finish in the points standings marked the second
successive year out of the top 10. Penske's other driver, Andre
Ribeiro, was 22nd in the standings. The biggest change of the
off-season was the team's decision to field one only entry Unser
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an easy decision for Team Penske,'' Penske said at a
February press conference in Homestead. ``Certainly we had a
long-term contract with Al and we were not happy with our
performance in 1998. Probably our unreliability was the biggest
issue. We had some great testing during the preseason, following
the end of the 1998 season and also going into 1999. Certainly as
we see the reliability of the car, we have run competitive times
with other teams during the preseason.''
</P>
<P>
   He closed that part of his statement by saying ``The racing
season will tell a little story.''
</P>
<P>
   However the story was put on hold when Unser was injured. Tarso
Marques, a 23-year-old Brazilian, took over Unser's seat for
today's race in Japan. Gonzalo Rodriquez and Jason Leffler have
also tested with Penske, though the team hasn't announced who drive
in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   What Unser is concerned with is trying to return to the front of
the pack, beginning in Nazareth. And how does he plan to do that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand on the gas,'' said Unser, whose father, Al, and uncle,
Bobby are racing legends.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Unser won't be standing on the gas at Long Beach,
where he won four consecutive times 1988-91 and then back-to-back
1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long Beach has been very, very good to me,'' Unser said.
``We've won more at that track than any other. To be missing the
25th anniversary is very disappointing. But that's the cards I've
been dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser was relegated to a spectator role last year at Long Beach
for a different reason. After qualifying 10th, his race day ended
in Turn 3 of the first lap when he slammed into the tire barriers
while avoiding Scott Pruett, and was struck from behind by Helio
Castro-Neves. This year, Unser said, was going to be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to winning at Long Beach,'' Unser said.
``We have a great car and I really thought I could have won the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   History says he may have been right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
