u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-LIGHTNING &LR;      04-09 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-LIGHTNING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING BEAT BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ The best that can be said for Thursday night's game was
that it was entirely predictable.
</P>
<P>
   One night after the Bruins clinched a playoff spot against the
Florida Panthers, they suffered a giant letdown against the Tampa
Bay Lightning, losing, 3-0, to a team on its way to finishing dead
last in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns, who has a roster full of banged-up players,
elected to rest defenseman Hal Gill (hip flexor) and Rob DiMaio
(finger/forearm) so that they, at the very least, wouldn't get
worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the most let down of all was goalie Rob Tallas, who
was making his first start since Feb. 21. Prior to this game,
Tallas, who had never lost to the Lightning in his career (5-0-1),
said he was well aware his teammates could have some difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   They were coming off a high after winning their fourth straight
and assuring themselves of a postseason slot. They were playing
their second game in two nights and their third game in four days.
A loss at this juncture was by no means going to be considered a
disaster, but even Burns said at the morning skate he was concerned
about how much help his players were going to be to his backup
goalie.
</P>
<P>
   The answer? Not very much.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning, who beat Boston for the first time since Dec. 17,
1997, when they earned a 2-0 decision, got on the board early in
the first period when rookie center Vincent Lecavalier, who shows
every sign that he will live up to his billing as the No. 1 pick
overall in last June's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Stephane Richer, who had two assists and has made a
career of being a Bruin killer, dished a pass from the far right
circle to Lecavalier, along the inside edge. Lecavalier fired a
wrister that beat Tallas to the stick side at 3:28. It was the 13th
goal of the year for the 18-year-old rookie.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins lost left wing Ken Baumgartner at 10:02 when he lined
up Tampa center Michael Nylander and drilled him head-first into
the glass. Nylander left the game bleeding from the head and having
suffered a concussion. Baumgartner left the game with a five-minute
major for boarding and a game misconduct. He also faces possible
supplementary discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins killed off the penalty. Tampa's best chance came with
30 seconds left on it when Alexandre Daigle ripped a one-timer from
the slot that Tallas gloved.
</P>
<P>
   At the 16:22 mark, Lecavalier set up Daigle for another scoring
chance, with Daigle firing a backhand shot from the right circle.
Tallas came out to cut it off, dropped sideways and enveloped the
puck in his body, securing it with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning replaced goalie Kevin Hodson with Corey Schwab to
start the second period because Hodson aggravated a groin strain,
but Schwab was just as stingy as Hodson had been. Boston had six
power plays in the first 40 minutes, including a brief two-man
advantage early in the second, but couldn't cash in any of them.
The Bruins just looked tired and out of sync.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas kept plugging away, hoping for some offensive help but
didn't get any. At 16:57 of the second, he made a great save on
right wing Mike Sillinger, who tried to redirect a Rob Zamuner feed
from the edge of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   With just over two minutes left in the period, Tallas made a
terrific stop with his stick on a bid by Lecavalier.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning boosted their lead to a pair of goals with under a
minute remaining. Center Darcy Tucker centered a pass to left wing
Colin Forbes in front of the net. Forbes, who was being pressured
by defenseman Don Sweeney, managed to pop a high shot in over
Tallas with 58.3 seconds left for the 2-0 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gratton capped the scoring with an empty-net goal with
48.6 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rough night for Boston, a result the Lightning
predicted long before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think we're going to win,'' said Richer, after the
morning skate.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for hard-luck Tallas, Richer was right on the
money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
