</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-RAPTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BEAT RAPTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Things did not go quite according to Hoyle Thursday
night. Rick Pitino was riding the referees over the medical
qualities of a pimple while Kenny Anderson, his new best friend,
was getting booed every time he touched the ball.
</P>
<P>
   A Buffalo Bills lineman was calling for Dontae Jones, either
unaware or unconcerned that Jones hasn't been in the league this
year. Throw that in with a botched karaoke contest and a technical
on mild-mannered Paul Pierce and, well, things aren't always what
they seem.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the flavor-of-the-month Raptors. They have the big-time
rookie, the wily vets, the spiffy new arena, the playoff
possibility _ and absolutely none of it mattered against the
supposedly dysfunctional Celtics. Boston wore out the Raptors in
the second half with its trap and long-range shooting and pulled
away for an easy 101-89 victory, a margin that would have continued
to grow had not the clock intervened.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big win. The Celtics had not won two straight since
Feb. 24-27, when they put together a three-gamer. They had been
manhandled by Toronto in their first two meetings and now Toronto
was making a move and talking about the postseason. But this was
decidedly different.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino high-fived Pierce on the way out and put his arm around
Anderson, who reacted to the booing with a 23-point, 7-assist
submission. The Celtics stayed competitive on the glass, bombed
away with impunity and success from international waters (8 for
13), forced 22 turnovers (good for 25 points) and got blissfully
balanced scoring _ Anderson's 23 led five starters in double
figures. That more than offset rocketman rookie Vince Carter, who
had 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt we were the better team, but I don't think we
were even in those other two games,'' said Pierce, (15 points, 7
rebounds), who was given his first pro `T' for hanging on the rim
after a sweet alley-oop. ``They banged us before. We wanted to be
more physical. I think we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Some credit has to go to Kiev strongman Vitaly Potapenko, who
would not be pushed around inside and finished with 11 points, 7
rebounds, and a blocked shot. His only problem was an alleged cut
in the first quarter; the referees said they saw blood and ordered
him to the bench for treatment. Pitino went bonkers, screaming that
it was a pimple and that there was no blood.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pitino, Potapenko had more bumps and bangs than he
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be cut a break,'' Pitino said. ``He's getting
bumped in there pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Raptors coach Butch Carter, ``Their new center handled
(Kevin) Willis very well and that had something to do with it. We
did not match their energy. I hope it's not a trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Also up to the task was Antoine Walker, who had 18 points, 10
rebounds, 6 assists, 4 steals, and 5 turnovers. Butch Carter
saluted Walker, saying, ``He played an unselfish game.'' Walker had
the hot hand from outside, knocking down four treys while Anderson
matched his season total of three. And what did Anderson think of
the boos directed his way because he refused to report here last
year after being traded for Damon Stoudamire?
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes me feel really important,'' he cracked. ``I didn't
even think they knew who Kenny Anderson was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics took control in the third, when a 3-point barrage
turned a Toronto lead into a 68-62 Boston advantage. Boston led,
71-67, after three and was clinging to an 83-77 lead in the fourth
with 5:49 left. Out of a timeout, Anderson took a pass from Walker
and hit a 15-footer. Vince Carter (12 for 22) matched that, but
then Ron Mercer (18 points) made a rare trey to ignite a 9-2 run
that sent the patrons scrambling to the exits.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Bills lineman Robert Hicks, who had a front-row
seat and went to Mississippi State with Dontae Jones, was calling
out ``SEC, SEC'' at every opportunity. Pitino may sometimes wonder
why he left Kentucky, and is still wondering why he doesn't get the
calls he got at Kentucky, but on this night, he saw a lot of good
things.
</P>
<P>
   His team beat a good team, on the road, having played the night
before, and doing it the way all his teams do it: with harassment,
hustle, and some plain old good luck. That comes to teams that work
and, Thursday night, the Celtics were the unquestioned worker bees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
