<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEYCOLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE A POET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poetry is the man's birthright. You have to remember that when
you're talking about Bruins goaltender Byron Dafoe. He's not just a
goaltender. He's a poetic goaltender. This may not be exactly what
Dafoe's mother had in mind 28 years ago in Sussex, England, but I
don't hear any Bruins fans complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know Lord Byron, the poet?'' Dafoe said Thursday. ``My
mother was a real big fan of his, so she named me after him. I
understand he was a pretty wild guy in his time.''
</P>
<P>
   He was. He liked to pen his clever verse. He liked his freedom
(he was a 19th-century pretty boy). He liked his drugs. And, the
gossip mongers of the 1800s whispered, he loved being intimate with
women _ including his half-sister. So that Byron was nearly run out
of town. Not this one. Almost everyone who talks with him likes
him. He is so popular that on Monday night, more than 17,000 people
at the FleetCenter didn't need to talk with him to let him know how
they felt. They simply chanted his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not like I have the easiest name to chant,'' he said.
``It doesn't roll like `Reg-gie, Reg-gie.' It's just `By-ron.' ''
</P>
<P>
   You say you've never read a poem in your life? You have if
you're a Bruins fan and have ever mentioned the name of Dafoe. The
following is a major difference between Dafoe's poetry and the
prose of his namesake.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Byron poetic line: ``The best of life is over and its
bitters double.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Dafoe poetic line: 10 shutouts, 9-2-3 in his last 14
games, Bruins in the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I exercised some poetic license toward the end of that
line. But have you seen the Eastern Conference lately? What's Lord
Byron talking about? The best of life has begun for the Bruins.
They have the schedule on their side, fate on their side, and the
poetic goaltender in their net.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Thursday night's games, the East was a mess. Seems
like each day, the Bruins leap over a fallen team mumbling about
what it could have been.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the beginning of the season when everyone thought the
Flyers would be great? Now they are more of a prayer group than a
hockey team. Eric Lindros recently gave the entire city a scare
when one of his lungs collapsed and six pints of blood filled his
chest cavity. He was released from one hospital Thursday, but
admitted to another and is probably out for the season. So forget
about the Flyers in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins? They've been moonwalking through the standings,
sliding farther and farther back to the land of seventh and eighth
seeds. And can we talk about the Carolina Hurricanes? They play in
front of about 10 people every night, probably making them wish for
the comparably good days when they were in Hartford. They are the
leaders of a dilapidated eyesore known as the Southeast Division.
They also, by default, hold the third spot in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   I know Pat Burns says that you should never try to pick your
opponents, but I'm sure the coach won't lie awake trembling if the
Bruins finish in sixth place and have to open the playoffs with a
series against the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get into saying who we'd want to play, because
that gets you in trouble,'' Dafoe said before the Bruins played the
Lightning in Tampa Bay. ``But the other night, four or five of us
were sitting around talking about who we could play in the
playoffs. A lot can happen. We match up pretty good with a lot of
teams in our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe is a nice man. He won't talk trash about anyone in the
East. But, yo, give me one Eastern team that is supposed to scare
the Bruins. Well, some team other than the Devils and Maple Leafs.
And even then, I like my chances against anybody as long as the man
who has ``Lord Byron'' scripted on his black-and-gold mask is
rejecting pucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say he's had a great run, but it's a little more than
that,'' Don Sweeney said of the bard. ``Even when he gives up a
goal, it's not really a bad one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney is right. As dominant as Dafoe has been at times, what
he's doing is not necessarily new. In 1995, when Dafoe was with LA,
teammate Rick Tocchet was asked to name his top Hart Trophy
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to vote,'' Tocchet said at the time, ``it would be
between Mario Lemieux, Jaromir Jagr, and Dafoe.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems silly when you look at it now, but the Kings were in a
quandary in '95 because Dafoe was playing well while Kelly Hrudey
was recovering from an injury. Eventually, the Bruins would make
one of their best trades of the '90s, dealing Jozef Stumpel, Sandy
Moger, and a fourth-round draft pick to the Kings in exchange for a
man who is now their leading goal scorer (Dmitri Khristich) and a
man who makes their fans unafraid to speak of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Dafoe will be a restricted free agent. That means
he will probably walk away with a contract in the $3.5
million-per-season range. That's enough loot to purchase a few
800-page Lord Byron anthologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read up on him a little bit,'' Dafoe said, ``but I can't
recite you any lines. I wouldn't consider myself a poet.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe him. He's a poet. All you have to do is read those
lyrical stat lines that appear next to his name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
