<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sweeping the Kansas City Royals, who play in
the heartland of America but will be nowhere to be found come
October, ranks as something less than the Norman Conquest.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox know that. But there's still something to be said
for being the only unbeaten team in the American League three games
into the season, especially when their best player, Nomar
Garciaparra, is hobbled indefinitely with a strained left
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox understand that, too, which is why there was a sense
of satisfaction in the visitors' clubhouse here after
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's 4-1 win over the Royals, leavened by the reality
of what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early,'' said Pedro Martinez, who pitched the opener
then watched as Bret Saberhagen (three hits allowed in six shutout
innings Wednesday) and Tim Wakefield (three hits and a run in 6 1/3
innings Thursday &UR;  &LR; night) shut down the Royals the next two games,
while the Boston bullpen went unscored upon in all three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the start of the season,'' Martinez said. ``We
have to stay focused, play the game the way we have been with
pitching, defense, and hits at key times, and try to sneak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about everything else. Get wins, wins and forget about
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals will be quite relieved to forget former teammate Jose
Offerman, whose one-man reign of terror culminated with two more
doubles Thursday night, as he scored the first Sox run on John
Valentin's sacrifice fly in the first and accounted for the second
on a force out with the bases loaded in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In three games, Offerman outscored his ex-team, 5 to 4. He had
eight hits in the series and five of the 11 Sox extra-base hits in
the three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   The polling booths, of course, will remain open all summer. But
based on the early returns, Dan Duquette was right about Offerman.
The rest of the world, ready to cast Offerman as Duke's Folly, can
jump off the Tobin Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offy had a great series,'' said Royals manager Tony Muser,
probably the first sentence he uttered this week that Offerman
would not dispute after taking exception to Muser musings about his
lack of hustle. ``We didn't pitch him well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to score over 100 runs. He'd probably have a real
good year if Mo Vaughn was still there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox nursed a 2-1 lead until there were two outs in the
ninth, when back-to-back thunder by Garciaparra's replacement,
Donnie Sadler (triple into the left-center field gap), and rookie
Trot Nixon (home run off a beer sign flanked by the waterfalls
beyond the right-field fence) made it easy for Tom Gordon. The Sox
closer gave up an infield hit and walk then struck out the side for
his second save of 1999 and 45th in a row dating back to last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw him this spring, and you saw what Donnie did last
year,'' manager Jimy Williams said of Sadler, whose fifth-inning
single off former Sox pitcher Jeff Suppan followed a base hit by
Jason Varitek in setting up the second Boston run. ``He really
didn't surprise me that he would go out there and play as well as
he did, and hit the ball as well as he did. To me, he has a lot
better idea at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon gave the Sox an idea of his power potential with his first
big-league home run, a drive off Royals reliever Don Wengert that
carried 412 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen did a great job, and Trot's hit was huge,'' said
Wakefield, who like Saberhagen the night before pitched with the
flu but revealed few of its effects, allowing the Royals just one
run on a walk, bunt single, and Rey Sanchez's grounder through the
left side in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's takeout slide of shortstop Sanchez on Offerman's
bases-loaded RBI grounder in the fifth, meanwhile, reinforced the
idea that he will be useful in other ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy to put good wood on the ball,'' Nixon said.
``I can't afford to panic if I'm not getting hits. I have to play
good defense, hit the ball, and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals scored just two runs on 11 hits in the last 26
innings against Red Sox pitching, and one of those runs was
unearned. In all, they were outscored, 15-4, and outhit, 36-14.
They had just three extra-base hits in the series, one in the last
25 innings, and fanned 27 times.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe, who relieved Wakefield with two on and one out in
the seventh, retired pinch hitter Larry Sutton on an easy fly and
rookie Carlos Febles on a tapper to second, then breezed through
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the ideal man in that situation,'' Wakefield said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Royals played the perfect patsy, for openers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we've only got 159 to go,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   On to Tampa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
