<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LeBRETON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUEHNE TAKING MASTERS IN STRIDE AFTER ROUGH START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Regrettably, there are no mulligans at the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   As golfer Hank Kuehne of Dallas waited Thursday for his heart to
stop thumping and his tee shot to stop rolling, he pondered that
gentlemanly omission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't too worried when I was on the practice green,'' the
SMU senior said. ``My putting wasn't bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``But somehow, along the way from the practice green to the
first tee, I started feeling like, `Hey _ I'm getting ready to tee
off in my first Masters.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His first Masters. The first time Kuehne ever picked up a golf
club _ at the tender age of 6 1/2 _ he dreamed of playing in the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   As reigning U.S amateur champion, Kuehne became one of the
invitees to this year's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Let it be noted that the ride up Magnolia Lane to the stately,
66-year-old clubhouse of Augusta National can be daunting. There is
Amen Corner. Rae's Creek. The dogwood in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   But the 23-year-old Kuehne was handling that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fine until we were walking up to the first tee and the
guy asked, `You ready?' '' Kuehne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it starts to hit you.''
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Kuehne's first shot of his first Masters left
the tee, he knew something was very wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get lucky! Get lucky!'' his sister Kelli prayed aloud.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring missile cleared not only the towering pine trees
lining the left side of the No. 1 fairway, but it whistled over the
adjoining ninth fairway before it came to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I got it airborne,'' Kuehne said with a wince.
</P>
<P>
   His two playing partners, Lee Westwood and Mark O'Meara,
immediately rushed to Kuehne's side and began consoling him with
stories about their own previous calamities at the Masters' No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't have hurt. From beyond the green on his second shot,
Kuehne scrambled to a less-than-textbook par.
</P>
<P>
   As turning points go, he called it huge.
</P>
<P>
   There might have been better opening rounds at a Masters by a
young amateur, eager to make the leap into golf's big time. But
none may have come so far and started so dreadfully as Kuehne's.
With a 35 on the back nine, Kuehne finished at 2-over 74 and found
a crowded corner of the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, he was battling alcohol addiction and being
treated at the Hazelden Rehab Clinic in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question,'' said his father, Ernie, in the fading
Augusta twilight. ``What Hank Kuehne has done, not just in golf,
but to his life is something very special.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Hank wears a golden key on a chain around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to a new beginning,'' Hank Kuehne explained. ``It's
from rehab. Kind of a reminder.''
</P>
<P>
   From his ghastly beginning on the No. 1 tee, Kuehne settled down
to an afternoon of soaring drives _ only four golfers were longer
off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   On the undulating, par-5 second hole, Kuehne sent his tee shot
345 yards _ with a 3-wood. His tee ball on No. 13 screamed through
the fairway and missed the dogleg, striking instead the belly of a
tall tree. The ball caromed back across the fairway at least 50
yards and found refuge in Augusta National's infamous ``second
cut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nailed it,'' Kuehne said. He ended up saving par.
</P>
<P>
   His birdies came on Nos. 5, 15 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the second shot of the first hole,'' Kuehne said, ``I
felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot today. The experience was great. I really
wasn't overly concerned whether I shot a 74 or an 84.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when the rain and thunder halted play, the best amateur
golfer in the country refused to be intimidated by where he was.
Two of his birdies came once play resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Round 2, will be different, Kuehne wished aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to hit it, try and go find it, and then hit it
again, like Arnold Palmer said.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
