<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN ON DL; ANGELS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Mo Vaughn joined Gary DiSarcina, Jim Edmonds and six
other Angels in a not-so-exclusive club Thursday -- they're all
members of the Angels' disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who sustained a bone bruise and sprained ligaments in
his left ankle while falling into the Indians dugout on Tuesday's
opening night, didn't try to talk the Angels medical staff out of
it. In fact, it was Vaughn's idea as much as anybody's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to argue, Vaughn said Thursday before the
Angels were routed by the Cleveland Indians, 9-1, before 25,084 at
Edison Field. ``I've stated my point. It's already been 48 hours
and it's not feeling that good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, we're playing with 24 guys so that limits
the club. I don't think I'll be feeling that good (today). It's
been three days now. The DL is 12 more. If I'm not ready in 12
days, I'll cut the whole damn foot off. It'll be ready.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is confident he'll be back when he'll be eligible to
return from the DL on April 22 in Toronto. But the medical staff
has indicated an injury the nature of Vaughn's could put someone
out anywhere from two to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, however, has a history of healing quickly. He had been
on the disabled list only one time previously in his career -- he
had torn cartilage in his left knee in 1997 but missed only three
weeks. He also seems to know his body well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tried to play in a couple days, I'd be in worse shape in
a couple weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins said the decision of what to do with
Vaughn was strictly out if his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the medical staff, Mo and (general manager) Billy
(Bavasi), he said. ``However they feel. If (Mo) thinks it's going
to be that long ...
</P>
<P>
   Angels medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum said the fact that the
injury is a high ankle sprain makes the injury more serious than a
lower ankle sprain and presents the possibility of Vaughn being out
beyond the 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   Yocum added he doesn't believe Vaughn will show bravado and try
to come back before he's ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, he's movitated (to follow doctors' advice), Yocum
said. ``There has been a little improvement each day, but there's
no reason to push it. It's not a matter of playing with pain -- he
cannot move around on it.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's trip to the disabled list wasn't the only bad news for
the Angels Thursday. Starting pitcher Steve Sparks (0-1) looked
nothing like the pitcher he was in spring training, getting knocked
around by the Indians for six runs and seven hits in four innings
before the rain came.
</P>
<P>
   The game was halted with Darin Erstad at the plate in the bottom
of the fourth inning and the Indians leading, 6-0. After a one hour
and 43-minute delay, the game resumed but it didn't get any better
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Indians starter Bartolo Colon (1-0), who had allowed only one
hit in three innings before the delay, picked up where he left off,
striking out Erstad and then Tim Salmon when the game resumed. He
went six innings, allowing one run and two hits, the run coming on
Troy Glaus' first home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, the Angels offense was weak.
They've had only four hits in each of their last two games. Going
back to the third inning of Wednesday's game, Angels hitters have
five hits in their last 51 at-bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
