<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE TO ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 QUOTES-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rain, the wind and the seemingly imminent threat of snow
gave Dodger Stadium that Coors Field, early April kind of feel. The
1 hour, 25-minute rain delay before the first pitch didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But the five hits the Dodgers managed clarified this is not Mile
High air, and also made it clear the Colorado Rockies can pitch, at
least on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies left-hander Brian Bohanon baffled his old 'mates for
seven innings and Todd Helton hit a three-run homer as Colorado
handed the Dodgers a 4-2 loss Thursday in the opener of a four-game
series.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Dodgers fail in their bid to start 4-0 for the
first time since 1981, but they lost left fielder Gary Sheffield
after he flied out to end the fifth inning. He left with what was
termed as muscle stiffness in his right hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of aching and swelling going on in there,'' Sheffield
said. ``I got loose as usual, but the spasms just started again.
When I got on the on-deck circle (in the fifth) I felt it again.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the gambles the Dodgers made on the final day of roster
cuts was carrying four outfielders and three catchers. It left
Jacob Brumfield, who replaced Sheffield in left, Devon White and
Raul Mondesi as the three remaining outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine he'll probably need a day or two off,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon (1-0) was effectively wild, allowing three hits, walking
five and striking out four. The only run he allowed was when he
walked Eric Karros with the bases loaded in the third inning. But
that was sandwiched by Raul Mondesi striking out and Mark
Grudzielanek lining out to first.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the only Dodger to get past second base was Dave
Hansen, who had a pinch-hit homer off reliever Dave Veres with two
outs in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the right guys up at the right time and we couldn't get
diddly,'' Johnson said. ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies experienced the same thing against Dodgers
left-hander Carlos Perez for the first six innings. Until then,
Rockies had one hit, a second-inning single by Vinny Castilla, and
Perez answered that by retiring the next 13 batters.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the seventh, and quickly. Dante Bichette doubled
into the left-field corner with two out to score Neifi Perez and
tie the game 1-1. Perez then intentionally walked Castilla to face
the lefty hitting Todd Helton, last year's runner-up in the
National League Rookie of the Year race.
</P>
<P>
   On a cold night in which the baseball wasn't carrying well,
Helton hit a shot to right-center field for a three-run homer.
Helton's first homer of the season and third hit in 16 at-bats gave
the Rockies a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch, a slider away,'' said Helton, who hit 25
homers last season. ``I didn't think it was gone, not when I hit
it. I haven't hit one in so long I forgot what it felt like.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then it looked like Perez was heading for the Dodgers'
first complete game of the season. Perez was so good that no
Rockies player got past first base until the seventh inning. He had
thrown less than 60 pitches through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   That was rendered meaningless by the slider to Helton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the only bad pitch he made,'' Dodgers catcher Paul
LoDuca said. ``It was just one bad pitch, and until then he was
sailing. If (Helton) pops it up, Carlos is out of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was delayed 1 hour, 25 minutes by a rain shower that
hit just as the first pitch was ready to be thrown. Perez was
warming up on the mound when the rain came.
</P>
<P>
   That the Dodgers were able to play is significant, mostly to the
organization. It prides itself on an 11-year streak without having
a game rained out, though that was tested last season when the
Dodgers and Phillies waited out a pair of rain delays totaling 2
hours, 31 minutes last May 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have avoided the poor weather all week in the Los
Angeles area, and have pushed their streak to 853 games without
being washed out at home. The last time the Dodgers were rained out
at Dodger Stadium was April 21, 1988, the third of three straight
washouts against the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   In the 38-year history of Chavez Ravine, the Dodgers have been
rained out 15 times. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
