<HEADER>
A1727 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROUNDWAR-GROUNDWAR-N     04-09 2062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUNDWAR-GROUNDWAR-NATO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM-STYLE MESS UNLIKELY IN NATO GROUND WAR, EXPERTS SAY  
   
  
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK VIVIANO  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
PARIS _ In Europe, no less than America, the debate over Kosovo is
increasingly focused on a single issue: the dangers of a ground
war.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Balkan re-enactment of Vietnam lies ahead, warn some, with
American and Allied troops bogged down in a protracted conflict for
years. Others predict a bloody guerrilla campaign, fought by the
grandchildren of Serbian Partisans under Marshal Josip Broz Tito,
whose hit-and-run tactics defeated an immense German Army in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the reality is that ground intervention is not only all but
inevitable _ it's already under way, with rising public support on
both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether NATO faces a new Vietnam or Partisan war
on the ground in Kosovo _ or a paper tiger on the model of Iraq's
Republican Guard, which was crushed in five days during the Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, Kosovo is neither Vietnam, nor the Yugoslavia in
which Marshall Tito defeated the Germans. Its geography and
demographics are not suited to a lengthy guerrilla war against
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The irregular units that were the backbone of the Viet Cong and
Tito's Partisans operated in dense jungle or mountainous terrain,
where the far more technologically sophisticated U.S. military and
Wehrmacht were at a profound disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Partisan campaign, which diverted vital Nazi resources away
from the Soviet front and Atlantic coast in the months before
D-Day, has become a legendary episode, recounted often by Yugoslavs
as an implicit warning against foreign intervention. It was the
basis of Tito's later power as president of Yugoslavia, which he
ruled until his death in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the war in 1943-44, 110,000 Partisans held off
19 Nazi divisions, in addition to 160,000 Bulgarian, Serb and Croat
collaborators _ over 360,000 men in all, according to General
Fitzroy Maclean, the chief British liaison officer in Yugoslavia
then.
</P>
<P>
   But as Maclean notes, the Partisans' activities were
concentrated almost entirely in the precipitous highlands of
Montenegro and Bosnia, with very few incursions into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the province is a gently rolling plain, with few
sanctuaries outside of the mountainous borders with Albania and
western Macedonia, which are effectively under the control of
unfriendly neighbors or NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more importantly, the Serbs lack a friendly countryside
in Kosovo to support their morale and supply lines, factors that
gave a crucial political and psychological edge to the Viet Cong
and the Partisans.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo was more than 90 percent Albanian when ethnic cleansing
began in earnest last year. Since then, an estimated 900,000 of the
1.8 million Albanian Kosovars have fled. But so too, according to
Belgrade, have 50,000 of Kosovo's 100,000 Serbs, leaving the
province overwhelmingly hostile to the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, defense analysts say, the Yugoslav National Army is
itself a deeply conventional military force, built around
mechanized divisions that dominated early stages of the war in
Croatia and Bosnia with classic ground tactics against outnumbered
and outgunned opponents. That makes it highly vulnerable to the
technological superiority of the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, say American and European officers, a revolution has
occurred in NATO's battlefield command-and-control infrastructure
over the past decade, while Yugoslavia's military equipment has
largely remained frozen in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known aspect of this gap is in the air, where NATO has
been virtually unchallenged since the earliest days of the assault.
But on the ground, too, Western officers told The Chronicle,
Yugoslav Army tanks and armored cars will encounter radically new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can track every single vehicle on a battlefield by
satellite, and we have personnel detection devices that accomplish
the same task,'' said Lieutenant Colonel John Angell, chief
operations officer at a NATO training program in Germany geared to
military intervention in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, from a command post, we'd only know if one of our own
tanks had been hit. Today, we know from which direction, with what
weapon, and how. We know exactly what's happening in a battle, as
opposed to what people think is happening. It's a quantum leap.''
</P>
<P>
   Against this background, escalation has steadily mounted toward
de facto ground intervention. The escalation took overt form
Wednesday, with daylight assaults on a Serbian armored column in
Kosovo by U.S. A-10 Warthogs and British Harriers, aircraft that
are usually attached to ground campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The commitment will deepen considerably by the end of the week,
with the arrival of Apache AH-64D Longbow assault helicopters,
which hover so close to the ground that Iraqi infantrymen were
known to surrender to them during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   The Warthogs and Apaches are designed to work together in
Advanced Joint Air Attacks operations, backing up an infantry
advance. During the Gulf War, according to NATO sources, such
sorties accounted for 1,200 of the 1,700 Iraqi tanks destroyed in
the Allied invasion, and 1,000 of 1,200 artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The top-rated of Yugoslavia's 1,300 tanks, about 300 of which
are believed to be in Kosovo, is the M-84, built to the same design
as the Soviet T/72 that fared so poorly for Iraq against Operation
Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon confirmed Thursday that Hunter unmanned
reconnaissance planes are in action over Kosovo. The Hunter's
normal purpose is to provide video images of a battlefield prior to
a land operation.
</P>
<P>
   More discreetly, NATO now has commando teams in place behind the
lines, report sources close to the French Ministry of Defence.
``They are there to direct air strikes, and to prepare for the
deployment of troops,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but relentlessly, NATO ground strength in the region has
also been rising _ it stands at just below 70,000 troops and
support personnel _ and changing in character, from peacekeeping
forces to offensive engagement.
</P>
<P>
   The number of U.S. troops presently involved in the operation
has grown to 22,500, including Marine detachments that have been
shipped to the Adriatic Sea for possible action. About 2,600 Army
personnel will accompany the Apache helicopter units to Albania by
week's end, and nearly 10,000 U.S. soldiers are less than 200 miles
away in Bosnia, along with 20,000 troops from other NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon says that Abrams tanks and Bradley Fighting
Vehicles will be transported to the Albanian-Kosovo border region
by mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch forces in Macedonia have been reinforced in the past two
days by artillery units, according to the Netherlands Ministry of
Defence. Altogether, there are now 12,000 NATO troops just across
Kosovo's southern border in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 6,200 French troops in Bosnia and Macedonia, say
government sources, are elements of the Commandement des Operations
Speciales (COS), an elite commando force used in raids behind enemy
lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Army has 75,000 troops _ 40,000 of whom are
currently in Kosovo _ backed up nationally by 75,000 Interior
Ministry police and 150,000 reservists with varying degrees of
battle-readiness.
</P>
<P>
   On the diplomatic front, NATO's shift to a more aggressive
military stance has been paralleled by what many observers regard
as a new and more open-ended version of its aims in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Across Europe, newspapers and parliamentary exchanges this week
have repeatedly cited an apparent change in Washington's definition
of the ``permissive environment'' necessary for U.S. troops to
advance into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   During the failed Kosovo negotiations at Rambouillet, France,
the phrase was understood to mean an explicit invitation from
Belgrade to serve on a peacekeeping mission in the province. But
Sunday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright declared that ``there
are other ways of creating this environment,'' which many Europeans
interpret as an armed expulsion of the Serbian military followed by
an invitation from the Kosovars themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in Brussels, NATO Secretary General Javier Solano
emphasized that the organization's objectives include ``the
deployment of an international security force (within Kosovo),''
and ``the retreat of Serb armed forces, police and paramilitary
forces.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the center-left politicians who govern most
European Union nations have rallied around a proposal to enforce a
security zone covering all of Kosovo, in which NATO would provide
military protection on the ground for the return of refugees to the
province. The idea was first broached on Monday by Socialist deputy
Paul Quilles, president of France's national Defence Commission.
</P>
<P>
   As in Germany, the leaders of France's historically anti-war
Green Party have strongly argued in favor of ground intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Political anxiety, rather than military weakness, has kept most
NATO leaders short of unambiguously endorsing escalation _ the fear
that their own citizens would rebel against a decision to send
troops into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But there is mounting evidence, in North America and Europe
alike, that the grisly images of Kosovo's ethnic cleansing and
terrified refugees are steeling Western voters' resolve.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Newsweek survey found that 54 percent of Americans
now support ground intervention. Less than one-third of respondents
to a New York Times/CBS poll published Thursday said they thought
bombing alone would end ethnic cleansing in Kosovo. If air strikes
do not work, according to an NBC/ Wall Street Journal survey also
published Thursday, 73 percent of Americans are in favor of ground
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   In an opinion poll in the Sunday Times of London, Britons
supported ground action against Yugoslav troops by 66 percent to 27
percent. Germans, who have been Europe's leading pacifists since
the end of World War Two, backed a Bundeswehr's role in the NATO
operation by 62 percent to 31 percent in a March 26 poll.
</P>
<P>
   Over seven consecutive opinion polls in France, an average of 55
percent of the public has steadfastly backed NATO operations.
</P>
<P>
   As almost all observers add, however, public support might
quickly dwindle if serious Western casualties were sustained.
</P>
<P>
   An unpredictable factor in this picture is the emotional power
of Serbian nationalism, and its historic obsession with Kosovo,
site of the 14th century defeat at Turkish hands that utterly
destroyed the medieval Kingdom of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Six hundred years later, would Serbs take the suicidal risks
necessary to stop a NATO invasion?
</P>
<P>
   In a poll conducted by Nin, a Belgrade weekly, 65 percent of
respondents said they would ``defend Kosovo at any price.'' Nearly
15 percent said the only solution to the crisis was to ``chase the
Albanians out of Kosovo'' or to ``liquidate'' them.
</P>
<P>
   Zeljko Raznjatovic, the Serb militia commander known as
``Arkan'' _ whose men were responsible for dozens of civilian
massacres in Croatia and Bosnia _ promises that the price of an
invasion will be high. ``We have a big heart to defend our
country,'' he said in a telephone interview with MSNBC, ``and
that's why I'm telling you, when you come here with ground troops,
we will make a hell out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history in Bosnia says otherwise. Serb nationalist
resistence there, both from regular army units and from
paramilitary groups like Arkan's ``Tigers,'' crumbled immediately
when 60,000 NATO-led combat troops were deployed to end the war.
Since then, the peacekeeping force has been cut by half without
hostilities resuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling is that this would not necessitate the deployment
of land forces in numbers as considerable as as those that are
cited here and there,'' said former French Defence Minister
Francois Leotard, alluding to the proposal to enforce a security
zone in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of NATO troops required to seize and
hold Kosovo have ranged from 100,000 to 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall that in Bosnia, in a vaster territory, 30,000 men are
at the moment enough to enforce the Dayton accords and the
co-existence of different communities so long at open war with each
other,'' Leotard wrote in Le Monde on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 0312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
