<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Young man, think before you turn
your thoughts
 &HT;    Lesson of love on a train to Milan
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ital)''In the spring, a young man's fancy lightly turns to
thoughts of love.'' _ Tennyson. (endital)
</P>
<P>
   Better, boys, that you should concentrate on baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But if you persist, there are some things you need to know about
women.
</P>
<P>
   Though I'm pretty well past the point of participation _ there's
not much spring in my step regardless of the season _ I received a
refresher course last fall, gratis of a beautiful young woman who
makes her home where once lived the world's most famous princess.
</P>
<P>
   This was in Monte Carlo, whose people still revere the late
Princess Grace as someone like unto a saint.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, was where Kathleen, the young woman I met boarding a
train to Milan, was living her own fairy tale.
</P>
<P>
   She was tall and willowy, with blondish brown hair, blue eyes
and lovely features. Her accent was Swedish. Close your eyes and
you would think hers was the voice of Greta Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   She had become a model at age 16 and toured much of the world _
Europe, America and Asia _ with the fashion runway as her stage. It
was at a show in Monte Carlo that her husband-to-be, whose family
has substantial real estate investments in Monaco, saw her for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   When I met her she was just 25, a woman who knew the world and
what it had to offer, and had chosen well. She had chosen a
Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something special about Frenchmen,'' she explained in
her lovely accent. ``They are very, very gentlemen, and very
romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Englishmen, I asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Russians?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Germans?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hah!''
</P>
<P>
   That had pretty well narrowed it down.
</P>
<P>
   How about American men?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Americans do not know how to treat a lady,'' she said.
Then she shrugged, in way of a apology, ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, too, I told her.
</P>
<P>
   So, what does the Frenchman have over most everyone else?
</P>
<P>
   ``You smoke a cigarette, and you get the light,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, she'd been smoking one cigarette after another on
the train. Silly me for not flicking my Bic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always open the door for you. You always go in before
them. They pull back the chair for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day you receive flowers, and they always call. Small
things, perhaps, but very important for a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Small gifts as well?
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, but it doesn't have to be expensive. It is the
...'' She paused, looking for the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought,'' I suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes! It is the thought that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   And she told this story:
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine, she was very sad one day because her
boyfriend was out of town. When he phoned her long distance she
told her how lonely she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately after they hanged up, he called a shop in her city
and had them send her their biggest stuffed animal and with the
note, 'To keep you company until I return.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Kathleen said, ``it was the thought that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, fellows, all a woman expects of you, now and
forever, is that you treat her like a princess.
</P>
<P>
   (ital)'' ... that is all ye know on earth, and all ye need to
know.'' _ Keats. (endital)
</P>
<P>
   Class dismissed. Baseball anybody?
</P>
<P>
   Anybody?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
