<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palm Beach: An island of white dogs, cell phones
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There are two requirements for living in Palm
Beach, besides the obvious one of having more money than God: a
little white dog and a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   I'm here on company business, staying in a hotel where one of
the Kennedy heirs died of a drug overdose in the 1980s. I've seen
Donald Trump's estate from afar. It's of course ridiculously big.
Driving a vehicle that costs less than a four-year education at the
University of Texas is apparently against the law here. A Mercedes
is the equivalent here of a Ford Taurus in the real world. The
Mobil station around the corner had four Rolls Royces in the
parking lot and no self-service gasoline. Every time I walked
around, I imagined the police were slowing down to scrutinize me,
someone who obviously doesn't belong here.
</P>
<P>
   I'm way out of my league here.
</P>
<P>
   Normal people live in West Palm Beach, across the bay, a typical
sprawling Florida city. West Palm is a melting pot of Yankees,
Cubans, Jamaicans and blacks _ my kind of place. Palm Beach, the
island, is tiny, about 10,000 residents, and by my guess 9,980 of
them are white.
</P>
<P>
   The police station even looks like a luxury hotel. There's not a
7-11 in sight.
</P>
<P>
   And the little white dogs are everywhere, mostly on leashes,
pulling old people along, yapping incessantly. I sat out by the
pool the first day there and watched as a little white dog on a
expandable leash tried to take a chunk out of a housekeeper who
ventured too close. The owner came out and glared at the maid as if
it was her fault. I glared at the owner.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I took a stroll down Worth Avenue, which is billed as
Florida's version of Beverly Hills' Rodeo Drive. I didn't bother to
go inside the stores _ Gucci, Ralph Lauren, Ferragmo, et al. _
since simply window shopping told me I had no business even
browsing. It was fairly early and many of the shops weren't open
yet. In about half of the shops still closed, a little white dog
stood at the door, yapping incessantly at the sight-seers and the
other little white dogs out for a morning stroll.
</P>
<P>
   The accent here is New York, by and large. I ate a patty melt at
a place called Hamburger Heaven, which is presumably where Palm
Beachites go when they're slumming (there are no franchises on the
island that I saw). I sat at the counter and listened to old people
with leathery tan skin talk with accents that made them sound like
Bronx cabdrivers. I thought to myself that this has got to be a
great place to be a dermatologist or a skin cancer specialist. I
paid $11 for a patty melt, fries and an iced tea, which is about
four bucks too much.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the cell phones. Yeech. While out at the pool, I
watched a 60-ish man wearing a way-too-tight Speedo and sporting a
forest of white chest hair, yap nonstop on a cell phone, making
deals right and left while sipping Perrier. To his credit, he did
not have a little white dog with him. Still, he annoyed me.
</P>
<P>
   I sat out there for about three hours, reading
``Cloudsplitter,'' a historical novel about radical abolitionist
John Brown. Three uninterrupted hours spent wearing shorts and
reading by a pool in March qualifies as heaven in my book. The man
never quit yapping on the cell phone. He would wander about,
sometimes dangerously close to me, ogling the women sunning
themselves. Admittedly, I was ogling the women too, being of the
male species, but I had neither a cell phone nor a white dog, so I
was harmless.
</P>
<P>
   I probably could have made a bundle just following his wheels
and deals, but all my money at present is invested in children
attending the University of Texas. I fantasized about pimp slapping
him, tossing his phone into the pool and screaming, ``You're on
vacation, bubba! Get off the danged phone! You have made enough
money for one day!''
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't. The police here are just itching to bust some
yokel who roughs up one of the nouveau riche, and I wasn't about to
give them the satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   The beach is beautiful at night, illuminated by floodlights
stationed on the high-rise condos, so that they catch the tips of
the waves and create artificial moonlight. I'm not making this up.
I'm reasonably sure there is an Artificial Light Wave Committee in
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the boats. I love the idea of boats, their
sleekness and beauty, but in truth I get sick as a dog on boats.
There are many boats here, most guarded fiercely by little white
dogs and captained by people who made their money in mysterious
ways. I would love to know how they made their money, but likely it
would depress me. Luckily, that night I was able to head across the
bridge to West Palm and find some basic Cuban food _ skirt steak
covered with onions, accompanied by black beans and rice, washed
down with some sangria wine, and with a side of plaintains.
</P>
<P>
   You have to know your limits.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
