<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN10-COX     04-09 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    We need to get better at naming computer viruses
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I wonder who is in charge of naming the new
computer viruses? They must work for the Bureau of Names, you know,
that place where they put titles on military campaigns, decide what
to call hurricanes every year and make up the official names for
bills so that no one will know what the bill is really about.
</P>
<P>
   I say this because two new virus doozies have just been
announced in the last couple of weeks. First came Melissa, then
came Papa.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa? Papa?
</P>
<P>
   If I didn't know better, the person who came up with Melissa was
an aging hippie who had had too much acid in his early years and
couldn't get the Allman Brothers song by the same name out of his
head. Except I do know better. People who deal in computers aren't
aging anythings, they are all kids. The truth, as we later found
out, is that Melissa was apparently named for a topless dancer,
which would have been all right if topless dancers still went by
names like ``Modesty'' or ``Fanny.''
</P>
<P>
   Papa seems a little more understandable, but it still isn't
descriptive. You can't read the name of the virus and have any idea
what it will do to your computer.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if viruses worked like life, I know what the Papa
virus would do: Exactly what the Mama virus told it to do. Find the
computer code equivalent of a recliner and you have the Papa virus
whipped.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you wonder what the Mama virus would do. That's simple.
Any darn thing it wants to.
</P>
<P>
   We would do a lot better if we used names that were
characteristic of what the virus really did. Here are my ideas for
some viruses we might see in the future (or that are already here,
perhaps?) and what to name them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bush virus: Causes you to be unable to tell whether your
computer will run or not. You must wait until the end of May to be
absolutely sure.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore virus: Computer keeps going into sleep mode. Appears to
have originated in a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   _ GOP virus: Computer starts out running better than you can
believe, followed by a sudden, severe crash. Happens over and over.
Does not appear as if this can be fixed; just get a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moral Majority virus: Affects computer's sound system. After
typing every word, computer repeats the sound, ``tsk, tsk, tsk.''
Costs considerable amount of money to repair as technician keeps
sending you bills saying he needs the money to keep the computer,
``on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Gates virus: Every computer in the world is already
infected and there is nothing you, the federal government, or
anyone else can do about it. So there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tyson virus: Uses more than expected number of bytes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pat Buchanan/Jesse Jackson viruses: Both have the same
characteristics. Computer runs once every four years, but nothing
ever really happens except that a lot of noise is generated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jerry Springer virus: Makes your computer get very, very dumb.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO virus: Message appears on screen that demands you allow
neighbor to use your computer whenever he wants or computer will
explode.
</P>
<P>
   _ Milosevic/Saddam virus: Extremely dangerous virus which can
move from machine to machine without any direct connection.
Computer will need to be destroyed as there is no fix.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
