<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1897 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN10-COX     04-09 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It is Opening Day in Cincinnati, a perfect spring
afternoon, replete with the mingled smells of hot dogs and popcorn,
the aesthetically satisfying contrast between the sea of red and
white shirts and the lurid green of the AstroTurf.
</P>
<P>
   My husband brings Doritos for the kids, instead of the promised
cheese nachos. It is an indignity not to be borne. ``Not those kind
of chips!'' one wails. ``I hate that kind!'' We bite our lips,
forcing ourselves not to say, ``In our day, we would have been
thrilled with sharing a bag of peanuts.'' We wonder why there are
tears instead of smiles.
</P>
<P>
   It happens all the time: When we're supposed to be having fun,
Americans find something to gripe about. In the midst of our
plenty, we focus on what's missing.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, we watched the CNN footage of the Albanian
refugees massed at the Macedonia border, wearing brightly-colored,
beautifully woven jackets and hats, a remnant of the more
prosperous life from which they have recently been torn.
Everywhere, men and women hold onto their children as if they'll
never let go.
</P>
<P>
   It was not to be borne. We turned off the TV and tried to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the images persist, this terrible week: An Albanian man
clutching his golden-haired child at the Petrovic airport. A woman
nursing her baby as she marches into Macedonia. Men fleeing along
railroad tracks to avoid land mines, carrying an elderly woman in
the makeshift rickshaw of a tattered red-checkered blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Now the news that some 25,000 refugees have been turned back,
herded into buses so quickly that some became separated from their
families. The piles of rubble in the modern provincial capital,
Pristina, begin to remind us of Sarajevo. The U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees Sadako Ogata said there are reports of
abandoned, burned-out cars along major roads in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Before this tragedy, many of the refugees _ in Pristina
particularly _ had attained a decent standard of living. Cars,
computers, the hope of a better life for their children. Not so
different from us.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being forced out of our homes, no time to pack a
suitcase. Everything we have burned behind us, our families split
up.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine not knowing where your children will sleep tonight, or
whether your government will try to use them as ``human shields.''
Imagine not knowing if you'll be able to protect them from
genocidal soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   We can't imagine it, try as we might. No war has been fought on
our soil since 1865.
</P>
<P>
   So we can afford to lose perspective about what's important. We
can afford to forget how lucky we are.
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati on Monday, 55,112 people swarmed out of Cinergy
Field following the Reds' opening day loss. A party atmosphere
prevailed, accompanied by a sultry sax rendition of the ``Addams
Family'' theme song, yet people groused that riverfront
construction forced them to park a dozen blocks from the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, tens of thousands of people _ a virtual human tide _
have embarked on a massive exodus on foot. Relief agencies have
provided shoes to those whose soles have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   We can push the images out of our minds, but they gnaw at us. We
can no sooner turn away from their suffering than we can comprehend
it _ or than we, never knowing such hardship, can feel the full
measure of gratitude for all that we have.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
