<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN10-COX     04-09 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Australia's a long hop unless you're born to shop
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ This report comes to you from somewhere in
the South Pacific. We are here because my wife, a direct descendant
of Christopher Columbus, and Beverly Mobley, her confederate in
wanderlust, discovered a University of Georgia-sponsored excursion
that's so cheap they practically pay you to go. At least that's
their story, and they're sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   A trip from Fayetteville to Australia equals approximately 3,152
shopping trips to Lenox Square, a mall in Atlanta. Since wives
travel mainly for the shopping opportunities, I am proposing a tour
that will accomplish the same purpose for a much smaller cost and
far less physical wear and tear.
</P>
<P>
   We will board at Hartsfield Airport after the supper hour, so
that instead of being in a comfortable bed during normal sleeping
hours we will be scrunched three abreast in seats designed for a
kindergarten classroom. After a delay to repair an equipment
malfunction, we will circle between two small Georgia towns until
everybody has swollen feet and a portion of mystery meat and a
small glass of wine has been served.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone begins to doze, we will wake them up and land in
Chattanooga, Tenn., where a bus will be waiting to take wives on a
shopping trip to Lenox Square with a stop at a factory outlet in
Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   An optional trip to Birmingham, Tenn., will be followed by a
return to Hartsfield, where, to add foreign flavor, everyone will
take cabs to a hotel in Chamblee, a diverse unincorporated area in
DeKalb County. After a bus trip below the gnat line, we will go to
Jacksonville for a return flight to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Australia isn't that simple. From Atlanta to Sydney is 18 1/2
hours flying time. Elderly travelers have been known to develop
fatal blood clots en route. I called Dr. Randy Martin, the renowned
television cardiologist, to inquire if there was anything I could
do to cut my chances of dying somewhere over the Pacific. ``Take an
aspirin and stand on your head at least once every hour,'' he
advised. I asked him if he gave that advice to all his patients.
``Only a favored few,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   My other concern was Bobby Mobley, entrusted into my care by his
long-suffering wife, Beverly. Bobby's normal range is limited to
lunching at Waffle Houses not far away. I was apprehensive about
his behavior when I discovered our tour group included several
couples from Atlanta's elite Northside.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the group was balanced with an equal number of
Southsiders, including the Clacks, Jeannette and Jerry from Lake
Spivey, and Barbara and Jim from Henry County. ``Those boys are
just like us,'' Bobby observed. ``They over-married.''
</P>
<P>
   Once we got circulation back in our lower extremities and our
eyes pried open, Sydney turned out three times as nice as San
Francisco, with great restaurants and a nearly completed Olympic
village that's threatening to make Atlanta look like Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Claude McBride, our tour commander who doubles as
chaplain for the UGA football team, got off the plane in Sydney
wearing his coaching staff shirt. ``My God!'' exclaimed a
bystander. ``You aren't recruiting over here, are you?'' He wasn't,
although considering the trouble we had on short yardage last year
a springy-legged kangaroo at fullback wouldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of our visit to Melbourne, ahead of a world-famous
botanical garden and historic buildings, was an opal store giving
away earrings, necklaces, rings, etc., at a price no red-blooded
American female could refuse. We saw penguins coming home from the
sea, bringing fish to mates and offspring. Penguins, along with a
handful of surviving Eisenhower-era Republicans, are thought to be
the only monogamous creatures left on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   We landed in Alice Springs, in the middle of the Outback and
100-degree heat, which became nearer 120 at Ayers Rock, which is
inclined to change colors three or four times a day. Alice Springs
is often mistaken for the sun side of the moon, or Yuma, Ariz. Just
the kind of place to ride camels to supper, which we did.
</P>
<P>
   Aborigines, otherwise known as Native Australians, are the
leading tourist attraction in the Outback. Our politically correct
local guide explained their sensible lifestyle. They don't take
baths because of what water does to skin oils and have a lot of
rules worth considering, one being that when a man takes a bride he
can never again speak to, or be in the same room with, her mother.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we headed for the Great Barrier Reef and a cooler
clime, Bobby had turned into a hero by pulling a fat lady from Long
Island to safety when their hot air balloon crashed into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think we'll ever get back to Georgia,'' he asked when it
was so hot our plane had to jettison fuel and baggage to get off
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably,'' I assured him. ``Some of the soldiers and sailors
who served down here in World War II survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor-in-chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
