<HEADER>
A1901 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD10-COX     04-09 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get the box right
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the Internet, a woodworker postulates that ``most
everything that a woodworker builds is based on a box,'' which is
another way to describe casework, but then he adds:
</P>
<P>
   ``How hard can it be to build a box?''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a man who's never built one.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one reply to his statement went like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can build 'a box', but to build a box that's square,
with perfectly fitting joinery, be it mitered corners, box jointed
or dovetailed sides, can be one of the greatest challenges facing
all. Me, I keep try'n.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it has long been my contention that there is no better
practice for the woodworker in general and the casework builder in
particular than small boxes.
</P>
<P>
   You will learn joinery. Virtually every joint known to the
professional can be employed in building a box and its lid.
Dovetails are a staple, and you'll have to cut them by hand, or
with a band saw, because router-cut joints would be far too large
for the dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   Read all the articles about easy and quick box joints, and then
try a delicate box joint of 15 slots or more. See how many jigs you
have to make before you get one right. Box joints are easy when you
don't have more than six or seven slots. But a dimensional error so
slight as not to be noticed there will be multiplied in a longer
joint until it simply won't go together.
</P>
<P>
   You want mitered corners? Fine, but that's a cut, not a joint.
The simplest way to joint mitered corners is with splines; makes an
outstanding joint in a box or a dresser. Want it a little tougher?
Try mitered secret dovetails. Only you will ever know they there
once they're in place, so you'll want to make a picture before you
glue it up.
</P>
<P>
   You can also make splines, or even dovetailed splines, that run
sideways through a mitered joint. Make them in a contrasting wood;
it's very showy, even gaudy.
</P>
<P>
   You'll more often that not use frame-and-panel construction in
the lid, but you can make the whole box that way. The panels offer
a great way to try veneering; they're not so big that you need any
special equipment for glueing the veneer in place.
</P>
<P>
   When I first got started, I made some nice boxes but I could
never get the lids to fit right. Like to drove me crazy until a
more skillful craftsman explained to me the importance of being
square. If you want to make a presentable box with a lid that fits,
you will learn that squareness is a basic principle of woodworking.
The box has got to be square or the lid will never be right.
</P>
<P>
   You'll learn a lot about proportions. You can make the most
skilfully-joined box out of the most beautiful wood you can find,
and if you got the dimensions wrong it will never be anything but
an ugly duckling. Fortunately, you can easily draw the dimensions
out full-size on newsprint or an artist's pad before you start;
it's hard to do that with a blanket chest.
</P>
<P>
   You won't have to spend a bundle of money building boxes,
because they don't require a lot of wood. You'll need a band saw,
for sure, because you'll need to resaw your stock. Nothing looks
clunkier than a small box built of four-quarter stock.
</P>
<P>
   Building a box is, in fact, no small thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
