<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, April 9, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday,
Sunday and Monday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNITY-SERVICE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Building on a trend
popular at many high schools, California Gov. Gray Davis wants to
require that students in every public college in California perform
community service as a condition of graduation. Davis said the
requirement would apply to every community college, California
State University and University of California campus _ 1.3 million
students. By ROBERT SALLADAY and KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY-CLUB (Albany, N.Y.) _ There are no requirements for
being in the First Friday Club. Core members began meeting almost
20 years ago in Manhattan. They named themselves after the Catholic
tradition that encourages going to church on the first Friday of
the month. So doing for nine consecutive months is believed to
ensure dying with a priest at your side. Their pact has a twist: If
you make nine club meetings in a row (usually held in bars, not
churches), you will die with a bartender. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-30 (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``Never trust anyone over 30'' was
the battle cry of the 1960s' Woodstock Nation, but this summer the
ultimate rock festival will itself turn 30 with a musical
celebration for a new generation. By GREG HAYMES.
</P>
<P>
   TV-AFTER-SOPRANOES (Undated) _ In a pretty lame TV season with
some bright flashes, the greatest surprise remains Rick Schroder,
the new character on ``NYPD Blue.'' As each episode passes, the
brilliance of selecting the ``Silver Spoons'' alum to replace Jimmy
Smits back in December comes into greater focus. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HARMONISTS (Undated) _ ``The Harmonists,'' a
European drama about the rise and fall of one of the century's
greatest vocal groups, is story-driven filmmaking of the sort that
doesn't much get made any longer. There's nothing flashy about it
but the heartfelt direction, thoughtful screenplay and the cast's
nuanced acting make for a well-told tale. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GO (Undated) _ By the time it gives itself over to
its ``Simon'' (Desmond Askew) third, ``Go'' already has its dirty
hooks sunk deep under your skin. It then proceeds to drag you
across its finish line andrenalized by the knowledge that it's the
sage+++ATH0
</P>
</TEXT>
