<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, April 9, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday,
Sunday and Monday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMMUNITY-SERVICE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Building on a trend
popular at many high schools, California Gov. Gray Davis wants to
require that students in every public college in California perform
community service as a condition of graduation. Davis said the
requirement would apply to every community college, California
State University and University of California campus _ 1.3 million
students. By ROBERT SALLADAY and KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOMMY-SINS (Undated) _ When Redbook magazine put out a call for
unforgettable mommy boo-boos, 133 readers responded. Read on _
you'll feel so much better! The stress of major holidays and other
special occasions seems to trigger the biggest mommy blunders. Next
time you're making excuses for the tooth fairy, take comfort:
You've got lots of company. By ALLISA MacMILLAN. (For release
Monday, April 12).
</P>
<P>
   LITERARY-CLUB (Albany, N.Y.) _ There are no requirements for
being in the First Friday Club. Core members began meeting almost
20 years ago in Manhattan. They named themselves after the Catholic
tradition that encourages going to church on the first Friday of
the month. So doing for nine consecutive months is believed to
ensure dying with a priest at your side. Their pact has a twist: If
you make nine club meetings in a row (usually held in bars, not
churches), you will die with a bartender. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-30 (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``Never trust anyone over 30'' was
the battle cry of the 1960s' Woodstock Nation, but this summer the
ultimate rock festival will itself turn 30 with a musical
celebration for a new generation. By GREG HAYMES.
</P>
<P>
   TV-AFTER-SOPRANOES (Undated) _ In a pretty lame TV season with
some bright flashes, the greatest surprise remains Rick Schroder,
the new character on ``NYPD Blue.'' As each episode passes, the
brilliance of selecting the ``Silver Spoons'' alum to replace Jimmy
Smits back in December comes into greater focus. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-HARMONISTS (Undated) _ ``The Harmonists,'' a
European drama about the rise and fall of one of the century's
greatest vocal groups, is story-driven filmmaking of the sort that
doesn't much get made any longer. There's nothing flashy about it
but the heartfelt direction, thoughtful screenplay and the cast's
nuanced acting make for a well-told tale. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GO (Undated) _ By the time it gives itself over to
its ``Simon'' (Desmond Askew) third, ``Go'' already has its dirty
hooks sunk deep under your skin. It then proceeds to drag you
across its finish line andrenalized by the knowledge that it's the
sagest, most invigorated spawn of' ``Pulp Fiction'' in a junkyard
littered with knock-offs. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-FORTUNE (Undated) _ The broken glass and
goosefeathers that lay fallen at the doorway of Jewel Mae Orcutt's
bedroom don't announce that ``Cookie's Fortune'' is open for
business. But when a gunshot uncorks a geyser of pillow stuffing
and a crystal salad bowl crashes to the floor, it's clear that
Robert Altman's neatly arranged, deceptively sunny comedy will
serve you now. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-NEVER (Undated) _ Going in, ``Never Been Kissed''
doesn't seem to have anything going for it: a geeky copy editor at
the Chicago Sun-Times who goes back to school to fulfill her dreams
of being a reporter. It's even got the limpest title of the recent
crop. But the film, directed with knowing affection by Raja
Grosnell, has wit and fearless self-awareness. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SEVENTH (Undated) _ When we're introduced to
29-year- old Mathilde (Sandrine Kiberlain) during the opening title
sequence of ``Seventh Heaven,'' she's a literal blur that steps
into our plain sight, only to jam a toy truck in her coat pocket.
The shock of being caught shoplifting knocks her cold, and her
husband Nico (the magnificent Vincent Lindon doing a lot for
drawn-mouthed, droopy-eyed men) can't determine how much he's to
blame for her listlessness and strange behavior. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ANGELS (Undated) _ Certainly it's a cineaste's
cliche to say that French films are driven by charac ter and
American films are driven by plot. In ``The Dreamlife of Angels,''
the two characters rivetingly played by young actresses Elodie
Bouchez and Natacha Regnier are just plain driven. By G. ALLEN.
JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-FEUD (San Francisco) _ The corporation that controls
the San Francisco 49ers has sued ousted co-owner Eddie DeBartolo in
a stunning move that could kill any chance of a quick end to the
bitter family feud casting doubt over the fate of the team and its
$525 million stadium-mall project. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   LAKE-PLACID (Lake Placid, N.Y.) _ It was wrought with
controversy, hampered by the warmest weather ever recorded and
handcuffed by the worldwide financial crisis. But the 1932 Winter
Olympic Games in the tiny Adirondack Mountains village of Lake
Placid also gave the United States its own winter sports mecca, a
status the village clings to more than 67 years later. By TIM
REYNOLDS. (For release Sunday, April 11.)
</P>
<P>
   RAC-JOCKEY-RETIRES (Jamaica, N.Y.) _ The queen of thoroughbred
racing is abdicating her throne. Julie Krone, far and away the most
successful female rider in racing history, will compete in her last
race April 18. She cited a ``constellation of reasons'' in
announcing her retirement, not the least of which was a series of
injuries. By MATT GRAVES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MILITARY (Alexandria, Va.) _ What if you gave a war and
despised the very military you asked to carry out your mission?
That is now the problem facing President Clinton and his
administration. Past comments and actions come back to haunt them
as they ineffectively try to wage war over Kosovo. By DOUGLAS
MACKINNON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
