<SLUG> BC-MOMMY-SINS-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERS TELL OF THEIR `MOMMY SINS' IN MAGAZINE SURVEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 For release Monday, April 12)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLISA MacMILLAN  
 c.1999 Redbook Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Redbook magazine put out a call for unforgettable mommy
boo-boos, 133 readers responded. Read on _ you'll feel so much
better!
</P>
<P>
   The stress of major holidays and other special occasions seems
to trigger the biggest mommy blunders. Next time you're making
excuses for the tooth fairy, take comfort: You've got lots of
company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Santa slipups: 22 percent of our readers were caught eating
the old guy's cookies, stuffing the stockings, or just stumbling
over an incoherent explanation for his existence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Easter Bunny, MIA: 3 percent mangled Easter morning by
forgetting to hide the eggs and candy for the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Birthday blowups: 2 percent overlooked a child's birthday,
missed a gift, or suffered some other snafu when under pressure on
the big day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flighty tooth fairy: 16 percent neglected their duties as
tooth fairy. They said the tooth fairy was sick, busy, or that
``Hey, look! I found the money while making the bed!''
</P>
<P>
   Margo Lujan, of Pflugerville, Texas, tried this creative save:
``My son was very upset when someone told him I was the tooth
fairy. I wanted him to believe, so I pretended to get upset at this
comment and said, `That is the dumbest thing I have ever heard.
Think about it, why would I pay for your teeth? If I wanted your
teeth, I would simply say, ``Give me your teeth.'' `Why would I
wait until you're asleep, sneak into your room, and replace them
with money?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought for a minute and said, `You're right, Mom, you'd
never give up sleep to pay for my teeth.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Trash trauma: Just between moms, many a precious object has
been secretly laid to rest in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   One daughter discovered her deceased goldfish in the garbage
(``Mom, what's my fish doing in there!?''); needless to say, it was
quickly removed and given a proper burial.
</P>
<P>
   Most of you who tried to ditch a prized work of kiddie art got
caught. Says Charisse Parisi, of Central Islip, N.Y., ``I was a
little too indiscreet when throwing away one of my five-year-old's
paintings made `just for me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only so much room for my little artist's
masterpieces, so I had to get rid of a few. He opened the garbage
can and, to his horror, found his painting covered in sauce on top
of the rest of the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I realized what I had done, I did my best to act just as
horrified. (`How in the world did that get there?') He fell for it
that time, and the spaghetti sauce painting hung on the
refrigerator for several months.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Zombie mommies: Kids have been stranded at school, left
rideless at friend's houses, and forgotten at restaurants, movie
theaters, skating parties, gas stations, and graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an especially good one from Diane Lizotte of Pascoag,
R.I.: ``When my son was about 11, he played Little League baseball.
Sometimes the games were scheduled for the evening. One night I
found myself bleary-eyed and tired as I sat on the bleachers
watching him play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to rest my head for a few minutes in the car. I fell
asleep and missed his great, game-saving catch. Not only that, but
I only woke up when I heard a tapping and saw my son and his coach
peeking in the car window at me. All the other parents were long
gone. Needless to say, I never really wiggled out of that one, but
I volunteered to work in the snack bar the following year, which
put me in the coach's good graces-and kept me awake.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Little love lies: Oh, what a tangled web we weave. The fibs we
tell seem harmless at first, but then seem to spin out of control.
Good luck trying to set the record straight later.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Mettler, of Perry, Ohio, writes: ``I told my son that I
dropped him when he was little and that's how he got the crack in
his butt. When his twin sisters were born he wanted to know when we
could drop them, because everyone has a butt crack! I had to come
clean and admit I was only teasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Bokshon, from Anderson, S.C., was fed up with McDonald's
and wanted her two- and six-year-old to eat something different.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the restaurant in her car, she turned a corner in
the other direction and explained, ``We can't eat at McDonald's
tonight, it's burned down.'' Her kids began to cry, and three days
later, when Bokshon couldn't take the guilt any longer, she thought
of a way to ease her conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Taking them back to McDonald's, she said, ``They built it back
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Her kids were understandably pleased, but, with a true
comprehension of time, her two-year-old asked, ``What took them so
long?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
