A1971 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-LANDSAT-$ADV1     04-09 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-LANDSAT-$ADV11-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, A PRACTICAL USE FOR SATELLITE PHOTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Later this week _ in fact, on Thursday, when you'll probably
wish you had started filling out your tax forms earlier _ NASA
plans to launch a satellite that will take 250 pictures of Earth
each day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it makes you feel better, you can tell yourself that probably
a little of the money you send to Washington will be used to pay
for some of this. If that doesn't improve your mood, well, you
strike me as pretty whiny and hard to please _ so contrary, in
fact, that I can't think of much I could tell you about taxes that
you'd like. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether you feel better about this or not, you may want to hold
real still and smile 250 times a day so as not to mess up this
work. A better idea would be to forget that. After all, the Landsat
7 satellite pictures will cover roughly 115 miles by 105 miles.
That means that whoever buys these images (at $475 a pop) won't be
able to pick you out very clearly, probably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I suppose, though, that depends on how big you are and what kind
of ridiculous hat you might have on. (What are you, a show-off or
something?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time this kind of satellite has been sent
into orbit to collect images of Earth. NASA, in fact, has been
studying the Earth since 1958 and there have been Landsat-type
satellites in use since the 1970s. Which means that you yourself _
unless you're a hermit who never comes out of your condo _ probably
have been included in hundreds of images captured by the
complicated cameras on board these satellites. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Landsat 5, launched in 1984, is still up there taking
pictures, snap, snap. The next satellite in line, however, Landsat
6, failed to achieve orbit after its 1993 launch and had to be
destroyed. That's how it is with satellites and horses _ quit
working and you're dead meat. (Unless, of course, you get put out
to stud, no doubt Bill Clinton's dream.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The folks responsible for this Landsat 7 project say it will
help us understand our environment _ especially once its work is
coordinated with the Terra Earth Observing System satellite to be
launched in July. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of scientists _ meteorologists, oceanographers,
biologists and worse _ will be studying these high-tech images of
Earth and trying to help improve weather forecasts, manage forests
better and so forth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And no doubt this is all a wonderful idea that has made _ and
will continue to make _ life better for all of us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard for me to understand why these satellites can't be
programmed to take more useful _ and much closer-up _ pictures that
would help us more directly with the stress of our lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, let's say it's the Christmas shopping season.
Well, in a few weeks weeks we won't have to imagine that's the case
because Christmas shopping now begins about Mother's Day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, say it's the weekend before Christmas Day and you've
made the boneheaded decision to go to a suburban shopping mall to
buy gifts _ the sort of presents that people who live their lives
more creatively than you do already have made by hand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What do you fear most in this scene _ besides, I mean, the
crowds and charge-card bills? Why, the parking, of course. Wouldn't
it be wonderful if there were a small TV screen on the dashboard of
your car that could receive constantly updated satellite photos of
the parking lot? It would save you from driving around and around
and around, looking for an empty space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and while they're at it, can't these satellites take
pictures that would warn us that the boss is on the way back from
lunch? Hey, our taxes are paying for this snazzy satellite stuff.
Why can't we get what we want? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, April 11, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
