<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SLIME TO SUBLIME IN THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   MONICA LEWINSKY: What? Monica is back in the news?
</P>
<P>
   Well, ``back'' isn't the right word. The right word is
``still.'' When you stop and think about it, the president's former
girlfriend never really vanished from the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   After ruling the tabloid universe for a year or so as the Starr
witness in Bill Clinton's sex-and-lies scandal, Lewinsky breezily
segued into the role of tell-all author and international pop idol.
She mingled with movie stars at last month's Academy Awards, and
she has drawn big crowds at book signings overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Monica bulletin, emanating from her book tour in
Norway and reported by USA Today: The love is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feelings are changing a lot,'' Lewinsky said, ``but I think
that one thing I do know for sure is that I'm not in love with him
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good to know. Do you suppose he's still in love with her?
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL ISIKOFF: Michael who?
</P>
<P>
   Some readers might not recognize the name, but just about
everyone is familiar with his work. Isikoff is the Newsweek
reporter who conspired with Lewinsky's ex-friend Linda Tripp and
Tripp's pal Lucianne Goldberg to help turn the Bill-and-Monica
sexcapades into the most read-about case of adultery since ``The
Scarlet Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff wrote a book detailing his pursuit of the White House
sex story and has been telling interviewers that he was a willing
participant in the Tripp-Goldberg plot to make a federal case out
of Clinton's sexual proclivities. Give him points for candor, if
not for good judgment and journalistic integrity.
</P>
<P>
   JENNY JONES: As long as we're down here splashing around in the
muck, we might as well mention the
stand-up-comic-turned-TV-talk-show-host who's being sued because a
guest on her show allegedly went out and killed another guest
because the show took a turn that the first guest didn't
appreciate. Seems that the program's theme was ``secret crushes''
and that the crushee was horrified to discover that he was the
object of a gay man's affection.
</P>
<P>
   The dead guest's survivors are suing ``The Jenny Jones Show''
for $50 million, claiming that the shooter was nuts and the program
made him nuttier. Wow. If putting wackos on the air can get a talk
show sued, Jerry Springer could end up spending more time in court
than he spends breaking up fistfights.
</P>
<P>
   MARK MCGWIRE: From the slime to the sublime. Having rescued
baseball from the trash heap of sport by blasting a mind-boggling
70 home runs last season, Big Mac has picked up where he left off.
McGwire launched the 1999 homer chase with an opposite-field smash
in the first game of the season, high-fived his batboy son, Matt,
as he did after so many trots around the bases in '98, and provided
a polite and humble interview on one of the TV news magazines.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget: He donates a chunk of his multimillion-dollar
salary to the battle against child abuse. Who says an athlete can't
be a role model?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN MCCAIN: I don't agree with him on all the issues _ he's
partial to the idea of deploying ground troops in Kosovo _ but the
Arizona senator/ex-prisoner of war is a man who says what he means
and means what he says.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is running for president, which means he'd be smart to
keep his opinions on Yugoslavia to himself. Most White House
hopefuls are waiting to see who wins the war before staking out a
position.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain isn't the sort of leader who waits for the parade to
go by and then sprints up the street to get in front of it. Right
or wrong, he takes a stand. Who says a politician can't be a role
model?
</P>
<P>
   BILL CLINTON: Talk about a pol who rushes to the front of the
parade to create the illusion that he's leading it. Clinton didn't
invent the strategy _ he just turned it into an art form.
</P>
<P>
   Give him credit, though: Clinton boldly went where others dared
not go in Yugoslavia, and recent polls indicate that the American
people are following.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: What will he do if the people turn against him?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
