<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET-LATINS-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEMPLOYED MASTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By LEON LAZAROFF 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Sitting behind a small rectangular desk that holds a
computer terminal and a small pile of papers, Jorge Piedrahita
spends much of his day in a rented Park Avenue office looking for a
job with a Wall Street banking firm. It has been about four months
since the Argentine trader was let go as director of Latin American
proprietary trading at West Merchant Bank, a job he held for just
one month after he decided to leave an equally notable position at
Citicorp Securities.
 &HT;    Piedrahita is not alone. In the past 12 months, hundreds of once
high-flying Latin American traders, analysts and deal makers have
been cut from their well-paid, high-stress posts at many of Wall
Streets largest firms. For the moment, they constitute the
Unemployed Masters of the Universe _ to borrow the phrase from Tom
Wolfe's ``Bonfire of the Vanities.''
 &HT;    In the highly competitive world of finance, jobs are usually
awarded or taken away for the most fundamental of reasons: the
bottom line. Either you make money for the firm or you go. The
mighty young wizards of Latin finance are no longer bringing in the
bulge bracket deals, so they must go.
 &HT;    As a market, Latin America has all but dried up for now.
Brazil's devaluation marks the end of an era in which firms built
entire Latin American divisions to handle massive deals. The people
who engineered the region's rise and fall made money, and had a lot
of fun, and took _ for a time _ center stage in the world of
finance.
 &HT;    Riding the boom and bust on Wall Street produced some very rich
young people, and in some cases, some very desperate ones. Chris
Taylor, a former telecom analyst at Bankers Trust, reports that a
couple of former colleagues earned as much as he did during their
tenures but simply forgot to put away any savings. Unlike Taylor,
who now plans to take a year off while carefully looking for his
next job, some former masters are more desperate than others.
 &HT;    But no one here says they are looking for sympathy. Wall Street
wages, justly or unjustly, reflect the high stakes and high
pressures of the industry. Booms and busts, whether in Latin
America or on the Internet, are simply part of the game. ``Hey, no
one should have pity on anyone who makes $200,000 or $500,000 [a
year,'' Taylor, fresh back from a trip to India, says. ``I don't
want to sound cocky, but during the good times some people get
hired who probably shouldn't be on Wall Street. And now, some
people lost out because of political battles, or they just didn't
cut it.'' Taylor, by his own account, was pushed out the shrinking
BT door following a heated internal fracas.
 &HT;    West Merchant's sudden decision to all but scrap its Latin
American operation forced Piedrahita and a group of his colleagues
onto the street. The firm blamed the cuts on Russia's sudden
default, but Piedrahita is quick to add that Russia wasn't the only
guilty party. Over the entire past 14 months, the once-mighty
emerging markets of South Asia, Latin America and Eastern Europe
have all but closed shop. ``I was downsized,'' he says frankly.
 &HT;    Downsizing at Wall Street's Latin American departments is
happening fast and furiously. At one firm, pink slips were handed
out by tapping people on their shoulders and asking them to clear
out their desks. So much for goodbye parties.
 &HT;    Insisting that he remains unfazed by his sudden job change,
Walter Molano, former director of Latin America macroeconomic
research at Warburg Dillon Reed, says he holds no bitterness over
being let go. ``When I came here, one Wall Street analyst gave me
some good advice. He said, There are very short windows of
opportunity here, don't think they'll go on forever,'' says Molano,
37, who now holds a similar position at BCP Securities, a
Greenwich, Connecticut-based brokerage specializing in Latin
America.
 &HT;    No one likes it when a glorious boom turns into a heartless
bust.
 &HT;    But that's what has happened. After a strong recovery from the
1995 Mexican peso crisis, Latin America was once again struck
broadside when financial failure in Russia sent Latin currency
rates tumbling and stock prices plunging; any talk of large
corporate or infrastructure bond deals was silenced. According to
Deborah Rivera of the Wall Street headhunting firm Allison, Gaines
&AMP; Rivera, many one-time Latin American gurus have moved on to
so-called buy-side firms such as fund management companies, and
even commercial banks. Others are still looking.
 &HT;    ``I clearly have more people looking for work than people who
want to hire them,'' says Rivera. ``It used to be that there were
huge bidding wars where people were getting giant guarantees and
cushy ex-pat packages to move to Latin America. Not anymore.''
 &HT;    To have been young, ambitious and riding the wave in Latin
American securities was exhilarating. It also was lucrative.
Looking back, Piedrahita says everyone has stories about watching
as a region known primarily as a financial backwater unaccustomed
to soliciting foreign markets turned into a major, if not the most
attractive, destination for global capital.
 &HT;    In 1991, the free-market gospel was being zealously embraced by
the region's economic leaders, both in government and corporate
boardrooms. In Argentina, then-Economy Minister Domingo Cavallo
unveiled his Convertibility Law, and Mexico's Carlos Salinas was
moving swiftly forward with large-scale privatizations. ``There was
a lot of talk about a new Latin America,'' Piedrahita says.
 &HT;    As far back as 1988, Latin American companies had begun to
return to the capital markets with private bond offerings, which
were followed by initial public offerings (IPOs) a few years later.
But Piedrahita recalls that many Latin American traders were far
more skeptical about Latin America's sudden popularity than those
based on Wall Street. In the early 1990s, Piedrahita was working
for Citicorp in Buenos Aires. He knew only too well that Argentina
was still a financial mess; other countries remained deep in debt.
``We knew there were still some big problems, so it was hard to
imagine what was coming,'' he says. ``We weren't sure just where it
would go.''
 &HT;    But by 1991, gradual economic improvements and newfound
international interest in the region _ sparked in part by a surge
in global liquidity _ transformed Latin American corporate bonds
and in some cases even sovereign debt paper into some of the most
sought-after assets in the world. ``Then it really did get
amazing,'' Piedrahita adds. In May 1991, Telefonos de Mexico
(Telmex) under the market guidance of Goldman Sachs, conducted its
landmark global stock offering. Telmex rapidly became the most
traded stock on the New York Stock Exchange, jump-starting Latin
America's equity boom.
 &HT;    For the next three years, everyone wanted a piece of Latin
America. Recruited out of Duke University in 1993 before completing
a doctorate in political economy, Molano went to work for First
Boston on its emerging-markets desk. In those days, Latin American
specialists got everything they wanted. ``There were a lot of
resources floating around. Firms were spending big money on Latin
America,'' Molano says. ``Christmas parties for Latin America were
major blowouts.''
 &HT;    Only the most conservative companies held them at the office.
Most brokerages staged the event at New York City's finest hotels
and restaurants, or _ why not? _ at a swank resort in the Bahamas.
Nothing was too good for the fine young men and women who were
bringing in billions in new business.
 &HT;    As 1993 and 1994 rolled on, general optimism began to border on
the excessive. Some brokers and analysts became so bullish they
began talking about certain Latin American countries becoming
investment grade and Latin America as a new asset class. ``Very few
voices were cautious,'' Piedrahita says. ``Business was booming.
People were toohappy to question things.''
 &HT;    Russell Ashcroft, who was at J.P. Morgan at the time, remembers
that heady talk. No longer were Latin American corporations or
their governments just performing routine commercial banking. They
were doing some of the most creative financing anywhere in the
world. Derivatives became commonplace. A bond market with annual
trading volumes of a trillion dollars had suddenly appeared out of
the rubble of the 1980s bank debt, as countries repackaged the old
loans into so-called Brady bonds backed by securities purchased
from the U.S. government. Investors were eager to buy this
high-yield paper.
 &HT;    ``There was this huge burst of a feeling that these countries
are trying to restructure their debts, they are our neighbors, and
most of these bonds have a U.S. Treasury component to them,''
Ashcroft says. ``For most of these countries, all of this was new
and they were uncertain how to do it.'' So, without much
hesitation, Wall Street firms, which had never thought seriously
about Brazil and Argentina, let alone Venezuela or Colombia, began
to send plane loads of their people southward.
 &HT;    The impact was immediate. ``Every graduate from an MBA program
wanted to get into emerging markets,'' Molano says. ``Departments
were growing willy nilly. People moved to other jobs after nine
months, doubling their salaries. It seemed as if there were no
restrictions on costs or expenses.''
 &HT;    Enrique Bustamante, who moved last fall from a waning ING
Barings to Merrill Lynch, recalls that riding the boom was
especially exciting for Latin Americans. Bustamante, a Mexican,
lived in his nation's capital during the 1980s, and watched with
proud eyes as his country became recognized as a leading emerging
market. It was nothing short of a local investment bankers dream.
``Coming from Latin America, there was this sense of doing
something good to develop the region,'' he says.
 &HT;    Ultimately, though, it was Bustamante's own Mexico and the
severe devaluation of the peso that would foreshadow the end of the
region's Wall Street boom. Mexico's overvalued currency came
crashing down in December 1994, and although Brazil's auspicious
Real Plan had just been introduced, the region spent the next year
in the doldrums. Thousands lost their jobs, and prices for basic
products soared out of reach for even those middle-class Mexicans
who had been the loudest supporters of free trade and foreign
investment.
 &HT;    But even as domestic and international money exited from Mexico,
investment banks did not execute the drastic restructuring measures
they would perform some four years later. Piedrahita's Citibank,
which has been in Latin America longer than any current competitor,
stayed on the ground, making only a handful of personnel changes.
``It was nice to see that the company was not changing its
strategy,'' Piedrahita says.
 &HT;    For those bankers who did lose their jobs after the Tequila
crisis, comparable positions could be found handling high-yield
debt elsewhere, particularly in the emerging markets of Southeast
Asia and Russia. ``Because demands for Russia were so strong,''
recalls the headhunter Rivera, ``if you could say you had been
doing emerging markets, you could end up somewhere else.'' And
there were still jobs to be found within Latin America. The
sleeping giant, Brazil, came to life with some of the world's
largest privatizations. Corporate and sovereign issues flew off the
shelf. It seemed that the region would continue to march toward
economic growth and stability.
 &HT;    Reality had other plans. Following the Asian collapse led by
Thailand in mid-1997 and Moscow's meltdown in August 1998, South
America's largest economy began to teeter. In the months leading up
to Brazil's devaluation last January, Latin America's boom-boom
decade came to a grinding close. Major international brokerage
houses began changing the way they cover the region.
 &HT;    Ruben Fernandez, an Argentine who joined Santander's
fixed-income department when the Spanish bank purchased Banco Rio
de la Plata in September 1997, was forced to leave just over a year
later. The experience left him wondering about the dedication of
foreign investors to his home continent. ``Some investment houses
have been in Latin America in a very erratic way,'' he says,
charging that most banks seek immediate profits without making any
real commitment to a region.
 &HT;    Of course, a bank's business is to make money, not commitments.
But for the smart young idealists who came to think they were
taking part in profound change, that bottom-line mentality deals a
double blow: their jobs have evaporated along with the region's
short-term financial outlook.
 &HT;    Comfortably ensconced now in the world of academia, Frank
Partnoy, a former Latin America derivatives trader, left Wall
Street altogether in 1995 after he accused his own brokerage house,
Morgan Stanley, of a concerted effort to deceptively force risky
products on unsuspecting clients. Watching the most recent
bloodletting on Wall Street, Partnoy, a law professor at the
University of San Diego, says he feels more sentimental than
vindictive about seeing so many people like himself tossed from
their jobs.
 &HT;    ``In a tortured kind of way I find it all sad,'' says Partnoy,
author of the widely acclaimed ``F.I.A.S.C.O. - Blood in the Water
on Wall Street.'' ``You define yourself as a macho Master of the
Universe and then you lose your job. So youre out looking for
something new and discover that the opportunities available will
pay you only a fraction of what you once made. That's going to hurt
no matter what you say.''
 &HT;    For the Latin American generation of Wall Street go-getters, the
current crisis has been sobering, admits Piedrahita. He thinks that
the next time around, some people may choose to go into a much less
volatile business. And he wonders what his long hours of frenetic
deal-making have gained him: ``Mostly, we all grew some gray
hair.''
 &HT;     
