<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-HARMONIST     04-09 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HARMONISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD STORY (AND MUSIC) IN `THE HARMONISTS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Harmonists,'' a tight European drama about the rise and
fall of one of the century's greatest vocal groups, is story-driven
filmmaking of the sort that doesn't much get made any longer.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing flashy about it _ the plot is basic
rags-to-riches, with a few fascinating historical subtleties _ but
Joseph Vilsmaier's heartfelt direction, Klaus Richter's thoughtful
screenplay and the cast's nuanced acting make for a brisk,
well-told tale.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in a speculative mood, ``The Harmonists'' (in German,
with subtitles) might remind you of ``The Commitments.'' The
difference being, of course, that ``The Commitments'' concerns a
contemporary Irish soul band that never existed (except in package
tours), while ``The Harmonists'' has to do with a syncopated
close-harmony male singing group that wowed Berlin in the late
1920s and soon thereafter seduced the world.
</P>
<P>
   They call themselves the Comedian Harmonists, and there are six
of them. Erwin Bootz (Kai Wiesinger) is the flighty pianist. Ari
Leschnikoff (Max Tidof) is the womanizing tenor. Erich Collin
(Heinrich Schafmeister) is the monocled baritone. Robert Biberti
(Ben Becker) is the corn-blond bass. Roman Cycowski (Heino Ferch)
is the other tenor, a profoundly religious Jew. And Harry
Frommermann (Ulrich Noethen) is the ensemble's fierce musical
engine, its founder, arranger, comic baritone, romantic idealist
and driving creative force. He is also, as it happens, Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Their true story _ which has already spawned two stage musicals,
one of them written by Barry Manilow _ has a good deal of soap in
it, examining the group's snarled love lives as well as their
bounding careers. But there are deeper levels, too, layers of
humanity and political tension sprung from the film's setting
between the two world wars. In an ensemble comprised of Jews and
staunch Aryans, conflict is inevitable _ with the government, and
with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises an interesting point: As accustomed as we've
become, these days, to Nazi-peopled period films, it's rare to find
one that addresses the struggle of musicians.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s the Third Reich placed severe restrictions on the
types of music played and the types of performers allowed to play
it. Jewish composers were banned. Jewish musicians were banned. And
as ``The Harmonists'' makes wistfully clear, a lot of careers
cracked up. (Many who failed to escape Nazi Germany in time landed
in the Theresienstadt concentration camp, where they continued to
make music before being shuttled off to the Auschwitz gas chambers,
but that's another story.)
</P>
<P>
   In one of the film's most affecting scenes, Harry and Robert
meet with a minister of the Reich Music Association to discuss
``the non-Aryans in the group.'' He commands them to quit singing
works by Jewish composers and threatens to ban the ensemble if they
fail to comply. Then, stiffly adjusting in his seat, he pulls out
one of the band's hit records and pushes it slowly across the desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I do have a small request,'' he says, and asks them for
autographs. His nephew, it seems, is a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Harmonists'' is built on such moments, elegant emotional
interplay that finds revelation in small things. Nothing is awkward
about it: Unlike a lot of fact-based dramas, Vilsmaier treats
history with an unfailingly dexterous touch. It zooms along,
hopping from Berlin night club to velvet celebrity to hints of the
century's darkest rumblings.
</P>
<P>
   The film's only real annoyance is its unidimensional female
characters, who consist of hookers, wives, assorted paramours and
mothers carting plates of sauerbraten.
</P>
<P>
   Noethen is mesmerizing as Harry _ his cool glare hides real fire
_ and Becker fills his role with great, blowhard puffs of ego.
Their performances, and Ferch's quiet turn as the spiritual Roman,
are standouts in a film of even-keeled artistry.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're wondering, those airtight, honeyed tones you hear
on the soundtrack are, in fact, those of the Comedian Harmonists.
Rather than hire a modern vocal group to render the group's old
tunes, the filmmakers dubbed in the originals. It was a smart move;
the recordings are clean, the cast lip-syncs convincingly, and the
results are enchanting throw-backs to an earlier era. So, in its
way, is the film.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
