<HEADLINE>
WOODSTOCK TURNS 30, OFFERING MUSIC FOR NEW ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREG HAYMES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ ``Never trust anyone over 30'' was the battle cry
of the 1960s' Woodstock Nation, but this summer the ultimate rock
festival will itself turn 30 with a musical celebration for a new
generation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the pop-'n'-rock music scene has splintered
into dozens of different factions ranging from funk-rock to
skate-punk to gangsta-rap, yet the Woodstock '99 festival slated
for July 23-25 at the former Griffiss Air Force Base in Rome
promises to be a literal gathering of the tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Such stylistically diverse musicians as Alanis Morissette, Korn,
Jewel, DMX, Metallica, Sugar Ray, the Dave Matthews Band and Willie
Nelson are among the 31 contemporary music acts announced Thursday
as performers at the three-day festival, marking the 30th
anniversary of the legendary 1969 Woodstock rock fest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three more days of mud, noise and logistical nightmares?
Wouldn't miss it for the world,'' said Metallica drummer Lars
Ulrich.
</P>
<P>
   Musically speaking, all roads will lead to Rome on Woodstock
weekend as this year's fest is expected to attract 250,000 fans to
the 3,600-acre Griffiss Park.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will be $150 for the three-day festival and will go on
sale at 9 a.m. April 25 at Ticketmaster outlets or by charging by
phone or through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other performers announced Thursday include Aerosmith, Bush, the
Chemical Brothers, George Clinton, Collective Soul, Counting Crows,
Creed, Sheryl Crow, Everlast, Fatboy Slim, Foo Fighters, Guster,
Ice Cube, Limp Bizkit, Live, Los Lobos, Rage Against the Machine,
Red Hot Chili Peppers, Rusted Root, the Brian Setzer Orchestra, the
Offspring and the Tragically Hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodstock isn't just a concert _ it's a rite of passage,''
festival co-producer Michael Lang said by telephone Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lang also was one of the producers of Woodstock '94 in and the
original 1969 Woodstock Festival in Bethel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodstock has become the Olympics of live music, so that every
five years we can step out of ourselves and celebrate diversity,
great music and each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical lineup features no musicians who performed at the
'69 Woodstock fest and only five _ Aerosmith, Sheryl Crow, Live,
Metallica and Red Hot Chili Peppers _ who played at the 25th
anniversary fest in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a festival that is designed for 17- to 28-year-olds,
not people in their 40s and 50s,'' said festival co-producer John
Scher. ``This is a huge commitment to come and camp and spend the
weekend with several hundred of your most intimate friends _ to
interact from a sociological and political basis as much as
watching a lot of great musical acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers indicated that probably about another half dozen
performers _ including ``a little more representation in the
hip-hop area,'' according to Scher _ will be added to the festival
lineup at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking for first and foremost is to capture the
spirit of the music of today _ to get the best and the biggest
bands performing today,'' Lang said. ``And then from that point,
we're trying to be a bit eclectic about who we book and also to
introduce bands that we feel are going to be important in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The bands will be performing on two main stages, located about a
mile apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't made a commitment yet, but we're considering adding
one more performance area that may be indoors or in the campgrounds
that would feature really brand new emerging artists,'' Scher said.
</P>
<P>
   While there currently are no plans to make a movie of the event
as was done at the '69 fest, Lang indicated that a pay-per-view
television broadcast of the event was a probability.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Woodstock 25th anniversary event in '94 lost money,
Scher _ who also co-produced that event _ was eager to try it
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just an extraordinary, incredible experience,'' Scher
said. ``History did indeed repeat itself. I don't know why. You put
a few hundred thousand kids in a field in upstate New York and
certain things happen. The pure magic of that, quite honestly, was
too irresistible not to try it one more time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
