<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AFTER-SOPRANOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW `NYPD BLUE' COP PASSES MUSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random thoughts bounced around my aching head on the first
depressing Friday since ``The Sopranos'' ended its epic first
season:
</P>
<P>
   _ In a pretty lame TV season with some bright flashes, the
greatest surprise remains Rick Schroder.
</P>
<P>
   As each new episode of ``NYPD Blue'' passes, the brilliance of
selecting the ``Silver Spoons'' alum to replace Jimmy Smits back in
December comes into greater focus. No one is snickering anymore, as
we did last summer when it was announced he was joining the show.
</P>
<P>
   The initial plan, according to co-creator David Milch, was for
Danny Sorenson to be somewhat of a rube. Sorenson has turned out to
be street-wise beyond his 28 years. On Tuesday, he even began
developing into a confidant of Andy Sipowicz (Denniz Franz).
</P>
<P>
   _ With all the new cartoons out there, the hottest one may be
... ``Scooby-Doo.'' Still shown on TBS and the Cartoon Network in
reruns (blow off those latter-day Scrappy-Doo episodes), Shaggy,
Scooby, Velma, Freddy, Daphne and, of course, The Mystery Machine,
are popping up on T-shirts, hats, Volkswagen ads, other shows
(including ``Family Guy,'' in a hilarious bit this Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   Question: Why does the rail-thin Shaggy always have the
munchies?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Titanic'' finally docks on television with its premiere at 8
p.m. Saturday on HBO. I saw the flick once, on a cross-country
flight last year. Halfway through, a thought hit me: Wait a minute,
this is a transportation disaster film ...
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Mod Squad'' stunk, according to reviews, and ``My
Favorite Martian'' was worse. ``Wild, Wild West'' and ``South
Park'' are coming out this summer. Now Hollywood is talking about a
movie version of ``Charlie's Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Here are some wholly unsolicited and probably
useless suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``WKRP in Cincinnati.'' Steve Buscemi as Dr. Johnny Fever,
Chris Rock as Venus Flytrap, Crispin Glover as Les Nessman, Dabney
Coleman as Herb Tarlek.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Waltons.'' Sam Watterston as John Walton, Meryl Streep
as Olivia Walton, Chris O'Donnell as John Boy, Wilford Brimley as
Grandpa Zeb Walton.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``My So-Called Life.'' Claire Danes can still play the part.
</P>
<P>
   While we're at it, here are three television-to-theater movies
we hope are never made:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Hazel.'' This has Roseanne written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``The Love Boat.'' Your captain: Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Veronica's Closet.'' Actually, it would be worth sitting
through the two hours if they promised never to make another
episode again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edie Falco looked familiar when she first popped up on ``The
Sopranos.'' Of course: she is also simultaneously in another great
HBO series, ``Oz.'' Then this week I rediscovered from a friend
another reason why I knew her: She was in my graduating class at
Northport High School on Long Island, N.Y. In our senior year she
had the lead in the school production of ``My Fair Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Just like any new mayor, Jason Nastke did the basics: Got
sworn in, settled into his office _ and appeared on ``Letterman.''
The 19-year-old mayor of Valatie, N.Y., was a guest on the ``Late
Show with David Letterman'' April 1. And he was good, even getting
Dave to crack up a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only one who didn't take me serious(ly) was the current
mayor,'' Nastke said. ``Now he is the ex-mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Letterman's on-air conclusion: ``Wow. you are pretty slick. You
are pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
