<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREEN SAVERS, THREE STOOGES ARE A JOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My screen saver stays on about 10 minutes and
then goes off. I think I must have made a mistake installing it.
</P>
<P>
   _ New to Computers
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NEW: Now why do people always assume they're the ones who
made a mistake when something goes kerflooey with their computers?
Trust me, most of the problems originate in faulty software design
or loony notions about how you should be forced to use your
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Screen savers are a good example. Back in the olden days, a
screen saver was necessary unless you wanted to see ``WordStar''
burned permanently into your monitor's phosphors. The way modern
monitors are designed, nobody really needs one. They're more of a
novelty, allowing you to think you're cooler than the other geeks
in the office because you have winged toasters flying all over your
screen.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to make fun of anybody for using screen savers,
though, because if you actually think they make you a supercool
hepcat, you obviously have much bigger problems to deal with. No,
what upsets me is how all the different screen-saving techniques
your computer employs work together about as well as the Three
Stooges on a plumbing job.
</P>
<P>
   That's your problem, New. Moe's pounding Curly over the head
with a big monkey wrench, and Larry's off on his own, digging up
the lawn, looking for the shutoff valve.
</P>
<P>
   All three are trying to blank your screen. Moe is the built-in
operating system, a program on a chip that runs the show when you
start up your computer. Moe usually has his power-saving mode
turned on, and he likes to turn your monitor and hard drive off
when he thinks you're not looking. Curly is your screen saver,
obliviously building a rat's nest of water pipes on your monitor
until Moe whacks him a good one and shuts it down. And poor, dopey
Larry is Windows, blithely off in some other world with a power
scheme all his own.
</P>
<P>
   You need to show these numbskulls who the boss is. First, tell
Moe to keep his hands off the power controls. You'll have to check
your owner's manual to get into the system setup program, but
that's where you can turn off power management. Next, yank out a
big hunk of Larry's hair so he'll pay attention. In the control
panel, click on the power management icon. Depending on your
Windows version, you may have a checkbox that lets Larry control
the power. Uncheck it. Or there may be separate settings for
turning off the monitor and the hard drive. I set them to
``never.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Curly. He's basically harmless. Let him build his
pipes.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: This is just a ``heads-up'' on a word you have
used in your column: nimrod. It is actually a great honor to be
called a nimrod. The dictionary defines ``nimrod'' as a ``great
hunter or sportsman.'' I hate having you use this appellation as
one of derision, when, in fact, it is quite the opposite!
</P>
<P>
   _ Word Czar
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CZAR: Oh, I understand now! You obviously didn't realize
that words mean what I want them to. Nimrod is simply too goofy a
word to use any other way. As for the dictionary: What a pile of
gorp! Now I suppose next you'll be telling me ``gorp'' is just
trail mix.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay is obviously trying to
slip another kakapo past the copy desk. He can be reached at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com,
</P>
<P>
   via snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth
76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
