<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
April 10, 1999. If you have any questions, please call the Star's
Universal Desk at (816) 234-4720.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRIEF (Washington, D.C.) _ The Pentagon's not giving us much
information about what the NATO forces are doing. Yeah, we get news
about what was hit, but little else about our side _ much less than
during the Gulf War. Has the Pentagon picked up the habit of being
mum from its non-war over Iraq? Or has the campaign's questionable
effectiveness kept everybody's head down? By Kevin Murphy. 25
inches. Story will move in the ``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEN (Kansas City, Mo.) _ At the end of World War II, South
Kansas Citian Ben Alvarado was part of the 80th Infantry Division
unit that conquered the tiny German town of Weimar. What the
conqueror's didn't do was destroy the place, and the people there
have been grateful for that ever since. This weekend, Alvarado will
be back in Weimar as part of a celebration organized by the people
Weimar to thank the Americans who spared their town. For Alvarado,
it's pretty confusing to embrace former enemies like this. The war,
by the way, changed his life profoundly. He was severely wounded
and had some psychological adjustment to do upon returning home.
And his younger brother Mike, who lied about his age to enlist,
came back so shell-shocked he never recovered. Mike lived a
quarter-century with Ben and his family of five children. By Donald
Bradley. With photos. Story will move in the ``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUNS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ The political fallout from Missouri's
concealed weapons race will continue into the new millennium. Two
biggies: Ashcroft-Carnahan race for U.S. Senate and the battle for
Missouri governor. By Kit Wagar. 20 inches. Story will move in the
``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KLEG (Topeka, Kan.) _ The Kansas Legislature's first adjournment
is scheduled for Friday, but the proceedings could drag into the
weekend; expect a story for Saturday that says lawmakers are
heading home with nothing to show for three months of work: no
highway bill, no tax cuts, no abortion legislation. By John
Petterson and John Dvorak. (Will be for Sunday if session spills
over into Saturday). Story will move in the ``a'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SANDRA (Merriam, Kan.) _ Sentencing for Sandra Wheeler, the
Merriam woman convicted of torturing two young relatives when they
visited her for two months last summer. The children, 6 and 8, were
beaten, bound with duct tape and burned with hot water and bleach.
By Tony Rizzo. 20 inches. With photo. Story will move in the ``a''
category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLANET (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Planet Hollywood now appears to be
an unlikely prime tenant in Kansas City's proposed Centertainment
District development. By Jennifer Mann. Story will move in the
``f'' category.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ COLUMN _ By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLAR _ Small-town folks
in Kansas and computer geeks from California will hold a hometown
barbecue today to celebrate a strange Y2K kinship that brought
together a dying town and an emerging online data management firm.
Story will move in the ``k'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
