<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-NEVER-HNS     04-09 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-NEVER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREW BARRYMORE MAKES A GREAT NERD IN `KISSED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, ``Never Been Kissed'' doesn't seem to have anything
going for it: a geeky copy editor at the Chicago Sun-Times who goes
back to school to fulfill her dreams of being a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. It even has the limpest title of the recent crop. But the
film, directed with knowing affection by Raja Grosnell, has the wit
and fearless self-awareness its months-old predecessors were afraid
of. It also has Drew Barrymore in a wacky, madcap performance
Goldie Hawn should use if she starts teaching little foxes roaming
the Hollywood Hills how to be uproarious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kissed'' is the first movie to which Barrymore brings more
than what the script asks her. Always a sunflower of
infectiousness, she usually sparkles to the point where it looks
like she's having more fun than she should be. Where Hawn was often
capable of putting her bubbles away, Barrymore's on-screen
solemnity had the obvious complexity of the lead in a school play.
</P>
<P>
   As Josie, the copy editor who desperately wants to be a writer,
Barrymore throws herself headlong into one 25-year-old's
self-esteemless plight for corridor-wide popularity. And Barrymore
suffers the girl's mountain of humiliation like the rubber-faced
phenom of pratfalls the role calls for.
</P>
<P>
   The film could succeed on its star's glee alone, but Grosnell,
working from a snappy script by Abby Kohn and Marc Silverstein, has
a terrific time juggling contempo camp and cheese. When not
plodding through tired scenes of more Hollywood newsrooms (this
one's presided over by Garry Marshall), ``Kissed'' gets an
earthbound whiff of ``Peggy Sue Got Married,'' moving between
Josie's sickly high school flashbacks circa '89 and her attempts to
find a salable story about ``young people'' before she and her
editor (John C. Reilly) get the hook.
</P>
<P>
   (Apparently, Hollywood would have us believe there's as much
pressure to get on this teen spirit bandwagon at newspapers as
there is at movie studios.)
</P>
<P>
   Faster than you can say Riley Weston, Josie is 17 again, trying
everything she can to be cool, but she falls in with the school
nerds, led by the unlikely but convincing Aldys (Leelee Sobieski).
Leave it to her equally daffy, formerly popular bro (David
Arquette) to reverse her rep by joining Josie undercover and still
out-cooling her. Where ``Never Been Kissed'' succeeds is in its
unabashed refusal to stoop to choosing sides in the high-school
hipness war. The kids are clique-y but with a comic humanity that
elevates jocks, geeks and airheads above archetype status.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, however. This is a chick flick so powerful it
can turn a high school baseball game into a love connection.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one with the open-mindedness to give its heroine the
option of the hot student (Jeremy Jordan, looking like he wandered
in from the ``Velvet Goldmine'' set) or the sensitive teacher
(Michael Vartan) with the hots for her.
</P>
<P>
   It's a testament to Barrymore's screwball legitimacy that she's
neither upstaged by quirkmeisters Molly Shannon (as Josie's
hilariously sexed-up co-worker) and Arquette nor out-geeked by the
luminously awkward Sobieski. But it's lousy that Arquette never
breaks into his ``800-CALL-ATT'' dance and gives us a free call.
We'd ring Barrymore and tell her we love her best as a full-tilt
dork.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
