<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-SEVENTH-H     04-09 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SEVENTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF MALAISE TAKES AN IRONIC TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benoit Jacquot has yet to meet a lonely, out-of-focus woman he
didn't like. When we're introduced to 29-year-old Mathilde
(Sandrine Kiberlain) during the opening title sequence of ``Seventh
Heaven,'' she's a literal blur that steps into our plain sight,
only to jam a toy truck in her coat pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The shock of being caught shoplifting knocks her cold, and her
husband Nico (the magnificent Vincent Lindon doing a lot for
drawn-mouthed, droopy-eyed men) can't determine how much he's to
blame for her listlessness and strange behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Mathilde winds up confiding her dissatisfaction to a man
(Francois Berleand) whom she's been running into at parties and
spotting on the subway. He turns out to be a hypnotist who tells
her feng shui will restore stability to her psyche and improve her
sex life.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor figures this out by completing a diagram of
Mathilde's apartment, then advising her to move her bedroom from
one end of the flat to another. There will come her ``seventh
heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, with Mathilde going AWOL at work and disturbing her
son with her unexplained domestic malaise, it feels like Jacquot's
headed in the woman-on-the-verge-of-psychosomatic breakdown a la
``Safe.'' But, mercifully, ``Seventh Heaven'' takes on the
inconvenient irony of an O. Henry story _ not to mention its
conciseness.
</P>
<P>
   Once Mathilde speedily regains her equilibrium, the film rests
squarely on Nico's shoulders as he wanders into an insecure
out-of-focusness of his own. Jacquot (who wrote the film with
Jerome Beaujour) has a thing for men whose psyches, egos and sex
drives are incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   Cad is the nicest thing you could say about the omnivorous
animal (played by Vincent Martinez) that brings a smile to Isabelle
Huppert's face and a tear to her eye in Jacquot's ``The School of
Flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Jealous of and flummoxed by Mathilde's breakthrough, Nico sheds
the veneer of the neglectful, adulterous husband and displays
genuine concern _ if not for his wife, then over the fact that he
can't believe he's finally satisfying her in bed. He staves off an
understated attack from his mother-in-law (deliciously insinuating
Francine Berge) and begins seeing a hypnotist in search of
psychological parity with Mathilde.
</P>
<P>
   Lindon, so good as Huppert's transvestite pal in ``The School of
Flesh,'' brings a critical gravity that counters the swift
evanescence Jacquot builds around him. The nervous irritation that
creeps onto his face when Nico fails to please his son with a
bedtime story is the same haggard, self-inflicted anger that'll
keep a guy like David Straithairn from being a star.
</P>
<P>
   It's beautiful _ especially when contrasted to the solar-powered
emptiness fueling Kiberlain. She often looks as if she knows the
camera's on her and it's adding 10 pounds to the level of her
self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   The film isn't to be confused with the Bible-belting television
show of the same name. Breezy as it is, Jacquot's film prefers to
do its conservative moralizing on the inside and keep God out of
its questions of erotic faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-GO-HNS &LR;      04-09 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GO' NEVER STOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Go'' is the sagest, most invigorated spawn o' ``Pulp Fiction''
in a junkyard littered with knock-offs.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly five years now, we've been forced to endure the
amateur-night ``Pulp Fiction'' tributes that amount to the scuzz
cinema equivalent of a ``Star Trek'' convention with Quentin
Tarantino its winking William Shatner god. There was scuzz before
Tarantino, but he managed to become the hypodermic for throngs of
C-movie crime junkies who dream of sublimating potty mouths and
literary verve into bewitching cinema.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go'' screenwriter John August gets buzzed on the ``Pulp
Fiction'' energy but is more enthused about the down-and-out losers
in Tarantino's ``Jackie Brown,'' spinning a single sequence from
that film into an entire movie of its own. Essentially,
exclusively, ``Go'' is a triptych whirling on a Lazy Susan of
revolving character perspectives of the mayhem that goes down when
Ronna, a supermarket wonder chick (Sarah Polley), sells some
Ecstasy to two pretty boys, Adam and Zack (Scott Wolf and Jay Mohr)
in order to pay the rent. Simon (Desmond Askew), their regular
dealer, just gave Ronna his extra shifts because he is Vegas-bound,
but these guys need to score. So Ronna wipes the sleep and dollar
signs from her eyes and does the stupidest, most desperate thing
she's ever done. She deals.
</P>
<P>
   Polley's Ronna has a fistful of self-control that belies the
fact that her nerves are fried from pulling a double. It's her
sidekicks-turned-accomplices Claire and Mannie (Katie Holmes and
Nathan Bexton) who get nervous. ``Swingers'' director Doug Liman
mines the situation's quick suspense. This on-the-job-training in
trafficking is going to go wrong. Just how bad does it get? Let's
put it this way: Once Ronna realizes she's short some cash and
leaves Claire with the menacing dealer (Timothy Olyphant) as
collateral, ``Go'' takes a hit of it own stuff and never stops
tripping.
</P>
<P>
   Under Liman's blistering, one-track-minded direction, ``Go'' is
so aerodynamic in its construction that there's no room for excess
baggage or delirious tangents. It has its sights set on delirium
but is too bleary-eyed to see them clearly. What you're left with
is an inflamed joy ride whose title says everything about the
frazzled hedonists living in the grooves of this pulsing 12-inch
single of a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Tay Diggs' conscientious thrill-seeking in the
``Simon'' chapter, none of these characters stops for a first
thought, let alone a second. Transfixed by electronic soundsmith
BT's throbbing score, ``Go'' moves on sex, drugs and techno, and
would have no idea how to control itself enough to encounter the
tantric orgasms Diggs talks about. It just wants instant
gratification.
</P>
<P>
   That speedy determination to get from ``Ronna'' to ``Simon'' to
``Adam and Zack'' in 100 minutes flat makes for wildly economic
filmmaking and exhausting moviegoing. But ``Go'' is neither the
transcendent, transporting experience of ``Pulp Fiction,'' nor does
it have it have the human depth that made ``Jackie Brown'' feel as
long as its characters were old. What it does have is an
exhilarating sense of now.
</P>
<P>
   The title functions as both a harried exclamation and the most
terse case ever against inertia. ``Go'' whizzes though a fear of
being bored in a culture too hyperactive to examine itself.
</P>
<P>
   Living isn't simply being on a roller coaster, it's being stoned
on one of those super-streamlined laser trains. ``Go'' revels in
the near-buzz-killing safety of knowing that like every amusement
park thrill ride, it'll return you to the platform a little shaken
but intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-FORTUNE-H     04-09 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-FORTUNE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORTUNE' DIRECTOR HAS A BALL WITH SMALL-TOWN ECCENTRICITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The broken glass and goosefeathers that lay fallen at the
doorway of Jewel Mae Orcutt's bedroom don't announce that
``Cookie's Fortune'' is open for business.
</P>
<P>
   But when a gunshot uncorks a geyser of pillow stuffing and a
crystal salad bowl crashes to the floor, it's clear that Robert
Altman's neatly arranged, deceptively sunny comedy will serve you
now.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jewel Mae ``Cookie'' Orcutt's broken-heart and loneliness
inspire her to blow her brains into a pillow, ``Cookie's Fortune''
meanders around Holly Springs, Miss., with the fuzzy benevolence of
a Hallmark Hall of Fame presentation. Toyomichi Kurita's
photography of the local juke-joint initially borders on lurid as
Josie (Ruby Wilson) smolders through the opening minutes with a
fire that tapers off the second she stops singing her smoky blues
number. It's one of the more riveting sequences Altman's composed _
the tone of which eludes him for nearly 25 minutes after.
</P>
<P>
   By way of Anne Rapp's traffic jam of a script, Altman introduces
us to everybody in Holly Springs. Cookie Orcutt (Patricia Neal) is
the regal town loon and its unofficial matriarch. Willis (Charles
S. Dutton) is the liquored-up handyman who lives on her crumbling
antebellum estate. The story disconnects the two from Camille
(Glenn Close) who's directing her sister Cora (Julianne Moore) in a
springtime production of ``Salome,'' one that promises to be as
pleasingly bizarre as the disco-era, severed-head-and-cocaine
version in James Ivory's ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries.''
(Though Camille's incarnation is based on the Oscar Wilde
adaptation and has greater bearing on the proceedings.)
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, it's vague how the catfisher (Lyle Lovett) with a
creepy eye on a striking, tomboy drifter named Emma (Liv Tyler) and
her estranged sheriff boyfriend (Chris O'Donnell) will situate
themselves among the dozen or so other characters. But you trust
Altman to get you there in spite of the fact that the rabbits in
Cookie's backyard hop faster than the movie. What you don't trust,
or don't believe, is the pleasant demeanor illuminating ``Cookie's
Fortune.'' The niceness is enervating and suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie's suicide brings the film's missing vitality. No
disrespect to Neal, who provides an elegant nonchalance, but when
what's surrounding her moseys more than she does, something's gotta
give. Fortunately, it's her will to live without her dead husband.
</P>
<P>
   Things don't speed on from here, they rollick and just seem more
focused and purposeful, as if Altman were never really interested
in the set-up of things, as if he, too, found the early warmth
artificial.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern-Gothic-lite tapestry Rapp builds allows Altman to
do some of his most nuanced storytelling with his best, non-gimmick
ensemble since '83's ``Streamers.'' Especially fine are Moore in a
perpetual state of kewpie-doll torpor and Niecy Nash as the randy
Sheriff's assistant with a jones for Courtney B. Vance's
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Camille discovers her alienated aunt's body along with the
suicide note. In a supreme fit of disgust, rage and consternation
over the chagrin a suicide in the family would wreak, Camille
stuffs the note in her mouth and proceeds to use her extensive
local theater training to stage Cookie's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Camille is nothing short of the most melodramatic lady alive.
Her antic scramble is Close's finest hour of histrionics. The
masticated note churns in Camille's stomach, fueling Close to feign
the coyness of a woman who just dropped a house on her sister _ or
her aunt's best friend, as the case may be.
</P>
<P>
   If Holly Springs were some bizarro Oz, those would be good
Willis' toes furling beneath that house. Dutton has a great,
refined way refusing to indulge in pathos, letting Tyler, Ned
Beatty as the town lieutenant and Donald Moffat as Willis' counsel
do his emoting for him. The days and nights Willis spends jailed
for Cookie's suicide bring Altman to further explore his very quiet
relationship with race and with the South. He's never been one to
make pulpit pronouncements about various ``isms,'' but the
harmonious jocularity he finds in Willis' predicament stirs an
unbitter poignancy that feels foreign to the tenor of his
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Whose South is this? The deep South of ``Cookie's Fortune'' is
as much an old South (the disregard for modern technologies, the
maintenance of aristocratic airs) as it is a new one. Even if
there's a romanticization of race relations, Altman finds Holly
Springs an idiosyncratic utopia where that ideal union can exist.
You're never less than aware of what a sensitive issue it is for
most of the town that Willis is sitting in a cell for something he
clearly didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   Altman's cynical urges disappear in the miles of unspooled
yellow ``crime scene'' tape spun all over Cookie's house, which
Camille has shamelessly orchestrated herself (and Cora) back into.
Camille becomes the screwball embodiment of a South so old and
institutional she seems like a figment, making her Blanche DuBois
send-off more than a sendup.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cheeky exorcism of a place far less sensationalistic than
the crime scene status Altman thinks it left years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
