<HEADER>
A2073 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CRISIS-PACKAGE     04-09 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CRISIS-PACKAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: To bolster your coverage of the crisis in Kosovo and
the Balkans, we offer the following stories from the roster of
Foreign Affairs Magazine's distinguished contributors.
</P>
<P>
   __ These articles have moved on the wire in the ``k'' commentary
and ``a'' general news categories. __ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BULLY of the FREE WORLD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By Garry Wills &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,600 words) As the world's only superpower, America is told
that it must act like ``a great nation,'' which still means
defending freedom around the world. That is a difficult enough task
for any nation. It is even more difficult for America, not only
because of its established Cold War pattern, but also because of
its longstanding tradition of holding aloof from global
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   __Garry Wills is the author, most recently, of ``Certain
Trumpets: The Nature of Leadership.'' (slugged:
BC-AMERICA-BULLY-WORLD-NYTSF &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LONELY SUPERPOWER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By SAMUEL P. HUNTINGTON &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,300 words) American officials seem peculiarly blind to the
fact that often the more the United States attacks a foreign
leader, the more his popularity soars among countrymen who applaud
him for standing tall against the greatest power on earth. The
demonizing of leaders has so far failed to shorten their tenure in
power, from Fidel Castro (who has survived eight American
presidents) to Slobodan Milosevic to Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   __ Samuel P. Huntington is the Albert J. Weatherhead III
University Professor at Harvard University, where he is also
Director of the John M. Olin Institute for Strategic Studies and
chairman of the Harvard Academy for International and Area Studies.
(slugged: BC-AMERICA-ROGUE-POWER-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL REPORTING, BEHIND THE SCENES  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By GARRICK UTLEY &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,400 words) To report international news, the cost of a
journalistic caravan, including hotels, per diem expenses, car
rentals and local support staff, begins at about $3,000 a day.
Airfare and excess-baggage charges can easily reach $12,000. Then
there are ``extras'' such as satellite fees. New digital
technology, including smaller and lighter cameras and editing
equipment, will eventually reduce costs, but there is no indication
that the networks will use the savings to increase international
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   __ Garrick Utley, former chief foreign correspondent for NBC
News and ABC News, is a contributor at CNN. (slugged:
BC-TV-WAR-NEWS-COVERAGE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEN IS IT RIGHT FOR POPULATIONS TO SECEDE? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By HURST HANNUM &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) There will always be ``trapped'' minorities, no
matter how carefully boundaries are drawn, except in the smallest
or most isolated environments. But when should secession be
supported by the international community? When massive human-rights
violations, approaching the scale of genocide, are being
perpetrated. Or when reasonable demands for minority rights have
been arbitrarily rejected by a central government.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hurst Hannum is professor of international law at Tufts
University's Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy and the author of
``Autonomy, Sovereignty, and Self-Determination: The Accommodation
of Conflicting Rights.'' (slugged: BC-KOSOVO-AUTONOMY-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TODAY'S KOSOVO CRISIS IS HARDLY A SURPRISE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By WARREN BASS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (2,000 words) The bloodshed in Kosovo is a symptom of the
approach, in the Dayton Accords of 1995, which strengthened
Slobodan Milosevic. In fact, Dayton plunged Serbia deeper into
ethnic chauvinism, whereby the ``sacred Serb soil'' of Kosovo
matters vastly more to Belgrade than do the Albanians who resided
there. As such, the Kosovo crisis comes as scant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   __ Warren Bass is an associate editor at Foreign Affairs and a
Wexner Fellow in history at Columbia University. (slugged:
BC-KOSOVO-BACKGROUND-DAYTON-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO MAKES WAR? MEN HATE IT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By BARBARA EHRENREICH &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,500 words) The male appetite for battle has always been far
less voracious than either biologically inclined theorists of war
or army commanders might like. In traditional societies, warriors
often had to be taunted, intoxicated or ritually ``transformed''
into animal form before battle. Throughout Western history,
individual men have gone to near-suicidal lengths to avoid wars _
cutting off fingers or limbs or risking execution by deserting.
</P>
<P>
   __ Barbara Ehrenreich is an author and lecturer whose essays
have appeared frequently in Time, The Nation and The Guardian. Her
most recent book is ``Blood Rites.'' (slugged:
BC-WAR-MEN-VIOLENCE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO MAKES WAR? THE ANSWER DEPENDS ON GENDER IDENTITY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANCIS FUKUYAMA &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (1,400 words) In the United States and other rich countries, a
pronounced gender gap with regard to foreign policy and national
security issues endures. American women have always been less
supportive than American men of U.S. involvement in war, including
World War II, Korea, Vietnam and the Persian Gulf War. They are
also consistently less supportive of defense spending and the use
of force abroad.
</P>
<P>
   __ Francis Fukuyama is Hirst Professor of Public Policy at
George Mason University. His most recent book is ``The Great
Disruption.'' (slugged: BC-WAR-WOMEN-VIOLENCE-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   ........................................
</P>
