the US military has never been so overextended. Not to mention the
shortage of cruise missiles. By Anne E. Kornblut. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEE-CAMP (Brazda, Macedonia) _ There was a birth. There was
a death. There was a 6-year-old, shot earlier by Serb troops, who
was reunited. There is a young man sobbing after he finds his
father. All of these personal stories, this emotional overload, in
24 hours. By Charles M. Sennott. 1400 words. PHOTOS (2).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-RIDICULE (Washington) _ A few banana-peel tumbles, and Al
Gore _ sultan of high seriousness and intellectual rectitude _
finds himself strangely vulnerable to an orchestrated campaign of
ridicule. For his strategists, it is a hot potatoe. By Michael
Kranish. 1300 words.
</P>
