<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMOVE ALL RUST BEFORE PAINTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The underside of an old cast iron sink is rusting, and looks
pretty bad. How can I paint it? There are rust spots around the
rusty drain cover in the sink. I plan to replace the drain cover;
can I put it right over the rust?
</P>
<P>
   MARY BETH COUGHLIN, Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is necessary to remove all rust from the underside of the
sink before painting it, and a good idea to remove the rust in the
sink before putting on the new cover.
</P>
<P>
   For the underside, sand heavily to remove all traces of rust. If
you cannot remove all traces, paint the remaining rust with a rust
reformer, which is a phosphoric acid compound that turns the rust
black and makes it paintable. Then paint with an oil-based primer
such as Kilz, and finish with an oil-based enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Do the same with the rust around the drain cover. With it
completely removed, paint the area around the cover with an
appliance touch-up paint. Now you can put on the new cover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I remove caulking compound smeared on a concrete walk
outdoors?
</P>
<P>
   GIGI McDONALD, Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Scrape up as much as you can with a putty knife. Soak the
remainder with paint thinner, enough so you can continue scraping
or scrubbing with very coarse steel wool. If the compound contains
silicone, try rubbing alcohol. If these tricks fail, apply chemical
paint remover; use a citrus-based remover so you can hose it off
when it softens the compound.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I put a wood stove in a fireplace. It works well, and the
draft is OK. But when the stove is not working, I get a bad smell
like creosote or burned, wet wood. I installed a chimney cap on top
of the chimney; that, and the closed damper in the stovepipe helped
a little, but the odor continues. How can I prevent that odor?
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN KOLBERT, Salem, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. That bad smell is because there is a downdraft when the stove
is not working, despite the chimney draft being OK when the stove
is working. It is a common problem, and sometimes blocking the
chimney at the top or at the stovepipe where it enters the chimney
will work, but the blockage has to be airtight, which makes it a
pain to do. The chimney cap helped some and so did the damper, but
as you found out, not quite enough.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope, and this is what Ed Grant of Beverly, Mass.
did to stop the odor coming down through his stove. He found an
old-fashioned kerosone lamp (not the one with a tall glass chimney
but a railroad type lamp), and set it in the stove (when it is not
working, of course). He then lit a newspaper torch and stuck it up
the stovepipe to get the air moving up, not down. Then he lit the
lamp, which produces enough heat to keep the air moving up.
Ingenious, what? You can do the same. It goes without saying (but
we'll say it anyway): Take the lamp out when you run the stove.
</P>
<P>
   You could probably run the lamp with the damper closed, because
such dampers are not airtight and can handle a small flame from a
kerosene lamp. After all, we lived with more than one kerosone lamp
in the good old days without venting them, and we were not
affected. I think. Those lamps are still sold; you could find one
in an antique store; maybe even in some hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Newspapers I was using to train my dog got wet and stuck to
the vinyl floor, creating a sizable black mark. How can I remove
it?
</P>
<P>
   NANCY RAILA, Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try a pre-wash spray such as Spray and Wash. Leave it on as
long as necessry, then scrub and rinse. A strong solution of baking
soda and water may do it, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My basement windows are flush with the ground. I was told to
put in window wells. I understand why they are needed, but how can
I install them?
</P>
<P>
   ANTONIO OLIART, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think places like Home Depot and building supply stores
carry them; they are painted galvanized steel, and rounded to form
a half circle. Dig a hole to match the size of the steel well; make
it as deep as the steel wall. Insert this wall and bolt or screw it
to the foundation. To fasten to concrete, drill a hole for the
screw or bolt and insert a fiber or plastic sleeve that will hold
the screw or bolt.
</P>
<P>
   To get the right size well, measure the window's width; if the
well is a little wide, going beyond the window, that is OK; if it
is short, it is not OK. Fill the well with crushed stone to within
six inches of the sill.
</P>
<P>
   You should be able to find the right size, and you can also buy
a cover for it, which will prevent rain water from filling the
well.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find a ready-made steel well, you can make your
own. Dig a hole the width of the window or a little wider. Make it
12 inches deep and let it extend about 18 inches out from the
window. Line the hole with pressure-treated 2 x 12s. Keep the 2 x
12s flush with the ground or a tad higher. Fill the well with six
inches of crushed stone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
