<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANGUARD EXTENDED MARKET MAY FIT BETTER INTO INVESTOR'S MIX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am single, in my mid-thirties and earn $25,000 a year
working for an employer who does not offer a pension, 401(k) plan
or a profit-sharing plan. Just recently I have started to invest
for my future needs. I have $4,000 in a Roth IRA invested in
Vanguard Growth and Income fund, and I also have $6,000 in a
taxable account invested in Vanguard Life-Strategy Growth, which
holds roughly 20 percent bonds and 80 percent stocks. I also have
some $18,000 in a NOW account that pays 1 percent interest. I plan
to move $12,000 of that to a Vanguard money market fund that pays
about 5 percent interest until I figure out what to do next. Maybe
I'll move some of that money to Vanguard Mid-Cap Index fund or
Vanguard Aggressive Growth fund to add some diversity to my taxable
fund holdings. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   L.L., Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think diversifying beyond the large-cap arena is a good
idea, but it's a tough job to choose between the two funds you're
looking at. Currently, both are classified by Morningstar Mutual
Funds as mid-cap funds, with Vanguard Aggressive Growth (curiously)
at the value end of the spectrum and the Mid-Cap Index fund is
classified as a mid-cap blend, holding both growth and value
issues. And let's also throw a third fund into the discussion _
Vanguard Extended Market Index. This is another mid-cap blend
issue, differing from the Mid-Cap Index issue in that Extended
Market Index tracks the results of the Wilshire 4500 index
(embracing both small and mid-cap issues) whereas the Mid-Cap Index
tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's Mid-Cap 400 Index.
</P>
<P>
   All three funds are managed by George U. Sauter. The most
notable difference among the three is that the Aggressive Growth
fund is not limited to the mid-cap universe, but rather places its
investments wherever its computer-directed strategy dictates that
the best market opportunities lurk.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Extended Market Index topped this group, with a
26.74 percent total return, closely followed by Aggressive Growth
with a 26.12 percent gain, and less closely by the Mid-Cap Index
fund, which was begun only about a year ago, producing an 8.78
percent return for eight months and ten days of operations. Through
the first quarter of 1999, Extended Market Index was again leading
the list, losing 3.50 percent, trailed by Mid-Cap Index with a 6.1
percent loss and Aggressive Growth with a 10.8 percent loss. All of
the funds looked good compared to their peers in 1998, with the
average mid-cap blend fund tracked by Morningstar producing a 9.33
percent total return and the average mid-cap value fund returning
1.36 percent. In the first quarter, though, only the Extended
Market Index fund came close to its peer group median return, which
was a loss of 3.1 percent; the median loss for the mid-cap value
segment was 2.3 percent for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   If we just go by the numbers, it seems to me that the Extended
Market Index is the clear winner here. Moreover, there are
drawbacks involving both of the other funds: Vanguard Aggressive
Growth is not by charter required to keep its portfolio in any
particular market segment, so at some point in the future you might
find that such a holding duplicates your current large-cap blend
position with Vanguard Growth and Income. And Vanguard Mid-Cap
Growth fund simply has a record that's too short to bear very much
analysis. So I would go with the fund you didn't suggest _ the
Vanguard Extended Market Index.
</P>
<P>
   One further note: You propose to leave $6,000 in that NOW
account, earning that token 1 percent interest. That seems to me to
be a lot of money loafing, especially for somebody earning $25,000
a year. I suggest either that you reduce this balance to the
minimum amount allowed to maintain the NOW account or, if you write
relatively few checks, abandon the NOW account entirely and put
this money, which I assume you are viewing as emergency savings, in
a money market account with check-writing privileges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 53 years-old and self-employed.
Through many years of hard work we have developed a $333,000
portfolio. We have paid for our children's college education and
just have a mortgage to pay off. I would like your opinion of our
current allocations and whether the investments we currently have
will get us to $1 million by age 62, assuming we make $5,000 annual
contributions. We have $260,000 in 15 large-cap blue-chip stocks,
$21,000 in bonds, and $52,000 in the New Perspective, Janus, Janus
20, and Vanguard Index 500 funds.
</P>
<P>
   B.C., Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. To get to $1 million from where you are and with the
contributions you contemplate would require average annual returns
of 11.98 percent over the course of the next nine years. That may
not seem like so much after viewing the results of market
investments over the next several years, but my view is that it's
pretty unlikely. In fact, I wouldn't even be very comfortable with
an expectation of 10 percent average returns, which would take you
to $856,337. To my view, a much safer expectation would be average
portfolio returns of 8 percent, which would take you only to
$730,486.
</P>
<P>
   One reason I prefer the lower expectations is that I think
you've reached the point where you should be a little more
conservative, putting some of your contributions into bond and
other fixed-income holdings. The current fixed-income position is
only 6.3 percent of the portfolio. Moreover, I think you should
diversify away from large-cap stocks, which now represent the
entire stock portfolio. Along with balanced funds, I would suggest
you establish positions in mid-cap and small-cap stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you don't mention where you are investing your
contributions to these accounts. Since you note that you built this
portfolio over many years, I suspect there would be ugly tax
consequences if you sold any of the individual stocks. But I would
commit no further money to those accounts, and if you are enrolled
in dividend reinvestment programs, I suggest you elect to take your
dividends in cash, using that money to help build greater portfolio
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
