<SLUG> BC-US-MILITARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ARGUE US FORCES STRETCHED TOO THIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMSTEIN AIR BASE, Germany _ Without the use of ground troops,
the US-led mission in Kosovo has been criticized as too weak, too
narrow, too ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as an increasing number of far-flung US military
resources have been diverted to the Balkans, another question has
cropped up: Is this miniwar leaving other US interests naked to
attack?
</P>
<P>
   Within the last two weeks, Pentagon officials have admitted US
forces are running down their supply of air-launched cruise
missiles, one of the heaviest and safest hitters in the lineup of
weapons fired from afar.
</P>
<P>
   Airpower has been shifted from Turkey and northern Iraq to
Yugoslavia. Aircraft carriers have been rearranged to free up one
for the Adriatic, leaving the north Pacific without.
</P>
<P>
   The shuffling has led some US military observers to argue, in
the words of the Congressional Research Service, ``that deployments
such as the ones in Bosnia or potentially in Kosovo harm US
military readiness and divert scarce military resources from
defense of vital US interests elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether such concerns are valid _ or are hysterical
exaggerations of the truth _ remains as much a matter of debate as
the strategy in Kosovo itself, according to a range of officials
and outside analysts.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the complaints are political hyperbole aimed at
persuading Congress to increase the military budget. To others, the
concerns are real, and a sign the Pentagon is ill-equipped to
handle the multiple brush fires of the world after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``If another challenge were to come simultaneously, what would
the implications be for our capabilities?'' said Robert
Pfaltzgraff, professor of international studies at the Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we're going to have to cut into some of
our capabilities. That worries me. It fits into a larger pattern in
the military, especially as we draw down forces as we have over the
last eight or nine years, since the end of the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, officials have over the last year begun paying close
attention to whether the military is ready for war and whether its
soldiers are adequately trained, lobbying Congress for an increased
Pentagon budget as well as a pay raise for the troops. In turn, the
military has blossomed again as a political issue, with both
Democrats and Republicans competing for the Pentagon budget
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Those worrying about defense deployments, argues military
analyst John Pike, may be trying to take advantage of the bidding
war between the parties. Pike said the missile shortage is
misleading _ while the air missiles are dwindling, sea-launched
missiles are in abundance and can be used just as effectively, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pike also said that ``to the extent that knowledgeable people
are worried about this, they're just trying to get us revved up for
a $15-billion defense budget increase in the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Heller, an Air Force specialist at the Center for Defense
Information, agreed. ``The idea that we're being stretched thin by
this operation, in terms of our overall force structure, is not
accurate,'' he said. ``I don't know if it's ignorance or
intentionally misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Pentagon policy, spelled out to Congress earlier
this year, the military is supposed to be prepared for two major
regional wars at the same time _ not including the ongoing and
relatively low-level forces committed to Iraq, Bosnia, and now
Kosovo. The Pentagon has told Congress the military meets that
standard and would be able, for example, to wage war against North
Korea as it battled Saddam Hussein in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, the Navy moved the aircraft carrier in the
Pacific, the Kitty Hawk, to the Persian Gulf, where it will
substitute for the Theodore Roosevelt, which was diverted to the
Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   Combat fighters have been put on alert near North Korea as a
result, and some 100,000 US troops are deployed in Asia, Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that moving the Kitty Hawk made a difference. Of Asia,
he said, ``it's not true that it's being left naked.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 10 F-15s and several EA-6B radar-jamming planes have
been moved to Italy from their usual posts guarding northern Iraq,
military analysts also denied Iraq would go unattended. The
southern no-fly zone, scene of a US attack Thursday, has picked up
the slack, analysts said. But in Germany, officials and airmen said
there is no question that adding Yugoslavia to the roster has
placed a strain on everyone, forcing them to compensate through
longer hours and less sleep.
</P>
<P>
   That, they said, could be the biggest military risk of all.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Buchanan, 25, a senior airman, worked a 24-hour shift on
the Ramstein airstrip Thursday _ his 12th such shift in recent
weeks. Lieutenant Colonel Thomas Christie, a military police
officer, acknowledged the hours were taking their toll, saying,
``the hours have been very, very busy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were busy during the African embassy bombings,'' he said,
recalling the August explosions, ``but that hardly compares to
this. And this seems to have the potential to go on a lot longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
