<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLBEAN-MOMENTUM-ART-B     04-09 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLBEAN-MOMENTUM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.L. BEAN BLAZES A NEW PATH TO REGAIN MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEPORT, Maine _ ``Wow, they're not dumpy anymore'' is one
consumer's reaction to the women's clothing featured in a new
catalog published by L.L. Bean Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1912, the legendary purveyor of the famous
Bean boot has held this belief: L.L. Bean doesn't go after fashion;
fashion comes to L.L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion came to L.L. Bean in the 1980s, when college students
embraced the preppie trend and flocked to Freeport for the
traditional styles Bean had been selling for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, fashion has looked elsewhere, and Bean's sales
have been flat for the last three years as consumer taste has moved
away from the functional, no-nonsense clothing for which Bean is
famous.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to regain momentum, Bean has launched several
out-of-character initiatives _ including a flirtation with fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Besides wooing women who want stylish career wear with its new
Freeport Studio catalog, Bean plans to open a half-dozen stores
along the East Coast, with some modeled on its famed Freeport
flagship store. Expect to see stores in or near New York and
Washington, D.C., but not in Boston, which was deemed too close to
Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bean kicked off its first major TV ad campaign this
week. Created by the Wenham ad agency Mullen, the ads unveiled the
theme ``Start here, go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon A. Gorman, Bean's president since 1967 and grandson of
founder L.L. Bean, seeks to put the changes into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are ``not seeing us as up-to-date and relevant to
their lifestyle,'' he says. ``We want to let people know we're not
just the same old company they liked in the '70s and '80s. We're
also contemporary.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean is by no means abandoning its past. Purists will still be
able to buy Bean boots and chamois shirts. The goal is to preserve
Bean's heritage while persuading folks to think of Bean in new ways
_ a combination that can be tricky.
</P>
<P>
   For a company that had long seemed to be on automatic pilot, the
sudden burst of activity surprises longtime observers of the $53
billion consumer catalog industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very un-Bean-like,'' says catalog consultant Maxwell
Sroge. ``Are they trying to do too many things at once?''
</P>
<P>
   And what happens to the company after Gorman? For all but a few
months of its 87-year history, the company has been led by two men,
founder Bean and grandson Gorman. Gorman, 64, has not said anything
publicly about a possible successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he getting the company ready to go public or to sell it?''
Sroge says of Gorman and the recent changes.
</P>
<P>
   Gorman strongly denies any such plans and says the new ventures
are strictly designed to regain the double-digit growth Gorman has
enjoyed for most of his 32-year tenure. The goal is to reach $1.4
billion in sales by 2002, up from $1.03 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bean after Gorman, a company spokesman notes that founder
Bean remained president until his death at age 94. For his part,
Gorman says he has ``no immediate plans to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The business is expected to pass to the fourth generation of
the family,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some fault Gorman for being slow to react to shifts in the
fast-changing catalog business. But it's hard to argue with his
track record. When he took over, sales were about $5 million. Bean
has exceeded $1 billion in sales for four straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Bean isn't alone in facing challenges. In the last few years,
many catalog companies selling outdoor clothing have lost some zip.
Eddie Bauer has had its ups and downs. Lands' End Inc. recently
ousted its chief executive and implemented layoffs after annual
profits dropped by half.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the explanations for such outdoor-catalog malaise is
intensifying competition, as many brick-and-mortar retailers such
as Macy's are starting or expanding catalog operations. The catalog
turf that Bean, Eddie Bauer, and Lands' End once had mostly to
themselves is now being encroached upon by many other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   At W.A. Dean &AMP; Associates, a catalog consulting firm, president
Bill Dean wonders whether consumers have reached a saturation point
with outdoor merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you can only sell so many backbpacks and Polartec
pullovers,'' Dean says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the wild card of e-commerce, though Gorman thinks
that stores, catalogs, and the Internet will coexist and that
retailers using all three channels will fare best.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Direct Marketing Association, catalog companies
mail out about 14 billion catalogs a year, which works out to more
than 100 per US household.
</P>
<P>
   But sophisticated databases can now identify the consumers who
make the most catalog purchases, and such buyers can be inundated
with far more catalogs than the average household.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're getting catalogs from people you've never heard of,''
Dean says.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this mailbox glut, catalogs from companies such as Bean and
Lands' End can get overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Bean is dealing with another challenge. In the early 1990s, its
goods were wildly popular in Japan. The currency exchange rate made
Bean-wear a bargain, and the Japanese were fascinated by the Bean
mystique of quality, durability, and service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if the Japanese loved us for who we are or
because our goods were stylish and cheap,'' Gorman recalls. ``It
was a little of both, probably.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the recession in Japan has been painful for Bean.
In 1994, Japan accounted for 20 percent of Bean's total sales; last
year, that figure fell to 5 percent, Gorman says.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with such troubles abroad and more competition at
home, Bean decided to respond with some drastic measures, including
what for it was a frontal assault on fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In January, it mailed out a catalog called Freeport Studio to
women who buy Bean's weekend attire; the idea is to give these
women an opportunity to buy clothes from Bean that are fashionable
enough to wear to the office and elsewhere during the week.
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans to sell Freeport Studio clothing in Bean's
flagship store _ that might blur Bean's brand identity and leave
longtime customers of backpacks and fly-fishing gear confused.
Freeport Studio clothing is available only through the catalog, in
which the L.L. Bean name appears in small letters.
</P>
<P>
   Many rivals already offer ``casual career'' clothing, notes
Glenda Shasho Jones, head of Shasho Jones Direct, a firm that
advises catalog retailers on branding and marketing issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.L. Bean stands for casual weekends and the outdoors,'' she
says. ``But they have to establish credibility with fashion. Bean
merchandise was never seen as fashionable. It was seen sensible and
comfortable. We'll see if the consumer can accept this from them.''
</P>
<P>
   One goal of the new ad campaign is to change some perceptions
about Bean and help customers accept some newfangled things from an
old-fashioned retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seen as a cold-weather New England company,'' says Bean
senior vice president Bill Shea. ``Now we're trying to get people
to think of us as an all-year-round company.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bean's Freeport store, sales run strong from summer vacation
to ski season, or roughly from July to January. But store sales
account for only about 10 percent of total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 90 percent come from catalogs or the Internet, with the
Internet making up 5 percent of last year's total.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to store sales, catalog sales bunch up in a much
shorter time frame, peaking at the holidays. An aim of Bean's new
initiatives is to build sales in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Freeport Studio gives Bean an entree into spring fashions.
Opening the new stores is another bid to attract customers all
year.
</P>
<P>
   And running a big ad campaign in the spring is one way to try to
get consumers to think of Bean as a year-round retailer that sells
more than just snowshoes, parkas, and fall hunting gear.
</P>
<P>
   Past ads tended to focus on products. New ads seek to convey a
more subtle message: that Bean's outdoors is not about mountaintops
and dangerous whitewater rapids, but about the outdoors that begins
just outside a family's back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ads are saying that Bean and the outdoors are more
relevant to your life than you think,'' says Bean advertising
manager Dave Holmblad. ``We want people to think that something is
going on at Bean.''
</P>
<P>
   As vice president Shea acknowledges, this is ``the most risk
this company has ever faced.''
</P>
<P>
   But in taking risks, Bean may have a secret weapon _ its name
and its mystique.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.L. Bean has got one of the great brand names in the catalog
industry, and Bean has not really capitalized on that,'' says
consultant Sroge.
</P>
<P>
   That's the plan now. With new initiatives under way, Gorman
says, ``We think we're going the right way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
