<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEE-CAMP-ART-BOS &LR;      04-09 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-CAMP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE, DEATH UNFOLD IN REFUGEE CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos (2) are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZDA, Macedonia _ The cries rose up Thursday over the misery
of this refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   Two daughters sobbing uncontrollably, mourning the death of
their mother. An infant, just born under a green canvas tent,
wailing her way into the world.
</P>
<P>
   In just one day in the Brazda refugee camp, the rhythm of life
and death unfolds amid the numbing enormity of human suffering. The
scenes, as archetypical asa mother clasping a new baby or as stark
as a son digging a shallow grave for his mother, make vivid the
desperation and the tragedy of the tens of thousands of refugees
who've fled to this side of the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life goes on... There is the sadness of death and the joy of
birth and a story that will break your heart in every tent,'' said
Major Christian Holler, the head of the International Red Cross
operation in the Brazda camp.
</P>
<P>
   In the quiet hour just past midnight, 55-year-old Hamida Zenili,
a mother of eight, died after falling ill in the squalor of the
refugee camps. She is one of roughly 40 people who have died in the
camps in the two weeks since the refugees began flowing across the
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the long shadows of late afternoon, Baharia Baricha was
gripping her husband's hand as she delivered her first child, a
girl, into the world. The baby was the 15th born in the two-week
period.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours that unfolded Thursday between the death of Hamida
and the birth of the baby girl, dramatic family reunions were
taking place from one tent to the next.
</P>
<P>
   In the early morning, a 10-year-old girl who had been shot by
Serbian troops in her left arm was reunited with her mother. An
elderly man, who suffered from a stroke and was unable to speak to
aid workers looking for his family, cried when his son found him in
a hospital tent. A man in the hospital bed next to him pointed to
the bloody bandage over his eye, saying a Macedonian soldier had
slammed him with the butt of a rifle when he asked if he could
leave the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Around thema line of thousands snaked through wooden stockade
fencing that led to aide workers handing out packaged meals and
loaves of bread. Another long line formed in front of folding
tables where United Nations workers painstakingly tried to document
the refugees' names for liststo be transferred around the world,
from Albania to Turkey and Germany and Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Children kicked a soccer ball in the dust with two NATO
soldiers. Families clutched the barbed wire fencing at the entrance
to the camp and waved to family and friends on the other side who
were kept back by armed Montenegran police who are refusing to
allow the refugees to leave the camp. Helicopters hovered overhead
transporting in more supplies and more tents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was 4:14 p.m. when Baharia Baricha, 24, gave birth to a girl
in a makeshift operating room in the tent hospital set up by a
Israeli team of 102 medics flown in as part of a massive aid effort
at the border camps.
</P>
<P>
   Baharia's husband, Sabit, held her hand as she pushed and winced
in pain as the child came into the world.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had fled their village just outside Pristina 10 days
earlier. They feared that all the tension, the violence, and the
walking in the long column of refugees fleeing Kosovo into
Macedonia would induce early labor. But the baby arrived on the due
date, a beautiful girl weighing just under seven pounds. Her
healthy new lungs triumphantly told the refugee camp she had
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to see her born into so much confusion,'' said a
proud Sabit as he held the baby in his arms. ``But she also brings
so much happiness into our lives. She helps us remember that
despite all these bad things, we have to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple still hadn't decided on a name. The Israeli surgeon
suggested Sarah, the Israeli matriarch. The Albanian Muslim
translator suggested the name ``Rania'' after Jordan's Queen Rania,
who made a ceremonial walk through the camp followed by an
entourage of paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had time to even think about it,'' said Sabit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another medical tent, Adelena Berisha, 10, explained how she
was shot in the arm. As doctors working on a plaster cast to hold
her small left arm in place, Adelena said she had gotten lost in
the massive refugee camp in the ``no man's land'' between Kosovo
and Macedonia. She wandered down a set of train tracks and strayed
back to the border almost into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lost. I couldn't find my way. And when I saw the
soldiers I thought they would help me,'' she said. ``But then I
heard the bangs and I was knocked down and my arm was bleeding. I
was crying.''
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers the little girl had run into were apparently
Yugoslav Army troops on the Kosovo side of the border. After she
was hit, Macedonian police picked her up and brought her to a
hospital on the Macedonian side. She remained there for several
days and the hospital staff could not find her parents. But her
mother had finally found her Thursday, and the Israeli doctors were
operating on what they say is nerve damage from the bullet wound.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli medical team has offered to fly the girl back to Tel
Aviv for delicate surgery correct the nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Sadia, comforted her daughter Thursday in the cool
shade of a green canvas tent in the emergency room of the makeshift
hospital. She was thankful to the doctors, relieved to have found
her daughter, and furious about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did this to a child?'' she asked. ``What is wrong with
this world?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hamida Zenili, 55, was the mother of eight children. She didn't
want to leave her Pristina home. The family had a comfortable life
thanks to the family patriarch who works as a waiter in St. Moritz,
Switzerland, and sent money home. Hamida, a protective mother,
demanded that her children take their education seriously. Six of
the eight children were college educated. They had a solid
middle-class life that she did not want to give up.
</P>
<P>
   But her son, Bekim, a law student, insisted that the family
flee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fled the paramilitaries. They said they would come to kill
us,'' he said. ``But we come here and still death finds us.''
</P>
<P>
   The family waited in the column of misery that stretched for
miles as they fled Pristina, and like tens of thousands of others
ended up in the mud and squalor of the ``no man's land.'' The
filth, disease, and daily indignity of the camp took its toll.
Hamida refused to sleep, and waited in long lines for food for her
family. Exhausted and consumed with anxiety, she fell ill. Then
heavy rains came. Her condition worsened. At first the symptoms
were flu, then dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the family along with 40,000 others were
forcibly uprooted and bused to this camp.
</P>
<P>
   The move was the breaking point. Ay 9 p.m. Wednesday she was
taken to an emergency medical tent where she suffered shortness of
breath, according to doctors. Just past midnight, her blood
pressure dropped and she died.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials worked tirelessly to help the family arrange
a proper Muslim burial. Hamida's body was ritually bathed, as is
the tradition, and wrapped in a white sheet. The family was
permitted to leave the camp for two hours to bury her in a hillside
cemetery just 500 yards from the stench of the Blace camp where she
had grown ill.
</P>
<P>
   Her sons dug her grave and marked her initials and the date of
her death on a simple piece of wood stuck in the dirt. But the
family vows that they will return to Kosovo, and that they will
exhume her remains and give her a proper burial in a graveyard in
Kosovo, where ancestors for four generations lay.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, her daughters and sons cried and comforted each other,
sitting on the ground outside a tent. Sabrije, 22, looked to the
heavens and sobbed. She was unconsolable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will return to Kosovo. And we will take her with us,'' said
Bekim, speaking over the wailing cries. ``We will not leave her
behind. Kosovo is our home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
