<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HINGSTON-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      04-09 1807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINGSTON-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR ANSWERS TO SAM HINGSTON'S SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILTON, Conn. _ Pride fairly shrieks from the cardboard sign.
``HOME OF SAM HINGSTON, CONNECTICUT STATE WRESTLING CHAMPION!''
announces the handmade landmark tacked to a telephone pole at the
bottom of the winding driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Lest there be any doubt, the living room of the red split-level
at the top of the hill is a virtual museum embellishing the
message. Samuel Hingston's grandmother, Dorothy, is the loving
curator. She guides a visitor along the table and back wall
bedecked with the mileposts that trace her maternal grandson's
journey of distinction, a journey that ended tragically and
suddenly some two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are photos of Sam with his mother, Marjorie, and his
father, Richard, his older sister, Jane, and his twin sister,
Sarah, smiling and hugging, always smiling and hugging.
</P>
<P>
   Sam in his baseball and football uniforms at Woodstown High in
New Jersey. Sam's medal as a New Jersey district wrestling
champion. Sam's Wilton High Warriors baseball jersey in a glass
frame, signifying that his No. 17 has been retired. Sam's wrestling
singlet, also encased in glass, signed by every member of the
Wilton squad, with a team picture beside it. And, at the far end,
the draw for the 160-pound division from the Connecticut wrestling
championships in mid-February at Glastonbury High, revealing that
Sam won four matches and the Class M title.
</P>
<P>
   It is a virtual continuum of honor and glory at two schools, in
two states. But there is a jarring gap in the middle, and it
reflects the tragic dichotomy that ended with a young man, hailed
as a hero by most and denounced as a pariah by others, choosing to
commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy pauses at the large framed photo that is the centerpiece
of the exhibit. It is a class picture of Sam, with his
short-cropped black hair and handsome, angular face set off by a
luminous smile. Tucked at the bottom lefthand corner, she spots a
much smaller picture, a religious card depicting Jesus embracing a
new arrival to the kingdom of heaven. She picks it up haltingly.
Her voice cracks. ``I'd like to give him a good kick in the
bottom,'' she says. ``Such a stupid, senseless act . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   She gazes around at the floral arrangements filling virtually
every available space in the room, at the basket beneath the table
overflowing with hundreds of cards. ``Everything's all over the
place,'' she says. ``We're trying to get some semblance . . . If we
could only understand . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   That is the curse of it for the Hingstons. They cannot
understand why this museum is in fact a memorial. They never will
comprehend why 17-year-old Samuel Hingston _ three-sport athlete,
honor student, ROTC scholarship recipient to Boston College, wildly
popular peer and mentor in Wilton _ took his own life. They do not
acknowledge or accept that his past in New Jersey _ where he is
known not only as a scholar-athlete but also as an accused
13-year-old rapist who was ultimately acquitted _ may have hounded
him to his grave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This much is known. Sometime in the middle of the night between
March 23 and 24, Sam Hingston arose from his corner bedroom and
walked into the garage of his grandparents' house near the base of
a secluded cul-de-sac in this affluent New York commuter community,
where the median house price is more than $400,000. He took an
empty plastic sports drink bottle, filled it with the contents of a
can marked ``white gas,'' left the can in the basement, returned to
the house, entered the bathroom, and locked the door behind him. He
took a swig of gas from the bottle. He doused himself with the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Then he lit a match and set himself ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing a thud, his mother raced from her bedroom, saw her son's
room empty, noticed the bathroom door locked _ it was never locked
before _ kicked the door, and frantically yelled, ``Sam, let me in!
Let me in!'' A 911 call was placed to police saying that Sam had
locked himself in the bathroom and wouldn't come out.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie kicked the door open. Another 911 call was made, this
time with screams in the background, saying there was a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Police and firefighters arrived on the scene almost
simultaneously at 3:05 a.m. There they discovered that the fire had
not been structural, as had been suspected, but had extinguished
itself because of the lack of oxygen caused by the closed door.
</P>
<P>
   They also discovered Sam Hingston, charred from head to toe, his
facial features obliterated. ``We could not immediately tell
whether the victim was African American or Caucasian,'' says Fire
Chief William von Zehle, who rode in the second of the two Wilton
engines that answered the call.
</P>
<P>
   Sam, somehow, was still alive, and he responded to the emergency
medical technicians' instructions to place an oxygen mask over his
face before they performed a tracheotomy. ``I think once he did
what he did, he quickly thought, `This is not the way I want to do
this,' '' says von Zehle. ``That's not the way to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam did not die, not right then. With third-degree burns over 85
percent of his body, he was rushed by ambulance to Norwalk Hospital
at 3:37, then immediately airlifted to the burn unit at Westchester
Medical Center in nearby Valhalla, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his father was racing up from Woodstown, from where
he has commuted on weekends and vacations since the rest of the
family suddenly relocated last April. Richard Hingston, an art
teacher and assistant tennis coach at Williamstown (N.J.) High, had
been asleep in his den with the television on and hadn't heard the
phone ring when the initial call came from Wilton. Finally,
Richard's father, a New Jersey physician, got through and informed
him that Sam had burned himself.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Richard arrived at the hospital, Sam was on life
support. Sarah met her father in the parking lot, and when he
inquired as to his son's condition, she told him he wasn't going to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at 4:30 in the afternoon, Samuel Hingston was declared
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor boy,'' sighs Richard. ``The poor beautiful boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Sam left no note, this may never be known: What prompted
such a grotesque act of seeming self-eradication?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never have the answer,'' says Richard.
</P>
<P>
   But as with any mystery, there are clues. They just aren't
evident in Wilton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the people of his adopted home, the news was
incomprehensible; the announcement of Sam's death set off waves of
grieving, and crisis counseling was provided for all 930 students,
plus staff and faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``From most likely (to commit suicide) to least likely,'' says
principal Deborah Low, who is serving as Wilton High's spokeswoman
on the matter, ``he'd be on the least likely list. When I heard, I
said, `Sam? Sam Hingston?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That's because this is the Sam Hingston they knew:
</P>
<P>
   To his admirers, it seemed he had a gift for both achievement
and service.
</P>
<P>
   At Wilton, he was a tricaptain of both the football and
wrestling teams this season, a designated hitter and second baseman
last spring in baseball, a member of Amnesty International, a
volunteer at a home for retired nuns, owner of a 3.7 grade-point
average who had applied to Georgetown, Harvard, and Yale but
already had settled on BC and a $23,000 ROTC scholarship, hoping to
pursue the military as a steppingstone to a career in either
business or politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made everybody feel special,'' says his sister Jane, 19, a
sophomore at St. Michael's College in Vermont. ``That's why
everybody liked him. He didn't focus on himself but on the other
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why he made an instant impact in Wilton.
</P>
<P>
   After eight days of preseason football camp in August, he was
voted a tricaptain. ``I think he made an immediate impression as a
leader,'' says athletic director Doug Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   An unassuming one, apparently. ``He never told us he was a
captain,'' says his father. ``We had to wait until it was announced
at the first game to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   He was an undersized middle linebacker on a 1-9 team, but he
wound up with more than 100 tackles and was named second-team
All-Fairfield County.
</P>
<P>
   On the wrestling mat, he surpassed those achievements. Yet that
wasn't necessarily his major legacy. ``I sought his advice about
some things,'' says Rubin. ``His gentlemanliness on the mat. Win or
lose, he'd always shake hands with the opposing wrestlers and
coaches. I wanted to know what motivated him to do that so I could
learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't just a good sport. Community service is part of
the curriculum at Wilton, and Sam volunteered at the Mother House
for the School Sisters of Notre Dame, a retirement home with 136
nuns. His assignment was to feed those nuns who were unable to care
for themselves, but he exceeded the job description. ``They said he
was absolutely delightful,'' says Sister Amalia Menardi, director
of volunteers at the home. ``He would make them laugh, hug them.
And when his service requirement was completed, he wanted to keep
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   In the classroom, his influence went beyond his stature as a
National Merit Commended Scholar and National Honor Society member.
Marjorie recounts a conversation with the mother of a freshman who
was in Sam's marketing class. Marketing, like most studies, came
quickly to Sam; the freshman was struggling. They wound up as
partners on a project, and the freshman expressed his misgivings to
Sam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what to study,'' Sam told him. ``We'll get a good
project grade, and that'll pump you right up.''
</P>
<P>
   They aced the project, and the freshman wound up greatly
surpassing expectations for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Hingston heard about that two weekends ago, as she
heard countless tributes from Wilton citizens who couldn't
understand why it was necessary to speak of her son in the past
tense.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they would have had they been aware of the other Sam,
the tortured Sam, the young man who might not have shaken the
stigma of an allegation for which he was ultimately acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody I know of at school was aware of anything about his
past,'' says a Wilton High staffer. ``Just that he came from New
Jersey and transferred last April.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the Woodstown Diner and Restaurant, in a dreary hamlet of
some 3,800 set amid truck stops and farms near the desolate foot of
the New Jersey Turnpike, his supporters never believed the charge:
that four years ago, Sam Hingston raped a fellow eighth grader in a
shed behind a friend's house at a summer party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were best friends,'' says a former classmate, who requests
anonymity. ``He would have said something to his best friends, and
he never did.''
</P>
