   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: This will be the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. It is
part of the continuing yearlong series looking at the 2000th
anniversary of Christianity.)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-LUTHERAN _ On Oct. 31, 1517, Martin Luther tacked a
paper to the Palace Church door in Wittenberg, sparking a movement
that changed Christianity. But the church Luther founded finds
itself in deep trouble in Europe, where the Lutheran World
Federation reported a ``general reduction in numbers.'' And the
problem is even greater in Germany, the homeland of Protestanism,
where more than a million people have left the church rolls in
the1990s. (Gwhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 67. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-PROTESTANTS _ Most German Protestants spend little
time in the pews, but the history of northern Germany, the
birthplace of the Protestant Reformation, can be traced through
three churches: The Palace Church in Wittenberg where Luther nailed
the theses that started the Reformation; the Berliner Dom, or great
emperial cathedral, that survived the tremendous forces that shaped
20th century East Berlin; and, St. Michael's in Hamburg, a city
famous for its churches and its red-light district, where the
rebuilding of St. Michael's after World War II has become a major
point of pride for the city. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-LUTHER _ Although Catholic monk Martin Luther never
intended to form his own church, millions of Christians around the
world are now in a family of denominations that bear his name.
Millions more are in other groups _ Reformed, Methodist,
Presbyterian _ that are part of the Protestant Reformation Luther
sparked. A brief bio of Luther. Photo. (Gwhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.5.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-BOX _ Although the government of Germany collects
funds for the Protestant and Catholic churches along with income
tax, many people have chosen to disaffiliate themselves from the
faith. And many of those who still pay money to the church seldom
attend. We take a quick look at the numbers. Gwhite. 7.4''
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-ENGLAND _ The Church of England has become a stodgy,
picturesque part of the British Isles, a place tourists visit, but
few Brits actually are involved with. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
20.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-CHART _ A country-by-country chart of European
religious affiliation. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution Art
Department). GRAPHIC
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-TIMELINE _ A detailed look at highlights of
Christianity through the Middle Ages. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution
Art Department). GRAPHIC.
</P>
