campaign aimed directly at consumers. (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COSMOS _ The Hubble Space Telescope and other new instruments
for examining the space we live in have generated a flood of new
discoveries during the 1990s, the fastest accumulation of insights
about the Universe in history, scientists say. Yet, fundamental
questions still exist about science and religion. Was there a Big
Bang? Did something happen before it? Was there a ``before it?''
Did something ``cause'' it to happen? Are human beings the only
``intelligent creatures'' to live in the space that it seems to
have created and to wonder about these things? The American
Association for the Advancement of Science will bring together
scientists and religious scholars from universities in the United
States and Europe next week (April 14-16) to talk these questions
and others. (Nesmith, Cox News Service). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
