<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2124 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HINGSTON-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     04-09 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINGSTON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WILTON, Conn.: ... never did.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To them, such an act would have been totally out of character.
Richard Hingston says his son had read Martin Luther King's
autobiography, ``Let My Trumpet Sound,'' and had been profoundly
affected by King's philosophy of effecting change without violence.
Josh DuBois, a childhood friend, recalls that ``with him, it was
sports mostly. He was always popular, really good-looking, very
sweet. He knew how to talk to the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in death, apparently, support has not waned. A source says
the family of the girl who filed the rape charge has been harassed
since Sam's suicide and that patrol cars have been dispatched for
occasional surveillance of their house.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was another faction that considered him guilty.
Charges were filed some two years later, Richard Hingston said in a
prepared statement last week, and the case did not come to trial
until last summer. ``These juvenile cases can take forever,'' says
a source. Though juvenile records by law are sealed, sources have
confirmed both the allegation and disposition.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting to go to court, Sam seemingly thrived at Woodstown
High.
</P>
<P>
   A regional AAU wrestling champion at the age of 8, a year after
taking up the sport when he was inspired by watching two cousins
win Vermont state titles, Sam added to his laurels at the
interscholastic level.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball was hands down his favorite sport; his father remembers
young Sam insisting that they go to the playground so Richard could
hit him 200 grounders at shortstop, either to his right or his
left. ``He'd get mad if I hit them right at him,'' recalls Richard.
``He wanted to go in the hole and pick it.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed on the Woodstown varsity, where Sam was a slick second
baseman and solid hitter.
</P>
<P>
   And his football coach, Clint Ware, recalls him as a linebacker
``who always knew where the ball was. He was so smart on the
field.'' What impressed Ware, a guidance counselor at the school,
even more was that Sam was ``such a leader and organizer.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he was selected to attend Governor's School,
representing Salem County as one of New Jersey's most promising
teen leaders. There he and another student organized and staged a
variety show, donating the proceeds to the Count Basie Center for
inner-city youth.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the veneer of accomplishment, the impending trial
lurked. ``Most kids believed he didn't do it,'' says the Woodstown
classmate who requests anonymity. ``But some thought he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The tension broiled on March 19, 1998, when, at 2:26 p.m.,
Marjorie Hingston called police to say her son had been the victim
of assault and battery. While no charges were filed, sources and
friends confirm that Sam was attacked at his Woodstown school by a
17-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say something, but I've been told not to comment
on it,'' says Billy Coles, the alleged assailant. But friends of
the Hingstons say Coles was convinced of Sam's guilt, and sources
indicate that was the motive for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sam was treated for minor injuries at Salem County Hospital and
released.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he complained to friends that he and his family
were receiving death threats, though he took no action, says his
classmate, ``because he had a lot of other things to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, some two weeks after the attack, Marjorie left her
job as head of the Upward Bound program at the University of
Delaware and transplanted the family to Wilton, where they moved in
with her parents while Richard retained his teaching job in New
Jersey, planning to join them full-time this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The trial took place in juvenile court in Salem County last
July; by the following month, Sam was a Wilton football tricaptain,
and all seemed tranquil. Last month, he was selected Wilton's male
nominee for the Scholar-Athlete Award, ``and a minute after I made
the announcement over the loudspeaker,'' says Rubin, ``he was in
here thanking me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sam was not one of the Wilton baseball captains, but he was no
less a leader. He had established himself almost immediately after
his arrival last April, according to center fielder Gary Dunn, a
cocaptain who considered himself Sam's closest friend at school.
Though a lingering wrestling injury limited him mostly to DH duties
last spring, ``I led off and he batted second, and he was doing
well,'' says Dunn. ``Me and him were a 1-2 punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ben Clar, the other cocaptain, recalls that Sam fit in
right away at school. ``We loved him,'' says Clar. ``He was the new
kid and he didn't come on. He laid low, knew his place. But on the
field, he stepped it up a little. He was kind of a sparkplug,
getting us going.''
</P>
<P>
   As this season approached, even while he was consumed by his
wrestling responsibilities, Sam didn't ignore his first love.
``He'd drop by every once in a while,'' says Clar, ``and he'd ask
us, `Are you guys ready for baseball? This is going to be our
year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago during Wilton's spring break, many of the baseball
players attended an optional camp in Orlando, Fla. But Richard
Hingston said his son was suffering from a gastrointestinal virus
and headaches for which he was taking a prescription medication.
``The baseball camp was optional, so it didn't mean anything that
he didn't go,'' says Clar. ``And nobody knew he hadn't been feeling
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam spent the break with his father in Woodstown, keeping a
decidedly low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sick the whole time,'' says DuBois.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never left the house,'' says Sean Lenahan, who lives across
the street and used to wrestle with Sam. ``He didn't really see
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The following Monday, Sam returned to school at Wilton, where
Low and her fellow faculty noticed nothing unusual in his demeanor.
That afternoon, the baseball team held its first practice, an
indoor session, and his teammates remember that Sam appeared
buoyant as he worked out with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really excited, talking about the season,'' says Clar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't seem sick at all,'' says Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   While school attendance records are confidential, teammates
confirm that Sam was absent the next day. They thought nothing of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is absent from school once in a while,'' says Clar,
``so it was no big deal. We expected him back the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunn saw Sarah Hingston in school and asked how Sam was feeling.
``She said he was doing fine,'' recalls Dunn. ``As far as I know,
the family were the only ones to see or talk to him that day.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Sam Hingston took his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never seemed down,'' says Dunn. ``That was the whole weird
part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked what might have prompted the act, Richard Hingston refuses
to speculate, instead issuing this statement:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our son was charged with a juvenile offense. The charges
stemmed from something that was alleged to have happened over four
years ago. The allegations surfaced two years later. My son pled
not guilty and he stood firm. It went to trial and he was found
innocent of all charges beyond a shadow of a doubt. The family had
already moved to Wilton, Conn., and had closed this chapter in our
lives. I would ask that you respect our privacy in this matter. Sam
had moved on to accomplish great things with humility and grace.
And this community of Wilton, Conn., embraced him wonderfully. The
family and the friends you must have talked to hold Sam in high
regard with loving memory.''
</P>
<P>
   But why would he kill himself? His classmate at the Woodstown
Diner has a theory: ``He did it on Billy Coles's birthday. It was
as if he was trying to send a message.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilton and Woodstown sent Sam a posthumous message.
</P>
<P>
   The day after his death, Dunn cleared out Sam's school and
baseball lockers and returned the contents to the Hingstons. ``And
we're gonna make sure nobody else uses those lockers,'' says Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   That Friday, the Wilton girls' field hockey team, of which Sarah
is a member, brought dinner to the family. ``There must have been
30 of them here,'' says Marjorie, ``all in their team jackets.''
</P>
<P>
   Students at both Wilton and Woodstown flooded the Hingstons with
cards celebrating what Sam had meant to them.
</P>
<P>
   And on Saturday, which would have been Sam's first scrimmage of
the season with the baseball team, Our Lady of Fatima Church in
Wilton was jammed to the vestibule for a memorial Mass. The
congregation numbered about 1,000, and it included nine buses
filled with some 400 students from Wilton High. Another two
busloads of students, part of a caravan totaling almost 100, made
the 3 1/2-hour drive from Woodstown.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilton students wore white carnations in tribute, the
baseball team canceled practice to attend, and Sam's ashes lay in a
gold-plated urn atop a wooden table as the Rev. Michael Palmer,
pastor of the church, told the assemblage that Sam's final moments
_ when he complied with the EMTs' requests _ were life-affirming.
</P>
<P>
   Both his sisters spoke. And his father offered this eulogy:
``Sam and I always had catches. We used to say the best thing about
them was that it takes two people, one to throw, one to receive.
Sam, I hope you can catch everyone's tears and throw back some
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   He cannot throw them answers. Was Samuel Hingston's
self-destruction triggered years back by something stemming from
the rape charge, the details of which lie forever sealed among New
Jersey juvenile court records? By the harassment he endured at
Woodstown High? By an urge to deliver a grisly message to his
attacker? By the virus and headaches that plagued him in his final
weeks? By some undetermined development in Wilton after he
seemingly had started life anew among people who were unaware and
unconcerned about his past? By some sudden emotional or
psychological breakdown? By some combination of those
possibilities?
</P>
<P>
   Or, as his family and admirers always will believe, was there no
satisfactory explanation for terminating a life of such apparent
promise?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
