<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CLOUDY LATTER '98, MOST SEE BRIGHTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happened to the doom and gloom?
</P>
<P>
   Corporate profits, the fuel for the stock market's climb,
weren't anything to write home about through the last half of 1998
and more dreary news had been feared for the beginning of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But profits for the first quarter, which will be reported in a
blizzard beginning next week, now seem like relatively good news
waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index are
expected to report earnings 6.1 percent higher than profits in the
same quarter of last year, according to First Call Corp., a Boston
financial data firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day earnings are going to drive the market
higher or lower, so for the time being, we have the wind at our
back,'' said Bob Jones, a portfolio manager at Boston Partners
Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, forty-four of the 100 largest public
companies, based on stock market value, are forecast by analysts to
report lower profits or steeper losses for the quarter, according
to a survey conducted by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   A similar survey conducted three months ago had also forecast
that 44 of 100 local companies would report declining performance
in the fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp., the state's most valuable company and one of the
stock market's hottest issues, is expected to post first-quarter
profits 43 percent higher than earnings in the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Among the state's other large companies, Fleet Financial Group,
Raytheon Co., Staples Inc., State Street Corp. and Boston
Scientific Corp. are expected to report double-digit earnings
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette Co. earnings are expected to increase by 4 percent.
BankBoston Corp. profits are forecast to be 8 percent lower than
the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings surprises, pleasant or disappointing, can rock
individual stocks. Gillette shares took their biggest one-day hit
since 1987 this week when the Boston company said profits would
probably fall a penny per share below forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Other stocks, particularly smaller issues, can take off like a
rocket on good news.
</P>
<P>
   For the broader stock market, corporate profits began to loom as
a serious problem last year because they were acting just as you
might expect in the late stages of an economic boom. They were
actually down slightly in the third quarter of 1998 and had been
forecast to only edge up in the last three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual fourth quarter results tallied in January turned
out to be stronger than expected, up about 6 percent, and the same
kind of growth seems to be continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is a better-looking picture on the earnings
front than what we were talking about last year,'' said Charles
Hill, director of research at First Call.
</P>
<P>
   The message, say many analysts, is never underestimate the power
of low interest rates. Very low inflation and corresponding rates
have helped every part of the economy, especially consumer
spending, and stretched the good times beyond their normal limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider earnings growth in excess of 5 percent in
the eighth inning of the economic cycle, that's very positive for
investors,'' said David Sowerby, a portfolio manager and market
strategist for Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings outlook is not uniformly upbeat. Some technology
companies, particularly software producers, have ``preannounced''
disappointments to come in the weeks ahead. They are important
beyond their number because technology companies account for about
half the market's overall profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying there's some big negative going on, but there
are subtle changes that are enough to wave a caution flag,'' said
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a few weeks of mostly good news should be pushing the
market even higher from here, right? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have gotten the idea that first-quarter profits should
be upbeat and have already priced some of that optimism into
stocks. The Dow Jones industrial average got most of the attention
busting through 10,000, but the S&AMP;P 500 and the Nasdaq index both
rested at record levels Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   So, earnings news probably won't prompt another miniboom. But
they won't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect the next few weeks should be fairly positive
ones for the market,'' said quantitative analyst Evan Grace of
State Street Research and Management.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
