<HEADER>
A2129 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-RUNNING-BOS &LR;      04-09 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RUNNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING TO THE MOUNTAIN FOR A GROUNDING EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RUNNING TO THE MOUNTAIN 
A Journey of Faith and Change 
By Jon Katz 
Villard, 242 pp., $20 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quick first look at Jon Katz's new book triggered a mental red
flag. The handsome little volume looked like another navel-gazing
saga by a baby boomer confronting his mortality and his personal
crisis of meaning. It's a theme that has spawned a publishing
boomlet, filling bookstores with sometimes irritating and whiny
laments.
</P>
<P>
   But Katz _ though he certainly seems to be gripped by a certain
angst as he faces turning 50 _ avoids any literary cliches, instead
offering a funny, moving, and triumphant voyage of the soul.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of this wonderfully hope-filled memoir, Katz finds
faith not by running away from family, friends, or work in search
of something more, but by realizing that spiritual sustenance can
come from within _ from the decency with which we handle our roles
as spouses, parents, and friends.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Running to the Mountain,'' Katz, a well-known media critic
and author, buys a rickety cabin with a magnificent vista of the
Adirondack Mountains in upstate New York because life on the bland
streets of suburban New Jersey is steadily sapping his vitality. In
lyrical prose, Katz succinctly captures the kinds of worries that
have become ubiquitous among many in the American middle class: a
sense of settling for safe choices, of settling for less, at home
and in the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nearly as afraid of dying as I am of the hinges inside
my mind and soul rusting closed,'' Katz writes. ``I am desperate to
keep them open, because I think that if they close, that's one's
first death, the loss of hope, curiosity, and possibility, the
spiritual death. After that, it seems to me, the second one is just
a formality. I wanted to oil the hinges, force the doors to stay
open.''
</P>
<P>
   But what makes Katz's book so appealing and valuable is that he
wants to find answers that do not necessarily involve embracing a
creed, or subscribing to the teachings of whichever guru happens to
be in vogue at the moment. Indeed, he's leery of terms like
religion, divine, and spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``As such notions _ solitude, spirituality _ have been made to
seem godly, they appear to float high above our mundane and
unheroic experiences,'' he writes. ``We want to read about
conversations with God but don't really expect to have any
ourselves. . . . My hope, coming to the mountain, was that change,
spirituality, and idealism aren't the only way Up There but also
Down Here, in the details of daily life _ family, work, friends,
dogs, dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   So he buys a dilapidated cabin _ against his own common sense
and despite the reservations of his marvelously supportive and
patient wife _ as a way to find himself and keep from becoming so
settled in life that ``he would vanish into the mud like some fat
old catfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz avoids the pitfall of becoming nauseatingly self-reflective
by leavening his tale with large doses of humor and with the
adventures of his faithful yellow Labradors, Julius and Stanley,
who accompany Katz to his mountain retreat. A pragmatic city
dweller whose father used to make fun of him for his awkward,
bookish ways, Katz is buoyed by his newfound competency as he
battles an army of mice and embarks on a quest to find well water
for his cabin.
</P>
<P>
   He also is pushed up the mountain by Thomas Merton, the
celebrated Trappist monk who had been a literary mentor to Katz
after he wrote to Merton as a lonely and unhappy child. But Katz
rejects the solitude, sacrifice, and physical hardship Merton chose
for himself. That's one level of spirituality that few people, Katz
believes, can ever attain. Instead, Katz finds inner peace in
helping a new friend he makes on the mountain prepare for
fatherhood, in his sense of accomplishment at having renovated the
worn cabin, and in learning to appreciate the sheer beauty of the
woods.
</P>
<P>
   Katz does not claim to have come down the mountain possessing
some unique brilliant spiritual insight. Doubt and crisis will
never be erased, he freely admits. But, he writes, ``I had stood my
ground, believed in myself, and so, in time, had some others. I had
clung for dear life to my dreams, in the face of common sense and
conventional wisdom, and they had not failed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Katz's inspiring book reminds us, we already possess
the great power of faith. Like others, Katz writes that he came to
believe he had ``a worthwhile place to be in the world, important
things to contribute; to accept that I, more than anyone or
anything else, could guide the way I fared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
