<HEADER>
A2130 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-COOKIE-BOS &LR;      04-09 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-COOKIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT ALTMAN'S `COOKIE' NEVER CRUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
COOKIE'S FORTUNE 
Directed by: Robert Altman 
Screenplay by: Anne Rapp 
Starring: Glenn Close, Julianne Moore, Liv Tyler, Chris O'Donnell,
Charles S. Dutton, Patricia Neal, Ned Beatty, Courtney B. Vance,
Donald Moffat, Lyle Lovett 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (the depiction of a violent act and for sensuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune,'' the new Robert Altman film, is something
like the even-numbered symphonies of Beethoven. It's the work of a
master in a lighter mood. It's one of Altman's better recent films
and perhaps his most warmly disarming. Unlike ``Nashville'' and
``Short Cuts,'' where his intercutting of various story strands was
in the service of a larger, darker vision, Altman's purpose here
seems to be the much sunnier and more relaxed one of diverting and
entertaining us. And he does that with surehanded skill, filling
the screen in almost Faulknerian fashion with the color and
eccentricity we have come to expect beneath the placid facades of
small Mississippi towns.
</P>
<P>
   Nominally, it revolves around a death which for a while is about
to be pinned on the most likable character in the film, Charles S.
Dutton's large-hearted and easygoing caretaker named Willis.
Cookie, the matriarch of the title and Willis's employer, lofts the
film into a beguilingly loopy orbit for starters, thanks to
Patricia Neal's immersion in her own world. But then she's found
dead of a gunshot wound the morning after Willis came home drunk
and cleaned all the guns in her cabinet. That means Willis is in
trouble, even though Cookie's officious and pretentious niece,
Camille, played with a nicely gauged arc of febrile intensity by
Glenn Close as a Wicked Witch of the South, has inexcusably
tampered with evidence and disrupted the crime scene in her rush to
loot the place.
</P>
<P>
   The most moving part of the film is the dignity with which
Dutton's Willis sits calmly in the town jail with its cell door
permanently unlocked, waiting for the mess to sort itself out. As
the town sheriff, Ned Beatty is slyly amusing in his apologetic
manner to Willis, whose innocence he proclaims at regular
intervals. He bases his certainty on the fact that he has fished
with Willis all his life, which gives him all the insight he needs.
``Cookie's Fortune'' is less a murder mystery than a shaggy dog
story groping toward putting everything to rights, including
Camille's long-standing domination of her younger sister, Julianne
Moore's Cora, and the cloud under which Cora's daughter, Emma,
played by Liv Tyler, has been living.
</P>
<P>
   Emma is something of a renegade, who works delivering catfish
for local entrepreneur Lyle Lovett, whose crush on Emma looks
simultaneously pathetic and slightly creepy. Even though Emma is a
big-time bad girl by the standards of Holly Springs, Miss., having
logged $234 in parking tickets, her heart is pure. She insists on
being jailed with Willis as a gesture of criminal solidarity. It
may also have something to do with the fact that she wants her
hormones to be in the right place, too, since she and Chris
O'Donnell's bumpkin jailer lust for each other and break away for
trysts behind the Coke machine whenever time and circumstances
permit.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in a church production of ``Salome,'' being directed in
totalitarian fashion by Camille, also Donald Moffat's voice of
reason as the town's only lawyer who knows everybody's secrets but
can't reveal them, and you can see where Altman keeps the film at a
lively boil, even without the sight of John the Baptist's head
being served up on a platter. Never hitting anything too hard,
Altman keeps things fluid and his cast responds with spirited
portrayals that make the most of the telling details with which he
packs this folksy tapestry. All you need to know about Camille, for
instance, you're told on a sign that bills her as co-author of
``Salome'' with Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' isn't in the suspense business, but it's a
humane comedy as well as a human comedy, given the emotional depth
it needs by Dutton's relaxed decency. He and Altman make it all
look easy, Dutton in his low-key naturalism, the others zestfully
eccentric in the best possible way, which is to say with never the
slighest hint that in their own minds they are anything but
paragons of normality. Pretty early on, the film signals us that it
isn't out to storm any heights, which adds to its appeal.
``Cookie's Fortune'' is a screenful of Southern comfort, lullingly
served up by a cast that persuades us it would be just as happy
going fishing, then cooking up a batch of catfish enchiladas, as
shooting a movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
