<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, April 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ President Clinton says that
Serbian atrocities and offensive continue. NATO says it might have
hit civilians in the Kosovo capital of Pristina. Robin Cook, the
British foreign secretary, disparages in advance a new peace
proposal expected from Yugoslavia. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia as politics
continues to mix with the Kosovo crisis: President Boris Yeltsin
warns NATO against using ground troops; the Kremlin denies a
statement by the Communist speaker of parliament that missiles have
been reaimed at NATO countries. The speaker, seeming to go for the
pan-Slav vote, also calls for a union of Serbia, Russia and
Belarus. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SURVEIL (Brussels) _ NATO says it is not using its
surveillance planes to look for the refugees forced back from
Albanian border by Serb forces. By Craig R. Whitney..
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF (Washington) _ Relief groups, NATO officials, and
others debate issues raised by the close coordination between
military efforts and aid efforts. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Developments in the
Yugoslav capital, including developments in talks about the three
U.S. in POWs. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ Refugee developments: Some
straggling across through mountains; accounts of wretched journeys.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MUSLIMS (Undated) _ Many Muslims in the U.S. strongly
support the NATO bombing. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUGOVA (Undated) _ A profile of the Ibrahim Rugova, the
ethnic Albanian leader who Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav
president, says has agreed on a peace plan. By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering, among others, stories on new
NATO-Russia tension, the war-crime tribunal's efforts on Milosevic
and the planned deployment of Apache helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ Zhu Rongji, China's prime minister,
meets with Vice President Al Gore; Alan Greenspan, the Fed
chairman; Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin and others, before
leaving for Denver. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: Why the WTO
deal didn't happen, and whether it had more to do with Congress,
labor or the Chinese. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-RIGHTS (Geneva) _ The U.N. Human Rights Commission
receives a report on torture in Turkey and elsewhere. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-CHIEFS (Washington) _ Big-city police chiefs confer on
their departments' problems with minority relations and report on
the state of things generally. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HEALTH (Philadelphia) _ President Clinton travels to
Philadelphia for a ``Patients Bill of Rights'' event. By Katharine
Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   SHIPYARD-STRIKE (Newport News, Va.) _ After enduring a five-year
pay freeze to help nurse the Newport News shipyard back to
financial health, its 9,200 unionized workers have gone on strike,
insisting that the shipyard, now that it is making strong profits
again, is being too stingy in sharing the wealth with its workers.
By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-YOUTH-CRIME (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Arkansas has adopted a new
law to allow prosecutors to try juveniles charged with certain
crimes as adults. Like similar laws around the country, the new
measure was adopted in reaction to a case that sparked outrage _ in
Arkansas's case, the Jonesboro shootings, in which the two boys
charged and convicted of murder will be released in a few years. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column: On Walter
Chronkite's efforts against the religious right. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   We are also staffing the Susan McDougal trial in Little Rock,
with the case in the hands of the jury.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   THRIFT-SUIT (Washington) _ A decade after Congress committed
nearly $150 billion to bail out the teetering savings and loan
industry, a federal court is expected to rule late this afternoon
on the first of a series of damage claims that could eventually add
billions more to the cost of the cleanup. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TOURISM (Undated) _ The impact on the travel and tourism
industry of the air campaign against Yugoslavia. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TRADE (Hong Kong) _ For Hong Kong, which has thrived as
a middleman between China's closed markets and the outside world,
the prospect of a more-open China that would come with WTO
membership is a worrying one. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   GENENTECH (Undated) _ Genentech says it will not seek approval
in this country of a nerve drug it is developing with Roche because
the drug did not meet the target that had been set for a late-stage
study. Confirming earlier reports, Genentech also says it may pay
$50 million to settle federal charges about improper promotions of
its growth hormones. Its shares are down a couple of percent. By
David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was off 41
points, or 0.4 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 11 points, or
0.4 percent. Elsewhere, prices were flat in Tokyo and up 1.6
percent in Hong Kong. They rose 1.1 percent in Frankfurt and 0.3
percent in London. Prices fell half a percent in Brazil and 0.1
percent in Mexico. On the American debt market, the long bond was
up 7/32 point.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
