<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEER DRIVE, GREAT ACTING MAKE `GO' GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GO 
Directed by: Doug Liman 
Screenplay by: John August 
Starring: Desmond Askew, Taye Diggs, William Fichtner, J.E.
Freeman, Katie Holmes, Jane Krakowski, Breckin Meyer, Zack, Timothy
Olyphant, Sarah Polley, Scott Wolf 
Running time: 102 minutes 
Rated: R (strong drug content, sexuality, language and some
violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pulp Fiction'' wannabes don't get much slicker or edgier than
``Go,'' the new caper from ``Swingers'' filmmaker Doug Liman. It's
a hard-working film that overcomes its obvious manipulativeness on
the strength of sheer drive and a screenful of juicy performances.
It parodies a drug rush as it careens from one piece of danger to
another, relooping as it repeatedly goes back to the starting point
to tell the stories of three sets of characters before bringing
them together in a rueful convergence that's not so much a bang-up
ending as an ironic downer. Although the linkages don't quite
deliver the high they promise, they demonstrate conclusively that
Liman can bring off his off-the-wall juggling act.
</P>
<P>
   He's helped enormously by the performances. Those who aren't
playing LA thrill-seekers are playing LA thrill-avoiders. It's the
latter who come off best, starting with Sarah Polley's exhausted
supermarket checkout clerk talked into working an extra shift by
Simon, a co-worker and part-time drug dealer who wants to go to
Vegas to party with his pals and is willing to pay her $200 to
cover for him. The trouble is that she needs $380 to avoid
eviction. When a couple of TV cop show actors played by Jay Mohr
and Scott Wolf arrive looking for Simon and don't find him, they
ask her if she can supply them with the drug Ecstasy to bring along
to a Christmas rave.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing a way to erase her deficit, she arranges a meet with
them, then goes to Simon's supplier and talks him into giving her
the drugs, which she plans to sell for a markup. When the deal goes
bad, the dealer (Timothy Olyphant) goes gunning for her. Before he
can pull the trigger, she's hit by a yellow convertible and left
for dead in a ditch. That's hardly all there is to it. Polley,
building upon her intriguing performance in ``The Sweet
Hereafter,'' is too compelling a screen presence to die. Besides,
the film isn't through with Olyphant's drug dealer or the actors
played by Mohr and Wolf. ``Go,'' which consists of three half-hour
films covering the same interval of time, also has plans for Simon
and his bad-luck pals in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the ante on his own Las Vegas interlude in ``Swingers,''
Liman focuses on Desmond Askew's loose cannon, Simon, who manages
to bed two women, set a hotel room on fire, steal a car with a
loaded gun in the glove compartment, break the rules in a lap
dancing parlor and send tham all fleeing for their lives when he
shoots a bouncer. Yet for all the manic propulsiveness of Askew's
performance, it's Taye Diggs's cool companion, Marcus, who
dominates this episode with his poise in the face of constantly
being mistaken for hired help and his line of chat about tantric
sex. The two actors don't get off the hook easily either, being
railroaded through an unexpectedly weird evening with a cop. If
Liman's objective is more transparent than you would wish, ``Go''
is nevertheless entertaining on a moment-to-moment basis, thanks to
spirited playing and stylish, savvy workmanship. Nobody can say it
doesn't live up to its title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
