<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2140 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-09 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ABOUT TIME CUP WAS RAISED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Peter Blake and the invincible Kiwis announced their plans
for the next America's Cup back in 1995 at the San Diego docks,
there were groans all around.
</P>
<P>
   The next Cup would be in the year 2000, Blake said, five long
years between challenges. Now, some 200 days before the gun starts
Round 1 of the Louis Vuitton Cup, the event picks up a thread after
the longest hiatus since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   For viewers and readers who used to expect to hear about the Cup
every three years or so, it has become a bit hard to pick up a
thread after such a layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the sailing teams and fundraisers who have been working
since May 1995 to win a best-of-five match race final series that
begins Feb. 19, and whose winner will then hold the oldest trophy
in all sports.
</P>
<P>
   For most of us East Coasters that thread was easy to follow when
the Cup left Newport in 1983 and went to Fremantle, Australia,
where Dennis Conner won it back in 1987. But when it went to San
Diego and the next 12 years with legal battles, the Catamaran
fiasco, a new Cup class boat for a light air venue, and the victory
by New Zealand, the America's Cup has not been easy to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a coherent story line will take shape by next fall to
reawaken interest in the Cup and whether Americans will stay up to
watch the races on ESPN _ as they did in 1986-87 _ is all an open
question.
</P>
<P>
   In that Australian season, the story line rang as clear as a
John Wayne movie, with Conner in the saddle: The Aussies had taken
away our Cup after 20 years of trying, using a sneaky weapon
(winged keel) at best, and by God, we were going down there and
show those upstarts a thing or two about American pride. For
emphasis, Conner flew a huge American flag from the masthead of
Stars &AMP; Stripes after every victory.
</P>
<P>
   And of course the conditions, those boisterous Australian winds
and big lumpy seas that blew out sails and dismasted many a
12-meter, all of which was compelling to the American viewers in
the early-morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   Sailboat racing as dull as paint drying? Tell that to the suits
at ESPN, for whom that '87 Cup was a watershed event. Unfortunately
for ESPN the magic never quite struck again when the Cup went to
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   What would spark some excitement around the old America's Cup
home grounds is if Young America, carrying colors of the New York
Yacht Club, can show some real strength in the early going. If they
look believable in the three fall round robins, with a bit of hype
going into the hoopla Down Under, the guess here is that the Cup
fans will be back.
</P>
<P>
   Once the dream becomes palpable (and rational) that the
America's Cup would be coming ``home'' to Newport, that droopy-eyed
legion of midnight race-followers will be back.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a few other challenging syndicates _ four from the
United States _ are trying hard to prove that this scenario remains
in the fantasy realm. One of them, America True from the San
Francisco Yacht Club, has just wrapped up four months of sailing in
New Zealand along with Young America and AmericaOne, Paul Cayard's
campaign, which is also based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are full on for New Zealand with a new boat,'' says Dawn
Riley, captain and CEO of America True, which is sailing in the
former Tag Heuer, Chris Dickson's boat in the last Cup. ``We are
really ahead, and on track. We have NASA and STRC software, and
also all of Bill Koch's '95 data.''
</P>
<P>
   America True, says Riley, has one boat under construction by
builder Jim Betts in Truckee, Calif., while both Young America and
America One claim to have two boat programs.
</P>
<P>
   But in some early intelligence gathering, Riley says she has
reason to believe that none of the other American challengers will
be able to pull off two boat programs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference could be night and day. Many Cup observers
believe that it is virtually impossible for a one-boat program to
beat a two-boat effort. The reason: A one-boat team simply can't
develop the design data fast enough to move forward at the speed of
a two-boat campaign, which can leapfrog its boats' performance
development.
</P>
<P>
   But Riley isn't so sure. ``The two-boat approach is minimized
these days by the strength of our computer programs,'' she says,
adding her serious doubts about the other US campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   To date, only three international America's Cup class numbers
have been assigned to US syndicates, one each to America One (USA
49), Aloha Racing (USA 50), and America True (USA 51). Under the
Cup rules, sail numbers are not allocated until boat building has
commenced, though two other US boats are under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Much speculation swirls around the question of how badly Young
America was set back in its fundraising when it had to break a
sponsorship deal with Fox Sports Net because of a conflict with
ESPN, the Cup's official broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox sponsorship deal included logos on sails and boats, and
ESPN objected to televising its rival's logos, so Young America was
released from that part of the Fox deal, said to have been worth
$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Eagleson said Wednesday in a phone interview from the
Portland, Maine, offices of Young America, that the setback with
Fox would not in any way slow down the syndicate's two-boat
program. Its boats are being built at Goetz Custom Yachts in
Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain covers the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
