<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITY THE BU TRUSTEE, TOILING IN THE HOT SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not sure I could handle the pressure of being a Boston
University trustee. John Silber's vast amen chorus (some names:
Scientology maven Earle Cooley; Wall Street Journal honcho Karen
Elliott House; the ubiquitous Jim Howell; developer Alan Leventhal;
the delightfully named French Wallop, and many, many more) is
congregating this week at the plush Scottsdale Conference Resort
developed by BU trustee Richard Joaquim.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the pace! The first order of business, the meeting of the
Committee on Executive Compensation (read: John Silber's ATM), took
place Wednesday before lunch. After the first plenary business
meeting Thursday, Joaquim offered up a golf clinic, a visit to
Frank Lloyd Wright's home at nearby Taliesin West, or ``an
afternoon of health and beauty . . . at a nearby spa.'' In a letter
to the trustees, he adds: ``Last year's popular desert jeep tour
will be repeated, with a pontoon ride on beautiful Saguaro Lake.''
Swell!
</P>
<P>
   Joaquim lays out an equally grueling schedule for Friday.
Speeches by Chancellor-for-Life Silber and president Jon Westling,
followed by teatime for the ladies _ and for the men! ``A golf
tournament will also be held at McCormick Ranch, with tee-off
scheduled for 12:36 p.m.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Globe gets results &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How odd that I wasn't on the guest list for Monday's swank
dinner at the Kennedy School's fifth-floor entertainment aerie,
where the swells assembled to inaugurate the Jeane and Evron
Kirkpatrick Professorship of International Affairs, donated by
Newton's own Leo and Emily Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know Emily Kahn; Leo's an interesting guy. He attended
Harvard, then got a degree from the Columbia Journalism School. He
wised up soon enough and got a real job in his father's supermarket
business. (His son Joseph apparently lacks the father's good sense;
he writes for The New York Times.) Leo made a pile with Purity
Supreme, then invested wisely in start-ups like Staples and organic
marketer Fresh Fields, a fairly blatant Bread and Circus rip-off.
More recently he helped start up the Nature's Heartland stores here
(off-price Bread and Circus), since sold to a larger chain.
</P>
<P>
   Leo takes a genuine interest in public affairs, and says he was
startled to read a Globe op-ed article that described Jeane
Kirkpatrick's troubles at Brandeis University a few years ago. In
1994, vociferous student protests at Brand X prompted the former
United Nations ambassador to decline a proferred honorary degree.
``I was really turned on by the column,'' Kahn recalls. The writer
``suggested that a leading university in the area could make up for
the insult to Kirkpatrick.'' Emily Kahn also has a degree from the
World's Greatest University, and Leo sat on the board of the
Kennedy School.
</P>
<P>
   Brandeis's loss translates into Harvard's gain. Leo has endowed
two WGU chairs over the years but hasn't made a large donation to
Brandeis. ``I'm very loyal to Harvard,'' he explains,
diplomatically. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This just in &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Writer/collaborator Bill Novak, praised as a great writing coach
in the just-published George Stephanopoulos memoir, has an
intriguing new project: He's working on a book that will never be
published, at least not in the conventional sense.
</P>
<P>
   Novak, who has ghostwritten books for Tip O'Neill, Nancy Reagan,
and Magic Johnson was approached six months ago by Chicago-based
real estate magnate Jay Pritzker to collaborate on his biography.
Pritzker would probably be worth a conventional biography; the
grandson of Russian immigrants, he helped build a $13 billion
business empire that included the Hyatt hotel chain, Nevada
casinos, and Ticketmaster. He also endowed the Pritzker Prize,
regarded as the Nobel Prize for architecture.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the publicity-shy Pritzker, who had some
well-publicized run-ins with government regulators, stipulated that
the book would be distributed only to family and friends. He and
Novak logged many interview hours up until the businessman's death
earlier this year. The book should be ready in a year or so _ but
your local bookstore is one place you needn't look for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
