<SLUG> BC-NY-MAGICIAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFFIN ACT AN OFF-BROADWAY HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's like Lenin's Tomb on the Hudson, except that the
bearded guy in the coffin is the magician David Blaine, who has
turned the conceit into one of the season's most unlikely publicity
stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Game for a good show, New Yorkers are playing along. More than
10,000 a day line up _ at peak hours for as long as 30 minutes _ to
get their free 30-second glimpse of the man who has buried himself
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old showman, who went underground last Monday
morning, plans to be dug up Monday morning, hours before ABC
broadcasts his television special, already taped.
</P>
<P>
   All day and night, Blaine lies shirtless in a plexiglass-topped
coffin that has been lowered six feet into the ground and then
covered with a two-ton tank of water _ to make escape, or even a
brief respite, out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   A ventilator pumps temperature-controlled air into the coffin.
He sips two tablespoonfuls of water a day. A catheter runs down his
left leg. A buzzer lets him call for help, in case anything goes
wrong. (A nurse and a crane operator, who can lift Blaine out in
five minutes, are constantly nearby.)
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, there's just a pillow, a sheet, and Blaine _ who
frequently waves and mugs to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   William MacLellan, one of two guards on the scene Thursday
afternoon, said, ``We're here 24 hours a day and there's literally
never a minute when nobody's viewing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the viewers are New Yorkers, possibly because the
locale is off the beaten track, a bleak construction site a few
blocks west of Lincoln Center, with nothing of note nearby but the
Hudson River and one of Donald Trump's residential towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here out of morbid curiosity,'' said Alan Thompas, who
works for a publishing company in Midtown Manhattan. ``It's kind of
like a `Seinfeld' moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Bartlow, an actress, skipped a rehearsal to see Blaine
for the second day in a row. ``It's wicked cool,'' she exclaimed.
``It's just cool that he's in the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Her companion, Bonnie Smith, also an actress, was less
ebullient. ``I had to see what sombody without a brain looks
like,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   This being New York, skeptics abound. Francis Bienvenido, who
was dragged to the site by his wife, shrugged. ``Where's the
dirt?'' he asked. ``When you're buried in real life, you got dirt
and you don't have any air pumped in. I'm not impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   James Reed, who took the subway down from the Bronx, entertained
still more cynical thoughts. ``You think he's really in there?'' he
mused. ``This guy's an illusionist, right? If he comes out of there
and doesn't look all emaciated, cheeks sunk in, all skinny, then
you know it's an illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   The event is being sponsored by a theater producer, James
Nederlander, at a cost of $200,000. Pat Smith, Nederlander's
publicist, explained Thursday, ``He is looking at a 25-year-old guy
who's going to be the next Houdini, and he wants to have a long
relationship with this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other promoters have also found ways to get into the act. A few
feet behind the coffin stands a vase of flowers, with a placard
reading, ``Good luck, but just in case, Flowers by Reuven.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaine said, before going into the tank, that he has wanted to
be buried alive ever since reading that Houdini had planned to pull
off a similar stunt but died, in 1926, before getting around to it.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Blaine was a street performer who would waltz
into fashionable restaurants and do tricks with cards and
levitation that amazed the likes of Robert DeNiro and Al Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   Word of his exploits soon spread. Monday's ABC-TV special is his
second. Blaine also gained a sort of prominence among teenyboppers
when the New York tabloids displayed him as a member of Leonardo
DeCaprio's posse, prowling the bars of SoHo and TriBeCa through the
wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   Several celebrities have come to peek at his show on Riverside
Drive. Today, Cathy Rigby, who is playing ``Peter Pan'' on
Broadway, is slated to stop by, to sprinkle fairy dust on the
coffin and exhort the crowd to think happy thoughts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
