A2148 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-09 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI SMITES `MOSES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Charlton Heston played Moses in ``The Ten Commandments,''
he said, ``It would take more than a man to lead the slaves from
bondage. It would take a god.''
</P>
<P>
   That was easy for Heston to say when the script gave him a
hotline to God. This week Heston was Rameses. No matter how much
money he threw at the sea, it would not part. Despite his appeals
to patriotism, the voters stayed on the opposite shore.
</P>
<P>
   Heston found out this week that it takes more than being a god
of the silver screen to make people slaves to handguns. With the
script on his side, the sea would part. Heston railed in vain as
the waters turned green with his limp, rotting dollars.
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Heston, president of the National Rifle
Association, waged an all-out assault on the state of Missouri.
That state has had a ban on concealed handguns since 1875, a ban
enacted during the gunslinging of outlaw Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is one of only seven states that bans concealed weapons
(Massachusetts allows concealed weapons with a permit). This
enrages the NRA. Despite America's status as the firearm murder
capital of the developed world, the NRA will not rest until
handguns are as easy to buy as computers and Coke.
</P>
<P>
   So pro-gun activists got a binding measure, Proposition B, put
on the ballot. A Yes vote would have lifted the ban.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA fired every bullet. It outspent the gun-control forces
by $3.8 million to $800,000 a nearly 5 to 1 ratio and outspent by
27 times Handgun Control, which contributed $141,504 against
Proposition B. Handgun Control is headed by Sarah Brady, wife of
James Brady, the White House press secretary who was shot in the
assassination attempt on President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA sent out at least a million mailings. It gave out at
least 60,000 signs to post in front yards. Confident of bedrock
support in rural areas, it tried to woo urban voters by touting
handguns as a tool of self defense against crime.
</P>
<P>
   Heston came to Missouri three times. Though it has not been a
``right'' to carry a concealed handgun for 124 years, the NRA kept
saying, ``Don't Give Up Your Right!'' The NRA likened a yes vote to
the American Revolution, saying, ``Welcome to Concord Bridge. On
April 6, step onto that bridge at Concord, take up the musket of
truth and help finish the fight for freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Heston and the NRA took up their muskets declaring ``If we are
successful in passing Proposition B, Missouri voters can send a
shot across the bow of the anti-gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA assault was so withering that Carole Kennedy, a
middle-school principal and a co-chair of Safe Schools and
Workplaces, the key group fighting Proposition B, said, ``We felt
like David and Goliath.''
</P>
<P>
   The slingshot shattered the musket. The urban areas and many of
the suburbs, sick of the gun violence of the 1980s and early '90s,
galvanized. Many police chiefs, interfaith coalitions and newspaper
editorials decried the proposition. The Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce, and several major companies like Sprint and Hallmark
Cards, and even the Kansas City and St. Louis pro football and
baseball teams came out against the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the voters acted on the facts, such as that gun
ownership itself, as researched in medical journals, makes one far
more likely to be killed by a gun. They understood that gun
ownership does not deter crime, as in statistics that showed that
violent crime dropped in the 1990s at twice the rate of some states
that allow concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition B lost by 52 to 48 percent. Rural areas indeed voted
overwhelmingly for concealed handguns. But the cities and suburbs
came out in such force that Missouri set a record for April
turnout. In the city of St. Louis, 74 percent of voters rejected
Proposition B. In St. Louis County, 70 percent said no. In Kansas
City, 72 percent of voters rejected the proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rev. B.T. Rice, president of St. Louis Clergy Coalition, said,
``Big Money can't buy us.'' State Auditor Claire McCaskill said,
``Money can't overcome common sense. Voters particularly in urban
areas, understand guns are not the answer for safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming just as many cities are suing gun makers, Missouri's vote
is one more sign that common sense is slowly becoming the rule,
rather than the exception of debate on handguns. No longer can the
NRA ride into town with a Ten Commandments that bear false witness
to the need for such weapons in a modern society. No longer can
Heston show up and assume that just because he has played Moses,
the sea will part on his command.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
