<HEADER>
A2152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-     04-09 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS HAS A CHECKUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Robert Edwards was trying to be
inconspicuous on his journey back to Foxborough Thursday. He didn't
want to do interviews. He really didn't want to see too many
people, except the doctors and trainer Ron O'Neil, who needed to
assess the progress of his the running back's damaged left knee.
</P>
<P>
   But the visit was fruitful, one he may never forget.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after arriving, owner Bob Kraft called him into his
office and handed him an envelope.
</P>
<P>
   In it was a check for $1 million. It was the final installment
of a $3.1 million signing bonus that the NFL had informed the
Patriots that they were not liable to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob didn't feel that was right,'' said Patriots vice president
Andy Wasynczuk. ``He never felt comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the check was extended and accepted. Now Edwards, who
feels with every beat of his heart that he will play in the NFL
again, will not have to worry about finances. The league, which
gave the Patriots ``Paragraph 5'' salary cap relief, which is
basically Edwards's $350,000 salary this year, said they will
commit to paying Edwards's contract, reviewing it on a year-to-year
basis. That amounts to about $400,000 next year and in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even thought about my contract and whether or not
I'd get paid,'' said Edwards after making the rounds at the stadium
Thursday. ``I was just trying to get better. I think I kind of took
for granted that things worked out money wise. I figured I'd have a
year of IR (injured reserve) to see how I'd do. I didn't know some
things until I spoke to Mr. Kraft today. I'm very thankful for him
and he's really reached out and lended a helping hand to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, dressed in a black warmup suit and able to get around
on his crutches pretty well, said he began his therapy in Georgia
last Monday. Doctors, he says, have been realistic about his
future, telling him, ``People have come back from this. They said
Bruce Armstrong had a similar injury, but they're also realistic
and tell me that I may never play.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly down and out emotionally and physically following the
Feb. 5 accident, Edwards has now stopped feeling sorry for himself
and has begun trying to buck the dramatic odds he faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going well,'' he said. ``It's going to take
time. I'm not going to get impatient or anything. It's nothing I
haven't faced before.'' Edwards missed most of his junior season at
Georgia with a fractured foot.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said doctors haven't been very specific with him on a
timetable for a possible return. He tore three of the four major
ligaments, suffered extensive nerve damage, and the dislocation
forced emergency surgery as doctors feared that waiting too long
would cut off his circulation and force amputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't told me anything,'' he said. ``It depends on how
extensive the nerve damage is. That will tell the whole story. If
my nerves come back, that's the point where I'll be back
completely, but nerves take a long time to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking softly and now with a sense of optimism, Edwards said
he's already encouraged with recent progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've seen improvement and change already since I started
therapy. I'm able to move my foot out. I wasn't able to do that
earlier. That's improved, but there's a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, especially when they told me I might not be able
to play again. It was hard on me because this is what I love to do.
And because I played only one year, it made it even harder. I had
to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was playing for the AFC in the four-on-four flag
football game on the beach, prior to the Pro Bowl in Hawaii. He
went up with teammate Charles Woodson of the Oakland Raiders to try
to deflect a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came down,'' he recalled. ``I don't know how it
happened, but I dislocated my knee. I felt it. I grabbed my leg,
but I wasn't in any pain. I just looked down and felt it wasn't
right. After I was in the hospital and they took some pictures, my
agent came over and said I messed up my knee. There was more of a
discomfort pain, because my knee was in the wrong place. It wasn't
really comfortable. When the doctor popped it back in place it was
one of the greatest feelings I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   After X-rays were taken, Edwards was rushed to surgery at the
Straub Medical Center in Honolulu. He said he was never really told
about the urgency of the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came to and they'd already done the surgery,'' said
Edwards. ``When I was waking up they told me. I didn't know my foot
was almost amputated. God knows that in my heart I want to do this
more than anything. Out of every bad thing, something good comes
out of it. I don't know what it is. Nobody knows what it is. It may
be that I never play again, but I know something good will happen
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He can somehow equate it to his injury at Georgia, where he had
to watch the team play without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wouldn't have bounced back from that as well
as I did, and I was able to accomplish things like have a good
senior year and get drafted in the first round, and do some things
for my family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is that hope that he lives with every day.
</P>
<P>
   He is also lifted by the hundreds of cards, letters, and phone
calls he's received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of support,'' Edwards said. ``A lot of letters
and kids and letters. People are doing everything they can to help
me. (University of) Georgia and their staff has invited me back
there to do my rehab, and they're trying to help me out and making
sure I get the best care while I'm in Georgia,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   His workouts are 3 1/2 hours a day. He will likely be up to five
hours when the weight work and pool begin.
</P>
<P>
   He said he only faces more surgery if the work he's doing now
doesn't reduce the amount of scar tissue around the knee.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has no idea what the future holds, but he said he will
be around Foxborough once the season begins. He said he hasn't
thought about life after football, if that's the way it has to be.
He says he'll stay involved in the game somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can lend my dreams to my brother (Chris, a receiver)
at Georgia,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if his dreams may no longer come true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
