<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DREAMLIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS' IS ON SOLID GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS 
 
Directed by: Erick Zonca 
Screenplay by: Zonca, Roger Bohbot 
Starring: Elodie Bouchez, Natacha Regnier, Gregoire Colin, Jo
Prestia, Patrick Mercado 
Running time: 113 minutes(in French with subtitles) 
Rated: R (a scene of extreme sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a medium that's supposed to be about people, it's amazing
how rarely films convey the impression of just letting people be
people. Erick Zonka's remarkable debut feature, ``The Dreamlife of
Angels,'' is arresting precisely because it convinces us it's doing
just that. At once drifty and hurtling, it's deceptively artless
and always raw and immediate as it details the lives of two young
women escaping from dreary factory jobs in the northern French city
of Lille. Although nowhere close to anything resembling heaven,
they are the angels of the title and on them Zonca's verite style
is a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Elodie Bouchez's Ida is the softly scrappy one with the gamine
look, her right eyebrow bisected by a scar and everything she owns
stuffed in a backpack. She begins the film on the road and for a
moment it looks as if we're getting a reprise of Agnes Varda's
``Vagabond.'' But no. Ida is more upbeat. As soon as she hits town,
she slices color reproductions out of an art book with a razor,
pastes them on heavy paper stock, and sells them for walking-around
money. She's handy and resourceful. She, it would seem, is a
survivor. But she can't sew very well, and quickly loses a job she
finds in a garment factory assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   She lasts just long enough there to befriend Natacha Regnier's
Marie, who needs only the impetus provided by Ida to walk out of
the place with her. They have one thing going for them. They have
the use of an apartment Marie has been occupying since the
residents _ a young woman and her mother _ have been lying comatose
in a hospital following a car accident. The more introverted Marie
appears to be a bit of a passive victim, but we soon see her
situation is more complicated than that. There's a lot of anger in
her, and she's determined not to end up bullied by a man, as her
mother has. But she feels powerless to do much about her
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The girls don't need much money, which means they have time to
get to know one another and note how different their personalities
are. They do a bit of mooching, a lot of time-killing, and
eventually they befriend a pair of greasy cycle-riding bouncers at
the local rock club. But Patrick Mercado's Charly and Jo Prestia's
Fredo are more than the bargain-basement thugs they appear to be.
They have feelings and a realistic view of the world and their
place in it. As Ida becomes engrossed in the diary of the comatose
girl, and continues making entries where its owner left off, Marie
begins a half-hearted affair with Charly.
</P>
<P>
   But her big problem becomes Gregoire Colin's Chriss, the
arrogant son of the club owner, whose brutality she tolerates as he
pushes her into sex and subservience. This soon tips her melancholy
personality into protracted brooding and clashes with Ida, whose
unsinkable nature prevents the film from sliding into
lugubriousness. Still, Regnier remains compelling, even in her
gloom, while Bouchez supplies nonstop sunny magnetism. It's no
accident that Zonca chose as his cinematographer Agnes Godard, who
photographed the invigorating ``Nenette et Boni'' (that film also
starred Colin, in a quite different sympathetic older brother
role). Her close-quarters hand-held camerawork imparts vigor and
parallels the jumpy tentativeness of the girls' lives. These angels
will grow on you, thanks to Zonca's up-close empathy and urgency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
