<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2158 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-BOS &LR;      04-09 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGWOOD SET FOR US-AUSSIE MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ He had only seen the winning point once.
``Through these eyes,'' Jim Courier said. ``I'm pretty sure it was
a serve to my backhand.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the Longwood folks punched up the video of Sunday's
stirring Davis Cup climax between the United States and Great
Britain, the man of the hour asked to have the monitor tilted his
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never saw so many people clapping for an error,'' Courier
cracked, after watching Greg Rusedski plop a volley into the net
and give the visiting Americans a stirring 3-2 victory in the 14th
game of the fifth set of the final match.
</P>
<P>
   At least it was a forced error, Courier was told, and only the
statkeeper cared anyway. What mattered was that the underdog Yanks
were still alive and slated for a dream quarterfinal against
archrival Australia (July 16-18) on the 100th anniversary of the
Cup at the club in the town where it was born.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until their celebratory dinner that all the lovely
coincidences sunk in. ``We're coming back home,'' Courier realized.
``We're coming to Boston. And we're going to play the Aussies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were coming to Boston this summer anyway for the
Cup centennial, the first time at the Longwood Cricket Club since
Australia and India played a 1959 semifinal. The International
Tennis Federation decided that two years ago. But facing the Uzbeks
or the Ecuadorans in a relegation match would have been like
serving flat champagne and stale cake. ``Australia is the match
everyone wanted,'' says US captain Tim Gullikson.
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies, who zapped Zimbabwe on the road last weekend to
avenge last year's home loss, wanted the Americans, too. But they
wanted them in Melbourne, where they would normally have had them,
since Australia played in Washington two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Aussie captain) John Newcombe and they weren't
too happy about it,'' Gullikson said Thursday. ``We should be down
there. But it isn't like it was sprung on them last week.''
</P>
<P>
   So while Tennis Australia says it will appeal to the ITF to
switch the venue down under, there's no chance that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of the decision being reversed are zero,'' Davis
Cup executive director Thomas Hallberg said by telephone from
London Thursday. ``No chance, I would think.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies weren't thinking about choice of ground last year,
when they had to beat the Uzbeks to get back into the World Group.
And the Americans were just hoping to survive last weekend's first
round in Birmingham after Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi both said
nix to a roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   So Gullikson went with Courier and Todd Martin and bristled when
critics said that Uncle Sam was going with the B team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, we're not sending the B team, we're sending the A
team,'' he says. ``This is America's team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Yanks were decided underdogs against a British team
fielding seventh-ranked Tim Henman and 11th-ranked Rusedski and
playing on a carpet before 9,300 screeching Union Jack-bedecked
partisans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just a tennis match,'' Courier realized. ``It was a
huge event for England.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was huge for Courier, who gets jazzed whenever he hears
the D-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Hong Kongs and Atlantas you play don't mean
anything,'' he says. ``You won't remember those when you're 80.
You'll remember what it was like at six-all in the fifth set of the
final match and you're playing for your country on the road with
everyone screaming. It doesn't get any more memorable than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier may be ranked 54th now, but he's been a part of two Cup
victories (in 1992 and 1995) and the Yanks have never lost (as in
13-0) when he's been aboard. So he's already volunteered for July's
match here and Martin is all but certain to re-up, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the right of first refusal,'' says Gullikson. ``They
were here at the beginning, so . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Sampras and Agassi, who've played 54 Cup matches
between them, are persona non grata.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a free country and they have freedom of choice,'' says
Courier.
</P>
<P>
   But Gullikson won't be asking pretty-please. Not a second time.
He and US Tennis Association president Judy Levering each went out
to California earlier this year to ask Sampras and Agassi in person
and were turned down flat. If you have to beg a man to play for his
country, Gullikson figures, why bother?
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is passion and commitment,'' he says. ``Those
are more important than rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier and Martin told Gullikson they're available anytime,
anywhere, and that was before they squelched the Brits, whom Dwight
Davis and friends knocked off in the inaugural Cup in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   It's a year for symbolic symmetry _ the US and Aussies are the
two most successful nations in Cup history (57 titles between them)
and have met more often (44 times) than anyone else. Is it
coincidence that brings them to Hammond Street after a century? Or
destiny?
</P>
<P>
   ``Destiny? That's like talking about a no-hitter,'' Courier
mused Thursday. ``We'll just have to sit back and let it all pan
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
