<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-EAGLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS IS WAY BEYOND WHAT SINGER EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
 EYE-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Eagle Eye Cherry, son of late jazz trumpeter Don
Cherry, got a lot of encouragement from his famous father while
growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad loved life, and he loved music,'' Eagle-Eye Cherry said
this week in a phone interview from Los Angeles. ``There was always
music when he was around.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he never pushed me too hard. I think he understood that
there's a balance you have to find when your parents are trying to
get you into something, and you just want to hang out with your
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Eagle-Eye, so-named because of how he squinted as a newborn,
pursued an acting career, unsuccessfully, before turning his
attention to music in the mid-'90s. It proved auspicious.
</P>
<P>
   The singer-songwriter's debut album, ``Desireless,'' has sold
more than 1 million copies since its release last year and spawned
a hit single, the sultry and romantic ``Save Tonight.'' The album's
smooth blend of rock, soul, jazz and blues evokes memories of
Marvin Gaye.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album's success is way beyond anything I expected,''
Cherry said. ``The label gives me (sales) numbers, and it's not
really tangible, but it sounds good. It's not until I get out on
stage and play the gigs and have a good crowd that I realize, `Oh,
OK, I guess it is going really well.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry, 27, also learned a lot from his half-sister, singer
Neneh Cherry, who recorded the 1989 hit ``Buffalo Stance.'' He was
18 at the time and proud of her albeit fleeting success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm savoring this moment in my life, because I know everyone
has their ups and downs,'' he said. ``If I were 10 years younger, I
would totally be taking this for granted and probably wasting a lot
of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry grew up in Sweden but moved to New York with his parents
and siblings when he was 14. Like a lot of famous American jazz
musicians in the '60s, his dad had been attracted to Europe by the
receptive audiences there.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, being black in the States was still a pretty
tough scene,'' Cherry said. ``There was a certain vibe, especially
in Stockholm and Paris, where the jazz scene was really bubbling
over, and there was a certain respect for the musicians that they
weren't getting over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Cherry returned to his native Sweden with his
actress-model girlfriend, Helena af Sandeberg. The furnished
apartment they rented in Stockholm came complete with a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the instruments I owned, I never had an acoustic
guitar, oddly enough,'' Cherry said.
</P>
<P>
   The newfound guitar, as well as the couple's relaxed Stockholm
lifestyle, spurred Cherry's songwriting. ``The songs just started
coming, and one day I realized, `This is it, here I go,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Save Tonight,'' the debut album's first single, was like a
gift. ``It just kind of hit me while I was strumming the guitar,''
he said. ``It felt like it had already been written.''
</P>
<P>
   The song, about savoring romance before a separation, has been
so popular on ``adult top 40'' stations that the Sony-distributed
Work label has delayed release of the follow-up single, ``Falling
in Love Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Save Tonight' is a stubborn tune,'' Cherry said. ``It keeps
getting played.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his love of Sweden, many of Cherry's songs were inspired
by life in New York, the Grammy-nominated singer's favorite city.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a very intense town,'' he said. ``It's the
greatest city in the world if you're into music and art and all
that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But New York's dark side is reflected in ``Shooting Up in Vain''
and ``Death Defied by Will,'' two songs about ``characters going
down the wrong road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it all there in New York,'' Cherry said. ``It's part
of my love-hate relationship with the city. It's the dark side of
reality, just staring you in the face. You can't sweep it under the
carpet.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's title song was written in the '70s by Cherry's
father. ``It was one of the first songs he taught me on the piano.
It's one of my favorites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Cherry died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had lived such a full life, made so many records, traveled
so much and touched so many people, it made me realize that I
hadn't even started what I wanted to do in life. It was a real kick
in the butt. You never know when your time's up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
