A2180 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SASQUATCH-PUBLI     04-09 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SASQUATCH-PUBLISHING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SASQUATCH BOOKS STEPS OUT INTO CALIF., ALASKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sasquatch Books, the Seattle-based regional publisher
which has so successfully harnessed the Northwest muse, is seeking
to repeat its winning formula in California and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The formula is just plain common sense. ``Our editorial stance:
give the people who live here what they want and need to know,''
said Publisher Chad Haight. Sasquatch signs homegrown writers _
experts in their field _ and publishes books about regional travel,
gardening, food, and literary nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   The results are well known to many Northwesterners who rely on
the utilitarian books in the Best Places series of guidebooks like
Northwest Best Places, Seattle Best Places and Oregon Coast Best
Places. Sasquatch titles revel in a sense of place such as a new
children's book called ``The Miser on the Mountain, A Nisqually
Legend of Mount Rainier'' and ``Gone Whaling, A Search for Orcas in
Northwest Waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Now California and Alaska can expect to see more Sasquatch
titles that reflect the land and life of those states. ``The reason
we are successful in the Northwest is that we know the region and
are part of it,'' said Haight. ``But we could not export it to
California. We need to organically grow it from within the state
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent hiring of Sasquatch's first California-based editor
Jennie McDonald marks the publisher's commitment to that organic
growth. There are already Best Places books like ``Northern
California Coast,'' which Sasquatch's spring catalog pegs as ``a
personal, portable guide ... written from a local's perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   But with McDonald on board, Bay Area book sellers will see even
more titles like the newly released ``A Yardscapes Year, Ideas and
Plants for Bay Area Gardeners.'' (The author was a long-time
columnist for the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area book, like so many on Sasquatch's list, boldly
proclaims that singular sense of place in a spot where people are
proud to live. The back cover reflects Sasquatch's editorial and
marketing strategy of how to grab the regional publishing niche.
``Here are innovative ideas for horticultural success in the
challenging and complex Bay Area ecosystem, which offers up
rainless summers, fickle fogs, and the occasional earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasquatch, when it first decided to expand its market, was
unsure whether to move into other regions by simply expanding the
definition of the Northwest. ``We were so in love with our region
that we decided to make it bigger,'' said Haight with a chuckle.
``But we were really deluding ourselves to think California had
anything to do with the Pacific Northwest. And we have observed the
same thing about Alaska too.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the March 1 opening of an office in Berkeley and the
hiring of McDonald. ``Regional publishing must begin with local
book acquisition and development and that's precisely what Jennie
will be doing,'' editorial director Gary Luke said.
</P>
<P>
   Luke said there is not a regional press in California quite like
Sasquatch. ``Many publishers in the Bay Area publish regional
titles within their national lists, but they do not focus on a
complete California program. We plan to publish a steady list of
titles _ all the books you'll ever need to travel to or live in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Haight expects in California the kind of strong competition that
Sasquatch has avoided up to now. ``In the Northwest, most of the
regional publishers didn't publish travel guides,'' Haight said.
``On the regional bookshelves, there is no one solely dedicated to
what we were trying to do.'' While there is some competition from
the Seattle-based Mountaineers, which publishes specialized outdoor
books, and Gaphic Arts Publishing of Portland, ``we have the place
(the Northwest) to ourselves in many ways,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The California market is immensely bigger than the Northwest.
But there are many more publishers, said Haight. ``To us, it will
be a matter of establishing the quality of books we publish in a
more frenzied environment. It is going to be a war.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on March 1, Sasquatch expanded its title list and
geographic reach with the purchase of Paws IV Publishing of Homer,
Alaska. The 14-title, Paws IV line of children's book for the
school and trade markets include titles that speak of place like
``Alaska's Three Bears.''
</P>
<P>
   While the company so far has avoided the expensive temptation to
develop a nationwide distribution infrastructure, the Alaska
expansion could make it more tempting. Because books about Alaskan
intrigue people everywhere, ``you have this very ripe opportunity
to distribute Alaska titles anywhere in the country,'' said Haight.
</P>
<P>
   When Sasquatch began distributing Paws IV titles, ``sales were
so strong that we knew it was a great fit right from the start,''
said Haight. ``We plan to change little, if anything about Paws IV.
Every region has its own personality. Sasquatch is one of the few
publishers to faithfully publish for a regional audience. We have
stretched our boundaries, but we intend to stay true to the
concept.''
</P>
<P>
   The privately held company will not release financial figures.
But Haight says Sasquatch has grown 30 to 50 percent every year
since its founding in 1986. Haight owns the company with Susan and
Furman Moseley, who is a retired president of Simpson Investment
Co.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1986 that David Brewster, then publisher of the
Seattle Weekly, sought out ideas to expand and capitalize on the
Weekly franchise. Haight suggested going beyond guidebooks and the
company began to grow. In 1995, the publishers of Seattle Weekly,
which included Brewster, sold Sasquatch to Haight and the Moseleys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
