<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITH-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO EASE DIFFICULT WORKPLACE CONVERSATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone' had them. Everyone dreads them.
</P>
<P>
   They're difficult conversations. Whether it's delivering
criticism to an employee, asking for a raise, or firing someone,
the workplace is filled with hazardous negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ways to make such conversations less
anxiety-provoking and more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Stone and Bruce Patton, both lawyers with the Harvard
Negotiation Project, have had more than their share of such
conversations. In the course of their careers, however, they've
discovered that people tend to make the same kinds of mistakes
whenever the stakes are high and they feel vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A difficult conversation is anything you dread talking about,
that keeps you up at night in anticipation and that you have no
confidence is going to go well,'' said Patton, co-author with Stone
and Sheila Heen, of ``Difficult Conversations; How to Discuss What
Matters Most,'' (Viking, 1999, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every difficult conversation is really three conversations at
once,'' Stone said. These three get mixed up in ways that confuse
people and make it difficult to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   The first involves the substance of what happened. The substance
conversation looks at who did what and how we got here, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second underlying conversation involves feelings.
</P>
<P>
   At work, people are taught to ``check their feelings at the
door,'' Stone said. ``People try to check them, but they leak out
in other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Feelings come out in tone of voice, or in actions, such as
avoiding working with certain people, or talking behind their
backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody with a job knows (the workplace) is fraught with
feelings,'' Patton said. ``The question is not whether there are
feelings involved, but how are you going to have them at work.''
</P>
<P>
   People tend to disguise their feelings as judgments when they're
in the throes of a difficult conversation. Telling someone their
actions are selfish is a judgment. Telling someone you felt hurt by
their actions is a feeling. Since people respond better to feelings
than judgments and it's important to sort them out before you talk.
</P>
<P>
   The third conversation underlying any difficult talk is the
``identity conversation,'' Patton said. Any time you're having
trouble with a particular conversation, it's probably because it
involves some aspect of your own self-image.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you're a boss who has to let someone go, but you don't
think of yourself as someone who is unkind, or who fails at
spotting talent. Having to fire someone is bound to generate
conflicts on both counts.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy for dealing with a difficult encounter is to think
through each of the three underlying conversations. What happened,
what feelings it brought up, and what aspect of your self-identity
might be under attack.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to consider what you want to accomplish in the
conversation. Maybe you want the other person to understand your
point of view. Maybe you want an apology. Maybe you want to solve a
problem. Knowing what you want will help you stay focused.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to get information.
</P>
<P>
   Most people attack a difficult conversation from their own point
of view, Stone said. It's important to spend some time figuring out
how the other party might view things.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can approach them by saying, `I know my story here, but
there's a whole bunch of stuff I don't know,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to reframe the conversation into an inquiry, a
chance to learn new information that could change the way you view
the situation and affect the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people at work play a kind of blame roulette,'' said
Patton. The objective is to find the person who screwed up and then
tell them it can't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's never just one person (to blame),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake people make when trying to have a difficult
conversation is assuming that they are right, Patton said. But
difficult conversations aren't about getting all the facts right,
they are about understanding conflicting perceptions, feelings and
values.
</P>
<P>
   Spending some time in advance thinking about how the other
person views the situation will also help you when you initiate the
conversation, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Every story has three sides _ the way you see it, the way the
other person sees it, and the way it would be perceived from the
``outside.''
</P>
<P>
   This so-called ``third story'' is the way a mediator might
describe what's going on, he said. It doesn't involve judgments
about who is right or wrong, but describes the issues on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Starting from the third story is a good neutral place to begin a
difficult conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to leap into problem solving,'' Stone said.
``First you need understanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
