<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKPACKS-STUDENTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTEN UP ON BACKPACKS, STUDENTS, PARENTS TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DEBERA CARLTON HARRELL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a spinal twist to education reform, more and more
kids are literally stooping to conquer.
</P>
<P>
   Youngsters, some carrying half their body weight in overloaded
backpacks, have become unwitting beasts of burden, some physicians
and chiropractors say.
</P>
<P>
   Their message to kids and parents: Lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about increasing numbers of kids with head, neck,
shoulder and back pain _ and worried about potential long-term
spinal problems _ some chiropractors in the Seattle area are
launching a public awareness campaign starting in the Bellevue,
Wash. School District later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The American and the International Chiropractic associations
have endorsed the non-profit ``Backpack Safety America'' campaign,
which already is under way in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The trend of kids from kindergarten through high school carrying
too much stuff in their backpacks is evident on any campus,
according to chiropractors, physicians and school administrators.
</P>
<P>
   With more books, after-school activities and less time between
classes to go to lockers, some kids carry not just classroom
supplies, but gym clothes, athletic shoes, water bottles,
calculators, CD players, cell phones and even inline skates and
skateboards, physicians and chiropractors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backpacks have become self-contained life-support systems for
adolescents,'' said Howard King, a pediatric spine physician with
Northwest Spine and Pediatric Orthopedic Surgeons and a clinical
associate professor in orthopedics at the University of Washington
Medical Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who climb Mount Rainier and Mount Everest don't have
as much weight on their shoulders, even with 45-pound packs, as
these kids,'' King said, adding that climbers, unlike most
schoolchildren, use frame packs with waist straps designed to
transfer weight to their pelvises.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a simple but entertaining 8-minute video and numerous
``do's'' and ``don't's,'' chiropractors Sheri Sherwood-Bolton and
husband Brett Bolton have received permission to visit Bellevue
schools to promote the backpack campaign. They want to persuade
kids _ and their parents _ not to carry backpacks that weigh more
than 15 percent of their body weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense tells us that a heavy load, distributed
improperly or unevenly, day after day, is indeed going to cause
stress to a growing spinal column,'' Sherwood-Bolton said, adding
that she has been seeing more patients at a younger age suffering
from non-traumatic back pain.
</P>
<P>
   The pain is not caused by accident or injury, Sherwood-Bolton
said, but from the stress of carrying too much weight in a backpack
or not loading or wearing the backpack properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old adage, `as the twig is bent, so grows the tree' comes
to mind,'' Sherwood-Bolton said. Teaching kids good habits early in
life ``could eliminate a lot of pain and grief later in life,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   King said he also has seen an increase in the number of kids
complaining of shoulder, neck and back pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We truly have seen more kids with vague upper neck and back
pain. It's not severe, but a 12-year-old with back pain is not a
normal thing,'' King said. ``When you point out how heavy their
backpacks are and encourage them to lighten their load, ... the
pain usually goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   King said he and his associates weigh kids' backpacks. One girl
who weighed 90 pounds was carrying a 29-pound pack _ one-third her
body weight, King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about scoliosis or spinal deformities forming
from backpack use,'' King said. ``But it's not a bad idea to make
people aware that they don't need to carry everything they own on
their backs and shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bolton's Bellevue office, Melissa Hendrix, 14, a Highland
Middle School student, offered her backpack for a weigh-in
Thursday. Injured in a car accident last November, Melissa
aggravated the injury by carrying a backpack that was too heavy.
But even though she trimmed her previous 45-pound pack to 35
pounds, it's still too heavy for her body weight, Sherwood-Bolton
said.
</P>
<P>
   A 974-page American history book, a 726-page science book and a
552-page French book _ all hardback and homework for the night _
made up the bulk of a pack that weighs more than two average
bowling balls. (An average bowling ball and an average human head,
Sherwood-Bolton said, each weigh about 16
</P>
<P>
   pounds.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It has helped to be more aware, but it's hard to cut down when
the books are all required,'' Melissa said. ``I'll catch myself
leaning forward, and by the end of the day, my back will be killing
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood-Bolton said when the heavy backpack pulls down and back
on Melissa's shoulders, the girl's head compensates by tilting
foward, further straining the neck, shoulders and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It completely alters the mechanics of the spine,'' Brett
Bolton
</P>
<P>
   said.
</P>
<P>
   Tips for relieving stress from backpacks
</P>
<P>
   -Choose the correct size backpack for your body size. A backpack
with a waist strap helps distribute weight evenly.
</P>
<P>
   -The maximum weight of the loaded backpack should not exceed 15
percent of body weight. Pack only what is necessary. If the
backpack forces the wearer to bend forward, it's overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   -Lift correctly. Face the pack; bend at the knees; use both
hands and check the weight of the pack; lift with your legs. Apply
one shoulder strap, then the other. Don't sling the backpack onto
one shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   -Wear it right: Use both shoulder straps, snug but not too
tight.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Backpack Safety America
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
