<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2186 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-JOCKEY-RETIRES-HN     04-09 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-JOCKEY-RETIRES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN OF THOROUGHBRED RACING CALLS IT QUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT GRAVES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAMAICA, N.Y. _ The queen of thoroughbred racing is abdicating
her throne.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone, far and away the most successful female rider in
racing history, said Thursday that she would compete in her last
race April 18 at Lone Star Park near Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Krone cited a ``constellation of reasons'' in announcing her
retirement, not the least of which was a series of injuries that
have damaged her physical ability and her psychological health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go out on top. I'm only 35, I don't want to get
hurt anymore, and I don't have anything to prove,'' said Krone, the
only female rider to win a Triple Crown race.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months after her greatest triumph, aboard
Colonial Affair in the 1993 Belmont Stakes, Krone suffered a severe
ankle fracture in a spill at Saratoga Race Course on closing day.
</P>
<P>
   The ankle required two plates and 14 screws to reconstruct. Two
weeks after having the screws removed, Krone broke both hands in a
fall at Gulfstream Park in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Krone regained her effectiveness only this past winter, when she
raced at the Fair Grounds in New Orleans for the first time. She
finished third in the jockey standings, but she said a frightening
incident in the starting gate in mid-February made her realize it
was time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse reared up and was just smashing me like this,'' she
said, banging her hands together. ``I hurt my knee and my stomach,
and I couldn't hardly ride for three days; my ankle hurt so much. I
would go to sleep and have jumpy dreams after that. Way down deep,
I knew I didn't want to fall again.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone, a 4-foot-10-inch, 100-pound favorite of fans everywhere
was adamant that her decision is final.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Christian, and it's so intense to make this decision
that there's no chance of me riding again after the 18th,'' Krone
said. ``Physically, I'm not capable of riding anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone, who lives in New Jersey, said she wants to take a break,
but hopes to pursue other interests, including TV analysis. She
said she also plans to return to school and possibly get a
psychology degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'm not retiring from the work world; it's just a
job change. I've been working since I was 17,'' said Krone, who
didn't rule out a second career in training horses.
</P>
<P>
   Krone is married to Matt Muzikar of Saratoga Springs, N.Y., and
she indicated the couple might build a house not far from the track
she loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she'll be missed by racing in general and Saratoga
specifically,'' said Glen Mathes, a spokesman for the New York
Racing Association. ``She was a great role model, especially for
young girls. She contributed a lot to the community and racing, and
we hope she will continue to do that in a different capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone won for the first time aboard Lord Farkle at Tampa Bay
Downs on Feb. 12, 1981. She has 3,541 victories to date, more than
three times as many wins as Donna Barton, who is second all-time
among female jockeys. Krone's mounts have collected more than $81
million in purses. Barton, who is retired, had 1,130 wins and
$19,084,603 in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For (Krone) to win 3,500 races is pretty remarkable,'' said
Hall of Fame trainer Allen Jerkens, who sent plenty of business
Krone's way over the years. ``She always worked hard, especially in
the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Krone also rode several stakes winners for Hall of Famer Scotty
Schulhofer, including Colonial Affair, Rubiano, Tactical Advantage
and Montreal Marty.
</P>
<P>
   One August day in 1987, Krone brought home a track-record-tying
six winners on a card at Monmouth Park in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Her dominance at Monmouth and The Meadowlands in the late 1980s
eventually led Krone to New York and Florida, where she quickly
became a fan favorite as well as a successful jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Krone won the riding title at Gulfstream in 1992 and 1993 and
also won the Belmont Park Spring Meet title in 1992. She often rode
day-night cards between New York and New Jersey, but one of her
greatest moments came at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Belmont, which doesn't really count, I'd have to say
my biggest moment was winning five races at Saratoga,'' Krone said.
</P>
<P>
   That was on Aug. 20, 1993. Ten days later she was in a hospital
bed with a severely injured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tony, my valet, brought me the five-win picture in the
hospital before my ankle surgery, I couldn't stop crying,'' Krone
recalled. ``It was like going from the very best of it to the very
worst of it; the top to the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone always was a well-respected wet-track and turf rider, but
her career wasn't the same after her second serious spill. She
appeared to be making a comeback this winter, winning 84 races at
the New Orleans track, but by then, it was more than a game of
winning and losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember reading a magazine article about an Olympic runner
who was tired of training,'' Krone said. ``She went to the Olympics
and broke three records. I felt like that after Louisiana; I just
wanted to get it over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go to sleep at night thinking, `I just can't wait to
get this over. I just don't want to do this anymore.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
