<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-LAKE-PLACID-$ADV1     04-09 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LAKE-PLACID-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPRESSION, WARM SPELL DOGGED THE FIRST LAKE PLACID GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ It was wrought with controversy, hampered by
the warmest weather ever recorded and handcuffed by the worldwide
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1932 Winter Olympic Games in the tiny Adirondack
Mountains village of Lake Placid also gave the United States its
own winter sports mecca, a status the village clings to more than
67 years later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, three narrow, windy, two-lane roads were the only land
routes into and out of Lake Placid, proving that some things never
change. The population is about the same now as it was when the
village found its way onto the world's map.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lake Placid hasn't grown, its legacy certainly has.
</P>
<P>
   Women's bobsledding still is not part of the Winter Olympics.
But New York's first lady, Eleanor Roosevelt, already decades ahead
of her time, caused a stir at the opening ceremonies by jumping
into a bobsled and demanding to be driven down the track at the
Mount VanHoevenberg complex.
</P>
<P>
   Women's speed skating was introduced as a demonstration sport
that year, 28 years before its athletes competed for medals.
Curling and sled-dog racing also were demonstration sports in Lake
Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most recognizable athletes of that era, Norwegian
skating goddess Sonja Henie and U.S. bobsledder Billy Fiske, both
won gold medals at Lake Placid. Henie would win her third
consecutive gold medal at 23 at the 1936 Games. Fiske later became
the first American to join Britain's Royal Air Force in World War
II and died a hero in the Battle of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Henie and Fiske left indelible marks with their achievements in
Lake Placid. So did Jack Shea, Lake Placid's native son, who won
the first gold medal awarded in the Games as champion of the
500-meter speed-skating competition and later won the 1,500-meter
race.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps Lake Placid's biggest Olympic hero wasn't even an
athlete. His name was Godfrey Dewey, and he was the force behind
Lake Placid's successful bid to play host to the 1932 Winter
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey was the son of Melvil Dewey, owner of the elite Lake
Placid Club and developer of the Dewey Decimal System.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey Dewey was a one-man presentation team when the
International Olympic Committee met in Lausanne, Switzerland, in
early 1929 to hear the bids for the 1932 Games. Officially, five
locations offered bids for review: Montreal; Oslo, Norway; a
collective effort from Great Britain; Yosemite National Park; and
Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   The two American sites were the front-runners going in, and
``Dewey felt hopelessly outnumbered,'' said Mary McKenzie, who was
a 17-year-old secretary for the 1932 Lake Placid Olympic Committee,
in a 1994 interview.
</P>
<P>
   There is no record of what exactly Dewey said in that 1929
meeting. The consensus is that he presented plenty of facts and,
when necessary, bluffed.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey addressed the IOC at length about Lake Placid's proud
half-century as a winter sports haven. He spoke of ice-harness
racing, the town's passion for ice skating and how Lake Placid had
organized a town hockey team at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about his father's decision to keep his Lake Placid
Club resort open during the winter of 1904. That was the year when
skiing came to Lake Placid for the first time, as Melvil Dewey
ordered several pairs of skis from Norwegian businesses and invited
club members back to Lake Placid to determine whether fun could be
had in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   As the younger Dewey detailed for the committee, Lake Placid
evolved during the 25 years after that weekend folly into a
world-class site for national and international winter sports
events, such as ski jumping and cross-country skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Dewey _ who carried the U.S. flag into the stadium during
opening ceremonies for the 1928 Winter Games in St. Moritz,
Switzerland _ also vowed Lake Placid would build an indoor arena
capable of hosting figure skating and ice hockey and would
construct what would be the United States' first bobsled track.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Placid was awarded the bid to host the third Winter Olympic
Games on April 10, 1929. Then the fun really began.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Depression started six months later, spurring rumors
that the Games would be postponed or canceled because many nations
did not have enough money to send their athletes to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, 350 or so athletes from 17 nations came to
Lake Placid, but about half of the competitors were from the United
States or Canada. Crowds during the 10-day period were estimated at
about 10,000, filling hotels and boarding houses. Many visitors
skied to and from venues to avoid the automotive logjams.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks before Feb. 4-13, 1932, there was an unanticipated
absence from the Olympics: snow.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 17, 1931, heavy snow blanketed the Lake Placid region
and was believed to be a harbinger of a long, hard winter to come.
But what followed were the most unusual weather conditions recorded
by the Lake Placid weather bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The ground had bare spots. The Hudson River did not freeze over
for the first time since at least the mid-1700s. Snow had to be
trucked in from Canada, and volunteers tobogganed snow from high
terrain to cover dangerous areas on ski trails. Even the bobsled
competition was postponed until after the closing ceremonies
because of rainy weather and temperatures near 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Every event was staged, despite the weather. And despite
worldwide financial turmoil, many of the premier athletes in the
world found their way to Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henie won the gold medal in women's figure skating by a narrow
margin over 11-year-old Ceceilia Colledge of Great Britain, who,
appropriately, wore a silver-colored dress during the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary Finnish speed-skater Clas Thunberg, who came to Lake
Placid ready to compete, refused to take part because he disagreed
with a rule change that required skaters to race pack-style against
one another rather than in pairs against the clock. Ultimately, he
won his protest: Pack-style skating was dropped after the 1932
Games, but not before Shea, who made an arduous five-hour car ride
from his college studies at Dartmouth to come home and compete, and
Irving Jaffee each won two gold medals for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers, a group composed mainly of Lake Placid businessmen,
would lose millions of dollars building a new stadium and two other
major venues for the Games. However, even before the 1930s ended,
the village was already plotting how to bring the Olympics back to
Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight years later, that dream came to fruition, and
although television had dramatically changed the face of the
Olympics, the face of Lake Placid remained essentially the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
