<HEADER>
A2233 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX     04-09 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public must demand legislature toughen educational standards
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Politicians talk a good game when it comes to
improving public education _ identified as the political hot-button
issue this year.
</P>
<P>
   All that bold talk about the critical need to improve public
education turns to Jell-O when politicians get around to enacting
meaningful reforms.
</P>
<P>
   About as bold as most lawmakers get is to give away public
school funds to private, parochial or charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   A better solution would be to fix, not transfer, the problems
that have been allowed to develop in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Few politicians or public officials, however, are willing to put
their big talk into action when the time comes to approve the
salaries that would attract and keep quality school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and public officials tuck tail and run when the
subject of weak teacher education programs is mentioned.
Intellectually feeble schools of education _ teacher mills _ have
remained largely unchanged for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers go all wobbly when education reformers mention the
need to test teachers to see if the people in charge of educating
the nation's children possess the basic skills needed to teach
assigned classroom courses.
</P>
<P>
   School teachers are models. Teachers who misspell words on the
blackboard, cannot solve simple math problems or use improper
grammar should be found out and fired.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers should ratchet up teacher pay in step with tougher
teacher standards and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of higher standards, it's been obvious for years that
America's public school students need to be held to higher
standards.
</P>
<P>
   America's young people have been graduating from high school
with excellent grades only to find that they score so poorly on
college-entrance examinations that the Scholastic Assessment Test
was dumbed down. Colleges across the nation have been forced to
fund an explosion of remedial programs for entering freshmen who
failed to learn enough to take first-year college courses.
</P>
<P>
   By giving students inflated grades, little homework and
undeserved promotions, America's young people graduated with high
self-esteem but tested at the bottom of all industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's quite another matter to get public officials to
actually increase academic standards and require objective,
standardized measurements to determine if learning has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier to talk about school prayer, vouchers, charter
schools, school uniforms, local control and other subjects rather
than require high standards and top-to-bottom accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians would rather talk about the importance of improving
public education than actually requiring it because they know if
they demand the best they will have to pay for the best.
</P>
<P>
   It's much easier to talk a good game while keeping public
education funding low enough to promise tax cuts. Besides, by
shifting some of the current funding to private and church schools,
perhaps someone else will solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Not all politicians and public officials run from the
accumulated problems that plague many of the nation's public
schools. With luck, public support will swing behind those
courageous politicians who are willing to put actions and funds
behind their words.
</P>
<P>
   Texas and North Carolina have begun to make steps toward raising
student standards and putting in place the beginnings of an
accountability system. Much more needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians who talk a good game when it comes to improving
public education know that there's no such thing as a free lunch.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for lawmakers and public education officials to
recognize that education is like everything else in life _ you get
quality when you demand quality. And you get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway's columns appear on Wednesdays and Fridays.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
