<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      04-09 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVROLET RETIRES ITS 2-DOOR TAHOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Chevy's full-size, two-door sport-utility vehicle,
beloved for three decades by hunters, campers and cruising
teenagers, goes the way of the dodo after this year.
</P>
<P>
   The two-door Chevy Tahoe, formerly called the Chevy Blazer
before that name was downsized to a compact, is a big, brawny
heavyweight based on the Chevy half-ton pickup with a shortened
wheelbase, two rows of seats and a utility body.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of sport-utility vehicles, the first-generation Blazer
was the original Tonka Toy, a way for adolescents and young
grown-ups to relive their sandbox fantasies, only life-size. But
its compromises as a large, somewhat ungainly two-door utility
truck made it a niche vehicle, overshadowed in recent years by the
four-door sport utes that are popping up everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The big two-doors, including the erstwhile full-size Ford Bronco
and Dodge Power Ram, are a dying breed, and the departure after the
'99 model year of the two-door Tahoe leaves their ranks empty.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, everything changes for Tahoe, Yukon and Suburban as a
new generation of full-size GM sport utes are hustled in. New look,
new suspension, two new engines and the general upgrades afforded
the acclaimed Silverado pickups will be rolled out for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   No two-door Tahoe is planned. So this is the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the longer, heavier four-door Tahoe, the two-door
drives sportier, if such a term can be applied to a
two-and-half-ton truck. This is the funmobile Tahoe, aimed at a
younger population, who couldn't care less if it has four doors to
ease access to the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, climbing into the back seat can be a real hardship,
especially in the four-wheel-drive version tested here, because of
its increased ride height. Once back there, it's plenty roomy and
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   GM could have come up with a third-door arrangement, similar to
what's available on the Saturn coupe, which would have made this
shortened version more palatable to people who actually wanted to
use their back seats.
</P>
<P>
   The driver and front-seat passenger will find the short Tahoe to
be as comfortable as any Suburban or stretch-cab pickup. For
extra-tall drivers like me, these behemoths are a perfect fit,
though shorter drivers also should appreciate the extra elbowroom.
Lots of headroom for a 10-gallon hat, too.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is very roomy and comfortable, and the thronelike
driving height creates a panoramic view of traffic or scenery. The
dashboard is the same as the pickup or Suburban, and generally, all
the sensory inputs driving the Tahoe are about the same as its
bigger brethren. The ride is a bit jouncier than the rest of the
group because of the shorter wheelbase.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the full-size Blazers and two-door Tahoes you see
bouncing down the road have been jacked-up, with huge tires and
plenty of attitude. Chevrolet's Z71 off-road package, which
includes huge all-terrain tires on custom-looking wheels, speaks to
that market. This is only a $400 option on the Tahoe, and certainly
worth it if you're planning on doing some boondocking. Or
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The big expense on our tester was $5,700 over base for a
preferred equipment group, including leather seats and a full boat
of comfort and convenience features, including full power
accessories and a decent stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Tahoe was reasonably nice to drive, the handling
does feel squirrelly, especially on curving roads where you have to
stay on top of things to keep it from wandering off on its own.
Cornering takes some skill and finesse. The steering is a bit too
light and numb, especially considering the size of the vehicles,
though its response is quick.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't get a chance to take the Tahoe off-road this time, but
I have in the past. It will take you anywhere you want to go with
ease.
</P>
<P>
   The standard engine is big and powerful, scooting the
heavyweight from a standstill with a rush. It's a thirsty beast,
though, slurping down the gasoline with great enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Tahoe is a good choice as a towing mule, and you can
see plenty of them on any weekend hitched up to boat trailers. The
sturdy automatic transmission is built for such heavy labor.
</P>
<P>
   All four-wheel-drive functions are push-button, a $400 option,
including an automatic setting that decides electronically whether
to add torque to the front wheels, depending on road conditions.
</P>
<P>
   With its load of options, the test Tahoe hit the $35,000, scary
territory for a Chevy. There's lots of choices out there at this
price.
</P>
<P>
   The two-door Tahoe, nee Blazer, was always a vehicle with lots
of blue-collar appeal, though the entry fee has gone decidedly
uptown. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chevrolet Tahoe &QL; 
- Vehicle type: &QL; 
Five-passenger, two-door sport-utility vehicle, rear/four-wheel
drive. &QL; 
- Base price: &QL; 
$26,500. &QL; 
- Price as tested: &QL; 
$34,993. &QL; 
- Engine: &QL; 
5.7-liter V-8, 255 horsepower at 4,600 rpm, 330 pound-feet of
torque at 2,800 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: &QL; 
Four-speed automatic. &QL; 
- Curb weight: &QL; 
4,876 pounds. &QL; 
- Wheelbase: &QL; 
111.5 inches. &QL; 
- EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
12 city, 16 highway. &QL; 
- Highs: &QL; 
Sporty appeal. Interior comfort. Off-road prowess. &QL; 
- Lows: &QL; 
Fuel ``economy.'' Back-seat entry. Dicey handling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at bob.golfen(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
