<HEADLINE>
TOOLS OF THE TRADE FOR GREAT GARNISHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANITA MABANTE LEACH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The right tools are essential for the finer work that
goes into garnishing. You can't expect to take a large chef's
knife, for example, and successfully render a carrot flower.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Ben Leach used a trio of small paring knives to do many of
the garnishes explained in this story. Buy these tools at a
reputable cooking store and you will have them for many years of
garnishing. Shown from the top, clockwise, are:
</P>
<P>
   - V-groove cutter for melons and citrus.
</P>
<P>
   - Grooved citrus cutter.
</P>
<P>
   - Paring knife.
</P>
<P>
   - A crinkle-cut slicer (for carrots and cucumbers).
</P>
<P>
   - Melon baller.
</P>
<P>
   - Serrated V-groove cutter (for citrus segments).
</P>
<P>
   - Serrated vegetable peeler.
</P>
<P>
   - Small acrylic paintbrush and pastry brush (for painting
chocolate leaves and clear fruit glazes). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
