A2245 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRYSTALGAYLE-MUSIC-AZ     04-09 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRYSTALGAYLE-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES, VELCRO, HAIR CARE: A CHAT WITH CRYSTAL GAYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - If you're over the age of 25, there are some things
you probably know about Crystal Gayle: She's got a ton of country
hits, a beautiful voice, a famous sister (Loretta Lynn) and some
absurdly long hair that she could sweep the floor with if she
wished. But who knew she hated Velcro?
</P>
<P>
   At age 48, the former Brenda Gail Webb is as busy as ever. She's
currently working on two albums _ one a collection of standards,
the other a long-promised duet disc with her big sis. Just having
gotten back from a relaxing weeklong cruise with her
manager/husband and two teenage kids, she was in a playful mood to
answer questions that were a little . . well, unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: &UR; Your first top-10 hit was ``Wrong Road Again.'' When was
the last time you got lost?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: Actually, I got lost on the cruise. I (begin ital)
always (end ital) got lost on the cruise. I could never find my way
to the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Do fans still check to see what color your eyes are?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: (sighing) All the time, ever since ``Don't It Make My
Brown Eyes Blue.'' ``I thought your eyes were brown!'' I tell them
that they used to be but they changed color because of the song.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Weirdest question a fan ever asked you?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: I try to block them out. Once, one of them asked me
what the definition of love was. I was like, ``Wait a minute _
isn't that a very broad question?''
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Last good movie you saw?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: On the cruise, every time I turned on the TV they were
showing ``(There's) Something About Mary.'' I am so sick of that
movie, so it's not that. I love intrigue and suspense movies. That
one with Denzel Washington and Gene Hackman (``Crimson Tide'') _
that was fabulous. And Charles Bronson is my hero. I like action _
I don't want to cry in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: As someone with a famous sibling, who do you prefer: Don
or Phil Everly?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: That's hard! (laughing) You're trying to be mean now. I
have to pick both of them because I'm trying to be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Your Tempe (Ariz.) shows (she will perform two shows
April 11 at the Red River Music Hall) are the same day as Andrea
Bocelli's Phoenix debut. MTV's ``Celebrity Deathmatch,'' you
against the tenor: Who wins?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: Me, of course. I would just hit him a few times with my
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Since you brought it up, what kind of shampoo?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: I tend to use different shampoos. Lately, I've been
using quite a bit of L'Oreal. I tend to use whatever's available _
it's not like I can let it go for a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Do you ever get your hair caught in things?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: What I hate the most is Velcro. My hair will get stuck
on Velcro on belts and purses and things like that. I have to be
careful around Velcro. If the TV remote control has Velcro on the
back, little bits of my hair will wind up on it. I've lost a lot of
hair to Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: Allen Reynolds, who produced many of your greatest
records, also produces Garth Brooks _ any advice for Garth on his
new baseball career?
</P>
<P>
   Crystal: Tell him to bat left-handed. And if he wants someone to
record with, I'm here. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at randy.cordova(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
