<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOCELLI-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      04-09 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOCELLI-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOCELLI: PHENOM OF THE OPERA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA AND KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Andrea Bocelli is blessed with a very distinctive form
of popularity. That is, people either seem to fall at his feet in
worship or hate the ground he walks on.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the 40-year-old tenor so far has sold more than 14
million albums. His fourth disc, a collection of Italian pop epics
dubbed ``Sogno,'' was released last week. He has almost sold out
America West Arena for his first Phoenix appearance; even a $500
ticket price didn't seem to deter hungry fans. His accessible style
has brought people to opera who normally would shy away from the
mere concept.
</P>
<P>
   But that's where it starts to get as fuzzy as the stubble on
Bocelli's chin. Classical purists aren't exactly singing the
praises of the guy. While ``Sogno'' and his massive-selling
``Romanza'' disc are basically pop offerings, his other two solo
albums were straight opera releases. And die-hard opera fans aren't
exactly fond of his technique, which lacks the polish and finesse
of the genre's greats.
</P>
<P>
   Pop music writer Randy Cordova and Classical music writer
Kenneth LaFave took a listen to ``Sogno'' before discussing the
pros and cons of Bocelli.
</P>
<P>
   Ken: I hope I won't disappoint you by being less spiteful than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   There are two issues: the music and the musician. I think I
understand the appeal of the latter, and I'm all but certain I
understand the appeal of the former.
</P>
<P>
   My critical calls regarding either are not so important, I
think, as the reasons Bocelli and the music he sings are loved.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: I agree. And I think part of the whole deal with the
Bocelli phenomenon _ and it is a phenomenon _ has to do with the
way the singer has been marketed and presented. In many ways, he
allows those who otherwise have little tolerance for the fine arts
to indulge and feel like they are somehow connecting with their
refined, gentler side. That's why you hear so many people saying
things like, ``I don't like classical music, but that Andrea
Bocelli _ wow!''
</P>
<P>
   Ken: And, Andrea Bocelli is attractive to the ladies, with a
face halfway between cute and dangerous. Then there's the
``he's-blind-but-look-how-he's-overcome-his-handicap'' thing, which
may be politically incorrect to observe but is too obvious to be
avoided. He sings mostly romantic-cum-sentimental repertory with a
very pleasant, if not always secure, voice. Package those elements
with the proper marketing, get the imprimatur of PBS, and there's a
mansion with your name on it and a Maserati in the driveway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And, he's a lot better than Michael Bolton.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: That's for sure. But I'm surprised that you sound like
you actually like Bocelli.
</P>
<P>
   Ken: Am I a fan? No. Do I resent him? No. But any pleasure I
might get from Bocelli's singing is undermined by his lack of pitch
focus. I can't always trust that the next note I hear will be in
tune. Sometimes, I can safely assume he'll be (begin ital) out (end
ital) of tune _ and I'm proven right.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: That may be true, but I don't think that affects the
listening pleasure for the average pop fan. Popular music is full
of singers that are technically awful, so most people are used to
voices that are full of imperfections. And Bocelli sounds
positively heavenly next to most pop singers, with his sweet,
quietly radiant tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Ken: The pop songs Bocelli sings seem meant to imitate the
operatic attitude _ the pleasant chords, the heroic melodies _ and
also a feeling of gentle restlessness, like wanting to go on a trip
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Current pop culture offers instead a selection of attitudes. You
got your hip-hop attitude, your rock and roll attitude, your pop
attitude, your country attitude, etc. This is the addition of
another attitude. Call it the opera 'tude, a shadow of its
namesake, but still more or less aiming in that direction. One can
only hope that people sampling this weak tea will go on to better,
stronger stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Randy: But the people who enjoy Bocelli for what he is _ a pop
star with a quasi-operatic style _ probably have no real interest
in the stronger stuff. If they did, they would have discovered the
real thing six years ago. When those singing monks made Gregorian
chants all the rage a few years ago, it didn't spark a hotbed of
new fans for centuries-old religious tunes. I think Bocelli's fans
are going to enjoy Bocelli the same way they enjoy Will Smith or
Barbra Streisand or Smashing Pumpkins or whoever else is in their
collection. Because ultimately, he is a pop star _ one with a
grand, melodramatic style _ but still a pop star. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
