<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLYJOEL-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      04-09 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLYJOEL-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAY GOODBYE TO PIANO MAN, HELLO TO MAESTRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Billy Joel has had so many hits over such a long
period of time, it's difficult to imagine the pop-music landscape
without him. Yet that's exactly what may happen after his current
``Greatest Hits'' tour wraps up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say this is the end of something,'' Joel said
last year in an interview with CNN. ``But I don't think I'm going
to do any more long tours after this tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The thing that seems to be occupying much of his time in recent
years is composing instrumental music for piano and orchestra.
Though no recordings have yet to appear, he has stated his
intentions several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't walked away from rock and roll,'' he said in a 1997
interview on National Public Radio. ``I'm just concentrating on
writing orchestral and piano pieces. . . This is where my interest
is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does become a full-time member of the tux-and-tails
brigade, it may mean the end of an era. Or it could simply be
another era in the wide-ranging history of Joel. From a distance,
his career looks like one long string of recognizable tunes, from
1974's ``Piano Man'' to 1993's ``River of Dreams.'' But he has
encompassed several different personalities and styles within that
span:
</P>
<P>
   The Tin Pan Alley Era _ This is perhaps Joel's most beloved
phase, which found him a lot closer to Cole Porter than to Paul
McCartney. In the early '70s, Joel was a rocker who did not rock.
Instead, he was known for his sharply literate songs that featured
instantly hummable melodies. Think of ``Piano Man,'' with its
familiar chorus and Broadway-esque story line. The song almost
sounds like the missing link from some long-ago theater production.
</P>
<P>
   Another highlight from this period is ``Just the Way You Are,''
a lounge-music standard with an oddly sexist lyric: ``I don't want
clever conversation . . . I love you just the way you are'' _ yes,
illiterate dummies make the best romantic partners. But people
overlooked the sentiment and embraced the song.
</P>
<P>
   Other Tin Pan-esque tunes include ``New York State of Mind''
(covered by the queen of Tin Pan Alley, Babs Streisand) and ``The
Entertainer,'' a dark look at the rock-star life driven by some
rollicking piano licks.
</P>
<P>
   The Leather Jacket Era _ The cover of 1980's ``Glass Houses''
said it all: Billy could rock. Well, Billy thought he could rock,
anyway. The disc, which spent six weeks at No. 1, featured Joel
throwing a rock at a glass building, perhaps a nod to him
shattering his image as a popster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Still Rock and Roll to Me'' signaled the new direction,
by de-emphasizing the piano and focusing instead on the song's
urgent rhythm track. ``Pressure,'' from ``The Nylon Curtain''
(1982), was another single that dropped the hummability, instead
going for an edgier, tenser vibe.
</P>
<P>
   The Christie Brinkley Era _ The time when almost every
red-blooded American male looked in the mirror and wondered, ``What
does Billy Joel have that I don't?'' In his ``Uptown Girl'' (1983)
video, Joel strutted with one of the most popular models in the
world. They later married and had a daughter, Alexa.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, Joel and Brinkley were the epitome of
celebrity-couple togetherness. She often was seen in the front rows
at his shows. The model even painted the cover for his ``River of
Dreams'' disc from 1996. ``(It's) a mixture _ some Expressionism,
some Impressionism. It's naive. It's, well . . . original.'' Whatta
guy!
</P>
<P>
   The couple split the following year, a bittersweet close to one
of Joel's most high-profile times. But musically, he left it with
some of his most distinctive music, including ``A Matter of Trust''
and ``I Go to Extremes.'' Then again, this era also produced the
excruciating ``We Didn't Start the Fire.'' Oh well, it's probably a
great history lesson for little Alexa.
</P>
<P>
   The Middle-of-the-Road Icon Era _ Where we stand today, when
Joel is able to sell out an arena with nothing new under his belt.
``Greatest H its Volume III'' came out more than a year ago,
featuring a number of hit songs and three new tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But what Joel offers is a hipper, less-spangly version of what
Neil Diamond gives to his audience: An astonishingly deep catalog
of familiar songs, performed with a crisp professionalism. You may
not be a fan, but it's next to impossible not to know at least a
few of his songs. And he's the kind of guy your dad loves, just as
his dad loved Perry Como. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
