<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2264 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WHO-CARES-NYTS     04-09 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WHO-CARES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 HOW ABOUT A BIT of URBAN CLEANSING?  
 &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Stop Urban Cleansing!'' __ Hand-lettered sign in the window of
a building on Orleans, just south of Division Street, in an area of
Chicago where projects are being torn down and $300,000 townhouses
are going up.
</P>
<P>
   ............................
</P>
<P>
   My teenage nephew got on the wrong bus the other day and ended
up in an unfamiliar and scary neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a bomb hit it,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I said, we've got a lot of those kinds of places in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If you've spent any time at all here _ and this is true of a lot
of big cities today _ you've seen the pockets of rubble and decay
and desolation. These areas are so bleak as to seem without hope.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you come from just such a place; maybe you live there now.
Maybe your old stomping grounds, the place where you grew up, has
turned into one of those ``bombed-out'' no man's lands.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've only seen the gravel lots and the boarded-up houses
and the crumbling projects from the relative safety of your car as
you tried to figure out how to get back on a main road or the
expressway.
</P>
<P>
   Every big city, no matter how magnificent its downtown and its
parks and its skyline, has these pockmarks. They dot the landscape
like BB holes in a stained-glass window.
</P>
<P>
   I think about such neighborhoods every time we get involved in
some conflict overseas and we try to make the world a better place,
because after all that's our job as the wealthiest and most
powerful country in modern times. I think about how readily we vow
to clean house elsewhere, when there's still a heck of a mess in
our own basement.
</P>
<P>
   Each time America jumps into a conflict, most of us have to dive
for the Atlas and dig into the handy maps provided by the
newspapers. Where's Somalia? Remind me where Kuwait is again. Can
somebody pinpoint Bosnia, Lebanon, the Panama Canal, Grenada, Iraq,
Iran?
</P>
<P>
   That's what's happening right now, on a daily basis. We read the
reports of the latest bombing or the most recent counterattack in
Yugoslavia, and we turn to the accompanying maps so we can get our
bearings. All right, I know where Skopje is, but where's Tetovo?
</P>
<P>
   And there's always a new Hitler to be defeated, or so we're
told. Amin, Ghadafi, Hussein, Milosevic. Our leaders draw the
Hitler comparison, not to insult those who remember the Holocaust,
but to provide easy shorthand for those who don't. Equating some
modern potentate-thug with the most hated man of the century is an
easy way to get the semi-interested populace emotionally involved
in the cause. If this guy is as evil as they're saying he is, we
have to step in!
</P>
<P>
   As the pictures are beamed into our living rooms, we shake our
heads at the barbarians on the other side of the world. Why are
those people still fighting one another? How can they treat their
own people like that? What kind of civilization needs to be saved
from itself?
</P>
<P>
   We conveniently forget that someone might have the same thoughts
while watching CNN's coverage of the riots in Los Angeles, or a
documentary about crack babies in Chicago, or a news report about
the murder rate in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Our world is not a simple place, and the United States of
America's place in this era is more complicated than at any time in
history. We can't just announce we're no longer the bodyguard of
underdog nations and peoples; we can't just take the $2 billion
that would be spent on the construction of a top-of-the-line
stealth fighter and redistribute it to the worst neighborhoods in
Detroit. It doesn't happen that way, and it never will.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a kind of controlled insanity in the way things
work. Americans have been told by NATO and by our president that
Kosovo is now the most important region in the world _ even though
you can find horrific examples of ethnic cleansing, oppression,
starvation and injustice in three or four dozen other areas around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Try that logic out on a 10-year-old girl who has to ride her
bike in the fence-enclosed walkways of her inner-city high-rise
because the sidewalks outside and below are too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows how long we'll stay there, and how much net value our
involvement will yield. Our track record in these affairs since
Vietnam is spotty at best. Last time I looked, Saddam Hussein was
still strutting tall and talking tough, eight years after Operation
Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   This much I'll guarantee: We'll get out of Kosovo one day, and
then we'll turn our full attention to some other godforsaken
outpost _ but it won't be the Bronx or South Central or the West
Side of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
