<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-INSURANCE-ART     04-09 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-INSURANCE-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE INSURANCE, OF SORTS, FOR MUTUAL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'd love to shoot the moon with your mutual fund, slapping
your money down on the wildest bet you can find. But, of course,
you're worried that you could lose your whole nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   If that describes your outlook, a handful of the nation's
biggest insurers have got a deal for you. Well, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   First, you pick one of their funds, from high-risk to
mild-mannered _ your choice. Then, for as little as 0.1 percent of
the investment annually or possibly as much as 0.5 percent, these
companies will guarantee that the money you put up, plus an annual
gain of 4 or 5 percent, will always be there, no matter how far the
market plunges.
</P>
<P>
   On a $50,000 investment, then, that guarantee would cost $50 to
$250 a year. Sounds good, but there is a catch: You have to die in
order to collect on the guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   What the companies are selling is life insurance tied to your
mutual fund or funds. You make a bad guess on the market, and you
will have less to spend, as usual. But under their new plans, your
gambling won't hurt your heirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what we're doing is creating peace of mind,'' said
J. Steven Neamtz at SunAmerica, where he is in charge of marketing
mutual funds, including what the company calls its Asset Protection
Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Peace of mind surely has its value. But many financial advisers
say that this is insurance that most people don't need. The reason,
they say, is that since the end of the Depression, long-term
investors in stocks have generally ended up with more than they
started with _ a lot more, actually, than if they had put their
money into absolutely-safe certificates of deposit, money funds or
almost-sure-fire bonds.
</P>
<P>
   With these new products, if your investment beats the gain
guaranteed by the insurers, you simply walk away with your higher
earnings. So an insurance company can collect premiums for years
and never have to pay out anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably makes sense for somebody who is older and wants to
take a little more risk to grow his nest egg for his family,'' said
Patrick Reinkemeyer, an analyst at Morningstar, the Chicago
financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   But, experts say, the fund insurance offers little to younger
investors with long horizons.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance is available with no questions asked about health.
That means people who are elderly or in poor health and cannot buy
ordinary life insurance at a reasonable price can insure at least
some of their assets.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced 18 months ago by American Skandia Life Assurance as a
sort of a stripped-down variable annuity, the product seems to be
an idea ahead of its time. While American Skandia and the two other
companies offering it _ SunAmerica and the Prudential Insurance
Company of America _ are effusive about its potential, customers
are not rushing to embrace the concept of fund insurance.
</P>
<P>
   SunAmerica and Prudential acknowledge that business has been
slow, but they won't say how slow. American Skandia says it has
signed up about 1,000 of the 100,000 owners of its affiliated
mutual fund accounts.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the lack of enthusiasm, the sellers say, has been
the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun isn't going to shine on this option until the market
backs off,'' said Michael Murray, who is in charge of marketing the
mutual funds of American Skandia and its version of the product,
known as AS Goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   The new investment, sometimes called a protected mutual fund,
gives you one of the most popular features of variable annuities _
a guarantee that you won't lose your initial investment _ while
eliminating other features, some positive and some negative.
</P>
<P>
   With a variable annuity, for example, you pay a penalty to the
insurance company if you withdraw your money within seven years or
so of investing it, as well as a 10 percent penalty to the federal
government if the withdrawal comes before you are 59{. With the new
product, you can cash out any time without penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the new product does not shelter your investment gains from
taxes, as variable annuities do. Your money is taxed on withdrawal,
at your then-current income tax rate. With the insured accounts,
you pay taxes on gains as you go along (as with any mutual fund),
and then pay capital gains taxes when you begin withdrawals.
Prudential alone sells the coverage in combination with
tax-deferred Individual Retirement Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Prudential and Skandia also lock in the value of an account
on the anniversary of its initial investment, as some companies do
with variable annuities. That provision can benefit investors: Say
the market drives up an original investment of $100,000 to $130,000
on its third anniversary. You die in the fourth year, when the
guaranteed value, at 5 percent, would be $121,554.94, but your
investment's market value has fallen to, say, $110,000. Your heirs
would still collect $130,000 _ some $20,000 of it free of income
tax because it is regarded as a life insurance benefit.
</P>
<P>
   With a variable annuity, finally, you can choose to have the
insurance company pay you a stream of regular payments for as long
as you live. This is known as annuitization. With the new product,
there is no annuitization option.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest complaints about variable annuities is the
costs: Insurers charge an average of about 1.24 percent of the
value of the investment for insurance and administrative expenses,
in addition to the management fees for the funds within the
annuity.
</P>
<P>
   These fees can put an enormous drag on the growth of variable
annuities, so that for the first 10 years or so, investments in
pure mutual funds almost always grow faster. As time goes on, the
variable annuity's tax deferral pushes its cumulative growth ahead
of the simple mutual fund's.
</P>
<P>
   The fees for the new fund insurance plans are much lower.
Prudential charges 0.1 percent annually for investors who are under
60 years old, 0.25 percent for those 60 to 69 and 0.5 percent for
those 70 and older. The other two companies charge everyone the
same amount: for SunAmerica, the cost is 0.2 percent annually; for
American Skandia, the fee is 0.3 percent. (Both SunAmerica and
Skandia also charge a start-up fee of $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Some investors might be discouraged from buying the new products
because the funds themselves have sales charges and, in some cases,
relatively high annual administrative charges _ expenses that cut
into returns.
</P>
<P>
   The companies, of course, do not want people to take advantage
of the guarantee by signing up right after they've had a heart
attack or a few days into what they figure is a market avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're at the blackjack table at Vegas,'' said one
insurance executive, ``you can't say, `Well, deal me a few hands;
then I'll decide whether I want to play.'''
</P>
<P>
   To improve the odds for themselves, the insurance companies
limit the period in which you can decide to insure your mutual
funds. American Skandia and SunAmerica give you 30 days from the
time you buy into their funds; Prudential gives you six months.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, with no provision for checking on people's health,
the insurers could find themselves with some pretty risky
customers. ``But so far,'' said Murray of American Skandia, ``that
hasn't been a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
