<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV11-     04-09 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE SHELF: MOM AS THE CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH STEAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   How to explain what seems to be a sudden interest in linking
family life to business management skills?
</P>
<P>
   One catalyst may be ``The Time Bind: When Work Becomes Home and
Home Becomes Work,'' Arlie Hochschild's 1997 book about the
blurring of domestic and office life. Or maybe business writers
have been mining so many other spheres for management ``wisdom'' _
including sports, Winnie the Pooh stories and the life of Jesus _
that they are low on inspiration and turning to the home in
desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, two new books attempt to put a domestic
spin on management. Taken together, they argue that managers should
listen to their moms and that moms should act as managers do.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wear Clean Underwear: Business Wisdom From Mom'' (Villard,
$22.95), Rhonda Abrams trots out business success stories and links
them to the ``familiar sayings and lessons'' of our mothers. Each
chapter revolves around a mom-ism: ``Don't Get Too Big for Your
Britches,'' ``Share'' or ``How Do You Know You Don't Like It When
You've Never Tried It?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a forgivable gimmick, perhaps. But some of the business
tales are themselves too familiar: In a chapter entitled ``It's Not
the End of the World,'' Ms. Abrams retells the story of how Post-It
Notes emerged from 3M's high tolerance for trial and error. In ``I
Don't Care Who Made This Mess, Just Clean It Up,'' she revisits
Nordstrom's commitment to customer service.
</P>
<P>
   In other chapters, she describes the much-noted quirkiness at
Southwest Airlines and the well-publicized altruism at Malden Mills
in Massachusetts, the Polartec fabric maker that kept all its
workers on the payroll while it rebuilt a factory that burned to
the ground in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mom-think is also discovered at other companies whose core
values the author admires. But even these unfamiliar stories begin
to sound the same, as the author praises this or that hiring policy
or employee motivational tactic. Also predictable are the sidebars,
in which business types talk about the wisdom they garnered from,
yes, their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abrams, a columnist for Gannett News Service and the author
of a best seller, ``The Successful Business Plan,'' is so
relentlessly upbeat in this book, in fact, that it ends up as a
collection of illustrated bromides. The mom-sayings are all benign.
(I looked in vain for the chapter called ``You'll All Be Sorry
Enough When I'm Dead.'') And the profiles are paeans to the
companies. That's what comes of listening to mom: You start to
accept that ``if you can't say something nice about someone . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   HOUSEHOLD MANAGEMENT
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, Inc.: Taking Your Work Skills Home,'' by Neale S. Godfrey
with Tad Richards (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23), tries to get harried
working mothers to manage their families by using tactics they've
learned at the office.
</P>
<P>
   The book, of course, isn't the first to suggest imposing a
business model on the home. In the early part of the century, Frank
Gilbreth, an eccentric efficiency expert, adapted ``scientific''
factory management to his household _ a lifelong experiment
described charmingly by 2 of his 12 offspring in ``Cheaper by the
Dozen,'' published in 1948. And Ms. Godfrey herself, in her earlier
book, ``Money Doesn't Grow on Trees,'' outlined a financial
services setup at home for teaching children about spending and
saving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, Inc.,'' as its title suggests, declares that ``you are
the CEO of your life'' and must manage your ``employees'' _
children and husband _ accordingly. ``At home you handle more
personnel changes than the human resources manager of a Fortune 500
company,'' the author writes, arguing that a 2-year-old becomes a
completely different ``employee'' when he or she turns 3.
</P>
<P>
   This being a modern management guide, the dreaded ``mission
statements'' are recommended, as are ``project'' teams _ for every
task.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book is belabored. Readers are encouraged to make
charts to see if solutions used at work can be found for the home;
lists must be drawn to figure out which tasks you love and which
you find ``yucky.'' (Ahem. Would a book aimed at male ``CEOs'' use
that word?) Over all, ``Mom, Inc.'' seems thin, with meat enough
for a magazine article perhaps, but not a book.
</P>
<P>
   But it is redeemed by the determination of Ms. Godfrey, formerly
a single parent of two, to give her readers some relief by teaching
them to delegate at home. This is a woman on intimate terms with
child-raising and housework. And a few of her tips _ a list of
weekly chores, for example, that can be performed by children of
various ages _ might just startle an overburdened or indulgent
working mom into action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
