<HEADER>
A2278 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETMUSIC-ROBINSON-PRO     04-09 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETMUSIC-ROBINSON-PROFILE-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MP3.COM'S MICHAEL ROBERTSON: THE MUSIC MAN OF THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEC FOEGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Hell's Bells,'' a raucous anthem by the rock group AC/DC,
blared from loudspeakers as Michael Robertson, the chief executive
of MP3.com, walked to the podium. It seemed an unlikely
introduction at last month's New York Music and Internet Expo for a
man who wore a conservative camel hair sports jacket _ and who had
an evangelical Christian background.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after his keynote speech, Robertson, a 32-year-old
entrepreneur with blond surfer looks, received warm handshakes from
teen-agers with nose rings and hip-hop artists in baggy jeans. In
the 16 months since he started his San Diego-based business, which
distributes music over the Internet with a digital compression
technology known as MP3, Robertson has been embraced by struggling
musicians as a fellow revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he says he really isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no revolutionary, I'm a purebred capitalist,'' Robertson
said later. ``I'm just talking about a new way of delivering
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Robertson is hoping that his outsider reputation will be
a plus. When he introduced his service, which enables musicians to
distribute their music cheaply over the Internet, he was virtually
ignored by top labels. But now that MP3.com offers free music from
7,000 artists and gets 250,000 visitors a day, the labels, as well
as investors, are taking notice. That brand recognition should come
in handy Tuesday, when Microsoft will introduce a rival music site
and its own compression software, MS-Audio.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson says he doesn't worry much about competition, even if
it's Microsoft. Over takeout chicken and french fries in his New
York hotel room, he asserted that in the Internet world, timing and
instincts could be as valuable as capital. It is a lesson he says
he learned observing his idol, Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it with Apple; he did it with Pixar,'' said Robertson
said. ``I've got a lot of respect for him because he zigged when
everybody else zagged, and that's what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com began two and a half years ago as the Z Company, a
Yahoo-style search engine founded by Robertson. In October 1997,
Greg Flores, now MP3.com's director of sales, showed the MP3
software to Robertson, who was impressed enough to buy the rights
to the MP3.com domain name and to rename his company.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, MP3.com had four employees, including Robertson,
working out of their homes. Last summer, it expanded into a
1,000-square-foot loft. ``We had this sign up for new employees,''
he recalled. ``It was the steps you had to do to join the company:
Order chair. Put chair together. Order desk. Put desk together.''
The business has since moved to a larger office and employs about
35 people.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Robertson's gamble appears to have paid off. In
January,  &UR; Sequoia Capital,  &LR; a venture capital firm, invested $10
million in the company. Then Tom Petty posted a new song on MP3.com
to promote an album. At the end of March, Gateway chief executive
Theodore Waitt signed on to MP3.com's board. The computer
mainstream has, in effect, signaled that Michael Robertson is the
leader in his field.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians also like Robertson's enterprise, which uses free
music as a lure to sell compact disks, because he pays a generous
50 percent royalty rate. He can pay more than the 7 to 10 percent
offered by record labels because he has none of their overhead or
distribution costs and he pays no advances. Like other commercial
sites offering free downloads, MP3.com makes money selling
advertising and marketing information about its visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics argue that Robertson has not built a viable business
model and that any free download policy can facilitate piracy. ``If
he sells music, more power to him,'' said Hilary Rosen, chief
executive and president of the Recording Industry Association of
America. ``I think it's the notion that music can be given away for
free forever and there not be a return that is the economic joke.''
</P>
<P>
   But observers like Ken Hertz, a partner in the law firm Hansen,
Jacobson, Teller &AMP; Hoberman, which represents popular acts like
Alanis Morissette and No Doubt, said the association was
misinterpreting Robertson's intentions. ``Michael Robertson is not
interested in being in the record business,'' said Hertz.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is the first to say that he is an music industry
novice. Before starting MP3.com, his main music credential was
playing clarinet in his high-school band in Huntington Beach,
Calif. He grew up in a working-class, fundamentalist household _
his late father was a handyman _ where listening to popular music
was discouraged. He graduated from the University of California at
San Diego in 1990 with a degree in cognitive science.
</P>
<P>
   After college, he started a computer consulting firm and later
sold software tools he had developed. Looking to expand, he started
Media Minds, which sold software for digital cameras _ a business
that ultimately failed. To start MP3.com, Robertson, who is married
and has two young children, took out a second mortgage on his home
in San Diego. Before receiving capital from Sequoia, he said,
MP3.com made a modest profit.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he spends most of his time traveling around the
country to meet with investment bankers, artist organizations and
other Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson anticipates a battle between his company and the
recording labels, something that has not been cause for concern so
far. ``I don't have any friends in the music industry,'' he said,
``so I didn't have to worry about upsetting anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-PACKARD-AR     04-09 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-PACKARD-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 1935 PACKARD IN FORMER SOVIET GEORGIA: THE TALES IT COULD TELL! 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUTAISI, Georgia _ Nodar Chechelashvili is a man with a sweep of
silver hair and a classic American tale _ of youth, of a car, of
romantic summer drives to the beach. But the cast of long-dead
characters, like Lavrenti Beria, Stalin's secret police chief, are
towering figures in Soviet history. And the story, stuck in a sad
cul-de-sac, still awaits an ending. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chechelashvili, 64, a Georgian pensioner, is quaintly out of
place amid civil war and economic ruin. He is absorbed in the
appalling state of the only car he has ever owned _ a red, white
and blue 1935 Packard that he bought when he was 20. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen its beauty before, and the good times I
had in it,'' Chechelashvili said, tears welling when a foreign
reporter and photographer appeared unannounced at his gate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you crying?'' asked his wife, Alla. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``From happiness,'' Chechelashvili replied. ``That they paid
attention.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chechelashvili's story reveals the lengths to which many people
went during the Soviet era and afterward to maintain possessions
that would have been long ago discarded in the West. It is also a
tale of the exceptional reach of what in the 1920s and '30s was a
premier American car _ the Packard, more prized even than Cadillac
and shipped around the globe to admiring leaders like Stalin, who
owned several. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In July, collectors will gather in Warren, Ohio, for the
centennial of the first Packard, built by the brothers William and
James Ward Packard. Hundreds of the cars are expected, including at
least one from each of the vehicle's 60 years of production. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But here in Kutaisi, a quiet city of 200,000 people, it has been
easy for Chechelashvili to feel misunderstood. While he has
conducted an international letter-writing campaign to save his
cherished car, unknowingly addressing his pleas to a company that
went out of business four decades ago, even some of those closest
to him have looked on with the sympathy accorded an eccentric. And
he has watched his Packard slowly deteriorate, parked in front of
his ramshackle wooden house next to a railroad depot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chechelashvili found the seven-passenger touring car in 1955
when, gassing up the taxi in which he earned his living, he noticed
a broken-down vehicle nearby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its dark green paint was faded, its convertible top ripped. The
upholstery was cracked and torn. The gas station owner said the car
had sat for seven years, abandoned by the police chief from
Tbilisi, the capital city 120 miles east, after a rod blew as the
rear axle snapped simultaneously. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Examining the Packard, Chechelashvili saw that the body was
undented, its detail intact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked it,'' he recalled, wearing a green V-neck sweater
under a leather jacket. ``I asked him to sell it to me. He said,
`I'll pay you to take it.' See, it was just occupying a lot of
space. So someone called the police chief and said, `There are some
boys here who want to take your car.' And he said, `Why not?''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So it was that Chechelashvili ended up paying a token 3,000
rubles _ even a bicycle cost 1,500 rubles at the time _ and, using
a bus, towed it home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tracking its history, Chechelashvili learned that the vehicle
was initially used by Beria, the first secretary of Georgia's
Communist Party, before Stalin summoned him to Moscow in 1938 and
he became one of the most feared men in Soviet history.
</P>
<P>
   A brass factory plate in the car is stamped ``1927,'' but the
model number supports the assertion of a Packard expert, Donald
Peterson of Roswell, Ga., that it is actually a 1935 Super Eight
Touring Car.
</P>
<P>
   The Packard Super Eight _ just 1,392 were made in 1935 in 16
body styles _ came with an 8-cylinder, 150-horsepower,
385-cubic-inch engine. In the United States, it cost $3,690. ``That
would buy you six, maybe seven new Chevys,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Packard buff, Jim Pearsall of Zarephath, N.J., said he
was unaware of any surviving '35 Packards with this body style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As popular as Packards were with Soviet strongmen, spare parts
were hard to come by. Chechelashvili has had access only to Russian
hardware and local ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   Working for two years to repair his car, he installed a
six-cylinder Soviet Gaz-51 engine. Inside, he upholstered the seats
with fake black leather and the door panels with striped,
multi-colored cloth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friends convinced him to replace the original paint. When
sanding didn't work, they tried a welding torch. ``It melted the
tin, and it was dripping into the bottom of the repair pit,''
Chechelashvili said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the result _ he repainted the Packard black and white _ was
a wonderful cruising car. He began making grand tours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over tea and the local cheese-filled bread called khachapuri,
Chechelashvili leafed through albums of photos in which he posed
with relatives in the Black Sea resorts of Georgia and Yalta. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around Kutaisi, grown men describe being taken as boys by
Chechelashvili for marvelous summer rides to the beach. He himself
recalls some hellish adventures, like the seaside drive during
which he flipped the car and crushed the windshield, and another in
which a fire consumed the interior. The repairs resulted in the
car's somewhat blockish appearance, including a windshield salvaged
from a three-ton cargo truck. The door panels are steel sheets.
</P>
<P>
   A curious sense of aesthetics accounts for other alterations.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, a local film company wrote the car into a script,
and the director ordered it repainted red, white and blue;
Chechelashvili decided he liked the colors, and he pocketed the
cash he was given to restore the old finish.
</P>
<P>
   He cannibalized Volga sedans for the front and back bumpers,
rear windows, hubcaps and _ extended from the rear _ a huge trunk.
(``Now there's room for 300 liters of gas,'' he said.) He
jury-rigged the taillights (salvaged from different trucks, and not
identical) and grille, and installed roll-up windows. The car
originally had side curtains that snapped into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, of course, highly modified,'' said Peterson, the
Packard authority, with considerable understatement. Art James, an
expert in Toronto, had a harsher assessment. ``It will never stand
on its own as a Packard,'' he said. ``It will stand out as a freak
model, which is not all that great.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but around here the car still attracts appreciative
gawks. To begin his ritual spins through town, Chechelashvili
simply twists the crank and pulls the choke. The Packard starts
instantly, rumbling more like a tank than a luxury cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Chechelashvili suggested that surviving members of the Packard
family might help, out of pride, to restore the car ``as it is in
the pictures.'' It is a measure of his isolation that he learned
only this year that Packard has long been out of business.
Struggling by the mid-1950s, it merged with Studebaker, which last
used the name on some bizarre Studebaker-derived models in 1958.
Studebaker was itself faltering, and it produced its last cars in
Canada in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Summers, a surviving Packard relative by marriage who
helps to administer the family inheritance from his home in Santa
Barbara, Calif., said he recently donated ``a sizeable sum'' for
restorations at the Packard Museum in Warren, Ohio, ``and it's
there that anyone should go for help.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the museum director, Terry Martin, said he had barely enough
money to restore the first Packard built, in 1899. ``I was hoping
you'd say he wanted to find it a home,'' Martin said. ``We accept
vehicles given to the museum. That's a good way of getting them
restored.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, that could happen, Chechelashvili said, but not so
fast. ``I bought this car when I was 20, and I've had it since,''
he said. ``For this, I deserve a reward. If the Packards facilitate
it, and they desire it after I restore it, I'll give it to them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He paused to add another condition. ``In two or three years,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
