<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PARENTS-LESSONS-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY MONEY, MY LIFE: HOW FATHER KNEW BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (editors: also see BIZ-BOOKS)  
 Gail Lynch is a licensed clinical social worker in Montclair, N.J.
Submit your account of struggling or succeeding in financial life
to My Money, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036, or e-mail to mymoney(AT)nytimes.com.  
 (bl)  
 By GAIL LYNCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My father had two investment caveats _ and I heard them often as
I was growing up: Don't buy mutual funds, and don't touch
principal. I knew that if he ever caught me doing either, I'd be in
big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Dad was a psychologist in private practice. His investing
originally was intended as a way to save for retirement; after all,
unlike his friends in the corporate world, he wouldn't get a
pension. Gradually, however, investing also became his hobby _ and,
at times, his obsession.
</P>
<P>
   My role, beginning when I was about 9 years old, was to check
the newspaper and read aloud the stock prices of the blue-chip
companies in his portfolio, names like AT&AMP;T and General Motors. Dad
happily became his own fund manager, buying and selling his own
stocks instead of letting someone else make the decisions _ an idea
he abhorred. To support his strategy, he directed my brother and me
to use the goods and services of the companies he owned.
</P>
<P>
   Dad took his portfolio very seriously. Proud of his AT&AMP;T shares,
he flaunted the keychain he once received at its annual meeting. On
vacations, when we drove past a telephone booth, he'd check to see
if someone was using his ``store.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, my family always owned GM cars _ Chevrolets when
my brother and I were young and Oldsmobiles and Buicks after Dad
put us through college.
</P>
<P>
   Mom owned stocks, too, and she adopted Dad's caveats
wholeheartedly. But she added a few money-related rules of her own.
Never consent to a joint bank account, she advised, because it can
take away your independence. When it comes to stocks, she said, you
should hold 'em, not trade 'em.
</P>
<P>
   If my brother and I had a favorite stock, it was one of Mom's:
American Chicle _ now Warner Lambert, and still one of my choices.
Every Christmas, it sent her a gift packet of Chiclets, Sen-Sen and
Beemans gum. We'd find them in the toes of our Christmas stockings.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, times have changed greatly since the 1950s, when
there were only handfuls of mutual funds _ and relatively few
sources of advice. So, several years ago, because my parents were
no longer here and my brother was refusing to advise me, fearing
he'd be blamed if my investments sank, I decided to seek counsel
from a financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   When the planner first broached the subject of mutual funds, I
began to hyperventilate. After all, his advice flew in the face of
Dad's: You need mutual funds to diversify your investments, the
planner said. As for principal, he added, it's OK to tap some of
it, as long as it continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, I was a good candidate for investing in mutual funds.
I knew I could never devote the time my father had to investing _
nor did I want to. I didn't even check my stocks' performance every
day _ or every week or month.
</P>
<P>
   I quieted my queasy stomach and thought long and hard about a
new strategy. Finally, I took action: I sent for mutual fund
prospectuses and moved some of my money from individual stocks to
stock and bond funds. I even cashed in some stock, to give myself
something to live on during my upcoming early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Some days, Dad's warnings still ring in my ears. But what he
taught me best was to trust my instincts _ even if those instincts
were to seek advice from someone else. Not only do times change, so
do investment strategies and life plans.
</P>
<P>
   Separately and together, my parents passed on their wisdom as
well as a decent-sized nest egg. For both, I am eternally grateful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
