<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL BUSINESS DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which Spouse Wields The Power at Tax Time?
</P>
<P>
   Handling the money used to be a sign of authority in marriages,
but with financial options and couples' work time expanding, the
most powerful partner may now be the one who can talk the other
into the task _ especially at tax time.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Yankelovich Partners for the Lutheran Brotherhood,
an insurance and financial company in Minneapolis, confirms that
working on income taxes is no one's favorite job. Asked to rate a
list of chores on a scale of loathsomeness, 1,006 American adults
rated tax preparation second-worst, behind window-washing. Even
cleaning basements was preferable.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which interviewed only one person in each household,
found that men and women disliked tax preparation equally.
Nevertheless, both husbands and wives tended to say that they did
more of the work than their partners. Among the 534 respondents who
said they were married, 67 percent of the men said they did most of
the tax work and 20 percent said their wives did. Among married
women, 45 percent said they did the job and only 42 percent said
their husbands did.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, more men seem to be stuck with the job: When the
responses were combined, 54 percent said the husband in the family
did the taxes, and 33 percent said the wife did. Most of the
remainder said the job was shared.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA IRELAND
</P>
<P>
   Once Upon a Bedding Search
</P>
<P>
   What Goldilocks learned about choosing a mattress still applies.
Selecting from among all the models, sizes, brands and types is as
complicated as it has ever been _ even when you order on line.
</P>
<P>
   Several mattress retailers that have long sold their kings and
queens in stores and by telephone now have sites on the World Wide
Web. But so far they offer only window-shopping on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   E-mattress, at www.emattress.com, staked out a different kind of
Internet presence in March, , offering consumers the convenience of
selecting, ordering and paying for a mattress online.
</P>
<P>
   But as Goldilocks might note, there is more to shopping for a
mattress than convenience. How about making sure it's not too hard
or too soft?
</P>
<P>
   E-mattress says it is looking into offering an in-home trial
period, but for now the best it can offer is approval on delivery.
(That means Goldilocks could refuse to take the mattress before the
truck drove away.) The more traditional companies have more
traditional guarantees. Dial-a-Mattress, for instance, will let a
consumer exchange a bed within 30 days, and the same deal is
offered for 60 days by Sleepy's _ plenty of time, presumably, to
make sure the mattress really is just right.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHELLY FREIERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Work Less. Get a Promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Working less than full-time need not mean leaving the fast
track, according to a two-year study by researchers at Purdue
University in West Lafayette, Ind., and McGill University in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The study followed 87 corporate professionals and managers, many
of them women, in 45 American and Canadian companies, who chose to
scale back work by an average of 18 hours a week, at salary
reductions of 20 to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The new schedules made 91 percent of the workers happier with
the balance between work and home, and 70 percent of their
supervisors said they supported the change. Thirty-five percent of
the workers were promoted after reducing their work time.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SUSAN J. WELLS &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
