<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DIVORCE, IN VITRO DAD NOT JUST SPERM DONOR, COURT SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A husband who donates sperm for the in vitro
fertilization of his wife's eggs is the legal father of the
resulting child even if the embryo is implanted after divorce, a
state appeals court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be a groundbreaking decision, the 1st Court of
Appeals upheld a March 1998 ruling by Harris County Family Law
Judge Don Ritter granting Don McGill of Houston parental rights to
Grace McGill, born in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was a wonderful victory, it's a fair and
appropriate decision,'' said McGill, 64, who owns Toyota, Porsche
and Audi dealerships in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   His ex-wife, Mildred Schmit, 44, said from her home in
Lexington, Miss., that she was ``horribly disappointed'' and did
not know if she would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don McGill is the one with all the money, I've had to borrow
money to go as far as I've gone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel of the appellate court unanimously agreed
that there were no laws or court decisions addressing the legal
issues in the case, and invited ``the Texas Legislature to enact
legislation deciding the rights of parties involved in the in vitro
fertilization process.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Grace was conceived through in vitro fertilization in
1994, when the parents were still married, the embryo was frozen
and implanted three months after they divorced in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Schmit claims she had the embryo implanted because McGill
promised he would not seek parental rights. She said their 20-year
marriage was miserable and she did not want him to be the father.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Earle Lilly, has argued that because the embryo
was implanted after the divorce and McGill agreed not to seek
parental rights, he was no longer the father, but the sperm donor.
</P>
<P>
   But McGill claims he only allowed Schmit to undergo the implant
on the condition he would be the father. He claims Schmit agreed to
that but changed her mind one month after Grace was born because he
became engaged to another woman.
</P>
<P>
   When the couple divorced, they had no written agreement on the
disposition of the four frozen embryos remaining from the 1994
fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   This decade there have been two highly publicized cases, in
Tennessee and New York, involving divorced couples who had produced
embryos in vitro. In both cases, the women wanted to have an embryo
implanted after the divorce, but the men said they had the right to
veto it because they did not want to be fathers if they were not
married.
</P>
<P>
   The highest courts in both states prevented the women from
acting without their ex-husbands' permission. In both decisions,
the embryos were considered property, not children.
</P>
<P>
   But this case is the only known instance in which an embryo
produced by a married couple was actually successfully implanted
after a divorce without a written agreement on parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, a jury granted Schmit primary custody of Grace and
gave McGill weekend and holiday visitation rights. He said he ``can
only hope'' that Schmit gives up her legal fight.
</P>
<P>
   Schmit had asked the appellate court to award her $320,000 in
legal costs she has incurred so far. The appellate court denied the
request.
</P>
<P>
   McGill's attorney, Roy W. Moore. said that if Schmit appeals he
expects the Texas Supreme Court to uphold the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's decision did not allow a mother to bastardize a
child,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said Schmit had testified she believes childbirth begins
at conception, but ``she changes her story to suit what she
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad, sad situation she puts her interests before the
little girl's,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmit said she wanted to raise the child without McGill because
he was not a good husband or father to their three other children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going back to the 18th century to say I'm bastardizing a
child,'' she said. ``If Rosie O'Donnell or Madonna raise a child by
themselves, do people call it bastardizing?''
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Lilly, said if the decision stands it will set a
dangerous precedent, turning back the clock on artificial
conception laws designed to protect parents and donors.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ruling ``should put fear in prospective donors''
that they could be forced to take on parental responsibilities.
Women who do not want sperm donors to share parentage may risk
losing their rights to be the sole parent, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lilly had argued that since there were no laws to address such a
situation, the court should have looked at the rights of donors in
Texas' artificial insemination statute, which says the contractual
agreement between the donor and the mother determines parental
rights. He said a jury should have decided in this case whether
there was a binding oral contract determining parentage.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court took ``a narrow reading'' of the statute,
saying the artificial insemination statue could not be applied to
in vitro fertilization, Lilly said. In artificial insemination,
sperm is injected directly into a woman's uterus.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court said since there are no laws addressing such
circumstances, it had to rely on general paternity laws. Because
McGill was listed as the father on the birth certificate, the court
said he is the legal parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' Lilly said. ``The court didn't deal
with the issue other than taking the technical position that there
is no specific statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Pamela George, an attorney who helped with McGill's appellate
briefs, said, ``the court can't take a specific statute and expand
it to fit all circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
