   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RECOVERY (Washington) _ After the guns fall silent across
Kosovo, the U.S.-led western alliance will face expensive,
open-ended challenges trying to put it back together again. We look
at the questions of security, aid to refugees, resettlement, the
form of government, long-term reconstruction and the treatment of
suspected war criminals. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Congress returns from its spring
break Monday with some Republicans girding for an attack on
President Clinton's handling of the Balkan crisis. Most Democrats
appear ready to rally around him. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTERNET (Washington) _ Just as television has brought
the Vietnam War and other conflicts into living rooms worldwide,
the Internet is bringing an even more intimate view of the struggle
over Kosovo to people around the globe. The propaganda war that
intensified with the outbreak of NATO air raids on Yugoslavia
quickly moved to the Internet. By MARK HELM. With:
KOSOVO-INTERNET-SITES. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT (Washington) _ If you're planning to make the
nation's capital your vacation spot April 23-25, think again. The
city is in a dither as 1,700 dignitaries _ including 42 heads of
state _ prepare to descend on it in a sea of motorcades for NATO'S
50th anniversary celebration. The federal government is so
concerned about gridlock that it has told 90,000 employees to stay
home, and a large section of downtown will be closed for security
reasons. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-YOUTH (Houston) _ George W. Bush graduated from Yale with
no apparent career plan and no particular place to go. While the
Chicago police battled rioters, Bush got ready to fly jet fighters.
He eventually moved on to a Harvard MBA and the oil business. But
unlike Presidents Carter, Reagan and Clinton, who wistfully refer
to their small-town roots, Bush has Houston partly to credit or
curse for his coming-of-age in a tumultuous time that he now blames
for the nation's societal shortcomings. By ALAN BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BIRD-FIGHT (McAllen, Texas) _ This fight is for the birds. For
big ungainly chachalacas that glide from tree to tree, the brightly
plumed green jay and raucous greater kiskadees, the boisterous
red-crowned parrots that nest in the tall palms. In this growing
border town that calls itself ``The City of Palms,'' people are
gearing up for a battle seldom seen in the Rio Grande Valley. The
city wants to widen the last mile of a street from two to four
lanes, and in the process cut down trees that are home to dozens of
species of birds. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ If President Clinton wants a U.S.
precedent for reversing his stand against sending American ground
forces to Yugoslavia, he can find it by turning the clock back to
an incident that occurred 50 years ago this month. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
