<SLUG> BC-NY-JAYWALKING-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS KEEP JAYWALKING AS CRACKDOWN FADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Eighth Avenue, during afternoon rush hour, they
stride four abreast in traffic lanes as if marching in a parade,
then cross en masse on the diagonal, mid-block, to stream into the
Port Authority Bus Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Jaywalkers, declared an endangered species in January 1998 as
part of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's quality of life campaign, seem to
be thriving. On the Avenue of the Americas at 50th Street, home of
the infamous pedestrian barricades, a police officer stationed at
the corner one afternoon this week simply advised people crossing
outside the crosswalk to be careful.
</P>
<P>
   And on Lexington Avenue, a jay-jogger (jay-runner?) scooted
between the cars to get across. It's enough to make that
proverbially jaded New Yorker think that the mayor's crackdown
isn't all it was cracked up to be. But take a closer look. Check
the facts: The New York Police Department issued 99 jaywalking
tickets last year.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a lot, think about how many times a day you
cross against the light. Now multiply by 7 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we can tell, there never was a jaywalking crackdown
_ it never started and it never stopped,'' said John Kaehny,
executive director of Transportation Alternatives, a pedestrian
advocacy group that takes such things pretty seriously. ``It was
much more a rhetorical crackdown than an actual crackdown.''
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani revived his civility campaign this week with a
push for police politeness, it seemed an apt moment to check up on
what has happened in the 15 months since the mayor hiked the fines
for jaywalking tickets from $2 to $50 and suggested that officers
start writing them.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Police Department wavered between saying the
anti-jaywalking initiative was over and that there never was an
anti-jaywalking initiative. The president of the police officers'
union said he had forgotten all about the crackdown. At 346
Broadway, where the few jaywalkers who have been nailed come to
appear before a judge and pay their fines, the clerks said they
have not noticed any spike in errant pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   In midtown Manhattan, illegal walkers by the dozen said they had
seen no change in behavior by pedestrians or the police since the
supposed crackdown began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a cop give anyone a ticket, nor have I ever
heard of a cop giving anyone a ticket,'' said Alan Pollack, a
lawyer who lives on the Upper East Side and was a little sheepish
after having crossed Lexington Avenue practically halfway between
the two corners. ``But I think it's the right thing to do, because
it's intended to protect pedestrians. Sometimes, pedestrians need
to be protected from themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, jaywalking is illegal, a clear violation of the
city's traffic rules. That means no crossing in front of oncoming
vehicles, no crossing mid-block, no crossing against the light, no
crossing anytime it says, well, ``Don't Walk.'' But, after all,
this is New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is New York, we do things in a New York minute,'' said
Debbi Robinson, 34, as she strode up Lexington, crossing against
the light at 49th Street, then again on 50th, and again on 51st.
``We've got places to go, things to do. We don't pay attention to
the lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Macluso, 26, who lives in Greenwich, Conn., but jaywalks
daily to get to his hotel-industry job, actually has gotten a
ticket. In Milwaukee. He paid his $50 fine, came home, and _ except
while on vacation _ kept on jaywalking.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The ecology of New York is based on ignoring arbitrary
rules,'' explained Mitchell Moss, director of the Taub Urban
Research Center at New York University. ``Jaywalking isn't an
ailment to people; it's a coping mechanism. Penalizing jaywalkers
is the equivalent of imposing martial law. The police are too smart
to start arresting jaywalkers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Mindel, Giuliani's press secretary, and Marilyn Mode, the
Police Department's top voice, said the point of the crackdown had
never been to write a lot of jaywalking tickets. Rather, they said,
it was a broad-based initiative to make the streets safer through
stricter enforcement of all the city's traffic laws.
</P>
<P>
   And they have pronounced it a success, noting that pedestrian
deaths were down to 193 last year, from 277 in 1997, and have
continued to fall, with just 35 in the first three months of this
year, compared with 51 during the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is safety,'' Ms. Mode said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a decline in pedestrians being killed _ that would
lead me to believe that people are being more cautious,'' Ms.
Mindel said. ``To focus on the violations is a mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
