<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACHELOR-PARTIES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACHELOR PARTIES TO MAKE A SATYR WEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 11) 
(jt) 
 By RICK MARIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In every man's life there comes a time when he must
ask himself, On a scale of Alan Alda to Maxim magazine, where do I
fall? His bachelor party is one of those times.
</P>
<P>
   Some men choose the traditional evening of red meat, alcohol
poisoning, verbal abuse and silicone-enhanced strippers. Others opt
for revelry that is more ... how shall we say? ... evolved.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a bunch of bankers will arrive in New York from
Wilmington, Del., to re-enact this rite of manly passage. Their
first stop: the Dorit Baxter day spa at 47 West 57th St. Here, the
20 men, all in their late 30s and early 40s, will indulge in an
afternoon of facials, pedicures, massages, salt scrubs and algae
wraps. You know, just one of those fabulous ``me'' days after a
stressful, pore-clogging day at the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all going to wear white robes and slippers and hang
around and chat between appointments in the reception area,'' said
the spa's owner, Dorit Baxter. ``It will be really a great event.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be such a thing as  &UR; too &LR;  evolved. Is an afternoon at
the beauty parlor any way for men to send off their fellow men from
singledom into ball-and-chaindom? Apparently, yes. In fact, it's
just one of the many new toxin-free, smutless forms of bachelor
recreation. Golf weekends, paint ball, laser tag, fly-fishing,
barbecues with the parents and civilized evenings of oenophilia
devoid of pornophilia haven't totally replaced old-school triple-X
entertainment. But they're gaining.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Beeman, a partner in a New York law firm, was the guest
of honor at a two-day bachelor marathon in New York in September.
The highlights: an epicurean tour of the Fulton Fish Market, pate
at Petrossian, a few spirited games of court tennis at the Racquet
Club, a sail around Manhattan for which all the men donned black
tie and dinner at the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a frat house,'' said Beeman, 37. ``No cigarette
butts in beers. No vomiting.'' And needless to say, no strippers.
Beeman was subjected to some ``lighthearted ribbing'' during
dinner, he said. ``But there weren't any vulgar references to the
more embarrassing parts of our lives. The tone was elegant and
fun.'' The theme of the toasts was promarriage.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of a bachelor party used to be to lament the
bridegroom's final night of freedom, his last shot at
nondivorceable infidelity. But at his bachelor dinner last year,
Robert Boynton, a magazine writer, toasted Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
for cleaning up the city's strip joints. Thanks to the crackdown,
Boynton explained, his buddies couldn't drag him out for a seedy
night of liquor and lap dances.
</P>
<P>
   An invitation via E-mail to New York friends of a Boston police
officer included the following stipulation: ``Jesse has made it
clear that he does not want any hired talent, and has very little
interest in going to see any talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, a bridegroom may not want a booze-up with hired talent
handcuffing him to his chair. But his friends often do. As much as
it purports to be a celebration of the poor sap who's getting
hitched, the bachelor party is a sanctioned excuse for the sap's
pals to carouse _ the single ones, and the marrieds paroled for the
night from their wives and children. They often end up feeling
burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a married man, I don't get that many chances to see
naked women other than my wife,'' said David Eddie, a novelist who
flew in from Toronto for the Beeman weekend. ``So I guess I felt
like that would have been an opportunity.'' Although he enjoyed the
pate, the first-growths and all the clubby perks, he felt that
something was lacking. ``My thought was, There's only so much
happiness you can take in through your mouth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And only so much ribaldry you can get away with in an atmosphere
of polite decorum. Roasts ridiculing the bridegroom and maligning
the bride's virtue are out at these wholesome gatherings.
Earnestness is in. Chris Calhoun, a literary agent who attended
Boynton's dinner, complained that the toasts ``sounded like a
Chamber of Commerce meeting.'' This was in stark contrast to
another bachelor bash a few years ago attended by virtually the
same circle of New York publishing types. ``I did a Carnac act,''
Calhoun said. ``I almost got my throat cut, we were saying such
horrible things.'' The bridegroom at that party had greeted his
guests naked. But Boynton said that after his party, ``I was in bed
by midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   An aversion to strip clubs is the reason many bridegrooms would
prefer their parties to be G-rated rather than G-strung. ``It
seemed like something out of a bad teen-age sex comedy,'' said
Philip Baltz, a New York publicity agent. To him, going somewhere
like Billy's Topless seemed too embarrassing or cliched. His
bachelor dinner at the Cub Room in SoHo was described by one guest
(who asked to remain nameless) as ``the tamest night of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Morrison, editor in chief of Modern Bride, attributed the
trend toward tameness to ``the demystification of stripper
culture.'' She said she knew one bride who gave her husband-to-be
vouchers for a strip club in Queens. That pretty much killed the
fun of it for the bridegroom, Ms. Morrison said, and he refused to
go. It's not exactly transgression if your fiancee gives her
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Couples are also more mature. A 1997 Roper study found that the
age of the average bridegroom had risen to 27.5 from 23 over the
previous 15 years, and of the average bride, to 26 from 21. ``This
generation is taking marriage very seriously,'' Ms. Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Mike Souter, a British magazine editor, will arrive
in New York to take the helm at Maxim, the monthly bible of bad
male behavior. He sounded appalled by the squeaky-clean bachelor
parties in this country. ``Men bond better when they're blind
drunk, I always find,'' he shouted into the phone. ``You can't bond
with another guy in a dressing gown, getting your nails done.''
</P>
<P>
   There are various interpretations of the old-school bachelor
debauch:
</P>
<P>
   _It's just a cheap sleaze rush.
</P>
<P>
   _Flushing out wanderlust is a necessary catharsis before a man
assumes the responsibilities of monogamous married life.
</P>
<P>
   _The raunchier the party, the more a man is ready to quit the
bachelor life. But this argument, acting in a manner one's future
wife would find appropriate, even commendable, may defeat the
purpose of the event.
</P>
<P>
   See, for instance, a movie called ``The Bachelor Party'' _ not
the 1984 Tom Hanks thing, but a dark 1957 drama written by Paddy
Chayefsky. A young newlywed played by Don Murray has just found out
that his wife is pregnant. Feeling boxed in by work, night school
and their tight budget, this is the last news he needs. That night,
he goes on a bachelor bender. The shy guy in the group is tying the
knot, with a woman he barely knows. The office playboy, played by
Jack Warden, with a black book full of hot ``broads,'' leads the
boys on a steamy summer night of burlesque shows, stag films and a
wild party in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the guys drop out, until just Murray's and Warden's
characters are left. Warden, drunk and pathetically lonely, begs
him to stay out. But Murray, after a flirtation with a
nymphomaniacal beatnik, has seen enough. By daybreak, the bachelor
party has made him realize he  &UR; wants &LR;  to go home, to his pregnant
wife and their cramped apartment in Stuyvesant Town.
</P>
<P>
   Some wisdom, it seems, a guy can't get from a pedicure and a
glass of chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
