<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS PITCH IN TO HELP ALBANIAN REFUGEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Ragan is among a group of Texans who see the Kosovo crisis
as more than a gruesome headline.
</P>
<P>
   He is interrupting his life to help Muslim refugees fleeing into
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those God things,'' he said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ragan, a Wichita Falls native, is one of 12 Texans who will
travel to Albania next week to assist in purifying water,
distributing food and providing medical aid in the refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe I'm going,'' said Ragan, a ministerial
student at Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Watching television in his dorm room, Ragan saw the fleeing
refugees, many carrying babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart was breaking for those people,'' he said. ``I began
praying, asking God how I could help. I never thought of going over
there, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Ragan learned that Texas Baptist Men, a Southern
Baptist group that often helps in disasters, had been asked to set
up refugee camps in Korce and Peshkopi, Albania.
</P>
<P>
   He asked how he could help, and was invited to go.
</P>
<P>
   The team plans to leave Wednesday from Dallas/Fort Worth Airport
and to spend two weeks in Albania, said Jim Furgerson, executive
director of Texas Baptist Men.
</P>
<P>
   Ragan, who spent three years in Ukraine working as a missionary,
said he wants to help the refugees to show that Christians care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here are these Muslims being run out of the country by
Orthodox Christians,'' he said. ``I don't think that is showing the
love of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO began the current bombing campaign to try to stop
Yugoslavia's President Slobodan Milosevic from having thousands of
Muslim ethnic Albanians killed or ousted from the small province.
As many as 500,000 have fled their homes.
</P>
<P>
   All major religious groups _ including Jewish, Muslim, Catholic
and Protestant benevolent groups _ are collecting money to help
refugees. Many are also organizing volunteer teams.
</P>
<P>
   Another Texas organization giving direct aid to refugees is
Mission Possible, a Denton-based group that has had a staff of six
in Tirania, Albania, for six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we focus on distributing Bibles, but now everything
has been dropped to help the refugees,'' said Jim Mann of Denton,
an official of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Another Texan scheduled to go on the trip to Albania with Texas
Baptist Men is Robert Mann of Arlington, a pediatrician and trustee
of Cook Children's Medical Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Mann was part of a Texas Baptist team providing medical aid in
the Kurdish refugee camps of Turkey and Iraq in the aftermath of
Operation Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what you are getting into,'' he said this week.
``When I was in Iraq we found (that) many refugees were so
dehydrated that we immediately began giving IVs.''
</P>
<P>
   Mann said he expects that many refugees in Albania who have been
living in squalid conditions will be suffering from respiratory and
skin problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also a part of the Baptist team will be Mann's son, Brad Mann,
who is taking time off from graduate studies to work with Mission
Arlington, a ministry of the First Baptist Church of Arlington that
gives food, clothing and other assistance to the needy.
</P>
<P>
   People of faith are drawn to helping people whether at home or
abroad, said Tillie Burgin, a former foreign missionary who founded
Mission Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Burgin mentioned the biblical command in Matthew 25, when Jesus
tells his followers to feed the hungry and thirsty, take in
strangers, visit those in prison, provide clothes for the needy and
give care to those who are sick.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of a God thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
