<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     04-09 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN MICHAEL MOORE AND BRAVO FIND HAPPINESS _ AND VIEWERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Moore is a pest, plain and simple. Anyone who has ever
dealt with him understands this, considering it either a compliment
or a complaint, depending on the side of the fence from which he's
eyeballing you.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen his classic ``Roger &AMP; Me,'' which shook the
publicity foundation of General Motors, the short-lived ``TV
Nation,'' or any of his many interviews, it's clear that you want
him for you and not against you. The defiant Moore isn't a
journalist as much as a pit bull camouflaged in droopy jeans and
dirty sneakers. He latches on, refusing to let go until you yell
``uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   That's never more evident than in the premiere episode of yet
another series of gotcha exposes on corporate greed and the little
people it often tramples in the name of profits.
</P>
<P>
   Bravo is hoping the 12 episodes of ``The Awful Truth,''
beginning at 8 p.m. CDT Sunday on the arts channel, are the right
vehicle for Moore. But is Moore the right vehicle for Bravo?
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Roger &AMP; Me,'' with which Moore will forever be linked,
the film provocateur has bounced around in search of a place to do
what he does best. Moore needs flexibility and autonomy. He needs
the support of those who feel that our health care system is sleazy
and our big corporations cold-hearted. And his thing is to expose
them with both facts and fun _ ``60 Minutes'' with a laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Moore's ``TV Nation'' aired briefly on NBC and later
on Fox. The series never built much of a fan base and was kicked
around the Fox schedule in 1994 and part of 1995. Moore has said
publicly that network censors chained him, the result being that
viewers expecting his irreverent style thought he'd gone soft. It's
a no-brainer that Moore would prefer the sizable viewership of
broadcast networks. But just as clear is the trade-off, that
networks would never go for anything that stings the advertisers
who pay the bills.
</P>
<P>
   What Bravo wants out of this marriage is a popular series giving
it reason to air more original programming and decrease its
dependence on films. The arts channel originated as a kind of
obscure supplier of fine arts like dance, opera, Broadway plays and
art films.
</P>
<P>
   But series like ``Inside the Actors Studio,'' where artists
explain their craft in uninterrupted detail, have attracted a
different viewer _ younger, inclined to at least occasionally watch
``E!.'' Moore falls within this new strategy, bringing with him
another segment Bravo often misses: the working class. But how will
Bravo's older audience take Moore's constant challenge of
authority?
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to the arts channel, you get the feeling that
this is one of the last places Moore can attempt his type of
guerrilla filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's cinema verite style is common to Bravo viewers, but his
ambush-style, in-your-face tactics are another matter. Take the
second segment in the two-story ``The Awful Truth,'' which involves
the plight of Christopher Donahue, a Florida man with a
life-threatening pancreatic illness. A transplant would save his
life but his health-care provider, the billion-dollar Humana, won't
pay for the operation.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Moore do? After explaining the situation to
viewers, showing refusal letters from Humana and even a close-up of
Donahue sobbing at the thought of leaving his 4-year-old daughter
fatherless, they show Donahue at his hometown Palm Beach Post
newspaper, listing his own obituary.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper staff member looks dumbfounded but takes it down,
word for word, as Donahue lists ``lack of quality care from his
HMO'' as cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Moore and Donahue travel to the corporate offices of the
insurance giant in Louisville, Ky., where Moore and his cronies
stage a mock funeral as company employees look on in shocked horror
and a bit of amusement.
</P>
<P>
   There's a casket brought in and taken out by a hearse, and some
eulogizing, mostly by Moore, with Donahue standing next to him,
adding bits and pieces of information about the life he's about to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Moore is at his pesky best when testing the patience of
a Humana public-relations type, who meets with Moore and Donahue.
Aware of the camera and probably of Moore's reputation for getting
spokesfolk to humiliate themselves and thus their companies on
camera, he is obviously peeved but amazingly restrained in showing
them both the door.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the segment is quite effective, as is the previous
story, in which Moore stages a witch hunt on the lawn of
independent prosecutor Ken Starr's home and in the corridors of
Congress with Bible-toting Puritans. At one point, he strolls into
U.S. Rep. Henry Hyde's office to ask, ``Isn't Henry Hyde an
adulterer?''
</P>
<P>
   A future segment includes Moore traveling with a group of
homosexual men in a recreational vehicle he calls ``the
sodomobile'' into states where sodomy is outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   Another brings a group of Christmas carolers to the headquarters
of a tobacco company. As tobacco executives look on, they quickly
learn that all are lung cancer victims singing with croaky
artificial voice boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Moore say he's nothing more than a comedian with a
camera crew, that he merely tricks his subjects into talking,
refuses to let them speak their mind and conveniently leaves out
the other side. (Moore says it's his nonthreatening manner that
makes people open up.)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Awful Truth,'' Moore does fancy himself as a stand-up
jokester. Before introducing segments, he stands before a live
crowd dishing on politics.
</P>
<P>
   Moore calls those who follow him ``The People's Democratic
Republic of Television,'' and insists at the end of tonight's show,
``We need to take on one of these guys every week.''
</P>
<P>
   How great that will be. But will anyone notice?
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Moon'' (8 p.m. CDT Sunday, CBS) _ This story about
longtime lovers (Sharon Lawrence and Jeffrey Nordling) struggling
with a marriage, a daughter's severe hearing impairment and other
pressures turns out sweet and a little more high-minded than the
usual made-for-TV fare. Always nice to see Lawrence tussle with
emotions. This also represents the late Richard Kiley's final role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Letters'' (8 p.m. CDT Monday, ABC) _ A sort of jolting
made-for-TV adaptation of the enduring play about a lifelong
bittersweet relationship, told in letters read by two actors, Laura
Linney and Steven Weber. A.R. Gurney's work has been performed on
stage by dozens of pairs of noted actors _ more than 60 in Los
Angeles alone. Filmmaker Stanley Donen directed this version, and
most of it works. Kirsten Storms and Tim Redwine portray the couple
as teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear America: Dreams in the Golden Country'' (6:30 p.m. CDT
Tuesday, HBO) _ A 12-year-old Russian immigrant (Nathalie Vansier)
struggles with her family to adjust to a new life on New York's
Lower East Side during the early 1900s. This is the second in a
terrific series of family specials about heroic young women from
different cultures and times. Great stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scared Straight! 20 Years Later'' (7 p.m. CDT Thursday, UPN) _
Twenty years ago, producer Arnold Shapiro's landmark documentary
``Scared Straight!'' brought youthful offenders face-to-face with
inmates as part of a special program at New Jersey's Rahway State
Prison. Shapiro revisits the offenders and convicts to see what
impact the meetings had on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' (9 p.m. CDT Friday, NBC) _
Here's another chance to see that ``Subway'' episode, which is
among the highlights of Andre Braugher's amazing work on this
low-rated but respected drama. Even if you've seen this 1997
episode a few times, see it again.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
