<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATING LATEST MODELS OF SCANNERS, PRINTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Finding a scanner or printer that hooked up to a newer
personal computer's Universal Serial Bus was a real challenge a
year ago. Users who understood that USB is a much faster connection
were left with an empty sense of longing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, USB devices are coming into their own and are much easier
to find. Most USB printers will allow you to connect to either a
traditional parallel port or the USB port, while most USB scanners
limit you to that type of connection.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at products from Epson America and Hewlett-Packard
_ two USB printers and two USB scanners.
</P>
<P>
   __ DeskJet 882C Printer _ $299, Hewlett-Packard. In the past,
I've not been overly fond of HP's color inkjet printers. They were
a little slow, the colors were not quite as bright as I like and
they went through ink cartridges too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   My, how things have improved. This new DeskJet printer is fast,
with gorgeous colors and _ so far _ I've not had to replace the
cartridge.
</P>
<P>
   The 882C replaces the DeskJet 880C, which was one of HP's
best-selling home printers. This is not a budget printer, but
rather one that would be excellent for those who run a home
business or do a lot of printing that requires high-quality output.
</P>
<P>
   It connects to the PC via either the parallel or the USB port.
However, print speed is limited by how fast the print head can spew
its ink, so you won't necessarily see zippier printing by using the
USB connection.
</P>
<P>
   The DeskJet 882C is rated at eight pages per minute for
black-and-white printing and five pages per minute for color.
However, that's in its fastest mode and thus lowest quality. Switch
to photo-quality, and the speed drops dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   It prints black and white at a resolution of 600 dots per inch.
HP does not list the resolution for color, instead saying it uses a
layering method called PhotoREt II for high-end color reproduction.
This reduces the banding effect you sometimes see on
high-resolution color prints.
</P>
<P>
   The 882C is very quiet, which is a plus because many new inkjets
are quite noisy. It also doesn't go through lengthy turn-on and
shut-down gyrations common to new Canon and Epson printers.
</P>
<P>
   __ ScanJet 5200Cse Scanner _ $299, Hewlett-Packard. &UR;  &LR; Scanning is
where USB's speed advantage really comes into play. The ScanJet is
an incredibly peppy little scanner _ at least as far as the scans
themselves are concerned. The software used to initiate them ...
well, that's another matter.
</P>
<P>
   The 5200Cse is very easy to use, with a single button on the
front panel to initiate a scan. It comes with software that can
automatically direct a scanned image to your e-mail program or
Web-page authoring package.
</P>
<P>
   This 36-bit color scanner can handle resolutions up to
600-by-1,200 dots per inch in hardware, or 9,600-by-9,600 dots per
inch with a software boost. It produced some of the best quality
images I've seen in a home scanner at this price, even at
relatively low resolutions. The 5200Cse also did it very quickly _
about as fast as if it was using a SCSI connection. If need be, you
also can plug the scanner into a parallel port.
</P>
<P>
   However, the software used to invoke and manage the TWAIN
drivers _ the components used to pull images from the scanner into
the computer _ is not fast at all. I first tried it on a
200-megahertz Pentium MMX system with 64 megabytes of memory, and
it sometimes took as long as 30 seconds just to launch. A friend
who bought a 5200Cse and ran it on his new 500-megahertz Pentium
III system reported much faster results. Beware if you have a
slower system. HP says the software is simplified, but frankly, it
lacks the image controls found on other scanners' software.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stylus Color 900 printer _ $399, Epson America. &UR;  &LR; Epson claims
this is the fastest inkjet printer you can buy, and I'm not going
to argue with them. This baby zips along at an unbelievable clip. I
won't say it is as fast as a laser printer _ but it's close.
</P>
<P>
   The Stylus Color 900 prints black and white at 12 pages per
minute, and, even more impressively, 10 pages per minute in color.
Moving to photo-realistic printing slows it down markedly, but it
still is relatively quick.
</P>
<P>
   There's one drawback to this warp speed, however. The 900's
print head moves back and forth so quickly that it's noisy, and it
literally shakes the table it's sitting on.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with all Epson printers, the color is excellent.
Some people find the Epson ``look'' to be a bit saturated, although
I think it produces more realistic photo images. The fact that it
can handle resolutions of 1,440-by-720 dots per inch doesn't hurt,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Like the HP printer, it connects to your PC using either the
parallel or USB port. Unlike the HP, though, it goes through
incredible gyrations when it is turned on or off. I'll be glad when
Epson figures out a way around that.
</P>
<P>
   __ Perfection 636U _ $299, Epson America. &UR;  &LR; This is an excellent
scanner for home users, though it's priced a little higher than
competing products _ many scanners of this quality sell in the $250
range.
</P>
<P>
   The Perfection 636U is a USB-only scanner, though a model is
available for those who prefer a SCSI connection. In fact, that one
even comes with a SCSI card for your computer.
</P>
<P>
   This 36-bit scanner handles resolutions of up to 600-by-2,400
dots per inch in hardware, and 9,600-by-9,600 with a software
boost. The images were not quite as nice as the HP scanner, but
they were still excellent.
</P>
<P>
   The scanning software, though, was much better than the HP's.
You can set up the Epson's software to run in a simplified view, or
click a button and adjust many different details. The software also
launches much faster than the HP's, though scans were a bit slower.
</P>
<P>
   It also has single-button launch to initiate a scan, but there's
another button on the front that many home scanners lack _ a power
button. Most folks don't use their scanners that frequently, and
having the ability to turn it off and save electricity _ and
possibly extend the life of the scanning lamp _ is a plus.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman (at) chron.com, or call
713-220-2000, access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
