<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-$ADV1     04-09 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PREPARES TO ADDRESS KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress returns from its spring break this week
with some Republicans ready to renew their own air and ground war
on President Clinton's handling of the Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, appear ready to rally around Clinton and
the NATO bombing campaign aimed at forcing Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to halt Serbian attacks in the embattled
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking in the background is the War Powers Act, a 1973 law
approved by Congress as U.S. forces departed from Vietnam. It
requires presidential troop commitments to end within 60 days
unless Congress declares war or authorizes continuation of the
deployments. But the law has never been invoked to prevent or
curtail a U.S. military action.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show rising support among Americans for the NATO air war,
and last week, Washington Post-ABC News and Wall Street Journal-NBC
surveys showed 57 percent and 53 percent, respectively, favoring
deployment of U.S.-led NATO ground forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the polls are not deterring a few House Republicans who
oppose U.S. presence in the NATO effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is war, and it's not an inherent power of the
commander-in-chief,'' said Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif.,
.MDRV/.MDNM/a House International Relations Committee member. ``I'm
not an isolationist. My sense of it is this (the Kosovo dispute) is
a civil war, and by invoking (the words) `genocide' and `Hitler,'
we make it into something that is very different.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a former Stanford law professor, said he plans to
invoke the 1973 law by introducing two resolutions Monday: a
declaration of war plus a measure calling for the withdrawal of
U.S. air and ground forces from the region. The twin votes,
Campbell said, will force lawmakers to choose which way to go and
end the state of undeclared war.
</P>
<P>
   On March 11, the House approved sending 4,000 U.S. peacekeeping
troops to carry out the peace accord signed in Rambouillet, France.
But Milosevic refused to endorse the agreement, a move that
precipitated NATO's air attacks that began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   In Campbell's view, the conflict in Kosovo _ the southern
province of Serbia, the dominant republic of Yugoslavia _ springs
from a tit-for-tat situation in which the ethnic Albanians' Kosovo
Liberation Army and Serbian military forces are both guilty of
atrocities against innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, said Campbell, ``This is not something we should be
engaged in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, a presidential contender, also argues
the U.S. has no national interests at stake in the Balkans, but he
prefaces his criticism with strong support of America combat units
in the air war.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Goodling, R-Penn., the committee's second-ranking
Republican, plans to introduce a resolution requiring congressional
approval of any plan to send U.S. ground forces to Kosovo. Goodling
has enlisted six GOP co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last week's polls, Clinton continued to discount the
need for ground forces. But Goodling said he wants to take no
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've depleted the military so dramatically, but we continue
these so-called peacekeeping missions,'' he said. ``If we
reinstitute the draft or if Americans start coming back in body
bags, I'll guarantee those polls will change very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodling said the 1991 Persian Gulf War ``spoiled'' the American
public because it was over quickly and it had the clear objective
of removing Iraq's military forces from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Goodling said, ``I don't know what our purpose is''
in the Balkans. ``I don't see (victory) happening quickly in
(mountainous) terrain such as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most House Democrats support Clinton. ``I think the policy we're
executing is the right one,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson of
Connecticut, the House International Relations Committee's senior
Democrat, after returning from a 48-hour fact-finding mission to
Brussels and the U.S. air base in Aviano, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat, Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., senior Democrat on the
House Armed Services Committee, supports the air war but has
criticized Clinton, saying he could have done better in preparing
the nation for the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., sided with Republicans in
their unsuccessful opposition to the House resolution supporting
U.S. participation in a NATO peacekeeping force. Now, Frank says
that if Milosevic gives in, he would reluctantly support some U.S.
troop involvement in a peacekeeping force. The brunt of the burden,
however, should fall on Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any fundamental reason why the large collection of
prosperous, technologically sophisticated nations of Western Europe
can't have a ground presence capable of acting without us,'' Frank
said. ``But I recognize they don't have that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank still opposes ground troops in a combat situation, but he
insists the House has in effect already authorized them by voting
for a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between ground troops to enforce a coerced
peace agreement and ground troops now is not of constitutional
significance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is less dissension in the Senate, which voted 58-41 to
support the air campaign on March 23, the day before NATO bombs and
missiles started falling on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., another presidential contender, has
strongly supported the military effort, and he was among the first
to call for considering the use of U.S. ground troops. Among those
supporting the McCain position are Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., and
Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.
</P>
</TEXT>
