<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S INEXPENSIVE COMPUTERS 
GREAT BARGAINS FOR AVERAGE USER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Q. I am very tempted to buy one of these new
under-$1,000 computers. (I guess you can't call them ``sub-$1,000''
anymore, since they are really ``sub-$500'' in some cases!) I've
read reviews of systems such as the eMachines, but I am still wary.
These manufacturers have to be cutting corners, big time! When I am
shopping for a budget PC, what should I look out for?
</P>
<P>
   A. Low-priced PCs really are a miracle of our time. They are
being snapped up by the thousands, so much so that the penetration
of PCs in U.S. homes as measured by the market research firm
Dataquest has now passed 50 percent for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the inexpensive machines are excellent bargains.
Processors have become powerful enough that even the
least-expensive ones can run most modern software _ even
power-hungry games _ quite nicely. Memory, hard drives and other
components are quite cheap, and competitive PC makers pass the
savings on to you.
</P>
<P>
   But yes, there are things to watch out for. Corners are being
cut. Some of them you can't avoid _ others you can.
</P>
<P>
   First, nearly all manufacturers include a very limited amount of
consumer software on these computers. That means you'll have to buy
your own, if you don't already have it. You can download many
shareware and even freeware titles from the Internet, but if you
are a novice, this can be confusing and daunting. Consider buying
software a hidden cost you'll likely have to bear.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers use processors _ such as the MII from Cyrix _
that can use part of the standard system memory for video memory.
That means if the computer comes with 32 megabytes of random access
memory, only some of it will be available for programs. Usually,
these chips take two to four megabytes away. However, the MII is
not always set up this way, so if you see a system that interests
you, ask how video memory is handled.
</P>
<P>
   PC makers also may scrimp on the video. Systems with just two
megabytes of video memory _ often used in the MII machines _ are
inadequate for many games. Those systems that have separate video
cards often come with just four megabytes of video memory, when
eight megabytes is really better for graphics applications and
games.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, many PC makers use winmodems as opposed to traditional
modems. Winmodems only can be run with Windows programs _ they
won't work with older DOS applications _ and they seem to be not as
good at handling dirty phone lines. However, winmodems almost are
universal in low-cost PCs, and it's almost impossible to avoid
them.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the sub-$500 models come with just 32 megabytes of
memory, and if you can afford to do so, it's a good idea to bump up
to at least 64 megabytes. This should be a minimal cost _ $35 to
$45 _ and it's worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Suddenly, I am not seeing any graphics in Internet Explorer
5.0! All I see are little boxes where the pictures are supposed to
be, but no pictures! Help!
</P>
<P>
   A. You're surfing with the graphics turned off. Although you are
missing things, you actually have one big benefit _ your surfing
sessions are probably faster!
</P>
<P>
   Here's how to fix it: Go to Tools, Internet Options, and click
the Advanced tab. Scroll down to the Show Pictures box and check
it. Click Apply, then OK to exit.
</P>
<P>
   You also can turn graphics on and off in Netscape Communicator.
Go to Edit, Preferences, then Advanced. To turn images off, click
``Automatically load images.''
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000 and enter
access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
