<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2420 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      04-09 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 11, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the section dress page:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ECOSYSTEM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Scientists at the Xerox
Palo Alto Research Center have squeezed a big portion of the Web,
about 55 million pages, onto 400 billion bytes of disk space. Held
in captivity, this Web in a box is poked and prodded by researchers
studying it like a great beast _ or, to use the metaphor they
prefer, like an ecosystem. They seek the laws by which the members
of the planetary community of Internet foragers compete and
cooperate in the constant search for information. The Internet is a
living laboratory to study mass human behavior with a precision and
scale never possible before. By George Johnson. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GENOCIDE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amid growing signs of a
genocidal campaign by Serbian forces against Kosovo's Albanians,
the conduct of ordinary Serbs is starting to attract the kinds of
questions raised in Daniel Jonah Goldhagen's book, `Hitler's
Willing Executioners: Ordinary Germans and the Holocaust.'
Goldhagen himself thinks that questioning the behavior of the
Serbian nation at this moment is not only fitting but essential. By
Michael T. Kaufman. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO-REVIEW (Brussels) _ NATO has been planning a 50th
anniversary summit this month to chart a new `strategic concept'
defining its role in European security. But that role is instead
being redefined in Kosovo. The role has become that of a bulwark
against the consequences of ethnic instability in Europe's
southeastern periphery, which is today the biggest threat to
European security, just as it was a century ago. If it cannot
resolve the Kosovo crisis, NATO may go the way of the League of
Nations. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MIDEAST-REVIEW (Damascus) _ NATO's punishment of Serb
Christians for their persecution of Kosovar Muslims presented the
Islamic world with a campaign that it could identify with. After
all, the U.S. and its allies were siding with Muslims this time,
not bashing Iraq or supporting Israel. But while sympathies for the
Kosovars are strong in the Muslim Middle East, they are tangled
with an abiding mistrust of the West, whose use of force against
the Serbs is seen as less than heroic. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FUGITIVES-REVIEW (Mexico City) _ A look at the
frequently-occurring phenomenon of Mexican government officials who
are accused of corruption and then flee. There are so many such
cases that, to Mexicans, the public figure turned fugitive has
become a cliche. `In our system, there's a thin line separating
public officials from outlaws, and legality from illegality,' said
poet Homero Aridjis. `Overnight, they can leave behind their
prerogatives of power and turn into fugitives.' By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   GADHAFI-LOCKERBIE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sources close to Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi say his agreement to turn over the suspects
in the Lockerbie jetliner bombing was not greatly influenced by
sanctions or other economic pressures. A need to end his isolation
and salvage his place in history may have been the most important
factor. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   COLDWAR-HEROES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Cold War Recognition
Certificate took its place in the pantheon of military honors last
week, when the Pentagon began accepting applications. Anyone who
served in the armed forces or in one of several federal government
positions between Sept. 2, 1945, when Japan surrendered to the
U.S., and Dec. 25, 1991, when Mikhail Gorbachev resigned as
president of the Soviet Union, is eligible to apply. The
certificate could go to as many as 22 million people. It carries no
financial benefits or privileges whatever _ but, oh, the glory! By
David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CUT-REVIEW (Washington) _ Recent public quiescence on the
issue of taxes is puzzling to conservatives who think that the time
is ripe for significant tax cutting or a sweeping overhaul of the
tax code. But Americans appear to have turned their political
energies and interests elsewhere. Although they would not reject a
tax cut, polls indicate many would prefer the money be dedicated to
Social Security or other programs. So congressional Republicans
have been working to tell Americans that they don't have to choose.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-JOBLESS-REVIEW (Washington) Unemployment has been falling
for seven years and economic growth remains robust. By conventional
economic theory, this should be producing inflation. But in fact,
inflation is nowhere to be found. And while theoretical economists
have been debating the issue for years, doubts about this
conventional wisdom on unemployment are now are beginning to change
the way the Federal Reserve sets policy. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CONFIDENTIAL-SOURCES-REVIEW (Cincinnati) _ Cincinnati Enquirer
reporter Mike Gallagher's decision to reveal the identity of a
confidential source, along with notes, documents and secretly taped
conversations, is echoing through the legal and journalistic
communities as a major assault on the revered principle of
protecting sources. The case is raising new questions about the
legal rights of sources who are burned by journalists. By Douglas
Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   ENTREPRENEUR-ADS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Get-rich-quick schemes
have been around a long time. But with this era's remarkable
economic expansion and concurrent growth of home-based businesses,
magazines that cater to small-scale entrepreneurs lately have
become thick with ads placing the home business smack dab on the
road to Easy Street.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
