<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2421 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-09 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TAX CONSEQUENCES OF COMMERCE ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you buy a book at a bookstore in Massachusetts, you pay a
sales tax. If you buy the same book over the Internet, you don't
pay a sales tax (in most cases).
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason why e-commerce, as it has come to be called,
is growing exponentially and why Web sites like Amazon.com have
become so popular.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by Chicago economics professor Austan Goolsbee
suggested that Internet sales would fall by 30 percent if sales
taxes were applied. Partly as a result of this study, the Clinton
administration and Congress last October agreed to a three-year
moratorium on Internet taxation.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet tax moratorium is, on balance, smart public policy.
Encouraging and enhancing e-commerce makes sense. It breaks down
trade barriers and fuels economic growth. And legislation that
prevents federal, state, and local governments from extracting yet
more tribute from creators of economic value is, almost by
definition, a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the policy is working. The growth of e-commerce is
phenomenal. This is especially true in the business-to-business
category. According to Business Week magazine, ``e-commerce between
businesses is five times as much as consumer e-commerce, or about
$43 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   And by 2003, Forrester Research Inc. figures it will balloon to
$1.3 trillion. That's 10 times consumer e-commerce, constituting 9
percent of all US business trade _ more than the Gross Domestic
Product of either Britain or Italy. Around 2006 or so, it might
reach up to 40 percent of all US business.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people in Washington expect that after the moratorium runs
out in 2001, some kind of sales tax will be imposed on e-commerce.
The idea is that by then the e-commerce model will have ``matured''
and thus serve as a veritable gold mine for federal, state, and
local taxation. By not taxing it now, the argument goes,
governments will be able to tax it to the teeth in a few short
years.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but the law of unintended consequences will almost
certainly come into play. The Internet is not just another
marketplace where taxes can be levied. It is a transforming
technology, one that rewrites rules and erases traditional
boundaries. Nowhere is this truer than in the area of taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the corporate income tax. In the physical world, US
companies are subject to local, state, and federal tax laws. In the
Internet world, companies need not be physically located anywhere
in the United States to do business with the world's largest
consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the idea of moving a company from a place where
taxation was considered onerous to a place where taxation was
considered less onerous was problematic. It cost a lot of money and
involved a ton of aggravation. If the company was moved overseas or
off-shore, there were real concerns about political stability,
labor pools, delivery of materials, existing infrastructure and the
like. There were ample reasons to just suck it up and pay the
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world of e-commerce, you can move a really big
company from Virginia to the Cayman Islands in two days. FedEx can
ship the computer servers and modems overnight. You plug all the
hardware into a satellite telecommunications system and _ presto _
America On Line is now a registered corporation in the Cayman
Islands, paying no federal, state or local corporate income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the information age, companies can be
``headquartered'' anywhere there is low or no taxation without
losing market share. My wife works for an advertising and marketing
company that last year paid more than $200 million in corporate
income taxes. Why would they continue to do that if they didn't
have to? Eighty percent of what they actually do can be converted
to the Web in 10 years. The rest is meetings.
</P>
<P>
   If 40 percent of all business commerce in 2006 takes place on
the Internet, it stands to reason that by 2015, more than
two-thirds of all business transactions will be e-commerce. It also
stands to reason that new and improved technologies will
dramatically increase consumer e-commerce. If the majority of all
business transactions and a large number of consumer sales are
occurring on the Web, what difference does it make where a company
is based? Companies will be based in cyberspace, out of reach of
traditional taxing authorities.
</P>
<P>
   This is why so much of the current debate in Washington about
tax policy has such a hollow ring to it. It is discussed in the
context of a model that soon will no longer apply. In the near
future, the policy-makers are going to have to create a new
taxation model. That model almost certainly will have to be based
on consumption taxes. Corporate income taxes will soon be made moot
by Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
