<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH PRIMARIES ON HORIZON, SOUTH ATTRACTS PRESIDENTIAL CONTENDERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SEAN LOUGHLIN AND CARL HULSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the azaleas in bloom and spring in the air,
the presidential contenders for 2000 are heading South, hoping some
early spade work will blossom into money and support.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican field, candidates appear to be focusing on
different states. Arizona Sen. John McCain has built an impressive
organization in South Carolina while conservative commentator Pat
Buchanan is concentrating on Louisiana, where he won the early
party caucuses four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer, New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith
and former Vice President Dan Quayle also have Louisiana on their
Southern tours.
</P>
<P>
   Florida isn't proving to be much of a GOP draw as yet despite it
sizable bloc of GOP voters because many party activists assume
Texas Gov. George W. Bush will lock up support there with the help
of his younger brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina political activists are feeling some frustration.
The state's relatively late primary _ May 4 of next year _ makes it
something of an afterthought for candidates looking to build
momentum with earlier wins in New Hampshire, Iowa, South Carolina
and the Super Tuesday states.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, a North Carolina native, has brought some
presidential attention to the state, but, interestingly, her
candidacy has not yet generated much enthusiasm in the South.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Tar Heel state legislators, for example, have
endorsed Bush. In neighboring South Carolina, GOP executive
director Trey Walker was almost dismissive of Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Salisbury, North Carolina, doesn't translate into
being a South Carolinian,'' Walker said of any possible Dole
advantage. Besides, Walker added, ``She's not lived in North
Carolina for a long time. She's a national figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle visited South Carolina and is planning trips to Alabama.
Former Tennessee governor Lamar Alexander has already been to
Birmingham this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody really has an edge yet,'' said Chris Neeley, executive
director of the Alabama GOP.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic front, Al Gore appears to have the Southern
stage to himself for now. He's regularly in Florida and flew to
Alabama to pick up the endorsement of Gov. Don Siegelman. His only
rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, has so far been
virtually invisible in the South.
</P>
<P>
   CARTE BLANCHE WITH TOBACCO SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   The nation's governors are ecstatic that Congress is about to
grant them carte blanche over the $246 billion states won from the
tobacco companies in the national settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in an emergency spending bill that is high on the
congressional agenda is a provision authored by Sens. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, and Bob Graham, D-Fla., that would block any
Clinton administration claim on the funds and let states spend the
money as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   But tobacco foes say states won't be the only winners if the
measure passes. They say the tobacco companies, losers in the legal
fight, will also come out ahead if none of the money is required to
be spent on reducing smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco companies are certain to be elated if the states
get all the settlement money without being required to spend it on
tobacco prevention,'' said the Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids,
which wants 25 percent of the money earmarked for such efforts.
</P>
<P>
   CROSSING THE AISLE
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Southern Democrats are forging a close relationship
with the new Speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert, an Illinois
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's Bud Cramer and Louisiana's Chris John were among
others who worked with Hastert on several recent issues, including
the GOP budget resolution and a Republican education initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has bent over backward to meet with us to talk about some
of the issues,'' said John.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Cramer, head of the Blue Dog coalition, was part
of a bipartisan, Hastert-led delegation that flew to Europe for a
spring recess work trip. The congressional travelers visited
Germany, Lithuania, Britain and Ireland, meeting with leaders to
discuss currency developments and the crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Given his narrow majority in the House, Hastert knows he needs
the support of conservative Democrats to keep his agenda moving.
</P>
<P>
   VISITING LOS ALAMOS
</P>
<P>
   While much of official Washington remains fixated on the bombing
of Yugoslavia, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., has another crisis on
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Senate Select Committee on Intelligence,
Shelby wants to get to the bottom of what happened with reported
espionage by the Chinese at a U.S. nuclear laboratory in New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He organized a committee trip to the Los Alamos National
Laboratory for this weekend with plans to meet with senior managers
at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This visit represents an excellent opportunity to see first
hand what is going on in the wake of revelations about possible
theft of some of our most important nuclear secrets,'' Shelby said.
``We must understand what happened and fix the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group)
</P>
</TEXT>
