<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, April 10. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HUNGER (Washington) _ Hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians uprooted from their homes by the Serbs and now sealed
inside the borders of Kosovo are at increasing risk of starvation
as food stocks quickly dwindle, Clinton administration officials
said today. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ Soldiers bearing
conscription notices have come to Dragon Soc's house on three
separate occasions, most recently Thursday morning, to demand that
he come with them to their barracks near the airport. Soc says he
regards these invites as a provocation for civil war. And he ought
to know. He is the Minister of Justice for the Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ The United States said Friday it
had reports of the systematic rape of Kosovo women at a Yugoslav
army training camp and said about 20 of them had been killed. NATO
says it might have hit civilians in the Kosovo capital of Pristina.
Robin Cook, the British foreign secretary, disparages in advance a
new peace proposal expected from Yugoslavia. Other developments. By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Developments in Russia as politics
continues to mix with the Kosovo crisis: President Boris Yeltsin
warns NATO against using ground troops; the Kremlin denies a
statement by the Communist speaker of parliament that missiles have
been re-aimed at NATO countries. The speaker, seeming to go for the
pan-Slav vote, also calls for a union of Serbia, Russia and
Belarus. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: Why the WTO
deal didn't happen, and whether it had more to do with Congress,
labor or the Chinese. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-PRESIDENT (Caracas, Venezuela) _ To the adoring,
impoverished masses who catapulted him to power, Hugo Chavez Frias
is El Comandante, their protector and benefactor, the bold leader
who will wipe out 40 years of inequality and corruption and
redirect this country's enormous oil wealth to better their lives.
To his opponents, the 44-year-old former army paratrooper who is
Venezuela's new President represents something unsettling, even
dangerous. With his talk of ``revolution,'' his contempt for
institutions he calls decadent and his violent coup attempt seven
years ago, he strikes many of them as an autocrat in the making. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MCDOUGAL-TRIAL (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Susan McDougal's trial was
disrupted today when one of the 12 jurors deliberating her fate
brought a law book into the jury room. While the case apparently
could continue with 11 jurors, deliberations were suspended this
morning and a conference was held before U.S. District Judge George
Howard Jr. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DOCTOR-SLAIN (Undated) _ Nearly six months after a Buffalo
area doctor who performed abortions was shot to death at home by a
rifle-wielding sniper, law enforcement authorities reported
yesterday that they had found a rifle in woods behind the doctor's
house in Amherst, N.Y. While the finding of the rifle appeared to
be the biggest break in the case so far, it raised question among
friends and relatives of Dr. Barnett Slepian why local police and
the FBI did not used high technology methods to locate the rifle
much sooner. By Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   THRIFT-SUIT (Washington) _ A Federal judge tonight will order
the Government to pay between $1 billion and $2 billion to a
California thrift that nearly went bankrupt after Congress and the
Bush Administration imposed tougher accounting changes on the
industry a decade ago. The decision awarded to Glendale Federal
Bank one of the largest claims ever assessed against the Federal
Government and is significant for the legal precedent it may set
for the more than 120 other similar cases filed by existing and
moribund savings associations and their shareholders. By Stephen
Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move on the ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-BIOETHICS (Undated) _ Not since 1940 when City College
tried to hire an atheist and advocate of free love, Bertrand
Russell, has the appointment of an academic philosopher by an
American university created such an uproar. The choice of Peter
Singer, a world renowned animal rights advocate, for a chair in
bioethics at Princeton University's Center for Human Values, has
jolted this genteel college town as well as the field of bioethics.
Singer has defended, in certain circumstances, euthanasia, not only
for terminally ill adults but also for severely disabled infants.
By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   ROTHSCHILD-AUCTION (Undated) _ A year after the Austrian
government agreed to return about $40 million worth of art and
objects that had been confiscated by the Nazis to the Austrian
branch of the Rothschild family, members of the 256-year-old
banking dynasty have decided to sell the collection, stripping many
leading museums in Vienna who have had them on display since World
War II. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
</TEXT>
