<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: EVERYONE HAS AN APRIL MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, April 15)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in February I passed a woman walking down the street
wearing cutoffs and sandals, looking out of place among the rest of
us still swaddled in wool scarves and fleece jackets. She seemed
quite comfortable, however, and had the private smile of someone
who has just discovered it will not be cold and wet forever.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that she was from Des Moines and celebrating a
California day of relative balminess, but I imagined she was merely
having a premature April moment.
</P>
<P>
   We feel it in our own time, following our own clock and
thermostat. One day you just start having a spring attitude.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be the vernal equinox or Easter or Passover
or the day you move the clocks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It is the morning you'd rather be outside than in bed under the
comforter. Even if your coffee gets cold and the newspapers fly off
in the wind, you are summoned to walk out the door, sweep the old
leaves off the chair and sit shivering, to wait to be touched by
the sun.
</P>
<P>
   It is when you want to simply stare at a vase of pink tulips,
the color of ballet slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is about change and new possibilities. It also makes you
want to do something that feels slightly out of character, like
taking off your shoes and running through the high grass, or being
a kid and going to hunt tadpoles in the creek and bring pussy
willow branches home to your mother.
</P>
<P>
   If autumn is the time when people well past school age have an
overwhelming desire to get serious and go back to class, spring is
the time when responsible people yearn to hop on a motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   But not quite yet. Right before spring blinds you with its
enormous beauty, it draws you out with little promises and sneak
previews. In the middle of a gray day there will be one brief hour
when you know how it is to be needing sunglasses. For a moment the
bird song will be louder than traffic and the light on a patch of
forget-me-nots will stop you in your tracks.
</P>
<P>
   You never know how spring is going to come and get you. It may
tempt you to call in sick so you can sneak out to weed the garden,
get dirty and dream of delphiniums.
</P>
<P>
   It may have you consider wearing colors that go by the names of
melon and citrus instead of basic black.
</P>
<P>
   There's a decided change in your energy. A quickening. It's like
being pregnant. You suddenly need to clean the house and put away
your boots. You crave a bowl of strawberries. You are a little bit
giddy.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't be touched by spring stuck inside a building and
staring at a calendar. You don't get it merely by shifting from
gabardine to linen.
</P>
<P>
   The cat understands. No longer resentful when ordered outside,
she one day lifts her head, twitches her nose, leaps off the couch,
lands on the window ledge and begins pacing like a lover, ready for
the primo spot on the chaise lounge.
</P>
<P>
   We have the religious rituals for spring with the joyful songs,
the eggs and the lilies, and if we're pagans we can get into it by
lighting green candles, planting seeds and dancing with ribbons in
our hair.
</P>
<P>
   But culturally, except for baseball training and department
store sales, we don't do much. We need to bust out. Spend a day
pursuing only pleasure. Blast ``Carmina Burana'' from the city
square.
</P>
<P>
   Can you feel it? The Earth is turning. The wisteria is fat and
feathery. Ignore the little voice saying, ``Those legs are not
ready for shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
