<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV11-     04-09 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN'S BEST FRIEND, AND DOESN'T BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
(lh) 
 By GEORGEANNE BRENNAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Chinese proverb says, ``The only way to keep a family in
existence for generations is to think cabbage-stalks nice.'' The
humble cabbage has long been associated with poverty and endurance.
Since a bit of it, boiled, might be the only food available,
countless cooks have encouraged their families to like it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by the cold weather and frosts that kill other
vegetables, cabbage has long been a mainstay of humankind. It can
be stored for months and is edible raw or cooked, pickled or
salted. There is evidence that wild cabbages were commonly used as
early as 2000 B.C. in Europe, and the wild version (from which
brussels sprouts, broccoli and cauliflower were developed, along
with modern cabbage) still grows along the rocky chalk coasts of
England and Denmark, in parts of France and along the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Wild cabbage, which doesn't form a head, is thought to have been
domesticated first in the eastern Mediterranean, then taken to
Europe. By the Middle Ages, the kind with a head that is commonly
grown now was being cultivated, and early voyagers and settlers
took seeds to North America.
</P>
<P>
   In China, a different cabbage developed. There is no evidence of
wild cabbage there, so the Chinese cabbage is thought to be a cross
between the loose-heading bok choy of the south and the wild turnip
of the north. Records of the cultivation of Chinese cabbage date to
500 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   While originally loose and floppy-leafed like the European wild
cabbage, today's main types of headed Chinese cabbages are tightly
packed barrels or cylinders of leaves, called, respectively, nappa
and michihli. Chinese seeds also arrived in the United States with
immigrants. Various Chinese cabbages are available now, many of
them hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbages are such an important crop, especially in cold
climates, that hundreds of varieties have been developed that
mature from May through November, and in warmer climates, from
December through February as well.
</P>
<P>
   European, or head, cabbages, are classified in Byzantine
fashion, first for their head shape (with ``pointed,'' ``drumhead''
and ``round'' being the most common), and then by their harvest
season (early, mid or main, and late). They are also classified by
purpose, mainly fresh market, storage or sauerkraut- and
slaw-making.
</P>
<P>
   They are further distinguished by color (green, sometimes called
white after the interior leaves, and red) and by leaf shape. Savoy
cabbage, sometimes called Italian cabbage or chou de Milan, has
puckered or blistered leaves that are dark green outside and pale
green inside. Cabbages range from a pound or 2 up to 11 pounds for
the hulking sauerkraut varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Home gardeners can grow many cabbages that rarely make it into
homogeneous supermarket displays. It is important to choose and
plant them according to their seasons; most seed companies will
answer questions on this point or give the information in catalogs.
Plants can be started from seed or bought at nurseries. Once the
danger of frost has passed, seeds can be planted directly in the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Among the early varieties are the pointed-head Early Jersey
Wakefield, a 19th-century English heirloom with a fine, sweet
flavor. It is quick to grow, maturing in just over 60 days from
transplanting. Although it is an early type where winters are warm,
it is best planted in fall.
</P>
<P>
   Copenhagen Market Early is an old-time open-pollinated favorite,
with a crisp round head that is ready to harvest as early as June,
maturing in only 68 days from transplanting. Charmant, a hybrid, is
ready to harvest in 65 days. At the other end of the spectrum, some
sauerkraut varieties can take 110 days.
</P>
<P>
   The tasty red cabbages include Fire Dance, a hybrid that
requires 90 days from transplanting to produce a 3{-pound head, and
Red Jewel, which can be harvested at 1{ pounds, a good family size
for making sweet and sour red cabbage. For a home garden, it is a
good idea to make successive plantings of early, mid- and
late-season varieties to ensure a steady supply most of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Most Chinese cabbages have a shorter growing period than the
European cabbages, about 50 to 80 days. These are best planted from
May to July and, unlike European cabbages, tolerate warm weather.
They are likely to bolt, so use bolt-resistant varieties for
early-spring planting, like Eiki or Kasumi, among the nappa types,
or the michihli Jade Pagoda.
</P>
<P>
   Both European and Chinese cabbages require quite a bit of space
in the garden, with seeds initially planted 2 to 3 inches apart,
then thinned to 1{ to 2 feet apart in rows 2 feet apart for the
European, and somewhat less for the Chinese. Transplants can be put
in at the final spacing.
</P>
<P>
   Some sources for cabbage seeds: Stokes Seeds, P.O. Box 548,
Buffalo, NY 14240, (716) 695-6980 (free catalog; 43 varieties,
including Early Jersey Wakefield, Red Jewel, Fire Dance, Charmant
and Copenhagen Early Market; 9 varieties of heading Chinese
cabbages, including Jade Pagoda, plus a selection of loose-heading
types), and Reed's Seeds/Cabbage Specialists, 3334 State Route 215,
Cortland, NY 13045, (607) 753-9095 (free catalog; 63 varieties of
European cabbage, including Charmant).
</P>
<P>
   This Week: Nematodes, for a Good Night's Sleep
</P>
<P>
   Black vine weevil is as destructive as it sounds: Its larvae
feed on and destroy the roots of rhododendrons (a favorite),
daphnes, roses, blueberries and many other shrubs. Some people wait
until adults emerge in summer, hand-picking them by the hundreds at
night when they feed. But it's more effective to spray the soil now
with beneficial microscopic nematodes that control the weevil's
grubs and those of cutworms and Japanese beetles.
</P>
<P>
   Introduce plants like fennel, yarrow, bee balm and tansy that
will attract insects that devour aphids, scale and mealybugs.
Divide overcrowded snowdrops (Galanthus species) when they finish
blooming. Lift and replant immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Many Easter lilies will bloom again next year if planted
outside. After they flower, cut back the flower stem to the base
and plant in soil amended with organic fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   _ PATRICIA JONAS
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
