<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA SEEKS RELEASE OF 2 AID WORKERS HELD BY YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yugoslavia seized two Australian aid workers nine days ago,
Australia said Friday, a development that has heightened concerns
of Slobodan Milosevic's possible use of foreigners as human
shields.
</P>
<P>
   Following the failure of private efforts to free the two men,
Australia Friday issued a public appeal for their release. The men
were arrested at the Yugoslav-Croatian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can think of no reason for them to be held, and every
reason for them to be released,'' said Malcolm Fraser, the former
Australian prime minister and director of CARE Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser identified the two as Steve Pratt, operations manager of
CARE Australia's office in Yugoslavia; and Peter Wallace, another
member of the office. He said Australia had received assurances
from Yugoslavia's deputy prime minister, Vuk Draskovic, that the
two were safe and in good health.
</P>
<P>
   By making a public appeal, Fraser is hoping the two aid workers
will not be left behind if President Milosevic's government
eventually makes good on promises to free three US servicemen
captured during a reconnaissance mission near the
Yugoslav-Macedonia border. Both the soldiers and the aid workers
were seized March 31.
</P>
<P>
   CARE Australia joined other aid groups in pulling out of
Yugoslavia's troubled Kosovo province ahead of NATO's air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, 49, and Wallace, 30, were headed to neighboring Croatia
when they were arrested by Yugoslav border guards, said Fraser, in
Boston for a conference at Harvard University's Kennedy School of
Government.
</P>
<P>
   The two were en route to the Yugoslav republic of Macedonia to
set up a camp for Kosovar Albanians driven out by Yugoslav
Milosevic's forces, Fraser said. He had no details on why they were
detained.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers said the capture underlines the dangers of doing
good in turbulent places. US and NATO officials have previously
expressed fears of Kosovar Albanians and other foreigners being
used as human shields to deter NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fear is something aid workers feel every day. Aid is put
on the front lines every day. We are looking at brave people who
are on the front lines who just want to help poor people,'' said
Rita Stone-Smith, a spokesman for CARE-USA in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser and aid workers, seeking more details on the detention,
remain mystified on why Yugoslavia would target members of a
non-NATO nation, uninvolved in the current bombing campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
