<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-FEUD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 49ERs SUE OUSTED CO-OWNER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The corporation that controls the San Francisco
49ers has sued ousted co-owner Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. in a
stunning move that could kill any chance of a quick end to the
family feud that is casting doubt over the future of the team's
$525 million stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo was accused Thursday in the lawsuit filed in San
Francisco Superior Court of reneging on a $94 million debt to the
corporation and cutting a side deal on the stadium project with the
developer of an adjoining mall, the Mills Corp. of Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged deal would have paid him $10 million and given him a
22 percent interest in the mall, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's conduct, the lawsuit said, ``jeopardizes the team,
the stadium project, and the interests of the greater San Francisco
community.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's spokesman, Rick Rice, denied the charges and said
DeBartolo intended to countersue for more than $100 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawsuit is a sad and desperate act,'' Rice said, saying it
was intended to keep DeBartolo from controlling the club and from
regaining an ``equal say in the running of the family businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The football team is controlled by the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp.
of Youngstown, Ohio, which is co-owned by DeBartolo and his sister,
Denise DeBartolo York, the corporation's chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   The siblings have been sparring for more than a year over
ownership of the team and its future. In late February, York placed
her husband, John York, in charge of the football team and ordered
Niners personnel not to answer DeBartolo's questions about the team
or allow him access to the club's cash without her written
approval.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, sources said DeBartolo owed the corporation more
than $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how the lawsuit filed Thursday
would affect the long-delayed plans for the stadium and adjoining
mall, originally intended to be completed by the 2003 football
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Singer, a spokesman for the DeBartolo Corp., said the
company remained committed to the project.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the club said, ``Anytime you get in a lawsuit,
it puts a damper on things, but it doesn't keep the corporation
from doing the work to make the stadium and mall a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit shows that ``if you lie down with crooks, you're
going to get dirty,'' said Doug Comstock, a leader of the Committee
to Stop the Giveaway. The group has sued to overturn the June 1997
ballot propositions narrowly approved by San Francisco voters that
gave the 49ers a green light for the stadium and mall and
authorized $100 million in city bonds for construction of the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit's allegation that DeBartolo engaged in
``self-dealing'' in a side arrangement with Mills ``is just
beautiful _ it makes my day,'' Comstock said.
</P>
<P>
   National Football League commissioner Paul Tagliabue suspended
DeBartolo from activity related to the Niners through February
2001. The suspension came after DeBartolo pleaded guilty in October
to a federal felony for his role in a Louisiana
gambling-and-bribery case. He has had no official position of
authority in the DeBartolo corporation or with the 49ers since
December 1997, when he stepped down voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accuses DeBartolo of, among other things, ``verbally
abusing team officers'' and ``charging substantial personal
expenses to the team.'' It also accuses him of ``orchestrating
meetings regarding the stadium project, arranging off-site meetings
of team managers, and demanding a voice in team affairs including
... top management and other personnel and player issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
