<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH ABOUT `NO-GAS FRIDAY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 30, you, gentle reader, can bring the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries to its knees. And, even better, see
gasoline prices plummet.
</P>
<P>
   That's the claim behind the latest chain-letter e-mail making
the Internet rounds. It calls for a No-Gas Friday on April 30;
purchases are to be made on the day before or the day after.
</P>
<P>
   That tactic won't make one whit of difference in the price of a
gallon of gasoline, which, even after creeping up 15 cents or so in
past weeks, is still priced at its lowest level in decades. But
this idea could have another _ albeit misdirected _ result: It
could show the power of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   First, here's the text, sent by an anonymous author and passed
along by millions:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time we did something about the price of gasoline in
America! We are all sick and tired of high prices when there are
literally millions of gallons in storage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know what I found out? If there was just ONE day when no one
purchased any gasoline, prices would drop drastically. The
so-called oil cartel has decided to slow production by some 2
million barrels per day to drive up the price. I have decided to
see how many Americans we can get to NOT BUY ANY GASOLINE on one
particular day!
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's have a GAS OUT! Do not buy any gasoline on APRIL 30,
1999!!!!!
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy on Thursday before, or Saturday after. Do not buy any
gasoline on FRIDAY, APRIL 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is a few million to participate in order to make a
difference. We CAN make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you get the impression that this is written by the same type
of person who writes about the viruses you can get by opening
e-mail ``SO DON'T OPEN `WIN A HOLIDAY' OR YOUR VCR WILL STOP
FLASHING 12:00!!!''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, there are all-capital letters here and the obligatory row
of exclamation points designed to lend urgency to the message.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another thing that's troubling: ``Know what I found out?
If there was just ONE day when no one purchased any gasoline,
prices would drop drastically.''
</P>
<P>
   Sez who?
</P>
<P>
   Where do you suppose the writer learned of such economic theory?
Alan Greenspan? Jay Leno? Cher? There's no attribution.
</P>
<P>
   I'd bet it wasn't Federal Reserve Board Chairman Greenspan. He
knows too much about economic theory, particularly about the
supply-and-demand part that works like this:
</P>
<P>
   OPEC isn't getting the prices it wants for its oil, so it cuts
production. That means there's less gas to go around, and people
who want it will bid up the price for what's left.
</P>
<P>
   The prices go up because the demand has not decreased along with
the supply.
</P>
<P>
   What does No-Gas Friday propose to do? It simply wants to move
the purchase date of gasoline from Friday to a day before or a day
after. Only the date of purchase has been changed _ not the demand
for gas.
</P>
<P>
   Customers are buying gas on a different day, but in the scheme
of things, no one has reduced consumption one ounce. Do you really
think OPEC cares if you don't buy gas collectively on a Friday or a
Wednesday _ so long as you buy the same amount?
</P>
<P>
   But that's one of the reasons this message is making such quick
rounds on the Internet: It requires no real sacrifice on anyone's
part, yet some great amount of good is supposed to be the end
result.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the e-mail (hoaxes, I'll warn now, so you don't fall
for them) messages that tell you to send copies of the e-mail to
the American Cancer Society (or some organization) and they'll
donate $5,000 to research for every 10,000 copies they receive.
``Buy gas on a day other than Friday and OPEC will send gasoline
prices tumbling.''
</P>
<P>
   No skin off your nose. Plenty of skin off the kneecaps of Saudi
kings when they hit the desert sand begging consumers to buy gas on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Let's also remember that gasoline prices have dropped in the
past decade, reaching their lowest point last year _ on an
inflation-adjusted basis _ in 30 years. We're now supposed to
launch a one-day boycott because gas prices are still at their
lowest prices in years?
</P>
<P>
   Why do I bother to even pass the message along?
</P>
<P>
   Unintentionally, this e-mail may have a different result than
its goal.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices aren't going to tumble because we buy gas on
Thursday or Saturday instead. But what it could demonstrate is the
tremendous influence, communication power, and consumer-buying
power of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And if you'd like to give the clueless a clue about what the
Internet is all about, you might want to stay away from the gas
pumps on April 30. You might even want to buy gasoline on Friday,
April 16, and again on Friday, April 23, leading up to the
last-Friday-in-April Gas Out to make the impact even more
noticeable.
</P>
<P>
   Before you decide to participate, I'll point to a cautionary
flag raised by Barbara Mikkelson, who helps run The San Fernando
Valley Folklore Society's Urban Legends Reference Pages
(www.snopes.com). She debunked the ``No-Gas Friday'' e-mail
recently and noted: ``Who's to say that service stations won't
simply cash in on a bonanza by jacking up their prices the day
after the great gas out?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   Will they notice in OPEC headquarters? They'll miss Friday
purchases as much as if someone had stolen a grain of sand from the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   Will they notice in corporate offices in America? If they're
smart they will.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
