<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2512 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-SUMMIT-$ADV11-HN     04-09 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITAL GIRDS FOR GRIDLOCK AND TIGHT SECURITY AT NATO SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you're planning a spring vacation in the
nation's capital on the weekend of April 23-25, you might want to
think again.
</P>
<P>
   The city is in a dither preparing for NATO's 50th anniversary
celebration, a weekend of pomp, parties and police dogs. U.S.
officials hosting the delegates from the 19 NATO nations are
bracing for the largest Washington gathering of foreign leaders
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The festive event was planned long before NATO began military
attacks last month against Yugoslavia. Suddenly, in the middle of
NATO's first-ever attack on a sovereign country, security concerns
are threatening to overwhelm what should have been a celebration of
allied unity and victory in the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Although few details have been released, streets for blocks
around the White House will be closed during the summit to local
traffic as 1,700 dignitaries _ including 42 heads of states _ and
3,000 international media representatives descend in miles of
motorcades.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say security demands will require rerouting of traffic
and a small army of bomb-sniffing dogs, Secret Service,
metropolitan police, U.S. Park Police, State Department security
personnel and agents from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Most official summit activity will take place between the White
House and the Ronald Reagan Building several blocks east on
Pennsylvania Avenue. Other summit events will stretch across town,
from Capitol Hill to Vice President Gore's residence on embassy row
along Massachusetts Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government is so concerned about the gridlock caused by
the security requirements and 40-plus motorcades that 90,000
federal employees are being told to stay home on Friday, April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a city long accustomed to car-bomb barriers and stretch
limousines, the birthday party for the NATO alliance founded in
1949 as a counterweight to the Soviet Union is a major event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it as a state visit times 50,'' said Mary Anne
Reynolds, a spokeswoman for the Greater Washington Board of Trade,
the regional chamber of commerce for the Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of workers are hammering out logistics. The executive
branch has opened an office with 50 employees to work on questions
of security, hotel rooms, food and transportation for the
delegations.
</P>
<P>
   The total price tag for the event is estimated at about $24
million, with the U.S. government contributing $16 million to $18
million, and private donations picking up the rest, according to
Kim Rubey, a spokeswoman for the NATO summit.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Hargrove, vice president of Hargrove Inc., in suburban
Lanham, Md., which is providing the stage sets and tables for the
meetings, said ``it isn't quite as big as an inauguration for us
because there aren't the parades and galas, but it's close.''
</P>
<P>
   The event will kick off on April 23 with a military ceremony
outside the Andrew Mellon Auditorium, site of the signing of the
original NATO treaty, on Constitution Avenue. The gathering will be
the first attended by NATO's three newest members: Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, foreign ministers from the 19 NATO countries
will move into the auditorium for a meeting of the North Atlantic
Council, NATO's governing political body. The meeting, which is
likely to focus on the current crisis in Yugoslavia and shaping
NATO for future peacekeeping missions, continues through the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, the NATO representatives will meet with
foreign ministers from 25 central and eastern European countries
which once were in the Soviet orbit to discuss military security
matters in the post-Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
   The summit concludes Sunday with a press conference by NATO
secretary General Javier Solana. NATO officials are expected to
unveil what they call a new strategic concept for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from sobering matters of state, there are parties, galas,
banquets and schmooze opportunities galore.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is hosting a dinner for the leaders of the
NATO countries; Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Secretary
of Defense Cohen are hosting a dinner for foreign and defense
ministers; Hillary Clinton is hosting a luncheon for the spouses of
heads of state; Tipper Gore is planning a luncheon. And those are
just a few.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the diplomatic corps is planning parties at
embassies across town.
</P>
<P>
   The menus are varied for the weekend, but the emphasis is on
American-style food.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't going to be a lot of fancy-shmancy European fare''
like caviar, said Susan Lacz, a partner at Ridgewell's Caterer,
Bethesda, Md., one of the area's largest caterers.
</P>
<P>
   Dignitaries coming to the United States usually expect American
food, Lacz said. ``We're going to serve traditional American foods
like lamb and asparagus and tenderloin of beef,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most pressing logistical feats is transportation for
low- and mid-level dignitaries who don't merit their own limousines
and motorcades.
</P>
<P>
   That job is managed by Event Pro-ssss, an event-planning company
in Silver Spring, Md. Sue Fern, a managing partner at the firm,
said 80 buses will be on hand to shuttle the delegations. ``We are
having high-caliber, high-quality buses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kane, a vice president of International Limousine
service which is providing about 35 buses for the NATO festivities,
said his drivers are girding for long days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to be moving people around town about 19 hours a
day,'' said Kane, with many runs to the region's three airports and
Andrews Air Force Base to pick up delegations and stragglers.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service is demanding that all bus drivers undergo
extensive background checks. Each vehicle will be searched for
weapons and bombs when seeking entry to an area sealed off to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Housing the crush of diplomats and international media hasn't
been difficult because the city has ample space, about 24,000 hotel
rooms, said Dan Mobley, president of the Washington, D.C.
Convention and Visitors Association.
</P>
<P>
   But a deft diplomatic hand at the State Department was
occasionally required to sort out conflicting hotel requests from
different delegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem was that some delegations from different
countries like the same hotels,'' said Mobley. ``Several countries
might want Hotel X and everybody can't have Hotel X.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
