<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GITMO-0410-COX     04-09 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GITMO-0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GUANTANAMO BAY PREPARED FOR REFUGEES ... BUT WILL ANYONE COME?
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI -- Aritonne Georges grew up in Haiti, the western
hemisphere's poorest country. At age 21, he spent three days at sea
aboard a flimsy boat in an attempt to escape a brutal military
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he claims he passed the worst days of his life at Guantanamo
Bay, the U.S. Navy base in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toilets spilled over and no one bothered to clean them,''
said Georges, 28, a Lake Worth, Fla., resident who stayed at the
base for a month in 1992. ``You had to wait two hours in the hot
sun to get your meals.''
</P>
<P>
   Georges said he prays none of the Kosovo refugees ever steps
foot on the base, some 4,700 miles from their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of that happening, however, was announced
Tuesday by President Clinton. He said the United States would
provide temporary refuge for up to 20,000 Albanian victims of the
Kosovo crisis there.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, some administration officials hinted the plan might
be scrapped because refugees are being better cared for in Albania,
Macedonia, and in other parts of Europe thanks to widespread relief
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And many refugees have expressed a desire to stay close to home.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, officials said they planned to retain the option of
housing refugees in Cuba. They said that just because Kosovo
refugees aren't anxious to go now does not mean they won't want to
go in two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This option may look more attractive to refugees down the
road,'' said Navy Lt. Jane Campbell of the U.S. Southern Command,
or Southcom. ``This may be an option the U.S. government keeps open
for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin acknowledged Friday
that -- for now -- most refugees aren't interested in being moved
to foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``we are prepared to implement our commitment, but the
commitment will be determined by what is required on the ground,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southcom officials continued Friday to prepare the dusty,
45-square-mile base for the refugees, saying they could immediately
accommodate 500 people, and up to 7,500 in one or two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They said ``several hundred'' planners, medical personnel, and
U.S. Army engineers from bases in Puerto Rico were due in Cuba over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the military transported enough lumber from Gulfport,
Miss., to build frames for at least 100 tents. The military is also
searching for linguists fluent in Albanian, and has found a Muslim
chaplain in the U.S. Atlantic fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that there's a strong reconsideration of the entire
plan, but we're still driving onward unless we're told to stop,''
said Southcom's Lt. Col. John Snyder of Southcom.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Charles E. Wilhelm, the head of Southcom, which oversees
military operations in the Caribbean and Central and South America,
visited Guantanamo Bay on Thursday to check on preparations. He was
expected to make a return trip within the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   Civilians who have spent time at Guantanamo Bay said they're
appalled that preparations continue, while refugee officials --
including the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees --
urged the Clinton administration to scratch the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat and the isolation and the mosquitoes, which are
called teeth because they hurt so bad, are enough to drive most
people nuts,'' said Joyce Feilke, a school counselor from Austin,
Texas, who worked on the base in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place is so isolated that living there feels like living
on Mars,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Feilke and others argue that Kosovo refugees --already
traumatized at the hands of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
-- should be housed at a comfortable, less-isolated location on the
U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can accommodate more than 20,000 people at rock concerts in
Austin,'' she said. ``Believe me, they'd be happier staying at a
campsite here than in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugee advocates also protested an announcement by the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service that refugees at Guantanamo
Bay would not be allowed to apply for political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the U.S. Committee for Refugees, a private
humanitarian group in Washington, estimated it would cost the
United States $180 million to house 20,000 Kosovars in Cuba for six
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe money should be put into helping Albania and
Macedonia care for them,'' said John Fredriksson, associate
executive director. ``We hope the administration will completely
change its policy by early next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hammer, a spokesman for the National Security Council in
Washington, said preparations at Guantanamo Bay will continue,
although no one will be forced to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we've heard any cries of outrage over the idea
of going to Cuba,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is figuring out the logistics of offering people
the option of going to different places,'' he said. ``It's not like
we have one table set up for Turkey, and one set up for Germany,
and then one for Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said no refugee has even been ``formally asked'' to go to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps over the weekend we might learn if anyone wants to
come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. plan to shelter refugees in Cuba has drawn a unique
offer of cooperation from the Cuban government, which condemns the
NATO attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human beings are really suffering and so the Cuban government
wants to support these people any way it can,'' said Luis
Fernandez, a spokesman for the Cuban Interests Section in
Washington. ``We offer our assistance, especially medical
assistance, which we're in a better position to give than food.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   The government of Fidel Castro objects to the U.S. presence at
Guantanamo Bay, some 620 miles from Havana. It which was leased in
perpetuity to the United States by Cuba's pre-revolutionary
government.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, the base was used to house some 50,000 Cubans
and Haitians trying to reach the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When he was there, Georges said, he shared a tent the size of a
typical U.S. bedroom with 15 other Haitian men. The tent had no
windows, meaning almost no air circulated inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would sit in that hot tent, day after day, playing cards or
dominoes, always wondering when we'd be able to get out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a prison,'' he said. ``I almost went insane.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
