<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPER-SCOTCHES-$ADV11     04-09 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-SCOTCHES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAT WALLETS AND PRICEY SCOTCH: WHISKEY AS RARE AS FINE WINE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A broken barrel stave found in the 1970s. Britain's
wartime energy pinch. What could such historical flotsam have to do
with modern American liquor chic?
</P>
<P>
   Ask the drinkers who pay up to $980 to taste one shot of fine
single-malt whiskey. Their palates and wallets, and their interest
in the curious origins of some of their favorite tipples, have set
off a scramble by Scottish distillers and their American marketers
to uncover ever rarer, more exotic single malts. Unlike blended
whiskeys, single malts are those produced in a single distillery in
a single production run.
</P>
<P>
   Single-malt drinking has become something between a mini-boom
and a cult phenomenon in some American bars, and the most prized
bottles can be as avidly pursued by as fine old Bordeaux: The
Macallan '46, for instance, is sold (mainly to collectors) at
$2,500 a bottle, and the Bowmore 40 _ referring to its age, not a
year _ brings $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   The cachet of top single malts like these rubs off on sibling
whiskies. ``In marketing jargon, it's the halo effect,'' said David
Cox, marketing controller for the Macallan brand at Highland
Distillers. ``It elevates the quality image of the whole range.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarcity is part of the appeal. ``People love the fact that it
can never happen again,'' said James French, of Remy Amerique, the
unit of Remy Cointreau that markets The Macallan in the United
States. ``Once you've got a bottle of that, there's no more left.''
The Macallan distillery turns out 220,000 12-bottle cases a year
these days, but only 250 cases were ever made of the Macallan '46 _
and 150 of them were exported, mostly to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowmore 40, produced by Morrison Bowmore Distillers, is even
rarer. Just 294 bottles were produced, said Anne Riives, who
handles the company's public relations in New York, and only 60
were shipped to America. Burglars stole a bottle from a Canadian
store, Ms. Riives said, and told the owner, `` `Pay us $3,000 or
the bottle gets it.''' The store did not pay and the whiskey was
not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Collectors buy by the bottle, but drinkers buy by the shot, at
astonishing prices. A shot of Bowmore 40 fetches $980 at the Hole
in One bar on Second Avenue in Manhattan; other rare malts cost up
to $385 a shot, and The Macallan '46 usually runs to $250.
</P>
<P>
   Who is paying? Recent recipients of fat Wall Street bonuses are
often cited. ``It's the result of a very healthy economy for six
years,'' said Michael Stoner, of Schieffelin &AMP; Somerset, which
markets the huge United Distillers and Vintners line in the United
States. ``This is an indulgence that people can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming at a time when Americans are buying less imported blended
whiskey, the high-end single-malt phenomenon has distillers hunting
for ever more arcane whiskies to offer. ``There has been an
enormous proliferation of expensive, rare bottlings,'' Stoner said.
But though the special bottlings grab the headlines, the single
malts selling for $30 to $60 a bottle drive the market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1997, imports of leading single-malt Scotch
whiskies almost doubled, to the equivalent of 512,000 nine-liter
cases, according to the Adams Liquor Handbook; the much larger
volume of blended scotch imports fell 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Experts don't think drinkers of blended scotch are switching to
single malts. ``They are not the same guys,'' Stoner said. ``The
single-malt game is 25- to 50-year-olds coming in without drinking
scotch before.'' If blended scotch is associated with
run-of-the-mill watering holes, single malts evoke upscale spots
where a shot is accompanied by a fine cigar or, at least, a
discussion of the whiskey's pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fair amount of ritual that goes along with it,''
Stoner said. ``The first sip is so important: they look and smell
it first, swirl it around and they love the ritual of it. For a
moment there, they are very alone with their favorite malt.''
</P>
<P>
   Single-malt whiskies are usually aged in wooden casks previously
used for other beverages, most often Spanish sherry or bourbon.
Distillers now try to invent new candidates for special single-malt
bottlings by shifting liquor among different combinations of casks
as it ages. But the top single malts got their special
characteristics largely by chance.
</P>
<P>
   While taking inventory in late 1997, David Robertson, Macallan's
whiskey maker, found six vats that had been aging unnoticed since
1946. On tasting it, he found a remarkable smoky ``nose,'' Cox
said, which was traced to a short-lived wartime switch to burning
peat for fuel in the distillery when coal was rationed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bowmore 40 was another accident. ``When it was made, nobody
had any intention of keeping it for 40 years,'' Ms. Riives said.
But, 20 years into its maturing, an apprentice cooper, Jim McEwan,
discovered a broken stave on a sherry cask full of whiskey. He
salvaged what he could and put it in a bourbon hogshead.
</P>
<P>
   His career took him away from the distillery, and the switched
barrel was overlooked for another two decades, until McEwan
returned to Bowmore as general manager and recognized his
handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tastes absolutely amazing,'' Ms. Riives said. ``At the end,
you get a little whiff of spice. If anything, it's exotic tropical
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was a complete fluke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
