<HEADER>
A2537 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV11     04-09 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING COLUMN: FIRST STRIKES AGAINST BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds to
readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them by
e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, N.Y.
10036.  
 (bl)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am black and a middle manager at a large company. Before
joining it several years ago, I made sure the company had strong
anti-discrimination policies and rising numbers of black and
Hispanic employees. But now it's apparent that members of racial
minority groups are concentrated in departments like public
relations and human resources, with limited prospects for
promotion. Some colleagues are considering a group complaint to the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. Should I join them, or
should I try to find a department that gives blacks the best
chances? Or should I leave?
</P>
<P>
   A. What you should do depends a great deal on what kind of
person you are _ and what cost you are willing to pay _ because
there really is no way forward without a price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are revolutionaries,'' said Ralph Dechabert,
director of diversity and employee relations at American President
Lines, a shipping company based in Oakland, Calif. ``When they
perceive injustice, they voice displeasure, push overtly, try to
kick in doors. Other people are reformers who say, `I will work
from within.''' The risk for revolutionaries is to find themselves
marginalized; for reformers, to appear to have been co-opted.
</P>
<P>
   Filing a complaint with the EEOC is the revolutionary's path.
You will get your employer's attention, but it is often not the
best first step.
</P>
<P>
   Executives can ``get into a defensive mode,'' said Kevin
Bradley, diversity manager at R.R. Donnelley &AMP; Sons, the commercial
printer in Chicago, which was sued by a group of African-American
former employees in 1996 over allegations of discrimination in
layoffs and transfers. Once a threat of legal action is in the air,
he said, opportunities to discuss the issue rationally and
professionally are more limited.
</P>
<P>
   Opening lines of communication and gathering information about
the problem _ the reformer's path _ is generally a smarter way to
start, said Bradley, who advised finding both minority and
nonminority managers with whom you feel comfortable airing
concerns. ``Talk to people who have been in the trenches and may be
able to help you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a personal level, if you feel undervalued for whatever
reason, you may want to transfer to another department. But
gravitating toward bosses who are seen as giving blacks the best
opportunities may be what caused the imbalance in the first place.
Rather than being shunted there deliberately by the company,
employees may be choosing to work in peripheral departments because
that's where the most enlightened bosses are. Consider whether a
move to a more supportive department is ``putting you in the
mainstream or taking you out,'' Dechabert said. ``Then decide if
you're willing to make that kind of trade-off.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can leave the company, but even that has a price.
A common corporate excuse for falling short of diversity goals is a
lack of good candidates in the pipeline, Dechabert said. ``If you
move on,'' he said, ``you make that real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XIAO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-09 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XIAO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`XIAO WU': PORTRAIT OF A THIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like ``Tokyo Eyes'' and ``Trans,'' which are also in the New
Directors/New Films series, the Chinese film ``Xiao Wu'' deals with
a young criminal alienated from his society.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance he is the title character, a nondescript young
man in a shabby city who practices his trade without remorse,
compassion or evident fear although he is known to police, who are
in the midst of a crackdown on crime announced in broadcasts
audible in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   As skillfully written and directed by Jia Zhang Ke, a product of
the Beijing Film Academy who uses a nonprofessional cast, the
cool-eyed ``Xiao Wu'' appears to be more than a relatively
nonjudgmental portrait of an emotionally repressed young thief
turned against the weight of conformity.
</P>
<P>
   The film is also a commentary on a society in flux. Xiao Wu's
old partner in crime is now a wealthy entrepreneur, a cigarette
wholesaler and club operator who is interviewed on television on
the eve of a lavish wedding at which Xiao is pointedly unwelcome.
But in Xiao's eyes, little has changed except nomenclature:
Trafficking in cigarettes is now free trade and running clubs
filled with bar girls is the entertainment business.
</P>
<P>
   Around the rundown city, tenants of small shops are being
evicted so buildings can be torn down to make way for more modern
structures. Mei Mei, the pretty club girl who manages to touch
Xiao's heart and make him drop some of his reserve, promptly runs
off with someone clearly more wealthy and financially stable. And
when Xiao returns to his native village, where he is condemned by
his father, it is a community still living in a past of peasantry,
tradition, dirt roads and crude dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   It is an irony of this film that Xiao is undone by that modern
instrument of communication, the pager, and that in the end, his
skilled hands are shackled.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `XIAO WU'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Jia Zhang Ke; in the Shaanxi dialect of
the Mandarin language, with English subtitles; director of
photography, Yu Lik Wai; edited by Lin Xiaoling; produced by Li
Kit-ming. Saturday at 9 p.m. and Sunday at noon at the Roy and
Niuta Titus Theater, Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St.,
Manhattan, as part of the 28th New Directors/New Films series of
the Film Society of Lincoln Center and the Department of Film of
the Museum of Modern Art. Running time: 107 minutes. This film is
not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Wang Hong Wei (Xiao Wu), Hao Hong Jian (Xiou Yong) and Zu
Bai Tao (Mei Mei).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
