<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; taf-z
p r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMISSION-REPAIR-PROBL     04-09 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMISSION-REPAIR-PROBLEMS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT MECHANICS LACK VITAL CAR COMPUTER DATA  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., APRIL 12, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By KURT KLEINER  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garage mechanics are being deprived of the information they need
to control emissions from computerized car engines. As a result,
pollution from cars could increase, say motor industry sources.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical knowledge alone is no longer enough to repair many of
today's cars. Some newer vehicles have up to 42 built-in computers,
controlling everything from the fuel mixture to the brake lights.
When something goes wrong, these can all be accessed through an
onboard diagnostic computer using special equipment. Car
manufacturers give their own dealers the computer protocols and
codes needed to understand the diagnostic system. They are also
supposed to supply it to independent repair shops and makers of
spares, but are often failing to do so _ especially in California,
where strict emission rules were introduced in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Now, say garage owners, the typical three-year warranties on
cars made around that time are running out. And rather than take
their vehicles to garages approved by the maker, owners are going
to cheaper independent mechanics who are being frustrated by the
lack of computer information. They need reference material that
explains how to interpret the output from the onboard diagnostic
computers in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the window into the electronic world of the car,'' says
Mark Warren, president of the Service Technicians Society, a
professional association that is based in Warrendale, Penn. ``In
order to do the repair properly, all of the information has to be
shared.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent garage owners and parts makers are now asking
the state of California to intervene, because they say it is
largely the state's air pollution regulations that have driven the
development of sophisticated emissions control computers.
</P>
<P>
   But California is slow to react. ``Qualified people must be able
to get the information. To our knowledge that is happening,'' says
Jerry Martin of the California Air Resources Board. The information
can be slow to arrive or be prohibitively expensive, however. And
to get it, Warren says, some mechanics are being forced to buy
proprietary diagnostic equipment when they could easily use their
own systems.
</P>
<P>
   The same applies to spare parts. ``We're trying to get the
information we need to make sure the parts do what the onboard
diagnostic system expects,'' says Aaron Lowe of the Automotive
Parts and Accessories Association in Bethesda, Md. ``We find it
kind of disturbing that California officials don't want to work
with us to resolve the issue.'' One effect could be to worsen air
pollution, Lowe says. Because lack of competition makes parts and
repairs more expensive, people may begin to ignore the warning
lights on their dashboards.
</P>
<P>
   John Cabaniss of the Association of International Automobile
Manufacturers believes that a standard format for the exchange of
engine computer information could help. But he adds that car makers
might not want to share information that could aid tampering with
the emission control system: ``Aftermarket shops really don't need
a lot of the information to do maintenance and service.'' Equipped
with the full information, amateurs or unscrupulous garages
sometimes hack into engine management systems to override the
controls and boost horsepower _ sometimes with dangerous results. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
