<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRD-FIGHT-$ADV11-ART     04-09 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRD-FIGHT-$ADV11-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN IN A STREET FIGHT OVER BIRDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, April 11) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas _ This fight is for the birds.
</P>
<P>
   It's for the ungainly chachalaca, known for its shrill morning
wake-up call, the brightly plumed green jay, the raucous great
kiskadee, and the red-crowned parrot that nests in the tall palms.
</P>
<P>
   In this growing border city that calls itself ``The City of
Palms,'' the people who live along South McColl Road are gearing up
for a battle seldom seen in the Rio Grande Valley. The city wants
to widen the last three-quarters of a mile of this street from two
to four lanes.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders estimate that would require cutting down or
transplanting up to two dozen trees that are home to numerous
species of birds. Residents fear many more trees could be lost, and
they say the cost of losing scarce habitat is too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trees we have through here just aren't going to be
replaced. They just aren't going to be grown again,'' said longtime
resident Trev Sparks, an organic farmer and musician who also sells
collectible automobiles. ``Man is real good at building things, but
the birds and the trees are God's creations and they have to be
tended by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamberto ``Bobby'' Balli, city engineer and director of the
Public Works Department, said the street widening is needed to
accommodate the 20,000 vehicles that travel down South McColl every
day. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I think we're trying to be sensitive to the environmental
issues as best we can while still being sensitive to our growth and
vehicular needs,'' he said. ``I do believe this would cause minimal
impact to the birding environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Balli emphasized that the city is also exploring a
less-intrusive option for widening the road that would reduce the
number of trees that would have to be cut or transplanted. A public
hearing on the project is set for April 19.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the quandary a visitor need only drive down
Business 83, a thoroughfare that cuts across McAllen and as the
name indicates, is all business. This stretch of pavement in the
Valley's busiest city is a four-lane, bustling corridor with block
after block of shiny new and used cars for sale, restaurants and
hamburger stands, gas stations, sporting goods shops, bargain
furniture outlets and tire stores.
</P>
<P>
   But turn off of Business 83 onto South McColl and a lush green
canopy closes in from both sides of the narrow, tree-lined street.
</P>
<P>
   And something else is immediately apparent: The air is filled
with the calls of scores of birds that glide from tree to tree or
graze the undergrowth and flower beds many residents have
cultivated to attract them to their yards.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are semitropical birds such as the chachalaca, a
variety of Mexican parrots, the green jay and others whose range
extends into South Texas and are seldom seen elsewhere in the
country. The local Chamber of Commerce, in the running for a
state-funded birding center, already includes the neighborhood in a
self-guided birding tour pamphlet it distributes.
</P>
<P>
   But now dozens of tiny blue survey flags wave in the front yards
of South McColl, evidence of a plan hatched by city traffic
engineers to widen the street to four lanes, and in some places
carving out a fifth turning lane. On the north side of Business 83
McColl has been widened to five lanes the entire six miles to the
city of Edinburg, and engineers want to finish the job by widening
the last mile of McColl where it runs into the Valley's east-west
expressway and a new shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   The project would create a swath of destruction in the front
yard of Sparks' rambling home at the corner of McColl and Dallas,
gobbling up a huge mesquite tree, a towering anacua tree favored by
birds for its plump berries, 60-foot washingtonia palms and a dozen
other oak, ash and cedar trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it would mow down everybody's trees up and down the
street,'' Sparks said in exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders, Sparks contends, have lost sight of the fragile
natural beauty that attracted so many to this border city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten so excited that we've become a commercial center
and we're on the map that it's numbed people's minds to what we
have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks' list of birds he has observed in his yard or the
neighborhood has reached 30, including four species of parrots,
four kinds of doves, two varieties of owls and two types of
woodpeckers.
</P>
<P>
   As Sparks sat in his living room, a pair of chachalacas strutted
atop a fence near one of 10 bird watering holes on the property,
searching for a morning meal. One of three mating pairs living on
Sparks' one-acre lot, the birds are part of a neighborhood flock he
estimates at more than 100 of the large, brownish pheasant-like
birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (city planners) seem to think the birds are going to go
somewhere else, but where are they going to go? Every year there
are less and less trees,'' said Virgil Cragar, a retired jet
fighter pilot from the Houston area who lives down the street from
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to scrape out trees on both sides of
this street, and every time you lose a tree you're going to lose
wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife experts agree the remaining habitat in cities is
critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a valid concern,'' said Larry Ditto, a U.S. Fish
and Wildlife biologist who is overseeing a federally funded project
to assemble a 132,000-acre wildlife corridor along the Rio Grande.
During this century, 95 percent of the Valley's native brush and
hardwood thickets were cleared as the region was converted into a
vast winter garden where citrus, vegetables, cotton, grain and
sugar cane are grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't realize it, but there are so many people in the
Valley that have created habitat in their yards and are feeding
wildlife, providing nesting cover areas for wildlife,'' Ditto said,
adding many cities encourage the practice by passing habitat
ordinances. ``We've done all this habitat creation along the river,
but the cities have a critical role to play in wildlife
conservation in South Texas. It's not just a rural thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What is especially galling to Sparks, Cragar and other residents
is that when residents requested stop lights or stop signs to slow
down the existing traffic, they were told there wasn't enough
volume to warrant the expense.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy City Manager Brent Branham defended the project as a way
to eliminate a traffic bottleneck on what is fast becoming a major
north-south artery, but he said city leaders will listen to the
residents' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to us to work with the neighborhood and determine if
there are alternatives that are more acceptable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1745EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
