<SLUG> BC-DRAGONS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TWIN DRAGONS': HIGH-SPIRITED ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long, long before scientists figured out a way to clone sheep,
filmmakers had divined the secrets of turning one actor into two.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as no surprise to see the popular Jackie Chan, Hong
Kong's comic master of martial arts, in a double role in ``Twin
Dragons,'' the high-spirited entertainment directed by Tsui Hark
and Ringo Lam, with action sequences contributed by them and an
assortment of Hong Kong directors like John Woo and Kirk Wong.
</P>
<P>
   Made as a fund-raising project for the Directors' Guild of Hong
Kong, this enjoyable blend of action, romance and humor requires
only that the audience suspend its disbelief at the popcorn
counter, ignore the paper-thin plot and dubbed dialogue and watch
the two Chans work out their destinies as twins separated at birth.
</P>
<P>
   As always in Chan's films, the screen is filled with spectacular
stunts: the escape that begins the film, a speedboat pursuit in the
harbor, a fight in the sporting goods section of a department
store, a bus and car chase, a dockside battle involving magnetic
crane and cargo netting and a prolonged finale in an automobile
test shop, where cars are drenched, heated and crashed into solid
walls at 50 miles an hour, the occupant's survival rate depending
on the use of a seat belt.
</P>
<P>
   And as always, no matter how many villains assault him, no
matter how many shots they fire, Chan comes up with a smile and
maybe a scrape or two.
</P>
<P>
   But this time he not only shows his sensitive side, as a
world-famous musician, he also winds up with not one girl but two.
</P>
<P>
   The action starts in 1965, when a wounded gangster shoots his
way out of a Hong Kong hospital, taking hostage a newborn twin boy,
who promptly gets lost in the gunplay, rolls down a hill in a
wheelchair and winds up as the object of devotion of a drunken
young lady of the night. Known as Boomer, he grows up to be an auto
mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   The other infant, John Ma, taken to the New World aboard a Pan
Am flight by his distraught parents, is a childhood piano prodigy
and, at 20, a renowned conductor who arrives in Hong Kong for a
concert, unaware that he has a brother.
</P>
<P>
   In the mischievous screenplay concocted by Barry Wong, Cheung
Tung Jo, Wong Yik and Hark, Boomer and his pint-sized pal, Tyson,
(Teddy Robin, the film's producer) are already in deep trouble with
an army of gangsters demanding that Boomer serve as their driver in
a plot to free their imprisoned boss. If not, Tyson, hospitalized
after a chase, will be penalized.
</P>
<P>
   When the reserved John Ma reaches Hong Kong, an old friend of
his father rapidly propels his pretty daughter, Tammy (Nina Li
Chi), into his bedroom, and it is not long before Tammy and Barbara
(Maggie Cheung), the object of the uninhibited Boomer's affection,
are confusing one for the other. So are the gangsters and the hotel
staff and just about everyone else in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Ma, of course, cannot understand why his physical actions
sometimes uncontrollably mimic those of someone steering a bouncing
boat. And Boomer, who is forced onstage in a packed concert hall
before an orchestra astonished at his technique, which resembles
that of a man steering a getaway bus, is equally puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that matters sort themselves out in time for a
happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TWIN DRAGONS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tsui Hark and Ringo Lam; dubbed into English;
written by Barry Wong, Hark, Cheung Tung Jo and Wong Yik; director
of photography, Wong Wing Hang and Wong Ngor Tai; edited by Mak Che
Sin; music by Phe Loung; produced by Teddy Robin; released by
Dimension Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jackie Chan (Boomer/John Ma), Maggie Cheung (Barbara),
Teddy Robin (Tyson) and Nina Li Chi (Tammy).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 88 minutes. ``Twin Dragons'' is rated PG-13
(Parents strongly cautioned). It involves violence, sexual
situations and a few epithets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
