<SLUG> BC-TRANS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRANS': YOUTHFUL TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prisons, real and metaphorical, frame ``Trans,'' the atmospheric
first feature written and directed by Julian Goldberger.
</P>
<P>
   Its poignant focus is Ryan Kazinski (played by Ryan Daugherty),
a 16-year-old inmate who escapes from a work detail at the
Southwest Florida Juvenile Detention Center and embarks on a
frenetic, yearning adventure to nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   In a moment of relative relaxation among some good ol' boys at a
rural general store, Ryan speaks his inchoate dream: Move out to
Colorado. Just live.
</P>
<P>
   But as sketched by Goldberger in ``Trans,'' Ryan is a prisoner
of his youth, his ignorance, his lack of money and the
psychological wounds represented by absent parents and solaced only
by an adoring younger brother (Jon Daugherty).
</P>
<P>
   As Ryan makes his way home and struggles toward freedom,
``Trans'' is at its best in depicting a night world of speeding
cars, roadside markets and fast-food shops, knots of young people
out too late _ all cast in the beams of headlights and the glow of
street lamps and neon signs and surrounded by the intermittent wail
of police sirens.
</P>
<P>
   At its weakest, ``Trans'' overstays its welcome among the
real-life characters at the general store and pads Ryan's thieving
visit to a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Living in the moment, the slim narrative slights the story of
Ryan's past, but ``Trans'' remains a sensitive evocation of
youthful turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TRANS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Julian Goldberger; director of
photography, Jesse Rosen; edited by Affonso Goncalves; music by Fat
Mama and her Trans World Orchestra; produced by Michael Robinson.
Saturday at 6 and Sunday at 3 p.m. at the Roy and Niuta Titus
Theater, Museum of Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., Manhattan, as part
of the 28th New Directors/New Films series of the Film Society of
Lincoln Center and the Department of Film of the Museum of Modern
Art. Running time: 83 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ryan Daugherty (Ryan Kazinski), Justin Lakes (Justin
Mallenkoff), Jon Daugherty (Little Brother), Michael Gulnac (Mike
Gonzalez), Elijah Smith, Charles Walker and Jeremiah Robinson
(Inmates/Party Rappers), Vince Kelly (Warden), Edge Edgerton (Bus
Ticket Agent) and Stephanie Davis (Boston Cream Girl).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
