<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEIN-NITEOUT-$ADV11-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR STEIN, THE HEL-LO KISS-KISS GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the evening began, Taylor Stein, dressed in a
black and white form-fitting Gucci suit, went to find her jacket. A
furry white low-cut tank top she had on was drawing too much
attention from the young (and not so young) gentlemen arriving
Thursday night at Brown's, the new Upper East Side boite where Ms.
Stein is an owner.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, men, some in navy blazers, others in
collarless Armani shirts, flirted with her, caressing her tan fit
arms, as they asked for tables at the club, whose patrons range
from boarding school chums to international playboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Taylor, we love you,'' said Aram Moezinia, who was sitting
by the open french doors having drinks with three other men.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein sat on the lap of one of his friends. ``We all tried
to date her at the same time,'' said Moezinia, adding they first
saw Ms. Stein at a nightclub. ``We met her when she was dressed as
Pocahontas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those guys owns an island off of Brazil,'' Ms. Stein
whispered, ``and we're all flying there in a private plane next
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she's known for her flamboyant outfits and blunt chatter,
Ms. Stein, 29, wants to be taken seriously. That's why she took on
Brown's. The American grill restaurant, bar and lounge had been
Gertrude's, a more sophisticated establishment with an older
clientele, run by her father, Howard Stein, who owns clubs like Au
Bar and keeps a watchful eye on this one. He turned it over to Ms.
Stein two months ago to convert into a hot spot. She immediately
replaced what she calls the ``fancy waiters'' with ``great-looking
disco waiters,'' turned up the music and invited her friends.
</P>
<P>
   Stein bankrolled his daughter's new project because he wanted
her to get back on her feet. What had knocked her down was an
article in The New York Observer in December naming her ``This
Year's Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My life fell apart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The article portrayed her as an outspoken, partying dilettante.
Soon after it was published, she lost her job at William B. May,
the conservative real estate company, where she had almost married
the owner's son.
</P>
<P>
   She retreated to Palm Beach for a few weeks. To her shock when
she returned, the embarrassing press had turned her into a
mini-media star. Someone from the office of Judith Regan, the
celebrity publisher, called to talk about doing a book titled ``How
to Be an It Girl.'' Last week, she said, producers on ``20/20''
interviewed her for a Diane Sawyer segment on New Yorkers who play
hard and work hard. Meantime, Ms. Stein's father gave her the
restaurant, now packed every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called in every favor I could,'' said Ms. Stein, who created
buzz for the restaurant by giving free dinner parties to
journalists, publicity agents and friends. Ms. Stein is at her
clubby restaurant every night, acting as impresario, like the late
Glenn Bernbaum of Mortimer's. Although he certainly never greeted
customers the way she does _ throwing her arms in the air, shaking
her body and cooing, ``Hel-lo.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 10, Ms. Stein was in the upstairs dining room with a
friend from Locust Valley. Within minutes, four well-mannered men
sat down to chat. When Ms. Stein went downstairs, Leonardo
Valentino, a tanned jet-setter in a neon yellow blazer, grabbed her
and wouldn't let her go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love all this kiss-kiss stuff,'' she said, glancing at her
watch, a Cartier Pasha with a diamond tick-tack-toe board (a
present from a former beau). But it was time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to keep moving,'' said Ms. Stein, heading toward Ralph
Destino III, the 30-something heir to the Cartier fortune. Jacket
off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
