</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-69-METS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: '69 METS GIVE US REASON TO BELIEVE IN UNDERDOGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing is too extreme. Nothing is too far from reality. This is
their gift to us.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how powerful the Yankees and Braves might be. No
matter how much we consider them a lock for the 1999 World Series
and the regular season just a tune-up, we have the '69 Mets to give
us hope, the '69 Mets, the little ant who indeed carried that load.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise to us, too,'' said shortstop Bud Harrelson.
</P>
<P>
   We have the '69 Mets, those Amazin' Mets, those incredible,
ridiculous, absurd, goofy, longshot,
put-on-your-seatbelt-daughter-I-can't-believe-this-is-happening
Mets. The '69 New York Mets are to baseball what the '69 Jets are
to football and what the 1980 U.S. men's hockey team are to the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are the reason we still will pay attention to this
baseball season, no matter how preordained it appears, no matter
how boring are the predictions.
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a team this year that finds the lucky bounce
...
</P>
<P>
   ``In Pittsburgh a ball bounced off the top of the fence and back
to Cleon Jones, our left fielder,'' Harrelson said. ``Cleon catches
it on the fly and throws Richie Zisk out at home. He saves the
ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a team this year that has a below average
hitter who decides to be Babe Ruth for an afternoon ...
</P>
<P>
   ``In my whole life, I had one hit off Steve Carlton, and it was
a single,'' said right fielder Ron Swoboda. ``Until that game ...
The Cardinals go up, 1-0, and I follow with a two-run homer. The
Cardinals go up, 3-2, and I follow with another two-run homer.
Carlton sets a National League record for most strikeouts in a game
(19) but I beat him with two two-run homers.''
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a team this year that has a pitcher who
suddenly becomes a hitter ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We won a doubleheader against Pittsburgh,'' Harrelson said,
``and the only run driven in each game was by a pitcher (Jerry
Koosman, Don Cardwell).''
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a team this year that gives us a sign from
above ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing the Cubs, the team we were trying to catch,''
said Swoboda, ``and during the game a black cat hops out on the
field. He doesn't go to our dugout. No, he walks right in front of
theirs. It was like right out of central casting. `Hey, let's cue
up the black cat.' And the cat doesn't leave. He keeps walking in
front of the Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a team this year that has no history, no
prospects, a team like the Mets who finished their previous seven
seasons averaging 45 games out of first place ...
</P>
<P>
   ``A victory for us would have been a season in which we ended up
with a .500 record,'' said Swoboda.
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a team that's a bigger loser than a 40-year-old
fat guy with bad breath and protruding ear hair trying to pick up
college coeds. We will look for a team ignored more than a stop
sign in Boston. We will look for a team that will be loved by its
fans for all those reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mets fans just wanted us to entertain them,'' said Swoboda.
``We didn't coe with heavy expectations. So when we won, it was
like paying off a loan. Going down Broadway in a New York City
ticker tape parade, we just slapped a smile on a million faces. We
grabbed a little piece of their heart and we never gave it back. I
know we did because every time I go back to New York, everyone
tells me what I did for them 30 years ago. This is heady stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   So heady the Mets will hold numerous celebrations in this 30th
anniversary year over that '69 team. It's as if the '69 Mets are as
alive now as they were then.
</P>
<P>
   ``No team has lived this long,'' said first baseman Ed
Kranepool. ``To think we would still be celebrating 30 years later,
name a team that has done that. I grew up in the Bronx as a Yankee
fan and as great as those Yankee teams were, I can't remember now
one over another.''
</P>
<P>
   But these are the '69 Mets, the hope for every fan this year who
lives outside of New York City, Atlanta and perhaps Los Angeles.
These are the '69 Mets, with a team batting average of .242, with
just 109 homers, with Tom Seaver the only one Hall of Famer (Nolan
Ryan was in a supporting role), beating the great Aaron and Niekro
in playoffs, and the great Brooks and Frank Robinson and Jim Palmer
in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a laughingstock,'' said Kranepool, an opinion he
doesn't dispute. ``Of course, Baltimore was a better team than us.
So was Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   But they won. They won just months after Neil Armstrong walked
on the moon, an accomplishment that left some people no more in
disbelief than calling the Mets the best team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what it felt like?'' said Harrelson. ``It was like
you remembering where you were when it happened. Like you
remembered where you were when Kennedy was assassinated. Like you
remembered where you were when man walked on the moon. Like you
remembered where you were when the Mets won the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   And oh, some of you might say, this couldn't have happened. How
absurd this sounds. And you'd be right ... if you are under the age
of 35. Yes, it was absurd and ridiculous and unimagineable. Too bad
you weren't around for it. It was fabulous. Absolutely fabulous.
Real heady stuff.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Padecky is a sports columnist for The Press Democrat in
Santa Rosa, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
