<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONDOM-DESIGNER-ART-2     04-09 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDOM-DESIGNER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `LEONARDO' OF CONDOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 11) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A condom confrontation is taking place in a federal courtroom in
Newark in an emotionally charged dispute over the exquisite
architecture of the prophylactic.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the imbroglio is Dr. Alla Venkata Krishna Reddy,
59, a surgeon turned businessman and inventor, who for the last
decade has been a quixotic and controversial figure in the
prophylactic world. Reddy's designs for condoms with built-in
bulges are an attempt to rethink the way condoms work, prompting
Adam Glickman, the founder of Condomania, a specialty retailer and
Internet-based mail-order company, to call the taciturn Indian
designer ``the Leonardo da Vinci of the condom.''
</P>
<P>
   The court case, which involves a patent dispute over two Reddy
designs, has unwittingly opened a window on the high art of condom
design, as conservatively dressed lawyers, clutching male
mannequins reduced to their most essential parts, argue the fine
points of pouches and bulges and what constitutes design innovation
in a condom.
</P>
<P>
   One of humankind's most ubiquitous, if humble, products, the
coiled protector secreted in foil had a Renaissance period during
the 1980's, when sales surged in the wake of AIDS anxiety. But
recently, in part because of fear fatigue and a reluctance even
among the converted to keep using condoms, sales nationally have
plateaued. Recent studies by Family Health International, a company
that focuses on reproductive health and intervention, show that
condom use disappears three months into a relationship, one reason
why, this summer, New York University will be the host of the third
annual National Symposium on Overcoming Barriers to Condom Use.
</P>
<P>
   Reddy, who is not affiliated with a big company, has been part
of a new school of thought that seeks to revamp the contemporary
image of condoms from necessary evil to alluring sex enhancer. He
began designing barrier contraceptives, some of them downright
bizarre, in 1986 while researching the AIDS virus, convinced that
condoms were the only hope. ``My gut feeling was there was not
going to be a cure or a vaccine,'' Reddy recalled.
</P>
<P>
   His Pleasure Plus condom, which when inflated resembles an
upside-down Boeing 747, was considered by some to be a radical
departure when it was introduced in the early 1990s. It embodied
Reddy's belief that ``if you developed a condom with more pleasure,
people would use it regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although condoms with mildly flared tops had been introduced
before, Pleasure Plus was notable for its asymmetry and for
exploiting the friction inherent in moving latex. It had a baggy
tubular pouch that sidled up against the underside of the glans
penis. ``He understood nerve endings and anatomy,'' Glickman of
Condomania said, adding that the Pleasure Plus developed a
``cult-like following'' and outsold all other condoms in
Condomania's retail stores in New York and Los Angeles by 10 to 1.
``Compared to what was out there, it was the difference between the
San Fernando Valley and the Grand Canyon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But less than a year after it was introduced, the Pleasure Plus
disappeared from shelves because of manufacturing problems. Reddy's
company went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tragedy _ consumers were desperately trying to find
this condom that had changed their sex lives,'' said Davin Wedel,
the founder of the Global Protection Corp., a Boston-based company
trying to bring back the Pleasure Plus. The company is working with
Portfolio Technologies, a group of investors based in Kenilworth
Ill., who bought the rights to the condom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Reddy, who divides his time between Chennai,
India, and Plainsboro, N.J., has dreamed up a new design, the
Inspiral, which he calls ``the best I've created.'' It is indeed a
visually stunning work that, when active, has a spiral shape
evocative of a whipped-cream dollop or a Nautilus shell. More
important is its spring action, a motion Reddy's patent lawyer,
John C. Evans, likens to a pogo stick and the doctor himself
compares to ``the shock absorber of a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Reddy has invested $7 million, including a $4 million loan from
the Indian Government, to build a factory in India, with 60 to 100
employees, to make the Inspiral. About 590,000 of the condoms were
on the verge of being distributed to the Eckerd and Genovese drug
store chains, to Planned Parenthood and to other customers when the
current legal squabble began. In the case, Portfolio Technologies _
the owner of the rights to the Pleasure Plus _ is seeking a
temporary injunction in the U.S. district court in Newark to block
the Inspiral, which the plaintiffs say is basically the same condom
as the Pleasure Plus.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the debate centers on whether there is a difference
between Pleasure Plus' pouch and Inspiral's grand, helix-shaped
bulge. ``If there's a bulge that creates a looseness in an area
that contacts the user, and moves back and forth to create enhanced
sensation, then it's covered by the patents,'' said Robert W.
Smith, a lawyer specializing in patent infringements who is
representing the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Reddy, who has been a far better designer than businessman _ he
left a string of creditors in the wake of his Pleasure Plus
collapse _ is arguing that the spring action of the Inspiral and
the resulting movement make it novel. A patent for the new device
is pending. Although not on the market, the condom was included in
a test by Cosmopolitan magazine recently, and was the only model
awarded a 10 out 10 by groups of men and women. Amy Fraley, a
health care clinic worker in northern Michigan who has tried the
Inspiral, said she noticed increased sensation. ``It was the closet
thing to not using anything at all I've had with a condom,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A judge's ruling on the injunction request is expected this
week. If the injunction is denied, Reddy says he is prepared to
have his 590,000 Inspirals, now in a warehouse in Tulsa, Okla.,
distributed immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Reddy said he ``never touched a condom'' until his AIDS
research. He is married with three sons _ ``three sons and a tubal
ligation, that's it!'' he muttered. He seems sincere, if fixated,
on his cause and speaks in the guarded, measured manner of a
doctor. He comes across as a reluctant entrepreneur, although he
stands to grow rich if the Inspiral captures even a fraction of the
market for condom sales in the United States, which was $247
million for the last 52-week period, according to A.C. Nielsen, the
ratings company.
</P>
<P>
   Like many inventors, Reddy's obsession borders on the eccentric,
and he always seems to be looking over his shoulder. ``The more
they know about the Inspiral, the crazier they will be to stop
it,'' he said of his rivals.
</P>
<P>
   His quest for the perfect condom is part of a grand tradition
documented in the book ``American Sex Machines: The Hidden History
of Sex at the U.S. Patent Office'' by Hoag Levins (Adams Media,
1996). Reddy's first ill-fated design was the so-called ``Bikini
condom,'' a scary looking contraption for women that looked like an
errant rubber garter belt. .....ke other products, condoms have
gone through booms and busts. Before the 1980s, when AIDS sparked a
flurry of new designs, the stylistic apogee came in the wake of the
1936 nullification of the Comstock Law, a 19th-century Act of
Congress that prohibited contraceptives, including ``immoral rubber
articles.'' The law had forced the condom underground, where it was
furtively sold in barbershops and shoeshine parlors.
</P>
<P>
   Condoms, which throughout their history have mirrored society's
attitudes toward sex, disease and body image, are believed to date
back to linen sheaths worn 3,000 years ago by the Egyptians. The
modern era of condom design began with the vulcanization of rubber
in the 1840s, which, as Levins writes, provided the first ``safe
and effective interface between machinery and internal human
organs.'' Attitudes toward the condom changed radically between the
two World Wars, culminating in the distribution of millions of
condoms to GI's during World War II by a military worried about the
spread of venereal disease.
</P>
<P>
   The embrace of the Pill in the 1960s rendered the condom almost
obsolete. But it rebounded in the 1980s with concern about AIDS.
Condom manufacturers flooded the market with new textures, colors
and scents. In 1987, the Japanese introduced the Kimono brand, a
superthin latex condom in which the idea of pleasure was prominent.
Thin condoms now account for 28 percent of the American market,
said Carol Carroza, marketing director for Ansell Healthcare
Products, makers of the Life Styles brand.
</P>
<P>
   Large-scale manufacturers are now attempting to tackle new
frontiers. Chief among them is anxiety about using condoms, or what
Catherine Taylor, a group director for London International Group,
makers of Durex, the world's largest condom brand, calls ``the
fumble factor _ where in the throes of passion you have to open the
pack.'' The prime reason condoms fail is because of misuse. The new
Durex Topaz condom, not yet available in the United States, is
geared to new users or ``those lacking confidence,'' Ms. Taylor
said. It comes with a glow-in-the-dark ring to guide quavering
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Ansell recently introduced packaging inspired by single-serve
butter packs with peel-off lids. It automatically positions the
condom. The idea came from a designer who noticed that many people
open condom packs with their teeth, Ms. Carozza said.
</P>
<P>
   The Reality female condom, made out of polyurethane, has been
widely distributed in developing countries. ``The issue is
attitude,'' said Mary Ann Leeper, president of the Female Health
Co., its manufacturer. ``The bottom line is that men and women want
to have naked sex, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reddy's fate hinges on the Inspiral, which he views
as ``a beautiful barrier for population control and disease
prevention.'' As a surgeon, he said, he was held in the highest
esteem by his patients; but now, he says somewhat wearily, ``when I
meet someone he thinks I'm there to sell him something.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sarojini, does not approve of the turn his career has
taken. ``She thinks I'm crazy,'' he said. ``She says one man cannot
save the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
