<HEADER>
A2557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-TRADE-700&AMP;AD     04-09 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TRADE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE OPEN MARKETS COULD THREATEN HONG KONG'S ROLE AS MIDDLEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ For China, which has spent years trying to claw its
way into the world's club of trading nations, the benefits of such
an expanded reach and strong connections are clear.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hong Kong, which has thrived as a middleman between
China's closed markets and the outside world, the possibility of a
more open China raises hard questions about the future of this
trading post.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, China's success in moving closer to joining the
World Trade Organization has buoyed local investors, on the theory
that Chinese membership would be a good thing for Hong Kong. Stocks
rose to their highest level in 12 months Friday, capping a week of
powerful gains, in part because investors liked the progress they
had seen in negotiations between the Chinese and U.S. governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of people who think if China wins, Hong Kong
wins,'' said Marc Faber, the managing director of Marc Faber Ltd.,
an investment firm here. ``But I'm not sure. I think, on balance,
the entry of China into the World Trade Organization is a negative
for Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a deal would greatly expand business with China, Faber
said it could also threaten Hong Kong's role as the broker for much
of the wheeling and dealing that surrounds the China trade. With so
many more ways into China, foreign companies may be ready to cut
their own deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is further marginalizing Hong Kong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a former British colony and now a semiautonomous region of
China, Hong Kong is a separate trading entity with its own
membership in the WTO. But its economic fortunes are so intertwined
with China that people here have followed Beijing's campaign as if
it were their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO issue has helped sentiment in the market,'' said Miron
Mushkat, global head of economics and strategy at Indocam Asset
Management. ``But it doesn't take much for sentiment to turn
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, investors might have second thoughts if they scrutinized
the implications of China's admission to the organization that sets
the rules of global commerce and arbitrates disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some of the concessions Beijing has made in trade
negotiations pose a threat to companies here. On Wednesday, just
before Prime Minister Zhu Rongji flew to Washington, Chinese and
U.S. officials agreed to double the frequency of commercial flights
between their countries and to increase the number of Chinese
cities that U.S. air carriers can serve with direct connections.
</P>
<P>
   That could deprive Hong Kong _ and its new $20 billion airport _
of its role as a gateway to China. Dragonair, the regional airline
that serves many mainland cities, could lose Western passengers who
fly to Hong Kong and switch carriers for the short hop to popular
Chinese destinations like Xian and Guilin.
</P>
<P>
   As China opens other industries, like telecommunications,
financial services, and accounting, some analysts said foreign
companies would rely less on Hong Kong as an interlocutor. That
shift is already occurring in shipping, where Hong Kong's role as a
gateway is still most pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, half of all Chinese exports passed through Hong Kong's
container port on their way out of the country. But as China has
opened more ports on the mainland, Hong Kong's share of exports
declined, from 60 percent in 1992. Last year, container traffic
rose less than 1 percent in Hong Kong, while Shenzhen, a large city
nearby in Guangdong Province, reported a 70 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, more and more trade is carried out between China and
other countries directly, rather than through Hong Kong,'' Faber
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for every downbeat consequence of freer trade with China,
there is an offsetting positive one. Even if China opens its
markets and adheres to global trade rules, analysts say it will
still be a bewildering place to do business. The only difference is
that more foreign companies will be taking the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a proliferation of people outside who are dealing
with China, you need someone to act as a go-between,'' Mushkat
said. ``It doesn't necessarily mean pushing cargo through Hong
Kong. But it may mean more skill-intensive activities, like lawyers
or bankers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other experts said Hong Kong could assume a new role as an
anchor of stability in a commercially freer China. Once China gains
entry into the WTO, analysts said it would be likely to make its
currency, the yuan, fully convertible. The Hong Kong dollar, with
an exchange rate linked to the U.S. dollar, could offset
fluctuations in the value of the Chinese yuan.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's local companies would also benefit from having
greater access to Chinese markets. Although Hong Kong is the
largest source of direct foreign investment in China _ a cumulative
$99.3 billion through 1996 _ its companies are still classified as
foreign entities. Like American companies, they are barred from
ownership in many Chinese industries.
</P>
<P>
   Once those restrictions were lifted, Hong Kong companies could
have an edge over others. For example, Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corp., a unit of HSBC Holdings, has decades of experience
in China and would be well placed if foreign banks were allowed
into Chinese consumer banking. Shares of HSBC helped propel the
stock market rally here over the last couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong should have demanded that its companies be
classified as Chinese when it was negotiating the handover,'' said
Robert C. Broadfoot, managing director of the Political and
Economic Risk Consultancy in Hong Kong. ``Now, it has a second
chance to invest in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the links between Hong Kong and China, some
economists said it would be several years before the impact of a
Chinese membership in the WTO made itself felt here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt the business community would regard this as a
positive,'' said Ian K. Perkin, chief economist of the Hong Kong
General Chamber of Commerce. ``Just how positive is impossible to
tell without knowing the details.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
