<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2558 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RECOVERY-$ADV1     04-09 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RECOVERY-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALKAN RECOVERY EXPERTS SAY KOSOVO FACES A LONG ROAD BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the guns fall silent across Kosovo, the
U.S.-led alliance will face open-ended challenges when it tries to
transform the province into a peaceful homeland for embittered
ethnic Albanian Muslims and the Serbian Orthodox Christians who
once governed them.
</P>
<P>
   Experts who have worked on recovery operations in the Balkans
say America and its allies will confront immense difficulties
trying to create a secure environment and provide emergency relief
to hundreds of thousands of Kosovar Albanians driven from their
homes by Yugoslavia's scorched earth-campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The allies will also have to create a new political system for
the province that guarantees the autonomy that Yugoslavia stripped
away a decade ago, setting the stage for the Kosovar Albanians'
struggle for independence that culminated with NATO intervention on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of Balkan relief and recovery efforts say it is too
early to forecast the cost of rebuilding Kosovo or the time it will
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting from square one,'' said Robert P. DeVecchi, who
dealt with refugees from the war in neighboring Bosnia. ``We have a
catastrophic humanitarian situation. No one expected its scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Recovery still lags in Bosnia, for example, where a
U.S.-brokered peace agreement ended three years of fighting in 1995
that claimed 200,000 lives and drove 3 million people from their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   International donations are falling behind for Bosnia's $5.1
billion recovery fund, and political wrangling continues between
rival ethnic factions there.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnian refugees have been slow to return: 400,000 of the
700,000 who fled elsewhere in Europe still live in the other
countries. Another 800,000 who were routed from their homes in
Bosnia but stayed in the area have yet to return to those homes.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Adm. Leighton Smith, the NATO commander who began
implementing the peace agreement in Bosnia in 1995, says of the
Kosovo challenges: ``Until the local politicians decide they want
peace and they want to contribute to reconstruction, you're dead in
the water.''
</P>
<P>
   _On providing security:
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that at a minimum, the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization will have to field a mobile force of more than 30,000
troops capable of quelling rear-guard resistance from either
Yugoslav Serbian forces or break-away elements of the ethnic
Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   As Smith put it, the alliance will need ``a robust force that
can kick the hell out of Serbian forces, if necessary.'' He added,
``No matter what's agreed to in a political settlement, the force
you send in is going to be challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony H. Cordesman, a military specialist at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies here, foresees allied forces
remaining in Kosovo for a decade to enforce ``some kind of no man's
land'' between Yugoslav Serbs and Kosovar Albanians. He added,
``One way or another, NATO and the U.S. are probably stuck the
Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   _On aiding the refugees:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has funneled $150 million in
emergency relief since last month, and other nations and
humanitarian relief organizations so far have contributed more than
$80 million.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton flew to Dover Air Force Base,
Del., Friday to watch a giant C-5A Galaxy being loaded with daily
ration packs for refugees in Albania and Macedonia _ part of the
1.1 million daily rations pledged by the administration last week.
</P>
<P>
   A United Nations relief effort is being bolstered by NATO
forces, including 8,000 soldiers bound for Albania and 12,000
troops already in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Experts disagree on whether the estimated 510,500 ethnic
Albanian refugees driven from Kosovo to Albania, Macedonia, Bosnia
and elsewhere in Yugoslavia in the last three weeks will return to
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   H. Roy Williams, director of emergency humanitarian relief at
the U.S. Agency for International Development (AID), foresees a
gradual return by the refugees, including 100,000 ethnic Albanians
being offered temporary asylum in NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has certainly been my experience that refugees above all
want to return home,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But DeVecchi, former president of the International Rescue
Committee who has handled refugee crises dating back to Vietnam,
disagrees. He said ethnic Albanians may not return to Kosovo unless
allied troops permanently partition Kosovo and set up a cordon of
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course refugees will say they want to go back,'' DeVecchi
says. ``But the prospect of having an international protection
force only for a limited period of time means it's unrealistic to
expect them to return to their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   _On creating a new political system:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Salla, a Balkans expert at the American University here,
said the allies will have to craft a new political structure that
protects the rights of both ethnic Albanians and Yugoslav Serbians.
The best way to do it is with a patchwork of powerful county-level
councils across the province that report to an umbrella assembly
that represents all ethnic factions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Salla, noting the difficulties of such a system, predicted
that ethnic Albanians will insist on control of the international
borders between Kosovo and neighboring Albania and Macedonia to
prevent the kind of Yugoslav clampdown on the borders that trapped
tens of thousands of fleeing Kosovars last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handing over control of those borders to the ethnic Albanians
will be a touchy issue for the Yugoslavs,'' Salla warned.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance also have to bolster the reform-minded leadership
in Montenegro, a republic that remains affiliated with Serbia. As
Ambassador Robert Gelbard, special U.S. representative for
implementation of the peace agreement in Bosnia, put it last week:
The Clinton administration will ``remain steadfast in its support
for the democratic government of Montenegro.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On reconstructing Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the AID relief specialist, said that once the allies
deal with the immediate needs of the refugees, they will focus on
the long-term recovery of the province that forms the southern part
of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   An international donors' conference on reconstruction will be
convened as soon as the fighting ends, Williams said. He added that
it's too early to know the extent of damage to Kosovo, pounded by
NATO bombs and Yugoslav forces that have burned whole villages.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who supervised initial recovery operations in Bosnia,
says the allied security force will undertake some initial
reconstruction projects. Allied forces in Bosnia rebuilt more than
60 bridges, laid dozens of miles of road and reconstructed four
airports in Bosnia, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military will automatically do a lot _ some of it out of
military necessity, some of it just because we're nice guys,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
