<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-HULBERT11-COX     04-09 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-HULBERT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's not such a long trip between `Daisy,' `Drive'
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes the simplest pictures hit home the hardest. Take the
two straight-back chairs on the empty stage of the Alliance Studio
Theatre. That's what the audience sees as it files in for ``How I
Learned to Drive,'' Paula Vogel's daring but dignified play about
coming of age, finding one's way, surviving incest (yes, there's
that) and moving on.
</P>
<P>
   If you've followed Atlanta theater for a decade or more, those
chairs say: ``Driving Miss Daisy.'' Especially now, so soon after
the passing of Mary Nell Santacroce, who from September 1988 until
the end of 1989 sat in such a chair on that same spot, next to the
several fine actors who played chauffeur Hoke. Together these
characters from the life of playwright Alfred Uhry ``drove''
through streets that all Atlantans recognize, moving from the
alienation of racial distrust to the bond of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, a playwright conjures a car. This time it's the
place where Lil' Bit _ a teenager of innocence and normal desires _
gets driving lessons and life lessons from her Uncle Peck _ a
40-ish man with forbidden desires but a generous heart. It's a tale
without martyrs or devils. Nothing is simple but the set. Laughter
and outrage alternate like the glass dividers of a revolving door.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Daisy,'' the car is a metaphor for life's journey. It's
a place of intimate exchange, a kind of secular confession booth.
We audience members, sitting just a few feet away, are in that
bubble with them. Our imaginations create the look, sound, smell of
a summer night in 1969, using a rough magic (Shakespeare's phrase)
that's closer to ancient ritual than to the special effects of a
George Lucas movie. That magic is called theater.
</P>
<P>
   For all their similarities in method, the two Pulitzer
Prize-winning plays are hugely different, of course. ``Daisy''
embraces sentiment; ``Drive'' distrusts it. ``Daisy'' soothes;
``Drive'' disturbs. It's a fair bet that a play about incest is not
going to match ``Daisy's'' run of 18 months in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a great shame if theatergoers turned away from
Vogel's play on the basis of the I-word, just as it would be a
mistake for them to go just for titillation (they won't get much,
anyway; there's no nudity or suggestive physical contact). It would
be a mistake if patrons assumed, on the basis of subject matter or
a quick synopsis, that ``Drive'' is ``not for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The American theater is at a crossroads, and if it is to thrive
it will need audiences who are willing to take a leap of faith on
plays and players that may not seem as comfortably familiar as
before. In coming years there are going to be more skilled actors
in Atlanta but fewer well-known stars such as the late, great
Santacroce, because the stories of our age do not lend themselves
to the traditional, bravura (and let's face it, sentimental) roles
from which stardom was spun. In coming years there will be fewer
plays that you've heard of. That doesn't mean they're not
entertaining, it only means that television and most magazines
ignore them because they don't have enough mass appeal to help with
ratings and subscription numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In coming years, sex _ as a universal concern _ will demand due
attention. The future is here. This weekend Horizon Theatre, a hip
but hardly randy troupe, opened ``Quills,'' a play about the
Marquis de Sade that includes nudity and you name it.
</P>
<P>
   In coming years it's going to be clearer that the demographic
profile of mainstream theatergoers (average age 46, according to a
new Broadway survey) is different on many levels from that of
theater artists, who tend to ``skew young'' in the jargon of such
studies. It's no secret that gays and lesbians play a more
prominent role in theater than society at large.
</P>
<P>
   The artists' challenge of the new millennium will be telling
stories that connect with the people who actually come to the box
office. ``Drive'' is such a story. Just as important will be the
willingness of audiences to meet artists halfway, to project
themselves into stories that may not appear relevant to their daily
lives. Yes, we need hilarious Southern comedies, but ones in step
with reality. There are only so many times that campy cash cows
(``Steel Magnolias,'' ``Pump Boys and Dinettes,'' ``Greater Tuna,''
etc.) can be squeezed before the milk runs dry.
</P>
<P>
   Unless this common ground between artist and audience is staked
out and explored, there simply won't be enough ticket buyers or
sympathetic corporate sponsors to support big, highly professional
nonprofits such as the Alliance (which in recent seasons has rolled
up a $700,000 deficit). Don't despair _ theater is too ancient and
powerful to die, especially in a sophisticated city such as Atlanta
_ but it may only carry on in small, underfunded houses even less
visible to the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   In his book of theater theory, ``Three Uses of the Knife,''
David Mamet writes: ``Just as TV reduces us to the status of
consumer slaves, so dramatic art can raise the creators and the
viewers to the status of communicants. We who made it, formed it,
saw it, went through something together, now we are veterans. Now
we are friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of that passage when you're watching Lil' Bit and Uncle
Peck in their ``car'' of straight-back chairs. Look to your left
and your right in the audience and you will see your fellow
travelers, fellow communicants around the ancient fire. Perhaps
you'll find that, subject matter aside, ``How I Learned to Drive''
is more like ``Driving Miss Daisy'' than you ever knew.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dhulbert(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
