<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-CONTACTLENS10-COX     04-09 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-CONTACTLENS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: New daily contact lenses convenient, low in
price
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you wear contact lenses, other people don't notice
them. Neither should you, says the maker of a new, ultra-thin daily
disposable lens.
</P>
<P>
   This week CIBA Vision, a contact lens manufacturer based in
Duluth, Ga., began widespread distribution of its new Focus Dailies
lenses. The lenses are notable for their convenience and low cost,
but especially for their reputed comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very comfortable, very convenient,'' said Dr. Brenda
Weirich, an Alpharetta (Ga.) optometrist who wears Focus Dailies.
``My husband also wears them _ I converted him.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret behind the new lenses' comfort is their extreme
thinness, partly because of the introduction of nelfilcon, a
polymer material never before used in contact lenses. CIBA also
developed a new manufacturing process that contributes to the
lenses' thinness and ultimately results in lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Focus Dailies can be made in just two minutes, thanks
to a fully automated system that relies on robotics for speed,
precision and consistency. Conventional contact lenses generally
take two to three days to make and require some manual steps. The
lens is formed between two molds, which are pinched together to
form the lens edge.
</P>
<P>
   CIBA also uses molds to produce the new lenses, but the molds
never touch. A drop of liquid nelfilcon is placed on the concave,
or ``female,'' side, and the convex, ``male'' mold presses the
liquid into the proper shape, while remaining microns apart from
the other mold.
</P>
<P>
   A beam of ultraviolet light passes through the molds, which are
made of glass and quartz, and essentially cooks the liquid into a
gel in seconds. The mold is designed so that the ultraviolet light
passes through only a certain area, creating a perfectly round
shape with a precise, thin edge. No further cutting or trimming is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make these things so efficiently, we can offer them at
a pretty nice price,'' said Michael Sinclair, CIBA's brand manager
for Focus Dailies.
</P>
<P>
   At about $1 per pair, the retail price of the new lenses is
roughly half that of the only other daily disposable lenses on the
market, Johnson &AMP; Johnson's Acuvue. Still, Focus Dailies' annual
cost is higher than that of other soft contacts, especially those
intended to be replaced yearly. But people are paying for the
convenience of wearing lenses for a single day and then throwing
them out.
</P>
<P>
   As Sinclair pointed out, however, wearers of daily disposable
lenses will save the money otherwise spent on contact solutions and
products. Also, replacing a lost or torn lens will cost only 50
cents, compared with $20 to $80 for a conventional lens.
</P>
<P>
   From a health standpoint, daily disposable lenses eliminate the
problem of protein buildup on lenses, to which the eyes can react
poorly. Protein buildup is particularly troublesome during allergy
season, Weirich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have bad allergies, your eyes are very active and
produce more protein buildup on the lenses,'' she explained. ``If
you replace the lenses every day, you don't have any buildup from
one day to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   Other varieties of disposable contacts include two-week and
monthly lenses. Disposable contacts of all types account for 65
percent of the contact lens market, Sinclair said, but only 2
percent of all lens wearers use daily disposables. Cost has been
the limiting factor, but CIBA hopes its lower prices will attract a
greater share of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Focus Dailies were released on a limited basis last year, but
until recently CIBA didn't have the manufacturing capacity for
large-scale production of the lenses. The company is expanding its
facilities and eventually will have the ability to turn out
billions of lenses per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot find a healthier way to wear contact lenses,'' said
Steve Schuster, president of CIBA Vision North America. ``This is a
major lifestyle opportunity for people.''
</P>
<P>
   EYE-OPENING FACTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The first contact lens was created in 1887 and was made of
glass. The modern contact lens, made of plastic, was developed in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A contact lens rests on a cushion of tears on the eyeball,
directly over the pupil and iris. Contacts come in hard and soft
varieties; the latter were introduced in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 73 million people worldwide wear contact lenses; about
30 million of those live in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Encyclopedia Britannica, CIBA Vision Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
