<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANCH MAY HOLD CLUES TO MYSTERY OF MISSING ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Two ex-convicts with violent pasts are behind
bars, a Texas ranch has been searched for the victims' remains and
the ``Today Show'' has been serving breakfast updates on the
ever-weirder case of Madalyn Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly four decades ago that O'Hair played a pivotal role
in the legal battle to ban prayer and Bible reading from public
schools. And it has been more than three years since O'Hair and her
two adult children disappeared from San Antonio with $500,000 in
gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows if they are dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in absentia, O'Hair has recaptured the public attention
she lost years go after she reigned briefly and belligerently as
the self-pronounced ``most hated woman in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother would have enjoyed this. It has brought her back
into the limelight, but you'll notice it has nothing to do with her
beliefs. It's all about celebrity,'' said Bill Murray, O'Hair's
surviving son, who is a fundamentalist Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always thought of herself as a major historical figure,
more than she ever was. Now she's receiving more attention than she
ever did when she was alive, except for a brief period in the
1960s,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Grand Dame of Atheism is on center stage.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Hair is making her comeback as the leading lady in a soapy
saga of greed and treachery, of gold coins and metal drums, of
disbelief and dismemberment.
</P>
<P>
   Few mourned when the O'Hair family vanished from Austin in
September 1995, and for more than three years, the Austin Police
Department treated it like an overblown missing-persons case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still an open case. Nothing indicates foul play,'' Sgt.
Steve Baker said in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel they just took off. It was a planned departure,'' said
Baker, who worked the O'Hair case until late last year.
</P>
<P>
   But other agencies have come to view things differently, and in
recent weeks, the police action has been fast and furious.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the FBI questioned people in Michigan, Illinois
and Texas. Searches in Austin and Detroit allegedly turned up
illegal weapons, and two ex-convicts are now behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   On Easter weekend, more than three dozen federal agents scoured
a ranch 120 miles west of San Antonio for the buried bodies of
O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and daughter Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI apparently found nothing in their search south of the
community of Camp Wood.
</P>
<P>
   The two men in jail, although linked to O'Hair, face only
federal firearms charges. As former convicts who served time for
felony offenses, they are forbidden to possess guns or ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Gary P. Karr, 50, is being held in Detroit. In a hearing in
Detroit, an FBI agent testified that Karr talked for more than 13
hours and admitted involvement in four Texas homicides, including
one that involved decapitation of one victim.
</P>
<P>
   The other arrested man, David R. Waters, 52, is a former office
manager of O'Hair's. Waters, who is being held in Texas, insists
he's innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no clue what they are talking about,'' said Austin
lawyer Patrick Ganne said of Waters. ``He's concerned that the
whole weight of the federal government is coming down on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Karr nor Waters has been charged with any crime
connected to the O'Hair case or with the slaying of a Florida man
named Danny Fry.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's nude, headless and handless body was dumped along a
riverbank near Dallas on Oct. 2, 1995, days after the O'Hair family
vanished with $500,000 in gold coins. He was not identified until
January.
</P>
<P>
   Fry family members say he went to Texas in mid-summer 1995 after
his old buddy, Waters, offered a lucrative _ if mysterious _ deal.
</P>
<P>
   Fry was last heard from Sept. 30, 1995, the day after O'Hair,
her son and daughter vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The search near Camp Wood, people close to the case believe, was
prompted by information Karr gave to the FBI. Specifically, they
were seeking metal drums containing the dismembered remains of the
three O'Hairs.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI declines even to acknowledge that the O'Hair case took
it to Camp Wood, a town of 595 people that usually stirs only
during deer season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no warning. It was really exciting. Everybody
wonders why they would bring them all out here and why they would
be on that place,'' Mayor Jim Blakeney said, referring to the men
and women in blue jumpsuits reading ``FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens next may depend on Karr, who, according to the FBI
testimony, has already implicated himself as an accessory in four
murders.
</P>
<P>
   If this is true, the only bargaining chip Karr may have left
would be to show the FBI exactly where the bodies were concealed.
</P>
<P>
   But there no signs that Karr will be returning soon to Texas. He
first faces a firearms charge in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   He also is charged in Texas with a count of transporting stolen
property across state lines. The item in question is believed to be
personal jewelry that belonged to one of the O'Hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's lawyer, Richard Helfrick, a public defender in Detroit,
said so far no one from Texas has approached him to discuss any
possible deals with his client.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrick said Karr's circumstances may become more clear in the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate anything happening until Monday when the
prosecutor returns from vacation. At least then we'll get to
talk,'' he said of Assistant U.S. Attorney Ken Chadwell.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair's son doubts that the bodies of his family are still on
the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the delay in investigating this thing, I'm
wondering if some individual had time on his hands to go back there
and remove them,'' Bill Murray said by telephone from his home in
Fredericksburg, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
