<HEADER>
A2577 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOM-GREENQ&AMP;A11-COX     04-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOM-GREENQ&AMP;A11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Skate punk' picks up fans via edgy pranks
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 11.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MTV's Tom Green has become a hit with under-30 viewers by going
where few TV hosts have gone before. We Caught up with him recently
in his New York office. Off the air, the 27-Year-old Canadian is as
thoughtful and subdued as he is manic and outrageous on it. Q: Why
do Canadian comedians seem so over-represented in the U.S.?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're this little insecure nation stuck beside this huge
country. We're kind of like: ``Look at me! I'm over here!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who's watching you?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're young, hanging out in malls, riding skateboards,
getting kicked out of places and told you can't do that _ they like
watching me do that. Sixteen-year-olds love the show.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who were your influences?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot of it was growing up as a skateboarder _ it's a
subculture, getting kicked off buses, out of places for being a
bratty skate punk. Growing up I was also always watching (David)
Letterman. When I was 14, I broke my toe and couldn't skate, so I
sat in bed every night watching him. Back then he was doing a lot
of things in the street with video, and I would watch and say,
``That's what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   A: I grew up as an Army brat, and my first seven years we were
moving every six months. I'd walk into school the last week of
class, this skinny kid, and the only way to exist without being an
outcast was to make everyone laugh. Those are my earliest memories
of school _ the point of going to school was to have an audience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You put your parents through a lot. You get along with them?
</P>
<P>
   A: I like them; we talk four or five times a week. They don't
really like this stuff happening to them, but there's not much I
can do about that. They're supportive of me going out and having a
career. There has always been pressure on me to go out and work, so
I don't think they took my comedy seriously until three years ago
when I was actually getting paid to do it. There's a funny irony to
that: They kind of never took me seriously, and now that it's
working out, part of that is getting paid to throw a dead cow's
head in their bed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the angriest they ever got?
</P>
<P>
   A: When I painted their house plaid while they were on a canoe
trip. They got really mad and took my car away. They wouldn't give
it back until I painted the house back the way it was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there such a thing as a bad idea for your show?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are plenty. It's all about getting a genuine reaction
from people, so if somebody understands the joke, starts playing to
the camera, then it's bad.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what's a good idea?
</P>
<P>
   A: Whatever makes what's going on so dominate the scene they
forget they're being filmed. It's not as funny to see me out there
acting silly; somebody watching me act silly is a big part of the
joke. I've interviewed enough that I can get people to interact in
a real way, whether it's confused, surprised, angry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Like the old guy who grabbed your mike and threatened you
with it?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's where we yell, ``Gold!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a line you won't cross?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are plenty. I don't want anyone to get hurt; I don't
want to be mean-spirited toward anybody. I've been doing this long
enough to know when to run away.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have to get in character for this?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've adapted the way I live to be able to do it on a constant
basis. When I'm not taping, I'm not funny anymore. I used to be a
constant goofball. Now I'm in recharge battery mode. Anybody only
has a certain amount of funny in them per week. If we're shooting
four or five days a week, I believe in just kind of being quiet and
recharging my funny battery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are Glenn (Humplik) and Phil (Giroux) on the show?
</P>
<P>
   A: I met Glenn while I was doing college radio, eight to 10
years ago. Phil I met skateboarding when I was 14, and Derek
(Harvie, the show's head writer) I met when I was 8 in elementary
school. So it just grew into this thing where Glenn would sit
beside me, I'd put him on the spot, and Phil would laugh. They make
it feel less like a TV show and more like three guys hanging out
making a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You worry about always having to up the bar for what
outrageous thing you're going to do next?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're always trying to top the last thing we did in our
``insanity bits.'' I am a little worried how in two years we're
going to end up _ throwing babies off the Empire State Building?
</P>
<P>
   Q: I thought the line you wouldn't cross is anybody getting
hurt?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's our line at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
