<HEADER>
A2578 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOMGREEN-MTV11-COX     04-09 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOMGREEN-MTV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outrageousness earns Tom Green cult status on MTV
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April, 11.
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has suckled milk from a cow, airbrushed a lesbian love scene
on the hood of his parents' car and scuba-dived for small change in
a mall fountain (when evicted by security, he bagged the money and
donated it to the rich at a nearby bank).
</P>
<P>
   He's also put a dead cow's head in his parents' bed (``This is a
message from Don Corleone!''), pretended to have sex with a dead
moose beside a Canadian highway and served chest-hair sandwiches to
vacationers on an ocean cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences? Tom Green has been threatened with arrest,
threatened with violence _ and given his own show on MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has incredible relevance to our audience, doing things I
know they all wish they could do,'' says John Miller, the MTV
executive who brought ``The Tom Green Show'' from Canada to his
network, where it has become a gross-out smash.
</P>
<P>
   Relevance? It's juvenile _ unless you're juvenile. Then it's
cutting edge, a hybrid that crosses irony with tastelessness to
produce its own out-there genre: the New Annoyance. It's stupid
simple: a half-hour of Green in a New York studio, flanked by a
couple of old friends, chatting up an audience and introducing his
unholy videos.
</P>
<P>
   You can hardly walk through a college campus without running
into fans _ Green's show is MTV's highest rated regular program
among 18- to 34-year-olds, and was the third-highest rated show on
cable, behind wrestling on USA and TNT, in its old Monday time
slot. (It now airs at 10:30 p.m. Thursdays, with 13 new episodes
beginning April 22.) Its audience is about 60 percent male.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sick,'' ``shameless'' and ``random'' are compliments one hears
walking through the Georgia State University campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes a complete fool out of himself. That's what's so
funny _ he does what no one else does,'' says Lindsay Galloway, a
GSU freshman education major. ``It's a young people thing. Old
people probably wouldn't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He relates to things that we would do, or friends would do,
and he gets paid for it,'' says Noel Stieglitz, a fellow GSU
freshman and a computer information systems major.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Green is a storky 27-year-old Canadian who has pranked and
bad-tasted his way to youth cult status, mainstream division. He
was featured in Pepsi commercials roaming campuses during the
recent NCAA tournament. (He shouted through a bullhorn inside a
library, made a student drink soda out of his mitten). He had to
cancel a comedy segment he tried to tape at the St. Patrick's Day
Parade in New York when too many young people mobbed him. He
recently completed a movie that stars ``Saturday Night Live''
regular Will Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his life outside the show, Green sighs, ``These days
there really isn't one.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has been doing what he does for about 10 years in Canada.
He began his show on radio, then moved it to an Ottawa public
access channel in 1994. Four years later it was picked up by
Canada's Comedy Network, where it became a hit.
</P>
<P>
   The MTV version is essentially what the show has looked like all
along. Beyond the taped man-on-the-street inanity, Green looks for
laughs while seated in a studio with old friends Glenn Humplik
(think a doughier Andy Richter of ``Late Night With Conan
O'Brien'') and Phil Giroux (who sits behind a fake window, drinking
coffee and laughing continuously). Its look is somewhere between
slick and schlocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more watchable now. There are more people working on it,
more thought goes into each minute,'' Green says. ``In Canada,
there were like three people working on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   TV PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tom Green Show''
</P>
<P>
   10:30 p.m. Thursdays on MTV
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   This site gets you to most of the other Green-related addresses:
ottawastart.com/tomgreen.shtml
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
