<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: dire around.   &HT;    The company, based in Costa Mesa, Calif., was formed Dec. 14
from the merger of 36 smaller firms. Overnight, 35 former
entrepreneurs were playing second or third fiddle to one large
organization. And 1,344 employees who had worked for tiny companies
were working for a middle-sized one that now plans to go public.
 &HT;    Long before the December D-Day, Christopher Massey, the prime
mover behind the new company and now its chief executive, met with
the other business heads to form integration teams that, as soon as
the deal was final, would visit every office to answer questions.
They charged one person with integrating all the computer systems.
They hammered out a stock option and benefits plan.
 &HT;    When the deal was done, the executives were ready with a 30-page
booklet that detailed compensation plans and career opportunities.
It addressed frankly the culture shocks that might be ahead but
also devoted considerable ink to the benefits of combining client
bases and cash flows.
 &HT;    ``We wanted employees, from Day One, to be able to go home and
prove to their spouses that there was a lot of security,'' Massey
said. ``And we needed to prove to ourselves that we really could
turn all those different firms into a single company with a single
culture.''
 &HT;    He had better prove it fast. EPS closed six more acquisitions
last month.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 PRACTICING THE STEPS EVEN BEFORE THE DANCE  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no cookie-cutter approach to merging two companies
successfully into one.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that buy other businesses only once in a while usually
create a full-time but temporary integration team for any new
purchase; the team is disbanded once the acquired company is
sufficiently acclimated. Companies like the specialty chemicals
maker Hercules Inc., which buy and merge at a steady but not heady
pace, often assign a high-level executive to oversee the
integration of a new company, giving him or her access to staff
support. And corporations like Lucent Technologies or Cisco
Systems, which make acquisitions often, tend to have permanent
teams whose sole job is to integrate the new companies into their
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have the same people doing it, then every deal
acts as a shock to your whole system,'' said Ammar Hanafi, Cisco's
director of business development, who coordinates integration
efforts both before and after acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Differences aside, more and more companies are planning for
integration even as they research deals. Well before an acquisition
is closed, both companies are deciding whose compensation programs
will survive, which offices or plants will close, which executives
will run the combined business units or be primary contacts for
customers, and how the integration process will be communicated to
employees. They are ferreting out potential culture clashes and
designing training programs to combat them.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, they are creating detailed implementation plans,
complete with milestones, for making the merger work _ and fast.
``Having a permanent integration team shaves months off the
integration process,'' said Patricia Russo, the executive vice
president who oversees Lucent's merger integration group.
</P>
</TEXT>
