<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP TARGETS TEXANS AS HOUSE CAMPAIGN STARTS EARLY
 &HT;    520&AMP;add. With CONSERVATIVES-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and
(p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the smallest House majority in 44 years, the
Republican Party is gearing up for the next election early by
targeting Democrats in districts friendly to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The voting may be more than 18 months away, but the National
Republican Congressional Committee has begun sending out press
releases attacking the voting records of conservative and moderate
House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely are keeping a close eye on key Democrats who we
think are vulnerable in 2000,'' said Jill Schroeder, spokesperson
for the NRCC.
</P>
<P>
   One focus of the campaign is Texas, where the hit list includes
Chet Edwards of Waco, Max Sandlin of Marshall and Jim Turner of
Crockett.
</P>
<P>
   The three are on a ``a big list'' of House seats that the NRCC
considers as possible GOP gains next year, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the House race has already started, Schroeder answered:
``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent press release criticized Edwards and Sandlin for voting
against the GOP budget blueprint for next year, saying they were
trying to block billions of dollars for schools and tax relief for
middle-class families.
</P>
<P>
   Another NRCC press release accused Sandlin of putting ``foreign
interests ahead of aid to Texas families'' by rejecting ``$153
million in much-needed assistance for farmers.'' It referred to a
$1.2 billion supplemental spending bill passed by the House last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said other Texas Democrats, including Turner, can
expect more NRCC press releases about their votes throughout the
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   She said the press releases are not meant to attack lawmakers,
but to inform voters. ``This is certainly an effort on our behalf
to let people back home know what their members are doing,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin said the attacks will not resonate with voters, who are
tired of partisan bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republicans spent as much time working on policy as
they do sending out bogus press releases, maybe we could get
something done in the country,'' he said. ``I guess it shows what
their mind set really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin was one of 211 House members who opposed the spending
bill. He said its provisions could hurt foreign markets for U.S.
agriculture. ``The very last thing that Texas farmers need is to
have another financial crisis abroad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' spokesperson, Vance Gore, said Edwards voted against
the GOP budget plan because it is ``nothing short of pie in the
sky,'' and that Edwards ``wants to see money put into Social
Security and Medicare and paying down the national debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Walter, who follows the House for the Cook Political Report,
said the Republicans' key to keeping control of the chamber, where
they now have a 10-seat majority, is finding strong challengers for
incumbent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sending out a press release and dogging them for their votes
is one thing. Getting a really strong candidate in against them is
the real test,'' she said. ``You can have everything going for you
on paper but if you don't have a good candidate, none of that is
going to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the GOP focus on Texas, some strategists say, is
that a presidential candidacy by popular Gov. George W. Bush could
translate into Republican gains in congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, Bush's re-election coattails extended only
to statewide races as every Democratic House incumbent from Texas
headed back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason was that some Texas Democrats have their own
conservative credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and Sandlin voted with Republicans for a tax cut last
year, and they voted in favor of a constitutional amendment to
allow school prayer that fell short of the two-thirds majority
needed for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Turner was among only 31 Democrats in the House to vote for the
GOP's open-ended impeachment inquiry of President Clinton's
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of key votes in the previous Congress showed that
Turner voted against his own party's majority 41 percent of the
time. Edwards voted against the Democrats only 16 percent of the
time, the analysis showed, leading many strategists to conclude
that the GOP missed a golden opportunity last year by not running a
Republican candidate against him.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the Texans' districts are considered conservative.
The Republican presidential candidate, Bob Dole, outpolled
President Clinton in Edwards' and Sandlin's districts in 1996 and
ran even with him in Turner's.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
