<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTER CRONKITE HONORS COURAGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Ala., La.)  By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A couple of years ago, the Interfaith Alliance, a
relatively small organization with the big-time goal of countering
the political activities of religious conservative groups, sent out
a fund-raising letter that turned out to be a news-maker.
</P>
<P>
   It contained a message from Walter Cronkite, former anchorman of
the ``CBS Evening News,'' whom polls once showed to be among the
most trusted figures in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a decade,'' he wrote, ``I have watched with growing
apprehension the rise to political influence in our country of a
genuinely radical movement known as the religious right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then the alliance _ whose directors come from across the
spectrum of major religions, Western and Eastern _ has seen its
membership nearly double to more than 80,000, said its executive
director, the Rev. C. Welton Gaddy, a Baptist minister from Monroe,
La.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alliance would not be as strong as it is today, if it were
not for the endorsement of Cronkite,'' Gaddy said.
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting next to the man he had praised, in Cronkite's
Manhattan apartment on Thursday. The next day, the organization
presented a new award, the Walter Cronkite Faith and Freedom Award,
intended to honor people who work for religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite said he had lent his name to the organization ``because
of my exceedingly deep concern that there are people who were
usurping the Christian doctrine to pursue a political agenda.'' He
said that the message of those people was that anyone who did not
agree with them was not a good Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite specifically criticized the Christian Coalition, the
organization founded by the religious broadcaster Pat Robertson,
and its widely distributed voter guides, which the coalition says
compare the positions of candidates seeking public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has the right to tell me if I'm a good Christian,''
Cronkite said. ``That's in my heart and in my soul. It's
particularly no one's business if it's a political objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he retired as CBS anchorman in March 1981, Cronkite, 82,
has kept a busy giving speeches, writing his autobiography and
making television documentaries. It was while working on a
documentary a few years ago that he encountered the alliance and
also grew concerned about the political influence of religious
conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite said he was later asked by Terry Anderson, the former
Associated Press reporter who spent five years as a hostage in
Lebanon, if he would help the alliance, which also describes its
mission as attempting to inject ``civility and compassion into
civil affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My conscience could not permit me to turn it down,'' Cronkite
said, adding that he felt free to help because he no longer worked
for a news organization and did not have to ``run from taking a
position on things.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite said he felt an affinity with the Interfaith Alliance,
a five-year-old group based in Washington. ``One of the misfortunes
is, we didn't organize earlier,'' he said. ``It gave the demagogues
of the extreme right a headstart.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it has more than 100 chapters nationwide, the
Interfaith Alliance seems dwarfed compared with the Christian
Coalition. The alliance, together with its own nonprofit
foundation, has a budget of $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the coalition's budget this year will total $15
million to $20 million, said its executive director, Randy Tate. It
also has a list of 2.1 million people who contribute either money
or time to its work.
</P>
<P>
   As for Cronkite's criticism, Tate responded generally: ``Our
belief is that all Americans, including religious conservatives,
have every right to be involved in the political process,'' he
said. ``Unfortunately, some on the religious left, including the
Interfaith Alliance, would attempt to stifle the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Cronkite asked not to have a hand in selecting recipients of the
award that bears his name. That was done by a six-person committee,
one of whose members, former President Gerald Ford, suggested the
award go to people not already well known, Gaddy said.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony in Manhattan Saturday, awards were given to the
Rev. Chriss H. Doss, director of the Center for the Study of Law
and the Church at Samford University in Birmingham, Ala., and to
Donna Red Wing, national field director of the Human Rights
Campaign, which supports gay and lesbian rights.
</P>
<P>
   According to the alliance, Doss encouraged public acceptance in
Alabama of a court ruling against school prayer, and Ms. Red Wing
created an interfaith worship event for supporters of gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we want to honor here is courage,'' Cronkite
said. ``Because it takes courage to stand up in most communities in
America and enunciate what might be a minority position.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he described himself as ``a person of faith'' in the
alliance's fund-raising letter, Cronkite did not think it was
appropriate to discuss his religious beliefs in detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``No, because that is the very principle that I
am defending,'' he said. ``I want to stand on that principle. It is
nobody's business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
