</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT10-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, April 10,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: Deletes CRONKITE-FAITH. Adds: KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-REFUGEES, TORNADO-FAMILY, TORNADO-COACH, TEST-TAMPERING,
TORT-REFORM-BILL, STOLEN-HOSTS.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ A top Yugoslav diplomat said Friday
it would be ``unnatural'' to release three U.S. soldiers while NATO
continues to bomb his country. Meanwhile, NATO pressed its air
attacks despite bad weather. In Moscow, Russian President Boris
Yeltsin warned NATO not to introduce ground forces into the
conflict. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Congress, which left town two
weeks ago as the bombing of Yugoslavia began, returns Monday to
confront a war that is escalating daily. Lawmakers have been quiet
on the issue, but some influential members are beginning to speak
up in favor of using ground troops. 20. (Malone, Cox News Service).
ETA: 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA _ KORCE, Albania _ More than 10,000 bewildered
Kosovo refugees are recovering from their second or even third
forced deportation in as many weeks, after authorities in
neighboring Macedonia tricked them onto buses and abruptly dumped
them off here in this chilly border town. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox
News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees Sadako Ogata said Friday that Macedonia's government has
assured her that its borders will remain open and that more fleeing
ethnic Albanians will be free to seek sanctuary here. The
announcement came after Macedonia relocated refugees a few days ago
and said it would not take any more. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-TRIP _ WASHINGTON _ Interview with Rep. Jim Turner,
D-Texas, who returned late Thursday from a trip to NATO
headquarters and NATO's Aviano air base. About a dozen lawmakers
traveled with Defense Secretary William Cohen on the two-day trip
to examine U.S. troop safety and readiness in the Balkans. Turner
represents the 2nd Congressional District of Texas, which includes
Huntsville, the home of Spc. Steven Gonzales, one of three American
soldiers captured last week by Serbian forces. (Cox News Service).
ETA: 7 p.m. ATTN: Texas eds.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO _ CINCINNATI _ An early morning tornado three to five
miles long ripped through the suburb of Blue Ash and the
surrounding area and left at least seven dead, a dozen injured,
200,000 without power. This was an F1 or F2 storm, which means
winds of up to 160 miles per hour. (Dayton Daily News, Cox News
Service) Eds: This national weather wrap will include material from
other states as needed. WITH PHOTOS from Dayton, which shot both on
the ground and in the air in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-FAMILY _ CINCINNATI _ The sound of a siren through an
open bedroom woke up high school senior Julie Streck in Blue Ash
just before 5 a.m. Good thing. She quickly alerted her three
siblings and parents and together they hustled into the basement as
the tornado hit. In seconds, their kitchen was in the back yard,
the flooring over the basement where the Strecks huddled was ripped
off and a huge outdoors deck was gone. This will be an eyewitness
account. (Budd, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-COACH _ CINCINNATI _ The home of Cincinnati Bengals
assistant coach Al Roberts in Blue Ash was destroyed and two
neighbors down his street were killed. Roberts was in bed at 5:30
when he heard the wind. He didn't have much time to think about it.
The wind lifted him and his wife out of his bed, tossed them aside
and the mattress landed on top of him. Roberts said he looked up at
the empty sky through his missing roof and prayed. Bricks from his
chimney smashed one of his two cars. (Ludwig, Dayton Daily News)
Eds: Moving in National, Sports categories
</P>
<P>
   TORNADO-ANNIVERSARY _ ATLANTA _ While Cincinattians awoke to
neighborhood destruction unlike anything they'd ever imagined,
Atlantans marked the one-year anniversary of a killer tornado that
spawned simillar destruction exactly one year ago. Georgia Gov. Roy
Barnes congratulated the residents of the Dunwoody section of
Atlanta on their spirit of survival, and the neighborhood
celebrated with block parties, a worship service and the giving
away of 8,000 trees to replant the Dunwoody forest. Residents also
reacted to the destruction in Ohio. (Jaskevich, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-TAMPERING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The criminal indictments
against the Austin school district and its No. 2 administrator
demonstrate the kind of pressure to perform that the state's
accountability has fostered. What began with the discovery that
mistakes in data could have caused an Austin school to get a lower
rating than it deserved, became deliberate altering of test data to
give schools higher ratings than they deserved. We get people to
talk about the atmosphere in which the tampering occurred and
layout the chronology. (Jayson, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TORT-REFORM-BILL _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Tort reformers' key bill is
expected to be voted out of a legislative subcommittee on Thursday,
but it might be too late. The bill languished for at least three
weeks in a special subcommittee created by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry to
handle all tort reform legislation. The subcommittee is chaired by
Perry's boyhood friend, Troy Fraser, who has positioned himself as
the key tort reform champion this year. Yet, he was unable to
quickly get the bill out of his own committee. The bill relates to
how juries assess blame _ and monetary damages _ against employers
for civil liability. (McCarthy, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   STOLEN-HOSTS _ PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ Thieves broke into St.
Ignatius Cathedral overnight, stole the tabernacle and descrated
it. The thieves took the sacred box into a nearby field, perhaps
thinking it contained money, and tore it open. They scattered the
consecrated hosts over the field. In the Catholic religion, the
consecrated hosts represent the body of Christ. This is not the
first time the cathedral, home to the bishop who presides over the
diocese of Palm Beach, has been vandalized. The clergy are in
shock, say the tabernacle and maybe even the whole cathedral will
have to reconsecrated. (Brogan, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKCOLLEGE-REUNION _ The Black College Reunion in Daytona
Beach is gathering steam with an expectedf 100,000 students
arriving from around the east coast and southeast. We look at
parallels to Atlanta _ how involved are local colleges, what is the
atittude of local police and governments, what is the acceptance of
the local residents.
</P>
<P>
   (Suggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-BEE _ MIAMI _ For 70 straight years, a U.S. citizen won
the annual national spelling bee. But last May, Jamaica's Jody-Anne
Maxwell became the first non-citizen to triumph. This year, though,
Jamaica is out. The island traditionally picks its winner in
August. But new rules disqualify any representative who wins her
regional spell-off before February. That's got a lot of Jamaicans,
as well as African-Americans, charging that racism is at work.
(Emling, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTO. MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-CONSERVATIVES _ WASHINGTON _ A powerful GOP group is
already attacking the voting records of conservative democrats in
the new Congress. Those on the hit list include Texans Chet
Edwards, of Waco; Max Sandlin, of Marshall; and Jim Turner, of
Crockett. All three represent conservative districts which could be
heavily targeted by the GOP in 2000. It looks like the battle to
control the House is underway _ a cool 18 months before the
election. And the excitement over a George W. Bush candidacy is
fueling GOP dreams of long coattails in conservative Texas
districts. (Moscoso, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Boxes for Edwards, Sandlin and Turner _ How conservative are
they? Ratings by conservative groups. And stats on the districts
they represent _ what percent of their constituents voted for the
GOP in the last election. (Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
