s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV11-N     04-09 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Earnings Radar, Clearer Skies Ahead  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corporate earnings growth remains below the double-digit annual
pace it hit during much of the 1990s. But after a lackluster
increase of 3.7 percent last year, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index seems back on track to reporting decent first-quarter gains,
according to First Call Corp. of Boston, which tracks the earnings
forecasts of Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   First Call estimates that S&AMP;P earnings from continuing
operations will jump 8 percent to 9 percent for the first quarter
versus the corresponding period last year. If the forecasts are
accurate, it would be the first time since 1997 that quarterly
results beat the index's long-term growth rate of 7 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the first-quarter growth is expected to come from
technology companies. The analysts surveyed by First Call predicted
a 33 percent increase in quarterly profits from such concerns.
Chuck Hill, First Call's research director, says many of these
companies have easy numbers to beat from last year, when computer
makers' first-quarter results suffered as retailers reduced
inventories.
</P>
<P>
   But the predictions call for very weak results from energy,
commodity and basic materials companies. Analysts expect
first-quarter energy profits, for example, to drop 50 percent,
according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more good news. The number of ``negative earnings
preannouncements'' _ disclosures that earnings are not going to
meet expectations _ is running far below previous tallies.
</P>
<P>
   IBES International, another earnings tracker, says just 76
percent of first-quarter preannouncements were negative _ the
smallest percentage since it started collecting the data three
years ago. (The average is 83 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 6,000 companies tracked by IBES will not report
results for a few weeks, but Joseph Abbott, an IBES equity
strategist, says the data are a good sign. ``Springtime is starting
to look sunny again, and the economy is getting warm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.
</P>
<P>
   April 15: The Deadline for Incremental Rate Applications
</P>
<P>
   With April 15 only four days away, harried investors are of
course rushing to open their ``Incremental Rate Applications'' for
1998. That is, their ``Indivisible Retirement Allowances.'' Or was
it their ``Income Ratification Arrangements?''
</P>
<P>
   If you are confused, you are not alone. According to a recent
poll by American Century Investments, 31 percent of investors could
not identify what ``IRA'' stood for in investing. When answering a
multiple-choice question, many chose from the examples listed
above, refused to answer or confessed to not knowing. (Technically,
IRA is an abbreviation for Individual Retirement Arrangement, but
pollsters also gave credit for the more common term, Individual
Retirement Account.)
</P>
<P>
   Nomenclature was not the only difficult subject for investors.
In the poll, 753 people who saved for retirement were asked 10
questions about IRAs; the average number of correct answers was 4.
And no one had a perfect score.
</P>
<P>
   A sample question: Can a person contribute to both a Roth IRA
and a traditional IRA? Answer: Yes (if the total is no more than
$2,000).
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD TEITELBAUM
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH: DO SMALL-CAP ANALYSTS MATTER?
</P>
<P>
   Is the Wall Street analyst becoming irrelevant to the top
executives of America's smaller companies and the mutual fund
managers who own small-capitalization shares? Possibly, according
to a survey by Tempest Consultants, a London-based firm.
</P>
<P>
   The survey examined several industry issues from the perspective
of corporations with market values of $3 billion or less. It showed
a growing conflict between the priorities of analysts and the
desires of both the fund families and the companies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The funds want the analysts to provide more basic research.
Unfortunately, the report said, roughly 500 analysts surveyed say
they would prefer to spend less time visiting small companies and
doing fundamental research and more time visiting institutional
clients, like fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   The top executives of these small companies already feel
neglected by Wall Street analysts, according to the survey. As a
result, they plan to spend more time with the funds' own analysts,
they said. ``In some cases this has marginalized the role of the
broker as the intermediary'' between small companies and the funds
that buy their shares, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   Tempest polled more than 1,000 small companies and 54 of the 100
largest small-cap funds, in addition to Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DIANA B. HENRIQUES
</P>
</TEXT>
