<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-SEVERANCE-BOS &LR;      04-09 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-SEVERANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TERMS LATEST SEVERANCE PACKAGE BEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Sensitive to criticism that its previous downsizing
programs were too harsh, Fleet Financial Group Inc. unveiled Friday
what it termed its best severance package ever for thousands of
staff members who will lose their jobs as a result of the company's
merger with BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   While falling slightly short of a similar plan announced last
week by BankBoston, Fleet's severance terms are ``very
comprehensive and generous,'' Fleet said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, New England's largest bank, said it expects a reduction
of about 5,000 jobs at the combined company _ at the upper end of
the 4,000 to 5,000 range cited earlier by both banks. The trimming
will reduce the new company's 60,000-strong work force by 8.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Fleet and BankBoston, which are merging to form the
nation's eighth-largest bank, hope actual layoffs will be lower due
to a hiring freeze and attrition. Fleet said layoff levels would
not exceed 5,000 and that actual numbers could be lower.
</P>
<P>
   A four-page Fleet memo sent to the company's 35,000 staff
members outlined the severance program and promised more details
later.
</P>
<P>
   With basic severance pay, ``enhanced'' pay, merger supplements,
extended medical and life insurance, and assistance in finding new
jobs, Fleet's program is nearly identical to BankBoston's.
</P>
<P>
   Payouts are calculated according to salary levels and years of
service. The main difference between the two companies' packages is
that laid-off Fleet workers can receive a maximum total severance
benefit equal to 60 weeks of base pay, while for BankBoston
employees the period is nearly 87 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our severance program provides a solid financial foundation
for employees to transition to new jobs,'' said Fleet spokesman
James Mahoney. ``We think it's generous by any measure.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to previous years, Fleet promised to provide
comprehensive assistance and job placement programs to help
laid-off employees find new work. Fleet had few such programs when
it cut approximately 3,000 workers after acquiring Shawmut National
Corp. in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Like BankBoston, Fleet is offering laid-off employees two weeks'
base pay for each year of service; an enhanced package ranging from
10 weeks to 30 weeks of base pay; and a supplement ranging from 4.3
to 8.7 weeks of base salary.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs help companies that are merging achieve savings by
eliminating job overlap. Job cuts at the combined bank will not
take place until after the merger is completed later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, which has acquired 50 companies in the past 10 years, has
let thousands go as a result of its acquisitions and cost-cutting
drives. While Fleet chief executive Terrence Murray is praised as
an efficient manager, he was criticized for an unpopular austerity
drive in 1993-1994 in which staff members who found ways to save
money lost their jobs anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, BankBoston took pains to be sensitive to employees
when it reduced its work force by 2,000 after acquiring BayBanks
Inc. in 1996. Then, the company consulted with religious and
academic figures to develop its severance program.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Fleet employees, many BankBoston workers will receive a
miniature windfall in stock options as a result of the merger. The
options, granted in recent years, can be exercised because
BankBoston is technically being acquired by Fleet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
