<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SIGNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO BILLBOARD AD CHANGE TO IMPACT 2 BOSTON COMPANES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Tobacco ads may soon have an impact on two Boston
companies.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts' largest billboard company has to wean
itself of all cigarette advertising revenues by the end of the
year, New England's largest ad agency, Arnold Communications, has a
chance to win millions of dollars in new business for devising
antismoking ads.
</P>
<P>
   Under a settlement reached last year between states and the
tobacco industry, billboard cigarette advertising will be pulled
down by the end of the month, even though tobacco companies had
already leased billboard space for all 12 months of 1999, said Liz
Palumbo, president of AK Media of Massachusetts, the state's
largest owner of billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cigarette ads come down, the billboards will feature
antismoking messages from state governments, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the state's Department of Public Health has
been running antismoking ads for nearly six years, but many states
don't have similar programs.
</P>
<P>
   So the National Cancer Institute has turned to two ad agencies
to come up with a national billboard campaign that will break on
these newly opened up billboards in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One of those ad agencies is Arnold, which already handles the
$11 million annual account for the Massachusetts Department of
Public Health's antismoking efforts.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of the National Cancer Institute, Arnold has devised a
series of ads that could appear on billboards in about 17 states,
including Georgia, Massachusetts, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold will receive only a small payment for these ads, but the
ads could give Arnold wide exposure at a time when a foundation set
up by the tobacco settlement is contemplating spending millions of
dollars on antismoking efforts.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gregory Connolly, director of the tobacco control
program at the Massachusetts Department of Public Health, that
foundation plans to spend $1.5 billion over five years, most of it
earmarked for antismoking ads.
</P>
<P>
   Given its experience in the field, Arnold is well positioned to
win a chunk of that money, said Connolly, who may be biased as the
head of an agency that's an Arnold client.
</P>
<P>
   Of course with as much as $300 million a year at stake, many ad
agencies will be vying for the account.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold got the state's antismoking account when it acquired
Houston Herstek Favat in early 1998. The campaign has won a slew of
industry awards, and the latest series of ads, with the theme
``Where's the outrage?'' broke this week.
</P>
<P>
   Award-winning work was one reason why Arnold was selected in
1998 by the US Food and Drug Administration to devise a $10
million-a-year ad campaign aimed at discouraging store clerks from
selling cigarettes to minors, said Lisa Unsworth, an Arnold
executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold is certainly interested in bidding for the Tobacco
Control Foundation's account, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But how that will play out is anyone's guess. Not everyone
thinks antismoking ads are a good idea. Potential critics could
include Governor Paul Cellucci, who has questioned the
effectiveness of antismoking ads and has suggested that public
money would be better spent on AIDS victims and fire prevention
programs for school children.
</P>
<P>
   As Arnold considers its next move, AK Media is adjusting to life
without tobacco ads, once the lifeblood of billboard companies. A
decade ago, about 25 percent of the company's billboards were
leased by tobacco companies, Palumbo said.
</P>
<P>
   But by the beginning of 1999, tobacco ads accounted for only 6
percent of AK's roughly 2,500 billboards; the plan was to have
completely phased out cigarette ads by 2001, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for AK, new technology means that billboard images
can be of comparable quality to a photo in a glossy magazine, and
that has made billboards attractive to Hollywood studios promoting
new movies and to retailers showing off fashions.
</P>
<P>
   These new clients have picked up some of the slack left by
tobacco clients. There's also some hope that the holding companies
that own cigarette brands, which have paid for the billboard space
through the end of 1999, will continue to lease billboards next
year but use the space to advertise their food products.
</P>
<P>
   For example, instead of advertising Marlboros, Philip Morris
might run ads for Kraft Foods.
</P>
<P>
   Palumbo declined to discuss the dollar impact of these changes.
AK Media is part of the Ackerley Group of Seattle, and the group
does not break out revenues by divisions, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
