A2618 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MEALS10-COX     04-09 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MEALS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PENTAGON ORDERS 1.1 MILLION MORE RATIONS FOR REFUGEES
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Defense Department has put in a rush order
for more humanitarian daily rations, the meal packages being
airlifted to help feed Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Three companies _ in Cincinnati, McAllen, Texas, and Mullins,
S.C. _ will share the contract for about 1.1 million more packs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've asked those three manufacturers to accelerate
deliveries,'' Frank Johnson, spokesman for the Defense Supply
Center in Philadelphia, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Doing so will mean some overtime for workers over the next
couple weeks, according to one of the suppliers, SOPAKCO (CQ)
Packaging, in Mullins, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which also prepares Meals Ready-to-Eat food packs
for U.S. soldiers, is to produce about 370,000 of the humanitarian
versions. The humanitarian food packs have about 2,200 calories
each, are designed to provide a full day's nutrition, and do not
contain meat. They cost the U.S. government $3.93 each, Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The other two companies with orders are Wornick Co., McAllen,
Texas, and Ameriqual (CQ), in Cincinnati. Neither could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Half a million humanitarian daily rations were flown from the
United States last week, and another 600,000 are being shipped this
week, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the additional 1.1 million rations will be used to
restock military depots, while part of the order will likely go to
the Balkans, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably will be additional orders coming,'' he said.
``Things are changing all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
