</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS SUPPORT FOR `PATIENT'S BILL OF RIGHTS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ With Congress reconvening next week, President
Clinton flew here Friday to try to whip up public enthusiasm for
the Democratic proposal to establish a ``patient's bill of
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told a group of about 400 union workers and health-care
providers that he had advocated the patients program until he was
``blue in the face,'' but he wanted the public to express its
support by signing a petition on the Internet to counter the
opposition of large health-maintenance organizations and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is a clear, unambiguous signal from the people of
the United States _ not just that we want this, not just that we
need this, not just that we believe in this _ the organized forces
of the status quo will do nothing,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He said opponents were counting on the fact that Friday's public
relations campaign, coordinated with 100 Democrats in Congress
across the country, would not be able to ``break through on the
evening news tonight because of Kosovo,'' and so the
Republican-controlled Congress would not feel any pressure to pass
the legislation, which is one of the Democrats' top priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal for new regulations on HMOs died last
year with the 105th Congress. So far this year, a Senate committee
has approved a Republican bill of rights, which Democrats say is
not strong enough. Republicans say the Democratic plan is too
expensive and overly restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Clinton imposed some aspects of the Democratic bill,
such as access to specialists and emergency treatment, on the 285
private insurance companies that provide coverage for the nation's
9 million federal employees and their families. On Friday he
announced he was requiring the plans to come into full compliance
with the bill, meaning they must add two more provisions: Give
patients more information about their plan and their doctor's fees,
and guarantee them continuity of care if they are in the middle of
a treatment or pregnancy and are forced to change health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a yearlong study of the bill showed that its
provisions would cost patients less than $10 a year on top of what
they pay now, which varies from patient to patient. He does not
have the authority to extend to patients what could be the most
expensive element of the Democratic proposal _ the right to sue
health plans and collect damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2620 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-NATO-BOS &LR;      04-09 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-NATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID CONFLICTING SIGNALS, YELTSIN ISSUES A WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Until Friday, President Boris N. Yeltsin ruled out
Russian military involvement in the conflict over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now that has changed _ to ``maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Western leaders have asked Russia to mediate with
its ally Yugoslavia on ways to end the crisis, Moscow Friday
drastically raised the ante. In a day of nuclear saber-rattling,
contradictory statements and subsequent denials, the clearest
message coming from the Kremlin was this:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have already told NATO, Americans and Germans: Don't force
us to take military action, since that will certainly lead to a
European war or even a world war, which is inadmissible,'' Yeltsin
said in televised remarks during his meeting with the Communist
speaker of the State Duma, the lower house of parliament, Gennady
Seleznyov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia will not get involved in the armed conflict in
Yugoslavia unless the Americans force us into it,'' Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin is under pressure from lawmakers and senior military
officers who interpret NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia as an
imperialist plot against Russia. Friday, the Russian leader
considered a proposal to unite Moscow and Belgrade politically, and
discussed reaiming Russia's nuclear weapons on NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov caused world markets and Western diplomats to shudder
when he said after the meeting that Yeltsin had already given the
command to retarget the missiles ``against those countries which
are carrying out military action against Yugoslavia,'' according to
the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov later backed away from his remarks, saying he had only
discussed the possibility of reaiming the weapons, and the Kremlin
and military commanders denied Yeltsin had given the order.
</P>
<P>
   Defense analysts say it is a quick and easy task for Russia to
redirect its nuclear missiles, currently aimed at nothing, on their
Cold War-era targets: the United States and its Western allies.
</P>
<P>
   But what would be a few seconds' work for programmers at
Russia's Strategic Rocket Forces would also represent a major break
in Moscow's post-Soviet relationship with the West, and a serious
escalation of Russia's oppostion to NATO's airtstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has made wild statements about nuclear weapons before,
once last year referring to Japan's nuclear arsenal (it does not
have one) and in 1997 announcing Russia had decided to remove the
warheads from its nuclear arsenal (it had not.) On those occasions,
Yeltsin's words were widely taken as a sign of his poor grasp of
events, due to illness, or rumored drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The latest remarks come in the context of Russia's harsh
reaction to the NATO attacks, which Yeltsin and his ministers have
called ``barbaric'' and an ``aggression'' against the Serbs, who
are Orthodox Christian Slavs like many Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and his powerful prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, have
carefully avoided doing anything that would cause a clean break
with the West, and have pointedly rejected calls to send troops and
arms to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin has been under pressure to respond to the growing
anti-American mood among Russians, and calls for action in the
State Duma, where he faces an impeachment vote next week. And
Russia's military leaders have sounded increasingly hawkish, and
independent, in their saber-rattling over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin Friday acccused the Duma of trying to blackmail him into
going to war by threatening him with an impeachment vote. Yeltsin's
chief of staff, Alexander Voloshin, threatenend military officers
with immediate dismissal is they made ``militant'' remarks.
Interfax mentioned Anatoly Kvashnin, who has made vague threats
about Russia's ability to use its nuclear weapons if threatened.
Another senior commander, Gen. Viktor Chechevatov, has publicly
called for Moscow to send troops to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Kremlin responded to the hawks, Yeltsin raised the
temperature of his own rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to go on to ground assault, to simply grab
Yugoslavia, make it their protectorate,'' said Yeltsin, speaking in
a hoarse voice a day after undergoing what the Kremlin called a
``check-up.'' ``We will not allow that. (NATO leaders) have to
understand, that Russia is next door...and we, of course, cannot
give up Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's spokesman said the president was seriously considering
Milosevic's request for Yugoslavia to join a political union
between Russia and its former Soviet neighbor, Belarus. Seleznyov
said he thought Yeltsin would make an announcement on the new union
``in a matter of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing what that would mean, Seleznyov again contradicted
himself, first saying he thought Russia would then send troops and
its navy to the Balkans, but later saying in an interview on NTV
television that the purpose of the alliance would be to preempt
further NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think NATO will start bombing our ally with whom we
form a united federation,'' Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's change of course comes after the United States and
other countries quietly appealed to Primakov to help get Milosevic
to agree to Western conditions for ending the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Halting the war would be a huge victory for Primakov, who has
sought to raise Russia's profile in the international arena despite
its weakened economic and political status. But a union with
Yugoslavia may weaken Moscow's already thin credibility in the
West.
</P>
<P>
   ``A union with Yugoslavia reduces Russia's room for manuver,''
said Moscow political analyst Andrei Piontowski. ``This is a really
big chance for Russia, and this is a foolish way to blow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said he would meet with Secretary
of State Madeleine K. Albright next week. Ivanov, who called
Albright to assure her that Russia had not retargeted its weapons,
also repeated Moscow's misigivings on Kosovo, saying he did not
believe NATO when the alliance denied any plans for a ground
invasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
