<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-10-COX     04-09 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    ANOTHER LEG IN PAINFUL ODYSSEY TAKES KOSOVO REFUGEES FURTHER
FROM HOME
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With PHOTOS 
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   KORCE, Albania More than 11,000 bewildered Kosovo refugees are
reeling from their second or even third forced deportation in as
many weeks, after police in neighboring Macedonia tricked them onto
buses and abruptly dumped them off here across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were deceived,'' said Stephen Galegor, (cq) 30, an
evangelical missionary from Fort Collins, Colo., who organized the
initial relief aid when at least 80 busloads of refugees suddenly
showed up at dawn on Wednesday in this mountain town.
</P>
<P>
   He said refugees were told that if they boarded buses in
Macedonia, they could choose their destination, including Britain
or Canada. Instead, they were taken here.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest installment of a sad odyssey for these
resigned, ragged people who tell of beatings, robbery and other
abuses en route from their homes in Serb-controlled Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   By now they speak dispassionately, until some nerve is sprung
and the tears quietly roll.
</P>
<P>
   Hava Kelani is a striking 22-year-old who reluctantly told how
members of a Serb militia stripped her naked.
</P>
<P>
   The women and elders of her family say they left their village
when Serb forces began threatening. They stayed with her uncle in
Pristina six miles away until the Serb police arrived there, too,
and ordered everyone to leave, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As Kelani walked out of the house, she said, five police singled
her out and told her to come back inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put a knife to my throat. They undressed me completely,''
she said. Kelani, who is unmarried, said the men did not rape her,
but took all her valuables, including identity papers and 500
German marks, and slashed most of her clothing with their knives.
Then they told her to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no thoughts of getting out alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Only her underwear and a pair of leggings were intact, but she
struggled into them and the rest of her shredded clothes while
fleeing the house, she recounted. Kelani caught up with her family,
and they headed for the trains that deposited them in a Macedonian
limbo between borders where they were held for nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   Kelani had no tears until talking later about her brother who
has gone missing.
</P>
<P>
   Raif Syla, a creased 80-year-old settled on blankets on a
gymnasium floor here close to his wife and relatives and another
700 or so refugees, also described a painful flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I had was burned, even the cows,'' said Syla.
</P>
<P>
   He said Serb police or paramilitary forces kicked his family out
of their Kosovo village five days before NATO started bombing
Serbia on March 24 . As they began the 10-mile walk to the Kosovo
capital of Pristina, Syla said he watched the Serbs douse his house
with petrol and set it afire. His cattle were killed, his car and
tractor destroyed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After about ten days in Pristina, Serb forces made their way to
the neighborhood where Syla's family had taken refuge. They were
given two hours to clear out, he said, so they went to the trains
as directed, and on to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere on the journey he lost track of two sons and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   He mentions them first, then bemoans the fact that in all this
time there has been no chance to wash his aging body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, I don't believe too much that I will come back to
my village,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Syla and his fellow Kosovar Albanians are stuck here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they were brought here was absolutely inhumane,'' said
the American missionary Galegor, who has worked here in
southeastern Albania for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday and Thursday Macedonian authorities shipped out an
estimated 55,000 refugees, whom they had kept penned up between the
Macedonian and Kosovo borders for as long as a week. Macedonia,
with a majority of restive Serbs, feared upending its own delicate
balance of ethnic peoples and refused entry to the ethnic Albanian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Under increasing international pressure to release the embattled
Kosovar Albanians from the border no-man's land, Macedonia acted.
Around 30,000 were taken to tent camps NATO built further inside
Macedonia, while others were dispersed as far as Turkey. Up to
10,000 still are not accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Galegor said some refugees sent here were told they could choose
their destination including Canada or Britain but then were shoved
onto buses and driven all night until they reached Korce, where
they were disgorged into the soccer stadium and gymnasium. Some
families were split up and sent to different destinations when
Macedonian police loaded them into buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police told us they were sending us to some other country,
like Germany. They said, 'You will go abroad,''' said Melihate
Rrmoku, 47, who sat Friday eating uncooked hot dogs with her
teenaged son and daughter on the section of hard gymnasium
bleachers they have staked out as home. There they sleep and eat
and simply sit all day along with hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
   They may not be abroad, but they are out of the rain. More than
1,000 refugees live in the gym, while others of the Korce
contingent have been taken by buses to stay in surrounding villages
or have been taken in by local families.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
