<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-ABORTION-BOS &LR;      04-09 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-ABORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE SOFTENS HER POSITION ON ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After weeks of contemplating and refining her position on
abortion, Elizabeth Dole Friday said Republicans must recognize
``that good and honorable people disagree'' about the issue and
that the battle to repeal the constitutional right to abortion is
all but a lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's comments continue a trend by some leading Republican
candidates for president to downplay the role of the abortion issue
_ long one of the most powerful and divisive in American politics _
in the national 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Arizona Senator John McCain and now
Dole have all pledged to stick by their anti-abortion principles
while recognizing that an inflexible stance is unlikely to help to
win back the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential field has essentially split into two
camps now, with one side calling for tolerance toward people who
support the right to an abortion and the other side calling the
abolition of abortion a moral imperative.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to a supporter in Phoenix, Dole described herself as
``pro-life, with exceptions in cases of rape or incest, or to save
the life of the mother.'' The one-page thank-you note to Sandy
Cowen-Miller, released by the Dole campaign Friday, is the most
extensive discussion of Dole's views on abortion since she formed
her presidential exploratory committee one month ago.
</P>
<P>
   In it, she said she would support the idea of a constitutional
amendment to ban abortions -- if it were possible. ``But of course,
it's not,'' Dole wrote. ``It's not going to happen because the
American people do not support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Continued discussion and questions about an amendment is
``irrelevant and highly divisive.'' Dole said Republican women can
set the example, refusing ``to be drawn into dead-end debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole said that, instead, she can concentrate on stopping
so-called partial-birth abortions, enacting parental notification
requirements, continuing the ban on government funding of abortion
and doing everything possible to place unwanted babies with
adoptive parents.
</P>
<P>
   Dole received criticism from both the sides of the abortion
debate Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That position means she is willing to accept the status quo
and cannot be counted on to do anything,'' new, said Phyllis
Schlafly, president of the Eagle Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Michelman, the president of the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, said Dole, like Bush and McCain,
is trying to have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has declared herself in opposition to a woman's right to
choose,'' said Michelman, whose group has aired television
commercials in Iowa, New Hampshire and California reminding voters
that Dole and Bush oppose abortion. ``At the same time, she is
trying to reassure the majority of Americans. . .that she won't
pursue an anti-choice amendment if she were in the White House.
That won't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Dole, said the former Red Cross
director issued the letter because she wanted to address the
subject of abortion in a thoughtful manner, rather than in a
television soundbite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of this is that Elizabeth Dole intends to run a
campaign that's an inclusive campaign that brings people
together,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   As Dole, Bush and McCain have tried to soft-pedal their
opposition to abortion, four other GOP hopefuls _ publisher Steve
Forbes, former TV commentator Patrick Buchanan, Gary Bauer, and New
Hampshire Senator Bob Smith _ have put opposition to abortion at
the center of their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   That split was evident Friday as a spokesman for Steve Forbes,
who has embraced the anti-abortion community, blasted Dole and
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds to me like she and Governor Bush are kind of taking
the same position and it basically is to suggest `We're pro-life
but there's not much we can do about this issue so let's put it by
the wayside,' '' said Greg Mueller. ``I don't think that sells to
the pro-life community. They want a candidate who has a clear
agenda to get us to the human life amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   James M. Farrell, a communication professor at the University of
New Hampshire, said it's not difficult to see what Dole, Bush and
McCain are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to find the position that offends the fewest
number of people,'' Farrell said.
</P>
<P>
   And that may play well in the Granite State, which holds the
first presidential primary in the nation and plays a decisive role
in selecting the nominees. New Hampshire has traditionally taken a
libertarian stance when it comes to abortion, preferring to leave
the subject alone. The Legislature tilts to the abortion rights
side of the debate, and the governor, Democrat Jeanne Shaheen,
favors the right to an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that an anti-abortion stance by the
Republican nominee in 1992 and 1996 hurt the candidate more than it
helped among general election voters. The result in 2000 may be a
more pragmatic acknowledgement that the topic is unhealthy for the
politically ambitious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0410-     04-09 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS RETURNS TO BIGGER CONFLICT, CALLS FOR GROUND TROOPS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (I) international categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan congressional delegation returned from
Europe Friday and issued a strongly worded letter urging President
Clinton to plan for the possible use of ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and eight other lawmakers informed
the president that in their view, the air war alone will never
achieve his goal of pushing Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic's
forces out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even assuming the success of the air campaign to significantly
degrade Milosevic's military,'' the letter said, there is ``less
certainty'' that bombing will clear the way for the return of
refugees under international protection.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, who had accompanied Defense Secretary William
Cohen to Europe, told Clinton that ``we believe it prudent for the
U.S. to urge NATO to plan for additional military missions,
including the use of ground forces, in the event that proves
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for ground troops came as Congress is returning from a
two-week spring break during which the crisis has exploded in the
Balkans and the world has watched nearly 1 million refugees forced
out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from both parties plan to meet late Monday with Clinton
to discuss the conflict, which until now the lawmakers have left in
the hands of the administration. However, lawmakers are expressing
growing nervousness over how the president is commanding the
military operation.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from certain what the lawmakers will do beyond
offering recommendations. Congress took no action to limit the
scope of the military operation before the air strikes began and
has so far followed the recent pattern of ceding responsibility to
the president when it comes to deploying the armed forces. Although
the power to declare war is given to Congress by the Constitution,
the power to make war has been increasingly taken by presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that Congress voted to authorize a military strike
was shortly before the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., doubtful of the
Balkan operation from the outset, has been conspicuously quiet
since the bombing campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   That would change if the president opens up the option of ground
troops, said Lott spokesman John Czwartacki (cq). ``If our strategy
and tactics change dramatically, I would expect Congress would
demand to be heard with a full debate and a vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the ground troops option on the table remains highly
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people talking about ground troops like a secret
formula that can make the situation end in a hurry,'' Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., said this week. He called such a plan dangerous
because ``the population that would be confronted would be very
hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's premature to talk about ground troops,'' Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She led a failed attempt to cut off funding for the military
action, at the time insisting Clinton outline his goals and exit
strategy beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met with many Texans who share my concerns about the
long-term effectiveness of our policy in Yugoslavia,'' Hutchison
said. ``I raised these concerns before this began, that we needed a
plan in case the bombing didn't bring Melosevic back to the table.
Sadly, the overwhelming number of refugees out of Kosovo is vivid
proof that we had no plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about the operation also are coming from Democrats.
Sen. Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey, one of Clinton's
staunchest supporters, this week blasted the handling of Kosovo.
``From the outset, this operation never had more vision than the
next day,'' he told the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
