<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-TORNADO-400&AMP;ADD-     04-09 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TORNADO-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORMS KILL SIX PEOPLE IN MIDWEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A line of surging storms and devastating tornadoes
swept across the Midwest Thursday and Friday, killing six people,
injuring dozens others and leaving a swath of damage hundreds of
miles long.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the destruction occurred in southwestern Ohio where
officials said at least two tornadoes touched down in the
Cincinnati area shortly after 5 a.m. Friday. More than 400 homes
were damaged in the area and 20,000 households were without power
Friday afternoon. While most customers had service by evening,
officials said they did not expect to have power fully restored
until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees have been thrown all over the place, and power lines
were snapped,'' said Jim Williams, the executive director of the
Ohio Emergency Management Agency. ``It's going to be quite a while
before things get sorted out. In terms of urban damage, it's
probably the worst storm we've seen since in 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nation Weather Service officials assessed the wreckage to be the
result of Class 3 or Class 4 tornadoes, meaning that at times the
winds exceeded 207 miles per hour. A class five tornado is the most
severe. Smaller twisters stretching back to Iowa uprooted trees,
tossed automobiles and flattened homes throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, parts of Interstate 71 were closed temporarily when a
semi-tractor trailer was lifted off the ground and deposited on its
side, blocking all lanes of traffic, and shopping centers
throughout the area showed walls blown in and roofs torn off,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a house this morning where workers were picking up
a highway sign from a quarter mile away off of the front lawn,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   He said four deaths occurred in Ohio, two when cars were picked
up and thrown by the swirling winds and the other two to a house.
Two women in Illinois were also killed when winds destroyed their
mobile homes.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Robert Taft of Ohio, who toured the area Friday, declared
three counties to be in a state of emergency, and the Red Cross
opened shelters in three local schools to house stranded victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nasty storm and it happened at the wrong time of the
day,'' said Greg Tipton, a meteorologist for the National Weather
Service in Wilmington, Ohio. He said it is rare to see severe
weather early in the morning at a time when many people were
sleeping.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The line of storms, pushed by a cold front that developed over
the Plains states, brewed up at least nine tornadoes in Iowa on
Thursday afternoon, destroying homes, and killing livestock in the
southern and central part of the state, said Ellen Gordon,
executive director of the Iowa Emergency Management Division. Mrs.
Gordon estimated the statewide damage to be $8 million, but said
nobody was killed or seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining strength as it moved east, the storm brought heavy winds
and rain to Illinois late Thursday, causing more tornadoes and
spreading severe damage. A 68-year-old women was found dead in the
remains of her mobile home in Ashland, 20 miles northwest of
Springfield and a 43-year-old women was killed in Cisco, 50 miles
east of Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sucked out the door and watched two trailers right in
front of me go up in the air, Louann Judd, whose trailer in
Illinois was one of those damaged in the storm, told The Associated
Press. She said her family of six ended up in a pile on top of her
2-year-old grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
