<HEADER>
A2627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0410-     04-09 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS RETURNS TO BIGGER CONFLICT, CALLS FOR GROUND TROOPS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (I) international categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan congressional delegation returned from
Europe Friday and issued a strongly worded letter urging President
Clinton to plan for the possible use of ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and eight other lawmakers informed
the president that in their view, the air war alone will never
achieve his goal of pushing Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic's
forces out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even assuming the success of the air campaign to significantly
degrade Milosevic's military,'' the letter said, there is ``less
certainty'' that bombing will clear the way for the return of
refugees under international protection.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers, who had accompanied Defense Secretary William
Cohen to Europe, told Clinton that ``we believe it prudent for the
U.S. to urge NATO to plan for additional military missions,
including the use of ground forces, in the event that proves
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The push for ground troops came as Congress is returning from a
two-week spring break during which the crisis has exploded in the
Balkans and the world has watched nearly 1 million refugees forced
out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from both parties plan to meet late Monday with Clinton
to discuss the conflict, which until now the lawmakers have left in
the hands of the administration. However, lawmakers are expressing
growing nervousness over how the president is commanding the
military operation.
</P>
<P>
   It is far from certain what the lawmakers will do beyond
offering recommendations. Congress took no action to limit the
scope of the military operation before the air strikes began and
has so far followed the recent pattern of ceding responsibility to
the president when it comes to deploying the armed forces. Although
the power to declare war is given to Congress by the Constitution,
the power to make war has been increasingly taken by presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that Congress voted to authorize a military strike
was shortly before the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., doubtful of the
Balkan operation from the outset, has been conspicuously quiet
since the bombing campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   That would change if the president opens up the option of ground
troops, said Lott spokesman John Czwartacki (cq). ``If our strategy
and tactics change dramatically, I would expect Congress would
demand to be heard with a full debate and a vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the ground troops option on the table remains highly
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people talking about ground troops like a secret
formula that can make the situation end in a hurry,'' Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., said this week. He called such a plan dangerous
because ``the population that would be confronted would be very
hostile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's premature to talk about ground troops,'' Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She led a failed attempt to cut off funding for the military
action, at the time insisting Clinton outline his goals and exit
strategy beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've met with many Texans who share my concerns about the
long-term effectiveness of our policy in Yugoslavia,'' Hutchison
said. ``I raised these concerns before this began, that we needed a
plan in case the bombing didn't bring Melosevic back to the table.
Sadly, the overwhelming number of refugees out of Kosovo is vivid
proof that we had no plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about the operation also are coming from Democrats.
Sen. Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey, one of Clinton's
staunchest supporters, this week blasted the handling of Kosovo.
``From the outset, this operation never had more vision than the
next day,'' he told the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
