<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS DIARY: DOING A DOUBLE TAKE OVER AN ANNUAL REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing about Tenneco Inc.: It may not officially confirm
rumors, but it doesn't let them die down either. Nine months ago,
Tenneco first floated the idea of splitting into two companies, one
making automotive products and one making packaging. Since then,
Wall Street has waited in vain for a definitive announcement.
</P>
<P>
   But any thought that the idea has been quietly dropped will be
erased by a look at the 1998 annual report _ or, rather, two looks.
</P>
<P>
   The report, mailed last week, has been issued in two versions:
One has a stylized Hefty One-Zip bag on the cover, the other a
Monroe Sensa-Trac shock absorber. (Both versions feature a mock bar
code with the words ``strong brands'' where the UPC number usually
appears, as if the annual report were itself a product for sale.)
</P>
<P>
   Neal Geary, a Tenneco spokesman, says the company's 70,000
shareholders will receive one or the other at random. But the two
business units will each get about 5,000 copies of the one that
focuses on its product, to distribute to customers, suppliers and
analysts. ``We are very purposefully indicating the potential of
the two companies to compete separately in the future,'' Geary
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
