<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BILLYJOEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SIGNS THE PIANO MAN IS MOVING OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Billy Joel admitted early in his sold-out show at
the Anaheim Pond Thursday night that it hasn't always been easy to
be a fan of his in Los Angeles. And, indeed, the gifted piano man,
who recently was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame,
never has received much respect in the Southland, where
flavor-of-the-month artists often are embraced at the expense of
genuine, enduring talent.
</P>
<P>
   Joel had no problem winning over his fans at the Pond, though,
playing a generous 20-song set that touched all the bases of his
illustrious career. (The baseball reference is apt; Joel and his
seven-member band took the stage to the strains of Randy Newman's
theme from ``The Natural.'') Joel didn't offer any new songs; he
hasn't recorded a new album in six years. But he did play a few
interesting instrumental passages on the piano that certainly could
foreshadow the classical composing work he intends to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unofficially, this is the old (stuff tour), Joel said at one
point. Later, he told the audience that while this is his last
tour, he didn't say it was his last show. ``So, it's not a farewell
thing. I saw the Who do that 15 times and it got kinda old.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel, one month shy of his 50th birthday, is getting kinda old,
too, although age certainly wasn't an issue during the two-hour,
15-minute show. The singer-songwriter frequently left his piano
bench to run around the stage, twirl the microphone stand and play
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   To fire up the crowd for his Gilbert and Sullivan-like history
lesson, ``We Didn't Start the Fire,'' he and his band ran through a
ragged, eight-song rock 'n roll sampler that started with Frank
Sinatra (``The Lady Is a Tramp''), ended with the Police (``Every
Breath You Take'') and included Jimi Hendrix, Led Zepplin and a
good-natured stab at the Eagles' ``Hotel California.'' By the time
he got around to his own No. 1 song it was almost anti-climactic.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly could not be said for the rest of the concert,
which concluded with rip-roaring renditions of ``It's Still Rock
and Roll to Me,'' ``You May be Right,'' ``The Majestic Scenes From
an Italian Restaurant,'' a two-song encore of ``Only the Good Die
Young'' and, of course, ``Piano Man.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joel let the audience sing the final chorus of that last
song, it was the perfect cap to an enjoyable evening of songs every
one there knew by heart. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
