<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Peace Talks To Resume
</P>
<P>
   The government and the largest left-wing guerrilla group have
agreed to resume talks on April 20 aimed at ending a conflict that
has ravaged Colombia for more than three decades. Despite being
given control of a safe haven the size of Switzerland, the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia suspended the talks in
January, calling on the government to bring right-wing paramilitary
groups under control.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Anger at Privatization
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators opposed to the government's proposal to privatize
the electric power industry roughed up Energy Secretary Luis
Tellez. After he testified before the Senate that the proposal
would help attract $25 billion in needed investment, Tellez was
surrounded, apparently by unionists opposed to the privatization,
who shoved and hit him with a plastic bottle. He was unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   Chile: A Pinochet Protest
</P>
<P>
   The Chilean navy is to refuse port facilities to British ships
from the Falkland Islands in protest at the continued detention in
London of the former dictator, Gen. Augusto Pinochet, BBC News
reported. The move follows the withdrawal last month of Chilean
flights between the southern Chilean city of Punta Arenas and the
islands.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia: Anwar Protesters Acquitted
</P>
<P>
   A magistrate acquitted 160 people arrested during street
demonstrations protesting the firing and detention of former Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim. The judge said there was not ``an
iota'' of evidence to support charges that they had been involved
in rioting. A verdict in the trial of Anwar is scheduled for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Philippines: Rebels Free Police Officer
</P>
<P>
   Communist rebels released a police inspector who had been held
hostage since mid-February. They still hold an army brigadier
general and four other hostages. The general is the highest-ranking
officer ever captured during the 30-year insurgency, which has
dwindled in recent years to a token presence.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: A Pledge To Investors
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wiranto, the country's top military officer, promised to
protect foreign investment during the tense weeks leading up to a
general election on June 7. ``I promise that your investments will
be safe here,'' he said. ``So I encourage you to take bold steps.
Invest now. Despite the outbursts of violence in several areas,
most of the country is still safe.''
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   France: Third Trial for Convicted Nazi
</P>
<P>
   A judge has cleared the way for the convicted Nazi war criminal
Alois Brunner, who is believed to be in hiding in Syria, to be
tried in absentia for the third time for crimes against humanity.
He was sentenced to death in his absence in 1953 and 1954. The new
trial will focus on allegations that he organized a July 1944
roundup of 340 Jewish orphans to Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Aid for Terrorism Victims
</P>
<P>
   The government sent a bill to Parliament calling for payments of
$272 million to be made to victims of terrorism in Spain since
1968, when the Basque separatist group ETA began its armed struggle
that is blamed for about 800 deaths and 3,000 injuries. The bill,
expected to become law, would sharply increase the size and scope
of state indemnities previously paid to victims or their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey: U.N. Report on Torture
</P>
<P>
   Turkish authorities continue to torture and mistreat detainees,
but systematic brutal torture, including electric shocks, is used
less widely now, a U.N. special investigator said. ``Torture was
systematic, very widespread and routine until a couple of years
ago,'' Nigel Rodley told the U.N. Human Rights Commission in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Gorilla-Shooter Jailed
</P>
<P>
   A fugitive burglar and rapist who shot a gorilla named Max at
the Johannesburg Zoo in 1997 was sentenced to 40 years for the
shooting and other charges. Isaac Mofokeng was given five years for
wounding the gorilla, 10 for a rape and the rest for charges
related to burglaries. Max became a celebrity in crime-ridden
Johannesburg for biting Mofokeng while protecting his mate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
