<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, April 10, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   POW-MOM (Los Angeles) _ Moments after Vivian Ramirez learned
that efforts to free her son failed, Los Angeles police officers
offered solace and encouragement. At a ceremony, Ramirez and her
son, Detective Steven Ramirez, were presented with posters bearing
a photograph of the imprisoned soldiers signed by officers from
each of the 18 LAPD Divisions offering their prayers for his safe
release. By Rick Orlov and Yvette Cabrera. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-COLD (Los Angeles) _ It's official: April so far is the
coldest on record. After an unusually warm, dry winter, the average
low temperature at the Los Angeles Civic Center has been 46.6
degrees, less than the average 48.3 degree record set in 1967,
according to the Western Regional Climate Center, a research
institute at the University of Nevada, Reno. And it won't get
better, as temperatures through the weekend will linger in the 60s
and dip into the 40s overnight. High winds are expected through the
weekend. By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   DODGER-ADS (Los Angeles) _ Commercialism has begun creeping
discreetly into Dodger Stadium, one of the final holdouts of
baseball tradition. Though not overwhelming, the amount of
advertising at the 37-year-old park has more than doubled with a
trio of ads (Dodge, Bud Lite and Pacific Bell) on the outfield
fence, along with one on the home-team dugout (New Era) and one in
the visitor's bullpen (MasterCard). ``On a scale of 1 to 10
compared to other teams, the Dodgers are probably a 3 right now,''
said Dean Bonham, head of a Denver-based sports consulting firm.
``But I would imagine they'll be a 7 or 8 in a few years.'' By Dave
McNary. (Will move in the ``s'' sports and ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TICKETS (Los Angeles) _ The $10 movie ticket looks more
and more inevitable. AMC becomes the first chain in Los Angeles to
hit the $8.50 price point, and it's likely that other chains will
follow suit. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
