<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Friday, April 9, and thereafter. The stories will carry the
``f'' financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For
questions about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News,
(818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   DODGER-ADS (Los Angeles) _ Commercialism has begun creeping
discreetly into Dodger Stadium, one of the final holdouts of
baseball tradition. Though not overwhelming, the amount of
advertising at the 37-year-old park has more than doubled with a
trio of ads (Dodge, Bud Lite and Pacific Bell) on the outfield
fence, along with one on the home-team dugout (New Era) and one in
the visitor's bullpen (MasterCard). ``On a scale of 1 to 10
compared to other teams, the Dodgers are probably a 3 right now,''
said Dean Bonham, head of a Denver-based sports consulting firm.
``But I would imagine they'll be a 7 or 8 in a few years.'' By Dave
McNary. (Will move in the ``s'' sports and ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TICKETS (Los Angeles) _ The $10 movie ticket looks more
and more inevitable. AMC becomes the first chain in Los Angeles to
hit the $8.50 price point, and it's likely that other chains will
follow suit. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
