<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN COMPOSERS, ORCHESTRA IN THE SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(``Tonight'' refers to Saturday, April 10) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What a difference a year or two has made for
Silvestre Revueltas. While the work of the Mexican composer
(1899-1940) has been known in Los Angeles for decades, recent
months have ushered in a kind of Revueltas renaissance that will
continue here tonight with a concert of all-Mexican modern
classical music at UCLA's Royce Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The program, performed by Mexico's national symphony, Orquesta
Sinfonica Nacional de Mexico, under the direction of Enrique Arturo
Diemecke, will include Revueltas' ``La Coronela'' and the world
premiere of ``Danza Silvestre'' by Arturo Marquez. Revueltas'
daughter, Eugenia, who lectures extensively on her father's work,
is accompanying the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Philharmonic just released a new recording of
several key Revueltas works, coinciding with this year's centennial
of his birth. The Sony Classical disc features his thunderous film
score for ``La Noche de los Mayas'' and ``Ocho por Radio'' (``8 x
radio''), a sardonically humorous short piece that one critic has
likened to ``a cubist Mariachi band.'' Tonight's other selections
will be Blas Galindo's ``Sones de Mariachi'' and Sinfonica No. 2,
``India,'' by Carlos Chavez, a kind of Mexican Aaron Copland to
Revueltas' Charles Ives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Revueltas, Chavez and Galindo ... are in the nationalistic
movement of Mexico, which began in the late '20s and went all the
way to the '50s, trying to compose with the idea of getting the
sounds and the melodies and the rhythms from the period influences
that Mexican culture has had throughout its history,'' conductor
Diemecke explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in Sinfonica `India' by Chavez, these are somewhat the
reflections of pre-Hispanic music, not in its totality but in some
of its ideas _ and the idea of bringing out the rhythm and some of
the colors, especially in the percussion instruments.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2644 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV11-B     04-09 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV11-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNTANGLING ECONOMIC COMPLEXITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 11, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What to make of the current vogue of ``complexity studies'' in
finance and economics?
</P>
<P>
   There's no missing the boomlet. It is rendered visible by a
picketline of popular books. In ``The New Pioneers,'' for example,
Wall Street Journal columnist Thomas Petzinger argues that a new
age of complexity has dawned in business. Suzanne Kelly of Citibank
and consultant Mary Ann Allison promise a ``Complexity Advantage''
if you follow the lessons of the new science of complexity in their
book And shareholder-rights activist Robert A.G. Monks concludes
his highly personal ``The Emperor's Nightingale'' with a
``complexity bibliography,'' a glossary and a Who's Who of the
complexity movement.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent they aren't drawn from two earlier popularizations
of science _ ``Chaos'' by James Gleick in 1988, and ``Complexity''
by M. Mitchell Waldrop in 1992 _ these books rest on a deeper
foundation of scholarly work, much of it coming from New Mexico's
Santa Fe Insitute, although at least two other centers of
complexity thought _ Stuttgart and Brussels _ have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   Overviews of the relevance of the new work to economics include
an article in the current issue of Science magazine by Brian Arthur
of the Santa Fe Institute, and the entry by William Brock of the
University of Wisconsin on ``complexity and chaos'' in the New
Palgrave Dictionary of Money and Finance. A conference volume from
a meeting on complexity last year at Middlebury College is in
preparation, edited by Brock and Middlebury professor David
Colander.
</P>
<P>
   What are the objectives of the new work? In his Palgrave's
article, Brock lists four. There's the hope that technical or
chartist analysis, the search for patterns in price movements that
long has been the province of market practitioners, may yet turn
out to have a deep intellectual basis.
</P>
<P>
   There's an attack on the statistical tests which have been used
by proponents of the efficient markets hypothesis to argue that
there are no hidden patterns in markets, so don't even bother to
look.
</P>
<P>
   There's the possibility that abrupt and seemingly inexplicable
movements in stock prices may be explained in new and unexpected
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, says Brock, there is the hope that work on complexity
and chaos may serve eventually as an underpinning for a rebirth of
Keynesian economics ``and a strengthening of arguments for an
activist, interventionist stabilization policy.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Peter Albin comes in.
</P>
<P>
   Albin, professor of economics emeritus at the City University of
New York, was a complexity pioneer. ``The Analysis of Complex
Socioeconomic Systems'' was published in 1975; ``Progress Without
Poverty: Socially Responsible Economic Growth'' appeared in 1978.
Albin's powers and reputation crested just as the wider interest in
complexity awakened. Then a cruel stroke delayed his progress.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's back with a collection of his path-breaking papers,
``Barriers and Bounds to Rationality: Essays on Economic Complexity
and Dynamics in interactive Systems.'' Duncan S. Foley of the New
School for Social Research, who edited the volume, contributes a
lengthy technical introduction.
</P>
<P>
   In his preface, Albin writes, ``In the social sciences,
generally, and in the literature of economics, particularily,
`structure` and `complexity` are poorly defined concepts which are
invested with weight, depth and magical significance and presumed
to be well understood by the reader.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not, he says: complexity can be used any number of
ways: to signify a high degree of specialization and/or strategic
interaction (the linotype is a complex machine;) of unfathomability
or uncontrolability (or controlability through intricate maneuver
(the world is a complex place;) of obstruction by detail or
organization (the problem is complex _ but soluble.)
</P>
<P>
   So it is that complexity can have precise meaning, Albin says.
In fact it already does, within the cognitive and informational
sciences. Languages, computer architectures, problems in
computation _ the complexity of each can be described, using a
variety of measuring devices: directed graphs, cellular automata
theory, mathematical tools of various sorts. The application of
these techniques to the problems of economics is the task of the
next generation.
</P>
<P>
   He continues, ``I have taken it as an obligation to do more than
just identifiy a gap in our knowledge. The essays reprintered here
provide tools with which an economist can take apart an
informational system'' -- whether a firm, an industry or an entire
economy.
</P>
<P>
   There may be nothing in the book that wasn't glimpsed _ and put
more directly _ when Albin wrote ``Progress Without Poverty'' in
1978. Then, he spelled out numerous practical applications of his
research program.
</P>
<P>
   Take industrialization, for example: why was it that
``urbanization'' could lead equally to upscale Zurich or New York's
Bedford Stuyvesant slum? Why was it ``factory organization'' could
translate equally as a worker's cooperative or the hierarchy of
General Motors' infamous Lordstown plant?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern then will be with the perverse patterns and
sydromes in the growth process that can swamp the primary positive
effects of industrialization and expanding output.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to quarrel with a program whose ultimate goal is to
alert us to the human traps and ecological disasters that may
accompany the pursuit of growth. A more wide-ranging and up-to-date
survey of how the new work on complexity may fit into economics as
it is understood in the present day can be found in ``New Keynesian
Economics/Post Keynesian Perspectives,'' a conference volume edited
by Roy Rotheim of Skidmore College. The original title of the
meeting ``On Butterflies' Wings and Haurricaines,'' reflects its
roots in the new mathematics of chaos an complexity.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of difficulties here. One is that the gurus
of complexity _ Albin, Arthur, Brock, Colander and Foley _ are
mostly men in their 50s. New breakthroughs that powerfully affect
science traditionally come from the young.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, those with long memories will remember the previous
promises in the 1970s of catastrophe theory to yield great new
insights into economic dynamics _ and the subsequent disappointment
when it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   There undoubtedly will be new ways of untangling economic
complexity. The ecologists, who were perhaps the first to take the
analytic category seriously, seem to have made a good start. In
economics, however, you get the feeling that this particular school
still has a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROTHSCHILD-AUCTION-87     04-09 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROTHSCHILD-AUCTION-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTION RETURNED TO ROTHSCHILDS WILL BE SOLD AT AUCTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after the Austrian government agreed to return about $40
million worth of art and objects that the Nazis confiscated from
the Austrian branch of the Rothschild family, members of the
256-year-old banking dynasty have decided to sell the collection.
</P>
<P>
   For sale at Christie's in London on July 8 will be an
extraordinary trove of Old Master paintings, 18th-century French
furniture, silver, porcelains, clocks, musical instruments, arms
and armor as well as one of the greatest collections of scientific
instruments in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The auction means the art and objects that had been on view in
Vienna museums are likely to leave Austria altogether. The
government returned the works to the Rothschilds last year after
more than a half-century of refusing to consider restitution. In
doing so, Elisabeth Gehrer, the Austrian minister of culture, said
she wanted to correct what she called immoral decisions at the end
of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The contentious issue of who should own art seized by the Nazis
was raised early last year by the disputed ownership of two Egon
Schiele paintings lent by an Austrian foundation for a show at the
Museum of Modern Art in New York. The works are still in New York
awaiting resolution of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart to see these things being sold; they are
the last of my childhood,'' said Baroness Bettina der Rothschild,
who along with her two children, a niece and a nephew, have decided
to part with their family heirlooms. ``But it just doesn't make
sense to keep them. We all live very differently today than my
parents did. Not only are the security questions terrifying and the
insurance costs prohibitive, but this type of 18th-century French
furniture needs a butler and two housemaids constantly polishing
it. That's just not the way we live.''
</P>
<P>
   The 75-year-old baroness, who lives in a country house southwest
of Vienna, fled into exile as a young girl days before the Germans
marched into Austria. She later married an American diplomat,
Matthew Loorman.
</P>
<P>
   The art was seized from the family palaces in 1938, and when
they tried to get it back in the late 1940s, government officials
forced them to leave it in Austria. Two months ago, however, the
Austrian government lifted a 54-year-old ban on the collection's
export and sale abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Both the baroness' grandfather, Albert von Rothschild, and her
great-uncle, Nathaniel von Rothschild, were great connoisseurs and
passionate collectors who spent their lives filling their
19th-century Viennese palaces with the finest paintings, French
furniture, silver, porcelains and other objects. They also
collected scientific instruments even though neither was a
scientist or a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, anything scientific was in,'' the baroness
recalled in a telephone interview. ``It was Nathaniel who
especially loved buying scientific instruments. Who could ever
think that microscopes were beautiful, but these were.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men's houses were so jammed with art and objects, the
baroness said, that when her father and uncle inherited them,
neither man continued to collect. ``Don't forget, the Austrians
lost the First World War and then there was a terrific depression
and the banks crashed,'' she said. ``We really had quite enough to
live with.''
</P>
<P>
   While her family is to sell nearly all of its art and objects
(she said she was keeping only a few minor knickknacks), it has
decided to give Austria a painting by Rigaud, a portrait of an
Austrian marshal who had received the Order of the Golden Fleece.
``The museums here don't have many French works,'' the baroness
said. ``Our family owes the Austrian government gratitude for the
gutsy act of giving these things back to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of the Rothschild collection stripped Vienna's
leading museums of many of the artworks they have had on display
since World War II. The Austrian Gallery, more popularly known as
the Belvedere, had 12 Rothschild artworks, mostly Baroque and
19th-century Austrian paintings. The Kunsthistorische had many of
the best paintings, including three extraordinary works by Hals,
one by Teniers and another by Wynants.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Gluck, a spokeswoman for the culture minister said Ms.
Gehrer had just heard the news of the sale and declined to comment,
other than to say that the government ``has done what we thought
was necessary,'' adding, ``Our responsibility is over, and now it
is up to the family to decide what happens next.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether either Christie's or the Rothschilds had
considered offering museums the chance to pre-empt any works in the
sale, a practice that is common in European auctions but not in the
United States, Lord Hindlip, chairman of Christie's, said they had
considered it but decided not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a different position than the English or the French
Rothschilds,'' the baroness said. ``We do not have any significant
amounts of money and have not been able to keep our family
houses.''
</P>
<P>
   For Christie's the sale will be a landmark event, perhaps the
largest single-owner sale in its 233-year history. ``It's the most
exciting collection I've seen in my 36 years at Christie's,''
Hindlip said, ``because it's the most varied and the most
captivatingly unusual.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROTHSCHILD-AUCTION-2N     04-09 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROTHSCHILD-AUCTION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: captivatingly unusual.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He said he had known the baroness and her husband for many years
and had been approached by the family about the possibility of
selling the collection just before Christmas. ``I went to see her
in Vienna on Jan. 3,'' Hindlip said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Rothschilds had decided to sell, Christie's recommended
that the sale take place in London rather than in New York because
some of the works, like four outstanding Persian carpets and
objects laden with ivory, cannot be brought into the United States.
``We also felt the Rothschild name meant more in Europe,'' Hindlip
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the sale will be one of Hals' most
famous portraits, that of the Amsterdam merchant Tielmann
Roostermann, which is expected to sell for $4 million to $5.6
million. There are also two other portraits by Hals, a
three-quarter-length one of a woman in a black dress with white
collar and cuffs, expected to bring $1.2 million to $1.9 million,
and a three-quarter-length one of a gentleman in a black coat and
cape with a black hat and gloves in his left hand, expected to
bring $1.9 million to $2.8 million. Other Old Master paintings
include Teniers' portrait of Archduke Leopold Wilhelm in his
picture gallery, which is priced between $960,000 and $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   A medieval manuscript known as the Rothschild Prayer Book is
also being sold. A Book of Hours in Latin, it has illuminated
manuscripts and 67 full-page miniatures and dates from 1510-15. It
is expected to sell for $2.4 million to $3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Rothschild family was famous for its fine French furniture,
and these pieces, too, will be on the auction block. A royal
marquetry commode, ordered on Aug. 31, 1776, and delivered to King
Louis XVI for Fontainebleau in October 1778 was made by Riesener,
the finest cabinet maker to work for Louis XVI. The commode, which
is expected to sell for $2.4 million to $4 million, was removed
from Fontainebleau in 1787, researchers at Christie's discovered,
and sent by the king to his library at Versailles. Other furniture
for sale includes a black lacquer commode by Bernard II van
Risenburgh, a desk by Leleu and three long-case clocks.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights from the sale will be on view in New York beginning
April 24, when Christie's officially opens its new American
headquarters in Rockefeller Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
