</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-UTILITIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITIES TEST COMMUNICATIONS WITH `Y2K BUG' IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major utilities say they are on track to upgrade their computer
systems to handle the software problem known as the ``Y2K bug.''
</P>
<P>
   The utilities also declared victory in a pre-Y2K test of their
backup communications systems, held Friday, although they released
few details. Nationally, the test's coordinator found problems such
as badly placed radio antennas and staffers who needed more
training to operate their new satellite telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly, utilities say they will be ready to prevent major
blackouts and brownouts come Jan. 1, 2000, when computers could
crash or fail to function if their software isn't corrected to cope
with the unfamiliar digits of the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Edison, a unit of BEC Energy, says it has finished 80
percent of the work needed to fix and test computer systems to make
sure they function on Jan. 1 of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Edison, says it plans to finish the work by June 30, as does
Northeast Utilities, which has now finished 82 percent of its
check-ups.
</P>
<P>
   New England Electric System also says it will meet the June 30
target date set by the North American Electric Reliability Council.
NEES says it has completed 97 percent of its Y2K work.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies are also working to finish contingency plans
to restore power quickly in case of an outage. Boston Edison, for
example, plans to have an extra 100 workers on duty Dec. 31, many
of whom will staff the company's 40 substations scattered around
its service territory.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of digital control systems in 1984, most of
these stations have been operated remotely from Edison's
centralized control facility on Massachusetts Avenue. But Jim
Ashkar, the company executive in charge of the Y2K program, said
the extra staffers will be able to control switches manually in
case central computers crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we're bored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three utilities Friday also participated in a test of their
back-up communications systems, held nationwide by the North
American Electric Reliability Council in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, tests were run by the region's so-called
``Independent System Operator,'' which oversees pricing functions
as states deregulate their power supply system. Employees at two
major control centers used microwave radios to contact utility
workers at various power plants around the region, and also tried
out a new set of satellite-telephones purchased especially to
prepare for the event.
</P>
<P>
   If traditional phones go down, the back-up radios would used to
keep the electrical grid functioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can establish alternative communications, then we've got
many important things conquered that could come up as possible
contingencies,'' said NEES Executive Vice President David Holt.
</P>
<P>
   The tests were conducted from two remote operating centers_one
operated by Northeast Utilities at its headquarters in Berlin,
Conn, the second run by New England Electric in Westboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Utility coordinators have been advertising the tests for weeks
as a symbol of their efforts to fix the problems. But New England
Electric and Northeast declined requests to observe the procedures
at their facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release after the test was conducted, the power
reliability council called the drill ``a successful exercise'' but
noted various problems. Among them, the council said, ``there were
some incorrect phone numbers identified,'' and some radio antennas
will have to be moved. Also, some personnel need more training to
operate the satellite phones.
</P>
<P>
   The press release didn't specify where the problems occurred.
Executives for the council haven't returned telephone calls seeking
comment for several days, and couldn't be reached after the test
was completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
