<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO-COACH10-COX     04-09 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-COACH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unforgettable `flight' one coach doesn't want to repeat
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The first thing Bengals assistant football coach Al
Roberts heard early Friday morning was the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Then he felt his bed move.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and his wife, Arvella, lay still in their upstairs
bedroom when the wind tore apart their home in Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the bathroom at 4:23,'' Roberts said. ``I knew that
because of my digital clock. I came back and heard that shewww _
the wind and the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said my prayer, `Our Father,' right away because I knew we
were ... lifted. We were ascending. All of a sudden we came back
down again and, bang, landed on the floor and that mattress landed
on top of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I tell you how fast the wind lifted us and threw us down?
It was fast. I never heard a siren. We were lifted. We were in
flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some seven hours after the destruction _ he lived a half block
from Sycamore High School near the intersection of Interstate 275
and I-71 _ Roberts was at the Bengals' Spinney Field headquarters
wondering how he was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw the house,'' he said, ``you wouldn't know how we
got out of there. I'll tell you again: God's hand was on me. I'll
tell you that a thousand times.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts got a ride to Spinney Field because both his cars were
demolished. He wore a Bengals coaching shirt, khaki slacks and
sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wardrobe,'' he said. ``Is what you're looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how wide the tornado was. I don't know how long
it was. But I felt like it set down right on top of us. The living
room, dining room, kitchen _ it's all gone and everything in it.''
</P>
<P>
   What about the other two bedrooms, hallway and bathroom
upstairs?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was blown. It was taken,'' he said. ``Nothing's left but
the brick standing on the side of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts originally thought the time of destruction lasted 15
seconds. ``But I'm gonna say three or four,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all over, I'm looking up at black sky. It's still
dark. My whole roof is gone, and rain is coming down on me. Now
I've got to put some clothes on. The only way I found a shirt was
because lightning struck someplace and I saw a shirt and some
pants. I picked that up, got my wife and we went downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   To get there, Roberts said, they slid on garbage down what
remained of the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was trying to open the front door. I said, `Sweetie,
you don't have to worry about it. We can walk out the living room
because there's no wall.'''
</P>
<P>
   He discovered that the chimney and garage door had crushed his
sport utility vehicle. As for his Chevy sedan?
</P>
<P>
   ``They can come and get that thing because it's gone,'' he said.
``The only thing left of it is the body and my golf clubs. The
glove compartment is still locked.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, Roberts helped a woman and her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mom was in a nightgown and the son had a T-shirt and
underwear on,'' he said. ``So we went over and gave 'em two Bengals
jackets, and one tennis shoe each.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he met with the Red Cross about 7:30 a.m. and
discovered a neighborhood couple had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The coach and his wife are moving into a Residence Inn hotel
with nothing but memories of a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't forget this,'' he said. ``I don't ever want to be in
another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1930EDT &QL; 
