<HEADER>
A2661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-10-CO     04-09 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    REFUGEE CRISIS IN MACEDONIA STABLE, SAYS UN CHIEF
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 400 
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia Amid intense criticism that her agency has
bungled Europe's worst humanitarian disaster since World War II,
the head of the United Nations agency for refugees said Friday that
efforts would be made to keep Kosovo refugees in countries
bordering Yugoslavia and ultimately seek their return to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sadako Ogata, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
said she received assurances from the government of Macedonia that
it would keep its borders open to refugees fleeing from Kosovo and
keep offering them asylum.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 ethnic Albanian refugees went missing Wednesday
after a hasty and disorganized overnight exodus of an estimated
55,000 refugees by the Macedonian government, which deposited them
on the border with neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees reportedly were ousted from the camp against their
will and were not told their destinations. Aid workers said
hundreds of families were separated in the confusion at the
makeshift camp near the Blace border crossing to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Those refugees had been located in camps in Macedonia and
neighboring Albania, the U.N. refugee agency said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the uprooting of the refugees from a camp on
Macedonia's northern border caught the U.N. and other aid agencies
unaware. Macedonia, a small republic formerly part of Yugoslavia,
has struggled to cope with the influx of more than 100,000 refugees
and failed to inform international humanitarian agencies of its
nighttime operation earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of NATO, which is providing the bulk of relief
operations in Macedonia, have privately criticized UNHCR for
failing to anticipate the refugee crisis and being slow to respond
to the mass exodus from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ogata said she was most concerned about tens of thousands of
unsettled Kosovars who were waiting to enter Macedonia and who
suddenly disappeared overnight earlier this week, apparently forced
back inside the Kosovo province by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia halted the exodus of refugees from Kosovo by closing
its borders Wednesday night, saying peace had been restored and
that ``a process of return of displaced persons ... has been
initiated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogata told a news conference in the Macedonian capital, Skopje,
that her agency was ``helpless'' to assist them because aid workers
cannot safely travel through Serb-held territory for fears for
their safety.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the Brazda refugee camp in northern Albania, a small
boy told Ogata that he wanted to return to his home. She replied:
``We can go back when we can go there safely.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATO continued its aid distribution program in Macedonia,
airlifting more nearly 3,000 tons of food and supplies this week.
NATO operates three refugee camps in Macedonia and a fourth is
administered by the Macedonian government. Plans exist to build
another four camps.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian aid officials said they were satisfied that the
needs of the refugees in Macedonia would be met. A plan for U.S.
Marines to erect a tent city to house refugees was scrubbed Friday
after NATO officials said the need was greater in neighboring
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   According to UNHCR, Macedonia now has 105,000 refugees, with
44,500 staying in camps and the rest being put up by local ethnic
Albanian families. Albania is hosting the bulk of refugees from
Kosovo, some 320,000.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and nearly a dozen other countries offered to
accept refugees when Macedonia asked for emergency assistance last
week. But Ogata said her agency and NATO had determined that it
would logical to house the refugees in neighboring countries to
Yugoslavia to hasten their return home if and when a settlement
allows.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, with a population of some 2.5 million, has an ethnic
Albanian minority of about 20 percent. Macedonian leaders fear the
massive flow of refugees will unsettle its sensitive ethnic balance
and strain its shaky economy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
