A2665 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON10-COX     04-09 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Weekend of Champions' ministry brings inmates together with pro
athletes, Christian counselors
 &HT;    By David Kepple
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton will become the focal point for a major
prison ministry effort this summer billed as the ``Weekend of
Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   The evangelical Christian program, set for July 9-11, will offer
the Gospel to about 8,500 inmates in five Ohio prisons, including
Dayton Correctional Institution and also the Lebanon, Warren,
London and Madison correctional facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton will serve as headquarters for the entire five-prison
project, which is expected to draw nearly 400 volunteer Christian
counselors from across the country to work on the program.
</P>
<P>
   The event is sponsored by Bill Glass Ministries _ a Cedar Hill,
Texas-based group, led by Glass, who starred in professional
football for the Cleveland Browns in the 1960s. Since Glass
launched the Weekend of Champions Prison Ministry in 1972, it has
become the nation's largest evangelical ministry to inmates, with
51 such weekend programs scheduled around the country this year.
</P>
<P>
   Glass will be the keynote speaker Thursday when Far Hills
Baptist Church in Kettering hosts an aptly named Kickoff Banquet to
recruit support for the July event, including additional volunteer
counselors and church sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   A Centerville resident and member of Far Hills Baptist, banquet
chairperson Sue Shay said the lifeblood of the Weekend of Champions
ministry flows from the hundreds of volunteer counselors who will
pay their own way to Dayton and ``share Christ'' with inmates for
two days.
</P>
<P>
   Shay herself has served as a volunteer counselor on weekends
elsewhere in Ohio and in Chicago. She said Montgomery County
Sheriff Gary Haines is sending representatives to the banquet and
considering whether to open the women's unit of the county jail to
the ministry in July.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Jackson, Midwest regional director for Bill Glass
Ministries, said the Weekend of Champions has been held in Ohio
every two years this decade, but this will be the first time Dayton
has served as a base.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is new territory, so we're excited about that,'' said
Jackson. He said it will be Glass' first time working in the
Dayton, Lebanon and Warren prisons, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry uses pro athletes, entertainers and ex-convicts to
grab the attention of inmates, who are then given an opportunity to
meet one-on-one with volunteer counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said it's too early to say which athletes or
entertainers will be involved in the July initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 alone, Jackson said, the Weekend of Champions ministry
involved 7,500 volunteer counselors and visited about 200,000
inmates in 315 prison units.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
