<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S CHIEF PRIORITY: FORWARD WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Aside from finding a quarterback, UCLA's primary
offensive goal in spring practice is to develop its young offensive
line _ a unit made younger by attrition, injuries and position
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are without three starters (Kris Farris, Andy Meyers
and Shawn Stuart) from last year's earth-moving unit. In addition,
they've lost reserve Dave Wilford to grade problems _ he's been
dismissed from school _ and reserve Micah Webb is out until August
with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Of the heralded 1998 recruiting class, only Jim Ghezzi, Mike
Saffer and Blake Worley remain. Steve Morgan has switched to
defensive tackle, and Jeff Wright and Scott Wiegand have quit
because of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we're not very deep, but we've never been
very deep,'' line coach Mark Weber said. ``Our goal this month is
to find the starters and the six-through-10 guys, and we need to
recruit some players next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three members of Weber's 10-man rotation played extensively
last season: Ghezzi, right tackle Brian Polak and left guard Oscar
Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   That means Worley, Saffer, center Troy Danoff, left tackle Josh
Webb (a converted defensive lineman) and reserve guard Matt Phelan
must be ready to play Sept. 4 against Boise State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look very athletic,'' Weber said. ``We run well and we move
well. We're further along, assignment-wise, than I thought we'd
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Position changes: Several Bruins will experiment with new
positions this month, with Morgan's shift from guard to defensive
tackle having perhaps the greatest impact.
</P>
<P>
   At 295 pounds, Morgan was immovable in blocking drills last
season. He joins Anthony Fletcher, Ken Kocher and Sean Phillips to
give UCLA a massive _ and unprecedented _ defensive-tackle
rotation. Just two seasons ago, the Bruins were using converted
linebackers on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Also, tight end Saia Makakaufaki has moved to defensive end and
defensive tackle Micah Webb (injured) has joined his brother Josh
on the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback trio: No change in the depth chart at tailback, at
least for now. Jermaine Lewis was listed as the starter when spring
drills began, with Keith Brown No. 2 and DeShaun Foster No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to compete,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
``There's not any need to make a decision now, but from spring to
fall it could change.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lewis had 130 carries, Foster 126 and Brown 99.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: The list is long and varied. Divided into three
categories, here's an overview.
</P>
<P>
   Serious: Linebacker Michael Wiley (back) has retired, defensive
end Doug Whiting (stress fracture/spine) will miss the 1999 season
and fullback Mark Verti might not play again because of a neck
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate: Cornerback Jason Bell (bone spur/heel), linebacker
Ramogi Huma (hip) and Micah Webb (knee) will not participate in
spring drills but are expected for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Minor: Receiver Freddie Mitchell (broken leg), receiver Brian
Poli-Dixon (wrist) and safety Lovell Houston (shoulders) will
practice on a limited basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-09 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ENDS AND MEANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ NATO now has three irreducible war aims: the removal of
all Serbian military, paramilitary and police forces from Kosovo;
the return of all the ethnic Albanian refugees, and their care and
protection by an international force.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, as in the United States, Serbian atrocities have
brought public opinion solidly behind those objectives. But the
leaders of NATO are not so clear in stating them.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and NATO spokesmen, for example, keep saying
that Slobodan Milosevic must accept the plan he rejected at
Rambouillet, France. But that proposal called for him to keep 5,000
Serbian troops in Kosovo and control its borders _ an unthinkable
outcome after the Serbian terror campaign. Could ethnic Albanian
families be expected to live in confidence if at the end of the
block there was a Serbian unit that had killed their husbands and
fathers?
</P>
<P>
   Even less clear is whether we are committed to the means
necessary to achieve those objectives. That is the crucial question
and a painful one, given the shameful miscalculation by the Clinton
administration when it gave the go-ahead for the air campaign
against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The president and his advisers evidently believed that after a
whiff of gunsmoke _ a few bombs _ Milosevic would say yes to
Rambouillet. They were totally unprepared for his murderous attack
on Kosovo civilians. They had no plan to house and feed refugees.
NATO air attacks over the first 10 days were pinpricks. Worst of
all, no tactical aircraft were used against the Serbian forces in
Kosovo to slow the killing and ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   It was two weeks after the start of the air campaign when the
bombing got serious. Milosevic countered with his call for a
cease-fire. His strategy now seems to be: I'll keep the remaining
ethnic Albanians in their shattered land, under Serbian control,
and let some refugees return if you stop the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a thinly disguised Milosevic victory, indeed
hardly disguised at all. It would abandon the Kosovar Albanians to
their fate, and it would destroy NATO's credibility. So Clinton and
others were right to brush the first Milosevic gambit off.
</P>
<P>
   But more peace proposals will surely follow, and it will not be
right to dismiss them out of hand. If the refugees are our prime
concern, as they should be, we must be willing to explore any
serious diplomatic effort to end their misery quickly and get them
home in safety. A willingness to talk will also serve to maintain
NATO unity.
</P>
<P>
   Some thoughtful people believe Milosevic will give enough ground
under the pressure of intensifying air attack to make possible an
honorable end. I do not. His record of murder and lies over the
last decade argues that, if it is necessary to talk, one can have
no confidence in doing business with Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   So we must carry the air war much further, especially against
his armed thugs on the ground in Kosovo. They should be harried,
trapped, deprived of heavy weapons, fuel and communications: driven
out by force. After cutting off the refugee flow, Milosevic
stationed tanks on Kosovo's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Second, NATO must now begin to assemble ground troops, ready to
enter Kosovo as a fighting force if necessary or to be a protection
force for returning refugees if and when the Serbian forces are
gone. Ruling out ground forces at the start was a grievous
political mistake, convincing Milosevic that we were not serious. A
majority of Americans, and a larger majority of Britons, now favor
the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Third, NATO must move more energetically to assemble evidence of
war crimes by Milosevic and his agents. The State Department took
an important step the other day when it announced that nine Serbian
military commanders may face prosecution before the International
War Crimes Tribunal. But the immunity of Milosevic should end.
</P>
<P>
   We have to face a hard fact: The United States and its allies
must be in this for the long haul. Reconstructing Kosovo after the
Serbian savagery will not be easy. Then we must work with
surrounding countries to confine the Serbian ultra-nationalism that
Milosevic has aroused. It is a heavy obligation, but the
alternatives are worse. James Hooper of the Balkan Action Council
is right when he says, ``The Balkans are the new Berlin: the test
of Western will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
