<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2668 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-730&AMP;ADD     04-09 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA CLARIFIES POSITION ON NATO BOMBING OF YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(rk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ No, President Boris Yeltsin did not order Russian
nuclear missiles to be retargeted at NATO countries taking part in
the bombing of Yugoslavia. Nor did he formally endorse the joining
together of Russia, Belarus and Yugoslavia in a geographically
awkward Slavic union.
</P>
<P>
   But at a meeting Friday with Gennadi Seleznyov, the Communist
who is speaker of the Russian Parliament's lower house, he
unmistakably warned the West not to push Russia into another war in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told NATO, the Americans, the Germans, don't push us toward
military action,'' he said, speaking before television cameras.
``Otherwise there will be a European war for sure, and possibly a
world war. We are against this.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the Kremlin the better part of the day Friday to clarify
just exactly what Yeltsin said and did not say in his Seleznyov
meeting. As he emerged from the session with Yeltsin Friday
morning, the speaker sent out the alarming report that Russia would
be targeting NATO states with nuclear warheads, touching off an
intense flurry of diplomatic activity in Western capitals.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, top Russian officials were issuing denials.
``As far as we know in the Foreign Ministry, no orders concerning
missiles have been issued.'' said Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov also appears to have overstated the president's
support for a union among Russia, Belarus and Yugoslavia, an idea
pushed by the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, as a way of
shoring up Moscow's support for Belgrade. According to remarks
televised Friday night, Yeltsin told Seleznyov that the proposal
should be studied.
</P>
<P>
   A union between Russian and Belarus is already under
negotiation, but as the proposal now stands, its main purpose is to
standardize economic relations between the two neighboring
countries, without any provision for military or security
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   As Kremlin spokesman Dmitri Yakushkin noted, including
Yugoslavia in such a union would involve several ``extremely
complicated and delicate'' questions that would take months to
resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has repeatedly pledged to keep Russia out of any
military involvement in Yugoslavia, a promise that the United
States and its NATO allies said Friday had been reaffirmed through
diplomatic contacts.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's harsh denunciations of the NATO campaign against
Yugoslavia, and vague threats to adjust its military doctrine, have
raised enough concern to prompt a meeting next week in Oslo between
Ivanov and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   In other remarks Friday, Yeltsin set down further markers on
future NATO policy in the Balkans. ``They want to use ground
troops, take over Yugoslavia, make it their protectorate,'' he
said. ``We cannot allow this. Russia and the access to the
Mediterranean Sea are nearby, so we can by no means give Yugoslavia
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia last week sent a reconnaissance ship from its Black Sea
fleet towards the Adriatic Sea to monitor NATO's activities off the
coast of Yugoslavia. The Turkish Foreign Ministry said Russia had
notified Turkey that as many as eight more ships might pass through
the Bosporus, with sailing dates staggered between April 12 and 16.
But so far, Moscow has not publicly announced a decision to send
any of those additional vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The Yeltsin administration, with its tough Cold War-style
oratory, has so far managed to stay abreast of the wave of
anti-American feeling that has swept Russia. But as the NATO
bombing continues, limiting Russia's opposition to just words may
prove increasingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 279 to 30, the Communist-led lower house of
Parliament demanded last Wednesday that the government send
military aid and advisers to Yugoslavia, in violation of U.N.
sanctions against Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Yugoslavia has added new tensions to Russia's already
overheated domestic political struggle. Yeltsin's Communist
opponents, emboldened by the anti-Western mood, have been pressing
an impeachment vote against the president, now scheduled for debate
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The political atmosphere has been further sullied by an
unresolved clash over the future of Russia's chief prosecutor, Yuri
I. Skuratov, whose dismissal by Yeltsin, for a second time, has
opened up a Pandora's box of charges and countercharges of
corruption and misconduct that have threatened to taint members of
the president's inner circle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a week marked by alarmist reports that the Kremlin is setting
the stage for a dramatic showdown with Parliament, Yelstin Friday
said publicly that he had no plans to dismiss Prime Minister
Yevgeni M. Primakov or to ban the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, he told a meeting of regional governors, will he support
any plans _ like one proposed recently by Primakov _ to eliminate
the direct elections of Russia's regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin gave only lukewarm support to Primakov and dropped
strong hints that a Cabinet shuffle might be in the works. ``At
this stage, Yevgeni Primakov is useful to us,'' he told the
governors. ``Later we will see. On the other hand, the Cabinet does
need reinforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent members of the Communist Party are ministers
in the Primakov government, and in a recent interview, the prime
minister confirmed reports that he had given his communist allies a
pledge that he would resign before agreeing to dismiss any of their
top ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, who met this week
with Yeltsin, said in an interview published in Friday night's
edition of Izvestia that he would support changes in the Cabinet.
``I wonder why reaction to all this has become so painful,'' he
said. ``I changed three cabinets, and no one reacted so painfully
to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
