<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-FAMILY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families feel lucky after surviving tornado
 &HT;    By Lawrence Budd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Julie Streck awoke Friday morning to the sound of
sirens outside her home minutes before a tornado tore apart her
family's small neighborhood, just east of Interstate 71 in Sycamore
Twp. in Hamilton County.
</P>
<P>
   The high school senior and her sister Jan, 21, ran for their
parents, who gathered up siblings Allen, 9, Jill, 6, and Hunter,
the family's golden retriever.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the family huddled hand-in-hand in the basement
at about 5:10 a.m. as a tornado unleashed its lethal power.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Streck's basement adjoins the rest of house,
so the basement roof _ made of wood and shingles _ was fully
exposed to the storm's force.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could actually feel it pulling,'' Streck said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, everything died down. We came upstairs, no
more house,'' she said, standing in front of her yard, surveying
what remained of the neighborhood, which backs onto Johnson Nature
Preserve, about six miles south of Warren County.
</P>
<P>
   The tall trees making up the preserve's forest had been blown
down or bent to extreme angles. Tree tops had been torn off.
</P>
<P>
   Large trees in the yards nearby also were knocked down, an array
of clothes, paper and other debris wrapped in their broken limbs.
Whole sheets of bricks from houses hung precariously and pieces of
wood framing lay everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   A couple walked through the second floor of the home next door
to Streck's, as people watched from the street. The front walls and
roof were missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woods are gone. Houses are gone,'' Streck said. ``Luckily,
we made it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Her family's garage roof lay against the basement foundation.
Much of the back of the house and part of the roof, along with a
backyard deck built off the back of the Streck's two-story brick
house, were gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kitchen's in the back yard. We can't find the dining room.
We had a huge deck. We don't even know where the deck is,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents were rooting through the rubble, trying to locate
their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Still the Strecks faired better than some of their neighbors.
Three died when the twister hit and others were rushed to hospitals
with ``everything from minor injuries to a woman with an amputated
leg,'' said Montgomery Police Chief Donald McGlothlin.
</P>
<P>
   To the east, in the Montgomery Town condominiums, the Schwarber
family awoke to the sounds of the approaching storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you could see was a dustball,'' Beverly Schwarber said.
``I thought a plane had landed in our yard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband said, `Grab the baby,' We didn't even make it
downstairs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because her father suffers from Alzheimer's disease, he and her
mother had chosen to sleep in the basement, rather than a
second-floor bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother had heard a loud thud.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought it an animal or something had fallen through the
fireplace. In fact, it was a tree,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Schwarber, an interior decorator, had finished their
bedroom in three shades of coral. Tasteful waterfront paintings and
a floral arrangement completed the Florida Room effect. Everything
seemed to be in its proper place, except for the tree limb
protruding from the ceiling directly over the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have impaled one of the in-laws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten feet away, 15-month old Adam was sleeping in his room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this happened there ... that's the scary thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the limb through the ceiling, the condominium
remained intact. The family planned on spending the night in their
home, regardless of whether electrical power had been restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very lucky, compared to everybody else,'' Beverly
Schwarber said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
