<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-DEFENSE-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAYED BOOST FOR MILITARY SUPPLIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The aerial bombardment of Serbia has been going on for more than
two weeks, but so far, Wall Street has been unmoved by the barking
dogs of war.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for this, of course. But some analysts and
money managers are of the opinion that military-sector stocks
represent a pocket of value that for more than a year has been
largely ignored by investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not Internet stocks, and you have to be patient,''
said Pierre Chao, senior aerospace-defense analyst at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. ``But for real investors these stocks are
selling at levels where you want to start building positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Wars don't always light a fire under military stocks, but they
usually don't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Persian Gulf war, a far bigger military operation than the
attack NATO has waged thus far against Yugoslavia, generated
interest in military stocks in 1990 and 1991, and the group
outperformed the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, said Cai von
Rumohr, an analyst at S.G. Cowen &AMP; Company in Boston. By contrast,
they barely budged during the military operations in Somalia and
Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 7 report, Byron Callan, an analyst at Merrill Lynch,
estimated that a three- to six-week air war would result in no more
than $200 million to $300 million in supplemental spending by the
Defense Department to replace munitions and electronics consumed in
the operation.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of money is not going to make much of a difference to
the six giant companies _ Lockheed Martin, Raytheon, Boeing,
Northrop Grumman, Litton Industries and General Dynamics _ that
survived the brutal consolidation that transformed the industry
earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The important numbers, according to those who follow and invest
in these stocks, are the Defense Department outlays requested by
the Clinton Administration for the coming fiscal year through 2005.
The numbers project the first major increases in military spending
since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Events like Iraq and Kosovo are important to the extent that
they draw attention to the sad fact that peace on earth is not
here,'' Chao said. ``But they won't drive earnings or the stocks.
Increasing defense budgets will.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the proposed increase would go to raising military
salaries and pensions and for operations and maintenance. But the
administration also wants steady increases in outlays for weapons
procurement, from $53 billion in fiscal 2000 to $75.1 billion in
fiscal 2005. Key areas earmarked for additional money are fighter
aircraft and air transports, surface ships and submarines and
ballistic-missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   In a report compiled in late March, Michael Bunyaner, an analyst
at CIBC Oppenheimer, said companies that should benefit from the
additional spending include Lockheed Martin (fighter aircraft),
Boeing (air transports and missile defense), General Dynamics
(submarines) and Raytheon (missiles). ``Raytheon and General
Dynamics are our top two picks, but we are bullish on the entire
group,'' Bunyaner said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee, of course, that the Clinton
administration will get what it is asking for. Congress has its own
ideas about where and how to spend money allotted for the Pentagon.
And it will be some time before any budget increases begin to raise
revenues at these companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have to muddle through the next four to six quarters
before these increases in procurement spending show up,'' said
Peter Aseritis, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, however, it is difficult to imagine that the
prices of these stocks could go much lower.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P Aerospace/Defense Index is 31.8 percent below its
52-week high, which was last April. Northrop Grumman closed Friday
at $58, just 9.5 times consensus estimates of its 1999 earnings.
And Lockheed Martin and Litton closed at 10.9 and 13 times their
1999 earnings estimates, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Chao, the Morgan Stanley analyst, said that since the 1950s,
military stocks have traded in a range of 40 to 100 percent of the
S&AMP;P 500's price-earnings multiple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, you get to the lower end at the end of major
conflicts, and at the top at the beginning of major ramp-ups'' in
spending, he said. ``Right now, the group on average is trading at
55 percent of the market multiple, which doesn't make sense because
you are at the beginning of a ramp-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some value investors are taking note. ``We think Lockheed Martin
and Northrop Grumman are very cheap stocks,'' said Larry Sondike,
co-portfolio manager of Mutual Shares and Mutual Beacon Funds.
``The environment is improving, but to date the market has not
cared. That is the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sanborn, manager of the $6 billion Oakmark fund, has
owned Lockheed Martin for a number of years and now controls a
stake of nearly 2 percent in the company. ``At this point, it's
probably my favorite stock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Callen of Merrill said that while the long-term outlook was
improving, he wasn't pounding the table for any stocks in the
group. ``Still, based on the calls I get from our retail brokers,''
he acknowledged, ``it seems there is a real interest out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
