<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2671 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-PORTFOLIOS-ART     04-09 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTFOLIOS, ETC.: ON INTEREST RATES, DON'T LET THE DATA LULL YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors worried about rising interest rates were calmed
recently by news of a decline in manufacturing jobs in March and a
slowdown in the rise of average hourly earnings, a key measure of
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in manufacturing jobs offset the ``bad news'' of the
strong rebound in the level of manufacturing, as measured by the
National Association of Purchasing Management. In March, its
manufacturing index jumped to 54.30, its highest level since
November 1997. Initially, the surge was taken as a sign of a
rebound in American manufacturing, which would make it less likely
that the economy could slow to the sustainable pace sought by the
Federal Reserve without an increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The slowdown in the pace of wage increases helped relieve
another fear, that pressure here would become too much for the
Federal Reserve, even though there are few signs now that companies
can pass along the cost of these increases as higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   That relief, coming on two fronts, helped set off a nice rally
in the bond market, bringing the yield on the 30-year bond down to
5.46 percent Friday from 5.67 percent on April 1, the day before
the March jobs data were released. And that rally helped lift the
stock market, with the three major gauges _ the Dow Jones
industrial average, the S&AMP;P 500 and the Nasdaq composite _
repeatedly reaching new highs last week.
</P>
<P>
   But investors may be taking more comfort from this new data than
they should.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, there has been a pretty good correlation
between the movement of the purchasing management manufacturing
index and long-term interest rates adjusted for inflation. Right
now, that index is pointing to a sharp rise in long-term rates _
into 6 percent territory _ according to Robert Barbera, the chief
economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. in Rye Brook, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera agreed that the decline in manufacturing jobs and the
continued weakness in industrial production may mean that that the
purchasing management index is sending a false signal. But he said
weekly jobless claims, which have remained below 300,000 for 10
weeks, are a signal of strength.
</P>
<P>
   And he argues that if the global economy, especially Asia's,
begins to rebound, a recovery in U.S. manufacturing is even more
certain. The cut in official interest rates on Thursday by the Bank
of England and the new European Central Bank just add to the
likelihood that a rebound in global economic growth will give
another boost to the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard part is guessing what will happen to global
momentum,'' Barbera said. But if it is picking up, then the past
correlation between the purchasing management index and interest
rates is far more worrisome for American investors.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera also has a doubt about the deceleration in average
hourly earnings. He agrees that the pace of growth has declined, to
3.6 percent last month from 4.4 percent in April 1998. But he says
the underlying data show that the rise of earnings in the service
sector is actually accelerating. What has slowed the overall pace
is a sharp decline in the growth rate for manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, if the purchasing management index is right _ and
the bet on a global turnaround is correct _ that trend will also
reverse, adding to the pressure on wages.
</P>
<P>
   All these trends will be watched closely by Fed policy-makers,
who next meet in May. If Barbera is right in his bets, the Fed
could be in a tight spot.
</P>
<P>
   Going into this year, policy makers were betting on a growth
slowdown to bring the pace of the economy to a sustainable rate
that would not add to inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   But even the Fed is acknowledging that the economy will be much
stronger than it expected. In the minutes of the February meeting
of the Federal Open Market Committee, released a week ago, Fed
governors and Federal Reserve Bank presidents said it was now
possible that the economy, even after slowing from the breakneck
annual growth rate of 6 percent in the fourth quarter, could still
be running ahead of the central bank's sustainable pace of around
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Fed will be more likely to lean toward higher
interest rates _ and Barbera's interest rate indicator, which is
clearly pointing higher, will be right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
