<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-ORANGINA-475&AMP;ADD     04-09 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-ORANGINA-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH COURT BLOCKS SALE OF ORANGINA TO COCA-COLA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Georgia, Australia, Mexico, Germany, Spain)  By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co.'s plans to buy Orangina faded Friday when France's
highest administrative court refused to overturn a government
ruling that had blocked the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The French government had been concerned that the sale would
give Coca-Cola control of too much of the soft-drink market in
France. The ruling by the Council of State in Paris means the
company can continue to negotiate a compromise with the government.
However, industry experts said the ruling, which came shortly after
10 p.m. Paris time and just after markets had closed in the United
States, does not help Coca-Cola's case.
</P>
<P>
   While Coca-Cola officials sought to put a positive spin on the
decision, it was clearly a setback for the company, which sees
global expansion as critical to earnings growth. It was the second
ruling against Coke's strategy of buying popular international
brands in two days.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Australian regulators rejected the company's plan
to buy brands now owned by Cadbury Schweppes PLC, although
negotiations are continuing on another proposal put forth by
Coca-Cola and Cadbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are disappointed with the decision, we remain
satisfied that our legal position was heard and taken seriously,''
said Mark Preisinger, a Coca-Cola spokesman. ``We will continue our
discussions with the French authorities and remain hopeful that the
deal will be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   The setbacks are particularly disappointing for Coca-Cola
shareholders. Many analysts have said the company's acquisition of
brands like Orangina and the Cadbury Schweppes line would boost
sales volume by about 600 million cases a year, and with sales of
Coke products falling off or flattening in many countries around
the world, the company needs that kind of help to improve its
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not good news for Coke,'' said Jennifer
Solomon, a beverage analyst for Salomon Smith Barney. But she added
that she did not think the ruling would hurt the company's stock
price.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Coca-Cola announced that it would buy
Orangina, a highly popular orange-flavored drink owned by Pernod
Ricard SA, for $844 million. The move was the first major
acquisition by the company after its chairman and chief executive,
M. Douglas Ivester, took over the top job following Roberto C.
Goizueta's death two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But France's competition council rejected the deal in September,
saying that it would give Coca-Cola too much of the soft-drink
market, particularly in what is known as on-premise sales, or sales
in restaurants and cafes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a shame,'' Ms. Solomon said of Friday's ruling.
``It's a great product, and it needs a better distributor. Coke
could do a lot with that brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Solomon suggested that French distrust of American influence
may have contributed to the decision. ``The French have very mixed
feelings about the influx of Americana,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In December, Coca-Cola announced that it would buy nearly all
the international brands owned by Cadbury Schweppes, including Dr
Pepper, Schweppes and Canada Dry. The $1.85 billion deal was
expected to face regulatory scrutiny, but the decision by
Australian trade officials is considered another disappointment for
Coca-Cola. In addition, reports have been circulating that
officials in Mexico, Germany and Spain are questioning the deal. In
all those countries, Preisinger said, rulings that reject the deal
would probably be ``negotiable and appealable.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Goldman, a global consumer products analyst for Merrill
Lynch, suggested that Pernod Ricard might next offer Orangina to
Pepsico, Coke's biggest rival. ``Were Pepsi to acquire Orangina,
this would double Pepsi's market share in France,'' Goldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Pernod Ricard, whose holdings include wine, liqueurs, whisky and
fruit products, wants to sell Orangina in order to concentrate on
its other businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
