<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2674 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINTER-PAPER-ART-$AD     04-09 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINTER-PAPER-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPER INDUSTRY TRIES TO MAKE WHITE EXCITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can Great White really do for printer paper what Frank Perdue
did for chicken? Can Xerox persuade consumers that a paper by any
other name would not print as sweet? Does the public believe that
one company's sheet of white stuff is all that different from
another's?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the answers are yes, yes and yes. ``Consumers are
not as sophisticated as corporations when it comes to paper, and
branding is what they rely on most,'' said David Rocheleau, a
director of the Supplies Advisory Service at Lyra Research, a
market analysis firm in Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the consumer paper market, once a quiet backwater,
is now burning with high-wattage advertising and branding
campaigns. Forest products companies long accustomed to
business-to-business marketing have had to learn all about in-store
promotions, flashy package design, even the economics of national
television campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in this industry's history, you're seeing
office papers on TV,'' said Michael Winters, a national sales
manager for Georgia-Pacific Corp., which will be eclipsed as the
country's largest cut-paper producer at the end of this month when
International Paper and Union Camp complete their merger.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see the retail market's allure. These days, even
the cheapest new printers can produce attractive greeting cards,
brochures, presentations and photographs _ but not on
plain-vanilla, penny-a-sheet paper. The fancy coated papers that
give the best results can retail for as much as $1.50 a sheet;
paper makers' margins on such sheets are a guarded industry secret,
but they are certainly higher than those on the copier paper that
corporations buy by the palletful. High margins and quality
distinctions are the classic recipe for a market ripe for building
brand names, even on commodity products.
</P>
<P>
   The prices for the high-end papers are not scaring consumers.
According to Lyra Research, the overall market for cut paper is
growing at an annual rate of only 3.8 percent. But sales are
climbing 11.1 percent a year in the SOHO market _ the initials
stand for small office-home office, but marketers often use the
term for all sales to consumers and small businesses. And branded
papers are selling best.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the retail arena, brand identity is what separates the
survivors from the losers,'' said Jack Plomgren, president of Union
Camp Corp.'s Great White Consumer Products Group, which makes Great
White papers.
</P>
<P>
   The printer companies, engaged in fierce competition themselves,
have also caught on to the trend. Companies like Xerox and
Hewlett-Packard welcome any chance to plunk their names in a
consumer's sight line _ particularly if they can profit along the
way. So they, too, are peppering the shelves at Office Depot,
Staples and other stores with branded specialty papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xerox-branded paper enhances awareness of our overall brand,''
said James Lesco, president of Xerox's supplies group. He said
Xerox's paper sales to the SOHO market grew 35 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The printer companies haven't bought or built paper mills; the
paper they sell is made for them by the same paper companies whose
branded products compete with theirs in the stores. But the printer
companies say their offerings still have an advantage: Because
their hardware, ink, toner and paper specialists are on the same
product development teams, they say, paper manufactured to their
specifications, and bearing their name, will give the best results
on their printers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other companies can only guess at what our ink formulation is
going to be,'' said Susan Schindelar, marketing manager for
Hewlett-Packard's Inkjet Media division, who added that paper ``is
definitely growing in importance to our top and bottom lines.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also growing more visible in stores, where competition has
transformed the once-staid printer-paper aisles. Gone are the days
when white paper came wrapped in white paper; most companies now
use splashy colors to catch the eye. And several pack their
highest-quality paper in clear shrink wrap to show off its
brightness.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the packaging choices are haphazard. Georgia-Pacific's
new line of Microprint photographic-quality printer paper comes in
a bright yellow package because ``packaging consultants said bright
yellow would be associated with Kodak yellow, and that would give
us great brand awareness,'' Winters said.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, research showed that men bought most home-office
supplies, so Great White tried to appeal to its customers' macho
side with a package that bore a shark baring a mouthful of sharp
teeth. But now that women are buying close to half of all office
supplies, Great White has made its shark much less ferocious.
``We've softened the teeth, and we're focusing on the fin,''
Plomgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the brand names chosen willy-nilly. Indeed, many
companies shove aside corporate egos and venerable trademarks when
they believe a fresh new name would do better with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific, which until recently put its corporate name on
all of its consumer papers, chose the name Microprint for its most
expensive coated papers ``because we wanted a brand name with a
high-tech sound to it,'' Winters said.
</P>
<P>
   Great White, itself a nom de papier for a company few consumers
know, decided that even detoothed sharks might not appeal to
children, so it licensed the Crayola name for new, brightly colored
papers for party banners, stickers and T-shirt transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard has made perhaps the ultimate ego sacrifice:
it's sharing the logo glory with others. Its photo-quality paper
packaging trumpets that it is made for Hewlett by Eastman Kodak,
and its new line of restickable paper shares branding with Post-It
notes. ``In photography, we knew that Kodak's name would enhance
the appeal, and most everyone knows what a Post-It note is,'' Ms.
Schindelar said.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper, meanwhile, is ruefully recognizing that its
Hammermill brand, long associated with classy writing paper, is not
sending the right message for more fanciful uses. So, while it
still markets printer paper as Hammermill, that name does not
appear on Jetprint Photo papers, Invent-It greeting-card paper, or
other products meant more for fun than work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to appeal directly to the consumer's playful side,''
said Kenneth Krieg, the company's business manager for office
papers, ``but we don't want to water down the Hammermill name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 1948EDT &QL; 
