<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-PRESIDENT-2     04-09 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-PRESIDENT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN PRESIDENT IS TRANSFORMING HIS COUNTRY'S POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ To the adoring, impoverished masses who
catapulted him to power, Hugo Chavez Frias is El Comandante, their
protector and benefactor, the bold leader who will wipe out 40
years of inequality and corruption and redirect this country's
enormous oil wealth to better their lives.
</P>
<P>
   To his opponents, the 44-year-old former army paratrooper who is
Venezuela's new president represents something unsettling, even
dangerous. With his talk of ``revolution,'' his contempt for
institutions he calls decadent and his violent coup attempt seven
years ago, he strikes many of them as an autocrat in the making.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is still out on Chavez, who took office on Feb. 2 while
riding a wave of popular disgust with a political system seen as
venal and unresponsive. But whether he turns out to be democrat or
dictator, his charisma and his vows to overturn the prevailing
order have already transformed politics in this country of 23
million people.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to divine Chavez's ultimate intentions from a flood of
contradictory public pronouncements has become a popular pastime
here, leading to the publication of several new books with titles
like ``Chavez the Wizard of Emotions: Psychosocial Analysis of a
Political Phenomenon.'' But ask Chavez, and he classifies himself
as a postmodernist politician, bound by none of the ``Cartesian''
limitations of established ideologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try to assess me by traditional canons of analysis,
you'll never emerge from confusion,'' he said in an interview in
his office at the same presidential palace he attacked in 1992.
``If you are attempting to determine whether Chavez is of the left,
right or center, if he is a socialist, communist or capitalist,
well, I am none of those, but I have a bit of all of those.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's minister of finance, Maritza Izaguirre Porras,
describes the president, who has never held public office before,
as a pragmatist going through ``a process of apprenticeship.''
Dealing with the budget, for instance, he was eager to learn even
the most arcane details of state spending, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the president's critics argue that Venezuela, the largest
supplier of crude oil to the United States in recent years, is
mired in a crisis so severe that it cannot afford the luxury of
giving him on-the-job training. Inflation and unemployment are near
all-time highs, oil prices slumped to their lowest level in years
just as Chavez was taking office, and the Venezuelan economy is
expected to contract this year for the second year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the situation, Chavez demanded from Congress, and
received late in March, the power to rule by decree for the next
six months. But the main, and most controversial, plank of his
campaign platform was a pledge to convene a constituent assembly to
do away with the country's ``moribund'' constitution and draw up a
new one. A referendum on that proposal is scheduled for April 25.
</P>
<P>
   (On April 8, Chavez rejected the ``enabling law'' that Congress
had approved, saying it did not go far enough. He threatened to
impose a state of national emergency, which would allow him to
suspend constitutional guarantees and to rule by decree.)
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by Chavez and his Fifth Republic Movement, the new
constitution would grant him expanded powers and allow him to run
for a second consecutive term, instead of waiting 10 years as
currently required. That has led his critics to charge that he
plans to make himself a caudillo, or classic Latin American
military strongman in the mold of Juan Peron, Fidel Castro or Omar
Torrijos, an accusation that Chavez ridicules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were going to be a tyrant, I would already have carried
out a coup d'etat,'' he said dismissively. ``How am I going to be a
caudillo when I am subject to the rules of a system?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet fears that Chavez plans to ignore the restraints of
traditional politics were fanned in mid-March, after he said that
he and his supporters would ``take to the streets'' if the Supreme
Court did not allow him to organize the constituent assembly as he
wanted. But when the court ruled against him, Chavez accepted the
decision and is now trying to make his decree conform to the court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that Chavez could come to believe himself that
his relation with the people is like that of a strongman with the
masses, like that of Il Duce, Der Fuhrer, El Comandante or the
secretary-general of the party,'' said Teodoro Petkoff, a former
guerrilla leader and a former minister of planning. ``This kind of
primitive conception, which disdains and demonizes political
parties or any other intermediary between the population and those
in power, could develop from this singular relationship he has
created with a good part of the poor population of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, though, ``Chavez has acted as a restraining wall to
those around him who have authoritarian impulses, whether they are
military men or from the old left,'' Petkoff continued. ``I think
he is finding he has the temperament and a taste for the political
game and that he is learning it quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's hand has clearly been strengthened by the disrepute
that clings to the political parties that have governed Venezuela
since the collapse of a military dictatorship in 1958. As ordinary
Venezuelans see it, poll after poll has indicated, the country's
political elite has either squandered or pocketed billions of
dollars of oil revenues that should have been used to make the
country and its people rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez's origins are those of the avenger, the instrument the
Venezuelan people use to debit the account of the political class
that has dominated this country for 40 years,'' said Alcibiades
Castro, leader of the congressional delegation of Copei, the more
conservative of the country's two traditional parties.
``Notwithstanding the election, not everyone in the parties is
fully aware of this, and so our very identities and viability are
at stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Traditional politicians may wince at the frankness of some of
Chavez's more colorful or incendiary observations, but most people
appear to like what they hear. He was elected with 57 percent of
the vote, but recent polls indicate that his support has soared
since taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Several gestures intended to demonstrate that the country is in
crisis have been particularly well received: Chavez has refused to
accept his $1,200 a month official salary, donating it to a
scholarship fund and saying he can live well enough on his military
pension, and he has also dispensed with use of a limousine and
other traditional perquisites of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez is of the people, with humble origins,'' said Eduardo
Beltran, 29, a security guard at a downtown building. ``When have
you ever seen a president of this country stop his limousine to get
out and talk to the poor? He is a second Bolivar, just the
president Venezuela needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Chavez's humble start as the child of two schoolteachers
is one of his strongest selling points. Eustoquio Duque Castro, a
retired military officer, was stationed in Chavez's hometown,
Sabaneta, when the president was a boy, and remembered him selling
fruit and ices outside the barracks after school every afternoon
before running off to baseball practice.
</P>
<P>
   A left-handed pitcher, Chavez ``could do it all, hit, field, run
and pitch, but couldn't afford the equipment he needed,'' Duque
remembered. As a teen-ager, Chavez was such a standout that the
army recruited him for its team. But an arm injury sidelined him
and ended his dreams of a big-league career. It also, as he
recalled in an autobiography published after the 1992 coup attempt,
led to an intense period of reading and study of political
doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought he could be president, but I voted for him,
and I don't regret it,'' Duque, 66, said. ``I have faith in him.
With a young president who wants to work hard, the country is
already more animated and disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky start caused by his populist declarations and
flirtation with Fidel Castro, his relations with Washington also
have improved. Chavez was for many years denied a visa to the
United States because of the 1992 coup attempt, but that ban was
lifted after his resounding election victory. He has already
visited Washington twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are behind him so long as he remains within constitutional
parameters for reforming the country,'' Peter Romero, the assistant
secretary of state for inter-American affairs, said on a recent
visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said he was acutely aware that his every word and action
was being dissected here and in the rest of Latin America, where he
is seen as an alarming throwback to the age of the strongman. But
he said he welcomed the scrutiny, and invited skeptics to ``analyze
with objectivity the truth of what is taking place here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to know where we are going, then let them watch
us, with satellites or lenses, from near or from far, and observe
our tracks,'' he said. ``We are heading toward the light, toward
the open horizon, gradually building a true democracy, and not
towards the darkness of the jungle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
