<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Saturday, April 10. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW MEDICINE (Tucson, Ariz.) - A historic debate on new medicine
versus old medicine is being debated Friday night at the University
of Arizona medical school. Dr. Andrew Weil, who is on the cutting
edge of what is new in alternative medicine, is debating Dr. Arnold
Relman, editor and chief emeritus of the New England School of
Medicine who is squarely from the old school of medicine. Relman
recently wrote a scathing article criticizing Weil. This debate may
be repeated at Stanford University at a later date. By MAUREEN
WEST. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
GARNISH-FOOD (Phoenix) - How to dress up everyd ay meals and plates
as well as special occasion dinners. Story includes step-by-step
instructions for eight garnish concepts. With PHOTOS moved Thursday
and GARNISHTOOLS-FOOD and GARNISHBOOKS-FOOD. By ANITA MABANTE
LEACH. Stories moved in the ``D'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CRYSTALGAYLE-MUSIC (Phoenix) - If you're over the age of 25, there
are some things you probably know about Crystal Gayle: She's got a
ton of country hits, a beautiful voice, a famous sister (Loretta
Lynn) and some absurdly long hair that she could sweep the floor
with if she wished. But who knew she hated Velcro? By RANDY
CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOCELLI-MUSIC Andrea Bocelli is blessed with a very distinctive
form of popularity. That is, people either seem to fall at his feet
in worship or hate the ground he walks on. For example, the
40-year-old tenor so far has sold more than 14 million albums. His
fourth disc, a collection of Italian pop epics dubbed ``Sogno,''
was released last week. He has almost sold out America West Arena
for his first Phoenix appearance; even a $500 ticket price didn't
seem to deter hungry fans. His accessible style has brought people
to opera who normally would shy away from the mere concept. By
RANDY CORDOVA and KENNETH LAFAVE. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BILLYJOEL-MUSIC (Phoenix) - Billy Joel has had so many hits over
such a long period of time, it's difficult to imagine the pop-music
landscape without him. Yet that's exactly what may happen after his
current ``Greatest Hits'' tour wraps up. ``I'm not going to say
this is the end of something,'' Joel said last year in an interview
with CNN. ``But I don't think I'm going to do any more long tours
after this tour.'' By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Pheonxi) - Chevy's full-size, two-door sport-utility
vehicle, beloved for three decades by hunters, campers and cruising
teenagers, goes the way of the dodo after this year.
</P>
<P>
   The two-door Chevy Tahoe, formerly called the Chevy Blazer
before that name was downsized to a compact, is a big, brawny
heavyweight based on the Chevy half-ton pickup with a shortened
wheelbase, two rows of seats and a utility body. Its compromises as
a large, somewhat ungainly two-door utility truck made it a niche
vehicle, overshadowed in recent years by the four-door sport utes
that are popping up everywhere. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the
``L'' category  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
