<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AWFUL-TRUTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL MOORE PICKS UP WHERE HE LEFT OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At his best, Michael Moore is Everyman.
</P>
<P>
   The unkempt, chubby, baseball cap-wearing gadfly who shot to
fame with ``Roger &AMP; Me'' has a remarkable gift for articulating the
greatest frustration of average Joes who lack connections and
resources: just getting their voices heard.
</P>
<P>
   It is only when he strays outside this role that he stumbles.
His fictional film ``Canadian Bacon,'' for example, was a one-note
disappointment, coming after the brilliant ``Roger.'' It's no
different with Moore's new half-hour TV series, ``The Awful
Truth,'' premiering Sunday on cable's Bravo network.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's last TV series, ``TV Nation,'' was similarly uneven. The
show was canceled after bouncing from NBC to Fox several years ago.
It would be nice to see Moore find his niche at the lower-rated but
perhaps more laissez-faire Bravo, which is trying to launch an
identity through original programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truth'' is split into two segments, which Moore introduces
from a stage in front of an enthusiastic audience. The first of
Sunday's segments is a silly and dated political prank titled ``A
Cheaper Way to Conduct a Witch Hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   As a protest against Kenneth Starr's investigation of President
Clinton, Moore leads a group of actors dressed as ``Puritans'' in
an assault on Washington. Moore collars a few Republicans,
including Asa Hutchinson, to harangue about Starr's ``witch hunt,''
while the actors flail around and cry out things like ``Shame!''
</P>
<P>
   The segment falls flat because it is dated and ham-handed. It's
obvious where Moore's sympathies lie, and equally obvious that he's
preaching to the converted. In introducing the piece, Moore gloats,
``We got to watch the Republican Party go down in flames.'' His
acolytes in the audience greet the statement with wild applause.
When he tacks on, ``I hope some of the Democrats aren't far
behind,'' the audience barely responds.
</P>
<P>
   The show's second segment, though, is classic Moore. He seeks _
and ultimately appears to get _ justice for a 34-year-old diabetic
man named Chris who's been denied a pancreas transplant by his HMO.
Chris' doctor has told him that, without the operation, he will
soon die.
</P>
<P>
   Moore accompanies Chris on a very dark journey, watching him
dictate his own obituary to a newspaper and accompanying him as he
shops for caskets. Then, as he did in ``Roger,'' Moore takes the
issue to the top: He gets a meeting for himself and Chris with a
vice president of the HMO, Humana.
</P>
<P>
   As they wait in a meeting room, Moore and Chris are approached
by Humana's head of public relations. The flak tells them the veep
has been ``delayed,'' and won't be able to meet with them today.
</P>
<P>
   The PR man squirms as Moore tries to corner him on the facts of
Chris' case and goad him by asking his opinion of which casket
Chris should buy. The PR man finally gets the two to leave the
building, though not before Chris removes his T-shirt _ which reads
``I signed with Humana and all I got was this lousy T-shirt ... but
no pancreas'' _ and gives it to the hapless company tool.
</P>
<P>
   After all this, plus staging a mock funeral later in front of
Humana's offices, we're told in Moore's epilogue that Humana agreed
shortly thereafter to cover Chris' pancreas transplant. When Chris,
in the audience and looking much healthier, stands up, pumps his
fists and throws a big kiss to Moore, it's a genuinely triumphant
moment. If Moore can come up with more moments like these, he and
Bravo will have a hit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
