<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth saying `aloha' to wireless unit in Hawaii
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth is selling its wireless operations in
Honolulu to AT&AMP;T, the companies announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would say how much the deal is worth. Bloomberg
News, citing a source familiar with the transaction, said AT&AMP;T
spent about $160 million for Honolulu Cellular.
</P>
<P>
   The number of subscribers for the Honolulu service was not
disclosed. Honolulu Cellular Telephone sells wireless services in a
market with a population of about 900,000.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth acquired Honolulu Cellular in 1986. It became a wholly
owned subsidiary of the Atlanta-based company in 1996. The
transaction is expected to close in the second half this year. The
deal is subject to regulatory and government approval.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is not that unusual, said Jeff Battcher, a BellSouth
spokesman. BellSouth swapped wireless properties in Wisconsin and
Indiana for U.S. Cellular properties in Mississippi and Alabama in
1997. In June, BellSouth traded a wireless property in Bakersfield,
Calif., for AT&AMP;T's College Station, Texas, coverage area.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth now offers wireless service in 13 states, mostly in
the South. Its coverage area also includes Indiana, Northern
Virginia and parts of East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Battcher said BellSouth's goal is to focus on geographic areas
where it can provide a wide range of telecommunications products
billed on one statement, including wireless digital television,
pagers, wireless phones, traditional phone service and Internet
access. BellSouth offers those services in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based AT&AMP;T wants to provide national wireless coverage.
Shares of BellSouth were down 62 1/2 cents, closing at $43.75.
AT&AMP;T's stock was up $1.62 1/2. It closed at $85.50.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
