<SLUG> BC-COKE-ORANGINA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola loses round in French court battle
 &HT;    EDs: This replaces MEXICO-COKE.
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. suffered its second international
setback in two days Friday when France's high court backed a
government decision blocking the company's purchase of the Orangina
drink from Pernod Ricard SA.
</P>
<P>
   The $822 million deal now hinges on whether the Atlanta-based
beverage company can satisfy the French government's antitrust
concerns, which it has not yet been able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue our discussion with the French authorities
and remain hopeful the deal will be approved,'' said Coca-Cola
spokesman Mark Preisinger.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the court's decision could increase the
government's leverage in obtaining concessions from Coca-Cola
before approving a deal, which the government initially rejected
last September.
</P>
<P>
   But time may be running out.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ricard, chairman of Pernod, has said that he has set
anunspecified date for the sale to go through or he will seek
alternatives to the Coca-Cola deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Australian antitrust regulators rejected
Coca-Cola's purchase of the Cadbury Schweppes beverages in that
country. The companies hope that a revised deal, which is now being
discussed, will win regulatory approval there.
</P>
<P>
   In both countries, Coca-Cola's huge market share is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   In France, Pepsi complained immediately to the government after
Coca-Cola and Pernod Ricard announced the deal in December 1997.
Pepsi argued that it would essentially be shut out of the country
because Orangina bottles and distributes Pepsi brands sold at
cafes, hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with the court's decision to allow healthy
competition in this industry in France,'' Pepsi spokesman Dave
DeCecco said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola hopes to sell the orange-flavored drink in France and
other European markets, as well as in the United States. It also
hopes to use the Orangina distribution system to sell its other
brands.
</P>
<P>
   In Australia, antitrust regulators ruled that Coca-Cola's
purchase of Cadbury Schweppes brands would substantially reduce
competition there, pushing the company's share of the market to 75
percent, from 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which plans to spend $1.85 billion to purchase
Cadbury brands in 120 countries, excluding the United States, South
Africa and France, also faces potential regulatory hurdles in about
10 nations, including Mexico and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock fell 12 1/2 cents Friday, closing at $60.75.
The decision by the French court was made public after the New York
market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
