<SLUG> BC-COXCOMMUNICATIONS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T, Cox rework At Home deal
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Communications confirmed Friday it has
renegotiated a contract that could give the Atlanta-based cable
operator greater control of the high-speed Internet provider At
Home Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the new one-year contract, AT&AMP;T would grant Cox
Communications more stock in At Home if the telecommunications
giant failed to sign up a certain number of its cable TV
subscribers to the Silicon Valley startup's service. Neither AT&AMP;T
or Cox Communications would disclose that number.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stock clause, it's not greater control of At Home
that Cox Communications is after. What it wants is to spur AT&AMP;T,
which owns a controlling stake in At Home, to sharply increase its
At Home subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want AT&AMP;T to pay us a penalty,'' says David Woodrow,
Cox Communications' senior vice president for broadband services.
``The value of At Home's stock is in the level of its
distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the greater the number of At Home's subscribers,
the higher its stock will go.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications presently owns 12.3 percent of At Home. AT&AMP;T
owns 71 percent and Comcast owns another 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is the largest single distributor of At
Home's service. More than 67,000 of its 3.8 million subscribers use
it.
</P>
<P>
   At Home provides Internet access through a device called a cable
modem. It connects to the Internet at speeds up to 100 times faster
than traditional telephone lines. At Home also provides Internet
content to its subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   At Home requires a two-way digital cable network, which is
unavailable in most of the country. One reason Cox Communications
has been able to sell so many At Home subscriptions is most of its
system have been rebuilt to offer digital services such as
high-speed Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for AT&AMP;T, which acquired its controlling stake in At Home
with the purchase earlier this year of cable TV operator
Tele-Communications Inc (TCI). TCI has been a laggard in rebuilding
its systems as a digital network.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications executives are betting the new contract will
be an incentive for AT&AMP;T to expedite the rebuilding of its cable TV
systems for digital traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is controlled by Cox Enterprises, which also
owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
