<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-BLAZER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brawny Blazer has golden touch
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Finally for 1999, Chevrolet has given its Blazer just
what every buyer has whined about needing ever since the popular
sport-utility was introduced in '83: gold-painted aluminum wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Who, after all, wants to go beating around the bush with plain
old wheels?
</P>
<P>
   To get the gold-trim wheels, though, it's necessary to opt for
the new-for-'99 TrailBlazer package. It also includes two-tone
embossed leather seats, monochromatic paint and _ this is
significant _ a touring suspension that really smooths out the ride
of the 3,700-pound sport-utility.
</P>
<P>
   The TrailBlazer carries a base price of $30,470 (plus $525
destination charge) for the four-door, two-wheel-drive version. The
base price for the not-TrailBlazer version two-door is $18,470;
buyers who want four-wheel drive can expect to add about $2,000 to
the cost on a four-door and about $3,000 on a two-door.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be about two years before the Blazer gets a major
reworking, so the TrailBlazer package is Chevy's interim step at
catching up in the high-end of the sport-ute market, now featuring
entries from virtually all the upscale manufacturers. As Russ
Clark, Blazer brand manager says, ``Today's sport-utility owners
are not only buying the performance ... they're buying image.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance is there in the Blazer, thanks to the venerable
4.3-liter V-6 engine, which has the power for expressway travel and
enough grunt to go off-road or for towing. With 190 horsepower and
250 pounds-feet of torque, the test TrailBlazer moved out smartly
and never seemed underpowered or particularly slow to respond in
ordinary driving conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a better ride, the TrailBlazer has improved
brakes, a comforting factor in sprint-and-stop traffic. Its height
(64.3 inches) makes for nice forward and side visibility, but the
rear view is less than ideal because of limited visibility in the
inside mirror and the scope of the outside power mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Partial atonement comes in the comfort department, with the
TrailBlazer sporting good front bucket seats, plenty of headroom
(39.6 inches up front) and a good supply of drink holders, power
outlets and storage spaces. The rear seating is adequate, although
it requires knees-up posture, and some occupants may be irked by
rear speakers mounted hip-high on the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Cargo space is good (about 37 cubic feet with the seats up,
about 74 with the rear folded). Access is easy through the side
doors and the rear hatch, which has an integral liftglass and a
glass-ajar warning light on the dash. Other niceties include the
automatic climate control, power equipment, an optional sunroof and
the simplicity of the instrumentation and controls.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy remains poor (16 and 21 mpg), but that's a given
with big-engined sport-utilities. But, as with others in its class,
the Blazer's evolution to carlike characteristics brings better
comfort and driveability despite trucklike handling. The
TrailBlazer package, gold wheels and all, is a solid step up for
Blazer in style and image, but, otherwise, the '99 isn't all that
different from its predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Chevrolet TrailBlazer four-door,
two-wheel-drive sport-utility vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $31,198 (includes discount not always
available; base price: $30,470)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual air bags, power anti-lock disc brakes,
side-impact beams, daytime running lights
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 4.3-liter V-6 engine (190 horsepower), four-speed
automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Standard features include: automatic heating/air conditioning
system, two-tone leather seats, stereo with cassette player, power
locks and windows, power dual heated mirrors, rear wiper/
</P>
<P>
   defroster, keyless entry system
</P>
<P>
   Options on test on vehicle: power sunroof, $750; CD player,
$100; six Bose speakers, $495; redundant steering-wheel-mounted
stereo controls, $125; 235/
</P>
<P>
   70R15 all-season tires, $133
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 16 mpg regular unleaded city; 21 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
