<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCDOUGAL TRIAL COMES CLOSE TO MISTRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The trial of Susan McDougal on charges of
criminal contempt and obstruction for refusing to testify before a
Whitewater grand jury about the Arkansas financial dealings of
President Clinton and his wife, Hillary, briefly teetered on the
verge of a mistrial Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As the jury deliberated for a second day, the proceeding was
thrown into disarray when a bailiff spotted one juror with a law
book on the duties of jurors in Arkansas state trials. The book was
quickly seized by court officials, and the judge and lawyers for
both sides immediately began pondering whether the jury's
deliberations had been tainted by the presence of the law book.
</P>
<P>
   But after interviewing the juror, the trial judge, George Howard
Jr., ruled that his use of the law book had had little effect, that
he could remain on the panel and that the trial could go on. The
jury was then sent home for the weekend to resume deliberations at
U.S. District Court here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fairly basic principle of American jurisprudence that
juries are obliged to consider only the law and the facts as given
to them in the course of a trial and may not do their own legal
research or seek advice outside the confines of the court
proceeding. Juries are always instructed explicitly in those rules,
as was this jury by Howard before it began its deliberations on
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the law book in the jury room took up most of the
day. ``I don't see how we can avoid a mistrial at this point,''
Mark Geragos, Ms. McDougal's defense lawyer, told reporters outside
the courthouse before the judge's ruling. The law book contained
business cards from a well-known local lawyer, John Purtle, a
former justice of the Arkansas Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, Howard ordered federal marshals to summon
Purtle from his home in Toadsuck, Ark., to answer questions about
how his book got into the hands of the juror, Michael Nance.
Purtle, appearing stunned and abashed in the judge's chambers, said
that he had sold his house to Nance in 1997 and probably left some
law books behind.
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing Nance, Howard said the juror had confirmed
that he found the book in an old study that had belonged to Purtle
and brought it to court to help him understand some legal terms.
</P>
<P>
   Purtle's background starkly demonstrates how intertwined are
many issues and personalities in Arkansas. He was originally named
to the state Supreme Court by Clinton when Clinton was governor.
While on the court, Purtle ruled in favor of Ms. McDougal and her
husband at the time, James McDougal, in a matter involving a
savings bank they owned which is at the heart of the current trial.
Ms. McDougal is charged with two counts of criminal contempt and
one of obstruction of justice in connection with her refusal to
answer questions before a grand jury investigating the financial
dealings of the Clintons. She had already served 18 months in jail
at the order of a federal judge for civil contempt for her refusal.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, then chose to
charge her with criminal contempt, a felony that requires a jury
trial. If convicted on all three counts, she faces a maximum
sentence of about seven years under complicated sentencing
guidelines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
