<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-ANNIVERSARY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anniversary of Atlanta tornado marked
 &HT;    By Marianne Jaskevich
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Providing residents with early warning against
tornadoes has been a priority of the state since last April's storm
ripped through four suburban counties, killing one and causing
millions in damage, officials said at a ceremony Friday to mark the
one-year anniversary of Atlanta's most devastating twister.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes and U.S. Sen. Max Cleland were among the
dignitaries who gathered at Brook Run in DeKalb County to talk
about tornado safety initiatives and to honor state and local
workers who helped many families in Cobb, Gwinnett, Fulton and
DeKalb counties recover in the storm's aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also paid tribute to John Janisch, who was the only
fatality during the twister.
</P>
<P>
   ``One year ago today ... while local residents slept, thousands
of homes and acres of property were being destroyed,'' Barnes said.
``We are here today to remember that loss of property and the one
life lost. ... The storm displaced thousands and injured so many.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the storm knocked out communications towers, the state
purchased a $650,000 transmitter so that various agencies can
communicate more effectively following storms. Detection devices
such as sirens and storm-tracking radar technology are being
upgraded to better predict a storm's arrival, officials said. For
example, Georgia Tech's Tornado Research Center's $1.5 million
Warning and Detection project aims to increase tornado warning time
from eight to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Other efforts include research to develop structures capable of
withstanding a tornado's fierce winds, and the addition of 13 new
weather towers, officials noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know how to better protect themselves by
building stronger walls, ceilings, and roofs that don't blow off,''
said Mary Hudak, a Federal Emergency Management Agency spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   While officials praised the state and local workers, volunteers
distributed young trees and seedlings to a stream of tornado
victims. Dunwoody alone lost more than 100,000 trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Springtime is a time of new beginnings,'' said DeKalb CEO
Liane Levetan, noting how the communities have worked to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
