<HEADER>
A2709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-BOOK-WARS-ART     04-09 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-BOOK-WARS-ART-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORE OR .COM? SEATTLE'S LITERARY HEART IS TORN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (ac) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle has long prided itself on being an unusually
literary city, where writers congregate and the drizzly climate
begs a resident to curl up in a chair and read. At its bookish
heart, most Seattleites would agree, is the Elliott Bay Book
Company, where customers can browse amid the cedar shelves or
listen to some of the 500 or more annual programs that make up its
esteemed series of author readings.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle also views itself as one of the world's most
technologically precocious cities, a natural place for a young man
named Jeffrey P. Bezos to launch his Internet company, Amazon.com,
which pioneered the concept of selling books through the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   But as the rising fortunes of Amazon.com threaten Elliott Bay,
these two visions are in conflict. While the clash is a familiar
one across the country, no where is it more sharply drawn than here
in Seattle, where many people's loyalties are keenly divided
between the progress of electronic commerce and the tradition
embodied in a great independent bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there was some tension recently, when Bezos, who was being
profiled by the ``NewsHour With Jim Lehrer,'' suggested that the
television crew accompany him to Elliott Bay, which he describes as
his favorite bookstore in the world, to show him buying books there
_ off line.
</P>
<P>
   If it was a gesture of support for the 26-year-old store, which
has been reeling financially, it seemed to have been lost on
Elliott Bay employees. They say people sometimes spend an afternoon
browsing and coffee-sipping in the store, then go home to save
money by ordering books they discovered on the shelves from
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand his intentions were to plug us,'' said Tracy
Taylor, the store manager, of Bezos. ``How do I describe what I
felt when I saw him here? I'm not sure he's the right spokesperson
for independent bookstores.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other independent book stores around the nation, whose
numbers as measured by their main trade association have dwindled
from 5,200 eight years ago to 3,300 today, Elliott Bay faces
pressures from all over. Chain bookstores, which have opened at
least a dozen branches in the Seattle area, and growing traffic and
parking problems downtown have made it difficult to get to its
Pioneer Square location.
</P>
<P>
   But Walter Carr, the founder of Elliott Bay, and the owners of
several bookstores that have closed in recent months, have cited
relentless competition and price-cutting from online booksellers as
a major force in their decline. And while plenty of readers view
online dealers as the great enemy and refuse to buy from them, many
Seattle literary leaders have much more conflicted feelings here in
the city where the revolution in electronic commerce started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to happen someplace, and if it's happening here, in
many ways that's great,'' said Sherry Prowda, who founded Seattle
Arts and Lectures, another popular author series, 12 years ago. ``I
really am glad that people view Seattle as a place to come and make
exciting and new and interesting things happen. I mean, if it
started in Philadelphia, Walter would have felt the results of it
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time though,'' she added, ``I feel that we have to
find some way for these two institutions to coexist here. Seattle
without the Elliott Bay Book Company seems unimaginable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Elliott Bay loyalists admit to a grudging respect for
Amazon.com and its many features, such as reader reviews and
chapter excerpts, despite the company's concession that it takes
publishers' money to treat some books favorably.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Raban, a British author who lives here and who
describes the Elliott Bay staff as perhaps the most knowledgeable
of any in bookstores all across the United States and the United
Kingdom, said he has started buying books online.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first went online, which was despicably recently, and
visited the Amazon site, I was so persuaded by its bookstorelike
quality that I felt sort of embarrassed to leave the site without
buying a book,'' said Raban, author of the upcoming ``Passage to
Juneau: A Sea and its Meanings,'' a maritime history set around his
solo sailing voyage from here to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I was buying books I didn't even want,'' he said, ``in
exactly the same way I buy books I don't even want in real
bookstores.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The decline of Elliott Bay and Carr's decision to sell it to a
local developer, Ron Sher, has been chronicled in part here as a
sort of Seattle version of ``You've Got Mail,'' the recent romantic
comedy movie, in which the bookstore gets the Meg Ryan role and
Amazon.com is the Tom Hanks megamerchant character.
</P>
<P>
   Bezos, 35, initiated meetings this year with Carr to ask what he
could do to help save the bookstore. Rumors flew for a while _ that
Bezos might buy the store, that he would buy a parking lot and
donate it to Elliott Bay.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Carr said, he was pleased to find Sher, who has
revived two shopping areas in the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   And, in time, it just may be that another Seattle giant,
Microsoft Corp., makes the whole notion of competition between
online sellers and old-fashioned bookstores seem quaint: Microsoft
is hoping to pioneer the concept of ``e-books,'' which would be
downloaded onto a portable electronic tablet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for now, many people resent the idea that they somehow
have to choose sides between Elliott Bay and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm torn in half,'' said Bill Radke, the host of ``Rewind,'' a
public-radio comedy show based in Seattle. ``I feel like Elliott
Bay used to be a trip to the bookstore and now it's a moral
crusade, it's a conscientious objection, which is a lot of pressure
to go through for an Al Franken book.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've turned it into good guys and bad guys,'' he said,
``but it's hard to hate Amazon.com because they're from your
hometown. My sister works there. When they started, they used old
doors as desk tops, which just doesn't say `Evil Empire' to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sher contends he can make Elliott Bay thrive again by adding
more seating, improving the food service, offering used as well as
new books and, yes, improving the store's Web site. But he also
said he expected a popular resurgence in the idea of the bookstore
as a gathering place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are getting way too alienated, especially in
the age of the Internet, and they know it,'' Sher said. ``They want
to come to connect back to places like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Many advocates of both online sellers and the big chains even
say that their presence will expand the public's appetite for
books, leading to a larger market for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers do not seem to bear out that vision: The most recent
annual survey showed that Americans were buying slightly fewer
books per capita annually, says a spokeswoman for the American
Booksellers Association. And independent bookstores' share of the
market declined to 17.2 percent in 1997, from 32.5 percent at the
beginning of the decade, the association said.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, who since opening the store in 1973 has seemed to be every
bit as much a fixture of the store as its exposed brick walls, said
that the store's sale became inevitable after single-digit
percentage decreases in sales became double digits in recent years
and his staff, once at a peak of 90, had been cut to 50. He and
other people at Elliott Bay say Amazon.com was a huge factor, in
many ways more than the chain stores like Borders or Barnes &AMP;
Noble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hit more like a neutron bomb,'' said Rick Simonson,
the head book buyer and developer of the author readings series,
which has been lauded &UR;  &LR; for its role in the state's literary life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain books stopped selling,'' he said. ``And you started
hearing, `What's the price on this, I could get it for less on
Amazon.com.'''
</P>
<P>
   But even Carr's feelings about Bezos, who has been a regular
store customer throughout Amazon.com's meteoric rise, are nuanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem like with all sincerity he says he loves great
bookstores, and we've been flattered to be among what he calls the
greatest,'' Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's a two-edged sword,'' he added. ``Maybe it's my
troubled worldly perspective, where I have a combination of
admiration for what he's done, because he has provided this way for
people all over to access books and information about books, but at
the same time, this store's downward fate is locked into the
success of his enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bezos declined to be interviewed about the store. ``He loves
it,'' his spokeswoman said. ``But I think we'll pass on the story
about Internet effects on bookshops, et cetera.''
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur's recent foray with cameras into the store drew
some derision. ``Kind of like Howard Schultz of Starbucks going
into a little mom-and-pop espresso place and saying, `This is what
I had in mind, this is what I really love about Seattle,''' said
David Brewster, the founder of Sasquatch Books in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many here continue to hope the two institutions can
somehow thrive together, and that the Internet company might
contribute to the literary scene here _ ``if, and when,'' Ms.
Prowda drily notes, ``Amazon starts to make some money.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are signs that Elliott Bay could be helped by the big
competitor _ after all, say store employees, sometimes people come
in with printouts of research they have done on the Amazon site and
say these are the books they would like to buy at Elliott Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this store, I love all its winding nooks and crannies,
I love everything about it,'' said Reagan Jackson, 19, a sophomore
at the University of Washington, browsing at the store recently.
``And besides, books have character. They have different covers.
They have different smells. I need to go through all that. It just
wouldn't be the same for me to buy books over the Web.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
