u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SURVEIL-ART-61     04-09 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SURVEIL-ART-610&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO REPORTS NO SIGN OF REFUGEES TURNED BACK AT KOSOVO BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Three days after Serbian troops closed
border crossing points from Kosovo into Macedonia and Albania, NATO
reconnaissance planes have failed to locate any of the tens of
thousands of refugees who were turned back from the frontier.
</P>
<P>
   ``A key question is what is happening to the people who were
trying to leave,'' the alliance's spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said,
referring in particular to those he called the ``car people,''
whose automobiles had been lined up about 12 miles inside Kosovo
near the Albanian border before vanishing overnight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Unpiloted American ``Predator'' and ``Hunter'' reconnaissance
drones have been flying over the province for the past several
days. But a NATO military spokesman, Air Commodore David Wilby,
said Friday that allied intelligence was concentrating mostly on
finding tanks and other armored vehicles to bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian paramilitary police and army units have been using the
tanks in attacks that have driven hundreds of thousands of
civilians out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A senior European diplomat said that NATO civilian authorities
had asked the military command on Thursday to intensify
reconnaissance over Kosovo to try to locate the missing civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Klaus Naumann, chairman of the Military Committee at the
alliance's headquarters here, has also requested surveillance
reports from individual allies' reconnaissance missions, officials
say, but so far, requests by NATO ambassadors for better
intelligence on the missing refugees have not produced any.
</P>
<P>
   Neither civilian nor military officials offered much explanation
for the failure.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said Thursday, ``We are certainly trying to identify all
movement of people, and we are obviously very concerned about where
those people are being moved to.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shea said Friday, ``We believe there may be 150,000 to
200,000 people in Kosovo living without shelter, in the woods, in
ruined villages, and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   But the allies, like international relief officials, have been
reduced mainly to guessing at what happened after the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, closed the borders Tuesday night,
declared a unilateral cease-fire Wednesday and said refugees were
free to return home. NATO has rejected those claims as a
duplicitous sham.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said Friday that the
Serbian troops inside Kosovo might have forced refugees back to
make them ``human shields'' around the military targets of the
allied bombing campaign, which continued Friday despite unfavorable
weather conditions in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Particular concern has been expressed about the fate of
thousands of people who were lined up behind the border crossing on
the road from Prizren to the Albanian border town of Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received reports from the few people who have come
through that all along the road behind the border, the cars and
wagons and tractors are just abandoned, with luggage and food left
behind and nobody visible on the road,'' Judith Kumin, a
spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Geneva,
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very much concerned for the fate of civilians remaining
in Kosovo,'' the high commissioner, Sadako Ogata, said Friday in
Skopje, the capital of Macedonia. Asked what her organization could
do for them, she said, ``I am helpless there.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all international organizations left Kosovo before March
24, when NATO began bombing to try to force Milosevic to accept a
peace settlement restoring autonomy to the ethnic Albanian
population of the province.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Naumann said in an interview on German radio Friday that it
would be difficult for the West to impose peace in Kosovo without
sending in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could not speculate whether allied governments would
think twice about their refusal to fight their way into Kosovo to
escort more than half a million refugees driven out by Serbian
forces back to their homes. ``Ultimately, a conflict is always
decided on the ground, of course,'' he said. ``Without a presence
on the ground, it's very, very difficult to achieve that.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a presence on the ground, there are also no allied
reconnaissance patrols from either Albania or Macedonia that can
fill in gaps in the allies' intelligence about the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has allowed 12,000 allied soldiers, including British,
French and American troops, onto its territory, but Macedonia's
defense minister, Nikola Kljusev, said on a visit to the alliance's
headquarters Friday that his country still insists that none of
those troops be used for offensive action against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is agreement with the Yugoslav government for the
entry of NATO forces into Yugoslavia, then they will be allowed to
enter Yugoslavia,'' he said. ``Unless this happens, the passage of
NATO forces into Yugoslavia cannot be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12,000 soldiers were originally sent to Macedonia as the
vanguard of the 28,000-strong peacekeeping force planned for Kosovo
as part of a negotiated settlement, but Milosevic refused even to
discuss peacekeepers. Now the troops have been put to work helping
Macedonia deal with more than 150,000 ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The Macedonians bused thousands of refugees who had been camped
at the border near Blace to Albania this week without so much as a
word to NATO troops or refugee officials.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials were full of praise Friday for Macedonia's
cooperation, according to the country's foreign minister,
Aleksandar Dimitrov, who met with allied ambassadors and Solana for
an hour Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said later that the allies had agreed to pay for any
damage to Macedonian property caused by the presence of allied
troops, and warned that the alliance would respond to any threats
to Macedonia from Yugoslavia while they were there.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance also plans to send 8,000 troops to Albania to help
deal with the refugee crisis there. Albania has agreed to let the
United States station 24 Apache anti-tank helicopters and Army
surface-to-surface rockets on its soil, with about 2,000 American
soldiers to operate them, to improve the effectiveness of the NATO
air campaign against Serbian forces in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
