<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-575&AMP;     04-09 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUFUGEES TRAIL: BEHIND THEM, A BURNING VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAZINCE, Macedonia _ Yugoslav forces are continuing to force
ethnic Albanians out of their homes in southern Kosovo, newly
arrived refugees said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh accounts of Yugoslav forces ordering ethnic Albanians
to leave Kosovo and torching villages came three days after
Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic, declared a unilateral
cease-fire in the province on Tuesday. But ethnic Albanians
trickling into northwestern Macedonia here told of Yugoslav forces
burning villages as recently as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Macedonian and Serbian border guards have almost
totally closed the border, only allowing the occasional carload of
refugees through. Hundreds of refugees remain massed at the Jazince
border crossing. The handful who crossed Friday said they had
waited nine days to pass through the border controls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, fear of Serbian military and police operations continues to
drive ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovo even if it means
a long and dangerous journey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bekim, a young man from Firaj, just a mile from the border
with Macedonia, said Friday that Serbian police had given the
villagers an ultimatum last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to the edge of the village and went to the first
families and said `You have two hours to leave the village, and
when we come back if we find you here you know what will
happen &UR; . &LR; '''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the villagers fled. The village is divided into two
parts, and Bekim _ who would not give the rest of his name _ said
the police began burning the northern part on Wednesday. He and
others left, climbing into the hills, but he returned to the
village on Thursday to look for relatives, who had not reached the
border.
</P>
<P>
   But there were only two old men in the village, who resolutely
refused to leave. Bekim said that as he climbed the hill to cross
back over the mountains at 7:30 p.m. he saw the southern part of
the village had begun to burn.
</P>
<P>
   Friday he stood alone on the road at the Jazince border
crossing, watching for a glimpse of his family, his father, mother,
brothers and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Ruzhdi Rexhepi, a 59-year-old farmer, said that after Yugolsav
soldiers burned his village, Bajnici in southern Kosovo, on
Saturday, he and his wife, their daughter-in-law, and three
grandchildren fled by horse-drawn cart to a second village, Raka.
But on Monday, he said, masked Yugoslav police and soldiers
descended on that village too, also burning houses and again
forcing Rexhepi and his family to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Their cart now carried his family and Emrane Raka, 30, and three
children. After fleeing down a main road with other civilians,
Rexhepi said he became worried when Yugoslav police ordered them to
go in the direction of a Serbian village.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing they might be killed, he drove the cart off the main
road and arrived in a deserted ethnic Albanian village, where they
spent the night in an abandoned house.
</P>
<P>
   Rexhepi's family then set out on foot and ran into a group of
roughly 100 Albanians also fleeing toward Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdi Raka, a 12-year-old boy in that group, said the worst
section of the 15-hour-trek was where the path bordered on a
ravine. ``You could fall and be killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, who navigated the path while carrying her whimpering
5-year-old son and holding her 10-year-old daughter's hand, said
her biggest fear was a gust of wind knocking a child over a
precipice. ``The children were blowing like cigarette paper,'' she
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At one point, a woman became ill and her husband stayed behind
with her on the mountain. ``I stopped and tried to help them, but I
had to take care of my own family,'' Rexhepi said. ``I don't know
if they are still up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexhepi and the rest of the group descended into Macedonia on
Wednesday and the local police placed them with 3,000 other
refugees in a sprawling tent city built by German NATO soldiers in
Neprostino.
</P>
<P>
   The pace of expulsions of people from their homes and the
burning of villages does not seem to have slackened in the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Ilazi family was ordered out of their village, Strpce, four
days ago when police arrived, saying ``Leave or we will kill you,''
said Bafti Ilazi, a 70-year-old farmer.
</P>
<P>
   Lying on a cot in Neprostino camp in northern Macedonia, Ilaza
said he knew exactly where to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took three or four blankets because it is cold that way,''
he said. ``We walked through the night, through the Lybeten
mountains. It was cold, we were almost perishing from the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Strpce backs onto Kosovo's highest mountains, near the ski
resort of Brezovica. The walk, through snow nearly 5 feet deep,
took him and his family 20 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the way. I am old and have been around a long time. I
had crossed over on that path before. I had done it eight times
since 1947 to buy wheat in Tetovo,'' he said, describing the ethnic
Albanian town in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   They were nine people in the family, including women and
children, he said. His 25-year-old son had stayed behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not want to leave the cows. I don't know if he will
survive, maybe they will kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Jazince border crossing, Ardita Dila was waving to her
father and husband, trapped behind metal barriers in the no man's
land between Kosovo and Macedonia. She had managed to get through
the border four days before with her small son, but the others had
been waiting nine days, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, an editor of an ethnic Albanian weekly magazine, had
been beaten by Serbs, she said. Yet after the grueling wait to
enter Macedonia, she had bitter words for the Macedonian
authorities, whom she saw as working together against the ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are killing them, like the Serbs, but in a different way.
This is cooperation, there is an agreement between them,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
