<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKCOLLEGE-REUNION10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida's version of Freaknik underway
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The precursor to Freaknik, at least in
terms of controversy, kicked off Friday as thousands of black
college students began swarming Daytona Beach for the Black College
Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, traffic had started to pick up on the beachside's main
strip, Atlantic Avenue, as well as on the beach, where cars are
allowed. Women in bathing suits posed for pictures and guys tried
to outdo each other with the loudest sound system in perfectly
polished cars. Fully clothed women were dunked into hotel swimming
pools, while women yelled up at balconies urging men to strip.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the city's 247 police officers are working this weekend,
and temperatures, which hit 90 degrees on Friday, are expected to
break records.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on and the traffic got slower, some of the
people got wilder. Straddled atop the sunroof of a jeep, one
bikini-clad woman did a seductive dance as the driver slapped her
bottom, while a throng of men videotaped it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't touch her. Don't touch her,'' cautioned one of the
onlookers. ''If you don't touch her, she'll keep on doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Atlanta's Freaknik, lewd, rude and loud behavior _ while
exhibited by just a few of the participants _ is what gains most of
the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are just trying to have fun. We aren't into that crazy,
wild stuff,'' said Jessica Pedrazza, 23, a student at Georgia State
University, who came down with seven other women.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100,000 people expected this weekend in Daytona
Beach, the growing popularity of the weekend beach party threatens
to siphon some of the expected attendance from next weekend's
Freaknik. Some people will travel from Daytona Beach to Galveston
for the Kappa Beach Party, instead of coming to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Pedrazza, who lives in Atlanta, said she is going to Tallahassee
for the Kappa Luau instead of staying home for Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   ''Freaknik is old,'' said Pedrazza. ''We have lived in Atlanta
all our lives and we need something new. I'm tired of it. It is
trite.''
</P>
<P>
   While some students chose not to attend Freaknik, a surprising
number of them assumed Freaknik had been canceled, therefore
eliminating that option altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Alondra Carr, a native of Stone Mountain, Ga., said she and her
friends from Tennessee State University are content with Daytona
Beach and don't plan on coming to Atlanta next weekend either.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is much better,'' said Carr, 21. ''We don't go to
Freaknik anymore because it is too restrictive.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Freaknik, BCR started off humbly enough 15 years ago as a
student party among friends at Bethune Cookman College, which is
located in Daytona Beach, and Florida A&AMP;M State University in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   When it started growing, fear of legal problems pushed Bethune
Cookman withdraw support.
</P>
<P>
   ''After it became community-wide, we were advised by our
insurance company not to give any support, because of the
possibility of a lawsuit,'' said Bethune Cookman President Oswald
Perry Bronson.
</P>
<P>
   Bronson, former president of the Interdenominational Theological
Center in Atlanta, said aside from the possible legal problems that
the event poses, he also has fundamental problems with the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are certain kinds of activities that may be done that
don't lend themselves to good behavior,'' said Bronson, who was in
Atlanta last year during Freaknik and got caught in a two-hour
traffic jam two blocks away from his hotel. ''It is an image that
we don't like for college students. Especially black college
students.''
</P>
<P>
   On an early morning flight from Chicago to Daytona Beach, Rodney
Jones, 24, was too tired to even eat his complimentary peanuts. He
is going to need his rest. He is planning on staying in Daytona
Beach until Thursday, then travel back to Atlanta for Freaknik.
</P>
<P>
   ''After last year, people started coming to Daytona, because it
keeps getting stricter in Atlanta,'' said Jones, who has been to
Freaknik twice. ''There is more to do in Daytona with the beach,
but Atlanta is going to be wild. That is why everybody goes there.
They know people are going to be acting crazy. But I'd rather
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pedrazza and Carr walk the beach, politicians fight and
Jones rests for his busy week, Bronson remains on campus going over
paperwork and holding his breath. ``I'll relax when it is over,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
