</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC REJECTS CHANCE FOR GOODWILL GESTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Slobodan Milosevic chose Friday
not to make a goodwill gesture toward the West by releasing three
captured American soldiers. Instead he used the visit of a Cypriot
politician to make another kind of propaganda point, about the
civilian damage caused by NATO's bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker of the Cypriot Parliament, Spyros Kyprianou, clearly
disappointed, said Friday evening that his mission to free the
three Americans had failed. He effectively blamed NATO itself for
the failure, saying the alliance had not only refused to halt
bombing briefly but had also intensified its attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is well known and it has always been the position of
President Milosevic that bombing should stop,'' Kyprianou said.
``From the moment I announced my initiative to undertake this
purely humanitarian mission for the release of the three Americans,
the bombings were intensified.''
</P>
<P>
   He said NATO should have shown ``at least some respect'' for his
mission, and added: ``Under the circumstances created and the fact
that the message received by the Yugoslav leadership and people is
that the relentless bombardments will continue,'' he said, those
leaders ``can't proceed with a new peace gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou spoke to journalists after meeting with Milosevic.
Earlier in the day, he was taken on a tour of Aleksinac, the
southern Serbian town hit hard by NATO bombs that missed their
target, killing 12 civilians and wounding 40 others. He was also
taken to Cuprija, which was hit on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and American officials had said they would welcome any
unconditional release of the soldiers, but had been explicit in
refusing a Yugoslav request for even a 24-hour cease-fire in the
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou said the bombing should stop, that ``Europe needs
peace'' and that even if the bombing continued ``100 days, it would
not solve the problem'' of the southern Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The three U.S. Army soldiers are Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24,
of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich.; and Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas. They
were captured along the Kosovo-Macedonia border on March 31.
American officials have accused the Yugoslavs of abducting the
three, but the Yugoslavs say the men were captured after entering
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After raising hopes of Americans for a goodwill gesture on the
Orthodox Easter weekend, Milosevic will now have earned himself
even more opprobrium in Washington for toying with the hopes of the
families of the three servicemen. It now looks as if they will be
held until the end of hostilities, Greek officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou's comments, which did not much touch on the plight of
the ethnic Albanians inside and now outside of Kosovo, were sure to
please Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   After his tour of the bomb damage, Kyprianou said the Balkan
crisis could not be solved by force. ``I am not a military expert,
but this is my own view after having heard things from people, and
after my visit to the bombed cities earlier today, where I have
seen things that shocked me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe and the world must understand that this particular
region needs peace, based on justice and morality, peace based on
freedom, respect of borders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Yugoslav officials sent mixed signals about the
three soldiers, with the relatively liberal Yugoslav information
minister, Milan Komnenic, promising ``good news.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-line nationalist Vojislav Seselj, the Yugoslav
deputy prime minister, said the freedom for the soldiers is ``out
of the question,'' because ``the United States is leading an
undeclared war against Yugoslavia.'' He said they should be tried
as terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou said he would stop his efforts for now, because ``it
is impossible to achieve any results in the present climate.''
</P>
<P>
   There was more anger here Friday over NATO's bombing early
Friday morning of the Zastava car and munitions factory in
Kragujevac, in central Yugoslavia. The workers of the factory had
announced that they would form a ``human shield'' to protect the
factory in shifts and remain in the building even during the night.
</P>
<P>
   They rejected a plea from factory managers to leave, and about
124 of them were wounded, some 20 of them seriously, by the NATO
attack, Yugoslav state media said.
</P>
<P>
   About 38,000 workers depend on the Zastava plant. Its munitions
subsidiary was no secret, as is the case with other factories NATO
hit, like the Sloboda factory in Cacak, which Yugoslav officials
insist made only domestic appliances, but which other Yugoslav and
NATO sources said also made ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavs continue to form human shields at night on major
bridges in Belgrade and in Novi Sad, where only one bridge spanning
the Danube has survived allied attacks. While they wait out the
night, they listen to rock and folk songs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2722 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBS-CARS-BOS &LR;      04-09 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBS-CARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT BORDER CROSSING, SERBS CAST EYES ON REFUGEES' CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJI, Macedonia _ Without explanation, Yugoslav border
officials suddenly opened a remote border crossing Friday to a
trickle of ethnic Albanians who had waited for more than a week in
a several-mile-long line trying to flee Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh influx of several hundred refugees brought with them
new tales of forced evictions, burnings and terror as international
human rights monitors voiced growing concern about the fate of
those left behind in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   At the Jevince border crossing, it was a scene reminiscent of
the novel ``Catch 22`` _ except there was no humor in it. It was
coldy executed by the Serbian forces, who ordered the Kosovars to
form two lines alongside their cars on the Serbian side of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Then they ordered one line to return to Kosovo but allowed the
other to pass through to Macedonia, separating families and loved
ones, said aid workers who were watching from the Macedonian side.
</P>
<P>
   They told those allowed to cross the border to leave their cars
behind with the keys in them, and some witnesses told aid workers
that the Serb soldiers then walked along the line of vehicles,
eyeing them and laughing as if they were shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians, clutching the few belongings they could carry,
were at first turned back by the Macedonian border police, but they
relented and finally allowed them to pass through. They scurried
across and were ushered onto waiting buses that shuttled them to a
refugee camp several miles down the road. Some aid workers there
placed the number of new arrivals at about 300, others at closer to
800.
</P>
<P>
   There they confronted their new fate: canvas tents in a muddy
field ringed with barbed wire, where Macedonian troops with
shouldered rifles and cold stares patrolled outside to make sure no
one left the camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their faces were unforgettable. They saw what they were headed
for and the bus grew silent. You could see the men just staring.
The women were crying,'' said Dr. Sheri Fink of the Boston-based
group Physicians for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of other ethnic Albanians are believed to be
still hiding in the woods on the Kosovo side, hoping for a chance
to get across a border that remained mostly sealed, and in some
places sewn with land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, an exchange of gunfire crackled along the
Macedonia-Kosovo border in the ``no man's land'' of Blace.
Macedonian government officials said that a band of armed men had
approached the Macedonian border guards and fired a shot. The
Macedonians returned fire, they said. Sometime later, a single shot
rang out and killed a Macedonian soldier.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO source said that the armed men were probably Kosovo
Liberation Army fighers taking revenge on the Macedonian troops for
their sometimes brutal treatment of ethnic Albanians allowed to
cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   In the camps there were reports of beatings of refugees by the
police, and some ethnic Albanian who live in Macedonia were turned
away from the camps by armed Macedonian police when they tried to
visit family members inside, who could only clutch the barbed wire
fences and tearfully wave to loved ones on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonians are resentful of the influx of ethnic Albanians,
fearing they will upset the delicate ethnic balance in the nation,
which declared independence from Yugoslavia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Friday that they would continue to maintain
a presence in the refugee camps, in part to protect the ethnic
Albanians from the rising violence by the Macedonian forces.
</P>
<P>
   An additonal 8,000 NATO troops were landing in neighboring
Albania on a humanitarian mission to build tent cities and
coordinate aid delivery to the roughly 300,000 refugees who've
amassed in Albania, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sadako Ogata, head of the United Nations refugee agency, said
she feared for the fate of ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo. And
U.N. human rights chief Mary Robinson expressed concern that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was forcibly gathering
refugees as ``human shields'' against NATO attacks. They were said
to be placing the refugees in sites where his army was hiding
military troops and hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian television in Tirana reported that tens of thousands of
ethnic Albanians were trapped by Serb forces in central Kosovo and
threatened with starvation, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   A visibly frustrated Ogata, who toured the camps in Macedonia
Friday, said her organization could do nothing for ethnic Albanians
in Kosovo except continue to bring their plight to the world's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very much concerned for the fate of civilians remaining
in Kosovo,'' she said at a news conference in the capital city of
Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   UN refugee officials Friday also said they had solved the
mystery of the 20,000 refugees who had been unaccounted for since
Wednesday night, when Macedonian authorities suddenly bused away
about 45,000 people who had been stranded in filth and squalor in
the Blace border crossing. They said the 20,000 had been taken,
many against their will, to the Albanian border, where they
gathered in a stadiumm that had been transformed into a refugee
camp.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the UN agency said, just under 517,000 people had
left Kosovo since fighting began there in March last year. It said
the total included 304,000 in Albania, 122,000 in Macedonia and
59,000 in Montenegro.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
