<SLUG> BC-MA-MEDBOARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE MEDICAL WATCHDOG PANEL SLIPS IN US RANKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A new national ranking of medical boards puts
Massachusetts third from the bottom for its failure to take
disciplinary actions against bad doctors. It is the fourth year in
a row the state has slipped in the ranking.
</P>
<P>
   With only 55 disciplinary actions taken by the medical board in
a state with more than 26,000 licensed physicians, Massachusetts
appears as one of the worst states, according to the annual ranking
released Friday by Public Citizen's Health Research Group, founded
by Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   In a note of sarcasm, Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of the Health
Research Group, said, ``Massachusetts has once again done a great
job.'' This latest ranking is the worst since 1991, when
Massachusetts was 48th in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The organization makes its rankings based on the number of
serious disciplinary actions taken for every 1,000 licensed
physicians. Although the report recommends no magic number, The
national average was 3.76, while the No. 1 state, Alaska, had 15.4
such actions in 1998. Massachusetts was near the bottom with just
2.06 actions per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts officials have in the past said fewer
actions reflect better-quality physicians here, recent events
suggest otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent controversy over the medical board's handling
of three doctors facing criminal charges and missing criminal
convictions from its on-line physician profile system, ``it's not
surprising'' to find the board near the bottom again, said Linda
DeBenedictis of the New England Patients' Rights Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board is not doing its job,'' said DeBenedictis, who
founded the patient advocacy group. She said board members should
ask themselves, ``Are we really protecting the public and are we
addressing complaints honestly and fairly to improve care?''
</P>
<P>
   Penelope Wells, acting executive director for the board,
disagreed with the ranking by the Health Research Group, saying
``it's not accurate'' because it compares a state like
Massachusetts, with more than 26,000 physicians, to a state like
Montana, which has fewer than 2,000 doctors.
</P>
<P>
   But, Wells added, she agrees that Massachusetts has slipped
compared to itself, based on statistics just released by the
Federation of State Medical Boards. She attributed part of the
problem to the Legislature's decision to no longer appropriate
$247,000 for the on-line physician profile system, forcing the
board to absorb that out of its regular budget.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the board has had to reduce its complement of four
investigators to the current 2.5 full-time equivalents, she said.
At one point last year, the board had only one investigator, Wells
said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Grabauskas, director of the state Office of Consumer
Affairs and Business Regulation, which oversees the board, said the
slippage is ``probably confirming many of the concerns that I know
the Governor and I have had.''
</P>
<P>
   In his proposed fiscal 2000 budget, Governor Paul Cellucci asked
the Legislature for about $450,000 more for the Board of
Registration in Medicine, to bring the total up to more than $3.8
million, including physician licensing fees, according to
Grabauskas.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts board had been slowly improving in the early
1990s, rising from 48th in 1991 to 37th by 1994. Then the board
began a decline, first to 40, then to 43, then to 45, and finally
to 47 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Research Group does its annual ranking using
statistics compiled by the Federation of State Medical Boards,
which just sent out its data, in advance of its annual meeting
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   But while the federation refrains from ranking the boards, the
Health Research Group takes the information and compares the states
based on the number of serious disciplinary actions taken for every
1,000 licensed physicians. Serious disciplinary actions are defined
as revocation, surrender or suspension of license, and probation or
restrictions on practice.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the ranking by state, however, the federation
figures show that Massachusetts has slipped compared to itself over
the last two years, based on a complicated composite index,
according to Wells. Given the resource cutbacks, ``It's not really
a surprise to us,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
