<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-TROOPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BAY STATE RESIDENTS OFFER HAVEN DURING CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ In a country with only one highway, only one
commercial airstrip and only one partially developed movie theater,
it seems fitting that there is just one set of Massachusetts
license plates.
</P>
<P>
   Less expected are its owners. Chris Dakas, once a police officer
in Worcester, Mass., came here with his wife Laura seven years ago
on a calling to help Europe's poorest _ and once most xenophobic _
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the crumbling country exploded with hundreds of
thousands of Kosovar refugees, the Dakas' found themselves on the
front lines of the worst humanitarian crisis in the continent in
more than a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   Their downtown apartment became a clearinghouse for refugee
workers. Their red Cherokee became an aid transport vehicle. And
their Mexican restaurant _ the only non-smoking restaurant in
Albania _ became a hub of information for a flood of humanitarian
workers on their way north.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there have ever been this many foreigners in
Albania at once,'' Laura, 49, said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there were few when the couple arrived in Tirana
shortly after the fall of Communism and well before the few signs
of modernization now sprinkled throughout the capital.
</P>
<P>
   They said they came on a calling from God _ and on Chris'
retirement plan from the Worcester police department _ and have
since tried to carve a ``safe haven'' out of an otherwise violent
region.
</P>
<P>
   There is still virtually no infrastructure in the country, save
the 700,000-odd concrete bunkers along the gravel roadways or
beaches, where soldiers once hid awaiting an attack from the
``capitalist running dogs'' from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The country is still desperately poor, in part thanks to pyramid
schemes, sanctioned by the previous government, that collapsed in
1997. It is still extremely dangerous, thanks to the military
weapons looted by civilians during the violent uprising then.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first got here, Josif gave me a warning,'' said Chris,
51, referring to the native Albanian who has been his closest aide
for seven years. ``He said, `If you are going to survive in
Albania, you need to know one thing _ don't trust anyone. Not even
me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And he was right. You can't be a liberal in Albania and last
more than three or four days.''
</P>
<P>
   It is into this environment that hundreds of thousands of
Kosovars have fled, many of them leaving quiet villages and routine
jobs, many driving decent cars and wearing nice, middle-class
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   They are, in many ways, as unprepared for the Albanian way of
life as any American might be _ speaking a different dialect,
bearing a different set of values, the couple said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Southerners and the Northerners,'' Laura said,
with a native New Englander's drop of the r.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Dakas' have begun to build a bridge between Albanian
and ethnic Albanian, driving from refugee camp to refugee camp with
supplies and volunteers. They've gathered enough foreign donations
to support six refugee centers in the port city of Durres, and
they've organized local volunteers in Tirana to entertain children
in the camps with puppet shows.
</P>
<P>
   They've made the eight-hour drive to the border town of Kukes,
where thousands of refugees first arrived. Friday, Chris drove to a
mattress factory outside Tirana, carrying $2,700 in US bills to pay
for 300 foam mattresses and ensure they were being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live by faith,'' he said, watching men in masks pour hot
foam into metal boxes to form the rudimentary beds. ``We spend the
money we've got and we hope the donations will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   In Durres, where several hundred Kosovars have recently arrived
into makeshift shelters, Chris was greeted by the mayor _ a robust
man who smiled and pumped Chris' hand up and down in gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Arqile Gorea had agreed to give the Dakas' control of
several municipal buildings. They, in turn, are managing nearly
1,000 of the 30,000 refugees in the port town, shipping tons of
flour and food into the 170,000-person community, trying to prevent
the instability that many outsiders fear will take over the region
as a result of the influx of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Gorea said it was a ``big, big thing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple do not presume they will help more than a fraction of
the refugees. Laura has informally adopted 28 Kosovars _ ``I am
like their mother'' _ bringing them kitchenware and cash. But she
has declared that her cutoff point for personally caring for
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, they are ad hoc parents to scores of
Americans as well _ relief workers, diplomats, journalists. The
Dakas' have opened the doors of their mission, Qendra Stefan, to
explain the quirks of the nation that many until recently could not
find on a map.
</P>
<P>
   Chris, who became a Christian at age 32, and Laura, say a prayer
before each supper, asking for guidance for the refugees.
Afterward, they retire to bed, locking the giant door to their
mission, which Josif described as ``safer than Fort Knox.'''
</P>
<P>
   But they say they never think of getting out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
