<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 11)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Profitable Broadening For the Boss' Portfolio  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How do you send a chief executive's compensation soaring if his
own company's shares are merely doing well? In the case of SBC
Communications, one of the Baby Bells, the board's answer seems to
have been to sweeten the pay of its top executive, Edward Whitacre,
with shares in a hot telecommunications software company he doesn't
even run.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a 1998 pay package worth $15 million, including
SBC stock options, Whitacre received a ``special retention award''
of $12.5 million worth of units, at the initial offering price,
representing stock in Amdocs Ltd., in which SBC has a 23 percent
interest.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Amdocs has been the better performer,
with a return of 60.7 percent, compared with 29.2 percent for SBC,
since Amdocs went public on June 19.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear why so much of Whitacre's pay should be tied
to the returns of a company that has only a slight impact on SBC's
overall performance, said Graef Crystal, editor of
crystalreport.com an Internet newsletter on executive compensation.
Amdocs has about $400 million in annual sales, less than 2 percent
of SBC's $28.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Paying an executive in another company's stock ``is a pretty
rare practice,'' Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
   If SBC's goal was to reward Whitacre with a hot stock, as
Crystal speculates, he wonders why the board did not simply give
him shares in Amazon.com, an even hotter performer. Though SBC has
no stake in it, Amazon.com, ``has about as much relationship to SBC
as a whole as does Amdocs itself,'' Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
   SBC explained in its proxy statement that it paid this bonus to
ward off ``inquiries and offers from competitors'' for Whitacre's
services and that it chose Amdocs units because the Amdocs
investment, which was made under Whitacre's management, had been so
good for SBC and its shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The Amdocs public stock offering coincided with the decision to
award Whitacre the shares, according to SBC general counsel James
Ellis. ``There was no expectation that Amdocs would grow faster
than SBC,'' he said. ``It was more or less a timing issue.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By REED ABELSON
</P>
<P>
   But Does She Do Windows?
</P>
<P>
   When Jack Rudin, the New York real estate executive, and his
wife, Susan, wanted some help with the yard work, they called on
Bette Midler. It helps that the yard is Central Park and that Ms.
Midler has an apartment facing it. At a party last week honoring
contributors to the Central Park Conservancy's Perimeter
Association, for which Mrs. Rudin is co-chairwoman, Ms. Midler
provided the star power.
</P>
<P>
   She thanked the group for restoring six miles of sidewalks and
other surroundings in a park that Rudin likes to call ``New York's
front lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By C.J. SATTERWHITE
</P>
<P>
   Biting Hands Before They Feed Him
</P>
<P>
   For a man in search of a foreign partner to contribute capital
and skill to his struggling bank, Masao Nishimura, the president of
the Industrial Bank of Japan, is a surprisingly vocal critic of
Western companies and their financial advisers.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, he accused Jurgen Schrempp, the
head of DaimlerChrysler, of violating the terms of a contract with
Nissan Motor Co., one of IBJ's biggest and most troubled clients,
and otherwise excoriated the business tactics of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   In March, DaimlerChrysler walked away from a deal with Nissan,
which then concluded a pact with Renault. Nishimura said the timing
of an announcement by Schrempp had conflicted with the terms of a
contract with Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   IBJ spokesman Hidehiko Ogawa said Friday that Nishimura was
raising questions about Schrempp's disclosure of a meeting with
Yoshikazu Hanawa, the president of Nissan, as a possible violation
of the usual secrecy of merger talks. (Never mind that the original
leaks about the talks emerged from a Nissan plant in Britain.)
</P>
<P>
   There was no conflict between Nishimura's comments and the
bank's search for foreign capital, Ogawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Nishimura also took to task Goldman Sachs, DaimlerChrysler's
adviser during the Nissan talks, suggesting that it might have had
a hidden agreement with another American investment bank, J.P.
Morgan, which was advising Nissan. ``I think it is possible the
foreign firms together made a secret deal behind the scenes,''
Nishimura said. He did not elaborate, but Goldman and J.P. Morgan,
both of which had no comment, could have been expected to make a
good deal more money had the deal gone through.
</P>
<P>
   Nishimura's mention of Goldman was particularly surprising since
he had been saying that Goldman would participate in a joint
venture with IBJ and Nomura Securities in pension fund management.
Goldman is only one of the foreign financial companies that IBJ has
approached for new money to replace the capital being eaten away by
its bad debts.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Nishimura described foreign financiers as a rather
rapacious lot. ``Foreign firms simply overcharge you,'' he said,
adding that they ``come here to take a shot at a corporate deal and
make quick profits, but they do not care about what may happen to
the companies involved after the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered the example of an insurance company seeking to
demutualize, saying that a foreign adviser would charge fees of
about 3 million yen, or $25 million at current exchange rates,
while IBJ would do the job for a third of that price.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHANIE STROM
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
