u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-YOUTH-$ADV11-2TA     04-09 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-YOUTH-$ADV11-2TAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I DIDN'T HAVE A GRAND PLAN,' BUSH SAYS OF HIS YOUTH IN HOUSTON (2
TAKES) 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, April 11) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ President Clinton cherishes his Arkansas town called
Hope. President Reagan was misty-eyed about life in little Dixon,
Ill., and President Carter spun stories about his farm in Plains,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas Gov. George W. Bush tells his story as a candidate
for president, though, it will include a central chapter on a place
that is anything but romanticized small-town America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, with a family pedigree and a Yale University
undergraduate diploma that might have opened doors anywhere in the
privileged world, Bush flew home to the nest in Houston with no
long-term goals under his wings.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was his off-and-on hometown for 15 years that included
the social and political spasms of the 1960s _ an era that Bush
says has soiled the moral fabric of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was where he bounced restlessly from a downtown
corporate job to social work in black neighborhoods, from flying
military jets over southeast Texas during the Vietnam War to
working in political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Now he prides himself on reaching out politically to minorities,
and he faces questions about what his military policies would be as
he takes his campaign experience nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was where he raised a little hell on the party circuit,
became engaged and broke it off, faced the expectations of an
accomplished and wealthy family, used family connections to land a
variety of jobs and, in a cock-sure way, avoided designing a
strategy for his life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a leading contender for the White House, he faces a
thorough examination of his personal behaviors and ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a grand plan,'' Bush said about his Houston
years in an interview last week. But, he added, ``I don't think the
plan will ever be clear. I didn't sit down dreaming about running
for president. I have been a bit more spontaneous in my
decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said famously that he was ``young and irresponsible''
in his youth. He has refused to answer questions about whether he
used marijuana or cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   But friends and acquaintances from the time say that in Houston,
Bush sat out much of the wild personal experiments of the 1960s.
They say he was responsible to the extreme in his hometown, that he
was steeped in the formality of a well-off life and that he cut
loose only in the context of a single man who drank and liked
single women.
</P>
<P>
   There is one suggestion that Bush shared in his generation's
rebelliousness, chafing against the politics of his father, former
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Houston art supply dealer Benton Russell said that George W.
Bush, a Republican who calls himself a compassionate conservative,
dabbled in left-wing causes and campaigns in Houston while his
father served in the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   As the liberal Peace and Freedom Party candidate in the 1970
U.S. Senate race, Russell pushed for women's rights and minority
rights and thought marijuana should be legalized. His opponents
were Bush's Republican father and Democrat Lloyd Bensten Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned vigorously for his father. But Russell said Bush
at the same time helped organize voters for the Peace and Freedom
Party and for the cause of electing progressives to the Houston
school board.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just liked our issues better than his father's,'' Russell
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he has no recollection of that ever happening,
and that he would have done nothing to undermine the candidacy of
his father, for whom he has shown vigilant love and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not wax nostalgic on how Houston shaped him as he grew
from a young teen-ager to a college graduate and a white-collar
worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Bush said. ``I'll leave how I was formed to the
psychoanalysts. Obviously Houston had an impact on me because I
lived there for a period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was born in 1946 in New Haven, Conn., home of Yale
University, where his father earned a degree.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his birth, his father moved their family to Midland,
Texas, to start an oil business. Bush says he picked up a sense of
pioneer optimism in the remote Midland-Odessa area of Texas near
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Moving again for business opportunities, the family arrived in
Houston in 1959, the year Bush turned 13. He had attended public
schools in Midland. But in Houston, his parents enrolled him for
two years in the prestigious, private Kinkaid School. Following his
father's path, he later attended high school at Phillips Academy in
Andover, Mass., and college at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Houston for most of the summers, working during
his college years as a sporting goods salesman at the Sears Roebuck
and Co. store on Main Street, as a clerk at a downtown brokerage
firm and as an oil field roughneck in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967 _ the year Dustin Hoffman starred in a ground-breaking
film, ``The Graduate,'' about an upper-income college man straining
against his family's expectations _ Bush became engaged to Cathryn
Wolfman of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up, like Bush, in the upper-crust Tanglewood area of
west Houston. She attended Smith College in Northampton, Mass.,
like Bush's mother. After being injured in a sledding accident at
Smith, Wolfman transferred to Rice University in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Within six months of the engagement announcement, however, ``we
just grew apart,'' Bush said. ``I was crazy about her, but we
decided not to get married in between my junior and senior year in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the breakup, Wolfman got married in Houston. She
did not return recent calls from the Chronicle to her home in Palo
Alto, Calif. In an interview with The Dallas Morning News, she was
no more specific than Bush about the reasons for their break-up.
</P>
<P>
   Bush finished work toward a history degree at Yale in May 1968 _
one month after the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and
three months after Yale student body leaders signed an Ivy League
manifesto saying they were ``seriously considering or have already
decided to leave the country or go to jail rather than serve in
(the war in) Vietnam.'' Bush was not among the signers.
</P>
<P>
   With no chosen career and no plans to attend graduate school,
Bush _ the son of a World War II Navy pilot who became a
congressman _ no longer had a student exemption from the Vietnam
War draft. He faced a choice of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your options either were to avoid the draft or sign up, and I
signed up,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
