<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROOPS MADE THE DIFFERENCE IN US EFFORT IN BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton was deciding whether US
warplanes should lead a NATO bombing effort to resolve the Kosovo
crisis, his advisers predicted that it could be just as effective
as the airstrikes that helped end the Bosnian conflict in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, the bombing pushed the Serbs to sign a peace
agreement. But now, the airstrikes have hardened Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's resolve and resulted in a mass expulsion of
ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Why hasn't the bombing halted the conflict in Kosovo as it did
in Bosnia? There are a number of reasons, but foreign policy
experts say the biggest difference comes down to a key issue facing
Clinton: ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bosnian war, the Bosnian Muslims and the Croatians had a
formidable, well-equipped, well-trained army that was in the
process of pounding the Bosnian Serbs into making a peace
agreement. The NATO bombing then helped persuade the Serbs to seal
such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``In Bosnia, yes, we bombed for 20 days,'' Brent Scowcroft,
national security adviser to former President George Bush, said in
an interview. ``What no one remembers is the bombing was
accompanied by a massive offensive by the Croatian army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air power played a role that it normally does,'' Scowcroft
said. ``The number of times that air power alone has made people
change their minds _ I can't think of any.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, where NATO bombing entered its 17th day Friday, there
has been nothing like the Croatian army on the ground. Instead, a
poorly equipped group of rebels loosely gathered as the Kosovo
Liberation Army already was in retreat before the advancing Serbs.
By the time the NATO bombing began, the KLA was in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference is that the smaller Bosnian Serb army fought
for Milosevic in Bosnia, while the larger and better-equipped
Yugoslav army is carrying the battle in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely different,'' said Kurt Bassuener, associate
director of the Washington-based Balkan Action Council, which
advocates using ground troops in the current conflict. ``In Kosovo,
you don't have forces comparable on the ground as a counterweight.
You are trying to completely counter Serbian forces on the ground
with air power.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials publicly said they knew all
along that the situations in Bosnia and Kosovo were different.
Clinton has said that he had no choice but to act for humanitarian
reasons, and that he doesn't want to send ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president was getting advice that Milosevic would back
down in the face of airstrikes as he had done in Bosnia,'' said
Michael Hammer, a spokesman for the National Security Council at
the White House. ``But there was also a very clear-eyed view that
if he did not back down quickly, we would be prepared to follow
through until he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration continues to hope that relentless bombing,
including the battering of Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital,
eventually will persuade Milosevic to back down. While Milosevic
has declared a cease-fire, administration officials said the offer
is meaningless unless the refugees, along with international
peacekeepers, can return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is different from Bosnia for other reasons. Unlike
Bosnia, which was divided among several ethnic groups, Kosovo had
an overwhelming ethnic Albanian majority, at least before the
refugee exodus. Before the war, as few as 7 percent of the
residents of the province were Serbs, according to some estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians indicated in a 1992 vote that they wanted
Kosovo to merge with Albania. At that time, Milosevic was
proceeding with ``ethnic cleansing'' in Bosnia, expelling many
non-Serbs in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overwhelming Albanian majority in Kosovo, Milosevic
has said he views the province as the ``heart of Serbia,'' a claim
he did not make about Bosnia. The Serbs lost a 14th century battle
in Kosovo to the Turks, an epic defeat that today is glorified by
many Serbs. Kosovo also has five historic monasteries considered
important to Orthodox Christian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point of view of Serbian nationalist philosophy,
Kosovo is where Serbia became a nation, so Serbs say that Kosovo is
to them as Jerusalem is to the Jews,'' said Barnett Rubin, senior
fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations. ``Some mordant or
sardonic Serbs say they will do anything for Kosovo but live there.
Albanians have lived there for hundreds of years.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bosnia, Rubin said, it doesn't have the same symbolic
importance. ``It is a place where Serbs live, but it is not the
cradle of their nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer, the White House official, said Clinton's advisers were
well-aware of the meaning of Kosovo to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an understanding that Kosovo is more dear and near
to Milosevic's heart than Bosnia,'' he said. ``Clearly, these are
different situations. All these things were being factored into the
decision to use military strikes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
