r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME&AMP;GARDEN-CHAIRS10-     04-09 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME&AMP;GARDEN-CHAIRS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artists, designers create artful thrones for charity
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough about Y2K. Samuel Battle is ready to put all
technological year-end angst behind him.
</P>
<P>
   So the architect has designed one burned-out, slightly frazzled
chair for ``Chairish the Future,'' the sixth annual gala and
auction benefiting the Metro Atlanta Furniture Bank on April 25.
</P>
<P>
   The chair is festooned with computer parts, from cables and
disks to keyboard and mouse, and sprayed with chrome paint to give
it a 21st-century techie look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing that everybody's scrambling to address the problem, I
wanted to build something that empathizes with the complexity of it
all,'' said Battle of Ai Group Architects. ``The computer, as you
know, has evolved over the past 15 years, but the basic form, size
and shape of the chair is still the same and has not evolved like
the rear ends of many of my fellow Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece, with ``Y2K'' emblazoned like red graffiti across its
dome back, is among 120 chairs designed by Atlanta-area interior
designers and artists, professionals and students, to be auctioned
at Lenox Square. Last year's event raised more than $37,000 for the
nonprofit furniture bank, which distributes furniture to the needy.
This year's goal is $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got some really professional-looking chairs, in
terms of the depth of detail and quality,'' said Thomas Burr, event
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the event, sponsored by the Georgia chapter of
the American Society of Interior Designers, start with a blank
canvas, many of them unfinished chair frames donated by Shelby
Williams Industries. From there, they are limited only by their
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Barber, a student at the Atlanta College of Art, spent 26
hours gluing Lego blocks onto the seat and legs of a chair to
create the Lego Candy Machine Chair. The back has been replaced
with a contraption through which M&AMP;Ms can be deposited; the candy
then trickles onto the seat. ``Since I have seven grandchildren, I
have much experience with Legos and candy,'' her artist's statement
reads.
</P>
<P>
   There are also:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paul Domini's hand-painted A Place for Cleopatra's Asp, a
replica of the famed imaginary chair made for the queen's snake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alisa Lewis' Tourister Chair containing old decoupaged
postcards, white feathered wings and a 1960s American Tourister
suitcase _ the inspiration for the piece.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tinka Green's The Key to the Mystery, a wooden chair with the
Greek key design, autographed phrases containing the word ``key''
(Key West, key hole, Francis Scott Key, skate key, Key lime pie)
and a collection of brass and metal keys dangling from hooks.
</P>
<P>
   Minimum bids range from less than $100 to more than $6,000. And
to sweeten the pot, a dozen national furniture manufacturers,
including Knoll, Bernhardt and PierceMartin, have donated chairs _
the totally functional kind, said J.Ed. Marston, the furniture
bank's assistant director.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because furniture, as a whole, is part of the art
community.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   ``Chairish the Future'' gala and auction
</P>
<P>
   Where: Lenox Square, Neiman Marcus wing, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   When: 8 p.m. April 25. The chairs will be on display for silent
bidding from April 19 to the day of the gala, when the most
sought-after entries will be sold during a live auction.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $70, or $60 in advance; includes an open bar and food.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-355-8530, Ext. 223.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
