<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2734 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-09 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS, KLA UNITS EXCHANGE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Fighting broke out along the border of Albania
and Kosovo early Friday and lasted throughout the day as Serbian
forces and Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas exchanged machine gun
fire and mortar shells.
</P>
<P>
   Several mortar shells landed in Albanian territory early in the
morning, and four loud explosions were heard late afternoon in the
most serious frontier skirmish since NATO bombing of Yugoslavia
began, said Andrea Angeli of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe. Friday night Yugoslavia briefly opened the
border _ to expel about 2,000 ethnic Albanians who had been forced
from their homes in the wartorn Kosovo province, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   The shifting border situation reflected a day of escalating
military action and diplomatic tensions, a day that also saw the
collapse of a Cypriot attempt to free three American soldiers held
captive by Yugoslavia since March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Among Friday's developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon said it had ``a reliable report'' that young
Kosovar women had been herded into a military training camp at
Dakovica, in southwest Kosovo, and systematically raped by Yugoslav
soldiers. As many as 20 women may have been killed, a Pentagon
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kremlin denied reports that President Boris Yeltsin had
ordered Russian strategic missiles be targeted at NATO countries
taking part in the air war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO officials confirmed that one of its bombs aimed at a
telephone center in Pristina, Kosovo, accidentally fell on a
residential neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   _ Senator John McCain, an Arizona Republican, said the Senate
will debate the issue of ground troops next week and ``talk about
what it takes for us to win this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Cyprus' acting president, Spyros Kyprianou, met for
90 minutes Friday with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic but
said he came away ``disappointed,'' believing the severe NATO air
campaign had hurt his chances for obtaining the US soldiers'
release. ``The intensified heavy bombing of the last couple of days
made my humanitarian mission more difficult,'' said Kyprianou,
Cypress's acting president.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials insisted there would be no negotiation to free
the soldiers, and President Clinton said Milosevic's promise of a
cease-fire over the Orthodox Easter weekend was a ``half-measure''
that NATO had to reject. ``What we have from Mr. Milosevic today is
not even partial compliance but the illusion of partial
compliance'' with conditions for an end to the NATO bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic still thinks he can manipulate the situation by
cynically using innocent people,'' Clinton said at the White House.
``He hopes that we will accept as permanent the results of his
ethnic cleansing. We will not.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said, ``Milosevic's actions have strengthened the
unity and resolve of the allies.'' But it was clear the White House
was disturbed by reports that Yeltsin, a harsh critic of the
bombing campaign, had discussed targeting nuclear weapons at NATO
allies and was threatening military action in support of the Serbs
if NATO deployed ground troops in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright got assurances Friday
from Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov that Moscow did not intend to get
involved militarily in Yugoslavia, said State Department spokesman
James P. Rubin. Neverthless, Rubin said Albright would meet with
Ivanov Tuesday in Oslo to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials dismissed Belgrade's claims that it was
observing a cease-fire, and for the first time US officials charged
Serb forces with a specific atrocity: the systematic rapes of
ethnic Albanian women in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very eerie and disturbing echo of documented
instances of rape and killing of women in Bosnia during the Bosnian
war, and it is obviously outrageous,'' said Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth H. Bacon, noting that US officials would attempt to confirm
the story, which was based on a single, ``reliable'' report.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also announced the deployment of six more F-15C fighters
and an extension of the USS Inchon's tour in the Eastern
Mediterranean to support the NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the weather deteriorated Friday, NATO pressed its
relentless air attack on military-industrial plants, fuel depots,
and communiciations centers around Belgrade and on Serbian forces
in Kosovo. On Thursday night a storage depot at Smederevo, 18 miles
from Belgrade, was hit, as was a factory at Kragujevac, which NATO
said produces military materiel as well as the Yugo automobile.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman David Wilby, air commodore of the British Royal
Air Force, said the military campaign inside Kosovo was ``moving in
the right direction'' but is difficult and far from finished.
``This is not an easy operation,'' Wilby said. ``We're up against a
wily enemy. He's beginning to dig in....It is quite difficult to
spot him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said one NATO bomb dropped Wednesday ``was seduced off the
target'' _ Pristina's main telephone exchange building _ and landed
in a small civilian neighborhood nearby. On Thursday, Wilby denied
Serb reports that NATO bombing had destroyed civilian sites and
killed 10 people in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said NATO intelligence noted a buildup of Serbian forces
north of Kosovo, but he could not confirm reports of fighting
between Yugoslav forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces have exchanged fire with local Albanians along
the border in the past, but Friday's skirmish was ``different
because of the context,'' Angeli said. ``There has been fighting
before, but a full day like this we haven't seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Angeli could not confirm official Albanian reports that four KLA
members were killed near Tropoje, just south of the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army accused Albania of ``aggression'' and said KLA
supporters would ``have to bear the consequences for the eventual
flare-up of the war in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees report that the KLA, which has set up training camps in
Albania's mountains, recently recruited hundreds of new members as
refugees crossed the border from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials expressed fears about the fate of the ``car
people'' _ Kosovars in a 12-mile line of autos along the border who
abandoned their cars when the frontier was sealed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know where the people are,'' said Jamie Shea, a NATO
spokesman. ``Perhaps they have crossed over into Albania on foot,
perhaps they have been turned back inside Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimates as many as 200,000 Kosovars are homeless inside
their land, living in the woods and the mountains. Red Cross and UN
relief workers have not been allowed access to them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Kosovo, the refugee situation is slowly improving, Shea
said, as more camps have been set up or are being planned in
Albania and Macedonia, and large supplies of food, water, and
medical supplies are reaching the refugee centers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, several hundred refugees from the region were
airlifted to Germany, Turkey, Norway, Switzerland, and Bulgaria.
More than 400,000 refugees have fled Kosovo since the NATO bombing
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Mary Leonard reported from Washington; Anne E. Kornblut reported
from Tirana, Albania. Wire service material was used to prepare
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
