<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2735 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN10-COX     04-09 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My garden on the go thrives in state of flux
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Whenever I point out to visitors the various plants
that have been shifted here and there in my garden, I always note
that they get moved so much they ought to be on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Their growing too large for the space, my miscalculation of the
light, and just plain poor design _ the wrong place for the plant _
are among the reasons for these rough moves.
</P>
<P>
   I say rough because I long ago stopped moving plants gently; as
many times as I have to do this, I look for expediency, which means
digging just enough around an established tree or shrub to pry it
out of the ground without losing too much of its root support.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know such moves may make the transition more difficult,
but I also have learned that plants are a lot tougher than I once
thought.
</P>
<P>
   That fine reality shows itself graphically in the Japanese black
pine that I moved a couple of years ago. After several years on the
sunny side of the house, the tree outgrew the space, threatening to
branch out into the driveway. I had thought a while about moving it
but didn't get seriously motivated until I was about to leave home
for a party one Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Hastily and with care not to trash my party clothes, I ripped
the unsuspecting tree from its longtime home and thrust it into a
new hole. Watering it in, I lamented the 90-degree day and my
inability to wait for cooler weather, but sometimes a change just
comes over you. I hoped I hadn't made my move too soon. So far the
pine stands as a poster plant for surviving against the odds.
</P>
<P>
   I've moved several plants in search of some way to make them
bloom. A rose with no name seemed to be getting enough sun, but
still it seemed stifled by surrounding plants, including juniper,
pine, blue balloon flower. Last year I moved it a few feet, to a
more open spot, and now I see buds.
</P>
<P>
   Lilac took a much longer trip _ to McCaysville (Ga.), a hundred
miles away. But not before it had gotten moved a couple of times in
my Atlanta garden.
</P>
<P>
   Many gardeners from up North tell me that lilac is the plant
they miss most when they move down South _ despite the wealth of
scented plants thriving in this region. Lilac just won't bloom
here, they say.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen successful lilac plantings around Atlanta, but not in
my garden. I lost a couple despite coddling them mightily, adding
lime to their soil; they declined mysteriously.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I decided to move one from sun to light shade. After a
couple of springs it was still alive but showed no signs of
blooming. So, I moved it to another, cooler section, on the north
side of the house. Still nothing. Last fall, I moved it to
McCaysville, having heard that the North Georgia mountain climate
is more New Jersey than Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise and delight this week, I noticed little bud
clusters, looking like green caviar.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether the lilac was fooled into thinking it was
north of the Mason-Dixon line or whether it just got tired of
getting moved. Whatever, this long-sought success is enough to keep
my garden on the go.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of gardening moves, I can't contemplate any without
thinking of how, after years in Saturday's paper (and Friday's
before that), this column is heading for Thursdays. See you then.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
