<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-YOUTH-$ADV11-2ND     04-09 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-YOUTH-$ADV11-2NDTAKE-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH-YOUTH-2ND TAKE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (UNDATED: Bush said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Bush did not directly sign up for combat in Vietnam. Before
leaving Yale, Bush signed papers for entrance into the Texas Air
National Guard unit at Houston's Ellington Air Force Base. While on
call for possible participation in the war, the unit flew fighter
planes over southeast Texas, said former commander and retired Gen.
Walter Staudt, now of New Braunfels, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush earned certification as a pilot and was never called to
war.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he joined the unit, rather than volunteer for Army
combat duty, because he wanted to learn how to fly jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going into the military and would have liked to
come out with a skill,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Staudt said he had met Bush's congressman father while serving
as a member of a Houston Chamber of Commerce aviation committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Staudt, like the governor, said no one exerted influence to
get Bush into the unit _ and that none was needed. Few applicants
offered the time commitment and the intelligence required for
admission into pilot training, Staudt said, so Bush was a
more-than-qualified candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Staudt said he never questioned the motives of prominent young
men who enlisted in the Guard rather than ask to be sent to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the stuff hit the fan (in Vietnam), the whole unit would
have gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush trained at bases in San Antonio, Texas, and Valdosta, Ga.,
while the Woodstock music festival in upstate New York captured the
``free love'' spirit of his generation. Bush returned to Houston in
1969 as the flier of single-seat F-102 planes, made in 1953, and
flew routine, local missions for the unit through mid-1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got behind it in the cockpit, you realized how serious it
was,'' Bush said. ``It required obviously a certain amount of
skill, and a lot of focus and attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's routine release from full-time Guard service allowed him
to dive into his father's 1970 Senate campaign. He traveled the
state giving speeches on his father's behalf, helped coordinate
college interns for the campaign and, on one occasion, strolled
shirtless behind his father on a charity walk, smirking in the
Houston heat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was supremely confident, according to New Mexico
businessman Dan Gillcrist, who was the 1970 campaign's scheduler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where you get that (confidence), but I see it in
others,'' Gillcrist said. ``I had brothers who were fighter pilots.
They just know when they get up there, they are going to kick ass.
And that's one of the characteristics I would chisel in stone for
(Bush). Some people see that as cockiness, but it's in the eye of
the beholder. I just think he knows what he can do, and he has no
reservations about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush lived then at Chateaux Dijon, an apartment complex near
Houston's upscale Galleria shopping area. The complex was known for
its singles scene, which included water volleyball games in its
swimming pools. Gillcrist said he saw Bush take a hearty approach
to his social life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you want a president who was some kind of person who
never left his room? He had fun and partied and raised a little
hell like the rest of us,'' Gillcrist said. He added that Bush was
``a normal young man'' who didn't pass up the opportunity to flirt
with any attractive single woman he met at a party.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush enjoyed single life, he hurt deeply for his father
when he lost the 1970 Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing his father absorb the defeat and move on with his
career helped him take the plunge as a first-time candidate eight
years later, the governor said. Bush lost a U.S. House race in west
Texas in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   After his father's 1970 campaign, Bush moved to a garage
apartment on tree-lined North Boulevard near Rice University.
Sampling the coat-and-tie corporate world that fit many Yale
graduates of the time, he went to work for Stratford of Houston, an
agricultural company owned by Robert Gow, who had attended Yale and
roomed with a Bush relative.
</P>
<P>
   Four years before hiring Bush at Stratford, Gow was an executive
at the Houston oil company run by Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   Gow, still a Houston entrepreneur, said he hired Bush because
the young man was qualified for management training.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father had been good to me in the sense that he had hired
me,'' Gow said, ``but there was no sense that I owed them
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was dispatched alone to Ohio, Pennsylvania and other states
to size up plant nurseries Gow wanted to acquire. Gow said Bush was
a highly responsible worker, ``a buttoned-down Brooks Brothers
type.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was restless. Gow said the two talked repeatedly about
how Bush could make a contribution to society in ``a nonbusiness
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ensenat, who roomed with Bush at Yale and on Houston's
North Boulevard in 1971, said Bush was a high-energy, outgoing,
``never boring'' young man who was secure in the fact that he would
eventually find inspiration for his life's work.
</P>
<P>
   Ensenat said that although he and Bush probably were
conservative for their age group, illegal drugs were available in
their social circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was there if you wanted to do it, but he didn't, as far as
I know,'' said Ensenat, now a New Orleans lawyer who has remained
close to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1973, former Houston Oilers football player John White
hired Bush to help run the Professional United Leadership League,
which turned athletes into mentors for poor African-American boys.
A press release from the time indicates PULL got off the ground in
1970 with financial grants from ``a few benevolent supporters'' _
especially Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong sports fan in search of a personal mission, Bush
forged a special bond with boys whose Houston upbringing in no way
resembled his own, said Ernie Ladd, a retired Houston Oiler who was
on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the first real white boy that all of the kids really
loved,'' said Ladd, now of Franklin, La.
</P>
<P>
   But in less than a year, Bush packed his bags again, giving up a
Houston address for the last time. He was accepted into Harvard
Business School, and White, the PULL founder who has since died,
urged him to go, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said White told him, ```Look, if you are really
interested in helping people, the best thing to do is to go to
Harvard Business School, and make some money, and come back and
help people.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bush graduated from Harvard in 1975 with a master's degree in
business administration. Retracing his family's steps, he moved to
Midland. He got into the oil business and married.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he moved to Dallas, becoming general managing partner
of the Texas Rangers baseball team. He won the governor's race in
1994 and 1998. By June, he is expected to hit the presidential
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tells voters that it's time for a ``responsibility era''
that holds individuals accountable for their actions and rejects
the 1960s-style blame-society approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really believes there was a cultural change in the '60s,
and he sincerely believes we can have that change back,'' former
Bush aide Dan Shelley told the Chronicle last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's thinking as a presidential candidate, therefore, will
hinge largely on the time he spent in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
