<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIANS-CHILDREN-BO     04-09 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIANS-CHILDREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL EFFORT MADE TO REUNITE CHILDREN, PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many ethnic Albanian children have become separated from
their parents that human rights groups have set up emergency
stations in Macedonia's refugee camps to reunite them, according to
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable and terrible situation,'' said Randy
Ackley, an American Red Cross worker based in Macedonia. ``Matching
these unaccompanied children with their parents is our top
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers also are using computer databases, radio broadcasts,
and Polaroid cameras to trace separated family members. ``There
isn't anything more imperative than rejoining the children with
their parents,'' said Stephen Lewis, deputy director of the United
Nations Children's Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Officials don't know how many children have been separated from
their parents but believe the numbers could run into the thousands.
Human rights workers have fanned out into the camps, handing out
leaflets and announcing on megaphones that parents who can't find
their children should register at the tracking tents.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two days, 450 parents have registered at the
stations. Some parents stop in with few, if any, documents
identifying their children. So they describe their children's
clothes or birth marks _ anything to help workers find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are registering all types of details of the child _ their
age, maybe even a behavioral problem,'' Lewis said. ``When you set
up a tracking tent, it's like a magnet.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Fullemann, a spokesman for the International Committee of
the Red Cross, estimated that 100 people a day are reporting a
missing relative. ``But the focus right now is trying to find the
parents of the unaccompanied children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many families were separated when waves of ethnic Albanians fled
Kosovo, rights workers said. Other children were lost this week
when thousands of refugees abruptly were herded onto buses and
taken to neighboring Albania. Some were torn from their families
when assigned to other camps or were lost inside their own
encampments, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Sadako Ogata, the UN high commissioner for refugees,
gently turned back an ethnic Albanian boy who ran up to her in the
Brazda camp, the first to set up a tracking station. The boy wanted
to know when he could go back to Kosovo. ``I would like to go there
too,'' Ogata told the boy, the Associated Press reported. ``We can
go back when we could go there safely.''
</P>
<P>
   Children woh remain in Kosovo apparently are trying to get out,
UNICEF said in Geneva. About 50 children already had come through
the border on the Albanian side on bicycles, using trails,
spokeswoman Marie Heuze said. ``It's very worrying because the
children are in a state of shock and can't tell us what has
happened to their families,'' she told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Many children are being cared for by other refugee families or
have been taken in by native Macedonians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a suspended nightmare for the children,'' Lewis said.
``It's very sad and traumatic and intensely important to get these
children reunified right away.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem, he said, is that Macedonia has made it difficult
for refugees to travel between camps, preventing some family
members from finding one another. But UNICEF has been using a
children's rights treaty, signed by the Balkan nations, to gain
more access to camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
