A2738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-DENIAL-BOS &LR;      04-09 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-DENIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAB DRIVER DENIES HE HOLDS $197 MILLION LOTTERY TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Patrick Okusanya, the Nigerian cab driver who has been
hiding since speculation spread three days ago that he won the $197
million Big Game lottery, hired a lawyer Friday to tell the world
he did not win.
</P>
<P>
   Okusanya walked into the Mattapan office of attorney Dane M.
Shulman at about 3 p.m. and pleaded with attorney John M. Ricci to
help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He described it as the horror of his life,'' Ricci said.
``People don't believe him when he says he didn't win. He's getting
phone calls from his family in Nigeria. He's being hounded by
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci and Okusanya talked for an hour in the lawyer's office,
and afterward Okusanya went to work _ but not at Town Taxi, the
garage that dispatches his cab. Ricci said it's unclear where
Okusanya was working, and that the two never talked about why
Okusanya hadn't returned the taxi _ and why he didn't speak up
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery of who won the lottery now grows, with some people
wondering if Okusanya is just trying to deflect attention by hiring
an attorney, and others wondering if the real winner is someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation about Okusanya being the winner started after
lottery officials announced Wednesday that the winning ticket in
the six-state Big Game was purchased at the Star Market in the
Fenway. The Town Taxi garage is about three blocks from the
supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the taxi firm's vice president John Ford was
telling reporters that he had heard that Okusanya had won from two
cab drivers who told him they had seen the winning ticket outside
Logan International Airport. That story seemed to grow as the hours
passed and Okusanya did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the lottery should give him some money for the
aggravation he's gone through, or somebody should,'' Shulman said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At a house Friday, where a man named Patrick Okusanya allegedly
lives, a woman who identified herself as his girlfriend yelled from
a window, ``He's not the winner. He's not the winner. He's going to
make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   And earlier in the day, a man who identified himself only as
Patrick, left a message on a Globe reporter's voice mail saying:
``My name is Patrick. You have been going around telling people I
won the lottery. Please, I want you to stop it. For my security
reason. Stop going around telling people. For my security reason,
please. Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   A dispatcher at Town Taxi said Friday that Okusanya still hadn't
returned the taxi.
</P>
<P>
   As the speculation about Patrick Okusanya spread this week, so
did variations about his family. Many people who worked with him
said he was married and had several children and lived in Chelsea,
a Boston neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman, the owner of the law practice, which specializes in
personal injury cases, said Okusanya came to his office because the
firm had represented him in the past. He declined to say on what
kind of case.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if perhaps Okusanya could be lying to keep his winnings
private, Ricci said he doubts Okusanya would do such a thing. Why
did the cabbie disappear for a time? Ricci says he just got scared
when the speculation began.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci said it wasn't until Okusanya's full name appeared in the
Boston Herald on Thursday that he decided to come forward to dispel
the speculation. Ricci said Okusanya never even had a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is really going through hell,'' Ricci said. ``He is
being paraded around the news as being the winner of the ticket.
People are hounding him and making his life impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lottery spokeswoman Susan Frigoletto said Friday that
the agency has not commented on the speculation about Okusanya
because ``until somebody shows up with the ticket in their hand,
you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever has won the jackpot has a year from the Tuesday drawing
to claim the prize.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Joanna Massey contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
