</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN-10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PENTAGON BEGINS MAJOR ESCALATION OF MASSIVE BOMBING CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    EDS: Optional trim at 800
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD and BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon, beginning a major escalation in the
massive bombing campaign against Yugoslavia, ordered six F-15C jet
fighters to Europe on Friday and made preparations to send some 50
additional warplanes to join the NATO air armada, a sign that the
allies are planning a protracted air war.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hopes evaporated Friday for the early release of
three U.S. soldiers captured by Serb forces along the Macedonian
border. Spyros Kyprianou, the acting president of Cyprus who had
hoped to negotiate their release in the Yugoslav capital of
Belgrade, blamed the failure of his mission on continued NATO
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's call for more warplanes came amid confusing but
nonetheless eyebrow-raising warnings from Russian President Boris
Tylosin of ``a European war or even a world war'' if NATO ground
forces are sent into Yugoslavia. Hours later, the State Department
said it had received Kremlin assurances that Russia will not get
involved militarily in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It also came as a barrage of allied air strikes on Orthodox Good
Friday targeted Yugoslavia's military-industrial complex as well as
supply and communication lines to the Serbian police and military
units _ the forces allegedly responsible for atrocities against
ethnic Albanians driven from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But after four relatively clear nights that created near ideal
conditions for NATO bombing, heavy clouds and fog impeded air
strikes as the conflict entered its 18th day on Saturday. Even so,
Gen. Sir Charles Garthis, the British chief of defense staff,
declared that the Serbian forces in Kosovo are ``on a slippery
slope'' as they are increasingly targeted by NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials made new allegations of atrocities Friday, citing
``disturbing reports'' that young Kosovar Albanian women had been
raped and up to 20 killed at a Serb army training camp near
Dakovica in southwest Kosovo, a province in Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very eerie and disturbing echo of documented
instances of rape and killing of women in Bosnia during the Bosnian
War,'' Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters. ``And it is
obviously outrageous that this is occurring.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bacon said the rape allegations came from credible
sources, there was no immediate independent confirmation. In
neighboring Bosnia, Serbs frequently used rape as a tool of terror
against Muslim women during three and a half years of fighting
there.
</P>
<P>
   In another troubling mystery, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told
reporters in Brussels that the alliance had verified a line of
abandoned cars some 12 miles long inside Kosovo near the Albanian
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know where the people are,'' said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Serb troops sealed the Albanian border early Wednesday, turning
back another group of thousands of ethnic Albanians who were
fleeing Kosovo and were forced to return to the embattled province.
Serb troops spent much of Thursday sowing land mines near the
border town of Morina.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has estimated that more than 600,000 ethnic
Albanians have fled Kosovo to take refuge in the neighboring
republics of Macedonia, Albania and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we believe that there may be about 150,000 to 200,000
people in Kosovo currently living without shelter in the woods and
on the mountain slopes,'' said Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the F-15C's dispatched to NATO on Friday are in
addition to dozens of other fresh warplanes already requested by
U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander. They would be
added to the 600 NATO aircraft waging ``Operation Allied Force.''
</P>
<P>
   The F-15C's, scheduled to deploy from Elmendorf Air Force Base
in Alaska, perform air-to-air combat missions to protect bombers
during air raids.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Defense Secretary William Cohen is expected soon to
approve the additional planes, some 50 in all, including bombers,
jet fighters, radar-jammers and refueling tankers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's reinforcement of Clark's air armada came as
President Clinton, accusing Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
of presenting an ``illusion of partial compliance'' with NATO
demands, insisted on the ``unconditional return'' of the hundreds
of thousands of ethnic Albanians driven from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said NATO is determined to ``persist and prevail'' with
air strikes despite Milosevic's unilateral cease-fire and closure
of borders to prevent refugees from fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic still thinks he can manipulate the situation by
cynically using innocent people,'' Clinton said in brief remarks at
the White House. ``He hopes that we will accept as permanent the
results of his ethnic cleansing. We will not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hard line and the barrage of NATO air strikes across
Yugoslovia on Friday were blamed by Kyprianou for his failure to
gain the release of three U.S. soldiers held by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia ``cannot resort to any peaceful gestures'' regarding
the American prisoners of war, Kyprianou said after a meeting with
Milosevic. ``It is impossible to achieve any results in the present
climate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, which has demanded the unconditional release of
the soldiers, was not surprised by the results of Kyprianou's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic atmosphere was muddied even more by Yeltsin's
televised remarks during his meeting with the Communist speaker of
the State Duma, the lower house of parliament, Gennady Seleznyov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have already told NATO, Americans and Germans: Don't force
us to take military action, since that will certainly lead to a
European war or even a world war, which is inadmissible,'' Yeltsin
said. ``Russia will not get involved in the armed conflict in
Yugoslavia unless the Americans force us into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov also caused a diplomatic stir when he said after the
meeting that Yeltsin had given the command to re-target the nuclear
missiles ``against those countries which are carrying out military
action against Yugoslavia.'' Seleznyov later backed away from his
remarks, saying he had only discussed the possibility of re-aiming
the weapons, and the Kremlin and military commanders denied Yeltsin
had given the order.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unilateral truce declared by Milosevic, there were
reports that machine gun exchanges between Serb forces and Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) guerrillas on the Albania-Kosovo border
escalated Friday into artillery shelling that killed four
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no indication whatsoever that the Serbs have ceased
fire,'' on the ground in Kosovo, said U.S. Air Force Gen. Charles
Wald, vice director for strategic plans for the U.S. Joint Chiefs
of Staff. ``They don't seem to be stopping their movement on the
Kosovo Albanians in Kosovo. And there are actually some reports of
atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash of Serbs and remnants of the KLA rebel force occurred
some 185 miles north of the Albanian capital of Tirana. It was the
first on the border for almost two weeks and erupted as the United
States prepared to fly in Apache anti-tank helicopters to Albania
to beef up NATO's air campaign against the Serbian soldiers
scattered in small units across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, which also borders Kosovo, reported Friday that its
forces had fired into Yugoslavia after a Macedonian soldier was
shot to death on the border with Kosovo a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
