<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-BEETLES-ART-2ND     04-09 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BEETLES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: than $5.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another factor in depressing prices has been the gray market in
imported beetles. Ohkuwagata also live elsewhere in Asia, and when
Japanese ohkuwagata were selling at outlandish prices, travelers
began to smuggle foreign ones into Japan. One advantage of the
foreign ohkuwagata is that they stay active year-round, while
Japanese ohkuwagata hibernate for several months in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Importing foreign beetles is illegal, but selling those that are
already in Japan is of uncertain legality. In any case, the imports
began to trade hands and depressed the market just as it was
collapsing anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smugglers would put threads on their ohkuwagata and tie them
up, and then put them in with their souvenirs,'' said Daiichiro
Koseki, an ohkuwagata breeder who sells foreign varieties. ``Or
they put them inside their clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   One might suspect that Japan is using the ban on beetle imports
to protect its own bug market, just as it curtails rice imports to
protect its own rice industry. The Japanese insect industry denies
that is the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not protectionism,'' said Hiroshi Fujita, editor of
Gekkan Mushi, which translates roughly as Bugs Monthly. ``It's to
protect ecology, because the fear is that the foreign beetles would
disrupt Japan's environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujita also said that the ohkuwagata market was too small for
Japanese bureaucrats to worry about. The whole market in Japan for
insects and accessories, he said, has annual sales that run only in
the tens of millions of dollars, although some estimates run into
the billions.
</P>
<P>
   While the bug market is now severely depressed, Tobu Department
Store still has one pair of ohkuwagata priced at $12,500 for the
two. They are so expensive because they have white eyes, a rarity,
but so far there have been no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Ohkuwagata live for four or five years, so owners have some time
to enjoy their pets _ some other kinds of beetles live a year or
less _ and they do not fly much, so an investment is unlikely to
disappear out the window. But of course owners have to look where
they step.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to watch them when you take them out for a walk,''
said Misaki, the insect salesman, with a nod to his $12,500
beetles. ``Otherwise, they could run away and disappear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
