u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-957&AMP;A     04-09 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-957&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARNS RUSSIA AGAINST GIVING MILITARY ASSISTANCE TO SERBS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF,
KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(ac) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The United States has quietly warned Russia
against providing military intelligence or assistance to Belgrade,
senior Western officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential warning follows bitter complaints from Moscow
about NATO's airstrikes and the Kremlin's decision to dispatch a
Russian spy ship toward the Adriatic, where the American aircraft
carrier Theodore Roosevelt and other alliance ships have been
participating in the air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials, a senior Western official said, ``have been
told that any effort by them to intervene in a militarily
significant way could have very serious consequences.'' The allies
have not said what these consequences could be. But evidence that
Russia was helping Belgrade would undermine public support in the
West for loans to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, while critical of
NATO, has pledged to stay out of the of the conflict in Yugoslavia.
But Friday he said that he would reconsider that position if NATO
troops entered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said that the message from the United States _
and similar warnings by Britain and other allied nations _ were
delivered before Yeltsin assailed NATO again Friday, insisting that
it refrain from sending group troops into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings from the West, officials said, were prompted by
demands by Russia's parliamentary deputies that it share
intelligence with Yugoslavia, provide arms, send military advisers
or even volunteers to fight.
</P>
<P>
   So far, a senior Western official said, there is no proof of any
such cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The caution comes as the already wide gap between NATO and
Russians over Yugoslavia appears to be widening.
</P>
<P>
   NATO says its airstrikes are needed to force a halt in the Serb
ethnic cleansing in Kosovo, and facilitate an agreement on autonomy
for the ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO's bombing has compounded the sense of weakness and
humiliation many Russians feel following their nation's fall from
superpower status. Many Russian nationalist and Communist
politicians have expressed support for the Serbs and have little
sympathy for the plight of the Kosovar Albanians, whom they view as
Muslim separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, for his part, has sought to soothe nationalist
sentiment regarding Yugoslavia while maintaining good relations
with the West, no small consideration given Moscow's effort to seal
a new loan agreement with the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's earlier appeals that NATO avoid airstrikes were
ignored. So Friday, Yeltsin sought to draw a new line in the sand,
saying that Russia would rethink its decision not to intervene in
the Yugoslav conflict if the alliance launched a ground operation
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia will not interfere in the armed conflict in Yugoslavia
if American does not push it to do that,'' Yeltsin said. ``They
want to use ground troops, take over Yugoslavia, make it their
protectorate. We cannot allow this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Yeltsin was referring to a land invasion,
which NATO has already ruled out, or whether he intended to refer
to a different scenario in which a NATO-led force might escort
ethnic Albanians back to Kosovo. The latter approach appears to be
NATO's basic game plan for now, though Western diplomats are
reluctant to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia's vitriolic words have far outstripped its actions,
it has taken several steps that concerned military specialists
here.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov, for example, brought two senior
intelligence officials with him when he went to Belgrade last month
for talks: Colonel General Valentin Korabelnikov, the head of
intelligence for the Russian military, and Vyacheslav Trubnikov,
the head of Russia's Foreign Intelligence Service, heir to the old
KGB.
</P>
<P>
   That raised the possibility that Russia might provide Belgrade
with intelligence about how to fight the West. Russia's defense
minister, Igor Sergeyev, also accompanied Primakov, who previously
served as the head of the Foreign Intelligence Service himself.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a Russia intelligence ship, the Liman, left the
port of Sevastopol soon after Primakov's visit in a step that
Russian officials described as a response to the allied airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Poland in 1972, the surveillance ship is now steaming
around the north Ionian Sea, just south of the Adriatic, NATO
military officials said. A flotilla of ships, which Russia also
talked about sending to the Adriatic, has yet to leave the Black
Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The political sensitivities surrounding the dispatch of the
Russian spy vessel may exceed its military capabilities. Even
Pentagon officials are divided over its military significance.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Pentagon official described the ship as a giant
electronic ``sponge,'' which is designed to intercept the
communication by allied warships.
</P>
<P>
   This official said it was possible the Russians dispatched the
ship to learn about Western military operations for the benefit of
their own military. He said it was not clear whether the Russians
had the capability to quickly digest the information and pass it on
the Yugoslav military.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said the ship was of concern to allied military
planners.
</P>
<P>
   Other Pentagon officials, however, offered a less worrisome
assessment, noting that the United States had grown accustomed to
operating in international waters near Russian reconnaissance ships
during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not overly concerned about it,'' Rear Adm. Thomas
Wilson, the director of intelligence for the military's Joint
Staff, said in an interview. ``We can deal with it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vice Adm. Mikhail Barskov of Russia, the deputy chief commander
of the Russian Navy, said earlier this month that the ship was sent
``just to monitor the situation.'' Russian navy officials have said
they expect NATO to use electronic jamming to try to thwart the
Liman's electronic snooping.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any indication that the Russians were using the ship to
try to help the Yugoslav military could deal a major blow to
American-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   For all the Russian complaints, both sides still seem to be
trying to prevent an even greater deterioration in American-Russian
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Seleznyov, the Communist speaker of the parliament, who
recently returned from a trip to Belgrade, insisted Friday that
Yeltsin had decided to re-target its nuclear missiles against the
United States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the United States have agreed to stop aiming their
nuclear missiles at each other in a largely symbolic understanding
to help reduce tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said nothing about such a step and later Friday Russia's
foreign minister, Igor Ivanov, said no change in targeting had been
ordered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
