u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TOURISM-700&AMP;AD     04-09 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TOURISM-700&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL TO SOME PARTS OF EUROPE STARTING TO BE HURT BY KOSOVO
CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Conn., Fla., Kan., Ky. R.I.)  (Eds., this story, eliminated earlier, is now restored) 
(See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(rk) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Balkans conflict and refugee crisis have started to hurt
leisure and business travel well beyond the combat zone, with
increasing numbers of Americans scrapping or delaying plans to
visit Europe during what ordinarily would be one of the best times
to go.
</P>
<P>
   Travel agents and tour operators say they have received
cancellations not only to Central and Eastern Europe, which is much
closer to the conflict, but also to popular destinations like Italy
and Greece and as far as Russia and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Sobered by television coverage of the nightly NATO bombings in
Serbia, the misery of Kosovo refugee families and anti-American
demonstrations in countries that support President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia, would-be American visitors to Europe are
deciding to make other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sister in Bologna, Italy, and we were thinking of
visiting her this summer,'' said Juan Sabalones, the director of
animal husbandry at the Newport Aquarium in Newport, Ky. ``But as
long as there's a war going on, I've decided to keep an eye on
things, and it's possible we may not go at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour operators say they have already noticed a small but
unexpected increase in bookings to the Canadian Rockies, South
America, Asia and America's national parks, which they attribute to
customers deciding against traveling to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tauck, president of Tauck Tours, a big tour operator with
headquarters in Westport, Conn., said that while people were still
traveling to popular Italian and Greek vacation spots, ``we've had
cancellations this week, and the pace of bookings is suddenly
relatively flat.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, Tauck said, there were 42 bookings this week for
the company's three tours to Italy this year, compared with about
100 bookings for Italy in a normal week this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kang, the president of Maupintour, another big tour
company, in Lawrence, Kan., said that he had seen little effect on
tours to Turkey and Greece, but that ``bookings to Italy are
unexpectedly slow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I can think of for that is that people see
Aviano on CNN, and they know it's a staging area in Italy,'' he
said. Aviano is the site of a NATO air base used in the bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Many tour operators quickly postponed tours through Yugoslavia
when the crisis began building last month and detoured trips when
NATO began bombing on March 24. But now they are canceling tours
months into the future on the assumption that the conflict will
last a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Maupintour canceled two 16-day cruises that were scheduled to go
from Bucharest, Romania, to Vienna, Austria, through Belgrade and
other points in Yugoslavia, departing May 25 and June 2. Regina
Tours, which specializes in Catholic pilgrimages, canceled its
monthly 10-day tours to Medjugorje, Bosnia, through the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even National Geographic, which specializes in relatively
adventurous tours, decided to postpone until this fall a tour to
Turkey that had been scheduled from April 26 to May 12, and to
cancel its Treasures of Russian Waterway, scheduled from May 28 to
June 10. While the Russian tour was canceled because of concern
over turmoil in the Balkans, the Turkish tour was postponed over
concern with recent terrorist bombings in the country attributed to
Kurdish terrorists, National Geographic said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the Association of Corporate Travel Executives issued a
``cautionary travel advisory'' warning members about traveling not
only to danger zones but also to other European cities. ``The PR
campaign waged by Serbian nationalists,'' said Earl Foster,
president of the 2,500-member association, ``has led to some
violent street protests in cities far from the battle. We're
advising our members to alert their travelers to these related
situations, specifically with an eye to avoiding them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the recent travel disruptions are not at all as widespread
as those surrounding the Persian Gulf War in 1991, the travel
industry's big concern is that the Balkans conflict could drag on
toward summer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The concern comes at a time when both the American economy and
the warming weather make it a particularly good time to visit
Europe. The dollar is strong, American incomes are rising, and many
people are spending money.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the evidence of a potentially serious slowdown in
travel to Europe is largely anecdotal. There are still signs that
travel to Europe remains little affected by the Balkans conflict.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. airlines said Friday that while there had been some
cancellations to central and Eastern Europe, on routes flown by
their European partners, there had been few cancellations to
Western European cities. ``April and May bookings are good,'' said
Tim Smith, a spokesman for American Airlines, ``and bookings for
the summer indicate those months will be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Joseph Buhler, the U.S. chairman of the European
Travel Commission, said its member tourist offices in several
countries in the immediate region of the hostilities had reported a
slowdown in bookings, with scattered cancellations. But overall, he
said, members reported ``relatively little adverse impact on travel
to Europe as a whole due to the fighting in Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   To forestall cancellations, the cruise industry moved quickly to
keep out of harm's way. Three Cunard Line ships and two belonging
to Seabourn Cruise Lines _ both companies are owned by Carnival
Corp. _ substituted stops at Italian ports on the west coast of the
Adriatic for the previously scheduled stops at Dubrovnik and other
Croatian ports along the eastern Adriatic. Windstar Cruises has
substituted stops in Italy for scheduled stops in Dubrovnik and
Rab. Holland America's Maasdam replaced Dubrovnik on three European
itineraries with stops in Italy and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've only had 15 or 20 cancellations,'' said Erik Elvejord, a
Holland America spokesman, ``but we've had a couple of hundred
calls from people concerned about those itineraries.'' He added
that bookings were lagging for the 12-day Venice-to-Venice
round-trip cruise, scheduled to depart April 19.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials say the reason the current fighting has not
depressed travel as much as during the Gulf War, when bookings on
U. S. airlines decreased 44 percent on trans-Atlantic routes in
1991, is that there is little fear of terrorism in connection with
the Balkans conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But most travel officials believe that a Balkans-inspired
terrorist incident in the West would set off a wave of airline
cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this turmoil and the demonstrations continue for a long
time, Americans are going to be afraid to go anywhere in Europe,''
said Predrag Krivokapic, whose Kompas Holiday International agency
in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., specializes in travel to Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Other travel officials agree. ```Especially if it's on TV on a
daily basis,'' said Tom Souza, executive vice president of Collette
Tours in Pawtucket, R.I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
