<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS ACTIVE AHEAD OF THE DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it won't actually take place until  &UR;  &LR; April 17, the
National Football League's annual draft really begins Saturday
morning with the New England Patriots waiting anxiously to see what
is going to transpire the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to call Chris Palmer (Saturday) and see what it is
going to take to get up to the first pick to take Ricky Williams,''
said Saints general manager Bill Kuharich. ``If we can't make a
deal there, then we will call Philadelphia, Cincinnati,
Indianapolis, and Washington, all the way down the top five
picks.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is the head coach of the Cleveland Browns, who have the
first pick. New Orleans is willing to give up its entire draft, and
either more picks or players next year, to get into position to
take Williams, the Heisman Trophy-winning running back out of the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots would like to move up and get into position to
select Williams, but the Saints' proposal will just about take them
out of the running. However, most teams, including the Patriots,
rate Miami's fine running back, Edgerrin James, just a shade below
Williams. The Saints want to drop their explosive package as close
to the top as they can. Cleveland isn't quite sure what it wants to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, general manager Dwight Clark wants Williams, and
Palmer prefers Oregon quarterback Akili Smith. However, the
``organization'' (as in the opinion of all scouts, assistant
coaches, etc.) likes Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch. The Browns are
supposed to be sending a contingent of 11 people to work out Couch
Sunday morning; that workout will determine which direction they
go.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, picking second, seems intent on keeping the pick
and using it on a quarterback. There is a feeling that the Eagles
like Donovan McNabb of Syracuse over either Smith or Couch.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati, picking third, wants a quarterback, and didn't send
anyone to Williams's final workout last Tuesday in San Diego.
Although scouts from other teams in attendance didn't think
Williams worked out well (slower than expected and didn't catch the
ball well), Kuharich wasn't disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just what we thought it would be,'' he said. ``He had
been on a diet losing weight (20 pounds). He weighed 224, ran in
the mid 4.5s, which is about where we expected he would be. We like
him for what he did on the football field, and that has not
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a first, according to the NFL, for a team to give up
all of its picks on draft day. The guessing is that the three top
teams will keep their picks, but that the fourth and fifth teams,
Indianapolis and Washington, will be open to trades.
</P>
<P>
   If the Saints make the deal they want with Indianapolis, this
could open the door for the Patriots to make a trade with the
Washington Redskins. Washington traded its first and third picks
this year, and a second next year, to Minnesota for quarterback
Brad Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have extra picks in the first, third, sixth, and
seventh rounds. This extra ammunition would seem to give them
enough to make a deal to get into position to take James, and in
return, give the Redskins enough picks to allow them to have a full
draft this year. Washington will be willing to listen. Unless
something surprising happens, the top six picks, in some order,
appear to be Williams, Couch, Smith, McNabb, James, and defensive
back Champ Bailey. Bailey is the Deion Sanders of this draft. He
figures to be the first defensive player drafted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry Sinden has just about made his mind up to back away from
the day-to-day duties of general manager and turn them over to Mike
O'Connell. Sinden would keep his title as president, and be
involved on the business side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to step away and cut back on what I was doing a
couple of years ago,'' said Sinden Friday. ``But then we finished
last and that changed my mind. I gave myself a couple of years to
help get the team turned around and headed in the right direction.
I feel like that has happened. I'll meet with (owner) Jerry Jacobs
when the season is over and I'll see how he feels about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden is very concerned with the financial condition of the
league, especially the franchises in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know there is trouble when you see Montreal struggling,''
he said. ``That would be like the New York Yankees struggling down
here. They gave up two of their best players, (Vincent) Damphousse
and (Mark) Recchi, because both of them were going to be free
agents at the end of the year and they couldn't afford to sign
them. Did anyone ever think they would see the day that something
like that would happen in Montreal? The rate of the currency up
there and the lack of tax breaks that the government gives to other
businesses, has put several of those franchises in serious
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our financial picture doesn't change, you could see some of
those teams going out of business and that would have a terrible
impact on our league. It would be a disaster. But right now, there
doesn't appear to be anything going on that would stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This memory came back with the death of Hall of Fame pitcher
Early Wynn this past week. Wynn needed one more victory to reach
the coveted 300-win plateau. Early in the season he came to Boston
and was a guest on the Dick ``Dr. Strangeglove'' Stuart show. This
was circa 1965 and Stuart had a 30-minute show Sunday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an honor and privilege for me to be in the lineup
when you get No. 300,'' Stuart told him, to which Wynn responded
with a smile, ``I hope you are too, Stu, and that I strike you out
four times.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart was with the Red Sox and Wynn was not, so in essence, he
was saying to Wynn, ``I hope you beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flutie was on the end of a Magic Johnson ``pass'' recently.
Johnson had been contracted to make a speaking appearance at Salem
State for $30,000. (Don't these schools have anything better to do
with their money?) However, shortly before the agreed-upon date,
the college reportedly got a call from a ``new'' agent, who said
Magic's fee was now double, $60,000. At this point, thankfully, the
school took a pass and reached out for Flutie . . . A person on the
inside of the recent Redskins ownership fiasco says Patriots owner
Bob Kraft negotiated the settlement between wannabe-owner Howard
Milstein and the NFL. The league owners were ready to vote down
Milstein again this past week and were fearful of a lawsuit. But
Kraft developed a plan whereby Milstein would get his $30 million
back from the trustees of the Redskins in return for not suing the
league and dropping out of the Washington ownership picture
completely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lou Gorman told a luncheon gathering at the Bostonian Hotel the
other day that when he was the Red Sox general manager, he almost
traded Roger Clemens as part of a nine-player deal ``that would
have completely turned our franchise around.'' Gorman says the deal
fell apart when the owner of the team he was making the deal with
didn't want one of his players in the deal and pulled him out.
Gorman says he will give more details in a book he is writing and
hopes to have published in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The University of Massachusetts is hoping that the rumor in the
western part of the state is true: that Adam Harrington would like
to come home and play basketball for the Minutemen. Harrington, who
played at tiny Pioneer Valley Regional High School in Northampton,
was the most highly recruited player in the state last year. He
signed early with North Carolina State, averaged 11 points a game
as a freshman starter, but now reportedly is pulling out of school,
and looking to play ball somewhere else. UMass would love to have
him . . . When Kenny Anderson gave Rick Pitino some lip, and the
Celtics coach didn't like it, there wasn't a lot more he could do
than sit him out for a game. You can't fine a player for mouthing
off, or loafing on defense in the NBA. It's against the collective
bargaining agreement, which has yet to be delivered in full to the
league teams. The Celtics are a long way from winning anything
because their point guards cannot defend up top, and Boston might
also have the worst defense under the basket in the league. That's
a hard combination to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been talking to Scott Zolak about coming back
next year. Zo wasn't too happy when he read after the season that
the team considered Tom Tupa its backup quarterback last year . . .
Go figure: The Montreal Expos got $15 million from major league
baseball's sharing plans (big-money teams contribute to help
smaller-market teams) and spent $12 million on this year's payroll.
How do they get away with that? . . . When Williams lost 20 pounds
in six weeks, he had to give up one of his favorite foods,
doughnuts. So when his workout for the pros was over Tuesday in San
Diego, his friend arrived with a dozen, and Ricky responded. When
he had had his fill, there was one left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
