<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEAR MISS ON TRADE AGREEMENT MAY HAVE STEMMED FROM CLINTON'S
DISTRACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(ac) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a bitterly cold day in Beijing in early January,
Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, was given a
startling message by Zhou Rongji, the Chinese prime minister who
was remaking the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite China's economic slowdown, Zhu said, he had decided that
China was finally ready to offer huge openings of its markets _ in
telecommunications, banking, insurance and agriculture _ in return
for getting the country into the World Trade Organization. He
offered some tantalizing details, apparently hoping that Greenspan
_ whose own portfolio has nothing to do with trade _ would make
sure the right people in Washington got the message.
</P>
<P>
   They did, and over the next three months the two sides made
enormous progress, resolving 95 percent of the issues that had
divided them for years. But in the end, President Clinton, the man
who has repeatedly made commercial diplomacy the centerpiece of his
foreign policy, backed away. Distracted by Kosovo, he did not let
his trade negotiators know how badly he wanted a deal, officials
close to the talks said. Nor did he make a strong public case for
what would have been the biggest economic deal in Chinese-American
relations until Zhu's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his top foreign policy aides, led by National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger, hoped for an agreement that would bolster
Zhu, whom they see as China's leading force for openness and
reform. At a meeting last Saturday, some State Department and Trade
officials argued that China had moved as far as it could, and the
president should take the deal on the table. But one official said
that there was ``a sense it won't quite do it'' with a Congress
that is increasingly suspicious of China's intentions. Others
expressed fears that any deal involving China would further divide
Democrats, enrage labor unions and end up in a huge battle on
Capitol Hill that the president would likely lose.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some argued, the congressional battle would itself
create a rallying cry for Republicans seeking an outlet to debate
charges that China has stolen nuclear secrets and surreptitiously
donated to Democratic coffers.
</P>
<P>
   In a major speech about China delivered the morning before his
meeting with Zhu, the president declared that ``if China is willing
to play by the global rules of trade, it would be an inexplicable
mistake for the United States to say no.'' Many of Clinton's
closest aides took that as a sign that the debate was over, that
the deal was done. They proved to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell what the long-term impact of Friday's
failure to reach a deal may be. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin,
who appeared in no particular hurry about striking an agreement of
this scope, insisted Friday that in the coming months a deal ``is
certainly doable.'' The U.S. trade representative, Charlene
Barshefsky, insists that ``we still want a deal, Zhu wants a deal,
and I'm sure it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But without question, momentum has been lost. A fear now is
that, once Zhu gets back to Beijing, the deal could unravel. Trade
negotiations are like a carefully staged opera, one that can come
to a rousing conclusion only after the most careful stagecraft. In
this case the singers were playing to very different audiences, and
the last act never came off.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, worried about the effects of a defeat on the rest of
his legislative agenda, apparently decided at the last minute not
to push Zhu at that Wednesday night meeting for a last flurry of
concessions. And Zhu was clearly worried that he already had given
too much. If he agreed to strict provisions that would give the
United States unilateral rights to retaliate against import surges,
and that would offer more protection to the American textile
workers by extending for years strict quotas on the volume of
textiles China can send to the United States, he would be subject
to enormous criticism from other Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen the president back away like this,'' one
veteran of trade negotiations said Friday. ``We're all still
scratching our heads.''
</P>
<P>
   By some measures this could be a prime example of how one of
America's most critical diplomatic initiatives fell victim to the
distractions of a war in the Balkans. Clinton has long argued that
WTO membership for China is not about economics, it is about global
integration. It gets China into a legal framework, forcing it to
work under Western-style trade laws. It creates huge market
openings that will, in time, expose more Chinese for foreign ideas.
And by spreading cell phones and Internet nodes in China, the West
helps create more outlets for political expression _ outlets the
Chinese government finds it increasingly difficult to control.
</P>
<P>
   So when Greenspan returned to Washington in January with his
message, Ms. Barshefsky, leaped at the opening. She sent her top
China negotiator, Robert Cassidy, to Beijing for what turned into
weeks of negotiations. In the first week of March she traveled to
Beijing herself, and spent two and half hours with Zhu.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first hour I talked non-stop,'' she said. ``And it was
clear that great progress was being made.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time the Chinese were talking about sweeping away
many of the barriers that had long stymied American farmers _
limits on agricultural imports, and requirements that they only
distribute their goods through state-owned companies. There was
talk about letting American firms invest in the telecommunications
industry for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came in dribs and drabs,'' one person involved in the
negotiations said. ``We would push, and we were often surprised
that the Chinese came back and said, `We can do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the Zhu visit here was the deadline, and everyone knew
it. But in the interim, a lot had changed in Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
