<HEADER>
A2754 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-2TAK     04-09 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: a lot had changed in Washington. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suspicions that China had obtained the design of the W-88
warhead, the most miniaturized in the American nuclear fleet,
created a new atmosphere on Capitol Hill and the White House found
itself under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the negotiating table, the Chinese kept giving.
``My overall sense is that the Chinese conceded more than I thought
would be politically possible,'' said Nicholas Lardy, an expert on
the Chinese economy at the Brookings Institution. ``You have to
remember that unemployment is at a 30-year high in China, corporate
profits are falling off a cliff, and here is Zhu arguing that this
is a moment to actually allow the foreigners to offer more domestic
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger argued that this was a moment to support Zhu, making him
the man who brought China the prestige of entering the global
trading system. Clinton seemed inclined to that view, and his
speech on Wednesday was filled with a discussion of America's
interests in both an economically stronger and more secure China.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the White House, there was less talk about the
dangers of a weak China than the dangers of an agreement that labor
unions, liberal Democrats or powerful senators from textile
producing states _ like Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and Ernest Hollings,
D-S.C. _ could use to rally opposition. The two men had already
introduced a bill to give Congress a clear vote on any deal.
(Indirectly, Congress has that already, because it would have to
amend the law allowing an annual review of China's trading status.)
</P>
<P>
   And there were other unhappy interest groups with strong
connections to the White House. China insisted on limits on the
import of Western films _ meaning that Hollywood might seek to kill
the deal. Nor would the Chinese allow American brokerages much
access to the rough and ready Chinese markets. That underwhelmed
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, the most important voice on any
economic matter.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments played out in regular meetings in the office of
John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, who was also
concerned about the damage that would be wrought trying to push the
deal through Congress. ``John had visions of NAFTA dancing in his
head,'' one participant in the discussions said, referring to the
North American Free Trade Agreement, which passed in 1993 only
because Clinton was able to rally Republicans to the free trade
cause. This year, though, few were expected to come to the
president's rescue.
</P>
<P>
   As the White House debate rolled on, Clinton was busy with other
things. He spoke with Ms. Barshefsky only sporadically; she made a
last-minute trip to Beijing last week without a clear sense of what
the President wanted. There were few meetings to prep the president
for a major meeting with Zhu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could barely focus on the summit,'' one foreign policy aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   So by the time Clinton was deeply involved in the details, it
was clear that negotiators had run out of time. In fact, they had
accomplished more than Clinton discussed at a news conference with
Zhu on Thursday afternoon. The president's prepared statement, his
aides said, had been written a day before _ and he had not had time
to review it before he stood next to Zhu and announced that
progress had been made, but not enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
