<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KOSOVAR ALBANIAN LEADER, LONG SHUNNED BY MILOSEVIC, IS NOW
WELCOMED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE,
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of the last ten years, Slobodan Milosevic, as the main
generator of aroused Serbian nationalism, has been trying to ignore
Ibrahim Rugova, the 53 year old literary historian who until
recently was the unquestioned leader of Kosovo's Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after the NATO attacks on Yugoslavia and the forced
flight of Albanians from Kosovo, President Milosevic has turned to
the adversary he spurned for so long, as if acknowledging him as a
suitable partner for building a peace. The tall, gangly Albanian
has been shown on television seated alongside and chatting with
Milosevic, though it remains unknown how the Albanian leader came
to Belgrade and what pressures he may be under.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have long opposed each other and each other's
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 Milosevic, then the president of Serbia, reignited the
dreams of Serbian nationalism by defending the Serbian minority in
Kosovo and stripping the Albanian-majority province of what
autonomy it had. Within months, Rugova helped to found the
Democratic League of Kosovo and became its first president.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the league quickly became something
between a political party and a mass movement, and in an interview
a few years later, Rugova claimed this strategy was inspired by the
approach taken by the Poles in creating Solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova provided a sharp contrast to Milosevic. While the Serb
looked and sounded like a pugnacious battler, snarling at opponents
and playing to the crowd, Rugova appeared like an other-worldly
intellectual, soft spoken and polite, claiming that his heroes were
Gandhi and Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   He had been the leader of the writers club of Kosovo before the
league was formed. When he was an infant, his father and
grandfather were killed, apparently by partisans, but he was so
committed to nonviolence that he would lecture his fellow Albanians
to avoid slurs or strong language when referring to the Serbs, to
avoid needlessly worsening the tension in the province.
</P>
<P>
   He always wore a long scarf coiled around his neck, even
indoors, and wore his hair long with ringlets over his ears. Though
his heritage, like that of most Kosovars, is Muslim, his doctoral
work had concerned the writings of a 17th-century Catholic
archbishop who preached and wrote in Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite his recondite interests, ascetic manner and the
stump personality of an aloof intellectual, he proved to be a
highly effective political figure, and on May 24, 1992, in an
officially unsanctioned ``election,'' ethnic Albanians throughout
the province overwhelmingly elected him president of the ``Kosovo
Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was shunned in this capacity by Milosevic, he made the
most of his victory, daily attending a small office behind the
soccer stadium, where he met and discussed issues with similarly
elected parliamentarians. He welcomed foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he established a shadow government for the
province, collecting taxes and distributing money contributed by
Kosovar Albanians working abroad. The payments were voluntary, but
taxpayers and donors generally amounted to 3 percent of their
income.
</P>
<P>
   The money was largely used to pay teachers and doctors. Albanian
teachers had been fired, either for taking part in protests or for
refusing to drop Albanian literature and history from the
curriculum. Once that happened, Rugova's ``republic'' helped set up
a network of schools in private homes that eventually were attended
by 400,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   This parallel system was extended into the spheres of culture
and sport.
</P>
<P>
   But most of Rugova's attention was concentrated on a three-part
strategy:
</P>
<P>
   _ To prevent a violent revolt against the Serbs. Not only was he
committed to non-violence on philosophical grounds, he argued that
Kosovo Albanians were ill equipped to take on Serbian or Yugoslav
forces.
</P>
<P>
   _ To draw international attention to the situation in Kosovo,
from photographs with visiting officials to contacts with
international organizations, religious groups, and non-governmental
organizations. Here he was quite successful.
</P>
<P>
   _ To do whatever could be done to deny legitimacy to Serbian
rule over the province.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with this last point, Rugova saw to it that Kosovo
Albanians boycotted elections held by Serbian or Yugoslav
authorities. That stand was opposed by some of his foreign
supporters, among them the United States. In their view, the
potential Albanian vote, when added to that of Milosevic's Serbian
opponents, would have been great enough to curb Milosevic's power
if not to end his rule.
</P>
<P>
   Hewing to these points, Rugova was able to maintain solid
support among Albanians until three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He had been urging Albanians to restrain themselves in the hope
that in the wake of the Dayton accords, which halted the war in
Bosnia, the international community would address the Kosovo issue.
When he received little more than a photo opportunity with
President Clinton, his popularity dipped.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the rise of more militant political rivals such as
Adem Demaci, who upon his release after 27 years in prison,
denounced Rugova's approach and favored a more aggressive policy.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, the separatist guerrillas, the Kosovo
Liberation Army, began emerging, obviously opposed to the
nonviolence that Rugova prized.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, Rugova's position was no longer dominant among the
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears that Milosevic, who in the past has succeeded in
turning his Serbian rivals into allies, is trying a similar tactic
with Rugova, perhaps calculating that by at least appearing to
finally take the man seriously, he might restore his status among
the Albanians of Kosovo to the point where the two could cut a
deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
