<SLUG> BC-METROJET10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    US Airways' MetroJet to start five daily flights to Northeast
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ US Airways' discount service, MetroJet,
will begin flying five times daily between West Palm Beach and the
Northeast for less than $100 one way starting in July, with two
additional flights slated for August, the carrier said this week.
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet will fly two daily flights from Palm Beach
International Airport to Hartford, Conn. two daily flights to
Baltimore and one daily to Boston, all nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   A second and third daily flight between West Palm Beach and
Boston will be added on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways already carries the second-largest number of
passengers monthly from PBIA, handling 19 percent of February's
traffic. Delta Air Lines carried 33 percent of PBIA passengers in
February, the latest figures available.
</P>
<P>
   Although other airlines fly to these cities, Delta is the main
competition to MetroJet on these routes because they offer some
nonstop service, US Airways spokesman David Castelveter said. Delta
flies three times daily to Boston, including one nonstop. It flies
twice to Hartford, with one of those nonstop. It does not fly to
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet, the discount arm of US Airways, began last year as a
no-frills carrier to compete with low-fare alternatives such as
Delta Express.
</P>
<P>
   MetroJet will offer one-way fares of $97 to Boston, $87 to
Hartford and $85 to Baltimore, with tickets bought at least seven
days in advance. Steve Barofsky of Sunrise Travel in West Palm
Beach said Delta is matching MetroJet's fares.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
