<HEADER>
A2763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KDRILL10-COX     04-09 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KDRILL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K drill goes well for utilities
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Electric companies around the nation
actually talked to each other Friday. Only a little bit was lost in
translation.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a nationwide Y2K prep test, system operators at
utilities, including Florida Power &AMP; Light Co., picked up cellular
and satellite phones and spoke the information that is usually
transmitted by computer. The purpose was to make sure utilities can
still communicate should computers fail when the clock strikes
midnight Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from some wrong phone numbers and confusion over language,
Florida's utilities had excellent results, said Linda Brousseau of
the Florida Reliability Coordinating Council, the industry group
that oversees the state's electricity supply.
</P>
<P>
   FPL learned one important lesson: Utilities use different names
for power substations. One might refer to it by a number and the
other by a name, said FPL spokeswoman Kathy Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we do drills,'' Scott said. ``We always learn
something.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Scott said they decided to call the substations by
name.
</P>
<P>
   It's critical that power plants be able to communicate with one
another to maintain the supply on Florida's power grid.
</P>
<P>
   The industry group that monitors the nation's power supply _ the
North American Reliability Council _ ordered Friday's test and sets
Y2K guidelines for the nations' utilities to follow. It reported no
major glitches throughout the nation as of late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The true ``dress rehearsal,'' as Brousseau calls it, is planned
for Sept. 8 and 9 when utilities will test not only whether they
can communicate, but whether electricity continues to flow even if
there's a whole host of Y2K-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug stems from the use of just two digits to mark the
year in older computer programs and chips. When 2000 rolls around,
some programs might think it is 1900, resulting in anything from
calculation mistakes to outright failures.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
