<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIPYARD-STRIKE-ART-6     04-09 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPYARD-STRIKE-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIPYARD STRIKERS DEMAND `JUSTICE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT NEWS, Va. _ As Marvin Lowrie, a 52-year-old machinist,
walked the picket line outside the giant shipyard here, there was
pride laced with bitterness when he talked _ pride that his
shipyard produces the world's most sophisticated nuclear aircraft
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowrie, who constructs intricate piping systems for the
carriers, voiced unmistakable bitterness that after 27 years on the
job making ships essential to the nation's defense, he was still
earning less than $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Seething about what they called stingy wages and pensions,
Lowrie and more than 8,000 other workers at Newport News
Shipbuilding went on strike after their contract expired last
Monday in one of the largest walkouts this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are world-class shipbuilders, yet they get
paid peanuts,'' Lowrie said.
</P>
<P>
   To Lowrie, the dispute is not about whether workers get a 14
percent raise or a 22 percent raise, but about economic justice,
about whether workers share in the fruits of economic prosperity.
The strikers, members of the United Steelworkers of America, are
demanding that the shipyard reward them after they helped nurse it
back to financial health by agreeing to a 50-month wage freeze in
their last contract. After losing money in 1997, the company earned
$66 million in 1998 _ not enough, company officials say, to award
the large increases sought by the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the company has had a big turnaround and has a
tremendous backlog of work, we want to get our fair share of the
pie,'' Lowrie said, adding that his annual pay was proving to be a
particular hardship now that it cost $9,800 a year to send his
21-year-old son to college.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other strikes in their early days, this one does not
appear to be shadowboxing. Both sides are digging in, with neither
asking the other to return to the bargaining table for fear that it
would look as if it blinked first. The shipyard insists it has made
its final offer, while the union, steel workers Local 8888, has
begun determining who among its strikers will need the most
financial assistance to endure a long walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize there is every chance that this could be a lengthy
strike,'' said Alfred Little Jr., the shipyard's vice president of
human resources. ``I think it could be months, but I hope not.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the workers are in a festive mood, excited by a sense
of solidarity while not yet feeling squeezed by weeks without
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the honeymoon phase,'' said Jan Hooks, a crane
operator for 23 years whose big complaint is that when she retires
in five years, her pension will be about $400 a month, not enough
to cover her monthly rent.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in groups of five, 20 and 50, the workers picketed in
front of 10 gates at a shipyard that stretches for two-and-a-half
miles along the Chesapeake Bay. Beyond the gates were gigantic,
1,100-foot-long, 90,000-ton aircraft carriers under construction or
undergoing nuclear refueling.
</P>
<P>
   In front of company headquarters, an austere brick building, 20
strikers, watched by nine police officers, sang variations of a
labor anthem with verses that included, ``We build first-class
ships. We shall not be moved,'' and ``We want a contract. We shall
not be moved.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipyard officials insist they have made a generous offer that
will increase pensions by at least 10 percent and raise wages by 18
percent over 47 months for most workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new offer essentially makes our top-rated mechanics the
highest paid in the industry when you take into account regional
differences in the cost of living,'' said Jerri Fuller Dickseski,
the shipyard's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides in strikes often see differing realities, and that
is certainly the case here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their offer is insulting,'' said Randolph Deloatch, a stocky
46-year-old who installs and removes nuclear fuel from the
carriers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While company officials hail their proposed 18-percent increase
as generous for four years, union members called it ridiculous,
saying it would translate into 18 percent over 10 years _ or less
than 2 percent a year _ since the workers have not received an
across-the-board raise since December 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Meredith, 37, another nuclear fueling worker, noted that
one full-time colleague in his highly skilled department earned so
little that he qualified for a welfare program to help feed his
children. Meredith also criticized the shipyard for paying him only
$12.59 an hour, even though his job is dangerous and demanding,
while workers at a nearby Anheuser-Busch brewery earn more than $20
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad for them, but I'm not sure what they do is as
important for the national interest,'' he said. ``There's real
suffering going on here. It's tearing families apart. A lot of this
is being precipitated by a lack of money.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the proposed pension increase of more than 10 percent,
Arnold Outlaw, Local 8888's president, termed it paltry, saying it
would be an increase from a small base _ most recent retirees
receive less than $500 each month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are, retirees can't even afford to bury
themselves after they die,'' Outlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Little, the vice president, said management's overall pay
proposal was the most generous made by any shipyard in years. He
also said that the improvements in wages and pensions would make
the shipyard the second-best-paying in the nation, behind only
Electric Boat in Groton, Conn., where the cost of living is
significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   Little warned that it would be unwise for the union to push for
too steep a raise. The union's proposals amounted to a 35 percent
increase, he said, and might push the shipyard into the red and
persuade the Pentagon to turn to lower-cost suppliers. He also said
the union was wrong to think the shipyard was highly profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on our way to doing better,'' Little said, ``but there's
certainly room to do better than this. We're always under a
tremendous amount of pressure from the Navy to reduce costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Outlaw, the union president, said one reason for the strike was
that far more shipyard workers belonged to the union than was the
case two years ago _ more than 80 percent of the 9,200 hourly
workers have joined, up from about 50 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at unionized companies in Virginia are not required to
join the union or pay dues. In theory, the more workers belonging
to the union, the fewer will cross the picket line, enabling the
union to put more pressure on the company. Pointing out that the
colossal cranes at the shipyard were dead still, Outlaw said the
company had largely been shut down, helped by the Teamsters'
decision to honor the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   Little voiced optimism that the shipyard could endure a long
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work is going to continue,'' he said, ``but at a much
lower level. It will grow as time goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   But William Rollins, a striking mechanic, said, ``They're
looking to break us and have us run back into the yard. But there's
so much unity this year. We have the heart of the shipyard out in
the streets. Without the heart, they have nothing to run the yard
with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
