<HEADER>
A2766 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-BABIES-800     04-09 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-BABIES-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE MONTHS AND COUNTING: THE RACE FOR THE MILLENNIUM BABY BEGINS
</HEADLINE>
   (ac) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Fitzpatrick Manhattan Hotel here was bracing for
it. With night approaching, the manager was reporting a rush of
last-minute orders for bouquets and requests for dinner
reservations at the most romantic spots in town.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, WJMN radio was promoting it. The station had
sequestered four lucky couples in a hotel, all competing for the
same prize _ and a measure of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   And in Germany, the minister of health was discouraging it. The
government even issued a statement expressing grave concern that
the country's hospitals would be overwhelmed on New Year's Day. Or
thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   It, of course, was the act of producing the ultimate millennial
accessory: a child born on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For those who somehow missed the media hype and the water-cooler
jokes, Friday night was the night that doctors and statisticians
had calculated would be the equivalent of a rare fertility eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the actual likelihood of having a baby on a
specific day _ let alone within a few strokes of midnight _ are
about 4 or 5 percent, said Dr. Magdy Mikhail, chairman of
obstetrics and gynecology at Bronx-Lebanon Hospital Center. This
was no ordinary Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight's the night; I ovulate today,'' a cheerful sounding
Jacquie Crumlich, 35, of Denver, said Friday afternoon, in
anticipation of her plans to bear a fourth child. ``We're going to
have a candlelight dinner. Some jazz or blues. The kids are all
going to friends' houses. It's a nice way to bring in the new year,
if it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, she added, that's fine, too. But like so many
things even remotely connected with 2000, the notion of a
millennial baby has provoked something of a marketing frenzy,
turning the most intimate of decisions _ and actions _ into a
public spectacle of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   One San Diego couple originally announced that they would fly to
the tiny island nation of Kirbati, near the international date
line, and undergo a Caesarean section at one second after midnight.
But the couple has since backed off, saying that the specter of a
media crush has been a bit overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   One web site (www.millenniumhell.com) concocted a Top Ten list
of ``Reasons To Try and Conceive the First Baby of the New
Millennium.'' No. 5 is ``It's not just sex. We're making history.''
No. 1, meanwhile, is ``Because your biological clock is not Y2K
compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two months, close to 1,000 people have purchased the
$49.99 Millennium Conception Kits from a San Francisco company
called Baby Center, said Mark Selcow, the company's president. The
kits include ovulation detection tests, pregnancy tests, candles
and massage oils.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the scads of radio stations and hotels that have
been seeking to mix fun and promotion, millennial fever and
pregnancy. In Houston, for instance, KHMX, a radio station, has
already offered a cornucopia of prizes _ including a Texas college
education _ to the first local baby born on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And in Boston, WJMN sponsored four couples, drawn from a
lottery, to spend Thursday night at a Days Inn hotel, with the
mandate to produce, produce, produce. The station promised to give
$1 million to one of those couples if they are the first in the
United States to bear the first baby next year.
</P>
<P>
   So, to soften the mood, the radio station paid for dinner at an
expensive Italian restaurant, as well as hotel rooms that lavished
roses, chocolates, champagne and _ yes _ edible underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't the millennium baby be fantastic?'' asked Bobbi
Milso, an administrative assistant from Weymouth, Mass., who spent
Thursday night with her husband Derek, 28, at the Days Inn. ``It
would make a special event even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband added: ``I know some people think being part of a
contest makes the process seem trivial. We planned to have a baby
all along. It's been fun, and we got a lot of good free stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, WKTU 103.5 FM tried to do something similar. The
station had originally hoped to send several couples to a hotel,
with the proviso that the couples report on their progress. But
there were technical and logistical difficulties with broadcasting
live from the hotel's lobby, so the station decided, instead, to
distribute free gift packs from the Baby Center, said Janeen
Shaitelman, the station's sales promotion director.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, of course, that the very idea of having the
first baby of the millennium deserves an asterisk or two. Does the
baby have to born in, say, Kirbati to qualify? Or can there be a
baby born in each time zone, or each country, or each city? And
who's checking, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   And don't even get started on the fact that the real,
scientifically approved millennium actually starts on Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the most part, though, it seems that many would-be parents
are taking things in stride, despite the suggestions that girls
born on Jan. 1 should be named Millie and boys Miles.
</P>
<P>
   Near Spokane, Wash., Camille Eldridge said that she and her
husband had originally hoped to have their fourth child later this
year, but decided to bump up their schedules when they learned
about the April 9 date. She figured it would be the best way to
mark the start of a new year, a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will ask you, what were you doing when JFK was shot?''
Mrs. Eldridge, 32. ``So it would be neat to remember, what did you
do to bring in the year 2000?''
</P>
<P>
   And at the Fitzpatrick Manhattan Hotel, on Lexington Avenue,
Trevor and Diana Facey, of London, said that they had planned to
have a third and final child long before they knew of any kind of
millennial connection. So, ``don't,'' Facey smiled wrly, ``ask us
how we're spending our evening.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't care, particularly, for the Year 2000 fever that has
gripped Britain. But they do have a knack, they say, for strange
twists of fate. Their 7-year-old son, Christian, was born on
Valentine's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Most remarkable, though, is the fact that the Faceys also share
the same birthday. That day was Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
