<SLUG> BC-GLENDALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 U.S. Loses $909 Million in Thrift Suit
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In a landmark case left over from the savings and loan bailout of
the early 1990s, a federal judge yesterday ordered the government
to pay $909 million for breaking a contract with a thrift that is
now part of San Francisco's Golden State Bancorp.
</P>
<P>
   The award is one of the largest ever against the federal
government but less than the $1.5 billion to $2 billion some
analysts had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by U.S. Claims Court Judge Loren Smith paves the way
for awards in more than 100 similar cases brought by thrifts whose
capital was slashed when the government changed accounting rules a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have estimated the government's liability at as much as
$30 billion,'' said Jefferies &AMP; Co. analyst Charlotte Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say the case is also significant because it reinforces
the principle that the government cannot use its special status to
violate its contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Stevens, lead attorney for the plaintiffs in the case,
said the ruling showed ``the government must honor its agreements
just like any private party.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern California's Glendale Federal Bank filed the suit in
1990, claiming the government had broken a promise to exempt it
from the usual capital requirements thrifts must meet. Golden
State, the parent of California Federal Bank, bought Glendale last
year, inheriting the case.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had previously ruled the government liable, a decision
approved in 1996 by the Supreme Court. The latest ruling came at
the end of a 15-month trial to determine how much the government
owed Glendale in damages.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith ruled that the government had to pay for breaking
its agreement with Glendale, he refused to accept the thrift's
requests to be compensated for profits it lost as it struggled to
raise new capital.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is reviewing the decision, a spokesman
said. Analysts said they expect the government to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   While it could be years before damages are paid, a major
beneficiary will be financier Ronald Perelman, who owns a 30
percent stake in Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State will get 15 percent of any award after legal costs
are paid. The rest will go to holders of special securities
Glendale spun off to shareholders last year. Most of those
securities have been bought by institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   The claims of Glendale and other thrifts are a legacy of the
savings-and -oan crisis of a decade ago. In the 1980s, dozens of
thrifts went bankrupt because of bad loans and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid costs to the government, federal regulators persuaded
strong thrifts to buy up weak ones. In exchange, they promised to
let the buyers use part of the purchase price to meet regulatory
capital requirements, an accounting asset called ``supervisory
goodwill.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital is the cash and other hard assets banks and thrifts are
required to set aside as a cushion against losses.
</P>
<P>
   When the real estate market crashed in the late 1980s, some of
the buyers were themselves near failure, creating tens of billions
of dollars in potential liability for the government, which insured
deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Congress then enacted the 1989 thrift bailout law which, among
other things, set tough capital standards and outlawed using
goodwill as capital.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale nearly failed when it was no longer allowed to use
goodwill from a 1981 acquisition as capital. Other thrifts weren't
so lucky. Dozens were seized by the federal government when their
capital fell below regulatory standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
