<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Fair, Isaac CEO OKs Demotion To Research
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In an unusual corporate reshuffling, Larry Rosenberger, chief
executive of Fair, Isaac, said yesterday he has agreed to take a
lower-ranking job after the maker of financial software finds a new
CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberger, 52, will stay with fast-growing San Rafael company
as research and development chief. While it's common for CEOs to be
replaced as companies grow, it's rare for the former chief to
accept a demotion.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberger said he agreed to step down because Fair, Isaac
needs a leader with experience in taking a company from small,
entrepreneurial status to a larger, more complex organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my entire business career of 25 years here,''
Rosenberger said. ``Quite frankly, the conclusion was that we
needed someone who had led a company through a transformation of
that size. I agree with that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair, Isaac said its board has launched a search for a new chief
and that Rosenberger is a member of the search committee. He will
continue as CEO until a successor is found.
</P>
<P>
   Fair, Isaac started by selling analysis tools to lenders and the
credit card industry designed to identify which customers were most
likely to pay off loans. In recent years, the company has expanded
its products to include a wide range of software for analyzing
consumer and business financial data, including software to help
make credit decisions on small business loans.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, as computerized data manipulation
techniques became more sophisticated, the market for credit
analysis tools grew explosively. Since Rosenberger became CEO eight
years ago, the company's sales and stock market value have
multiplied tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year ended September 30, the company earned $24.3
million on sales of $245.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Fair, Isaac approved a new strategy to sell
data analysis products to health care, telecommunications and
electronic commerce companies, as well as financial services firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
