<HEADER>
A2769 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADO10-COX     04-09 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midwest hit by deadly tornado
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Ohio's deadliest tornado since 1985 ripped
through Cincinnati's affluent northeastern suburbs just before
sunup Friday, killed four people, destroyed 200 homes and damaged
hundreds of other businesses and residences.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people were killed in Illinois as powerful storms tore
through the Midwest overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The storm killed a married couple in their Montgomery, Ohio,
home and two motorists whose cars were tossed by the violent winds.
Dozens of people were taken to area hospitals, mostly suffering
from cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   In Ashland, Ill., a community of 1,200, a tornado ripped into a
trailer park and killed a 68-year-old woman. And a 43-year-old
woman was killed in a mobile home in Cisco, 65 miles to the east.
</P>
<P>
   The storms also damaged homes in Indiana. In Iowa, at least nine
suspected tornadoes destroyed homes, flattened barns and uprooted
trees.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado also ravaged a five-block area in the Nebraska town of
North Bend on Thursday afternoon, and the storm damaged buildings
and downed power lines in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   In upscale Cincinnati suburbs of Montgomery, Blue Ash and Symmes
Twp., the storms uprooted or snapped tall trees, knocked down power
lines and flattened homes and businesses, littering usually
pristine lawns with debris. Electrical power was disrupted to more
than 200,000 customers of the utility Cinergy, although service was
restored to all but about 30,000 homes by Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I have never witnessed such tragic, overwhelming
destruction of neighborhoods,'' Gov. Bob Taft said after he toured
the devastation and declared states of emergency in Hamilton,
Warren and Clinton counties. ``It has been one of the most serious
disasters we have experienced in Ohio. The force of the tornado is
something we have not seen for many, many years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the deadliest Ohio tornado since May 31, 1985, when 10
died and 250 were injured in a Trumbull County twister, according
to the Ohio Insurance Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Taft's declaration means the three counties are eligible for
state disaster relief services. Meanwhile, Ohio's U.S. senators,
George Voinovich and Mike DeWine, wrote a joint letter to President
Clinton, urging his attention to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado was part of a storm system that hammered several
counties in Ohio and southeastern Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The storm also flipped motor homes and campers that convert to
tents at the Dave Arbogast dealership in Tipp City, 60 miles north
of Cincinnati. ``We got about 10 tent campers in a nice, neat
pile,'' said Ron West, a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Less severe damage was reported in Wayne County, Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued the tornado warning for
south and central Ohio and northern Kentucky at 4:52 a.m. Friday
after a funnel cloud was sighted in the sky 17 miles west of
Cincinnati. Radar also indicated presence of a tornado,
meteorologist Brian Coniglio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it appears it was just one tornado,'' said
meteorologist Sam McNeil of the National Weather Service. ``There
is a possibility in theory that it could have been more than one.''
The main tornado could have spawned several smaller vortices, he
said, as it did in the devastating April 3, 1974, Xenia, Ohio,
tornado that killed 33 and injured more than 1,300.
</P>
<P>
   The only touchdown confirmed Friday was in the Blue Ash area,
McNeil said. The tornado's path was from 400 feet to nearly a mile
wide and 6-7 miles long. Straight-line winds destroyed a dozen
homes in rural Clinton County near Clarksville, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary reports indicate the tornado that touched down in
Blue Ash rated F-3 on the Fujita scale with wind speeds of 158 to
205 miles per hour, McNeil said. In comparison, the tornado that
hit Xenia 25 years ago received a more serious F-5 rating. The
Fujita scale classifies tornados based on a wind speed range and
damage on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are indications the tornado in Blue Ash may have touched
down with F-4 force in isolated areas,'' McNeil said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the number of injuries and fatalities, we're getting
reports that people heard warning sirens activated and were able to
take cover,'' McNeil said. ``We're encouraged by that.''
</P>
<P>
   But some residents said they didn't hear sirens. Montgomery
Mayor Richard Tuten heard a siren, but said its significance may
have escaped some people so early in the morning. ``If you're in
bed asleep, it's not like an alarm clock. You may hear it and not
know exactly what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ambrose and Megan Britt said they were asleep in their
Symmes Twp. apartment when noise from the storm awakened them.
Alarmed, they decided to evacuate. ``I went into the spare bedroom
to grab my socks,'' Britt said, ``and realized the wall was
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   When they fled outside, Britt, 23, said, they saw ``mayhem'' _
dumpsters blown in the street, cars with windows shattered. One
wall of their Village Brooke Apartments building was blown away,
and couches and beds protruded from upper-story apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to return to his apartment throughout the day for a
change of clothes, Ambrose had to attend his mother's wedding
rehearsal dinner in a T-shirt and khaki pants.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters were established at Sycamore Junior High School and
Cincinnati Hills Christian Academy with food, cots and phones for
displaced people. But relief workers said it appeared most of those
affected by the storm would stay with family or friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area that was hit was more self-sufficient
(financially),'' said Sara Peller, chief executive of the
Cincinnati area chapter of the American Red Cross. ``We are
estimating that 95 percent have insurance, which usually doesn't
happen in a disaster area.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Lawrence Budd, John Keilman, Chick Ludwig, Joann
Rouse and Joanne Huist Smith contributed to his report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
