r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONES-SFCHRON &LR;      04-09 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Neighbors Wind Up on Unintended Party Line
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In the movie ``Pillow Talk,'' neighbors Rock Hudson and Doris Day
unwillingly share a telephone line but eventually fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   For three people sharing a phone line in Burlingame, the results
have not been as amorous.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a month, David Parkinson and David Guzman, two
roommates in Burlingame, Calif., unknowingly shared their phone
number with Michelle Karan, a neighbor down the street.
</P>
<P>
   There were signs that something was amiss _ the two men got a
lot of calls for someone named Michelle, their phone would ring
twice then suddenly stop, and friends who tried to call the
roommates said a woman often answered their phone.
</P>
<P>
   The situation also puzzled Karan, who would often pick up the
phone and hear voices.
</P>
<P>
   At first Guzman and Parkinson thought it was just crossed wires.
But they eventually discovered that Pacific Bell had assigned their
phone number to Karan, who lives a few buildings away.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend called and said `Some woman has been answering your
phone for the past week. She said she lives two buildings down from
you and has the same phone number,''' Parkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the phone number that Parkinson and Guzman had
gotten four months earlier had been given to Karan about a month
ago, after she moved into a new apartment. Karan had asked Pac Bell
if she could keep her old Burlingame phone number, but was told no
and assigned the same number Parkinson and Guzman already had.
</P>
<P>
   After figuring out what was going on, Parkinson called Pac Bell
to see what could be done. ``They laughed at me and said that
couldn't be possible; that they couldn't assign the same number to
two people.''
</P>
<P>
   Karan had better luck. Pac Bell told her she would get her old
phone number on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell and the California Public Utilities Commission say
it is extremely rare for two customers to share a line.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman John Britton denied that the two neighbors
were assigned the same phone number, although both told The
Chronicle they had the same number.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said human error caused the same phone line to feed into
two different apartments and that the problem is being fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman said he hopes it's been resolved, since the situation has
created confusion and a little friction between the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People call us late. She was getting our phone calls at 11
p.m. She probably didn't like that,'' Guzman said.
</P>
<P>
   Karan said she did grow weary of getting so many phone calls for
``David.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd had enough phone calls for David and finally told someone
who called, `When you get hold of David, tell him this is my
situation. I don't know what's going on, but I'm getting his phone
calls.'''
</P>
<P>
   That someone was Michael Evenson, Parkinson's friend who figured
out that the neighbors shared a phone number. He said at first he
thought Guzman and Parkinson were leading a secret life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was curious as to why a lady answered the phone,'' said
Evenson. ``My first words to her were `Who's this?' She wanted to
know who I was too.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the situation may sound amusing, Parkinson, who has
been jobhunting for several weeks, said he may have missed
opportunities because of the mix-up.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman said the two wondered why Parkinson wasn't getting any
calls from prospective employers. Several recruiters told Parkinson
they had tried to call the phone number on his resume, but were
told they had the wrong number.
</P>
<P>
   And the two are also concerned about their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman said he overheard some of Karan's conversations and is
sure she overheard some of his.
</P>
<P>
   Parkinson said, ``I talked to my doctor heavily this month about
things I wouldn't want anyone to overhear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
