u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF-660&AMP;ADD     04-09 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AID GROUP'S PARTNERSHIP WITH NATO RAISES CONCERN OVER TRADITION OF
NEUTRALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-HUNGER,
KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The new partnership between NATO and the U.N.
refugee organization is bringing supplies and shelter to hundreds
of thousands who have fled Kosovo, but some fear it is straining
the traditional neutrality of aid groups.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops have set up refugee camps in Albania and Macedonia,
NATO airplanes are flying badly needed supplies to those camps and
NATO technicians are running all the logistics for the relief
flights, even from inside the U.N. refugee headquarters in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that by working so closely with one side's
military in an ongoing assault, the U.N. refugee organization may
have crossed the line that allows relief organizations to care for
the victims of both sides of a conflict, some governments and aid
organizations said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid that in the minds of Americans and Europeans the
military and the relief organizations are working on one side of
the war together, we're all part of the same operation, but we
can't be.'' said Joelle Tanguy, the executive director of Doctors
Without Borders. ``Independence is our main asset _ to be able to
walk into a war zone and act as independent relief workers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary-general, defended the
relationship during a Security Council meeting, saying he
personally approved and ``gratefully accepted'' NATO's involvement
in the U.N. relief operation. At the request of the Russian
delegate to the United Nations, Annan also made public the exchange
of letters between Secretary-General Javier Solana of NATO and
Sadako Ogata, the U.N. high commissioner for refugees establishing
the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, NATO spokesmen in Brussels were answering the
same questions, emphasizing that ``NATO will not seek to create an
independent humanitarian role for itself `` and that the military
was working under the lead of the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously an extremely uncomfortable position for the
UNHCR,'' said Kathleen Newland, a refugee expert at the Carnegie
Endowment. ``They're trying to emphasize the civilian character of
the operation, but that protest pretty much flies in the face of
what is obvious _ that UNHCR is lining up with one side of the
conflict.``
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the concerns of relief organizations, she said that ``as
far as the NATO participation in relief operations goes, that's all
for the good, they are life savers.'' What is at issue is how to
keep that participation at an arms length and ensure neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   Neutrality is a responsibility under international law for many
refugee organizations, including the International Committee of the
Red Cross, which said this week it could not become partners with
NATO the way the UNHCR has.
</P>
<P>
   When asked for alternatives, Ms. Tanguy and other refugee
officials suggested keeping the operations entirely separate, with
individual countries making their contributions but with the United
Nations in charge of all the operations. Establishing NATO refugee
camps in Macedonia was her top example.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be UNHCR camps from the very start,`' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of NATO troops under NATO command setting up and running
the camps, she and other officials said the Macedonian government
should have been forced to negotiate with the UNHCR, whose
officials would then have supervised the construction by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But other officials who have had to handle refugee crises in
this decade say that there is no getting around the fact that the
military has to be called into these operations and, inevitably,
take charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosovo, in great part, the military has taken over the
relief effort.'' said Morton Abramowitz, of the Council of Foreign
Relations who as U.S. ambassador to Turkey helped conceive a
ground-breaking cooperative effort by relief organizations and the
U.S. and British militaries to help Iraqi Kurds. ``The magnitude of
suffering has to be relieved as quickly as you can _ and you have
to put aside all other questions.``
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the 1990s, the U.S. military has taken an increasingly
active role in refugee crises. In the 1991 mission that Abramowitz
oversaw, the United States and allied forces escorted tens of
thousands of Iraqi Kurds from Turkey back to a safe haven area in
northern Iraq after the Persian Gulf War ended. To this day the
Kurds are being protected by U.S. and allied combat jets patrolling
the skies over their villages.
</P>
<P>
   That operation was followed by U.S. military involvement in
relief missions in Somalia, Rwanda and Bosnia, and in each case
``mission-creep'' brought the relief agencies closer to the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Questions were raised about military escorts for aid convoys and
whether the proximity of U.S. troops would spoil neutrality. But in
all of these cases the United States was not an active belligerent,
or it was part of a U.N. mission that provided its own mantle of
neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kosovo conflict NATO is not fighting under a U.N.
mandate, in part because Russia and China said they would veto
approval for the air attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Bosnia, when we were also working with NATO countries, our
relief operations were under the U.N. and they were well-balanced
with Russians,'' said a relief agency official who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``There should be some way to preserve
neutrality and still take advantage of NATO's logistics. Otherwise
humanitarian organizations should just become part of the military
operations.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
