<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BID TO SECURE U.S. SOLDIERS' FREEDOM FAILS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Cypriot leader Spyros Kyprianou failed
Friday to win the release of three U.S. soldiers held captive by
the Serbs and blamed NATO's intensified bombing campaign in
Yugoslavia for making his mission ``more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyprianou angrily denounced the continuing allied airstrikes
shortly after he emerged from a 90-minute meeting in Belgrade with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. The Serb leader told him
that the Americans would continue to be held as prisoners of war
until the allies stop bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensified heavy bombing of the last couple of days made
my humanitarian mission more difficult. It is well known, and it
has always been the position of President Milosevic, that bombing
should stop,'' Kyprianou told reporters after his talks.
</P>
<P>
   He complained that NATO should have shown ``some respect'' for
his mission by at least interrupting the bombing in and around the
Yugoslav capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of stopping, NATO intensified and expanded its
targets in Serbia and Kosovo during Kyprianou's two day visit,
attacking a large automobile plant, more fuel storage areas, and
Yugoslav troops and weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials expressed disappointment at the
failure of Kyprianou's mission, but said they were not surprised by
the outcome. They also stressed that Kyprianou was well aware when
he undertook his humanitarian effort that the release of the
soldiers would have be to unconditional.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers _ Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich. and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas _ were
captured by Yugoslav forces on March 31 as they were patrolling
along the Macedonia-Kosovo border as part of a NATO peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   The news that the three soldiers would not be freed came amid
new reports of atrocities being committed by Milosevic's army
troops and security police in Kosovo, where an estimated 1.2
million ethnic Albanians have been driven from their homes over the
past year and into refugee camps in Albania, Macedonia and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting some very disturbing reports out of Kosovo ...
of young Kosovo women who are being herded into a Serb army
training camp at Dakovica in southwest Kosovo, where they are being
raped by troops. And we have reports that as many as 20 may have
been killed in the course of this,'' said Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This a very eerie and disturbing echo of documented instances
of rape and killing of women in Bosnia during the Bosnian war,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the NATO air campaign started, the allies had accused
Milosevic's forces of killing more than 2,000 ethnic Albanians in
an offensive against separatist rebels fighting for an independent
Kosovo, which is a province of Serbia. Since the NATO bombing
began, Milosevic's forces have expanded and intensified their
efforts to rid Kosovo of its predominantly ethnic Albanian
population. Refugees fleeing the country have reported mass
killings and whole villages being emptied and burned to the ground.
Allied officials fear that thousands more may have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Milosevic's forces closed the borders of
Kosovo and turned back refugees trying to leave even as the Serb
leader was announcing a unilateral cease-fire against Kosovar
rebels. But there is no evidence that his army and police units
have abided by it.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Friday that Milosevic's latest actions in
Kosovo have only ``strengthened the unity and resolve'' of NATO
allies ``to persist and prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Milosevic is hoping that the allies ``will accept
as permanent the results of his `ethnic cleansing.''' But, he
continued, ``We will not. Not when a quarter of Kosovo's people are
living in refugee camps beyond Kosovo's borders. Not when hundreds
of thousands more are trapped inside, afraid to go home but unable
to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stop the Serb actions in Kosovo, NATO has
focused more of its bombing missions in recent days on Yugoslav
troops and equipment. But Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme NATO
commander, said it is becoming more difficult to attack Yugoslav
units from the air because many of them ``are in hiding.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said the allies have had great success in
stopping a number of Serb operations, by cutting off food and fuel
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton had insisted that NATO ground forces will not be
committed to the fight. But he came under pressure Friday from nine
U.S. lawmakers to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Clinton, Rep. Jim Turner, D-Texas, joined with
eight other members of Congress, to urge that NATO begin planning
for the commitment of ground troops ``to achieve NATO's broader
objective'' of ``reversing Milosevic's genocide actions in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was also signed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a
former Vietnam POW who is considering a run for the presidency next
year. McCain said he hopes to introduce a resolution in the Senate
next week that would authorize the use of ``whatever force is
necessary'' to drive Milosevic's troops out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, however, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., said he
intends to introduce a resolution that would deny funding for
ground troops unless approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin also issued a strong warning to
NATO, suggesting that Moscow may have no choice but to enter the
fighting if the bombing continues and NATO decides to send in
ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement in Moscow, Yeltsin said there could be a
``European war and possibly a world war.'' There were also reports
out of Russia that Yeltsin had ordered that nuclear missiles be
targeted at NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   But State Department officials played down the Yeltsin comments,
and a spokesman at the Kremlin later denied that any missiles were
being aimed at the United States and its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the incident was serious enough that Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright spoke with Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov
about it and planned a meeting with him next week in Oslo, Norway,
to discuss the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO officials were planning to beef up their forces in the
Balkans, they were also increasing efforts to help with the refugee
crisis caused by the Kosovo conflict. There were signs, though,
that relief efforts were beginning to make things better for
thousands still confined to camps.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to airlift up to 20,000 Kosovar Albanians to Guantanamo
Bay naval base in Cuba were put on hold. The facilities there are
still being readied, but U.S. officials said that ``the
bottleneck'' at refugee centers had improved. Officials also
acknowledged that the refugees were reluctant to go to Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
