<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL PROVES INJURY IS IN HIS PAST BY TAKING LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ There was a time, not so long ago, when climbing
a hill meant pure agony for Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to walk for more than a year because of a unique medical
condition, scaling a leader board at a professional golf tournament
_ let alone the Masters _ seemed completely out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal prefers not to think about those dark days, an 18-month
stretch when he feared his career might be over.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spaniard, who won the 1994 Masters, could not avoid
reflecting on them yesterday after peering down from atop the
leader board at a major championship for the first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal fired a second-round 66 yesterday at Augusta National
Golf Club, moving to 8-under par through 36 holes, and taking a
one-stroke lead over Scott McCarron. Nobody else is closer than
three strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels great,'' said Olazabal, 33, who missed the 1996
Masters because of his ailment. ``I try not to think too much about
what happened in the past. But it helps me to appreciate what I've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Olazabal attempts to block out the memories of a
misdiagnosis that left him at home in Fuenterrabia, Spain, on his
back and listening to music, while the world watched Greg Norman
gift-wrap the 1996 Masters for Nick Faldo. Eventually, a German
doctor discovered that Olazabal suffered not from arthritis in his
feet, but from a muscle ailment in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Physical therapy and cortisone injections allowed Olazabal to
walk without pain. Now, he leads a major championship for the first
time since shooting an opening 66 at the 1995 Masters _ roughly
four months before the start of his medical odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal got there with the only bogey-free effort of the second
round, which moved him a stroke ahead of McCarron and three in
front of Greg Norman (5 under) and Lee Janzen (5 under). Nick Price
and Davis Love III, both at 3 under, are the only others who
survived the cut of 4-over 148 that are within five strokes of the
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six golfers will play the weekend rounds at Augusta,
including Fort Worth resident Mark Brooks (4 over), who survived
his second Masters cut in nine career attempts. David Duval, the
world's top-ranked golfer, is nine strokes off the pace, at 1 over.
Tiger Woods, the No. 2 player in the world rankings, is at
even-par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm discouraged, but I'm not down,'' said Duval, the PGA
Tour's leading money winner who is attempting to win his third
consecutive event. ``You can make up a lot of shots in two days
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal covered significant ground yesterday by bagging six
birdies, all on putts inside 18 feet. He found 14 of 18 greens in
regulation, saved par from two sand traps and might have regained
lost confidence. Olazabal has yet to crack the top 20 in a European
Tour event this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't had a great round this season, so it's really nice to
have two good rounds in a row here to somehow make you believe more
in what you can do,'' said Olazabal, who has needed just 49 putts
through 36 holes on Augusta's undulating greens.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top six names on the leader board, all but McCarron have
won major championships. McCarron, 33, has two victories in five
seasons on the PGA Tour: the 1996 Freeport McDermott Classic and
the 1997 BellSouth Classic. But don't try to convince McCarron, who
collected six birdies and two bogeys in his second-round effort,
that he will be out of his element in trying to fend off the
weekend charges of Norman, Price, Janzen and Love.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are sometimes lesser-knowns who lead golf tournaments. I
don't consider myself a lesser-known,'' said McCarron, who holed a
55-foot putt for the day's only birdie at No. 4, a 205-yard par-3
that played to a scoring average of 3.5. ``When I'm playing with
Norman, I feel I'm as good as him. You have to believe that or you
don't belong out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, on the other hand, is glad to prove that he belongs
again, from a physical standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to try to be positive in a situation like
that,'' Olazabal said of his 18 months away from competitive golf.
``When I watched the Masters in '96, I was always thinking that,
one day, I will be back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's all the way back. And all the way to the top of the
leader board.  &LR; tagtop:Jimmy Burch, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:jburch &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
