<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PUSHES FOR PATIENTS BILL OF RIGHTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Trying to revive an issue that has been
overshadowed by impeachment and war, President Clinton on Friday
joined Democratic lawmakers in pushing for passage of legislation
regulating managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   The president urged Congress to pass the Patients Bill of
Rights, which would give consumers more rights to challenge medical
decisions by their HMOs, and give them more access to specialists
and emergency rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the primary purpose of managed care plans
should not be ``to deliver cheap health care; the primary purpose
is to deliver quality health care as cheaply and inexpensively as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   With Congress scheduled to come back from a two-week recess this
week, the president scolded GOP leaders for not allowing the
Democratic health care bills to be considered despite broad public
support.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed their reluctance to pressure from the managed care
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically the large HMOs, the insurers, have got the ear of
the congressional majority, and they have a lot of political
influence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the break from dealing with the NATO military campaign
in Yugoslavia, Clinton noted that the situation abroad had the
potential to harm his domestic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the managed care bill's opponents were probably
dismissing the health care event held with members of Congress,
based on the assumption that ``they probably can't break through
the evening news tonight because of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The managed care legislation has lost momentum before because of
other more sensational events. Last year, Congress had been
considering changes when the impeachment proceedings against
Clinton intruded and consumed most of their time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite congressional inaction, Clinton announced he would
direct that the health plans that cover federal workers comply with
two new requirements designed to protect consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The 289 health plans serving federal workers would have to pay
for or provide transitional care for certain chronically ill or
pregnant patients who are forced to change health plans or
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the health plans would have to provide additional
information to consumers on customer satisfaction and clinical
quality measures.
</P>
<P>
   The president already had ordered the federal health plans to
meet a series of other requirements, including access to emergency
rooms and specialists outside the plan's network when medically
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also countered the Republicans' argument that the
managed care changes would drive up health care costs, citing a
recent study analyzing the costs of the changes in effect for
federal workers. The study by the Office of Personnel Management
estimated the additional costs as $10 a year for each of the 4.1
million enrollees in the federal system.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope to make health care a major issue in the current
legislative session and perhaps through the 2000 election.
Democrats and health care advocacy groups have launched a national
petition drive to pressure Republican leaders to consider the
Democratic legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, aware of public discontent with managed care, have
proposed remedies. But Democrats claim the GOP bills do not go far
enough in giving people the ability to appeal decisions and would
not cover all health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant difference between Democratic and GOP
health care bills concerns the right to sue managed care plans.
Democrats want to amend federal law to ensure that consumers can
sue their HMOs in state courts. Currently, federal laws governing
multistate employer based health care plans bans such suits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have balked at permitting such suits, suggesting it
would be a bonanza for trial lawyers and drive up health care
costs.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the HMO issue will play on the presidential
campaign trail. Republican presidential contender Gov. George W.
Bush has been ambivalent about the issue. He refused to sign the
1997 HMO bill, citing concerns about the increased litigation. But
he also did not veto the bill, which passed the Legislature with
bipartisan support, and therefore allowed it to become law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
