<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S TATTERED COALITION FRAYS A BIT MORE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI _ India is going through another paroxysm of
finger-pointing, hand-wringing, arm-twisting, head-counting and
back-stabbing as its third coalition government in three years
threatens to come apart.
</P>
<P>
   Hindu nationalists came to power a year ago on a platform of
stable, clean and effective governance. They now face the strong
possibility of losing their coalition majority in Parliament next
week because of a falling out with their largest, most tempestuous
and _ many believe _ most corrupt coalition partner, Jayalalitha
Jayaram, who leads a state party from Tamil Nadu.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Jayalalitha, as she is known here, is to arrive in the
capital. While it is always possible she may patch up her
differences with Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and his
Bharatiya Janata Party, the expectation is otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   All week newspapers have been filled with the comings and goings
of political emissaries trying to cut deals. India has two major
national political forces _ Bharatiya Janata and the Congress
Party. With neither able to win a majority in Parliament, three
dozen smaller parties holding seats take on inflated importance.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha's party, the All India Anna Dravida Munnetra
Kazagham, has 18 seats. Her withdrawal from the coalition could
cause a no-confidence vote against the government some time after
Parliament reconvenes on April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as the rumor-mill produced an abundant inventory,
Jayalalitha took another step toward making her differences with
the BJP irreconcilable, quitting the coalition's coordinating
committee. Earlier in the week, two Cabinet ministers from her
party resigned from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha, a former leading lady in Tamil films, has had a
stormy relationship with Bharatiya Janata, repeatedly threatening
to walk off the set. Her latest complaint has been about Defense
Minister George Fernandes, who she says is corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting fieriness with fieriness, a Bharatiya Janata spokesman,
K.L. Sharma, said the government had no need of Jayalalitha's
advice on military matters.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he accused her of turning against the Hindu nationalists
because she wants state corruption cases against her to be
withdrawn and demands that the government dismiss Tamil Nadu's
elected chief minister, her political rival.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Jayalalitha's motives, she has the nation wondering
what she will do next, though in this regard she is only the
second-most watched woman in India: Complicating all this frantic
politicking is the inscrutability of Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born
heir to the Nehru-Gandhi political dynasty and a woman who has
rejuvenated the Congress Party in her year as its president. She
has given little hint of whether she wants her party to reclaim
power in what would surely be a troublesome coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not jump into anything in haste,'' Mrs. Gandhi said
this week.
</P>
<P>
   If the government loses a no-confidence vote, Mrs. Gandhi could
seek the prime minister's post for herself, or defer to a Congress
colleague, or support a third-force coalition, or call for early
elections or allow the BJP to continue as a minority government.
</P>
<P>
   She has yet to give an indication of her preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Gandhi has not made up her mind,'' said Mani Shankar
Aiyar, a Congress Party stalwart.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the government coalition ``puts Humpty Dumpty back
together again'' and survives this latest crisis, Aiyar said, it
will probably fall within weeks or months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
