<SLUG> BC-RAC-SUSPENSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRB SUSPENDS TRAINER WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The California Horse Racing Board suspended
trainer Ted West 90 days Friday and fined him $12,000 as part of a
settlement reached in a a case that involved eight West horses
which tested positive for the banned substance clenbuterol.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension begins April 20 and runs through virtually the
entire Hollywood Park meet. Accusations were filed against West and
six other thoroughbred trainers last September after clenbuterol
was detected in urine samples from several horses.
</P>
<P>
   West said he agreed to the settlement because he had no other
choice. Clenbuterol is legal for horses in training, but cannot
show up in post race tests.
</P>
<P>
   West admits using the drug, but said he stopped administering it
to horses three days before a race. Post race testing can detect
the drug 14 days after its last use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fighting a battle we couldn't win,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Three other trainers in the case have also reached settlements
with the CHRB. Three more, Paco Gonzales, Darrell Vienna and Bruce
Headley are scheduled for formal hearings in May and June.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally the Santa Anita Board of Stewards ruled that purses
given to West-trained horses in the clenbuterol case must be
redistributed.
</P>
<P>
   Those horses include: Slew O War, third on May 22, 1998 at
Hollywood Park; Slews Royal Son, second on May 25 at Hollywood
Park, Budroyale first on June 13 at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any good that comes out of this thing I would hope
that they'll find a way for us to use clenbuterol effectively,''
West said. ``Because it is an effective for medication for horses
with breathing troubles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
