<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL SUSPENDS BLAKE FOR TWO GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rob Blake is the Los Angeles Kings' captain and
last year's winner of the Norris Trophy as the NHL's best
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, he received a new title: repeat offender.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was suspended two games by the NHL for cross-checking San
Jose's Alexander Korolyuk late in the Kings' 3-2 victory Thursday
night over the Sharks. He will not play Sunday in Dallas or Monday
in Nashville. Jan Nemecek or Jaroslav Modry will be recalled from
the Long Beach Ice Dogs to take Blake's place.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, barely breathing in their pursuit of a playoff berth,
are 3-15 this season in games Blake has missed.
</P>
<P>
   Blake was suspended three games in December for slashing
Vancouver's Harry York. The incident cost him an automatic $1,000
fine and three days' salary (of the 192-day NHL schedule), which
came out to $82,304.69.
</P>
<P>
   This time, under NHL rules, Blake is considered a repeat
offender, meaning he will be docked pay for two games, a
$128,475.60 hit on his $5.2675-million salary. All told, Blake has
lost $211,780.29 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do about it,'' said Blake, adding he was
surprised that his discipline ultimately exceeded the two-minute
minor penalty he received from referee Mark Faucette on Thursday.
``I've been through it before. You sit your games, then you come
back and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake and Korolyuk had battled the entire game, but Blake's
cross check caught Korolyuk on his head. The incident came to the
attention of NHL discipline czar Colin Campbell after the Sharks
requested he review videotape of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro not quitting: Earlier in the year, Kings center Ray
Ferraro said this season, his 15th in the NHL, might be his last.
Friday, the 34-year-old Ferraro - who has 10 goals and 27 points in
60 games - said he wants to keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I'm 99 percent sure I would like to play, and I
would like to play here,'' said Ferraro, in the final year of a
contract that paid him $1.75 million this season. ``I certainly
haven't talked to anybody. I don't know if there would be any
interest or not. I know I can still play. I wasn't sure of it
earlier in the season. Now, I'm convinced I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have deferred personnel decisions until after the
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0417 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-DOCTOR-NYT &LR;      04-09 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-DOCTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURIED RIFLE FOUND NEAR HOME OF SLAIN ABORTION-CLINIC DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Canada)  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly six months after a Buffalo, N.Y.-area doctor who
performed abortions was shot to death at his home by a sniper,
law-enforcement authorities reported Friday that they had recently
discovered a rifle buried in the ground in woods behind the
doctor's house.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of the rifle appeared to be one of the biggest
breaks in a case that has thus far produced no arrests. Although
the authorities have been seeking to question an itinerant abortion
protester named James Charles Kopp, he has not been found, and some
officials in the Justice Department fear Kopp may be hiding in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that a rifle had been found raised questions
among friends and relatives of the slain obstetrician, Dr. Barnett
Slepian, about how thoroughly local police officers and FBI agents
searched the wooded area near Slepian's home in Amherst where the
gunman fired the fatal shot on Oct 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are wondering and are surprised it wasn't
found previously,'' said Glenn Edward Murray, who had been
Slepian's lawyer and is still the lawyer for the Slepian family.
</P>
<P>
   A terse news release jointly issued Friday by the Buffalo office
of the FBI, New York State Police and police in Amherst said the
rifle had been found one foot underground in a 4-acre, heavily
wooded area in the vicinity of the Slepian house and taken to the
FBI laboratory in Washington. The news release did not characterize
the rifle as the weapon used in the slaying, nor did it further
describe the rifle, pinpoint its proximity to the house, nor say
how and when it had been found. The news release implied, however,
that the rifle had been found recently.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law-enforcement officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the rifle had not yet been checked for fingerprints
or chemically tested, but that it roughly matched the kind of gun
that used bullets of the caliber found in Slepian's house. The
officials also said the rifle was discovered ``very close'' to the
site where other evidence _ including a cap and a hair _ were found
after the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   The police news release suggested that the weather had prevented
officers from conducting a search. ``Due to weather and ground
conditions previously in existence at the site, this search,
although planned early in the investigation, was not conducted
until this time,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray, who said he was told that the rifle was found
Thursday afternoon, recalled that the weather had been mild enough
to permit shoveling for weeks after the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't any severe conditions until January,'' he said.
He added that he was mystified that the rifle had not been found
earlier, because he felt that the police investigation had
otherwise been ``massive, intense, and dedicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Some federal law-enforcement officials in Washington speculated
that investigators in Buffalo never imagined that a sniper would
have taken the time to bury a rifle before fleeing the scene of a
killing.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle's discovery comes 10 days before the scheduled start
of anti-abortion protests at Slepian's former clinic in Buffalo, as
well as at other sites in Rochester and Batavia, which are being
organized by Operation Rescue, which staged sometimes unruly
rallies outside Slepian's clinic in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Slepian, who was the mainstay of the downtown Buffalo clinic,
was slain while he was standing in the kitchen talking to his wife
and children. The sniper had fired from woods behind the large
brick house. Witnesses in the upper-middle-class neighborhood told
police that in the days before the killing they spotted Kopp
jogging near the Slepian house.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp is also being sought for questioning in the shootings in
1994, 1995 and 1997 of three doctors who performed abortions in
Canada, and in the shooting of a fourth doctor in Rochester, N.Y.,
in 1997. None of the four earlier shootings were fatal.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Kopp's black 1987 Chevrolet Cavalier was found in
the long-term parking lot at Newark, N.J., International Airport,
its key still in the ignition. In mid-January, an unidentified
Justice Department official told The Associated Press that there
was evidence Kopp had fled to Mexico. A Customs Service videotape
from a border-crossing point, the official said, showed a female
friend of Kopp's returning from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   There also have been reports that the DNA on a hair recovered
from a cap found behind Slepian's house matched that of hair taken
from Kopp's last known address, an apartment in Jersey City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   WKBW-TV in Buffalo also reported on its Web site Friday that a
bag of bullets had been found two months ago buried near Slepian's
home, and that it also contained a strand of hair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
