<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pitcher is still in picture
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The disappointment may be even bigger this time around
for Mark Wohlers, who showed major signs of progress in spring
training from his 1998 control meltdown, but then lost it with the
opening of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, who walked six in two-thirds of an inning, was
designated for assignment Friday to Class AAA Richmond. The Braves
brought up right-hander Joe Winkelsas, a nonroster invitee to the
major league camp in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers has until Monday to refuse the assignment. Wohlers told
manager Bobby Cox Friday he planned to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sounded to me like he is dying to go down and get started
and throw to bases and do everything,'' Cox said. ``He doesn't want
any special attention. (Whenever) they need him to pitch, he
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   With $5.2 million invested in Wohlers this season, the Braves
are going to extend every effort to get him back in form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not be engaging in this whole process if we didn't
believe (he could come back),'' general manager John Schuerholz
said. ``He showed us in spring training there's enough there to
believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers has the option of rejecting the offer, in which case the
Braves would release him and he would still receive his salary.
</P>
<P>
   This is the final year of a three-year contract, with an option
for 2000 included. But unless Wohlers appears in 55 games this
season _ in which case the option would automatically kick in _ the
Braves can buy out the final year for $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Given the bottom line of Wohlers' contract and the steps back
he's taken with his control problems, trading Wohlers would be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's attitude is still great and we've seen him pitch
good,'' Cox said. ``It's there. It just went away for a little
while for whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox spoke to Wohlers about 2 p.m. Friday and left Turner Field
not long after. Wohlers was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers had poor outings to start and finish the spring but
otherwise pitched well. He had a 6.52 ERA in 10 appearances.
Without Wohlers
</P>
<P>
   The Braves bullpen is looking thin and young at the moment with
John Rocker, Rudy Seanez, Mike Cather, Kevin McGlinchy, Derrin
Ebert (replaced Mike Remlinger, on the 15-day disabled list with a
back muscle pull) and Winkelsas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our bullpen's going to be OK,'' Schuerholz said. ``I
feel fine with what we have here and what we have in our system.''
</P>
<P>
   The move to bring in Winkelsas (8.38 ERA in seven spring
appearances) is likely temporary. The Braves would have preferred
bringing up a member of the 40-man roster but under baseball rules
cannot return a player to the major leagues after he's been
designated for a minor league assignment in fewer than 10 days. The
season is only six days old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winks is OK,'' Cox said. ``He's got a great sinker. We'll
see.'' Ligtenberg back
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg was back in the Braves clubhouse Friday, three
days after having surgery to repair the ligament in his elbow. His
right arm was in a soft cast inside of a sling. He'll be in Atlanta
for several weeks while doctors monitor his progress before he
returns to Minnesota until midsummer. This and that
</P>
<P>
   Russ Springer threw on the side again Friday and should be ready
for his rehabilitation assignment. ``I think he's real close,''
Mazzone said. . . . Andruw Jones said he got a glove on Rico
Brogna's home run Thursday night. Jones very nearly made an
acrobatic catch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
