<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace sets qualifying mark to take pole
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. _ Most drivers detest Bristol Motor Speedway,
where accidents on the half-mile oval seem as common as victories
by Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   But for veteran NASCAR driver Rusty Wallace, the 38-year-old
facility always seems to offer an opportunity for recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell everybody that Bristol has always been my favorite
track,'' Wallace says. ``I like the shape of the track, and I
always seem to get around it well. It seems every time I come to
this place, if I'm behind or in trouble in the points or something,
I always feel like I can make something up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has plenty to make up after six races. He is 11th in
standings points, 203 behind Winston Cup leader Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, 43, helped himself tremendously Friday by winning the
pole for Sunday's Food City 500. His No. 2 Ford covered the track
at an average speed of 125.142 mph, breaking Bristol's qualifying
record of 125.093 mph set by Mark Martin in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've gotta (turn it around) right now,'' Wallace said. ``We
couldn't afford what happened at Atlanta and Darlington,'' where he
finished 35th and 33rd, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that saved me is that both Martin and Gordon
have had two DNFs,'' he said, ``and that's helped me a ton. I'm
11th, four points out of 10th, and they're not too far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace won his sixth pole in 31 races at Bristol, including his
fourth in the last five events here. He was nearly two-hundredths
of a second faster than Gordon, who will start second with an
average speed of 124.979 mph. Gordon is going for his fifth
consecutive victory in the spring race at Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, fourth in points and 119 behind Burton, complained of
sore ribs after his qualifying attempt. He was 43rd at Texas on
March 28 _ the worst finish of his Cup career _ after hitting the
outside wall hard in lap 69 of the 334-lap event
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a little bit of pain,'' Gordon said. ``I was sore on
that lap. I was getting everything I could out of the car. At the
speed we're qualifying, I'm a little sore in my ribs. I still feel
like I'll be able to go the distance on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, who broke his right shoulder blade just three
weeks ago in a wreck at Darlington, qualified third at 124.484 mph.
Rookie Tony Stewart was fourth, and veteran Ricky Rudd qualified
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it will be a little bit tough, but we had that
weekend off, and that helped,'' Labonte said. ``It's probably going
to be sore. The bone has healed up, and everything is strong. But
once we hustle around, it will get a little tender.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise on Friday was Darrell Waltrip, who had not
qualified for a race on speed this season until the Primestar 500
at Texas. Waltrip had an average speed of 123.857 mph and finished
12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not dead last,'' Waltrip said. ``That's really exciting.
I knew all along that if we could get some testing done we'd be OK.
I've got a great team. We've just gotta get some luck going.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
