<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walker enshrined in first year of eligibility
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Less than a year after his retirement from
football, Herschel Walker was tabbed Friday for one of the game's
most prestigious honors.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, the former Heisman Trophy winner at Georgia, was elected
to the National Football Foundation's College Hall of Fame. The
announcement was made during ceremonies Friday afternoon in South
Bend, Ind. It was Walker's first year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did Herschel make it in the first year, he breezed
in,'' said Georgia athletics director Vince Dooley, who is a member
of the Hall of Fame's Honors Court, which makes the final selection
of nominees. ``There wasn't much discussion, which is an indication
of the high esteem in which Herschel is held. He was the most
productive player I've ever been associated with. You can talk
about a lot of things, but the bottom line is production.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Johnson County High in Wrightsville, Walker won
the 1982 Heisman Trophy after finishing second in 1981 and third as
a freshman in 1980. He led Georgia to a 33-3 record in his three
seasons in Athens, including three SEC championships and a national
championship in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was a three-time All-American, broke Tony Dorsett's
freshman rushing record with 1,616 yards and finished with 5,259
yards before turning pro after his junior season.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of three Georgia residents inducted on Friday. Former
Notre Dame defensive end Ross Browner of Atlanta and former
Tennessee linebacker Steve Kiner of Carrollton also were voted in.
</P>
<P>
   Other players elected included: Chuck Dicus (Arkansas WR), John
Hannah (Alabama, OL), Billy Kilmer (UCLA, RB), Frank Loria
(Virginia Tech, DB), Joe Palumbo (Virginia, DL) and Greg Pruitt
(Oklahoma, RB). Coaches inducted were Jerry Claiborne, Don Coryell
and Jim Young.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
