</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT-LINEBACKER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speed puts Gators' trio at top of list
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the program produced such defenders as Jack Ham,
Greg Buttle, Shane Conlan and Lance Mehl, NFL scouts tabbed Penn
State as ``Linebacker U.'' In this year's draft, however, that
title might be passed to the University of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In Jevon Kearse, Mike Peterson and Johnny Rutledge, the Gators
might provide three of the top eight linebacker selections next
weekend. Kearse is a certain top-10 choice and the other two figure
to be off the board by the end of the second round. The run on
Gators linebackers is an interesting twist at a school more
renowned for turning out offensive skill-position players.
</P>
<P>
   It is not by accident, though, that Florida suddenly has so many
standout linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure defense designed by former coordinator Bob Stoops,
now the head coach at Oklahoma, demanded versatile, athletic
linebackers, and the staff went to great lengths to fill that
profile, even if it meant converting players from other positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Coach Stoops wanted (hybrid) players,'' Kearse
said. ``The priority was on getting people who could run and hit.
So the coaches were taking guys from all over the place and making
them linebackers.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the three Gators prospects arrived at Gainesville as
linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge was an All-America defensive end in high school.
Peterson was recruited as a quarterback and defensive back. Kearse
began his college career as a strong safety and nickel back. It
didn't take long for Stoops to see that all three had the kind of
pursuit mentality required to play linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   In a defense predicated on the overall quickness of the unit,
all three became impact playmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't run, you can't play in that defense,'' Baltimore
personnel director Ozzie Newsome said. ``And all those guys can
run.''
</P>
<P>
   While his size limits him to playing the weak side in the NFL,
Peterson may be the best pure linebacker of the three and has been
compared to Tampa Bay standout Derrick Brooks. Rutledge will
benefit from his toughness and his ability to play inside or
outside. But the player teams covet is Kearse, nicknamed ``The
Freak'' for his combination of size (6 feet 4 7/8, 262 pounds) and
speed (sub-4.5 seconds in the 40-yard dash).
</P>
<P>
   At the combine, Kearse indicated a preference for playing
defensive end. But while the video of his on-campus workout shows
some deficiencies in his pass-drop, most teams plan to play him at
linebacker on early downs and move him to end on third down. His
large wingspan and explosiveness could make him a double-digit
sacker, if his productivity ever matches his potential.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
