<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Altered grip on putter leads to 66 for Langer
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Two-time Masters winner Bernhard Langer beat his
lowest round at Augusta National by two shots with a 66 Friday.
That was a whopping 10 strokes better than his first round, all
because he moved his right hand down the shaft of his putter _ the
one long enough to rest under his chin when he uses it.
</P>
<P>
   His newfound touch converted three 20-footers, one of them for
par. He canned one from 45 feet on No. 9 that Langer imagined
``moved the hole 3 feet further away.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make a lot of bombs in 1985 and 1993, though. He had
one one-putt in 1985 and in '93 drained just about everything
within six feet. That was before he traded in the short stick _ and
before the changes to the course that, in Langer's opinion, made it
a couple of shots harder.
</P>
<P>
   Woods 8 back, but unruffled
</P>
<P>
   Two 72s seem a little tame for Tiger Woods, but he's not
counting himself out of the hunt, even eight shots back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rolling the rock pretty well and it's a matter of giving
myself chances,'' the 1997 winner said. ``If I can get a couple of
good runs going I can do well.''
</P>
<P>
   One swing he'd like to take back came on the 12th hole Friday,
when an 8-iron he tried to punch got caught up in a gust and landed
in the middle of Rae's Creek, not even close to getting to the
other side. An uninviting par 5
</P>
<P>
   At most PGA venues, the list of easiest holes usually starts
with the par 5's, and Augusta's are especially vulnerable to long
hitters. This week, though, the 15th hole has turned into a beast.
Just ask David Duval, who made 8 there.
</P>
<P>
   There were 20 double bogeys or worse so far. The hole is only
500 yards, but a new stand of trees narrowed the landing area, and
a very hard green makes going for it in two a huge gamble. Even
lobbed wedge shots, like Jeff Sluman hit en route to an 8, spin
back into the pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the people around that green and I think, man, these
people, they must like to see us really battle here,'' said Nick
Price, who made 6 there.
</P>
<P>
   Kuchar regroups
</P>
<P>
   At 6-over heading into the back nine, ailing Georgia Tech junior
Matt Kuchar looked like someone about to watch the final two rounds
on TV. But he holed out twice on the back nine _ from the sand for
eagle on 13 and the fringe on 14 for birdie _ to rally for a 71. He
made the cut, along with fellow amateurs Sergio Garcia (72-75),
Trevor Immelman (72-76) and Tom McKnight (73-74). They tie the
largest group of amateurs to make the cut since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Like father, not like son
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island native Davis Love III's opening 69 duplicated his
father's score to share the 1964 Masters lead. But history doesn't
look like it will repeat itself. Davis Love Jr. went on to shoot
75-74-76 and tie for 34th; son shot 72 Friday and is tied for
fifth.... Here's how the other Georgia players did: Stewart Cink of
Smyrna (74-70) is eight back, followed by Larry Mize of Columbus
(76-70) and Billy Andrade of Atlanta (76-72). Tommy Aaron of
Gainesville (77-82) missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Who's hot
</P>
<P>
   Bill Glasson fired a 32 on the back nine for 70 and is tied for
seventh. So is Colin Montgomerie (70-72), who on the par-4 third
hole cut a 90-yard sand wedge that found the hole for his first
eagle in eight trips here. ... Jay Haas made four straight birdies
in his 69, with 16-year-old son Bill on his bag. ... Phil Mickelson
birdied three of his last six for a 69.
</P>
<P>
   Who's not
</P>
<P>
   Defending champ Mark O'Meara misread the speed of the greens all
day in slumping to a 76. ... First-round co-leader Brandel Chamblee
didn't birdie until No. 9 and had a 73. ... PGA champion Vijay
Singh, at 72-76, called his putting ``very awful.'' ... Some
notables hitting the road: Tom Watson (74-77), Mark Calcavecchia
(75-77), Paul Azinger (74-78), Nick Faldo (80-73) and U.S. Amateur
champ Hank Kuehne (74-78). ... Andrew Magee, one shot off the lead
after Thursday, followed with a 77, as did Sandy Lyle. First round
(continued)
</P>
<P>
   After darkness suspended the rain-delayed first round, 12
players got to finish Friday morning. The good: Brandt Jobe, who
started 1-over on the 17th hole, finished par-birdie for a 72 and
then birdied the first three holes of his second round en route to
a 71. Jim Furyk played his last four holes 1-under for 72.
</P>
<P>
   The bad: Paul Azinger was even after 14, but finished with two
bogeys for a 74. Cink was 1-under but bogeyed 16 and shot 72, a
score that stood for a few hours until a ruling was made that added
two shots to that score. Mark Brooks bogeyed three of the last four
for 76.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
