</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NUHN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norman won't let weight of botched Sundays bog him down
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Close your eyes tighter than you've ever closed
them before. Put your hands over your ears. Now go to a closet and
don't come out until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Greg Norman's back on the leaderboard at the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to see or hear what comes next because it's
generally the saddest story of the sports year.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, fate's favorite whipping boy, has come back for more.
It's as if he escaped Devil's Island, got a whiff of the good life,
then swam back.
</P>
<P>
   The man has eight top-6 finishes at Augusta National Golf Club
(three seconds; two thirds; a fourth, a fifth and a sixth), but no
firsts. He knows only heartbreak and agony. He knows only
concession speeches.
</P>
<P>
   The worst was the most recent _ 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was 41, had stacked up failures here higher than the oak tree
in back of the clubhouse, and was thus the sentimental favorite as
he strode into Sunday's round with a six-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
   Even he couldn't blow that one.
</P>
<P>
   The optimists thought.
</P>
<P>
   Wrongly.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Norman hit more crooked shots than in the 10-and-under
flight of the local city juniors tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the horror.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, after Nick Faldo had clicked off a 67 and Norman had
gunked a 78 and Faldo had won by five, Faldo did the unthinkable _
for him: He hugged Norman on the 18th green. To appreciate that,
Faldo is so cold that on his wedding day, when the minister told
him he could kiss the bride, he shook hands with her instead.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe not. But he did hug Norman and say, ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Norman came to the interview room and gave a State of the
Shark address, shrugging and saying things happen for the best. He
then went fishing and every day another 1,000 or so letters of
condolence piled up at his house.
</P>
<P>
   Go to your favorite local card shop because, Moody Blues fans,
we might be revisiting days of future past. Norman is tied for
third, three shots behind Jose Maria Olazabal, going into today's
round, so there's still a chance Olazabal might run away and spare
Norman another Sunday, Bloody Sunday. For those of us who don't
want to write another Norman obituary, we can only say, ``Go, Jose,
go.''
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, at least, Norman showed no fear of returning to
the fire. ``It feels great to be in this position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, absolutely. It feels great to be hurtling down a mountain at
90 mph in a car whose steering wheel has just come off in your
hands.
</P>
<P>
   He said he got religion _ at least golf religion _ during and
after that 1996 five-star collapse. ``That's done,'' he said. ``One
thing I realize is golf is not everything. Yes, I want to win the
Masters. But it's not a priority. There are other priorities that I
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's 43. Isn't time running out?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the point,'' he said. ``I don't have a sense of urgency
anymore. I feel like I'm more in balance.''
</P>
<P>
   How much difficulty would he have controlling that old sense of
urgency if Sunday dawns and there he is again, in the fray, the
weight of all those other Sundays dragging behind him? ``It won't
affect me at all,'' he said. ``It's like riding a bike. If you get
the chance to win, you're going after it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has ridden the bike here eight times and has fallen off eight
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me if this place owes me one,'' Norman said.
``I don't believe in that. I believe you go out and play well and
get them yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   As he said this, I'm pretty sure I saw him holding the steering
wheel out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
