</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ROPES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swing doctors: Mending an ailing game
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ They stand on the driving range or putting green,
arms crossed, dark sunglasses on, legs lock-kneed at shoulder's
width, like security guards in Panama hats. With earplugs, they
would pass for golf's version of the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   They know something you don't: what makes the world's best
players tick. They are the golf instructors, grooming their most
famous students at the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Most easily slip into the crowds to spy on how well their
proteges are applying their teachings. Others are recognizable,
including Greg Norman's guru David Leadbetter, now starring in his
own shoe commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the top players summon their instructors here to
fine-tune swings and putting strokes, coach on-course strategy and,
not the least, stroke egos humbled by Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   On the range, the teachers stand next to the caddies,
occasionally pointing and nodding as their students strike balls
that follow repetitious parabolas. Even though the golf swing takes
only a few seconds, the teacher's eye seizes on the tiniest lapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just more of a reaffirming in your mind that your swing
is in the right groove,'' Norman said after shooting 68 Friday,
``and if it's not in the right groove, it's very easy to sometimes
change it when he's there, because you pick up two or three things
that you're not doing right.''
</P>
<P>
   You know Ernie Els has got to feel good when probably the most
important person in his life this week, Robert Baker, proclaims:
``His whole game is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, though, the pros share something with the common
golfer, in that they tend to do the same things wrong. Even Els.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ernie's very, very flexible, so we want to make his swing
short,'' said Baker, a fellow South African now based in Orlando,
Fla. He paid house calls to 35 tournaments last year to help
students, who this week include Tim Herron and amateur Trevor
Immelman.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Harmon is helping Tiger Woods slow his swing down, ``so
it's not out of control. We're working on the pace of his golf
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most relaxed I've ever seen Tiger at a major,''
Harmon said. ``He feels great about his game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is family reunion week for Harmon. He has three brothers in
the field: Craig teaches Jeff Sluman, Billy teaches Jay Haas, and
Dick teaches Steve Elkington and Craig Stadler.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Claude, won the 1948 Masters, and 55-year-old
Butch, the oldest son, remembers his mother putting him on a leash
so he wouldn't run all over the course.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Harmon has observed the Masters' pressure from many
angles, but that doesn't make him more nervous about giving
counsel. ``It's a matter of reinforcing things and giving
support,'' he said, ``to keep their confidence and energy level
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Harmon's other student, Mark Calcavecchia, has been
struggling with his putting. And his swing? ``Mark's had a little
problem with his short irons lately,'' Harmon said. ``We're working
on the mechanics of his takeaway and his position at the top. ''
</P>
<P>
   Got that? A listener unfamiliar with the game easily could get
lost in the golf-speak. The instructors are like physicians who
can't help but talk in medical terms; there's a special language to
dissect the anatomy of the swing. Baker even said he's on call ``in
case there's a hiccup in the short game or a couple of bad shots.''
</P>
<P>
   And none of these docs is performing major surgery this week.
``We did most of the work two weeks ago,'' Harmon said. ``If you're
having to do that here, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
