<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-SIDE10-CO     04-09 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SIDE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olazabal steps into lead
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ He once went to a doctor who treated his back and
healed his foot troubles, so it's only fitting that Jose Maria
Olazabal _ who had recent difficulties hitting fairways _ would
come to the Masters at an extended Augusta National and discover
his long game.
</P>
<P>
   This paragon and paradox used his daring and aggression on a
course that's playing more difficult than ever to ascend to the top
of a leaderboard splattered with champions. He shot a 6-under 66
Friday for a two-day total of 136, leaving him one stroke ahead of
Scott McCarron and at least two shots in front of a star-studded
group.
</P>
<P>
   And this from a guy who on Tuesday described his swing as
``so-so.'' It would seem weird if it were anyone but Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow I managed to go through two good rounds in a row,''
Olazabal said. ``When I said `so-so,' I was not ready but not too
bad. But when you score well, it makes it look better.''
</P>
<P>
   When Olazabal's feet got better, he said he saw no reason not to
return to the prominence that wrought him a green jacket in 1994.
But there was a time that he even wondered if he'd play again. In
'95, a mysterious ailment caused his feet to hurt so much that he
couldn't even walk _ and missed 18 months of playing.
</P>
<P>
   He watched the '96 Masters on television in his home in Spain
and spent much of his time with his feet propped up listening to
music and reading. He went to several doctors, none of whom could
alleviate the pain. ``I reached a time when I thought about the
possibilities of not playing again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a physician in Germany applied therapy on his back and the
pain in his feet diminished. ``My feet are not causing me any
problem right now,'' he said. ``I try not to think too much about
what happened in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   However (here comes another contradiction), he admitted that his
past performances at Augusta National have aided his handling of
the course to this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps everybody who's played here enough,'' he said. ``I
won in '94 and it makes me feel better than someone who hasn't won
before.''
</P>
<P>
   He played better than everyone Friday, perhaps because he
attacked the course instead of being tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Augusta National) gives me a chance to use my imagination a
little more, especially around the greens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-5 15th, where most everyone laid up in front of the
water, Olazabal screamed his second shot onto and behind the green
with a 1-iron, pitched to within inches and tapped in for a birdie
to go 7 under.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was so aggressive on a hole he called ``scary,'' he
said, jokingly: ``Because I got a 6 there (Thursday).''
</P>
<P>
   There were no 6s on Friday, no bogeys at all. And hitting 11 of
14 fairways after a period of uneasy driving speaks for how
accurate he suddenly has become off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain about my driving,'' he said. ``Today was
good, yesterday not great. At least I got them on the fairways.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not all he did. His birdies _ on Nos. 2, 6, 11, 13, 15
and 18 _ were the product of firing at the pins, deft shot-making
and quality putting. He got a break on 13 Thursday when a
line-drive 4-iron bounced over the creek and onto the green,
setting up an eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes breaks are necessary, and many times, saving par is
just as critical and making birdies. And Olazabal seemed just as
proud of doing so on holes 5 and 7 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great, but it's a wide-open tournament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
