<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TORTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TO ALLOW U.N. RIGHTS INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ A U.N. investigator said Friday that China
had agreed to allow him to examine allegations of torture in China.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator, Nigel Rodley, said China had invited him to
visit and that he planned a tour early next year. Rodley, a British
law professor, began asking China four years ago to allow a visit.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual report to the U.N. Human Rights Commission, Rodley
said dozens of people had reportedly been tortured in China.
</P>
<P>
   He cited Tibetan religious figures, including two nuns who he
said had been ``subjected to harsh interrogation and ill
treatment,'' including beatings and solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Rodley said he would ask China to allow him to visit Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch, the advocacy and monitoring organization,
suggested that China's agreement to allow the trip was ``part of a
careful game of modulated concessions'' intended to avert censure
at the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Because of China's recent crackdown on pro-democracy advocates,
the United States plans to sponsor a resolution by the commission
criticizing China's human rights policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
