<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT &LR;      04-09 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISONERS
</P>
<P>
   A Cypriot envoy said he had failed to win the release of three
captured American soldiers in talks with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and blamed continued NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   DIPLOMACY
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin warned NATO not to drag Russia into the
Kosovo conflict, saying it could spark a far wider war.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov would meet in Oslo next
week to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan called on Yugoslavia to stop
all action by military and paramilitary forces in Kosovo and
withdraw them from the province. The call was part of a five-point
program of commitments to be presented to Belgrade to bring an end
to the crisis.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia continued for a 17th day. Alliance
supreme commander Gen. Wesley Clark said the bombing would continue
``regardless of the diplomatic atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting and gunfire were reported on the Albania-Kosovo border.
The Yugoslav army accused Albania of mounting an artillery attack
against its border guards during an attempt ``by a large group of
armed terrorists'' to cross into Kosovo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. high commissioner for refugees said more than 620,000
people have left Kosovo since conflict broke out in the province in
March 1998. The number of refugees who fled the province after NATO
airstrikes began March 24 to Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro
exceeded 487,000.
</P>
<P>
   A headquarters for the 8,000-strong force that NATO plans to
deploy in Albania to help cope with the refugee influx will be
established by April 16, a NATO spokesman Jamie P. Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   Two senior Yugoslav officials met Ibrahim Rugova, moderate
political leader of the Kosovo Albanians, to discuss ``the
follow-up of the political process'' and the means to find a
solution to the current situation in Kosovo, the official Tanjug
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Kosovo is available from
The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
