<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P INDEXES SET NEW HIGHS ONCE AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   A rally in technology shares helped lift both the Nasdaq
composite index and Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index to records
for a fourth time this week. The Nasdaq jumped 19.66 points, to
2,593.05, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 4.37
points, to 1,348.35.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average faltered as traders took
profits on blue-chip issues. The Dow fell 23.86 points, to
10,173.84. The average of 30 blue-chip stocks rose to record levels
three times this week, including on Thursday, when it closed at
10,197.70. Despite Friday's decline, the Dow is up 10.81 percent so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 5.46 percent,
from 5.44 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. LOSES BIG BANKING CASE
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered the government to pay nearly $909
million to Glendale Federal Bank, a California savings association
that nearly went bankrupt after Congress and the Bush
administration imposed tougher accounting standards on the industry
a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   A LOSS FOR A NURSING HOME OPERATOR
</P>
<P>
   Sun Healthcare Group reported heavy losses for the fourth
quarter and all of 1998, mainly as the result of severe cuts in
Medicare payments for elderly nursing home patients.
</P>
<P>
   COURT RULES AGAINST COCA-COLA BID
</P>
<P>
   France's highest administrative court refused to overturn a
government ruling that had blocked the sale of Orangina to
Coca-Cola. The French government has been concerned that the sale
would give Coca-Cola control of too much of the soft-drink market
in France. Coca-Cola must now negotiate a compromise with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM ITALIA HOLDERS WEIGH BID
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of Telecom Italia will decide Saturday whether to
approve the company's proposed defense against Olivetti's $65
billion takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH DEAL FOR TEAM BLOCKED
</P>
<P>
   The British government blocked British Sky Broadcasting's $1
billion deal for the English soccer team Manchester United. It was
the third major setback this year to Rupert Murdoch's plans for
expansion in television and sports broadcasting in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES LISTS PUNITIVE TARIFFS
</P>
<P>
   The United States issued a final list of European products that
will be subject to 100 percent tariffs in retaliation for the
European Union's levies on bananas. To the delight of some
Europeans, the list excluded many products that had been on the
original one, including Italian pecorino cheese and cashmere
sweaters from Scotland. The World Trade Organization allowed
Washington to raise $191.4 million in sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANS CANCEL EUROPEAN TRIPS
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Balkans conflict and refugee crisis, Americans
are scrapping plans for leisure and business travel well beyond the
combat zone.
</P>
<P>
   GENENTECH CAUGHT IN DUAL SETBACKS
</P>
<P>
   The biotechnology company Genentech was caught in double
setbacks. It said Neuleze, its highly anticipated drug to promote
nerve growth in diabetes patients, had not worked in late-stage
clinical trials. The company also said that it was negotiating a
$50 million settlement to resolve federal charges that it had
illegally marketed a growth hormone for uses not approved by the
FDA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
