<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS KEEP FOCUS AND FIRE IN RAINY HOME OPENER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ohio, Conn.)   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Footprints became man-made ponds in the Yankee
Stadium infield Friday, and there were likely to be more
groundskeepers than players on the field at any given moment. The
Yankees' home opener was all about mud stains, rakes and drying
compound.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees played as if it were a comfortable 78 degrees,
said the Detroit catcher Brad Ausmus, the pinstriped hitters
ignoring human instinct and patiently waiting in the relentless,
cold rain for a good pitch. With the same deliberate approach they
used so impressively in winning a record total of 125 games in
1998, the defending World Series champion Yankees dismantled the
Tigers, 12-3, before the umpires mercifully waved for the tarp and
ended the game with two out in the bottom of the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the Yankees' trauma and dysfunction in spring
training, they are already playing .750 ball with three victories
and one loss.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone did not allow a hit until the sixth inning Friday,
taking advantage of the aggressiveness of Detroit's hitters, and
Chili Davis had four hits, including a grand slam. Yogi Berra, who
threw out the ceremonial first pitch, was about the only person who
appeared on the field without getting drenched.
</P>
<P>
   Cone changed his undershirt six times, fielders stood with their
hands tucked inside their jerseys like so many Napoleons and gloves
and spikes and caps were soaked. All 56,583 tickets were sold, but
most fans whose seats were in unprotected areas scurried for cover,
departed or never arrived, leaving whole sections unfilled, save
for the ushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These conditions were as bad as I've ever played in,'' said
Joe Girardi, the Yankees' catcher. ``I mean, by the fourth inning,
there was standing water all over the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Ausmus added: ``The field was soaked. These were the worst
conditions I've seen _ and I played in snow in high school.''
</P>
<P>
   A human reaction to such conditions is to seek shelter, and as
several players mentioned after the game, some hitters will attack
aggressively under such squalid conditions, hoping to determine
their fate as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   As several Tigers mentioned to one another during the game,
however, the Yankee batters never flinched, never changed their
approach in the rain against Beiker Graterol, a right-hander making
his major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Chuck Knoblauch stepped out of the box after every
pitch, methodically adjusted his gloves and touched his helmet as
sheets of rain drenched him. Paul O'Neill stepped back and
practiced his swing between offerings. Winds were blowing in
hitters' faces, rain obscured the pitcher as he delivered the ball,
thick raindrops fell from the brims of their caps, and through it
all, the Yankees waited for Graterol and his relievers to throw
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in those elements is a question of mind over matter,''
said Willie Randolph, the Yankees' third base coach.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen of the Yankees' first 17 hitters took the first pitch in
their at-bat, and 9 of the first 17 took the first two pitches.
``They'll make you throw strikes, and then when you do, they'll
murder you if you make a mistake,'' said Doug Brocail, a Tigers
reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez slugged a home run to open the second inning, and
Graterol had thrown 28 pitches by the time Scott Brosius batted one
out later; Brosius lifted a two-run home run into the left-field
stands.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Derek Jeter walked on seven pitches,
O'Neill walked after fouling off three two-strike pitches and
Martinez was intentionally passed after a groundout advanced the
runners. Having learned all they needed to know about Graterol, the
Yankee hitters seemed locked in on his consistent use of the lower
half of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander threw a change-up to Davis, who reached down
and golfed a line drive over the wall in right field, the eighth
grand slam of his career. The Yankees had a 7-0 lead after three
innings, the rain fell steadily and there was some concern that the
umpires might stop the game before the completion of the Tiger
fifth, the point at which the game would be official.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Girardi said, he made a point of swinging at
the first pitch leading off the fourth inning, to speed the game
along.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi's teammates, however, continued with all deliberate
speed, to the point that Randolph started yelling at them from the
third base coach's box: ``C'mon, let's go, swing the bat, let's get
moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (1-3) swung aggressively throughout, as they usually
do, and Cone seemed to exploit this. He walked seven batters, three
in the sixth inning before he departed, but the Tigers nonetheless
appeared to help him at times, often swinging wildly at high
fastballs or the breaking balls he spun out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Strikes resulted from just 55 of his 104 pitches, but Cone
probably had a much lower percentage of pitches in the strike zone,
perhaps 30 percent. He pitched high and low, and the Tigers chased
high and low. The Yankees chased nothing.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees batted and went deep into ball-strike counts,
Ausmus recalled, it seemed as if the Tigers stood on the field for
30 minutes at a time, in the cold and the rain and the wind,
building ponds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
