<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORT-REFORM-BILL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strategic mistakes led to delay of key tort reform bill,
lawmakers say
 &HT;    Sen. Troy Fraser: Perry's point man for tort reform had trouble
getting bill out of his subcommittee.
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Strategic miscalculations by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry
and Sen. Troy Fraser, his point man on tort reform, left a key bill
stranded in a subcommittee for three weeks, jeopardizing its
chances of passing the Legislature this late in the session,
several key lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry denied any miscues and said bringing up the bill for a
Senate vote as late as next week should not harm its chances for
final legislative approval.
</P>
<P>
   But senators and lobbyists on both sides of the issue said
privately that Perry's referral of the bill directly to Fraser's
subcommittee, which is handling all tort reform legislation this
session, led to leaving the legislation in limbo for three weeks
after its hearing because the subcommittee did not have enough
votes to pass it. If Perry had referred the bill to the full
Economic Development Committee, the committee chairman _ the bill's
sponsor, Sen. David Sibley (R-Waco) _ could have brought it up to
the full committee for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser tried Tuesday to get the full Senate's permission to
refer the bill to Sibley's committee without a subcommittee vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser withdrew the request after senators protested that it
violated Senate procedures. The bill passed out of his subcommittee
on technology and business growth Thursday. Senators and lobbyists
advocating the tort reform effort say Houston developer Dick
Weekley, the driving force behind Texans for Tort Reform, was
``livid'' and ``went berserk'' about the delay in getting the bill
to the Senate floor. Weekley denied that and said the delay does
not mean the bill is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Tort reform is a moniker for efforts to impose limits on damages
paid by businesses in personal-injury lawsuits and to otherwise
restrict lawsuits. Some of the Legislature's most powerful lobbies,
business and trial lawyers, have battled over tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
