<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2843 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      04-09 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ACCORDS WITH CHINA BILLED AS ICING BECOME PART OF A SIMPLER
CAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China and the United States took steps Friday to
protect the environment and to increase airline traffic between the
two countries, but Prime Minister Zhu Rongji left little doubt that
he considered those agreements a poor substitute for the big trade
deal that he hoped to clinch as the centerpiece of his visit.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Chinese officials voiced deep disappointment at
their inability to win U.S. backing for China's application to join
the World Trade Organization. In a private meeting with members of
Congress on Friday morning at Blair House, Zhu vented his
frustration that President Clinton ``did not dare'' to complete the
trade accord, according to people who attended. The failure left
Zhu to continue on his U.S. tour without the prize he had sought.
</P>
<P>
   In a dinner address Friday night, Zhu continued voicing his
displeasure over the way the Clinton administration handled the
trade negotiations. Zhu emphasized that even Friday night,
negotiators were still deep in discussions to hammer out an interim
agreement that would allow the two sides to resume negotiations
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely the American side realizes that the time has come to
end negotiations which have already gone on for 13 years,'' Zhu
told his audience at the Willard Hotel. ``Surely the time has come
to end these talks and move forward to open new channels of
U.S.-China trade.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Blair House meeting Friday morning, members of Congress
argued that China had regressed in its human rights performance
since Clinton's state visit there last summer and pressed the prime
minister to explain why. Some cited specific cases to illustrate
their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements and the human rights confrontation came on the
final day of Zhu's stay in Washington. He is to leave Saturday
morning for Denver, followed by stops in Chicago, New York and
Boston. Chinese officials hope those stops on Zhu's trip will give
him a chance to interact with ordinary Americans and to escape the
charged political climate in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the deadlock over trade talks Thursday, the two
sides were able to finish several accords Friday. Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright signed a
pact that doubles, to 54 from 27, the number of weekly flights
between the countries. By 2001, when the increase takes effect,
each side will also have the right to add one airline company to
the three on each side that now fly the trans-Pacific route.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu and Vice President Al Gore spent much of the day presiding
over a forum on the environment. The two countries, the world's
biggest producers of greenhouse gases thought by many experts to
cause global warming, signed an accord that provides U.S. financing
for clean-air projects in China. They also witnessed the signing of
a commercial agreement to build a natural gas pipeline in southern
China.
</P>
<P>
   Though the environment is a special area of focus for Gore, it
was Zhu, at least in the public session, who appeared more eager to
discuss the details of the two countries' environmental policies.
In contrast to Gore, who read some perfunctory opening remarks from
notes, the prime minister discarded his prepared speech after a few
minutes and spoke off-the-cuff, in some detail, about the
seriousness of the country's pollution problems and his efforts to
bring them under control.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu spoke frankly of ``the devastation of Mother Nature'' in
China as a result of soil erosion, deforestation, and emissions
from factories, cars and coal-burning furnaces, the country's main
source of heat. He also called closer environmental cooperation one
of the keys to reducing what the United States estimates is a $57
billion trade deficit with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would even say that you could wipe out your large trade
deficit, or turn the trade deficit into a surplus,'' Zhu said,
citing China's big appetite for technology and expertise to clean
up air and water supplies. ``If that happens, I would be very
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Friday's agreements related to the environment will not
make much of a dent in China's huge trade surplus, though
administration officials called them useful steps toward a broader
environmental alliance that could lead to robust trade in the
future. The highlight was a $100 million deal under which the U.S.
Export-Import Bank will finance the export of U.S. clean-air
technology to China, including projects to make more efficient use
of energy and to reduce pollution from existing power sources.
</P>
<P>
   Though administration officials had hoped that several companies
that might benefit from such financing would announce commercial
agreements Friday, no contracts were made public. Officials said
they expect at least several U.S. companies to push forward with
clean-air projects in China shortly.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate commercial deal, Enron and China National
Petroleum Corporation signed a memorandum of understanding at the
environmental forum for the joint development of a natural gas
pipeline in south central China.
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States also took a first step toward
setting up a United States-style emission trading regime in China.
Polluters in America have the right to buy and sell emissions
quotas, which some environmental experts have praised as a way of
using the market to help solve pollution problems. China has so far
resisted adopting that kind of mechanism, but administration
officials said Zhu was at least prepared to experiment with the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast meeting at Blair House, the guest house near the
White House where heads of state often stay when visiting
Washington, was attended by 15 members of the House of
Representatives and the Senate. Zhu, true to his promise early in
the week to allow critics free reign to voice their frustrations
with China, did almost no talking during the session, people who
attended it said. But in some opening remarks he expressed distress
over the failure to conclude talks over China's accession to the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress said they were surprised when Zhu,
speaking through an interpreter, said he believed that Clinton
lacked the ``courage'' to try to push the agreement through
Congress now, given recent allegations of Chinese spying. The
language was unusually blunt and undiplomatic, even though Zhu has
shown several times that he will speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   But at the conclusion of the session, Chinese officials
approached several members of Congress offering what they called a
more accurate translation. Zhu's words should have been translated
as the verb ``dare to'' not the noun ``courage,'' they said, adding
that the prime minister in no way intended to challenge Clinton
directly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Zhu's frustration was evident, some said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure he expected the climate to be as difficult as it
has been,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who attended the session
and who supports China's entry into the trade organization. ``In
the end he made a strong pitch for us to step up to the plate and
get it done, though I am a little concerned that this will drift
now because we missed the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The members of Congress also pressed Zhu to improve China's
human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Wu, R-Ore., praised America's open political system
for giving him, an immigrant from China, the chance to serve in
Congress. He then brought to Zhu's attention the arrest of a
19-year-old high school graduate from Wu's own home province of
Jiangsu, near Shanghai. The youth was sentenced to serve 10 years
in prison for writing an essay on corruption in the Communist
Party, Wu said. Zhu did not respond to that case or defend China's
rights record in the forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
