<DOCNO> NYT19990409.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2851 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HUNGER-1STLD-W     04-09 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HUNGER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DANGER FOR ETHNIC ALBANIANS IN KOSOVO: STARVATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 4th and 5th grafs. Light rewrite of lede and
first several grafs.) (See also: KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-RUSSIA,
KOSOVO-SURVEIL, KOSOVO-RELIEF, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-RUGOVA.) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About 700,000 ethnic Albanians have been uprooted
from their homes by the Yugoslavs and are still in Kosovo facing
the risk of famine as food stocks quickly dwindle, administration
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have considered air drops of food but rejected the
idea as too dangerous for NATO pilots, who would have to fly at low
levels and risk being hit by Yugoslav ground fire, an official
said. The gravity of the situation is becoming clearer as analysts
study satellite imagery of the destruction in Kosovo and interview
refugees who have escaped, but few specifics have been made public.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, President Clinton spoke about Kosovo for the
fifth day in a row and continued his public attacks on President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, accusing him of blocking the
escape routes of ethnic Albanians by sealing the borders.
</P>
<P>
   The border with Albania, which was closed by the Yugoslavs on
Wednesday, was reopened Friday night, at least temporarily, and
about 2,000 refugees were reported to have entered Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Only a trickle of refugees got across the border into Macedonia,
which essentially remains closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic still thinks he can manipulate the situation by
cynically using innocent people,'' Clinton said. ``He hopes that we
will accept as permanent the results of his ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would not accept Milosevic's offer of a
cease-fire, which was accompanied by the border closings, saying a
quarter of Kosovo's people are living in camps outside Kosovo while
``hundreds of thousands'' more are trapped inside, afraid to go
home but unable to leave.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the NATO bombing began, the
administration released details Friday of young ethnic Albanian
women being raped by Yugoslav soldiers at an army training camp
near the town of Dakovica.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said a single, but
reliable, source had provided ``very disturbing reports'' of mass
rapes, and it was believed that as many as 20 women may have been
killed. Bacon said the report was given added credence because it
fit the pattern of mass rapes by Yugoslav soldiers during the
Bosnian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, the American ambassador at large for
war crimes, David Scheffer, gave a public briefing on interviews he
made with refugees in Macedonia last week. The refugees, he said,
described the execution of military-age ethnic Albanian men and the
burning of villages.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden rush of information from the administration Friday on
atrocities committed by Milosevic's troops appeared aimed in part
at keeping up the public support for the airstrikes. The details
released by Scheffer Friday were not new: He returned from
Macedonia last weekend and his report was posted on the Internet
midweek.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls show that the American people are in favor
of the air campaign on the grounds that it is an assault against a
brutal dictator.
</P>
<P>
   But as the administration releases details of the atrocities,
officials must carefully calibrate the timing and tenor of the
information so that it does not appear that the NATO bombing is the
major cause of the calamity inside the province.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of information on the brutalities in Kosovo contrasts
with the denials by Washington that the Yugoslavs were holding
Bosnian Muslims in concentration camps in the early stages of the
Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Milosevic, by closing the borders of Kosovo two
days ago, was using the tactic of holding hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanians virtually hostage inside the province.
</P>
<P>
   With diminishing supplies of food and water, the ethnic
Albanians would increasingly suffer, officials said, putting the
Western allies in the awkward position of watching the population
it was trying to help, suffer even more.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's ploy of threatening to starve the remaining
population in Kosovo was already drawing the kind of attention that
the administration, adamant about not negotiating with Milosevic,
might find difficult to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. high commissioner for refugees was considering asking
NATO and Belgrade for permission to send an assessment team to
Kosovo to look at the food situation, a European diplomat said
Friday. Such a proposal would have to be negotiated with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of starvation inside Kosovo was of mounting
concern, an administration official said, because some of the
displaced people have been outdoors since before the NATO bombing
began.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were believed to be about 700,000 people who had been
thrown out of their homes by the Yugoslavs who had found other
accommodation or were camping in the outdoors, the official said.
He could not estimate how many of the roughly 700,000 were outdoors
or indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Those most threatened with starvation were in the Shala
Mountains, the Berisha Hills and the Cicavica Hills, where people
were camping much as they were last autumn when 250,000 ethnic
Albanians came down from the hills after a ceasefire agreement with
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have said for nearly two weeks that they believed
the condition of the ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo was far worse
than that of those who were expelled or had escaped.
</P>
<P>
   There were probably still stocks of food in Kosovo, the
administration official who has studied the intelligence reports
said, but the food was not near the displaced people who were
camped in the hills to avoid the Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   It was known, from officials of the Kosovo Verification Mission,
who evacuated from Kosovo five days before the bombing began, that
Yugoslav soldiers had torched large amounts of the food stocks
owned by ethnic Albanians. These officials also reported that the
last harvest, because of the upsurge in fighting, was very slim.
</P>
<P>
   A European military official said air drops had been rejected by
NATO last week as too risky. If planes assigned to air drops of
food flew high enough to avoid Yugoslav ground fire, the food
packages would probably be ruined by the time they hit the ground
or could fall into the hands of Yugoslavs.
</P>
<P>
   But, the military official said, the food situation was
deteriorating so fast that the possibility of air drops should be
examined again.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing some sketchy information about the reports of mass
rapes and the murder of as many as 20 women, Bacon drew some
parallels with the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very eerie and disturbing echo of documented
instances of rape and killing of women in Bosnia during the Bosnian
war, and it is obviously outrageous that this is occurring,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a reliable report, but it is not completely
confirmed yet,'' he said. ``Two things, I think, make it reliable.
One is the source, and I can't get into details about that. But,
two, it fits a pattern that we've seen in the Balkans before.`
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Pentagon would attempt to confirm the reports of
the rapes and murders at Dakovica over the next few days through
interviews with refugees and `other ways.'
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have estimated that more than 30,000 women
and young girls were sexually abused by Yugoslav forces during
earlier fighting in the Balkans, especially in Bosnia. Some Bosnia
Serb rapists explicitly told their Muslim victims that their
purpose was to impregnate them with Serbian babies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
