<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENENTECH-NYT &LR;      04-09 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENENTECH DROPS NERVE DRUG FOR DIABETICS AFTER TESTS FAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genentech Inc., one of the world's largest biotechnology
companies, said Friday that Neuleze, its highly anticipated drug to
promote nerve growth in diabetes patients, would not be sold in the
United States because late-stage clinical trials had failed to
prove the compound worked.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the setback was a significant blow to Genentech
and its majority shareholder, Roche Holding AG of Switzerland.
Since Genentech and Roche would have been the first companies to
market a drug like Neuleze, peak worldwide sales could have reached
$600 million, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Genentech's trouble, the South San Francisco-based
company also said Friday that it was negotiating a settlement that
could cost it $50 million to resolve federal charges that it had
illegally marketed Protropin, a growth hormone, for uses that were
not approved by the Food and Drug Administration. If the settlement
is reached, it would be the first time that a pharmaceutical
company had been criminally prosecuted for the off-label use of a
drug, the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted casually to Genentech's woes, and the
company's stock dropped just 68.75 cents to close at $84.8125,
after trading as low as $83. The American depository receipts of
Roche fell $1.75, or 1.4 percent, to close at $125.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this news came out, we expected Genentech's stock to drop
4 percent or 5 percent,'' said Sena Lund, an analyst with Mehta
Partners. ``But that didn't happen. Investors were confident in
some of Genentech's other products, which were performing better
than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pointed to Genentech's strong oncology franchise. The
company received FDA approval in 1997 to sell Rituxan, for
non-Hodgkins lymphoma, and Herceptin last year, for metastatic
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, investors may have still other reasons to hold their
Genentech shares. Roche, which owns about two-thirds of Genentech's
stock, has until July 1 to decide whether it will buy the remaining
shares for about $82.50 each, analysts said. This option has given
Genentech's stock some unusual stability.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of Neuleze may alter the pharmaceutical market.
Several other companies _ notably Pfizer and Warner-Lambert _ are
developing similar compounds that now have their chances to be the
first to arrive on the market. Analysts noted that the first new
treatment for an illness typically outsells competitors' later
entries.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Friday, Genentech executives said that they would
continue human growth factor research similar to Neuleze, but
played down the company's troubles with the Justice Department. The
company had promoted its growth hormones for such unapproved uses
as obesity, one person at the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech said Friday that if it reached an agreement with
government attorneys in California, the $50 million fine would be
taken as a one-time charge against first-quarter earnings and would
have no lasting effect on operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
