<HEADER>
A2855 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-MASTERS-LEDE10-CO     04-09 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LEDE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olazabal pursued by Norman and pack of champions
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It's getting to be like old times at the 63rd
Masters. Next thing you know, there will be Nicklaus roars on Amen
Corner; Palmer will be going for the par 5s in two; and Tom Watson
will be breaking out the plaid bell-bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's pushing it, but guess what?
</P>
<P>
   Jose Maria Olazabal, the 1994 champion, is leading by a stroke
at 8-under-par 136 after a 6-under 66, and Greg Norman is three
shots back after a 68.
</P>
<P>
   You heard correctly. Greg Norman. Yes, there is life after the
train wreck of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad Seve Ballesteros' game is too far gone to join the
reunion. Too bad Jack's hip is still on the mend. The fun is just
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   That's wannabe Scott McCarron, who plays Augusta National better
than your average PGA Tour track, who shot a 68 to trail by a
stroke, but behind him there's enough major championship experience
for a series of Golf Channel specials.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring three missed cuts in a row, two-time U.S. Open champion
Lee Janzen saw the new Masters rough, imagined a USGA setup and
shot a 69 to stand three back at 139.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price, with three majors on his record, stalled slightly
with a 72 but is tied for fifth at 3-under 141. He's with
first-round co-leader Davis Love III of Sea Island, the 1997 PGA
champ, who could not break par, either.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Bernhard Langer, a two-time Masters champion, tied
Olazabal for low round of the day with a 66 and is at 142, along
with Scotland's Colin Montgomerie (72), Bill Glasson (70),
first-round co-leader Brandel Chamblee (73), 1995 PGA champion
Steve Elkington (70) and 1997 British Open champion Justin Leonard
(72).
</P>
<P>
   Favorite David Duval, upended by a triple-bogey 8 at the 15th
hole, slipped to a 74 and is at 1-over 145. That's a stroke worse
than 1997 Masters champion Tiger Woods, who shot a second
consecutive 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cut (top 44 and ties) came at 4-over 148, eliminating such
names as two-time champion Watson, Mark Calcavecchia, Nick Faldo
(for the third time since winning in '96) and U.S. Amateur champion
Hank Kuehne.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech amateur Matt Kuchar, who chipped in twice, rallied
for a 71 to make the cut for the second consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Norman joining the contenders was the shocker. Just when
everybody thought he might need a psychiatrist on his bag to make
another run at a green jacket after the disaster of 1996, Norman,
44, resurfaced Friday with a crowd-pleasing, nostalgic display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like riding a bike,'' Norman said, putting more meaning
in his surgically improved shoulder than the six-stroke, 54-hole
lead he squandered in 1996. ``If you get a chance to win, you're
going after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal, 33, was a bit of a surprise himself. He has suffered
lately with a misguided driver, but this week has returned to the
form that brought him a green jacket five years ago. If his Sunday
back nine shows any resemblance to his Friday one, the Spaniard
will be tough to unseat. He walked proudly up the 18th _ three
years ago, with foot problems, a painful exercise in itself _ with
a 4-under 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tournament will start most probably on the back nine of
the last day,'' Olazabal said. ``We all know that. So I'll try to
keep doing a good job the next couple of days.... I think it's a
wide open golf tournament. There are a lot of players who can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Norman, who underwent left shoulder surgery immediately
after he missed last year's cut, can do it still remains to be
seen. Coming into Augusta weakened by a virus that knocked him out
of the BellSouth Classic last week, Norman was barely mentioned in
pre-tournament speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be in this position,'' said Norman, who held the
lead alone early in the round. ``It's great when you've worked
yourself so hard to get back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a third consecutive victory and his first major
title, Duval could be out of it at nine shots off the lead. The
same for Woods, who is eight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to play better,'' Duval said, ``if I want to have a
chance Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els (71) and Phil Mickelson (69) are within range at
1-under 143. Defending champion Mark O'Meara is 10 shots back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think experience is a great factor here,'' Olazabal said.
``The more you know the course, the more you know what you have to
do, where you have to hit the ball, how you have to have to play
the holes. Day after day, you have to play well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
