<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     04-09 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHARK IS PROWLING IN A DATE WITH DESTINY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia)   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ From the 18th fairway, Greg Norman's ball floated
onto the green Friday, skipped past the flagstick and spun to a
stop about 10 feet away. The way so many of his approach shots once
did. The Masters gallery that had waited for him clapped, the way
they once did, in a burst of appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Norman still climbing the hill to the green, the
applause began. He has heard applause at the Masters since he first
arrived here in 1981, but this applause was different.
</P>
<P>
   This applause wasn't jubilant, as it was in those years when he
nearly won. It wasn't sympathetic, as it was in 1996 when he
arrived at the 18th after losing a six-shot lead as Nick Faldo flew
past him. It wasn't sad, as it was the last two years when he
missed the 36-hole cut.
</P>
<P>
   This applause resembled a warm and firm hug to an old friend.
When it turned to cheers, it lasted so long, he had to tip his
black cap half a dozen times as he strode across the green to mark
his ball.
</P>
<P>
   But when the 44-year-old Australian stood over his putt, the
silence was such that a voice was heard to say, ``This is the
quietest it's been here all day.'' He missed his birdie, to the
gallery's groan. But when he tapped in a four-under-par 68 for 139,
the applause and the cheers resumed.
</P>
<P>
   After the second round ended hours later, Jose Maria Olazabal of
Spain was the leader at 136, but Norman, the Great White Shark, was
in the hunt at the Masters, again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be in this position,'' Norman said. ``It's great
that I feel a little less sense of urgency when I approach things
on the golf course or approach things off the golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   But his golf guru, David Leadbetter, had mentioned how Norman
was so much more focused now, so Norman was asked to explain how he
could be so focused without a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Urgency is something where you're trying to force the issue,''
he said. ``I'm not trying to force it. David's been trying to let
me know how well I'm swinging, and if you're urgent with it, then
you're trying to force the issue. And if you try to force the
issue, you don't relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Norman was thinking of the strategic way he birdied the
485-yard par-5 dogleg left 13th hole with Rae's Creek to the left
of the fairway and then in front of the green. He hit a 3-wood on
the tee, laid up with a 6-iron, then spun a sand wedge to about 6
inches as the gallery cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to really play it with a lot of authority because you
needed the backspin,'' he said. ``You only have about 4 yards of
green up top to play with. If you don't get much spin on it, it's
over the back of the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman has always had philosophical explanations whether he's
playing well or badly, whether he lost the 1987 Masters playoff
when Larry Mize chipped in on the second hole, or whether he shot
78 in his collapse against Faldo after shooting a record-tying 63
in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   When he mentioned, ``I've always believed in destiny,'' he was
asked what he thought his destiny was for this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my destiny is,'' he said. ``Somebody asked
me, `Does this place owe you one?' I don't believe in things
getting owed to you. I think you go out there and play well enough
to get them yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman continued: ``What is the definition of destiny? I've
played here long enough to see where things have happened for me
and against me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that really sticks in my mind is what happened to
Freddy Couples on the front of 12 when his ball hung up there,''
Norman said, referring to Couples' victory in 1992. ``No other ball
in the entire tournament hung up there. Is that destiny or a little
bit of luck?''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after missing the Masters cut last year, Norman underwent
surgery on his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the way I came back to play in the Presidents Cup late
last year,'' he said of the December event in Melbourne, Australia,
``I felt I was back on the horse I was riding before.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the sentimental favorite, Norman has the Masters gallery
rooting for him. His wife, Laura, knew why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found that people inside are basically good, that
everyone has had a certain amount of heartache in their life, and a
lot of people have definitely seen Greg's heartache here,'' she
said of his 1996 collapse. ``But he just loves it here. Loves the
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman would love it even more if he were to be wearing a
green jacket Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
