<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-09 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     04-09 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MICHAEL JORDAN ADDS A YANKEE SHORTSTOP TO HIS TEAM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Jordan sat in a luxury suite at Yankee
Stadium Friday afternoon, watching the Yankees open the season by
annihilating Detroit in a rain-shortened game, and adding to his
growing aura of invincibility. Jordan said he was on hand as a fan,
though he admitted that it took more than his love of the game to
come out on a miserable Friday. In fact, Jordan was also on hand to
support Derek Jeter, his latest client and a player who, in many
ways, reminds Jordan of his athletic self.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Jordan announced that the Yankees' fabulous
shortstop had joined Jordan Brand, a sub-brand of Nike that was
created in 1997. The line of sports apparel has a Jumpman logo, a
silhouette of a soaring Jordan. Jordan Brand will be endorsed by a
collection of athletes, handpicked by Jordan, who he feels
exemplify the virtues of his National Basketball Association
career. In Jeter's case, Jordan sees a mirror image: a shortstop
with speed and power; great defensive range. Also a player with a
sense of fashion, style and a folk-hero appeal that goes beyond the
sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's legit,'' Jordan said of Jeter. ``He's versatile; you see
him on the cover of GQ, then the next week he's on the cover of
Sports Illustrated. He's focused, he works hard. He's in a major
market with a lot of pressure, but he handles the pressure. I'm
proud of him; I'm glad we're working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Jeter sported a pair of Air Jordan cleats and Jumpman
wristbands. ``We're still trying to develop a product for him,''
Jordan said. ``What we like is that he's a positive role model,
reflects a positive image. He's unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Jordan sat and talked with Jeter's parents, who recently
relocated to New Jersey. When Jeter reached first base in the third
and sixth innings, Jordan, ever the competitor, exhorted him to
steal second.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's partnership with Jeter and subsequent association with
the Yankees represents another variation of the corporate symmetry
of the 1990s. Jordan is one of the greatest athletes of this
century. The Yankees, who raised their 24th world championship flag
Friday, are the most storied professional sports franchise of the
century. The 24-year-old Jeter, through his glove, bat and
presence, is on the verge of establishing an individual identity in
the context of a fiercely team-oriented game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want there to be a mystique connected to being part of the
Jordan Brand,'' Jordan said. ``Not something everybody will be
involved with.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jeter was leaving the Stadium, he said the decision to go
with Jordan Brand was a no-brainer. ``It was an easy decision,'' he
said. ``Measure what he stands for on and off the court. I don't
know if there's an athlete out there who wouldn't want to be
affiliated.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who was already a Nike athlete, joins Randy Moss, the
Minnesota Vikings' wide receiver, the boxer Roy Jones and five NBA
players who endorse Jordan Brand. Jeter is special because of his
youth, his sport, his affiliation with the Yankees and his unique
blend of talent and appeal. ``We want to expand from basketball,''
Jordan said. ``This is something that's new, something different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are definitely part of a new modern mystique. But
unlike Jordan's NBA, or the National Football League's success,
Major League Baseball is not quite as mysterious anymore: it boils
down to which team has the most money to spend. Friday's opening
day, a lopsided victory on a rain-swept afternoon, may mark the
shape of things to come. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Bob Sheppard's golden voice floated from the
public address system over the Bronx and Harlem. Sheppard recounted
the Yankees' 1998 record: 125 victories and 50 losses. As Phil
Rizzuto and Whitey Ford raised the world championship banner,
Sheppard proudly said, ``The flag we are about to raise is a symbol
of courage, conviction and everlasting truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He forgot to mention the 1999 Yankees' $86 million payroll, the
highest in baseball. Money gives a backbone to courage, glue to
conviction and a rosy color to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees opened the season by taking 2 of 3 from the Oakland
Athletics, a team with a $22 million payroll. Detroit has a $35
million payroll. If the corollary between money and winning holds
true, the Yankees' stiffest tests will be Baltimore ($81.4 million)
and Texas ($75 million).
</P>
<P>
   Is it all about money? Of course not: Jeter, the player Jordan
so admires, is the product of the Yankees' farm system, as are
Ricky Ledee and Andy Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of wealth is that money can buy what the farm can't
grow. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
