</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- April 9, 1999 -- CHINA-U.S.-TRADE, 4-09 --
From left, Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan and Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji pose
for photographers at Blair House on Friday. It is too early to tell
what the long-term impact of Friday's failure to reach a trade deal
with China may be. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TOKYO -- April 9, 1999 -- JAPAN-BEETLES, 4-09 --
Katsutoshi Misaki, the insect salesman at Tobu Department Store in
Tokyo, showing off a $300 ohkuwagata, or Japanese stag beetle. Five
or 10 years ago, before the beetle market crashed, it might have
sold for $6,000. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) KUKES, Albania -- April 9, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SURVEIL-3,
4-09 -- An Italian worker checking tents in Kukes. Three days after
Serbian troops closed border crossing points from Kosovo into
Macedonia and Albania, NATO reconnaissance planes have failed to
locate any of the tens of thousands of refugees who were turned
back from the frontier. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) KUKES, Albania -- April 9, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SURVEIL-2,
4-09 -- Italian workers unloading tents (to be assembled) from
trucks in Kukes. Three days after Serbian troops closed border
crossing points from Kosovo into Macedonia and Albania, NATO
reconnaissance planes have failed to locate any of the tens of
thousands of refugees who were turned back from the frontier.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) KUKES, Albania -- April 9, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SURVEIL-1,
4-09 -- An aerial view of a nearly complete tent city in Kukes.
Three days after Serbian troops closed border crossing points from
Kosovo into Macedonia and Albania, NATO reconnaissance planes have
failed to locate any of the tens of thousands of refugees who were
turned back from the frontier. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEPROSTINO, Macedonia -- April 9, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, 4-09 -- Serr Jashari, 82, an ethnic Albanian
refugee from a town near Pristina, in a temporary home in a tent
camp in Neprostino. She crossed the border into Macedonia on Friday
after waiting for nine days on the Yugoslav side. (Alan Chin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) LOS ANGELES -- April 9, 1999 -- CELEBRITY-CHEFS, 4-09 --
Joachim Splichal, chef and owner of Patina in Los Angeles. Today's
hot chef is a multimedia wizard. As well-known culinary figures
spend less time in the kitchen and more in front of cameras or on
book tours, publicists help them secure all sorts of
extracurricular activities, from kitchenware endorsements to
consulting, book writing and selling products (including
themselves) on Web sites. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- BIBLIOWICZ-NATIONAL, 4-08
-- Jessica M. Bibliowicz has been named chief executive of National
Finance Partners, a start-up financial-services company. Ms.
Bibliowicz is the daughter of Sanford I. Weill, co-chief of
Citigroup. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- April 9, 1999 -- CLINTON-HEALTH, 4-09 --
President Clinton walking to the South Lawn of the White House on
Friday with Chief of Staff John Podesta, left, and Gen. Donald
Kerrick. Clinton made a brief statement on Kosovo before departing
for a trip to Philadelphia to try to whip up public enthusiasm for
the Democratic proposal to establish a ``patient's bill of
rights.'' (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BLUE ASH, Ohio -- April 9, 1999 -- OHIO-TORNADO, 04-09
-- This aerial photograph shows the damage done in this upscale
suburb of Cincinnati as homes were destroyed by a powerful tornado
and thunderstorms. The National Weather Service's Storm Prediction
Center reported 63 tornado sightings in Iowa, Missouri, Nebraska
and Illinois on Thursday and Friday. (Ty Greenlees/Dayton Daily
News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
MILK-DEREG, 4-09 -- The complicated path to policy on the
production and pricing of milk pricing was recently lampooned by
Citizens Against government Waste. Federal milk-pricing rules
dating from the 1930s drive up the price that consumers pay for
milk, in effect taking money from urban parents, among others, and
handing it over to rural dairy farmers. (Barbara Alper/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11
-- FCC-KENNARD-PROFILE, 4-09 -- William E. Kennard says his mother,
Helen, far right, and his father showed him the value of cultural
diversity. As FCC chairman, he has tried to show how
telecommunications issues are linked to social issues. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 11 -- MERGER-TROUBLESHOOTERS-3, 4-09 -- General Electric
teams have assembled a data base on mergers. Don Borwhat, at left,
human resources senior vice president at GE Fanuc Automation, talks
with colleagues. (Dean Hoffmeyer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MURRAY HILL, N.J. -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 11 -- MERGER-TROUBLESHOOTERS-2, 4-09 -- At Lucent
Technologies, where acquisitions are common, Patricia F. Russo,
right, executive vice president, oversees the merger integration
group. Mary Jane Raymond is post-merger integration vice president.
(Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 11 -- MERGER-TROUBLESHOOTERS-1, 4-09 -- A Cisco Systems team
evaluates potential acquisitions to make sure mergers work, and
warns about which ones won't. ``We've walked away from companies''
where the culture wasn't right, says Ammar Hanafi, director of
business development. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
MUTFUND-INSURANCE, 4-09 -- J. Steven Neamtz, in charge of marketing
mutual funds at SunAmerica. ``Basically, what we're doing is
creating peace of mind,'' he says of his company's Asset Protection
Plan for mutual fund investments. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAN DIEGO -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
NETMUSIC-ROBINSON-PROFILE, 4-09 -- Michael Robertson, chief
executive of MP3.com, is hailed by some musicians as a
revolutionary because of his distribution of music on the Internet.
But he says he's just ``a purebred capitalist.'' (Robert
Burroughs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) KUTAISI, Georgia -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
APRIL 11 -- ABOUT-CARS-PACKARD, 4-09 -- Nodar Chechelashvili, 64, a
Georgian pensioner, with his red, white and blue 1935 Packard. The
car, which he bought when he was 20, was once used by Stalin's
secret police chief. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
CONDOM-DESIGNER, 4-09 -- Dr. Alla Venkata Krishna Reddy holds a
pack of Inspiral, his new-shaped condoms. Reddy, who is not
affiliated with a big company, has been part of a new school of
thought that seeks to revamp the contemporary image of condoms from
necessary evil to alluring sex enhancer. (Frances Roberts/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11 --
STEIN-NITEOUT, 4-09 -- Taylor Stein, playgirl turned business
woman, at Brown's. Though she's known for her flamboyant outfits
and blunt chatter, Ms. Stein, 29, wants to be taken seriously. ``I
called in every favor I could,'' says Ms. Stein, who created buzz
for the restaurant by giving free dinner parties to journalists,
publicity agents and friends. (Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HOUSTON -- April 9, 1999 -- FUSIONFOOD-HNS, 04-08 --
Cookbook author Hugh Carpenter says fusion cuisine can apply to
techniques or ingredients from any cooking tradition, such as
Southwestern. He displays an example of this cuisine with a dish of
chilies rellenos with goat cheese, currants and cilantro dish from
his ``Fusion Food Cookbook,'' published in 1994 by Artisan. (E.
Joseph Deering/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- April 9, 1999 -- ONLINE-COURSES-EDLIFE, 04-04
-- David Sonnenschein, a professor of music at Northeastern
University, shows the headphones he uses to listen to music on his
computer. Students who sign up for his Music 1101, ``Music: A
Listening Experience,'' agree to study Mozart's minuets and
Beethoven's symphonies entirely via computer. (Michael Quan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PHOENIX -- April 9, 1999 -- GARNISH-FOOD-AZR, 04-09 --
Vegetables such as radishes, chiles, carrots and onions burst into
bloom with a few strategic cuts, while tomatoes stand ready to take
on a new life as rose look-alikes. These easy garnishes will add a
stylish touch to everyday foods. (Suzanne Starr/Arizona Republic
photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FREEPORT, Maine -- April 9, 1999 -- LLBEAN-MOMENTUM-BOS,
04-09 -- Leon A. Gorman, Bean's president since 1967 and grandson
of founder L.L. Bean, seeks to update the company's image.
Consumers are ``not seeing us as up-to-date and relevant to their
lifestyle,'' says Gorman, 64. ``We want to let people know we're
not just the same old company they liked in the '70s and '80s.
We're also contemporary.'' (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BRAZDE, Macedonia -- April 9, 1999 -- REFUGEE-CAMP-BOS-2,
04-09 -- Sabit Baricha holds his wife Barharia's hand as she is
attended to by Dr. Israel Handler following the birth of their
first born in the operating unit of the Israeli Defense Forces
medical corp hospital. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BRAZDE, Macedonia -- April 9, 1999 -- REFUGEE-CAMP-BOS,
04-09 -- Zenili Family members are grief stricken over the death of
55-year-old Hamida Zenili - a mother of 8 -- ouside their tent at
the Brazda camp Friday. From left, cousins Arizije, Minire and
Elhame mourn the loss with Mrs. Zenili's daughters, Hamida, Merita
and Sabrije. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) STANKOVIC, Macedonia -- April 9, 1999 --
GUANTANAMO-REFUGEES-BOS, 04-08 -- Refugee boys cheer and run away
from a French helicopter as it takes off from the Stankovic refugee
camp after dropping off supplies. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PLYMOUTH, Mass. -- April 9, 1999 -- HOME-VOYSEY-BOS,
04-08 -- David E. Berman of Plymouth sits in a Voysey garden chair
in Plymouth. In restoring Charles Francis Annersley Voysey, Berman
must also restore his scale. He works from documentary prints, and
he treasures the friendship and help of the last living link to the
Voysey architectural practice, John Brandon-Jones of Hampstead, who
worked for Voysey's son. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
