<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/09/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) INDIANTOWN, Fla. -- April 9, 1999 -- BLUEGRASS-MENIFEE,
4-09 -- Menifee, who returns to Kentucky to test his talent in the
big leagues, during a February morning workout with Shannon Ridder.
Menifee won his first two races last summer and even defeated Cat
Thief and Lemon Drop Kid, two of his rivals in the Blue Grass, on
Saturday. (Gary I. Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-2, 4-09 --
The Tigers' Deivi Cruz waiting while groundskeepers battle the rain
at Yankee Stadium on Friday. ``It was like a lake out there,'' the
Yankees' interim manager, Don Zimmer, says. But the Yankees managed
to defeat Detroit 12-3, before the umpires mercifully ended the
game with two out in the bottom of the seventh inning. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-1, 4-09 --
Chili Davis, being congratulated by Tino Martinez after his grand
slam Friday, brightened what, for most, was a dreary day. But the
Yankees played as if it were a comfortable 78 degrees, defeating
the Detroit Tigers 12-3, before the umpires mercifully waved for
the tarp and ended the game with two out in the bottom of the
seventh inning. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) LOS ANGELES -- April 9, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 11
-- FCC-KENNARD-PROFILE-2, 4-09 -- William E. Kennard, the chairman
of the Federal Communications Commission. Kennard, a black
telecommunications lawyer raised in an integrated Los Angeles
neighborhood, has tried to show how telecommunications issues are
linked to social issues. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- CELEBRITY-CHEFS-2, 4-09 --
Bob Thomas, right, is getting lessons on how to be a TV chef from
David Kratz, the president of Kratz &AMP; Jensen. About 30 percent of
the New York public relations firm's business is with restaurants
and chefs. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) LOS ANGELES -- April 9, 1999 -- CAMPAIGN-DOLE, 4-09 --
Elizabeth Dole, meeting Friday with a group in Beverly Hills. She
says a constitutional amendment to ban abortion is ``not going to
happen.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) TIRANA, Albania -- April 9, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SURVEIL-4,
4-09 -- A Kosovo refugee airlifted by NATO waits for an ambulance
with a NATO medic Friday at the airport in Tirana. NATO's takeover
of the relief effort is raising questions about the neutrality of
aid groups. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEWPORT NEWS, Va. -- April 9, 1999 -- SHIPYARD-STRIKE-2,
4-09 -- The Newport News shipyard produces nuclear carriers.
Seething about what they called stingy wages and pensions, more
than 8,000 workers at Newport News Shipbuilding went on strike
after their contract expired last Monday. (Timothy Wright/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) NEWPORT NEWS, Va. -- April 9, 1999 -- SHIPYARD-STRIKE-1,
4-09 -- Jennifer Skidmore, whose parents are on strike, makes a
sign Friday in Newport News. Seething about what they called stingy
wages and pensions, more than 8,000 workers at Newport News
Shipbuilding went on strike after their contract expired last
Monday in one of the largest walkouts this decade. (Timothy
Wright/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) SEATTLE -- April 9, 1999 -- SEATTLE-BOOK-WARS-2, 4-09 --
Ron Sher, a Seattle developer who is the new owner of the Elliott
Bay Book Co., says he can make the venerable bookstore thrive
again. At the store, customers can browse amid the cedar shelves or
listen to some of the 500 or more annual programs that make up its
esteemed series of author readings. (Larry Davis/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- SEATTLE-BOOK-WARS-1, 4-09
-- Jeffrey P. Bezos, founder of the online bookseller Amazon.com.
Throughout Amazon.com's meteoric rise, Bezos, 35, has been a
regular customer at Seattle's Elliott Bay Book Co. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- April 9, 1999 -- RELIGION-COLUMN, 4-09 --
Walter Cronkite, right, at his Manhattan home with the Rev C.
Welton Gaddy, executive director of the Interfaith Alliance. The
group presented its first Walter Cronkite Faith and Freedom Awards
on Friday. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
