<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VALENZUELA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES DROPPED AGAINST VALENZUELA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Prosecutors dropped their robbery case
against ex-jockey Patrick Valenzuela after they determined they had
the wrong man, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, 36, had been accused of taking $150 from a Rosemead
cab driver at gunpoint. He was arrested and charged with the crime
in February. Deputy District Attorney Tamia Hope asked Superior
Court Judge Janice Claire Croft to dismiss the case ``in the
interest of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief hearing, Croft granted that request. In the days
since his arrest, Valenzuela maintained his innocence and indicated
he had an alibi. He said he was watching the Grammy Awards on
television with a friend. Valenzuela's attorney, Donald Calabria,
did not return three phone calls seeking comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   R. Dan Murphy, the head deputy district attorney in Pasadena,
said that asking the judge to dismiss the charges against
Valenzuela was not all that unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kick cases all the time and no one ever notices,'' Murphy
said. ``Occasionally we get cases where we are convinced we have
the wrong guy and this was one of those instances.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, who won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes in
1989 aboard Sunday Silence, could have been sent to prison for up
to 16 years had he been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   No one else has been arrested or charged in the Feb. 24 robbery
of Green Valley Cab driver Jose Valdez, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Valenzuela began to lose steam in mid-March,
when the ex-jockey appeared in Rio Hondo Municipal Court for a
preliminary hearing.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, cabbie Jose Valdez testified he was robbed at
gunpoint by a clean-shaven man, about 5-foot-6 or 5-7, weighing 140
to 150 pounds, clad in a dark jacket and wearing a baseball cap.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, who has a mustache and goatee, is 5-4 and weighs
about 125 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The robber took $150 in ones, fives, 10s and 20s, Valdez
testified. When Valenzuela was arrested a little more than 24 hours
later, he had no money in any of those denominations and was
unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez was unable to identify Valenzuela either by sight or by
voice during the preliminary hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just appears from everything we know about the case that
Valenzuela was close enough in appearance to the robber that at
first the cab driver thought it was him,'' Murphy said. ``But
(Valdez's) ID got very shaky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing we saw told us we had the right guy,'' Murphy said.
``We always worry about ID cases and in this case (Valdez) should
have been able to ID (Valenzuela) with much greater clarity in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela's close-knit family stood by the ex-jockey throughout
his ordeal. His sister Christine Wing, a resident of Chino Hills,
predicted Friday's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat didn't do this,'' she said. ``There's a lot of evidence to
show that and it will be brought out in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Known affectionately as ``P-Val'' in the horse racing community,
Valenzuela was once one of the premier jockeys in the world. But, a
string a drug-related problems, misdemeanor criminal charges and
brushes with boards of stewards at various tracks caused him to
lose his rider's license several times.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela was suspended from racing in October 1997 after his
failure to show up for work during the Oak Tree Meet. He has not
raced since. In recent months he has promised his friends and
family that he will return to the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Ted West said he'd be happy to see the ex-jockey return.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a lot of chances and its never worked, but it's up to
him,'' West said. ``I wish him well and I would be extremely
pleased if he could put his career back together again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
