<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A. Jones' hit gives Braves 3-2 victory over Arizona
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Andruw Jones broke out of his season-opening slump in
a big way Friday night, singling in the winner in the 10th as the
Braves beat Arizona 3-2 before 34,939 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Brian Jordan doubled down the right-field line off
John Frascatore. The Diamondbacks put Javy Lopez on with an
intentional walk. Jones, whose walk keyed a ninth-inning rally that
brought the Braves back from a 2-0 deficit, singled up the middle
for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine and Randy Johnson are going to have a hard time
topping the showdown Odalis Perez and Omar Daal put on Friday
night. The left-handers pitched shutout ball through six innings,
leaving it up to the Arizona and Atlanta bullpens to decide the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were the ones flinching first as Luis Gonzalez
rocketed a pinch-hit solo homer off Rudy Seanez to start the eighth
inning. Arizona added a run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed only two hits through six innings to end his
major-league starting debut in style. He walked three but struck
out five.
</P>
<P>
   Perez allowed three runners in the first two innings _ a double
by Matt Williams and two walks _ but didn't let any of them hurt.
After Williams' double in the first inning, Perez struck out
cleanup hitter Travis Lee looking with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   A double-play grounder from Tony Batista and a Dante Powell
flyout erased the two walks and Perez was still in business. Perez
set down the next eight hitters, striking out half of them.
</P>
<P>
   Daal battled him the entire way, which is what the Diamondbacks
expected from the middle reliever turned quality starter last year.
After taking over for injured Joel Adamson last season, Daal became
one of Arizona's most dependable starters. He wound up fifth in the
National League with a 2.88 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Daal, who lost a 1-0 matchup with Denny Neagle last year, foiled
the Braves again Friday night. He kept a lineup that has been
dormant since the 17-hit night Tuesday against the Phillies quiet
for the first six innings, scattering four hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had runners at second and third in the first but
failed to score when Lopez sent a fly ball to shallow center field
for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
