<HEADLINE>
INJURIES START TO HIT DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Mighty Ducks have been one of the league's
least injured teams this season. They had lost only 89 man games
due to injury coming into Friday's game with San Jose. But center
Steve Rucchin has missed eight of the last nine games with a groin
injury and defenseman Pascal Trepanier is out for the season with a
torn anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Neither injury was suffered in a game, Rucchin was hurt in
practice on March 20 and Trepanier was injured while playing
basketball on a off-day during the recent road trip.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rucchin was having the best season of his career before
getting hurt -- 23 goals and 61 points in 66 games. But his
comeback attempt in New Jersey on March 31 set him back and now
he's hoping to be ready for next Wednesday's game against St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I lay in bed and want to scream, said Rucchin.
``This is an especially fun time for this team and it's so
frustrating not to play.
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne, who tried to rush back from a thigh injury
earlier this season, cautions that Rucchin must take his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such important player, he can't rush, he's got to be 100
percent for the playoffs, said Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin, who said he ``had to try to play in New Jersey, admits
the game against the Devils set him back. But he insists that ``no
question it will be 100 percent by the playoffs. When I come back
it will be a lot stronger.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Trepanier, who was acquired in the NHL Waiver Draft just before
the season, had slowly, but surely earned more ice time in Anaheim
coach Craig Hartsburg's seven-defenseman rotation. But he will
undergo surgery next week and will be spectator once the playoffs
roll around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been better that's for sure, said Trepanier, who had two
goals and six points 45 games. ``It's not easy when the fun part
(of the season) is coming up, but it's part of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate, he was starting to be a pretty good player,
said Hartsburg. (The injury) hurts us depth wise, but we have Dan
Trebil, who we feel can play for us.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Backup goalie Dominic Roussel had to leave the Dallas game on
Wednesday due to back spasms. According to Hartsburg, he won't be
available this weekend, but should be ready for the season's last
three games.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Roussel, the Ducks recalled Patrick Lalime from
Kansas City of the International Hockey League, where he was 36-20
with a 2.99 goals against average.
</P>
<P>
   -- When the Ducks clinched their playoff spot they did so in
their 74th game (a 4-1 victory versus the New York Rangers last
Friday). Anaheim needed 80 to clinch its first playoff spot back in
1996-97.
</P>
</TEXT>
