<SLUG> BC-CAR-DRAG-RACING-RECORD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP FUEL DRIVER SETS ELAPSED-TIME MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYTOWN, Texas _ Larry Dixon says that when he ran the quickest
quarter-mile pass in drag racing history last night, he was driving
while blind.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by a wheelstand that carried the front end of his Top Fuel
dragster in the air for approximately 250 feet, Dixon became the
first driver to crack the 4.50-second barrier during qualifying for
the NHRA's O'Reilly Nationals. Dixon covered the strip at Houston
Raceway Park in 4.486 seconds and 318.54 mph.
</P>
<P>
   His elapsed time eclipsed Mike Dunn's record of 4.503 seconds
set during the National Hot Rod Association's season opener in
Pomona, Calif., in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awesome pass,'' said Dixon, driver of the Miller
Lite Dragster owned by retired four-time Funny Car champion Don
``The Snake'' Prudhomme. ``Leaving the starting line, it had the
front end up _ higher than I feel comfortable with _ for a long
way. It was a couple of feet off the ground, to where you can't see
down the track. All you see is the car. At that point, you just
have to aim straight.''
</P>
<P>
   NHRA rules require a national record to be backed up by a run
within 1 percent of the provisional record number during the same
meet. Dixon, 32, met that requirement on his first pass at 4.516
seconds, which was a track record.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, eight-time champion John Force lowered the Funny Car
national ET record to 4.798 seconds, one-thousandth of a second
better than he clocked in Gainesville, Fla., last month. Force's ET
was accompanied by a track record speed of 321.88 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Four-time and reigning Pro Stock champion Warren Johnson tops
that qualifying ladder after two rounds at 6.898 seconds and 200.26
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Allen, of Arlington, Texas, who has qualified for only one
of three events this season, is 14th at 6.992 seconds and 197.42
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminations in Pro Stock Truck are scheduled to begin this
morning, with Brad Jeter of Greenville, S.C., the No. 1 qualifier
at 7.995 seconds and 177.91 mph. Both numbers are track records.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
