<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS ADJUSTS TO RASH OF INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Tex. _ The Anaheim Angels went into their four-game
series with division rival Texas missing three of their best
players in Mo Vaughn, Jim Edmonds and Gary DiSarcina.
</P>
<P>
   But Rangers manager Johnny Oates wasn't feeling sorry for
anybody. After a reporter mentioned that the Angels also were
banged up when the two teams met at the end of last season, Oates
shot back and reminded the reporter that the Rangers were beaten up
early last season, particularly the pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   They were so beaten up they started Todd Van Poppel and Matt
Perisho in two games against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it's going to happen to you at some time during the
year,'' Oates said. ``You just hope it's not severe. A hamstring,
things like that, you can get over. Ligament replacement surgery,
like what Kerry Wood had, that's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Edmonds and Vaughn in his lineup, Angels manager Terry
Collins admits he must manage the offense differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to deal with what you have,'' he said. ``If you
don't have power you make adjustments. The key is to get guys on,
otherwise you can't steal bases or hit-and-run.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of Edmonds and Vaughn also puts more focus on Troy
Glaus and Todd Greene. Glaus has gotten off to a fast start, but
Greene has struggled, so Collins flip-flopped the two in the order
Friday _ Glaus hit sixth and Greene seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had (Greene) protecting Glaus (in the batting order), but
heck, Todd's got only 100 major-league at-bats himself,'' Collins
said. ``We've got to get him to relax. He thinks he's got to
produce runs because Mo's not there.... We've got a couple young
guys in big spots.''
</P>
<P>
   The change worked Friday, as Glaus singled and Greene followed
with a home run in the second inning. Glaus also had a two-run
double.
</P>
<P>
   Abbreviated stint?: Collins said Edmonds (strained groin, cyst
in shoulder) will be ready when he is eligible to come off the
disabled list Wednesday in Oakland. That could mean a short stay
with the big club for Chris Pritchett, who joined the team here
Friday, replacing Vaughn on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   But it's something Pritchett, 29, is used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a player in my situation, especially in the American
League, goes into spring training, there's a slim chance of making
the team every year,'' he said. ``There's really only one spot
available and you really have to do well to even have a chance. So
with guys like me it really isn't a slap in the face because the
odds are stacked so high against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahead: The Angels and Rangers continue their series tonight in
Arlington. Omar Olivares (9-9, 4.03 ERA in '98) will start for
Anaheim against Texas' Rick Helling (0-1, 15.00).
</P>
</TEXT>
