<SLUG> BC-GLF-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN FIGHTS FIELD AND FATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Because this is his Waterloo, Greg Norman was
asked yesterday about The Kingdom He Can't Conquer.
</P>
<P>
   Is it his destiny, someone wanted to know, for Norman to be
eternally frustrated by Augusta?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my destiny is,'' Norman said, after his
second-round 68 had given him the early second-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me the question, `Does this place owe you one?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't believe in things being owed to you. I think you
go out there and play well enough to get them yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the random victim philosophy. At Augusta National Golf Club,
home of the Masters, Norman could be the poster boy for random
victimization. In 18 previous trips here, though he has won 18 PGA
Tour events and won tournaments in 13 countries, Norman has yet to
claim the green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The crying towel, yes. But other people _ people named Nick and
Larry, to name two _ keep donning Norman's jacket.
</P>
<P>
   When his name burst atop the leader board during yesterday's
second round, mostly on the strength of birdies on the first three
holes, Norman again found himself in the spotlight. The obvious
topic was the shoulder surgery that kept him out of all but three
1998 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   But Norman also attracts a crowd at Augusta National because he
can't seem to win here. He is the eternal ambulance, waiting to be
chased.
</P>
<P>
   He has finished in the Masters' top 10 on eight occasions. He
lost in 1987 because Larry Mize sank a 140-foot chip shot.
</P>
<P>
   More infamously, he lost to Nick Faldo in 1996 after blowing a
final-day six-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny?
</P>
<P>
   ``Destiny and luck,'' Norman answered, ``go hand in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norman meltdown at the '96 Masters has been called the
``greatest Sunday collapse in the history of major championship
golf.'' Look at it another way _ Norman single-handedly changed the
Sunday viewing habits of millions of American TV watchers.
</P>
<P>
   From that 1996 day forward, who dares leave their TV when a
golfer has a mere six-stroke lead?
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the definition of destiny?'' Norman asked. ``The thing
that really sticks in my mind is what happened to Fred Couples \Rin
1992\S when a ball hung up there on the front of No. 12. No other
ball in the entire tournament hung up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that destiny or a little bit of luck?''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us would say it was the latter. But when foul luck
happens one year, followed by another year, and followed by yet
another year, that smells like a destiny.
</P>
<P>
   In the same year as Norman's Masters meltdown, Bob Tway chipped
in from the bunker to pass Norman and win the PGA Championship.
Norman had the distinction that year of leading all four major golf
championships ... after three rounds. A ``Saturday Slam,'' the golf
literati called it.
</P>
<P>
   Norman got mail after his derailment here in '96. He said the
outpouring of sympathy and public kindness changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to see and appreciate other things in life more than
just golf,'' he said. ``You realize that there are other things out
there that can touch you, and '96 did that. It made me appreciate
people in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no sense of urgency, Norman said. No internal clock ticks
away on his supposedly dwindling Masters chances.
</P>
<P>
   He said he acquired the virtue of perspective during the long
rehab following his shoulder surgery. Norman reminded the media
yesterday that after a final-round 77 in 1993, he had given himself
a seven-year deadline to decide if he still enjoyed playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a big hurry anymore to do too many things,'' Norman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``Don't get me wrong. I love to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The gallery at Augusta, for what it's worth, showered Norman
with warm applause all day as he shot his 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sentimental favorite?'' Norman asked, repeating a question
with a laugh. ``How would you determine that? From '96, or because
I'm getting old?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, someone suggested, the galleries have simply decided that
Greg Norman, at age 44, has suffered enough. He has finished second
three times at Augusta _ with a PGA-record 27 runner-up finishes on
the tour in all.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdom He Can't Conquer awaits to hear Greg Norman's
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Masters owes him all right.
</P>
<P>
   And either way _ siren or no siren _ they watch. Oh, they watch.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
