</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOW THE MASTERS LOOKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 10:
</P>
<P>
   In the venerable world of golf, the Masters Tournament at the
Augusta National Golf Club in Augusta, Ga., is a relative newcomer
among major tournaments. The first Masters was held in 1934; the
first green jacket _ awarded to the winner _ was presented in 1949,
and the first telecast of the Masters appeared in 1956. You would
never guess that from the coverage. Tradition has accrued to the
Masters at a rate that is nearly unfathomable, and nothing chokes
up a network sportscaster like tradition. The azaleas bloom, the
pine-straw in the rough enforces a deep hush, and nowhere on earth
is the subject of grass discussed so thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   As David Owen demonstrates in his insightful new book, ``The
Making of the Masters,'' the Masters tradition is not an exercise
in nostalgia. It is the result of restless, often brilliant
innovation by two men, Bobby Jones, the golf legend who died in
1971, and especially Clifford Roberts, a complex perfectionist who
was the first chairman of Augusta National Golf Club, which he and
Jones built.
</P>
<P>
   For Roberts, who died in 1977, the question was never how to
create tradition. It was how to make each year's tournament better
than the last. He and Jones had precise, inflexible ideas about the
game of golf _ but Roberts' ideas about the tournament were
anything but inflexible.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of race, for example, the club itself was
segregated until 1991, and Owen says it ``was certainly part of the
culture that for decades made golf virtually unapproachable for
black players.'' But the Masters admitted without hesitation the
first black player to qualify _ Lee Elder in 1975 _ and Elder
himself testified to the warmth of his reception.
</P>
<P>
   The innovation behind the Masters became apparent in Clifford
Roberts' negotiations with CBS. Roberts pressed for the use of more
cameras, the coverage of more holes, the introduction of color
broadcasts and many other less visible technical improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, he insisted that advertising be kept to a minimum,
and in his negotiations he always argued that the quality of golf
and of the telecast itself took precedence over money. What Roberts
clearly foresaw was the feedback loop that has come to govern
modern televised sports _ a high price for broadcast rights means
more commercials and fewer minutes of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters is still broadcast by CBS the way Roberts wanted it,
with tight restrictions on advertising and a sense of time that is
nearly as generous as Augusta's fairways. There are many reasons to
watch this tournament, but for those of us unable to join the
greenside galleries at Augusta, the best reason is to see what
televised sports should really look like, when money is not the
only object.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
