A2966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROKER-GUILTY-NYT &LR;      04-09 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKER-GUILTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE &AMP; CO. BROKER PLEAS GUILTY IN CASE INVOLVING NEW ISSUES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Calif., Utah, Conn., Ill.)   By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As part of an investigation into corrupt activities
in the securities industry, the Manhattan district attorney, Robert
M. Morgenthau, said Friday that a former stockbroker at Duke &AMP; Co.,
a defunct New York brokerage firm, had pleaded guilty to attempted
enterprise corruption. The broker, Pasquale D'Onofrio, who is known
as John, will be sentenced on Oct. 21 and faces up to 15 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   D'Onofrio, 25, was charged with participating in a scheme in
which Duke conspired with other brokerage firms to maintain the
price of initial public offerings at artificially high levels. The
offerings that were sold to unsuspecting customers, according to
Morgenthau, included the Renaissance Entertainment Corp., Sel-Leb
Marketing Inc., Paravant Computer Systems, Bristol Technology
Systems Inc., and IFS International Inc. The stocks eventually
collapsed when buyers for them dried up. Of the five companies,
only one has shares that still trade: Paravant Computer, which
closed Friday at $2.3125.
</P>
<P>
   Duke &AMP; Co., which went out of business in March 1998, had two
offices, one in midtown Manhattan and another on Long Island. The
brokerage firm had come under scrutiny by state securities
regulators in late 1996 when officials from 20 states _ including
Alabama, California, Utah, Connecticut and Illinois _ began a
nationwide crackdown on fraudulent brokerage firms using hard-sell
tactics to peddle obscure, over-the-counter stocks. Duke was the
subject of 26 regulatory actions before it went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said his office began its investigation into Duke in
the summer of 1997, and he called the guilty plea, ``a significant
step in this continuing investigation.'' He expects to get guilty
pleas from others in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While law enforcement officials are not yet able to tally
investors' losses in the Duke failure, Morgenthau said that $171
million had been invested through the company. Two weeks ago, the
Securities Investor Protection Corp., the industry-financed agency
that insures individuals' brokerage firm accounts, appointed
Elizabeth Page Smith, a lawyer at LeBoeuf, Lamb, Greene &AMP; MacRae in
New York, to oversee the liquidation of any assets that might
remain at Duke. The firm had about 34,000 customer accounts when it
closed.
</P>
<P>
   According to law enforcement officials, Duke brokers would
entice investors into stocks that the firm was underwriting,
promising them fast profits. But when customers sought to sell
their holdings, the brokers prevented them from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Duke was the creation of Victor Wang, a former broker and
executive at Stratton Oakmont, a Long Island brokerage firm that
was the subject of numerous regulatory actions before it was
expelled by the industry's own regulators in late 1996. Prosecutors
said that the firms, besides Duke, that were part of the conspiracy
to manipulate initial public offerings were First Cambridge
Securities and Bishop Allen &AMP; Co. Both are defunct.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Manhattan district attorney, Ray Newton, 48, of
Andalusia, Ala., invested $350,000 with Duke, money he had received
as a settlement from an accident in which he broke his back.
Newton's funds were put into speculative stocks by D'Onofrio even
though he had told the broker that he and his wife had a joint
income of $21,000 a year. As a result of losing his investment,
Newton lost his home and a small business he had owned.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Krebs, a lawyer at Ritchie &AMP; Rediker in Birmingham,
Ala., represented Newton. Krebs, who was Securities Commissioner of
Alabama from 1975 to 1981, said: ``I've been in the securities
industry since 1973, and I've never seen anything this bad. These
guys were totally out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Beauchamp, spokesman for the North American Securities
Administrators Association Inc., said: ``This is a good example of
how state securities regulators and law enforcement agencies can
work together to prosecute fraud and protect investors. With half
of U.S. households now invested in the stock market, we need to do
more cases like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
