<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL'S SAVVY PROPELS HIM INTO THE LEAD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It was a day for Jose Maria Olazabal to display
his talent on a worldwide stage.
</P>
<P>
   He showed the diverse shot-making skill of a player who has won
tournaments round the globe. He showed the wisdom and poise of a
former Masters champion. He showed the passion of a player whose
career was threatened by injury, a man thankful to have his health,
and his game.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a blistering, bogey-free, six-under-par 66, including a
32 on the back nine, Olazabal left Augusta National Golf Club
holding a one-stroke lead over Scott McCarron heading into
Saturday's third round of the Masters. Olazabal stood at eight
under par (136, 70-66), one stroke better than McCarron (137), an
unexpected contender who followed Thursday's 69 with a 68 Friday.
But while Olazabal put himself in prime position for the weekend,
his journey is only half over.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Janzen, a two-time U. S. Open winner, and Greg Norman, a
two-time British Open champion, are tied for third place at five
under par, followed by Davis Love III and Nick Price at three under
par. Six players are tied at two under _ Steve Elkington, Bernhard
Langer, Justin Leonard, Brandel Chamblee, Bill Glasson and Colin
Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   With so much golf left, there were so many possibilities. Can
Norman, clearly the sentimental favorite, finally triumph in a
tournament that has haunted him and humbled him, most recently in
1996, when he lost a six-stroke lead to Nick Faldo in the final
round? Will Janzen, underrated by many despite winning two U. S.
Opens, add another major to his collection? Can either Tiger Woods
(even par), or David Duval (one over), mount a weekend charge, or
will the world's top two players be disappointed in the year's
first major?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions will be answered this weekend. Olazabal, who won
the Masters in 1994, knew enough not to celebrate yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are two more days to go, tough days,'' said
Olazabal, a 33-year-old Spaniard, who has finished no worse than
14th in his last five Masters. ``It's a wide-open golf tournament.
We've seen many, many things happen on this golf course. Experience
is very important. And because I won here in '94, that makes me
feel a little bit better than the players who haven't won.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a nerve problem in Olazabal's lower back caused
excruciating pain in his feet, so severe that by the summer of
1996, he could no longer walk. There were days when he literally
crawled to the bathroom, and in those dark moments, he cried in
solitude, fearing his career was over.
</P>
<P>
   A German doctor finally detected the cause of Olazabal's
problem, and the pain subsided with therapy and back injections. By
1997, Olazabal had returned to golf full time.
</P>
<P>
   On No. 16, he saved par with a brilliant chip shot from behind
the green, 30 feet from the pin, severely downhill. A poorly hit
ball could have rolled off the green and into the water, but
Olazabal delicately rolled the ball to within two feet for a
tap-in. At No. 13, he holed a wedge shot from 18 feet for birdie.
At the par-5 15th, he boldly hit a 1-iron approach shot, then hit
another superb chip shot from 35 feet to within a foot for an easy
birdie. And he capped the day with a birdie at No. 18, hitting a
9-iron approach shot to 10 feet, then making the putt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Olazabal received the kind of luck that good
players get on Thursday, when a poorly hit 4-iron took a lucky
bounce over the creek at No. 13 that runs in front of the green.
The ball finally stopped 20-feet from the pin, and Olazabal
capitalized by making the putt for eagle, the only eagle at No. 13
in two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to have good breaks,'' Olazabal said. ``It
was a good break. I haven't had too many in my life, so I'll take
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCarron made his own breaks, becoming the only
player with two rounds in the 60's. A 33-year-old native of
California, McCarron has not won on the PGA Tour since 1997, but he
has a history of playing well at Augusta, including a tie for 16th
last year. Many people expected McCarron to fade Saturday, and some
still expect the pressure to get the better of McCarron on
Saturday. But he thinks otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a lesser known,'' McCarron, a long
hitter who had six birdies and only two bogeys, said today. ``I
finished 10th at the U.S. Open. I finished 16th at Augusta. When
I'm playing with Norman or Fred Couples, I feel I'm as good as
them. If you don't, you don't belong out here.''
</P>
<P>
   So McCarron found himself much higher on the leader board than
either Woods or Duval, the two players focused on before the
tournament. Both players have been hurt badly by big numbers. Woods
had a double-bogey at the par-3 No. 12, hitting an 8-iron tee shot
into Rae's Creek, after a gust of wind held up his ball. ``Eight
shots back still isn't that bad,'' Woods said after he birdied No.
18 to finish with his second consecutive 72. ``I just have to play
solid golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who shot a 74 Friday, had a triple-bogey at No. 15,
hitting his third shot into the water. After the drop and penalty
stroke, Duval's next shot sailed over the green, from where he
chipped and two-putted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little discouraged right now, no question,'' said Duval,
the world's top-ranked player, who has four victories this year.
``This is a place where mistakes can hurt you, and I've made
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson (151), Mark Calcavecchia (152), Paul Azinger (153),
Nick Faldo (153), Hal Sutton (155) and Steve Jones (156) all missed
the 148 cut. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
