<HEADLINE>
WOMEN PETITION TO GET EQUAL PRIZE MONEY AT GRAND SLAM TOURNAMENTS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NEIL AMDUR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1970, a group of female tennis players, frustrated by the
disparity in tournament prize money with their male counterparts,
formed the first women's professional tour. Last week, another
group of female pros signed a petition authorizing the WTA Tour to
demand equal prize money with the men at all four Grand Slam
championships.
</P>
<P>
   If the organizers of the Australian Open, French Open and
Wimbledon fail to embrace the equal prize-money principle by next
year, the women say they are prepared to vote to boycott these
tournaments. The U.S. Open offers equal prize money for men and
women.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 60 female players signed the petition during the
Family Circle Cup tournament last week in Hilton Head Island, S.C.,
including such top 10 pros as Martina Hingis, Lindsay Davenport,
Jana Novotna and Monica Seles. More players are expected to sign
the petition when the tour moves to Europe next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a top priority,'' said Bart McGuire, the chief
executive officer of the WTA Tour, who has been authorized by the
players to meet with officials of the Grand Slam tournaments. ``I
think it's important for the Slams to know that it's not just
administrators running around saying we deserve equitable
treatment. The players feel very strongly about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the French Open increased the women's purse to 90
percent of the men's. Wimbledon, which offered the women 80 percent
last year, is expected to announce its prize-money breakdown for
this year's tournament later this month. The women received 94
percent at the 1999 Australian Open in January.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments for paying the men more have been their playing
three-of-five-set singles matches (the women play two-of-three-set
matches), having more depth on their tour and being more in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, when asked about the question of equal pay for
the women at Wimbledon, John Curry, the chairman of the tournament,
told The London Daily Telegraph: ``It is an incredibly emotional
subject. The women walk through the gates, see the men and say,
`Why should he get more than me?' It's like a heavyweight and a
middleweight in boxing. They might be on the same bill, but no
matter how good the middleweight is, the heavyweight gets paid
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in Europe. But in the United States, with the excitement
generated by Hingis, Davenport, Venus and Serena Williams and
others, the women are outdrawing the men in coverage by the news
media, television ratings and spectator interest. HBO may devote as
much as 70 percent of its Wimbledon coverage this year to the
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a cliff after Sampras and Agassi,'' Ross Greenburg,
the senior vice president and executive producer of HBO's Wimbledon
coverage, said of Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi and Americans'
interest in the men's tour.
</P>
<P>
   Although the women are still searching for a title sponsor for
their tour, they say they are united on the question of equal prize
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need that guarantee very soon,'' said Nicole Pratt, an
Australian player who helped organize the petition and told McGuire
she could produce 200 more signatures if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise there will have to be some action taken,'' Pratt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how soon the women would move on a boycott, McGuire said:
``I'm not going to go there now. I'm working to persuade the Grand
Slams to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
