<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND POLICE OFFICIAL CLAIMS RELIGIOUS DISCRIMINATION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. _ A high-ranking Suffolk County police official
has filed a federal civil rights suit against the county and its
police commissioner, charging them with denying him promotion to
inspector because he is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Deputy Inspector Howard E. Mandell, a 30-year
member of the department who worked his way up through the ranks,
says in the lawsuit that promotions have also been withheld because
he has spoken out publicly against police practices, including what
he says is bigotry in the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's regarded as a whistle-blower, and has been treated
adversely as a result,'' said Mandell's lawyer, Alan Polsky . He
said his client was not available to comment on the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Polsky filed the complaint against the county and Commissioner
John C. Gallagher on March 11 in U.S. District Court here, asking
that the Police Department be ordered to promote Mandell to
inspector, and pay him back wages and fringe benefits for that
rank, as well as compensatory and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   William Burke, the chief deputy county attorney, said Friday
that the county planned to ``vigorously oppose'' the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiff is one of the highest-ranking police officers in
the department, and that by itself pretty much speaks to whether
his claim is meritorious,'' Burke said. ``This is not a patrolman,
a sergeant, a lieutenant or even a captain. He's right up there in
the top echelon in a department with 2,700 officers.''
</P>
<P>
   As deputy inspector, Mandell, who makes $110,000 a year,
commands the department's Staff Services Bureau. The only higher
appointive ranks are inspector, deputy chief and chief.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Mandell said that almost from the time he joined
the department in 1969, he has been subject to many ethnic insults,
including being referred to as ``that Jew'' and ``Jew boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These biased remarks were made by police officers with ranks
as high as inspector, have been pervasive throughout the
plaintiff's employment and created a hostile environment for the
plaintiff to work in, which persists to this day,'' the complaint
says.
</P>
<P>
   It also claims that Gallagher has begun speeches at division
meetings at which Mandell has been present by stating, ``We are all
good Christians.'' Under the commissioner, it says, the department
also holds Ash Wednesday religious services each year at its
headquarters in Yaphank.
</P>
<P>
   ``These circumstances have created an atmosphere within the
Police Department that is decidedly pro-Christian and is
necessarily anti-Jewish,'' the complaint says. ``The department is
and has been traditionally dominated by a clique that is
predominantly Irish Catholic, and this tradition has been continued
by defendant Gallagher.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher would not comment on Mandell's suit, a spokesman said,
because it is before the courts.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Commissioner James M. Abbott said, ``From the time
Gallagher was appointed in January 1997, he informed his chiefs
that he would not tolerate any expressions of racism or any jokes
or humor based on race or ethnicity.''
</P>
<P>
   The department has been the subject of past discrimination
complaints. In 1996, the federal Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission cited ``a pattern of discrimination'' against black,
Hispanic and female officers that included the denial of
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Polsky acknowledged that his client had received many
promotions, but he said that they were based on objective criteria,
like length of service, and that the only discretionary promotion
Mandell received was to his current rank, made in 1989 by the
police commissioner at the time, Daniel Guido.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
