<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BERRA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS WELCOME BERRA BACK TO YANKEE STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before Bob Sheppard could complete the introduction
of Friday's special guest, the fans stood among the raindrops and
screamed. More than 56,000 pairs of eyes gazed toward the Yankee
dugout, looking for the beloved man who had come back home to
Yankee Stadium. They were searching for Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after Sheppard called the 73-year-old Berra ``a man
of conviction,'' Berra ended 14 years of self-imposed exile from
the Stadium. Berra walked in front of the mound, shook hands with
David Cone and lofted a high and inside pitch to Joe Girardi.
Finally, Berra was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous out there,'' Berra said. ``It was like
any opening day. I don't care how long you've played. You're always
a little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   An awed Cone said: ``To see Yogi walk out there and get the
ovation he got after all these years was tremendous. It was one of
the loudest ovations I've heard at Yankee Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Berra sat in George Steinbrenner's private box during the game,
three months after he received an apology from the owner who had
dismissed him 16 games into the 1985 season. Since that peace
meeting, Berra and Steinbrenner may feel as if they are on tour
together. Friday was at least the third time they have appeared
warm and fuzzy in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great after 14 years,'' said Berra, who predicted
Chili Davis' grand slam from the television booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always a Yankees fan. I always watched them on TV. I
think they have a good team this year. I think they can win it
again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famers Whitey Ford and Phil Rizzuto raised the 1998
championship flag, but Berra, another Hall of Famer, was the
marquee attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asking him for 14 years,'' Ford said. ``I don't care
what you think of Steinbrenner. The people really miss you. It's
nice to have him back.''
</P>
<P>
   For Berra, it was nice to finally be back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy,'' he said. ``I'm glad it's over.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-99 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
