A2978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BLUEGRASS-MENIFEE     04-09 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BLUEGRASS-MENIFEE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENIFEE TO TEST METTLE IN BLUE GRASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(dw) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ Three weeks before the Kentucky Derby, the
people who invested their time, money and passion in Menifee were
standing at the crossroads of his career.
</P>
<P>
   It was one day before the Blue Grass Stakes, the final and most
important prep race in the East. The man who trains the colt,
Elliott Walden, reflecting the team's sense of the moment and its
anxiety, said, ``The next race will tell us what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   What they have got is a promising bay colt who cost $37,000 when
they bought him at Keeneland two years ago and now costs $35,000 a
year to keep him trained and sound. Menifee won his first two races
last summer and even defeated Cat Thief and Lemon Drop Kid, two of
his rivals in the Blue Grass on Saturday. Then he took six months
off to heal a chip in his right knee, won his comeback race at
Gulfstream Park in February but missed by less than a length in the
Tampa Bay Derby in March. Now, Menifee is back home in Kentucky to
test his talent in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Can he handle Cat Thief, Vicar, Wondertross and the rest of
those heavy hitters? Can he even handle Pineaff, who upset him in
Tampa? Can he handle anybody at a mile and an eighth?
</P>
<P>
   The linemaker at Keeneland was still rating them in fractions:
Wondertross as the 5-2 favorite, followed by Vicar at 3-1, Cat
Thief and Menifee at 4-1 and Lemon Drop Kid at 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   It may be brinksmanship to stake all that investment on the way
one race is run, but 3-year-old horses have one shot at glory: the
Kentucky Derby. The road to the Derby winds through Keeneland,
where the 75th Blue Grass has drawn a field of eight horses with
talent and eight owners with ambition to match their investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He costs about as much as it costs to run my airplane for a
while,'' said Jimmy Stone, the Louisiana oil and gas executive who
owns Menifee with the colt's breeder, Arthur Hancock IIIof nearby
Paris, Ky. ``I've never had a horse in the Derby. But I won the
Ascot Gold Cup twice and lost the Arc de Triomphe by a nose.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's partner, the elder son of the legendary Bull Hancock of
Claiborne Farm, has won the Kentucky Derby twice: with Gato del Sol
in 1982 (he ran second in that year's Blue Grass) and Sunday
Silence in 1989. But Hancock frets about everything from the
weather to the draw for post position. He finds omens in many
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer an inside post,'' Hancock said before the Blue
Grass draw. ``In the Tampa Bay Derby, we drew on the outside and
got parked there. On the inside, we'd have choices, whether to go
straight ahead or tuck back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Tampa, he broke wide. He got behind horses. He went way
wide on the second turn. Yet, he finished less than a length
behind. I figure he lost five lengths in all that running. The
track was deep and it was his first time around two turns. You
know, he didn't do so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, Hancock and his wife, Staci, and Walden sat in the
Keeneland sales pavilion watching the draw for post positions for
the Blue Grass. Menifee drew the No. 8 slot on the far outside. So
much for the omens.
</P>
<P>
   Walden is no stranger to Triple Crown adventures. Last year he
trained Victory Gallop, who ran second to Real Quiet in the
Kentucky Derby and the Preakness before finally nailing him in the
last strides in the Belmont Stakes.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
