<SLUG> BC-NY-SAFIR-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE COMMISSIONER DEFENDS INQUIRY AFTER WIFE'S TRAFFIC
ACCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard
Safir Friday defended the commissioner's decision to send two
detectives to the home of a Queens woman who was involved in a
minor car accident with Safir's wife, saying the visit was an
appropriate inquiry into a potential security risk.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the circumstances surrounding the accident two years
ago had concerned him, given the threats that he routinely receives
as the city's top law-enforcement official. The woman, Monica B.
Nascimento, rear-ended his wife's car on the Queensboro Bridge, he
said, and then gave a false name before leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to determine why somebody who ran into the back of
my wife, the police commissioner's wife _ whether it was a security
problem,'' Safir said at a hastily called news conference Friday
afternoon. ``There was a determination by my detail to follow up
and see who this person was.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's explanation, which came a day after he and
his aides refused to confirm the detectives' visit, seemed to
satisfy Giuliani, who said, ``I would be surprised if the Police
Department did not follow up on that for questions of security.''
</P>
<P>
   But it did not mollify City Councilman Sheldon Leffler, the
chairman of the Council's public safety committee, who said the
accident was a personal matter and did not warrant the involvement
of police detectives.
</P>
<P>
   In defending his actions, Safir also acknowledged that he had
left a message on Ms. Nascimento's answering machine, and then had
spoken to her on the telephone _ but as a husband, he emphasized,
not as the police commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm OK if I do things as a husband, aren't I?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The testiness of that remark reflects the aura of embattlement
that now envelops Safir. In recent weeks he has been criticized for
leaving the city shortly after four white officers shot and killed
Amadou Diallo, an unarmed black immigrant, in the Bronx two months
ago, and then for attending the Academy Awards in Los Angeles last
month just as the outcry over the Diallo shooting was reaching a
crescendo.
</P>
<P>
   His California trip has also spurred a conflict-of-interest
inquiry because it was paid for by George Fellows, the president of
Revlon, whom Safir describes as a longtime friend with no business
ties to the city. But Revlon's parent company, MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes,
participates in a city-sponsored program that enables it to hire
off-duty police officers, in uniform, to provide nighttime security
at its offices.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Safir has shaken off a call for his resignation
from Public Advocate Mark Green, and has received the unqualified
endorsement of Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Then, this week, Safir and his wife, Carol, filed a $1.25
million civil suit against Ms. Nascimento, alleging that Mrs.
Safir's injuries from the accident have required ongoing physical
therapy, and that the accident had deprived Safir of his wife's
``companionship and consortium.''
.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
