<HEADLINE>
BOB PECK, 53, ACTOR OF STAGE AND SCREEN 
EMMETT COLVIN, 80, LAWYER FOR JACK RUBY 
H.S. KESSLER, 56, ANIMAL HOSPITAL FOUNDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Mich., Mo., N.J., N.Y., Penn., Texas, Va.)  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Peck, who appeared in the film ``Jurassic Park'' as well as
on stage and television in Britain, died on Sunday in London.
</P>
<P>
   He was 53 and had cancer, The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Peck, who lived in London, was much better known in Britain than
in the United States, where his biggest role was that of a game
warden, Robert Muldoon, in ``Jurassic Park,'' Steven Spielberg's
1993 dinosaur film.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Peck started as an actor with the National Theater
and the Royal Shakespeare Co., performing in plays like ``Nicholas
Nickleby,'' ``King Lear'' and ``The Tempest.''
</P>
<P>
   He later starred in numerous television dramas, including the
popular 1985 television series ``Edge of Darkness.'' In the series,
which featured music by Eric Clapton, Peck played Craven, a
grief-stricken police officer looking in an underground nuclear
reactor for clues to the death of his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Peck was regarded as an adaptable actor with a gift for
portraying Everyman. ``He was a hero, but without the heroics,''
said an obituary in The Guardian. ``We looked at the television
screen and saw ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Peck was born on Aug. 23, 1945, in Leeds, England, and was a
graduate of the Leeds College of Art.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Jill, two daughters and a son.
</P>
<P>
   Emmett Colvin, 80, Lawyer for Jack Ruby
</P>
<P>
   Emmett Colvin, a criminal defense lawyer from Texas, died on
April 2 at his home in Fairfax, Va. He was 80 and had retired to
Virginia from Dallas three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin was among the lawyers who represented Jack Ruby in an
appeal of his murder conviction for shooting Lee Harvey Oswald, the
assassin of President John F. Kennedy. They successfully argued for
Ruby's right to a new trial, but Ruby died of cancer before it
could be held.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin practiced criminal law defense for more than 50 years,
mostly in Texas. He argued several cases before the U.S. Supreme
Court and for two years was dean of the National College of
Criminal Defense, a post-graduate school for practicing lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He was educated at Arkansas State University and St. Louis
University and received a law degree from the University of
Arkansas in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin is survived by his wife of 57 years, Mary Lee Colvin; two
sons, Lance, of Seattle, and Mark, of Fairfax; a daughter, Laurel
Colvin of Chappaqua, N.Y.; six grandchildren and two
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   H.S. Kessler, 56, Animal Hospital Founder
</P>
<P>
   Howard S. Kessler, a Manhattan veterinarian and former president
of the board of the Bide-a-Wee Association, died on Thursday at the
Southampton Hospital in Southampton, N.Y. He was 56.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said his mother, Gail Kessler of Atlantic
City.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler, who lived on the Upper East Side of Manhattan, was the
director of the New York Veterinary Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   He was born on Jan. 12, 1943, in Milville, N.J., and graduated
from Michigan State University and the University of Pennsylvania
School of Veterinary Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Dr. Kessler founded the New York Veterinary Hospital,
which he directed until his death.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the co-founder and co-director of the Ansonia
Veterinary Center in Manhattan and was active in animal charities.
He was a sponsor for the Pet Owners with AIDS/ARC Resource Service.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his mother, Dr. Kessler is survived by his brother,
Barry Kessler of Egg Harbor, N.J., and a sister, Lois Kessler of
Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
